<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-PREVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS-GAZING: A 7-MONTH JOURNY TO STANLEY TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yu don't win a Stanley Cup without planning. Then again, it's
difficult to plan for the unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   That's the quandary facing the Stars as they prepare for the
1998-99 season, scheduled to begin at 7 p.m. tomorrowwhen the
Buffalo Sabres and goalie Dominik Hasek, the reigning and two-time
MVP, visit Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believed we had a pretty good chance at the start of the
playoffs last season, but then the injuries got to us,'' Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``So it's hard to look that far in
advance.''
</P>
<P>
   But obvious key moments await as the Stars try to turn a room
full of talent into Stanley Cup champions. It won't be easy, with
Hitchcock emphasizing that the team must remain one of the top
defensive groups in the NHL, while acknowledging that the Stars'
biggest problem in last season's playoffs was that the team didn't
score enough goals.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said he knows there are issues, but he also said the
team can't solve its problems without playing games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never plan more than 30 days in advance,'' he said. ``We
take it month by month and week by week.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's how some of those months and weeks might unfold:
October Key stat: Seven home games, two on the road. Key dates:
Stars raise Presidents' Trophy banner tomorrow. The first
appearance of San Jose Sharks defenseman and Public Enemy No. 1
Bryan Marchment to Reunion Arena, on Oct. 24. The first rematch
with defending Stanley Cup champion Detroit Red Wings, on Oct. 31
at Reunion Arena. Key issues: Hitchcock has emphasized that if the
line of Hull, Mike Modano and Jere Lehtinen isn't defensively
responsible, he will break them up. Hitchcock's target date for the
experiment is one month.
</P>
<P>
   When does Joe Nieuwendyk return and will he be bothered by his
injured knees? He said he wants to err on the side of caution, and
he knows his body well. Nieuwendyk interacting with linemates Pat
Verbeek and Jamie Langenbrunner, as well as with Hull and Modano on
the power play, will be crucial to the team's success. November Key
stat: Of 10 games in November, nine are against playoff teams from
last season. Key dates: Stars make first visit to Joe Louis Arena
in Detroit on Friday the 13th _ why does that sound bad? Brett Hull
makes first return to St. Louis, on Nov. 21. Key issues: In the
Stars' trip to San Jose, tough guy Brent Severyn will likely be
pushed to the wall by the Sharks and the rivalry. How Severyn reads
his team's need for physical play and fighting will be a key.
Timing his fights is as important as winning them.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have to win convincingly in Detroit to show they can
compete with the Stanley Cup champions.
December Key stat: 10 of 15 games on the road, including five-game
trip sandwiched around Christmas. Key dates: Four-game West Coast
road trip to start the month tests the durability of Stars'
television-watching fan base. Second and final trip to Detroit, on
Dec. 18. Key issues: By now, the Stars have likely suffered
injuries, and the heavy road schedule will test that. By the end of
the month, the Stars will have played the Sharks four times and
will have played 10 games in their physical division.
</P>
<P>
   With games against Vancouver, Edmonton, Calgary, Toronto and
Nashville, the Stars need to prove they can beat lesser teams on a
consistent basis.
January Key stat: Eight of 12 games against nonplayoff teams from
last season. Key dates: Longest road trip of the season takes Stars
to West Coast and Canada for five games Jan. 7-15. All-Star Game on
Jan. 24 in Tampa, Fla. Make reservations early, Stars players could
be filling hotels with friends and family. Key issues: If the
mental welfare of the team is an issue, this month could test it
most severely. The Stars are loaded with potential goal-scorers in
Hull, Modano, Nieuwendyk and Pat Verbeek _ yet it's likely at least
one or two will be left off the All-Star team. Does a potential
slight harm the chemistry of the team?
February Key stat: nine of 12 games at home. Key games: Avalanche
come to town for two Sunday afternoon games Feb. 7 and 21.
</P>
<P>
   Only visit of Pittsburgh Penguins and Jaromir Jagr, on Feb. 26.
Don't get too excited, last season was a 0-0 tie. Key issues: There
is the chance that Roman Turek could be playing better than Ed
Belfour at this stage, particularly in key games. Will the Stars
test Turek's ability as a possible replacement for Belfour or do
they quash a potential controversy by playing Belfour as much as he
likes?
</P>
<P>
   By this time, the Stars will have been taken a good look at
rookie Jamie Wright and potential looks at Jason Botterill or Jon
Sim with the Michigan K-Wings. If they hope to use any of the
rookies on a regular basis, now is the time to start working them
into the lineup.
March Key stat: 10 road games out of 15, 10 games against playoff
teams from last season. Key games: Stars in a New York state of
mind with road games against Rangers (second), Islanders (fourth)
and Sabres (fifth). Stars' only game with Flyers this season is
March 14 in Philadelphia. New schedule means Flyers don't visit
Texas. Key issues: It's hard to imagine that the Stars need
anything to add to the mix, but the trade deadline in late March
will provide interesting discussion. Do the Stars seek a guarantee
for the Stanley Cup and spend more?
April Key stat: Five-game homestand April 4-14. Key games: Hull
returns again to St. Louis. April 3. Stars play host to Red Wings
on April 4. Wow, what a weekend. Wayne Gretzky makes only trip to
Reunion Arena with New York Rangers, on April 9. Key issues: Stars
played near perfect in April last season and appeared ready to
crush any opponent. With five-game homestand including meeting with
Red Wings, they should again be trying to shape into form.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock's philosophy is always to ask 100 percent from his
players, but there will be questions whether he should rest players
early in the month _ or in late March _ to get them ready for the
playoffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
