<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PADRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN'S IN CHARGE, AND SO ARE PADRES 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Before this National League Championship Series began,
John Smoltz had warned that, no matter what happened to the Atlanta
Braves this year, when fans looked back on the 1990s they would
finally realize how good they had it.
</P>
<P>
   When the Braves look back on the last two seasons, though, all
they are likely to see are bad memories of Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   For the third consecutive time in the last two league
championship series, Brown took it to the Braves. Brown, a
33-year-old right-hander, tossed a three-hit shutout Thursday
night, struck out 11 and singled twice, during the game's only two
fruitful rallies, as the San Diego Padres beat the Braves, 3-0,
before 43,083 fans at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   The victory sent the four-of-seven-game series to San Diego for
the weekend with the Padres in command, two games to none. They are
two victories short of reaching the World Series for the first time
since 1984. Worse for Atlanta, which will start Greg Maddux on
Saturday, is the fact that since the league championship series
went to a four-of-seven format, in 1985, no team in either league
has ever advanced to the Series after losing the first two games at
home.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has now defeated Atlanta six straight times, dating from
September 1996, and Thursday night he did it with 122 pitches, 79
of which were strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Braves scrap their way back into this series, they
will have to face Brown one more time.
</P>
<P>
   Brown guarded a 1-0 lead through the eighth inning Thursday
night, then triggered a two-run San Diego ninth with an
inning-opening single. He defeated Atlanta twice for the Florida
Marlins in a six-game upset of the Braves in the NLCS last fall.
The Padres might not need that many games this year.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the Padres outlasted the Braves by 3-2 on Ken
Caminiti's 10th-inning home run in Game 1 on Thursday morning, Tony
Gwynn said his underdog Padres had originally come to Atlanta just
hoping for a split.
</P>
<P>
   ``You change your thinking,'' Gwynn said after Game 1. ``Now,
you go for two.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres did so without their best power hitter, Greg Vaughn,
who strained his left quadriceps muscle on the wet outfield grass
of Turner Field chasing a line drive in the fourth inning of Game
1. There was a chance that Vaughn, who hit 50 home runs this
season, could be out for the remainder of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's sore and it's hard to say how long,'' San Diego Manager
Bruce Bochy said Thursday afternoon. ``The doctors think possibly
three to four days, but it could be up to 10 days.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughan said he felt as if he had let his teammates down. ``We
got to this point and I can't play,'' he said. ``I don't know how
long they said I'm going to be out, but it's not going to be that
long.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn said he hoped to be ready to play left field in Game 3 on
Saturday in San Diego. Bochy and general manager Kevin Towers did
not sound so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best-case scenario is that he will be ready in time for
the first couple of games back home,'' Towers said. ``But the
worst-case scenario is that Greg might not be ready until the end
of this series.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Rivera, the 24-year-old outfielder the New York Yankees
traded to San Diego on May 30, 1997, as part of the deal in which
they obtained Hideki Irabu's negotiating rights, did just fine as
Vaughn's replacement Wednesday night. It was Rivera's hitting and
daring base running in the eighth inning that gave the Padres a
short-lived lead.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera was less impressive Thursday night, going 0 or 5 with
three strikeouts. The Padres could have used Vaughn in the middle
of their order Thursday night. Tom Glavine was uncharacteristically
wild. He walked a season-high six Thursday night, including
Caminiti in his first three at-bats, and Wally Joyner in his first
two.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the walks hurt Glavine, who threw 31 pitches in the
second inning and 26 in the third, and left the bases loaded both
times.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was a little sharper. He struck out the side in the first,
but walked the first two batters he faced in the second, before
pitching out of the jam. Two innings later, Brown was able to
induce Javy Lopez into an inning-ending pop-up to left field with
runners on second and third.
</P>
<P>
   By the fifth, Glavine's pitch count had reached 100. An inning
later, the Padres finally broke through. With two out and nobody
on, Glavine allowed a single between short and third to Chris
Gomez, his second hit of the game. Up stepped Brown, who had taken
a called third strike to leave the bases loaded in the second.
</P>
<P>
   On a 1-2 count, Brown grounded a single between short and third,
and the Padres, 0 for 8 with runners in scoring position, had
runners on first and second.
</P>
<P>
   This time, they came through. On Glavine's 121st pitch of the
game, Quilvio Veras singled up the middle to score Gomez. Andruw
Jones' throw from center skipped away from Lopez, but Glavine
backed up the play, and his throw to third was in time to get the
sliding Brown to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown had helped create one run. And he was enough for the
Padres to create all sorts of trouble for the Braves by heading
west with an improbable sweep of the first two games in Atlanta. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
