<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE RIVALS JUGGLE DUTIES AND DENUNCIATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At the Republican National Committee on Second
Street, allies of Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., held a news
conference Thursday to chide Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y.,
D'Amato's challenger, for missing 90 percent of the House Judiciary
Committee's votes this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al D'Amato, the tough campaigner, is staying here in
Washington doing his job and making his votes, while Schumer is
running around the state campaigning at taxpayer expense,'' said
Rep. Peter King, R-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Barely two hours later, at the Democratic National Committee on
South Capitol Street, Schumer and two Democratic senators attacked
D'Amato for opposing gun control and accepting $36,000 in campaign
contributions from the National Rifle Association during his 18
years in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al D'Amato has done everything that the National Rifle
Association has asked for,'' Schumer said. ``If there were ever a
clearer case of a senator from New York siding with the special
interests rather than the people's interests, I haven't seen it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinched in one of the nation's closest Senate races this year,
Schumer and D'Amato have brought their bare-fisted campaigns 350
miles south to Capitol Hill, where Congress is rushing to finish an
overflowing schedule by this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Congress' end-of-the-session sprint has produced an odd and
awkward geographic challenge to the candidates, who are trying to
conduct their legislative business while grabbing the attention of
voters and news media that are at least a 60-minute plane ride
away.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates have sought to make the most of this juggling
act all week. But while this has been something of a new task for
Schumer, it is very much in keeping with the style of D'Amato, who
has focused his time, and public relations efforts, on Washington
all year.
</P>
<P>
   The differences say much about the two men's contrasting
political needs. Schumer, largely unknown in large swaths of the
state, has needed to campaign more than D'Amato back home. And
D'Amato, facing a candidate who is running on his lengthy
legislative resume, has sought to cast himself as the state's most
effective legislator, someone who gets bills passed against the
odds.
</P>
<P>
   So it is that in recent weeks, as Schumer has been traveling
about New York, D'Amato has ensconced himself in Washington,
testifying for acid rain legislation, helping negotiate a sweeping
banking bill, and speaking at a commemorative event for Nelson
Mandela, the South African president.
</P>
<P>
   Ever the nimble-footed politician, D'Amato has also tried to
seize on Schumer's spotty attendance record by citing it in
television commercials, news conferences by surrogates and campaign
remarks as evidence that the congressman ``puts politics ahead of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato's aides say the strategy is intended to strike at the
heart of what Schumer considers his strongest political asset: his
legislative record and widely accepted reputation as an effective
lawmaker. The aides say they think they can also cast Schumer as a
publicity-grabbing opportunist.
</P>
<P>
   But Schumer's aides contend that D'Amato's Washington campaign
is really intended to mask what they consider the senator's
greatest liabilities: a lack of interest in legislation, a
reputation for placing politics ahead of policy and high negative
ratings among many New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic strategists contend that D'Amato is so concerned
about his weak approval ratings that he has done his best to avoid
public events in New York, even to the point of not appearing in
his own television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man's been there 18 years,'' said Hank Morris, Schumer's
media consultant. ``He has a negative rating. And his handlers are
smart enough that they don't want to remind people of him. He knows
he can't win an up or down vote on him. He has to try to turn this
into two bad choices.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato's campaign Thursday released a study of the Judiciary
Committee votes Schumer had missed, showing that he had
participated in only 21 of 267 votes this year. Among those he
missed were votes on bills dealing with sexual abuse of children,
anti-drug-abuse programs and parents who fail to pay child support.
</P>
</TEXT>
