<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CREDITCARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: COMPETITION FOR CREDIT CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Oct. 9:
</P>
<P>
   Americans are bombarded constantly by telephone and mail
solicitations for credit cards, offering all sorts of incentives to
apply. So it may be hard for many to believe that Visa and
Mastercard, which dominate the field, are guilty of restricting the
choices for consumers, as the Justice Department charged in an
antitrust suit filed this week. But the department has marshaled
impressive evidence that these two credit card companies have
conspired to stifle competition between themselves and keep other
competitors out.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, when the credit card phenomenon got under way,
each bank offered either Visa or Mastercard. But in the years
since, banks have generally offered both on the same terms. The
core of the antitrust argument is that because Visa and Mastercard
are both effectively owned by the same large alliances of banks,
they have little incentive to improve services and win customers
away from each other, since doing so would simply siphon profits
from one network into the other.
</P>
<P>
   Many banks are also barred by the terms of their Visa and
Mastercard agreements from offering any other cards, like American
Express or Discover, according to the department. The suit argues
further that if there had been more competition between them, Visa
and Mastercard would have offered many new services by now,
including ``smart cards'' with stored information like airline and
hotel preferences, identification codes, medical data and the like.
Plans for such technology were shelved by Mastercard after Visa
said it was opposed to introducing such a product, according to the
suit.
</P>
<P>
   These are serious charges that deserve scrutiny in court. The
credit card industry argues that there is already plenty of
competition among banks on credit terms for their cards, and says
that is the reason their credit cards generally require no annual
fees and provide tens of thousands of dollars worth of unsecured
credit.
</P>
<P>
   The credit card companies contend that government intervention
in an already competitive marketplace could prove disruptive. But
at a time of growing consolidation in the financial services
industry, the Justice Department is right to be concerned that
competition among cards not be constrained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 0006EDT &QL; 
