<HEADER>
A7735 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CLINTON-IMPEACH-     10-09 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLINTON-IMPEACH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A GRIM BUT HISTORIC DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Oct. 9:
</P>
<P>
   By becoming the third president to face an impeachment inquiry,
Bill Clinton has secured an unfortunate historic distinction that
he provoked with reckless personal actions and self-defeating
political and legal tactics. But he was able to forestall the wave
of defections that the White House had feared. In the end, only 31
Democrats crossed over to vote for the Republican resolution that
passed 258 to 176. The debate was harsh, but at last the road ahead
is clear. While the Democrats favored a shorter, less expansive
inquiry, they in effect conceded that the nation deserves a formal
conclusion to the charges of lying under oath, witness-tampering
and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   That is the proper direction. Absent a negotiated settlement,
the debate over whether Clinton's behavior is merely unwise or
violative of the law and the Constitution needs to move forward on
the path provided by the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The vote highlighted a striking and probably permanent reality
of this president's image. As a political personality, Clinton has
been stripped of defenders in the Congress or outside it. One of
his most dogged House supporters, Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, called
Clinton's behavior ``outrageous, reprehensible and disappointing.''
The prominent New Yorkers who ran an ad in this newspaper earlier
this week defending Clinton against impeachment nonetheless noted
that the president had ``destroyed his own dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   The real importance of the vote was that it allows a weighing of
the legal and constitutional implications of this much-condemned
behavior. It also provided a more orderly forum for other questions
of considerable weight, including the issues of prosecutorial
conduct and invasion of privacy that worry many citizens.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's debate on the legal case, the essence of the
Democratic argument remained that Clinton's behavior was repugnant
but that his was an individual failing rather than an offense
against the state that warrants removal from office. As its most
elemental, the Republican response is that by lying under oath and
sending others out to make sworn statements he knew to be false the
president failed in his constitutional duty to see that the laws
are faithfully executed.
</P>
<P>
   On the evidence so far, we regard Clinton's false testimony as
an offense against the rule of law that Congress cannot ignore. In
a nation whose legal system depends on sworn testimony and where
plain citizens are prosecuted for lying, there cannot be a special
standard for presidents who lie under oath. That has led this page
and many citizens of all stations to advocate a censure conditioned
on Clinton's admission of lying under oath and provided that we
have seen the worst evidence against him. But we accept the
political reality that a plea bargain is not likely before the Nov.
3 election.
</P>
<P>
   The public is clearly getting used to the idea of slogging on
with a flawed leader, and an impeachment inquiry could allow for a
valuable airing of other issues. We take seriously the debates over
Kenneth Starr's tactics, over whether the investigation of Clinton
raises privacy dangers for the general society and whether Clinton
has been denied the rights of a common citizen.
</P>
<P>
   On these issues it is important to remember how Congress arrived
at the point of having to vote on an impeachment inquiry. By
settling on a strategy of personal attacks, lying and possibly
enlisting others in those enterprises rather than settling the
Paula Jones lawsuit, Clinton embarked on a course that seriously
distended the legal system. His personal privacy was intact until
he invited a discovery process in which he knew he would have to
dissemble to hide his reckless stewardship of his office. As the
Democrats repeatedly noted Thursday, the president has said he is
sorry. But the House correctly said that is not enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
