r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     10-09 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARIYA SHAKEN, STIRRED, READY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paul Kariya's life was rended by a temblor so terrible that the
aftershocks continue to reverberate throughout the NHL. In fewer
seconds than it took a Northridge apartment complex to crumble, the
career of one of hockey's designated guardians was cleaved from its
foundations.
</P>
<P>
   The epicenter was the Arrowhead Pond, on Feb. 1. Defenseman Gary
Suter, then with the Chicago Blackhawks, cross-checked Kariya in
the jaw after the league's preeminent left winger had scored. It
would be a few minutes before Kariya woozily got up and a few
months before the fog that settled inside his head totally lifted.
</P>
<P>
   He sat out the remainder of the season, struggling to shake the
cumulative effects of his fourth concussion. The 23-year-old will
be back on the ice when the Mighty Ducks open their sixth season
Saturday at Washington, D.C., for the same reason most of us
returned to our homes after the 1994 Northridge earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   You live in Southern California, you resign yourself to the fact
the earth beneath your feet is going to shake now and then. You
play hockey for a living, you figure you're going to get hit.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya is aware of the risks he is taking by returning to the
ice. How can he sugarcoat his circumstances when a respected expert
in the field of brain injuries has come right out and said he would
advise him not to play?
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, Kariya is not ready to pull up the skates on a
career he has been building since he was a teen-ager in Vancouver,
B.C. So he is going to continue on as he did before Suter's blow
and leave the worrying to the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (another concussion) happens, it happens, and I'll have to
deal with it at that time,'' Kariya said recently at the Ducks'
practice facility in Anaheim. ``So far, I feel great. I don't even
think about what happened. It's totally out of my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Or would be, anyway, if reporters didn't continue to ask about
it. The fact is, head injuries are a legitimate concern in the NHL.
Pat LaFontaine, a diminutive (5-foot-10) dervish the same as
Kariya, recently announced his retirement after suffering his sixth
concussion.
</P>
<P>
   How many more skaters will be lost before the players stop
swinging their sticks like baseball bats? The league has notified
teams that it intends to mete out severe discipline for any
deliberate action by a player that is directed to the head of an
opponent or results in a head injury.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably that means no more puny four-game suspensions like
the one Suter served for his crosscheck on Kariya. And yet there's
reason to wonder if the seriousness of the situation is escaping
notice by everybody from the NHL front office types on down.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Tampa Bay left wing Andrei Nazarov cross-checked
Florida center Rob Niedermayer in the back of the head. The NHL
should have acted swiftly to suspend Nazarov, especially
considering Niedermayer suffered two concussions that sidelined him
for most of last season.
</P>
<P>
   But the league did nothing, making you wonder how meaningful are
the NHL's own missives. The league's silence this week has been
like a cross-check to the gut of Niedermayer, who wonders what
it'll take for the NHL to start protecting its most valuable
investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Kariya is) a draw, somebody fans want to watch,''
Niedermayer, who was selected directly after Kariya in the 1993
draft, told the Sun-Sentinel. ``And you have guys who can't even
play the game just skating around and hitting these people. It's
ridiculous. If they (gave stiffer penalties) it would make these
guys think twice about doing something stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Kariya has the right idea, calling for the abolishment of
the instigator penalty so players are free to police the ice
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody has got to play the bad cop. If it's not going to be
Colin Campbell, the league's new director of hockey operations,
then why not the likes of newly acquired Ducks enforcers Stu
Grimson and Jim McKenzie?
</P>
<P>
   Grimson, aka ``The Grim Reaper,'' was part of the inaugural
Ducks team in 1993-94. Before being traded to Detroit in April of
1995, Grimson dressed alongside Kariya for 31 games during Kariya's
rookie season. The Ducks made an offseason deal with the Carolina
Hurricanes to get Grimson back to watch Kariya's back.
</P>
<P>
   The Kariya who Grimson first got to know took hockey so
seriously he seldom permitted himself a smile. The player he
returned to find is much more approachable.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the first thing I noticed about Paul when I came
back,'' Grimson said. ``He's still very intense but he has found a
way to enjoy himself at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, you'd have to be a Buckingham Palace guard not to laugh
in the presence of fun-loving forward Teemu Selanne, who led the
Ducks in scoring last season. But there's more to the unbuttoning
of Kariya than that. He can't help but revel in where he is,
considering where he came from.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time in April when the headaches seemed to get worse
instead of better, making Kariya confront the possibility of a life
without hockey. ``I don't know what I would have done,'' he said.
``It's basically been my life.''
</P>
<P>
   The hope here is that it remains so for a long time. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 0008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
