<SLUG> BC-PHOENIX-OZONE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR QUALITY IN PHOENIX STILL FALLING SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY JO PITZL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite recent reports that Phoenix has cleaned up its summer
air pollution, a new, stricter federal ozone standard is expected
to show that the air continues to harm people with respiratory
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix area would have violated the new standard 36 times
from May through July, according to a report released by the U.S.
Public Interest Research Group and its Arizona affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The frequently asked question is, `Is Arizona's air getting
better?' '' said Carl Perry, the group's Arizona organizer. ``And
the answer is, `Not yet.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Valley's success in meeting the existing federal standard
for ozone has suggested that the quality of the region's air is
improving. For the second summer in a row, levels of ozone stayed
below the maximum level allowed by the federal Environmental
Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
   But clean-air advocates say the new rule, which will take effect
in 2000, more accurately reflects ozone's toll on health.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to do today is declare a state of
emergency,'' said David Feuerherd, program director for the
American Lung Association of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The research group, which analyzed air-quality data from 41
states and the District of Columbia, reported at least 5,208
violations throughout the nation between April 5 and Sept. 14 of
this year. California led the states with 1,025 violations. North
Carolina was second, at 517.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona had far fewer _ 41, including five in Yuma. The
measurements in Arizona were taken during three months this summer,
rather than five as in most other states.
</P>
<P>
   Feuerherd reeled off a list of things the Arizona Legislature
could do to cut down on ozone-forming emissions, ranging from
tighter vehicle-emissions standards, to getting old cars off the
road, to banning such gas-powered lawn equipment as mowers and leaf
blowers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Angie Weaver of Phoenix said she suffered from the
effects of ozone, even though this was supposed to be a clean
summer in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   A smoker who lived in smoggy Los Angeles, Weaver said she didn't
come down with asthmatic conditions until she moved to Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I experienced symptoms was this summer,'' she
said. She now uses an inhaler and stays indoors during extreme
temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver, who since has quit smoking, said her doctor attributed
her asthmatic condition in part to the Valley's smog and dust.
</P>
<P>
   The report's authors examined local air pollution data from this
summer and projected how it would measure up to the new standard.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new standard, air is considered dangerously polluted
when concentrations of smog reach .085 parts per million during an
eight-hour period. The idea is to mirror real life by setting the
health standard for prolonged exposure to the pollutant. The
current standard is 0.12 parts per million over one hour.
</P>
<P>
   Perry acknowledged that no matter when the new rule kicks in,
the pollution is there for people to breathe.
</P>
<P>
   ``A mountain of evidence showed the old standard didn't
adequately protect public health,'' he said. Based on that, the EPA
adopted the tougher standard last year.
</P>
<P>
   The report's findings are consistent with those of the Arizona
Department of Environmental Quality.
</P>
<P>
   Local regulators say they don't know what could be done to bring
the area into compliance under the new standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phoenix, clearly, is going to be non-attainment,'' said Gary
Neuroth, air-quality assesment manager at DEQ. ``Yuma, it's
questionable. And Tucson, too.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jo Pitzl can be reached at 444-8963 or at
maryjo.pitzl(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 0012EDT &QL; 
