<SLUG> BC-BBN-PADRES-BRAVES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN DOMINATES BRAVES ON 3-HITTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Braves pitchers Greg Maddux, Tom Glavine and
John Smoltz have six Cy Young Awards between them. Kevin Brown has
none, but it doesn't keep him from outpitching the Braves aces when
it counts the most.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's October supremacy over the Braves continued last night
with perhaps his best performance yet, a three-hit shutout that
carried the San Diego Padres to a 3-0 victory in Game 2 of the
National League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   The victory gave the Padres a 2-0 lead in the best-of-seven
series with the next three games scheduled for San Diego's Qualcomm
Stadium. The possibility exists that the 43,083 fans at Turner
Field last night, many of whom turned a cold shoulder by booing the
Braves in the eighth inning, might have seen baseball live for the
last time in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``What more could you ask for than this,'' Brown said. ``This
was huge. It's a real moral victory to come in here and play this
well against a team the caliber of the Braves and the type of
pitching they have. It speaks to the heart and character of this
team to come in here and not be intimidated.''
</P>
<P>
   Braves manager Bobby Cox acknowledged, ``You can't feel good
being down 0-2 but we have the type of ballclub and the type of
pitching that can reel off four in a row. Rather be 2-0 than 0-2,
but I think we can still rally back.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who beat the Braves twice in last year's NLCS while with
the Marlins, dominated this game like the big boy on the block
dominates Little League. Not only did he completely overwhelm the
Braves with his pitching, but he also had two singles that figured
prominently in all the Padres scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Gomez, Brown and Quilvio Veras had three consecutive
two-out singles in the sixth to score a run and break up 0-0 duel
between Brown and Glavine. Brown then led off the ninth with a
single, and the Padres gave him a cushion by scoring two more runs
that inning.
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely he needed them. Brown started the game by striking
out the side in the first inning and ended it by getting Chipper
Jones on a weak grounder and striking out Andres Galarraga and Ryan
Klesko in the ninth. The rest of the night was more of the same.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown said he wasn't as good last night as he was in a
16-strikeout performance against Houston in Game 1 of the
Padres-Astros divisional series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to make adjustments and go with what was
working for me at the time,'' Brown said. ``Facing a team like the
Braves, with the type of club they have, I was trying a variety of
things, throwing everything up there but the kitchen sink. I was
making stuff up as I went along.''
</P>
<P>
   There were just two shaky moments. He walked Galarraga and
Klesko to start the second, but got Javier Lopez to hit into a
double play and Andruw Jones to ground out to shortstop. Brown also
threw a wild pitch that put runners on second and third in the
fourth before retiring Javier Lopez on a weak pop to left, ending
the threat.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves managed just three singles, a couple of grounders by
Chipper Jones and Glavine that found a hole and a weak roller by
pinch-hitter Greg Colbrunn that third baseman Ken Caminiti couldn't
come up with in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who retired 14 of the last 15 hitters he faced, walked
three and struck out 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched him pitch the no-hitter against the Giants on
television, and I thought he had the same kind of stuff tonight
that he did in that game,'' Cox said. ``Against us, this was the
best he's ever thrown. I know my club, we were trying like crazy,
we just couldn't touch this guy. Houston has one of the best
hitting clubs in the league and they couldn't touch him \Rin the
division series\S either.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
