<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESPN-STORES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY BRAND SET TO EXPAND WITH ESPN STORES' OPENING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Walt Disney Co., continuing aggressive expansion
of its lucrative ESPN brand, plans to open two more ESPN stores
next month in Southern California, the Daily News has learned.
</P>
<P>
   The stores -- replete with video monitors, team apparel,
interactive kiosks and collectibles -- will open at the Del Amo
Fashion Center in Torrance and the Main Place at Santa Ana, a
Disney representative confirmed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The original ESPN -- The Store opened a year ago at the Glendale
Galleria shopping center. Disney officials have reported strong
results from the 4,000-square-foot location and the new stores will
closely resemble the prototype.
</P>
<P>
   Burbank-based Disney, widely regarded as the ablest marketer
among entertainment conglomerates, has been trying for the past
year to make the sports cable network and its logo ubiquitous by
launching retailing, restaurants and publishing operations. An
industry tracker said ESPN, which gears broadcasts toward the
coveted segment of males between 18 and 34, has plenty of room for
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, by extending the brand further into retail stores,
they're still not in any danger of overexposure,'' said retail
consultant Mark Kissel of Rockville, Md. ``More stores are a way to
further leverage what Disney's already got.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN, with 75 million U.S. subscribers and three cable
affiliates, has been by far the most valuable part of Disney's $19
billion acquisition of Capital Cities/ABC in 1996. Analysts have
forecast ESPN, which peppers telecasts with humor and insider
jargon, will generate more than $600 million in operating profit on
revenues of nearly $2 billion this year -- profits well above any
of the three major networks.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's decision to boost ESPN's exposure comes a month after
it announced a deal with Sears to open 450 ESPN shops within Sears
stores by next spring. It launched ESPN Magazine in March and the
ESPN Zone restaurant in June in Baltimore and plans to open
eateries next year in Chicago and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Disney executives have said they plan to open hundreds of ESPN
stores in the coming years but have not been more specific.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they choose to saturate the market and go into every
regional mall, it could cut a new frontier for sporting goods
stores,'' Kissel said. ``The idea of combining an electronic
broadcast product with apparel is very clever, because those are
two types of products that are more and more dependent on each
other. Selling team apparel is entrenched; it's gone from wearing
something for a school you like to wearing something because you
like the colors.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately held Hearst Corp. owns 20 percent of ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
