<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7756 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     10-09 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALONE CONFIDENT HE CAN LURE ALOU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kevin Malone heard the Montreal Expos plea to Felipe Alou. He
has heard it before.
</P>
<P>
   Big dreams of a big stadium and the chance to build the Expos
into a championship team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sadly, that is one of the reasons I left Montreal,'' said
Malone, the Expos general manager in 1994-95 and now the Dodgers
GM. ``They were always excited about the future but the future
never came.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone, however, also knows he was just passing through when he
was in Montreal. Alou, 63, has been with the organization for 24
years and is its most popular figure.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers new GM remains confident he can make Alou his
team's next manager by the end of the World Series, even though the
Expos say they will do whatever it takes to keep him in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sensitive to Felipe's concerns, that he wants to do
right by his family and his friends in Montreal,'' said Malone, who
has spent the past three days in the Dominican Republic speaking to
Alou. ``I believe he will make the right decision. He is encouraged
and excited about the opportunities of the Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a lifestyle decision as much as anything. But even
though he is known as a great manager and developer of talent, I
think at this stage of his career, he wants to win a World Series.
We offer him that chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday in Montreal, the cost-conscious Expos unveiled a new
plan to extend the deadline for funding a new downtown stadium and
get Alou to be there when it opens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is not an issue,'' said Expos general manager Jim
Beattie, who insists the Expos plan to match any offer the Dodgers
make Alou. ``We are going to try our damnedest to keep him in
Montreal.''
</P>
<P>
   With two teams aggressively pursuing Alou, the contract offers
could go pretty high. On Monday, the Colorado Rockies signed
manager Jim Leyland to a three-year contract worth $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Four days earlier, Leyland opted out of the final three years
and $4.5 million with the Florida Marlins, where he won the World
Series last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think those numbers will have an impact on the market
because everything is like free agency now,'' Malone said. ``But I
don't see those kinds of numbers here, although I don't think this
will come down to a money issue with Felipe.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers can offer Alou the luxury of a $75 million
payroll and the nearly unlimited financial resources of Rupert
Murdoch's NewsCorp. Last season, the Expos had a payroll of $13
million, which was not expected to rise in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Montreal has traded many of Alou's top players,
including Pedro Martinez, Larry Walker, Marquis Grissom and John
Wetteland to keep the Expos' bottom line near the bottom of the
major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   But with the blessing of new commissioner Bud Selig, who was in
Montreal last week when the new ballpark appeared dead, the Expos
now have five more months to raise money.
</P>
<P>
   They also appear ready to infuse capital into the club by adding
several new owners. Claude Brochu, who has served as the mouthpiece
for the organization despite owning just 7.6 percent of the club,
will be bought out, according to sources.
</P>
<P>
   Brochu originally attempted to get $150 million from the
government, $75 million from the province of Quebec and $75 million
from the federal government. That plan was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new plan, the government would kick in a total of $75
million, with the new owner putting in the rest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
