<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7758 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ASU-ARIZONA &UR; TV-AZ     10-09 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-ARIZONA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRISH HOT TICKET; ABC IRKS UA 
</HEADLINE>
  TV-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Notre Dame's football team arrived Thursday night in the Valley,
where tickets are hot, and so are Arizona fans and officials.
</P>
<P>
   Brokers are receiving up to $350 for tickets to Saturday's
sold-out game between the Fighting Irish and Arizona State at Sun
Devil Stadium. The game will be televised by ABC, whose decision to
select it over Arizona-UCLA has irked Wildcats supporters, who
believe the meeting between the nation's No. 3 and No. 10 teams
deserves top billing.
</P>
<P>
   ASU's policy for this game was to offer the tickets to only
season-ticket holders, leaving Notre Dame's legion of fans
scrambling.
</P>
<P>
   The Notre Dame alumni club of Phoenix has 1,600 members.
Thousands of other graduates live in the Valley, not to mention
Notre Dame's famous (or infamous) ``Subway Alumni.'' Some bought
season tickets just so they could attend the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still getting a lot of calls, people trying to buy and
sell,'' said Pat Dugan, spokesman for the Phoenix alumni club. ``We
have ASU season-ticket holders trying to sell their tickets, but we
won't take their name if they're selling for over face value.''
</P>
<P>
   Ticket agencies are selling tickets from $45 to $350. None would
go on the record because of a recent decision among the owners to
not speak to the media, but several said privately that sales have
been strong and availability has been good. ASU's disappointing 2-3
start may have prompted some fair-weather season-ticket holders to
seek a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets also are being offered in classified ads for up to $400.
</P>
<P>
   Media interest in the game is high. Arizona State has issued
about 450 credentials for the contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It provides a national forum to showcase ASU football and the
university,'' ASU Athletic Director Kevin White said.
</P>
<P>
   Which is precisely what irritates Arizona Athletic Director Jim
Livengood. He was told last week by ABC that the network would wait
until after the Wildcats' game against Washington last Saturday
night to make a decision. But while watching the ASU-USC game
Saturday afternoon, Livengood noticed ABC already was promoting the
ASU-Notre Dame game for the following weekend. The Fighting Irish
had defeated Stanford earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I handle news pretty good when somebody's up-front with me,''
Livengood said. ``But don't tell me you're going to wait and then
promote it. Notre Dame won, and they made their decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a big boy in terms of television, and I understand how
things work. But it really is odd how they handled it. This is a
big game in terms of history of the Pac-10.''
</P>
<P>
   FoxSportsNet immediately jumped on the game, which also is a
sellout, and Livengood emphasized that's he's not disappointed by
that. ``Arizona and the Pac-10 have been wonderful partners with
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ABC has been besieged by calls from fans wanting an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, it was a decision made with great reluctance,''
said Tim Pernetti, ABC's director of programming. ``In a perfect
world, we'd show both games. This was a clear case of damned if we
do, damned if we don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Pernetti said his decision was based on two factors: market
saturation and ratings. ASU-Notre Dame won on both counts.
</P>
<P>
   At least 43 percent of the country will get this contest.
Because of Notre Dame's appeal, it will land in the Chicago and New
York markets as well as the West. The UCLA-Arizona game would have
saturated only the Pac-10 markets, which is about 20 percent of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   More homes will actually have the game available since Fox's
broadcast will be national, but the prestige of being seen on ABC,
with its top broadcast team of Keith Jackson and Bob Griese, and an
earlier start (12:30 vs. 7:15 p.m), is what irked some.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never even occurred to me it wouldn't be on ABC,'' said
Terry Braden, 27, of Casa Grande. ``I have to work. And I'm one of
those rare breeds that don't have cable.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Pernetti, ``We saw it as one of the first real big tests
for Notre Dame, and we saw that ASU was starting to bounce back. It
has the makings of an exciting game.''
</P>
<P>
   Each team will receive approximately $275,000 from ABC. Fox's
payout is about $175,000 per team. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
