<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7762 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BICKLEY_COYOTES-A     10-09 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BICKLEY_COYOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME, THEY REALLY WANT TO WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Keith Tkachuk is on his best behavior. Polite as an English
butler. Smiling as if he'd been given a midnight reprieve from the
governor.
</P>
<P>
   He has heard the boos, has accepted the wrath and is determined
to prove he deserves the big letter on his sweater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a human being. Of course, it hurts,'' Tkachuk said. ``But
I understand how they feel, and I know I have to produce to get
them back.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Smith has performed all the necessary surgeries. His
defense is completely revamped. His offense has improved. His
coaching staff has pulled in the reins on an undisciplined outfit,
one that won't spend most of the season killing penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the ingredients are in place,'' the general manager said.
``With enough firepower on the first two lines, with enough role
players and character guys, with the best defense we've had since
I've been here, we could be a very good team.''
</P>
<P>
   Nikolai Khabibulin, whose pride was pierced last season, is
determined to prove he's a top-flight goalie. Brad Isbister has
bulked up significantly, no longer awed by the company he keeps.
The pedigree of Rick Tocchet has started to rub off. And Jeremy
Roenick has rededicated himself to the pursuit of greatness,
spending most of the summer lifting weights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked out until I cried,'' he said. ``And I worked out
until I puked.''
</P>
<P>
   It all sounds wonderful. Except for one thing.
</P>
<P>
   You get zero points for talking. You get nothing for potential,
get nowhere on paper.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for the Coyotes to prove they can play a good game,
too. Starting Sunday. And lasting for the duration of the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   Entering their third season in the Valley, it appears the
Coyotes have grown from their mistakes. They have acknowledged that
chemistry and teamwork mean something in the chase for the Cup.
They understand the previous level of commitment was a few notches
short of championship material. They realize they can't slog
through the regular season and expect to pull the switch when it
matters.
</P>
<P>
   They have learned the hard way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bottom line, we have to get home ice,'' Tkachuk said.
``Finishing in the top four is definitely our goal.''
</P>
<P>
   As well it should be. In the Western Conference, Detroit and
Dallas share the pedestal. Colorado lost defenseman Uwe Krupp but
still is loaded. Beyond that, it's wide open, and there's no reason
the Coyotes can't outpoint Los Angeles, St. Louis or Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Anything less would be a disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   You can count on a few things entering a pivotal season. The
Coyotes won't lose 473 man-games to injury. Roenick will not be
held under 60 points again. And with two of the most skilled
defensive lines in the NHL, the odd-man rush won't be a nightly
hazard.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're in every game with a good defense,'' Smith said.
``Teams without a skilled defense play a territory game. It's
almost like a punt, flipping the puck out and hoping for the best.
Now, you'll see us control the puck a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Another thing: Tkachuk knows he's under the microscope, that the
value of his leadership is in question. He knows he has to correct
an image problem threatening to overshadow his game.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Tkachuk is trying hard. He has even given a bedroom to
Daniel Briere, the wunderkind who should make an impact this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what it was like when I was that age, living by myself.
It's no fun, especially when you're in a hotel,'' Tkachuk said.
</P>
<P>
   It's no fun losing in the first round of the playoffs, either.
No fun carrying the label as one of the biggest underachievers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make it past the first round, and I'm looking way
beyond that,'' Tkachuk said.
</P>
<P>
   Talking like champions, too. But once the puck drops Sunday, the
words will mean nothing. The excuses will have expired. And it will
be time for the perennial playoff patsies to change their woeful
image. For good. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
