A7763 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LOW-POWER-COX     10-09 0464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOW-POWER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves' big guns face power outage
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_ The heavy lumber in the Braves' batting order has been
hollow as a carved-out pumpkin. Andres Galarraga, Chipper Jones,
Ryan Klesko and Javy Lopez might as well had been swinging forks in
the opening two games of the NLCS against San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Start right there when looking for reasons why Atlanta faces an
imposing 0-2 series deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's futility in losing 3-0 in Game 2 to
frighteningly awesome Kevin Brown was in keeping with the meat of
the lineup's continued ineptitude since bumping off the inferior
Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Check it out: In the two games, the quartet of big boppers
produced three hits _ all singles _ in 28 at-bats. Worse, they
drove in exactly zero runs, several times failing with runners in
scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating because I know our offense is better than
that,'' said Klesko, who had no hits in two at-bats with three
walks. ``We just didn't get anything going.''
</P>
<P>
   Not much at all. Jones, the No. 3 batter, has a single in eight
tries, but nothing with men on base. He had a long out to center in
the sixth that threatened the seats. It was one of two balls hit
``good all night,'' manager Bobby Cox said. The other was a line
single by pitcher Tom Glavine in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see the best pitching in the postseason,'' Braves hitting
coach Clarence Jones said. ``That's why they're in the playoffs.
(The Padres) have been pitching good. What can you say?''
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga has not said much with his bat. He has no hits in
eight at-bats. He has struck out four times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing,'' the Big Cat said of his kitten-like
performance. ``But I will stay positive. We're probably going to
turn it around on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the hope, anyway. Lopez, a perennial postseason producer,
hoped his bouncer in the second inning would find the outfield.
Instead, it turned into a double play that killed a potential
rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not working out in our favor right now,'' Lopez
said.
</P>
<P>
   Good pitching overcomes good hitting, the axiom goes. And that
has held true to form for the beleaguered Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he pitches outstanding,'' centerfielder Andruw Jones
said, ``you struggle. And we struggled.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had won 10 in a row coming in here and we had hit the ball
pretty good,'' Cox said. ``(Game 1 starter Andy) Ashby, I thought,
was tough. And this guy tonight (Brown) was even tougher. We had
him in trouble with a couple of walks a couple of times. But we
couldn't get the ball to fall in. We just need to hit the ball
better. Getting one run a night is not going to cut it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
