<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7764 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-PADRES2-COX     10-09 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PADRES2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves get 3 hits in 3-0 loss, trail 2-0
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Forty-eight hours ago, they had the right opponent,
had the pitching rigged like a nicked deck and they owned the home
field.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, the Atlanta Braves have none of those things. Only
trouble. Deep, wide trouble.
</P>
<P>
   In what has become his autumnal rite, Kevin Brown again
paralyzed the Braves on a three-hitter Thursday night to allow the
San Diego Padres to beat Atlanta 3-0, leaving a dark funk over a
Braves team thought by many to be the best assembled. But by the
time this one was over, the same team looked liked it just fell off
the bus from Greenville. A four-hit, one-error, two-run top of the
ninth had fumigated Turner Field like a roach bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a position you want to be in,'' said losing pitcher
Tom Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   This hole is a deep one. The Braves trail the NLCS 0-2, which no
Braves team has done during this run through the 1990s. Since the
playoffs began in 1969, 11 teams have won the first two games of
the NLCS. Only two of those failed to advance to the World Series
(1984 Cubs and 1985 Dodgers). Worse, no team that lost the first
two games at home has ever recovered to win an NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   After traveling west today, the series resumes in San Diego on
Saturday night, with Greg Maddux (18-9) facing Sterling Hitchcock
(9-7).
</P>
<P>
   ``They did it to us,'' catcher Javy Lopez said, ``so we can do
it to them. No doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably we'll turn it around on the road,'' Andres Galarraga
said. ``Probably we'll play better there.''
</P>
<P>
   Not unless the middle of the Braves order regains consciousness.
Galarraga, Chipper Jones and Ryan Klesko are a combined 1-for-21 in
this series while the Braves have squeezed out merely two runs in
19 innings. Braves starters have allowed three earned runs thus far
and it hasn't mattered, the Padres earning their fourth postseason
win when scoring three runs or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it's the best-of-seven,'' Padres manager Bruce Bochy
said. ``The two games, you haven't done anything yet. We know
there's still a lot of baseball left. It's nice to win two games
here but we still have to go home and continue to play the way
we're playing right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres left the Braves in shambles, the San Diego ninth
making a farce of what had been a one-run game. Lopez's throwing
error (trying to pick off Brown at second on consecutive pitches)
opened the way, spicing a string of singles, said less about how
the Padres won and more of how the Braves lost. Another sparse
gallery of 43,083 paused to boo on the way out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're not there now, I don't know what it takes to get
our backs against the wall,'' said Glavine, who joined Jerry Reuss
as the only pitchers to lose seven NLCS games. ``It's not an
enviable position to be in, down 0-2 going to the other ballpark.
But it wasn't too long ago that we were up 2-0 in a World Series
and wound up being swept. It can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Not as long as Brown is around. He beat the Braves for the sixth
straight time, including three straight NLCS victories dating back
to his Florida tenure last October. Glavine gave up six walks and
six hits and still allowed just one sixth-inning run but was
overshadowed by the Padres starter. Brown allowed just three
singles while striking out 11.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves left three men in scoring position and Brown bore
down harder as he went, retiring 13 of the last 14 men he faced.
Not that he could explain what he was doing to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the fact that I had a variety of stuff,'' Brown said.
``I wasn't trying to stay with any one thing. I think I threw
everything but the kitchen sink at 'em out there tonight. Just
winging it, make stuff up as you go.''
</P>
<P>
   So will the Braves, who lost two of their three games at
Qualcomm Stadium this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were down 3-1 to the Cardinals (in 1996 and won),'' said
manager Bobby Cox. ``And with this club, we have the type of
pitching and I think we've got the hitting, once it gets going, we
could do that. It's that type of club.''
</P>
<P>
   Not the last two games.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
