<HEADER>
A7766 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-ARIZONASTATE-WULK     10-09 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRAISE POURS IN FOR WULK  
 ASU COURT NAMING IS CALLED OVERDUE 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-WULK-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ned Wulk always seemed more at home talking himself down, as
opposed to up, so it wasn't a big surprise that when asked about
his legacy, he sort of groped and fumbled for an answer without
really finding one.
</P>
<P>
   But he had no trouble recalling the time when he was the head
basketball coach at Arizona State and someone threw a wadded-up
paper cup at him during a game at Wyoming, and he returned the fire
and accidentally hit the team bus driver, who wanted to keep Wulk
off the bus. Or the time he drop-kicked a chair into the mezzanine.
Or the time. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Stories, not speeches, suited Wulk best, and plenty were going
around Thursday at ASU when it was officially announced that the
floor at Wells Fargo Arena will be named Ned Wulk Court during
dedication ceremonies on March 6.
</P>
<P>
   When that happens, it will be almost 17 years to the day in 1982
that Wulk was fired by a university vice president, long since gone
from the scene, who never bothered to inform Wulk directly, thus
ending a 25-year, 406-victory tenure that spanned presidents from
Eisenhower to Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   You think Roger Maris' home run record stood a long time?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to retire here,'' new ASU Coach Rob Evans told Wulk and
a gathering that included old friends and coaching colleagues such
as Bill Kajikawa (football) and Baldy Castillo (track), and former
players. ``But I think you can feel safe that your 406 wins are
safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans, facing the latest in a series of rebuilding jobs since
Wulk's departure, represents the present and the future of Sun
Devils basketball. Naming the court is a sturdy bridge to the past.
</P>
<P>
   Wulk is the biggest piece of that past.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long time in coming,'' Athletic Director Kevin White
said. ``It's terribly befitting.''
</P>
<P>
   Wulk said: ``After a while . . . you feel like you didn't do
enough to warrant it.''
</P>
<P>
   That being said, this otherwise was a happy occasion for Wulk,
who is 78 and lives in Ahwatukee. So he broached the moment with a
still-impish sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first reaction I had was, `Boy, this is really gonna floor
me,' '' he said, clearly enjoying the pun.
</P>
<P>
   But seriously, folks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm overwhelmed,'' said Wulk.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidence or not, the court is being named during the first
full season the former University Activity Center gets a different
label, thanks to a healthy donation. Wulk didn't have to give any
money for his honor, merely the better part of his working life.
Completed in 1974 at the now ridiculous-sounding cost of $8
million, the Activity Center was built because ASU basketball under
Wulk had outgrown the old gym. Wulk had a lot to do with the
arena's design, especially the floor area.
</P>
<P>
   ``The building means a lot to me,'' he said. ``I spent an awful
lot of time (working) on this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his players, Art Becker, said Wulk should be remembered
for being an innovator. You know the Chicago Bulls' triangle
offense, the alleged brainchild of Tex Winter?
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran an offense similar to that in the 1960s,'' said Becker,
the athletic director at Scottsdale Community College.
</P>
<P>
   Up-tempo offense and trapping defense were Wulk hallmarks before
they became en vogue. He sprung something radical called a zone
press on a UCLA team coached by John Wooden, and ASU beat the
Bruins by 30. Evans played for New Mexico State against the Sun
Devils in the late '60s and recalls the relentless pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want our basketball team to exemplify the same effort and
toughness,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the prevalent assessment of Wulk relates to his
post-coaching days. Despite being suddenly and unceremoniously let
go five victories shy of 500 for his career (he also coached at
Xavier of Ohio), and despite his dismissal resulting in a reduced
pension that would cost him serious dollars the rest of his life,
he remains an avid and visible supporter of ASU.
</P>
<P>
   Wasn't it difficult?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said. ``I like basketball. I like ASU basketball, no
matter what.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
