<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SCHLOTTER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING ON A CRUZ FOR TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL SCHLOTTER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Camarillo drag racer Cruz Pedregon will be a busy
man over the final month of the NHRA season as he tries to put
himself back into contention for the Funny Car title.
</P>
<P>
   Pedregon, in fourth place with 249 points behind leader John
Force, will be at the Pennzoil Nationals in Memphis this weekend,
the Parts America Nationals in Topeka on Oct. 17, the Revell
Nationals in Dallas Oct. 22-25 and the Matco Tools Supernationals
in Houston Oct. 29-Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Between events, Pedregon will spend little time at home as he
tries to pull what began as a championship-caliber season back
together in time for the NHRA finale, the Winston Finals Nov. 12-15
at Pomona.
</P>
<P>
   Following the Fram Nationals back on April 20, Pedregon had two
of his three victories and was in first place in Funny Car points.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he has won just once despite qualifying first five
times in the ensuing 12 events.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a thousand ways to lose and only one way to win,''
said Pedregon, who has a penchant of late for qualifying high but
going out in early elimination rounds. ``It seems like we've
experienced all the ways to lose this year.''
</P>
<P>
   But through the losing, Pedregon said he and new crew chief Wes
Cerny are starting to come together as a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our first year with Wes,'' Pedregon said. ``And there
have been some instances where our being new to each other has
caused us to second-guess what we were doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Those days are gone, Pedregon said. Cerny has Pedregon's
Interstate Batteries car roaring.
</P>
<P>
   And Pedregon qualified first again last weekend at Topeka before
rain forced postponement of the event to later this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any problems ahead,'' Pedregon said. ``We need to
win and (the drivers in front of him) need to stumble a few times.
This car flies. There is no reason for us to believe we're not
still in this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   IRL finale: The Indy Racing League will celebrate the conclusion
of its third season and perhaps crown a new champion Sunday with
the running of the Las Vegas 500K at Las Vegas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Brack takes a 31-point lead into the event and needs to
finish eighth or better to guarantee himself the title.
</P>
<P>
   Runner-up Davey Hamilton and third-place Tony Stewart, who needs
Brack to wind up no better than 15th to have a chance, remain
mathematically in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Vacation is over:After a month's respite, the two-man points
battle for the NASCAR Winston West title resumes with the
Iomega/Fry's 100 Sunday at Sears Point Raceway in Sonoma.
</P>
<P>
   With three races remaining in the 14-event series, Palmdale's
Kevin Harvick has a 34-point lead over Valencia's Sean Woodside. In
third place, 215 points back of Harvick, is Gary Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Best of the Southwest: Granada Hills driver M.K. Kanke is one of
the veterans of the NASCAR Featherlite Southwest Tour. And as he
tries to pass Steve Portenga for the 1998 points title over the
season's final three races, he may also put his name in the tour
record book.
</P>
<P>
   In winning the pole at the Featherlite Trailer Manufacturers 125
in September, Kanke tied Ron Hornaday Jr. for the most poles
all-time with 19.
</P>
<P>
   And when he won the race, he moved into fifth place all-time in
wins (12), third on the all-time top-10 finishes list (76) and
second on the all-time top-five list (55).
</P>
<P>
   Kanke trails Portenga by 87 points. The next race is Oct. 16 at
Mesa Marin Speedway in Bakersfield.
</P>
<P>
   Like a jet: Four area jet ski racers will be at the
International Jet Sports Boating Association championships at Lake
Havasu next week.
</P>
<P>
   Racing in the Pro Runabout 1200 class will be Jason Howard of
Granada Hills, Paul Pistone of West Hills and Tom Powell of
Thousand Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   Entered in the Pro-Am Women's Runabout class is Jennifer Jeppson
of Thousand Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   The events run Sunday through Sunday, Oct. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Nuts and bolts: Retiring CART driver Bobby Rahal stopped by Los
Angeles' Petersen Automotive Museum Thursday to donate one of his
fireproof driver's suits.... Brazilian racing icon Emerson
Fittipaldi has signed a five-year contract to manage and promote
the CART Rio 400 in Rio de Janeiro.... Traditionally held in
November, the NHRA California Hot Rod Reunion will be held Oct.
16-18 this year to avoid conflicting with the NHRA's season-ending
event, the Winston Finals. The CHRR will be held at Famoso Raceway
in Bakersfield.... The Saugus Speedway Oldies and Goodies Classic
Car, Truck and Motorcycle Show has been rescheduled for Saturday,
Oct. 24. (4-10 p.m.) Information: (805) 259-3886.... Honda has
sewed up its second straight CART season manufacturer's title with
a total of 11 victories so far (six by Alex Zanardi, three by Dario
Franchitti and two by Jimmy Vasser).... Simi Valley's Alex Harris
won his eighth USAC three-quarters midget main event of the season
and has a 446-325 lead over Gene Godepski in season points....
Fontana's California Speedway has opened a racing theme restaurant
at Ontario International Airport called the California Speedway
Cafe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
