<HEADER>
A7778 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-DEFENSI     10-09 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-DEFENSIVE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CACTUS CURTAIN  
 FRONT 4 LIKENED TO BEST EVER 
</HEADLINE>
 LINE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a chance, as some Cardinals coaches suggest, that
Chicago Bears Coach Dave Wannstedt was just setting up the opponent
when he gushed about the Arizona defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best I've seen in a long time, since back in the
early '70s _ the Steel Curtain,'' Wannstedt said.
</P>
<P>
   So after five games, the Cardinals' defensive front of Andre
Wadsworth, Eric Swann, Mark Smith and Simeon Rice is being compared
to the Pittsburgh Steelers' Steel Curtain, which won four Super
Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   What about the Fearsome Foursome, Purple People Eaters and
Doomsday lines?
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, Mean Joe Greene is coaching their defensive
(linemen), and that speaks for itself,'' Wannstedt said. ``Those
guys are just phenomenal athletes. They could probably play
linebacker in somebody else's defensive scheme, that's how good and
athletic they are. They can change a game in a matter of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene, the Cardinals assistant and Hall of Famer with the
Steelers, laughed when told of Wannstedt's praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was sincere, but they have a long ways to go,'' Greene said
of the Cardinals' defensive line. ``They don't know one another.
They're starting to get to know each other. But they don't know
completely how the game should be played, how it is to be hunted.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past three weeks, the defensive line starters have had
nine sacks, six pass deflections, two fumble recoveries and one
forced fumble.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth, who has a team-high four sacks, has had two sacks in
two consecutive games, only the third Cardinals player to
accomplish that feat since the statistic was first recorded in the
early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cardinals have the potential to be the most dominating
front four in football,'' said Gary Horton, former Tampa Bay and
Cleveland scout who now is the editor of the ``War Room'' football
publication.
</P>
<P>
   There doesn't appear to be a defensive line that is clearly the
best in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay has the NFL's top rushing defense, but the Packers
were shredded through the air in Monday night's loss to Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Packers' line has been a pleasant surprise,'' said
Horton of a line that is led by Reggie White. ``But I think people
will take advantage of them as the year goes on. At times, I think
they will look tired and overmatched.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle, led by All-Pro defensive tackle Cortez Kennedy, also
has the AFC's co-sack leader in Mike Sinclair with seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``On paper, Seattle's line is very good,'' Horton said.
``Kennedy and (Sam) Adams are run stuffers. Sinclair is a great
edge pass rusher. But they also benefit from good linebacker play
and two good corners (Shawn Springs and Willie Williams).''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City has the NFL's best defense even without injured
tackle Chester McGlockton.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota has a star in John Randle, and Tampa Bay has the NFL's
best young tackle in Warren Sapp, but both teams' other linemen
aren't standouts.
</P>
<P>
   Other good lines include the New York Giants, paced by Mike
Strahan; New Orleans, led by Joe Johnson and Wayne Martin; and
Miami, which has huge defensive tackles in Tim Bowens and Daryl
Gardener and a speed pass rusher in Jason Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland Raiders executive Bruce Allen thinks none is as
potentially good as the Cardinals' line.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a (1997) Rookie of the Year in Simeon Rice, a
perennial All-Pro in Eric Swann and drafted a guy (Andre Wadsworth)
that some people are calling the next Bruce Smith,'' Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always said the Rams' Fearsome Foursome is the best ever,
but this has a chance to be just as dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals offensive tackle Lomas Brown, a seven-time Pro Bowl
performer, said Mark Smith ``is no slouch. He is just overshadowed
by everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a seventh-round pick a year ago, made the All-Rookie Team
last season with six sacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's starting to be the guy who makes the plays,'' Swann said.
``I'm the demolition expert. I'm the guy blowing things up. There's
no doubt Mark is going to be one of the leading defensive tackles
in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice said the Cardinals' line is still a long way from a
finished product.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're building, growing, evolving as a team,'' he said. ``Each
week, we're getting better. None of us has had a blockbuster game
yet. We've showed a lot of brilliance, but there is a big game
coming for each of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Horton said the Cardinals' front causes big match-up problems
for opposing offensive lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be when you played the Cardinals, you figured that
if you stopped Swann you could get everything done that you needed
to,'' Horton said. ``Then last year, if you took Swann or Rice out
of the game _ either one of them _ you were all right. Now, any one
of those (starters) can give you fits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, people were running at Rice. Now, if you do that,
Wadsworth is going to chase you down.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 0118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
