<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7780 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     10-09 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATLANTA _ Bob sells bicycles for a living, but come this time of
year his mind tends to wander.
</P>
<P>
   To the Braves. His Braves. There's nothing fair-weather about
Bob the fan, no matter how many times they have tested his devotion
to their usual lost playoffs cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lemme tell you,'' he said Thursday afternoon, shrugging off a
consoling comment regarding the unfortunate wee-hours outcome of
Game 1 of the National League Championship Series. ``We're gonna
put a whuppin' on that Georgia Tech boy tonight. You can go write
your story right now. `Braves beat Brown' _ that's your headline.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing Bob knows bikes. He wouldn't make a
comfortable living as a seer. I suppose we need to question his
memory as well.
</P>
<P>
   Bob had the whuppin' part right, except he had it backward. He
confused the ``whuppee'' with the ``whupper,'' whose name was Kevin
Brown. A Macon, Ga., resident in the winter, Brown now devotes his
autumns to makin' whoopee at the expense of Atlanta's big-league
team.
</P>
<P>
   Long ago, he did attend Georgia Tech. Now, because of him, the
Braves are rambling wrecks.
</P>
<P>
   Again.
</P>
<P>
   As a flu-bug-bitten Marlins mercenary a year ago, Brown beat
Atlanta twice in the NLCS, earning wins in the first and last
games. As a hale-and-hearty Padre, he did it once more this
evening, showing the Braves pretty much the same right stuff he
unleashed upon the Astros last week. If they gave a Cy Young Award
for the postseason, he would be well on his way to claiming it. His
ERA against the Astros was 0.61. His ERA against the Braves is
0.00.
</P>
<P>
   Adding insult to insult, Brown also managed one-third as many
hits as he gave Atlanta. His sixth-inning single was integral to
the Padres scoring the one run they needed in a 3-0 victory that
left the Braves in a possibly impossible place. Since the NLCS went
to its best-of-seven format in 1985, no team has recovered from
dropping the first two games at home.
</P>
<P>
   Brown struck out 21 Astros in 14 innings, including an almost
historic 16 in the opener at the Astrodome, a figure exceeded in
the playoffs only by a Mr. Bob Gibson. Then, to prove he really
meant it, Brown mowed down Braves Walt Weiss, Keith Lockhart and
Chipper Jones back-to-back-to-back in the first inning here.
</P>
<P>
   The game would conclude with consecutive whiffs of Andres
Galarraga and Ryan Klesko. While there was a minor wobble or two in
between, neither Brown's command nor his control was doubt. He has
four ``out'' pitches, ranging from a 96-mph running fastball to a
wicked, hooking slider, and Atlanta rarely had a decent look, or
cut, at any of them.
</P>
<P>
   Jones would rip a fly ball to the right-center warning track in
the sixth, but Steve Finley chugged over to flag it down. Of the
last 18 Atlantans to dare venture to the plate, 16 returned
directly to the dugout, seven with bats on their shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw everything at them except the kitchen sink,'' Brown
said. ``Just winging it, you know, making up stuff as you go,
really. I don't like to back off and look at the big picture. I try
to stay focused on the little things and minimize my mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't apply to his baserunning. He tried to take
third on Quilvio Veras' RBI single in the sixth and, even with a
foolhardy headfirst slide into the bag, was easily gunned down.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so Brown isn't perfect. Not that Bruce Bochy felt like
complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just how he plays the game _ all out,'' the Padres'
skipper said. ``He's a throwback. But, to be honest, he scares me
sometimes out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine how the other guys feel. The Braves, baseball's team of
the decade in every way except World Series championships
accumulated, brought a 10-0 run into their seventh NLCS in a row,
but they have run smack into the same immovable object that
abruptly terminated the Astros' best season ever.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the long-forgotten Friars, a non-factor in the
playoffs since being routed by the Tigers in the 1984 World Series,
are the fire and the frying pan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying like crazy to win a ballgame tonight,'' Braves
manager Bobby Cox said, sounding more discouraged than he owned up
to being, ``but we couldn't touch Brown. The Houston club has as
good a hitting team as anybody, and they didn't touch him either.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was a spot of good news for Atlanta, it's this: Because
San Diego goes home with a 2-0 lead, Bochy will feel no need to
pitch Brown in Game 4 on two days' rest. Call it a stay of
execution, not a pardon.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta must face Brown again, unless it gets swept. So there
can be no joy in Georgia tonight _ except in one Macon household.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, Bob. Sorry, Braves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 0119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
