r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-OLYMPIC-CONGRESS-     10-09 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYMPIC-CONGRESS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALLEY READY TO SHOW OFF FOR OLYMPIC CONGRESS  
 COUNTY COMMISSION PURSUES EVENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For more than four years, the U.S. Olympic Congress has sat like
a forbidden-to-open present under the Christmas tree.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic Games in Atlanta and Nagano have come and gone since the
annual convention of the U.S. Olympic movement was awarded to
Phoenix in June 1994. The group that successfully bid for the
Congress has changed its name from Maricopa County Sports
``Authority'' to ``Commission'' and changed its Mike, from Lawrence
to Sculley, as executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Even the purpose of courting the U.S. Olympic Committee is
different.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, the U.S. Olympic Festival existed, with Phoenix
among four finalists in the 1999 bidding. But the multisport event
that by its 14th and final staging in 1995 had grown to 36 sports
and 3,000 athletes was deemed as providing too little bang for a
$12 million budget.
</P>
<P>
   Now the chase is on for individual-sport Olympic events. In that
endeavor, the Maricopa County Sports Commission, with a $400,000
annual budget mostly met via corporate fund-raising, is like David
Dellucci challenging Mark McGwire in a home run hitting contest.
</P>
<P>
   Sculley and his three-person staff can only be gracious and
somewhat envious hosts as Baltimore-Washington, Cincinnati, Dallas,
Houston, Los Angeles, New York, Orlando-Tampa, San Francisco and
Seattle come into their home to schmooze for the chance to bid on
the 2012 Summer Olympics that will cost more than $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   More than 800 participants are registered for the eighth
Congress, which for the first time will include a golf tournament
and an interactive sport expo. The Sports Commission is hosting an
opening reception Sunday night that will include tours of Bank One
Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   The Congress is preceded today through Sunday by the bi-annual
meeting of the 107-member USOC Board of Directors, which includes a
report to the 20-member Executive Committee on the 2012 bid cities
and whether they meet minimum requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The Executive Committee includes USOC Vice Presidents Sandra
Baldwin and Herman Frazier, both of Phoenix, who are de facto
hosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great for Sandy and I to have this in our back yard,''
said Frazier, also chairman of the Maricopa County Sports
Commission. ``There are a lot of (National Governing Bodies) who
have annual meetings or some kind of competition who will figure
out that Phoenix is ideal for what they have to do later on. It's a
win-win situation for our state and for our city.''
</P>
<P>
   But nothing comes free in the Olympic sports world, especially
in attracting major events such as gymnastics, swimming or track
and field trials. And until the commission is bankrolled by a
significant funding source, it is unlikely to be able to compete
with the likes of the Indianapolis Sports Corporation (20-person
staff, $15 million budget), no matter how nice the weather is here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the venues and ideal location for what everybody
wants,'' Sculley said. ``But when someone else offers a $50,000
check, all we can say is congratulations, we'll try again next
time. Money is the only thing holding us back, and that's sad.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Sculley floated the idea of a minimal surcharge,
perhaps a dime, being added to Valley pro sports tickets to fund
the sports commission. No legislative action would be required,
only an agreement with the pro teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get any negative feedback'' on the concept, Sculley
said. ``We haven't pushed it because of the Cardinals situation and
Coyotes (seeking new facilities). Everyone is trying to jump on the
sports bandwagon. I don't want to throw something else into the
pie. I needed to get more established by bringing in some events.''
</P>
<P>
   To the end, Phoenix will host the Reese's Gymnastics Cup on Jan.
30 at Veterans Memorial Coliseum. The Senior Softball World
Championships and AAU 18-under baseball championships are coming to
the Peoria Sports Complex next year. Phoenix Swim Club will host
the U.S. Masters Nationals in 2000 and 2001, replacing the Grand
Prix meet it held for three years that is moving to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The softball, baseball and swim events will not quicken the
pulse of most sports fans, Sculley conceded. That's why this
Congress is important.
</P>
<P>
   His tour schedule includes a visit with USA Track &AMP; Field
officials to Sun Angel Track Stadium at Arizona State, where
Frazier is senior associate athletic director. As a quarter-miler,
Frazier trained there to win bronze and gold medals at the 1976
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ASU's Joe Sellah Track received a $700,000 remodeling in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Track is our best bet'' for a major event, said Sculley. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 0121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981009.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7785 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FANTASYFOOTBALL-A     10-09 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FANTASY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL COULD USE MORE FANTASY, LESS OF REAL THING 
</HEADLINE>
 FOOTBALL-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the NFL ever wanted to retreat into a fantasy world, this
would be a good time.
</P>
<P>
   The No Fun League was especially so Sunday. In Phoenix, where
our TV games are chosen by sadistic network weasels, we were
treated to the Dolphins-Jets punt-a-thon and the ultimate atomic
stink bomb: Philadelphia at Denver.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not saying the Eagles gave up in the second half. They gave
up in the first half. At one point, the Philadelphia secondary was
actually playing hacky sack.
</P>
<P>
   But in all fairness, I noted that the Eagles were careful never
to actually touch the hem of Terrell Davis' garment.
</P>
<P>
   Other rotten match-ups: Giants-Bucs, Chargers-Colts and, of
course, Seahawks-Chiefs, which was halted for 54 minutes because of
heavy rain and lightning _ the only fireworks during a dismal NFL
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   For the average fan, this turn of events might lead to dire
consequences _ yardwork, baby-sitting or, horror of horrors, a
Sunday afternoon cooking show.
</P>
<P>
   While braising pork chops might seem more appealing than
watching Danny Kanell impersonate an NFL quarterback, this isn't a
problem for fantasy leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some might argue that fantasy leagues are saving the
NFL from itself.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the league. Five weeks into the season, there are three
winless teams (Washington, Carolina and Philadelphia) and seven
teams with one victory. Other teams with slightly better records
(Arizona, New Orleans and Atlanta) just don't have the legs to
last.
</P>
<P>
   Quick quiz. The Dallas Cowboys' next three opponents have how
many wins among them? Answer: one.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, two of them are actually tied with Bye Week.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the bad football, fantasy owners always have a
reason to watch the games.
</P>
<P>
   Without fantasy football, the Eagles-Broncos might have seemed a
little, ah, dull. Don't tell that to the guy who started John Elway
at quarterback, only to watch Bubby Brister get the privilege of
whacking out the Eagles. (By the way, it's really hard to pry a
shoe out of a big-screen TV.)
</P>
<P>
   This game featured a slew of fantasy favorites besides Elway.
With Denver, you had Davis, wide receivers Rod Smith and Ed
McCaffrey and tight end Shannon Sharpe. As for the Eagles, some
poor souls were rooting for receiver Irving Fryar and running backs
Duce Staley and Charlie Garner.
</P>
<P>
   News that the Falcons were blowing out the Panthers was fine
with fantasy owners who started Falcons quarterback Chris Chandler,
running back Jamal Anderson or receiver Tony Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Purists argue that fantasy leaguers don't watch the games for
the right reasons, that we should be more interested in wins and
losses than statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Well, this weekend, the winless Eagles play the winless
Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   The purists can have my ticket. &QL;  &QL; 
Tip of the week &QL;  &QL; 
Don't be fooled by the performance of Panthers quarterback Kerry
Collins against Atlanta. He ran up his numbers after Carolina was
behind, 38-3, and this week he benched himself in favor of backup
Steve Beuerlein. I think Pittsburgh quarterback Kordell Stewart
will have a bounce-back game against Cincinnati. &QL;  &QL; 
Waiver wire &QL;  &QL; 
Look for Miami rookie John Avery to find his way into the lineup.
Coach Jimmy Johnson never has been enamored with starter Karim
Abdul-Jabbar. In Kansas City, Rashaan Shehee looked good in relief
of Donnell Bennett on Sunday, but Bennett should be back this week
despite a bruised hand. Don't expect Cowboys running back Chris
Warren to score two touchdowns every week, but he will get
significant time spelling Emmitt Smith. Running back Gary Brown
appears to have the starting job for the Giants, such as it is. &QL;  &QL; 
One-hit wonder &QL;  &QL; 
This week it's Detroit receiver Johnnie Morton, who had two catches
for 138 yards and two touchdowns. Morton is good, but he's not
going to catch too many more 98-yard bombs. &QL;  &QL; 
Bill Muller can be reached at bill.muller(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
