<HEADER>
A7786 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-GOMEZ-PADRES-BRAV     10-09 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GOMEZ-PADRES-BRAVES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUDDENLY, BRAVES HAVE LOST SWAGGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Familiarity has bred contempt, and reality is setting
in for the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   The sheen is fading and the Braves' mighty mystique is giving
way, opening the way for a new king to take over in the National
League.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, Atlanta is no longer the most feared and dominating
club in the league, a point that was especially punctuated after
San Diego grabbed its second straight victory in the NL
Championship Series on Thursday night, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   The victory allowed the Padres to snag a 2-0 lead in the
best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the next three games are scheduled at what promises
to be a thunderously raucous Qualcomm Stadium, the Braves' chances
of returning to their fifth World Series this decade are
staggeringly low right now.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego, which received a suffocating performance from starter
Kevin Brown, has taken it right to the Braves, dispatching John
Smoltz and Tom Glavine in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Greg Maddux will try to keep the Padres from assuming a
nearly insurmountable 3-0 lead in the series, but San Diego already
has beaten Atlanta's other two All-Star horses, so how could a
four-time Cy Young Award winner possibly intimidate this bunch?
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't come out overconfident against Atlanta,'' Padres
third baseman Ken Caminiti said. ``But we fully expected to be
prepared. We have a good, veteran club and we aren't afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres had Atlanta thrown off so much that Braves Manager
Bobby Cox had reliever Kevin Millwood warming up in the third
inning.
</P>
<P>
   That startling fact alone is enough to underscore how the
balance of power in the NL no longer resides in the Deep South.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, normally one of the coolest customers in the game,
walked the bases loaded in the second and had walked a season-high
five batters through three innings.
</P>
<P>
   It was a most un-Glavine-like performance, which mirrored the
Braves' implosion during the ninth inning. This is a club that has
fashioned itself as steady as any in recent decades.
</P>
<P>
   Mentioning the Atlanta Braves is like talking about Shaft in the
early '70s. This is a club that always maintained a coolness about
itself, even under the most difficult circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   But after watching the Braves' self-destruction in the ninth
inning, when the score was still within reach at 1-0, it may be
time to say Atlanta has fallen back to the pack.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, it's time to say the Braves no longer are
placed on some mythical pedestal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our backs aren't up against the wall now, I don't know what
it's going to take to get them there,'' said Glavine, who is
winless in his past three postseason starts. ``We're still trying
to win a World Series. I don't think we need anymore motivation
then that.''
</P>
<P>
   Motivation is one thing, but the Braves are now staring history
in the face, and the record says Atlanta is in a difficult
quandary.
</P>
<P>
   Only the 1984 Padres and the '85 Cardinals have managed to
overcome 0-2 deficits in the NL Championship Series. But each time,
those clubs lost the first two games on the road.
</P>
<P>
   If the Braves are to advance, they must accomplish something
that never has occurred in NLCS history. Of course, Atlanta can
take solace in remembering how the Yankees lost the first two games
of the 1996 World Series at Yankee Stadium before coming to Atlanta
and winning three in a row and eventually winning it all in six
games.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's defensive lapses in the ninth began shortly after
Brown led off the inning with a sharp single to right field.
Another single followed before Braves catcher Javier Lopez got cute
and his pickoff attempt of Brown at second base sailed into center
field.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie pitcher Odalys Perez failed to cover first base on a
grounder between first and second and Andres Galarraga compounded
it all when he couldn't make a play on an easy chopper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got really weird,'' San Diego right fielder Tony Gwynn
said. ``Sometimes in a playoff situation, those things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Those things might happen to the Chicago Cubs, Boston or even
the Yankees, but they haven't happened to these Braves very often.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' stranglehold over the rest of the NL seems to be
slipping away. Quickly. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 0129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
