<DOCNO> NYT19981009.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7788 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-PADRES-BRAVES-HNS     10-09 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PADRES-BRAVES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ The National League Championship Series is far from
locked up, but the San Diego Padres are doing some serious fiddling
with the deadbolt.
<TEXT>
<P>
   All along, the Atlanta Braves have said the key to winning the
best-of-seven series was whether they could beat Padres ace Kevin
Brown. Maybe they should try another key.
</P>
<P>
   Brown slammed the door on the Braves with another masterful
performance, tossing a three-hit shutout to lead the Padres to a
3-0 victory Thursday at Turner Field. The Padres took a 2-0 lead in
the series and could clinch their first NL pennant since 1984 in
front of a home crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``What more could we want?'' said Brown, who is 3-0 this
postseason. ``This (being up 2-0) is a lot better than being down
0-2, and it's better than a split.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a real moral victory for us to come here and beat
a team of this caliber in their ballpark. It really speaks to the
heart and soul of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   After an open date today, the series shifts to Qualcomm Stadium
for Games 3, 4 and, if necessary, 5. This constitutes new ground
for the Braves, who never have dropped the first two games of a
series during their dominant stretch of postseason play in the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, no team has ever won the NLCS after losing the first
two games at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an enviable position to be in,'' Braves pitcher
Tom Glavine said. ``But this thing is not over until someone wins
four games. Coming back from two games down is not an easy thing to
do, but we don't need to look any further than what happened to us
in 1996.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves won the first two games of the 1996 World Series
before the Yankees took the next four.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're glad to be up 2-0,'' Padres first baseman Wally Joyner
said. ``But we're not going to get overconfident. It was hard
enough to beat Atlanta these two times; now, we have to do it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like the Killer B's and Co., the Braves had no luck
unlocking the mystery of Brown, who lowered his ERA to a
microscopic 0.38 this postseason. He has 32 strikeouts and has
allowed just eight hits in 23 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Brown had 11 strikeouts Thursday and didn't allow a runner to
advance past second base after the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   He shut down the middle of the Braves' lineup _ Chipper Jones,
Andres Galarraga and Ryan Klesko _ holding them to one hit in nine
at-bats. The trio is hitting .048 (1-for-21) in the first two games
of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if any teams would have hit him (Brown),'' Braves
manager Bobby Cox said. ``Houston has as good a lineup as any team
in the National League, and they didn't touch him. We have a good
lineup, and we didn't touch him.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine allowed just one run despite pitching in trouble all
night and was no match for Brown, who also was 2-for-4 at the plate
and scored in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom of the Padres' lineup started a two-out rally in the
sixth when Glavine finally ran out of ways to escape trouble. Chris
Gomez, Brown and Quilvio Veras hit consecutive singles, Gomez
scoring on Veras' base hit up the middle to give the Padres a 1-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres had runners in scoring position in four of their six
innings against Glavine. It was a laborious night for the Braves
lefthander, who threw 83 pitches in the first four innings and 121
for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They scored on two seeing-eye singles and a ball up the middle
that was just out of (second baseman) Keith Lockhart's reach,''
said Glavine. ``When you're in as much trouble as I was in, sooner
or later something is going to go wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who is 6-0 with a 1.85 ERA in his last eight starts
against Atlanta, wouldn't know that feeling. He retired nine of the
first 11 batters he faced and didn't allow a hit until Jones'
one-out single in the fourth inning. The 33-year-old righthander
allowed two more harmless singles the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had great stuff,'' Padres manager Bruce Bochy said. ``When
Kevin is on, he's as tough as any pitcher. He's just locked in
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres cushioned the lead against rookie Odalis Perez in the
ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Brown got things started with a single and scored on a single by
Veras, who was 3-for-4. Veras scored the final run on Joyner's
infield single.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed,'' Galarraga said. ``But I still feel
positive about this team. We still have a chance. Maybe things will
be better for us on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   They can't be any worse.
</P>
</TEXT>
