A7873 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RESEARCH-DEAL-SFCHRON     10-09 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESEARCH-DEAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCH DEAL BETWEEN UC BERKELEY, BIOTECH FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARL T. HALL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    SAN FRANCISCO _ An unprecedented $50 million research alliance
is nearing the final stage of negotiation between the University of
California at Berkeley and a unit of Swiss biotechnology giant
Novartis.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The five-year deal promises to bring $5 million a year in
research grants to the Berkeley campus, mostly to faculty in the
College of Natural Resources who specialize in unlocking the
genetic secrets of agricultural products. Talks also envision
expanded new laboratories on the Berkeley campus worth an
additional $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Alliances with industry have become commonplace throughout
academia as cash-strapped institutions seek both financial
salvation and technological know-how. But the unusually broad scope
of the Berkeley-Novartis deal is expected to raise new questions
about the danger of corporate influences subverting academic
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Tentative outlines of the UC Berkeley deal were confirmed
publicly this week after several months of private talks between
the university and the Novartis Agribusiness Discovery Institute, a
new San Diego-based subsidiary of a company-sponsored research
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the $25 million in research grants would be funneled to
plant and microbial gene researchers through a faculty-controlled
committee that would evaluate proposals. In return, Novartis would
get certain negotiating rights to develop the most promising
scientific discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   Novartis may also pay to refurbish and expand a building on
campus that would provide laboratory space for three
Novartis-affiliated researchers, who also would be adjunct members
of the Berkeley faculty.
</P>
<P>
   That part of the deal is tentative, and negotiators also are
looking into the possibility of locating the Novartis-run labs
somewhere off campus. The UC Board of Regents would have to approve
the capital-spending part of any deal. Also, any company
researchers would have to meet all the standard university
requirements to gain faculty status.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Rausser, dean of the College of Natural Resources, said
he already has been hearing from skeptics concerned about such cozy
relations between a public university and a single industrial
partner.
</P>
<P>
   But he predicted most of the concerns will vanish once the full
details of the plan become known.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a unique alliance,'' he said. ``It allows total
freedom on the part of the faculty.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the main advantages for the university, according to
faculty members and administrators, is access to Novartis
technology _ stores of genetic-sequence information that is
becoming critical in virtually all the life sciences.
</P>
<P>
   It takes big teams _ and corporate-size budgets _ to decipher
and compile the key genomic information. Without it, faculty
members cannot keep pace at the ``frontiers of cutting-edge
research,'' Rausser said.
</P>
<P>
   For Novartis, company decisionmakers could take up to 120 days
to look over research results to determine whether to seek patent
rights. If the company decided to pass, the university could then
seek development rights with any other company.
</P>
<P>
   Such features are designed to mollify critics of other
university-corporate deals that, they say, could lock up important
research if it doesn't meet short-term profit potential or perhaps
might benefit competitors more than the sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear whether such concerns will become a major
impediment to the Novartis-Berkeley deal. The first full public
airing of the agreement is scheduled for next month, although
academic authorities already are being briefed on key aspects.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Berkeley Chancellor Robert Berdahl said that
while Berdahl supports the ``general concept,'' he has yet to sign
off on the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this is premature as far as the chancellor is
concerned,'' said campus spokesman Jesus Mena. ``Discussions are
going on. Things may shift.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Briggs, president of the Novartis agricultural-research
institute, said talks ``from the beginning'' have focused on
finding ways to collaborate without violating campus traditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're really doing is simply adding resources, more
funding and more technology, so the faculty can do more work,'' he
said. ``We're in no way trying to change the mission of the
university.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
