A7878 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRISH-PRISONERS-SFCHR     10-09 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISH-PRISONERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO AREA'S IRISH PRISONERS AWAIT PEACETIME AMNESTY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM DOYLE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    SAN FRANCISCO _ With dramatic advances being made almost daily
in the Irish peace talks, Britain has begun releasing hundreds of
political prisoners convicted of terrorist crimes in Northern
Ireland.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But three Irish fugitives whom the FBI apprehended in California
several years ago remain imprisoned at the federal penitentiary in
Pleasanton with little hope of early release. Kevin Barry Artt, Pol
((cq)) Brennan and Terry Kirby have slipped through the cracks of
Northern Ireland's peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Four hundred and twenty prisoners in Northern Ireland are
eligible to apply for early release under the peace accord. So far,
68 have been released. Two hundred inmates are expected to be back
on the streets by Christmas. About 200 more will be let go by June
2000.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bay Area, the three fugitives are caught in a limbo of
legal uncertainty. British officials are continuing to pursue
extradition warrants against Artt, Brennan and Kirby, and have also
blocked their requests for bail. Artt and Kirby were convicted of
murder, Brennan of possessing an IRA bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Irish activists complain that Britain's hard line is vindictive.
British officials say they are simply seeking criminal justice.
</P>
<P>
   The three took part in a 1983 mass escape from the Maze Prison
near Belfast and then settled in California. All have families in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prisoners need to be released to their own communities,
wherever that might be,'' said John Fogarty, regional vice
president of the Irish American Unity Conference. ``There is
potential here of uprooting families or destroying them. My feeling
is that common sense and a sense of compassion should rule here.''
</P>
<P>
   The inmates fear that if returned to Belfast and eventually
released there, they will not be allowed to return to their homes
in the United States because of their alleged or acknowledged ties
to the Irish Republican Army. Traditionally, the State Department
has refused to grant entry visas to suspected terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be an appropriate part of the peace process to drop
the extradition of these men,'' said former U.S. Representative
Bruce Morrison, an adviser of President Clinton on Irish issues.
``There seems to be little benefit to anyone to extradite them and
separate them from their families.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Mastrogiorgio, editor of the New Irish Gael newspaper in
San Francisco, said British officials are singling out Artt,
Brennan and Kirby ``because they were embarrassed by them. Their
anti-extradition fights in America focused a lot of media attention
on Britain's human rights record in Northern Ireland and the
collusion between security forces and pro-British assassins.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Justice Department, which is representing Britain in
the extradition cases, says its hands are tied. ``If the U.K.
withdraws its request, the extradition proceedings will be
discontinued,'' said Sara Criscitelli, a lawyer for the department.
``But unless that occurs, we have an obligation under the treaty.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Britain is holding fast. ``They have all been convicted
of very serious offenses,'' said Paul Johnston, a British spokesman
in New York. ``When they return to custody in Northern Ireland,
Artt, Brennan and Kirby will be eligible to (apply) to the
Sentences Commission for early release.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein president Gerry Adams is expected to raise the cases
of Artt, Brennan and Kirby when he visits the White House on
Sunday. Sinn Fein, the IRA's political wing, has asked Britain to
withdraw its extradition requests.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Adams and his arch-rival, David Trimble, minister of
the new Northern Ireland Assembly, held private talks for the first
time. A few days later, Britain removed its troops from the streets
of Belfast and began releasing paramilitary prisoners, including
men convicted of bombings and political killings.
</P>
<P>
   Under the peace accord, approved in May by Irish voters, Britain
has agreed to release all prisoners linked to the IRA and certain
Protestant loyalist groups in the next two years _ except for those
considered a danger to society.
</P>
<P>
   Artt and San Francisco house painter Jimmy Smyth, who also was
among the 38 inmates who escaped from the Maze Prison, were
arrested by the FBI in June 1992. FBI agents arrested Brennan in
Berkeley in 1993, and picked up Kirby in Concord in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Smyth, who was extradited to Northern Ireland in 1996, has
applied for early release. He is likely to be freed soon and plans
to settle in Belfast with his American wife, Julie Smyth, and their
son, Conner, who was born August 2.
</P>
<P>
   All four Catholic nationalist fugitives claim to be victims of
religious and political persecution in the British-controlled
province. Artt and Kirby said that Belfast detectives beat them
into making false confessions.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, U.S. District Judge Charles A. Legge of San Francisco
ruled that Artt, Brennan and Kirby should be extradited. Legge said
that although he might find Artt and Kirby's confessions
involuntary under U.S. law, he had no authority to reconsider their
guilt. The inmates appealed his ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Artt, 38, was convicted by a nonjury trial of the 1979 murder of
an off-duty prison warden and sentenced to life in prison. At his
extradition hearing, Artt's lawyers presented evidence that
detectives' notes of his 10-day interrogation were falsified. Artt
is engaged to Erin Riley, a U.S. citizen who works in San
Francisco. He has two children: Kara, 10, of San Diego; and Barry,
18, of Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   Kirby, 42, was sentenced to life in prison for the 1976 killing
of a gas station attendant during a suspected IRA bombing. He
admits being an IRA member, but denies any involvement in the
killing. After his escape, he settled in Concord and married
Colleen Dolan, a U.S. citizen. They have a 3-year-old daughter,
Keely.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan, 45, was arrested in 1976 in possession of an IRA bomb
and sentenced to 16 years in Maze Prison. After his escape, Brennan
took an American wife, Joanna Volz, and worked as a carpenter in
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Release of these three is totally consistent with the spirit
of the peace agreement _ its intent to put all the agony
experienced by people on all sides of the conflict behind them,''
said San Francisco attorney Jim Brosnahan, who represents Artt.
``As prisoners are released, there's no reason to make an exception
of these three men.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
