A7879 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUDGE-APPROVED-SFCHRO     10-09 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDGE-APPROVED-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE OKS CLINTON'S PICK FOR 9TH CIRCUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   By LOUIS FREEDBERG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    WASHINGTON _ Despite opposition from conservative lawmakers,
the U.S. Senate confirmed Berkeley law professor William Fletcher
to be a federal judge Thursday, more than three years after he was
nominated.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fletcher, who was approved by a 57-to-41 vote, had been waiting
longer than any other Clinton nominee to secure his post. His
nomination by President Clinton to the Ninth Circuit Court of
Appeals in San Francisco had become bogged down in complex
political maneuvers that were resolved only after Congress approved
a law this week barring family members from sitting on the same
bench.
</P>
<P>
   After being nominated in April 1995, the Boalt Hall School of
Law professor ran into problems because his mother, Betty Fletcher,
is also a judge on the Ninth Circuit court.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the Judiciary Committee,
blocked Fletcher's appointment, saying it would violate federal
anti-nepotism laws. To break the logjam, Fletcher's mother agreed
to step down if her son were confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   But even after clearing that hurdle, Fletcher faced opposition
from conservatives who said he would continue to tilt the Ninth
Circuit court in a too activist or liberal direction, as they said
his mother had done. Fletcher vigorously denied the charges, saying
he holds centrist positions that differ from his mother's.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Fletcher, a Rhodes Scholar, was also a friend of
Clinton's and had helped run his Northern California campaign for
president in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   His nomination languished for months, and then years. Along the
way, a controversial deal was struck in the Senate in which Clinton
would nominate a conservative Republican judge from Washington
state in exchange for his confirmation by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the House and the Senate cleared the final obstacle
in Fletcher's path by approving a bill sponsored by Sen. Jon Kyl,
R-Ariz., barring close relatives from sitting on the same court.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, in one of the last days of the congressional session,
Hatch made only oblique references to the battles that surrounded
the nomination, and instead warmly praised Fletcher. ``I am the
first to say that I may not agree with all of Mr. Fletcher's
views,'' he said. ``But the president is entitled to have his
nominees confirmed provided that the nominee is well qualified and
will abide by the limitations on federal judges.''
</P>
<P>
   Some conservative lawmakers were not willing to let Fletcher's
confirmation go through without a fight. ``Mr. Fletcher's writings
and statements simply do not convince me that he will move the
Ninth Circuit closer to the mainstream of judicial thought,'' said
Sen. Michael DeWine, R-Ohio, a member of the Judiciary Committee,
who voted against Fletcher.
</P>
<P>
   After 21 years as a law professor, Fletcher will finish up
classes at Boalt this semester before taking up his post on the San
Francisco bench in January. Thursday, he declined to comment on the
controversy and delays that plagued his nomination, except to say:
``I am very grateful for the faith the president has shown in me,
and for the Senate's confirmation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
