<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A wrastlin' good time with the Superstars
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's far too hot for an October night, especially inside the
Nacogdoches
</P>
<P>
   Expo Center, where there's not a hint of a breeze. Flies are
buzzing around
</P>
<P>
   languidly, as if even they don't have enough energy in this
infernal heat,
</P>
<P>
   which won't go away despite our pleas and prayers.
</P>
<P>
   I soon realize I've overdressed for the Superstars of Wrestling
</P>
<P>
   Extravaganza about to take place. My blue jeans and golf shirt
look out of
</P>
<P>
   place among the tank tops, gym shorts and wide array of T-shirts
sporting
</P>
<P>
   wrestling logos: Mean People Rule. New World Order. Austin 3:16.
WWF. I
</P>
<P>
   start wondering where one buys pro-wrestling sports attire.
Never seen it in
</P>
<P>
   the mall, though I haven't been paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   The dirt floor of the Expo has been covered with the old SFA
stadium
</P>
<P>
   artificial turf, an excellent example of recycling. A small ring
has been
</P>
<P>
   set up in the middle, surrounded by folding chairs. I'm in the
cheap seats,
</P>
<P>
   the bleachers about 75 feet from the ring, along with a gaggle
of children
</P>
<P>
   and dads, most of whom are quick to tell me they're only here
because their
</P>
<P>
   kids made them come. That's why I'm here at that, and my wife is
a member of the civic club sponsoring the show.
</P>
<P>
   I don't follow wrestling. My 91-year-old grandmother watches it
with a
</P>
<P>
   passion, talking to the TV ninety-to-nothing, booing the bad
guys and
</P>
<P>
   cheering on the heroes. She steadfastly refuses to believe
wrestling might
</P>
<P>
   be, ahem, fake or to put it more kindly, staged.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of folks here tonight who do follow the likes
of King Kong
</P>
<P>
   Bundy ( no kin to Al, apparently), Nasty Boys, Red Dog or Greg
``The Hammer ``
</P>
<P>
   Valentine, a second-generation wrestler whose dad, Johnny ``The
Hammer ``
</P>
<P>
   Valentine roamed the ring in the 1970s. Wrestling is hot among
adolescent
</P>
<P>
   boys right now, and they are here in force tonight.
</P>
<P>
   This event is being taped for future broadcasting, we're
informed by the
</P>
<P>
   ring announcer, who implores the audience to cheer lustily and
make lots of
</P>
<P>
   noise. Not a problem. This crowd is ready to rumble.
</P>
<P>
   The first match is between Red Dog and Dapper Dan. Red Dog is
wearing
</P>
<P>
   black-and-red Spandex that barely holds in his sumo-class gut.
Wrestling is
</P>
<P>
   a morality play, good vs. evil. Most times the good guy wins,
but not
</P>
<P>
   always.
</P>
<P>
   By GARY BORDERS
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately the air punches and canvas-stomping to approximate
the sound
</P>
<P>
   of a vicious forearm to the chest look even less convincing in
real life.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes I can see air between the fist and its intended
target, though the
</P>
<P>
   victim still moans loudly and grimaces in artificial pain.
</P>
<P>
   But the wrestlers are good athletes, bouncing off the ropes and
flipping
</P>
<P>
   over each other with grace and skill. The crowd loves it, and I
find myself
</P>
<P>
   enjoying it more than I thought I would.
</P>
<P>
   The second match features King Kong Bundy vs. an utterly
outmatched and
</P>
<P>
   thoroughly outweighed fellow from Longview by the name of Jason
Nash. Bundy,
</P>
<P>
   I'm told, is well-known in wrestling circles. He is certainly
hard to miss
</P>
<P>
   at 460 pounds stuffed into a black single-piece outfit. Nash, at
a mere 242
</P>
<P>
   pounds, doesn't stand a chance. He's dispatched in 85 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Bundy grabs the microphone and declares, ``Every man in Texas
fears me;
</P>
<P>
   every woman in Texas wants me. `` I don't know about the women,
but I'd
</P>
<P>
   certainly address him in a deferential manner. He weighs three
times as much
</P>
<P>
   as I do.
</P>
<P>
   My youngest daughter and her compadres ask me the crucial
question: ``Is
</P>
<P>
   wrestling fake? Are they really hitting each other? ``
</P>
<P>
   I feel like the grinch telling a child about Santa Claus as I
explain that
</P>
<P>
   the odds of someone surviving 27 straight forearms to the head
without even
</P>
<P>
   sustaining a mild concussion a let alone a headache a are slim.
They seem
</P>
<P>
   vaguely disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   The last match we watch turns into a typical wrasslin' melee
with four
</P>
<P>
   combatants taking the fight out of the ring and onto the floor.
The referee,
</P>
<P>
   of course, does nothing to stop the riot. It's up to Nasty Boy
to save the
</P>
<P>
   day.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know who Nasty Boy is, other than he has a blond shag
haircut and a
</P>
<P>
   foul mouth. After giving a short speech laced with words we
can't put in the
</P>
<P>
   newspaper (even after Kenneth Starr's report), he leaves and
then comes back
</P>
<P>
   with a folding chair that he bangs over the head of the bad-guy
wrestler
</P>
<P>
   with a convincing clang. End of the match. I'm not sure good
triumphed over
</P>
<P>
   evil. More like evil triumphing over the banal. The crowd loves
it. Small
</P>
<P>
   children surround Nasty Boy as he leaves the ring. Who says
there aren't
</P>
<P>
   heroes anymore?
</P>
<P>
   It's a school night, and we leave early, dragging unwilling
children away.
</P>
<P>
   The step-son takes note of the Superstars of Wrestling web site
for future
</P>
<P>
   reference (www.ssow.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned. The show might end up on late-night TV sometime. If
they show a crowd shot, I'm the guy in the back eating nachos and
taking notes, hoping
</P>
<P>
   King Kong Bundy isn't offended by my attire or attitude. He
could squash me
</P>
<P>
   like a fly.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel His
</P>
<P>
   e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
