<HEADER>
A8121 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEY-B/O10-COX     10-09 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-B/O10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Disney magic? Two brothers, perfect foils
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ BUILDING A COMPANY: Roy O. Disney and
the Creation of an Entertainment Empire, by Bob Thomas. Hyperion;
359 pages; $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in this resolutely interesting biography of the
other Disney, someone speculates that, without his brother, Walt
Disney would have been a mediocre cartoonist for somebody else's
company. And without his brother, Roy would have been a provincial
bank manager in Glendale, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, the Disney brothers had each other. Actually, Walt
needed Roy more than Roy needed Walt, because nobody but family
would have continually acquiesced to Walt's wild dreams.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney brothers were Missouri farm boys whose father was a
fiery Socialist with a gift for failure. That both of Elias
Disney's sons grew up to be rock-ribbed Republicans, not to mention
self-made millionaires, is a delicious, possibly profound
generational joke.
</P>
<P>
   All their lives, Walt was the locomotive, and Roy was the
engineer who was frantically trying to keep the train on the
tracks. Their relationship was an extension of the familiar
childhood dynamic in which the older boy is instructed to take care
of his younger brother. Roy did, all his life.
</P>
<P>
   When Walt wanted to make cartoons, Roy, armed with a small
disability pension from his service in World War I, went out to
California to lend him a hand.
</P>
<P>
   When Walt, barely breaking even on black-and-white cartoons,
wanted to upgrade to color, Roy found the money.
</P>
<P>
   When Walt wanted to violate every ounce of conventional wisdom
and make a feature-length cartoon, Roy found the money.
</P>
<P>
   When the studio teetered on the edge of bankruptcy after the
consecutive failures of Bambi, Pinocchio and Fantasia, Roy somehow
managed to make payroll every week, even though nobody is sure how
to this day.
</P>
<P>
   And, when Walt developed a compulsion to build an amusement park
in Anaheim which could only overextend an already perilously
financed company, Roy went along, against his better judgment.
</P>
<P>
   The venerable Hollywood reporter Bob Thomas tells a story of
old-fashioned empire building, but he keeps the scale human. Thomas
simplifies the financial complexities but doesn't simplify the
fascinating emotional dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney was similar to the man his publicists created, but
not identical. He smoke, he drank, he had a good line in profanity,
he carried a strong residual grudge against his father, who was
prone to physically lashing out when angry, and who never believed
in his son.
</P>
<P>
   After they became successful, the brothers bought their parents
a house and took care of them, but it was Roy who did the grunt
work of keeping in touch, listening to them complain about their
declining health, etc. Walt was very careful to keep them at arm's
length.
</P>
<P>
   Nor were Roy and Walt a latter-day Damon and Pythias act. They
argued. At one point, late in their lives, they didn't speak for
two years, over a holding company engineered by Walt that, Roy
believed, verged on the unethical, and opened the company up to
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Disneyland brought the company to the edge of catastrophe. To
get the money, Roy used the film library as collateral, hocked
every lease they had, used up all of ABC's _ the brothers' partner
on the deal _ credit line. Roy even borrowed on the brothers' life
insurance. None of it fazed Walt.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know the worst thing that can happen to you?'' Walt mused
one day during construction. ``You could go broke. I look at it
this way: I've been broke five times in my life. One more time
won't hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   The park ended up costing $15 million. Had it failed, it would
have taken the company with it. But Walt was right; Disneyland, and
Disneyland alone, was the vehicle that drove the company to
ultimate success; by 1961, Roy had paid off every company loan.
</P>
<P>
   Building A Company _ a drab, unworthy title _ holds interest
throughout, especially toward the end, as Roy, in his mid-70s, puts
aside his desire for retirement and girds his loins to build Disney
World after Walt's death. (According to Thomas, 12,000 acres in
North Palm Beach owned by John D. MacArthur was an early
possibility for the site, but the deal fell apart early on.)
</P>
<P>
   It was Roy who ramrodded the planning and construction of the
Florida park, and it undoubtedly took years off his life _ he died
of a sudden stroke just months after the park's 1971 opening.
</P>
<P>
   Although Roy had appointed a successor to run the business side,
his brother's inability to delegate meant that the creative side
was barren of anybody who could approach Walt's drive and vision.
The studio entered upon a long period of drift. Before the arrival
of Michael Eisner, who combined some of the best parts of both
brothers, all that kept Disney afloat was the parks.
</P>
<P>
   One of the continually surprising things about the Disneys is
how limited they were intellectually. Thomas quotes liberally from
Roy's letters, and they're like something out of an early Sinclair
Lewis novel, with the banal vocabulary and fusty mind of a
19th-century Plains banker.
</P>
<P>
   Roy talked about walking into a planning session for Fantasia.
``Can't you select some music that just the ordinary guy like me
can like?'' Roy asked. ``They all froze up and Walt ordered me out
of the room. `Go back down and keep the books,' he said.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if the Disney brothers' horizons had been
wider, their minds wouldn't have been so focused. As it was, they
bonded with their generation, and their generation's children and
grandchildren and great-grandchildren to develop an unparalleled
sense of brand loyalty to the values contained in the name Disney.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
