<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When surfboards were long and the craze was young
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Surfing San Onofre to Point Dume:
1936-1942 (Chronicle, $24.95) is a superlative collection of
photographs by the late Don James, who was in at the inception of
the coming of surfing to Southern California in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   These images, individually unremarkable, cumulatively haunting,
document young men who built and finished their own surfboards,
strapped them to the top of battered Model A's and headed for the
beach with their girlfriends. The faces are
</P>
<P>
   specifically American, strong young bodies built without the aid
of steroids, recognizable even today as classic examples of the
California gene pool.
</P>
<P>
   Don James became a dentist and died at the end of 1996, just
after he saw an early, privately published edition of this book. I
hold no particular brief for surfing and know little about it
beyond a cursory exposure to Bruce Brown movies. But these
photographs are about innocence and time as much as they're about
surfing, and I recommend this deeply atmospheric collection.
</P>
<P>
   NICHOLAS AND ALEXANDRA AND SON . . . Abrams has signed up The
Escape of Alexei, a book about a St. Petersburg customs inspector
named Oleg Filatov, who believed he was the hemophiliac son of
Nicholas II, miraculously escaped from the slaughter of his family
in Ekaterinburg.
</P>
<P>
   The book, to be published in November, is written by Filatov's
son and will feature 100 photographs documenting the supposedly
amazing resemblance between Alexei Romanov and Oleg Filatov.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond a doubtful escape from the Red death squad, to believe
this particular story you have to posit that Alexei somehow
vanquished a case of hemophilia so severe that he wasn't expected
to live long enough to assume the throne, not to mention living for
another 60 years undetected by a government with a considerable
stake in making sure no Romanov was alive anywhere in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Selling this book to anybody but hard-core fantasists and
disappointed adherents of Anna Anderson will be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   WRETCHED EXCESS . . . Molly Jong-Fast _ say her name quickly and
she sounds like one of Fu Manchu's minions _ is the daughter of
Erica Jong and Jonathan Fast, and the granddaughter of Howard Fast.
She has been signed to write Girl, a novel about youth coming of
age amid sex and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Molly Jong-Fast is 19 years old. Joyce Maynard must be furious.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE UNQUOTE . . . ``If you bring forth what is inside you,
what you bring forth will save you. If you do not bring forth what
is inside you, what is inside you will destroy you.'' _ St. Thomas,
Gnostic Gospels
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
