<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glenn prepares fopr launch with all the same jitters
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, FLA. _ The advances in rocketry and space ship
systems may give Sen. John Glenn a smoother, roomier trip in orbit
than his last one 36 years ago, but he admitted Thursday that he
still has one recurring anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, I was scared to death I was going to catch a cold
or something and might be replaced,'' Glenn said. ``I feel the same
way right now.''
</P>
<P>
   With the mammoth launch pad and shuttle looming behind them,
Glenn and the rest of the Discovery space shuttle crew scheduled to
fly Oct. 29, met briefly with reporters to talk about the final
weeks of preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready to go,'' Glenn said. ``Three weeks from
(Thursday). . . that thing will light off back there. And I'm
really looking forward to this, as you can imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   The seven-member shuttle crew arrived Tuesday night from
Houston, where they do most of their training, for three days of
countdown practice at the launch facility of the Kennedy Space
Center. The primary function of the countdown test is to bring
together the flight crew and the launch crew to iron out any
wrinkles in the strict launch day schedule NASA has planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that the flight crew get to talk and work with
the launch team,'' said Steve Altemus, the NASA test director.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the crew will strap into their seats in the orbiter and
run through the countdown to liftoff, stopping five seconds short.
Each of the shuttle's main systems will be activated in sequence,
and the astronauts will switch from outside air to the oxygen
supply in their suits before the countdown test ends. Then, they'll
fake an emergency and evacuate.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency retreat was a part of training Wednesday, too. The
crew was instructed on how to drive a small, armored personnel
carrier that will be stationed at the base of the launch pad. The
tank-like buggy is a safety precaution, like a concrete bunker near
by, that could be used if a fuel tank leaks or a fire ignites.
</P>
<P>
   The personnel carrier has never been used, but the training is
done for every launch and every crew member.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first one in the tank scrambles up the driver seat and
becomes the operator (in an emergency),'' said George Hoggard, fire
captain in the space center's own fire department. ``That's why we
teach everybody to do this; first come first served.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoggard, who sits atop the personnel carrier while the crew
member steers from inside through the half-mile training course,
tried to be blase about his most famous pupil, saying, ``One ride's
as bumpy as the next ride.''
</P>
<P>
   But it took little prompting to get the 61-year-old to 'fess up
about his view of Glenn: ``I admire him a heck of a lot for his
efforts and I think that the information gathered on this mission
can be very valuable to us senior citizens
</P>
<P>
   _Montgomery is a reporter with the Dayton Daily News
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
