r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINTER-COLUMN10-COX     10-09 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Let's hear from the small towns
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With all the paid-for lies and distortions running on television
this political season, I was heartened to read something Roy Barnes
said on a campaign trip to Jesup, population 10,000 more or less,
deep in southeast Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a close election, and I think it's going to
be decided south of Macon,'' he predicted. In other words, it's
going to be even-steven in the Atlanta doughnut, with South Georgia
tipping the scale.
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, I can sleep a little better.
</P>
<P>
   ``South of Macon'' translates into the small-town and rural
vote, still largely guided by old-fashioned values and horse sense.
</P>
<P>
   My first visit to Jesup was about 100 years ago. The Jesup
football team had pulled off the impossible, beating mighty
Valdosta for the state championship. Furman Bisher, my boss at The
Atlanta Journal, sent me down to report on the victory banquet.
</P>
<P>
   It was a memorable evening, starting at 7 p.m. and ending
slightly before midnight. The cooks who had prepared the food in
the school cafeteria were asked to come out and take a bow.
Everybody who contributed to the successful season was introduced.
It soon became apparent everyone in town had contributed. I
especially remember the mothers who baby-sat for other mothers who
drove cheerleaders to cheerleading practice.
</P>
<P>
   Wally Butts, the football coach at the University of Georgia,
was the guest speaker. It was past 11:30 when he finally was called
to the podium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like ol' Clegg, our water boy, felt last year when we
were getting beat so bad by Auburn,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``After they scored their fourth touchdown in the third quarter,
Clegg came up to me and said, `Coach, ain't there no way we can get
this thing over with and go home?'''
</P>
<P>
   It was a long night, but it was easy to see something special in
people who cared so much for their town and for each other.
</P>
<P>
   Later on, I got to know Dink NeSmith Jr., owner of the local
newspaper. Any time I passed that way, I stopped to visit and go
around the corner to Jones' Kitchen for fried chicken, turnip
greens, fried okra, mashed potatoes and banana pudding.
</P>
<P>
   I also got to know Dink NeSmith Sr., who owned the local funeral
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must be awfully proud of your son,'' I said to him in one
of our conversations. Little Dink was coming off his term as
president of the Georgia Press Association, the youngest ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am,'' NeSmith replied, ``but I sure was worried about him
for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How was that?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sent him up to Athens to the university to get an education,
and he joined everything except the Ladies Missionary Society. I
didn't see how he was going to have time for an education.''
</P>
<P>
   Little Dink must have learned something. About 10 years ago, he
hooked up with Tom Wood, the innovative former CEO of the
Journal-Constitution, to start a community newspaper company. At
last count, they were up to nearly 50 papers and growing.
</P>
<P>
   When I drove to Jesup a few days ago, I arrived at the First
Baptist Church 40 minutes before the funeral service was to begin.
The church was already full. I had to sit with a lot of other
people and a TV set in the cafeteria. Dink NeSmith Sr., who went to
work at the age of 11, scrimped and saved to send three children to
college, and wore a starched white shirt and tie even when he mowed
the lawn, in his 74 years filled just about every community and
church role in town _ except the Ladies Missionary Society.
</P>
<P>
   Little Dink told about finally getting rid of his clip-on
necktie and having a regular grown-up tie to wear to Sunday school.
He didn't know how to tie a real tie and had to ask his father for
help.
</P>
<P>
   After several unsuccessful tries, the frustrated
undertaker/father solved the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go over to the couch and lie down on your back,'' he
commanded. Until he learned to tie his own knot, Little Dink had to
lie on his back, like a corpse, every Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   After a round of Bach, tributes by numerous townfolk, and
favorite renditions by a gospel quartet, Little Dink announced that
interment at the cemetery would be delayed two hours so everybody
could enjoy dinner on the ground, because ``that's what Daddy would
want.'' Food tables ran from inside the cafeteria to under the oaks
outside.
</P>
<P>
   NeSmith loved to entertain friends and family in his back yard.
Fish fries and barbecues were always topped off with hand-cranked
ice cream and boiled peanuts, his signature favorites. Everybody
who came to his funeral got a dish of homemade ice cream and a bag
of boiled peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   High school banquets and funerals are a good way to take the
measure of a town. Although it's grown a lot, Jesup hasn't changed
much since that night in 1950-something when they spent an evening
celebrating a football championship.
</P>
<P>
   With the mess in Washington and paid political lies at home, I
was about to throw in with Neal Boortz and give up on the country.
Now I'm not quite ready. As long as we have small towns, and values
that endure in small towns, we can hope.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
