r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN09-COX-1     10-09 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN09-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Tea time and politics in Paris
 &HT;    (Resending to fix line breaks.)
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ It's Sunday, 4 p.m., and tea time for Americans in Paris
who gather at George Whitman's famed bookstore, Shakespeare &AMP; Co.,
just across the River Seine from Notre Dame Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman, 86, has operated his store from this site since coming
to Paris in 1951. The location itself goes back somewhat further,
at least to the 16th century, when it served as a monastery.
</P>
<P>
   These days it is a place of congregation for those of us who
worship books and good writing.
</P>
<P>
   But on this particular day, in a cramped third-floor room
crowded wall-to-wall with some 20 students and writers, the topic
at tea time was politics, and the devilment thereof. Nobody to
blame but myself.
</P>
<P>
   I'd made the mistake of asking a middle-aged poet who recently
moved to Paris from Kentucky, a natural progression of sorts, what
the talk was of Bill and Monica.
</P>
<P>
   He all but exploded. ``It's asinine to speak of it,'' he said,
fuming, ``a ridiculous waste of time, conversation and ink, a
subject that people are tired of, fed up and disgusted with.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry I asked _ and even more so when for the next hour the
group talked of nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   A number of the younger women, U.S. exchange students living
with French families, had the most to say. They represented a wide
area of America, from Florida to Michigan, Washington, D.C., to
California.
</P>
<P>
   The quotes here are approximate. I find it all but impossible to
take tea and notes at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I can't believe America is making such an issue of it. This
is a private affair. It should be kept private.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``My French family is more disgusted with Hillary than Bill.
They can't understand why she isn't showing more jealousy and
outrage. They say, `I would look for love elsewhere myself if I
were married to such an uncaring person.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I feel sorry for Chelsea. Imagine what she is going through.
A politician's family shouldn't be made part of this.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Blame that on the politicians for the way they campaign,
exhibiting their families as if they were trophies and show horses.
The image of the family becomes part of the campaign promises.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``But when did we ever expect politicians to keep their
campaign promises?''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Too bad Clinton didn't get involved with a military woman.
The military is sworn to protect the president.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Better had he found someone a little older and a little less
tacky.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Instead, he picked the ugliest women on the face of the
earth.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I feel sorry for Monica. Just think how it must be, that
every awful thing you ever did is laid out on a table for all to
see.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Yes, but she was the one who put them there.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Excuse me, but I can't forgive her for keeping the dress.
And then, of all things, sending it to her mother. My mother would
have ... I can't imagine what my mother would have done to me.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``It was a message she was sending to her mother. `Look, I've
slept with the most powerful man in the world.' ''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Well, they never actually slept together. They never took
that much time.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Did you see the latest poll results? When asked, 66 percent
of the women in Washington said they'd never have sex with
President Clinton again.''
</P>
<P>
   So it went: Bill and Monica, tea and sympathy, or the lack
thereof.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is
</P>
<P>
   senior writer for Cox Newspapers.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
