<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWITZER10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Switzer's life after football remains in high gear
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Barry Switzer is too busy riding his motorcycle
through the wilderness of Wyoming to worry about trivial matters
such as the annual Oklahoma-Texas football game.
</P>
<P>
   Switzer, easy rider and former football coach, is a busy man.
When he isn't riding his Harley-Davidson on scenic highways, he is
visiting Hollywood movie sets, opening restaurants and making cameo
appearances on an Oklahoma City TV station.
</P>
<P>
   Switzer, 61, does not plan to be at the Cotton Bowl for the
grudge match between Texas and Oklahoma, the school he coached at
for 23 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the same anymore,'' Switzer said of the border
rivalry. ``There was a time when one team would be No. 1 in the
country and the other would be No. 2. Both OU and Texas had
national prestige.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither team is ranked, and the game will be televised only in
this part of the country (KTBC).
</P>
<P>
   Switzer, who resigned as head coach of the Dallas Cowboys eight
months ago, is filled with memories about his college career. In
1973, his first year as head coach of the Sooners, OU defeated
Texas 52-13.
</P>
<P>
   In 16 years as a head coach at OU, Switzer's team was 9-5-2
against the Longhorns. When he retired from the college game in
1988, he left OU with a 157-29-4 mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had better talent than Texas in '73,'' Switzer said, ``and
Texas had damn good talent. But we had guys like the Selmon
brothers and Joe Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Another favorite memory is the 1984 OU-Texas game. Switzer had
just hired a new offensive coordinator, a man named Mack Brown, and
the Sooners and Longhorns struggled to a 15-15 tie.
</P>
<P>
   It was the only Red River rivalry matchup for Brown, a
33-year-old assistant who became the head coach of the Texas
Longhorns 14 years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mack Brown was the best and smartest offensive coordinator we
ever had at OU,'' Switzer said this week. ``Mack was a complete
coach. He helped turn the whole program around.''
</P>
<P>
   Switzer recently visited Brown at the UT coach's office. Switzer
offered this prediction on Longhorns football: ``I've said that it
will take Mack less than three years to turn the program around.''
</P>
<P>
   Switzer might have been the most hated sports figure in Texas
from 1973 to 1988. He was a terrific recruiter, and Oklahoma
developed a knack for signing the best high school players in the
Lone Star state.
</P>
<P>
   Switzer easily was the most successful and popular coach in
Sooners football history. His games against Texas icon Darrell
Royal are legendary. Yet the best part of coaching was not the
thrill of winning or losing a game in the Cotton Bowl or various
stadiums in Oklahoma and beyond, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Switzer enjoyed his relationships with his players. It's the
reason he prefers the college game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved the college game much more than the pros,'' he said.
``A college coach has a better opportunity to shape and mold the
lives of the young people.''
</P>
<P>
   Switzer does not have similar feelings about his four-year
tenure with the Cowboys, which ended after the team finished 6-10
last season. Overall his record was a respectable 45-26, but he was
blamed for the team's gradual decline the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   He is not crying sour grapes, though, over his days with the
Cowboys. After Dallas defeated Washington recently, three players _
Leon Lett, Michael Irvin and Erik Williams _ visited Switzer at a
Dallas restaurant. And he still talks frequently with his former
boss, Cowboys owner Jerry Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Switzer is much too busy to coach again. He currently is reading
a script for a movie that will be directed by Oliver Stone. In the
movie, which begins shooting in the spring, Al Pacino plays the
role of an NFL coach. Switzer will audition for the part of an
assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   It will mark Switzer's second turn in acting. He had a bit part
in ``Varsity Blues,'' another football movie that will be released
later this year.
</P>
<P>
   He is also preparing to open two restaurants in Oklahoma City
and contributes commentaries on college football for an Oklahoma TV
station. He plans to sell his house near Dallas and return to
Oklahoma soon.
</P>
<P>
   Switzer recently spent two weeks riding his motorcycle with five
buddies through Wyoming, Utah and Colorado. It's a trip he has made
several times in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether he will coach again, he gave an emphatic no.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in the fourth quarter of my life, getting close to the
two-minute warning,'' Switzer said, pausing for a hearty laugh.
``But I'm planning to go into overtime.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
