<HEADER>
A8129 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-MCDUFFIE     10-09 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-MCDUFFIE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Is Copeland the answer at wide receiver?
 &HT;    By Tom D'Angelo
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ If the Miami Dolphins' wide receivers showed as
much emotion during a recent game as they did in the locker room,
perhaps the blame for Miami's ineffective offense would have been
placed elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   O.J. McDuffie cursed out the print media and refused questions.
The normally talkative Lamar Thomas didn't even look up while
rummaging through his locker. Only newcomer Horace Copeland faced
the onslaught of cameras and note pads. Of course, Copeland didn't
have to worry about being fingered as part of the problem. At least
not until he plays a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The enthusiasm, guys giving high fives, I didn't see a lot of
that,'' Copeland said of Miami's listless loss to the Jets on
Sunday. ``The emotion part is a big part of the game . . . yelling,
getting hyped up. If we can get that going (Monday at
Jacksonville), it will be a better outcome. We missed that.''
</P>
<P>
   Enthusiasm. Sense of urgency. Aggressiveness. The catch words of
the week at Dolphins camp. Coach Jimmy Johnson and his coaches
insist the receivers have the talent and ability to make big plays.
Nevermind that they are ranked 29th in passing offense and as a
group have combined for 76 fewer yards and three fewer TDs than
Minnesota rookie Randy Moss.
</P>
<P>
   With Charles Jordan (groin) out, Copeland will get his chance
Monday. Copeland is 6-feet-3, 210 pounds and has impressed coaches
with his speed. But before he is anointed as the savior, like
Jordan and Lamar Thomas and Oronde Gadsden, Copeland is an NFL
reject, having been released by Tampa Bay in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could help us,'' Johnson said. ``The way the system is now
he should be ready to contribute this week.''
</P>
<P>
   The system has a crack when it comes to the passing game.
Television replays recently continually showed Jets defenders
step-for-step with Dolphins receivers. And Jets later questioned
whether the Dolphins had a clue about where to attack their
defense.
</P>
<P>
   But like Johnson, position coach Robert Ford is shrugging off
the poor performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not overmatched,'' Ford said. ``We were very cautious
in the way we attacked. It was just like we were afraid to go
dadgum to the end of the dadgum limb.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing could not have been worse with Moss, a player Miami
could have selected in the first round if it had not traded down,
showing he may be the next Jerry Rice on national TV recently. Moss
is exactly what Miami needs: a game-breaker who can stretch the
defense and find the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Now Copeland, who signed a two-year contract last week, will be
given a chance to make any kind of plays.
</P>
<P>
   Copeland's best season was as a rookie in 1993 when he had 30
receptions for 633 yards, four TDs and a 21.1 average. He missed
the entire 1996 season after suffering a knee injury in the
pre-season and came back to catch 33 passes for 431 yards last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of the knee surgery, a high salary and his
inability to help on special teams led to the Buccaneers releasing
Copeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know my performance and the way I was practicing wasn't the
reason (he was released),'' Copeland said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good camp. But I understand the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
