<HEADER>
A8131 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-DEMOCRATS10-COX     10-09 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-DEMOCRATS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Disinterest could mean trouble for Democrats, democracy
 &HT;    By Dale Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ In 1992, Ohio voters helped elevate Bill Clinton
to the presidency by going to the polls in the greatest numbers of
the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, Clinton is mired in scandal, the public seems
more disinterested than ever in politics and some experts fear
turnout in the Nov. 3 election will mark an all-time low.
</P>
<P>
   That could spell trouble for the Democratic Party and, some
believe, for the country's form of government as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are witnessing is a progressive meltdown in civic
engagement, a major danger to American democracy,'' said Curtis
Gans, director of the Committee for the Study of the American
Electorate, a nonprofit public policy center located in Washington,
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Gans' study shows voter turnout nationally has decreased 25
percent in the last 36 years, plunging to the the lowest levels in
mid-term history in the 1998 statewide primaries. Ohio and the
Miami Valley mirror those national trends.
</P>
<P>
   Low voter turnout may merely be a symptom of far deeper problems
_ beyond apathy, general satisfaction with the economy or simply
being fed up with l'affair Clinton-Lewinsky-Starr. There is
evidence of widespread loss of faith by people in their government
and other public institutions. The possibility of affecting change
will still draw people to the polls, but those opportunities seem
fewer and farther between.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that people voted because it was the responsible
thing to do,'' said Dennis Lieberman, chairman of the Montgomery
County Democratic Party. ``That is a day gone by.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said that close-to-home issues, such as workers'
compensation, will still draw people to the polls. However, two
issues on the Nov. 3 ballot _ a 2.5-mill refunding renewal levy for
Sinclair Community College and the new Dayton City Charter changes
_ have backers worried that a low turnout could lead to defeat.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Jeff Jacobson of Phillipsburg, chairman of the
Montgomery County Republican Party, said that low voter
participation can hurt both parties, but that the Democratic Party
has seen a loss of active voters nationally in some traditional
strongholds like New York. In this year's primaries, Democrats saw
voter turnout hit record lows in 20 states, according to Gans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you have people too complacent to vote it can hurt
those leading the races as well,'' Jacobson said. ``They don't vote
because they think it is in the bag.''
</P>
<P>
   As recently as 1982, Democrats held a 2-1 ratio over Republicans
in both primaries and registration, Gans' report says. Now
Democrats are in the minority in Congress, governorships and many
state legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Gans notes, the decline in voter participation comes
at a time when there are fewer barriers to voting than at any time
in the nation's history. Women, who won the right to vote in 1920,
started voting in equal numbers as men in the 1980s, and
liberalized voting and registration laws led to the demise of the
whites-only political system that dominated the South for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should have produced higher turnout,'' Gans said. ``What
has eroded over the last three decades is the motivation to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   The high point of public involvement in the political process
were the years 1860 to 1900, according to Walter Dean Burnham,
political science professor at the University of Texas. Lincoln won
the presidency in 1860 with 82 percent of eligible voters showing
up to vote. In the election year of 1898, 92 percent of eligible
voters in Ohio cast a ballot.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the story is quite different.
</P>
<P>
   The report by the Committee for the Study of the American
Electorate found:
</P>
<P>
   Overall turnout of eligible voters fell 10 percent, from 19.4 in
1994 to 17.4 in the 1998 primaries.
</P>
<P>
   The average Democratic turnout fell 12 percent, to a record low
of 9.5 percent of those eligible to vote. Average Republican
turnout was even lower, dropping from 8.7 percent in 1994 to 8
percent in 1998. Based on this average, a majority winner in these
primaries could have emerged the victor with less than 5 percent of
the eligible vote.
</P>
<P>
   Overall turnout in the May primary was down sharply in Ohio,
with both Republicans and Democrats losing voters. Overall turnout
was 24 percent in Montgomery County, 25 percent in Warren County
and 28 percent in Greene County.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis of census data indicates that Americans over the age
of 65 are the only group increasing turnout. Turnouts declined for
both the 25-34 and the 35-44 age groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``That portrays a pretty bleak future for the nation's
leadership,'' Gans said. ``Voting tends to be the lowest common
denominator in politics. People who don't vote don't participate in
anything else, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Low voter turnout also opens the door for relatively small
groups of people committed to a limited agenda to control the
process, Gans said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a situation where an average of less than 5
percent of the electorate can determine the nominees and direction
of either major political party, you are inviting intense factions
to take over one or both parties and skew the public agenda,'' Gans
said.
</P>
<P>
   Common wisdom says that rainy days and low voter turnout favors
Republicans, but Montgomery County Democratic chairman Lieberman
thinks the current downward trend hurts both parties and the entire
electoral political process itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is definitely a problem,'' he said. ``In some elections,
just 17 percent of the people eligible have selected our leaders.
That is not representative of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Gans' study shows that the nation's poorest people _ those
making less than $15,000 _ are among the least frequent voters.
Gans and others believe that debunks the theory that satisfaction
with the economy can lead to voter apathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The poor are completely disenfranchised, they are in a
survival mode,'' Lieberman said. ``We are trying to work on that
because those are our people, but it is difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Reasons for voter apathy are hard to pinpoint, but a report by
the Kettering Foundation, Governing in America, offers some clues.
It was released in June of this year after the foundation conducted
a series of focus groups with citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``What became clear is that despite good economic times people
feel disconnected with our government institutions,'' said John
Doble, who runs a New Jersey research firm and helped prepare the
foundation report.
</P>
<P>
   Among the frustrations voiced were the increasing incivility of
the public debate and the growing influence of money and special
interests, Doble said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel they don't have a voice in the debate,'' he added.
``Citizens are the lifeblood of a democratic society. When people
feel alienated from its institutions, something is seriously
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
