<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reynolds works out payment agreement
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A judge approved Burt Reynolds' plan for
reorganization, and the actor will emerge from bankruptcy
protection in the next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased that this matter is behind me, and I'm now looking
forward to focusing on my work and enjoying time with my family and
friends,'' Reynolds, 62, said in a statement from his Los Angeles
publicist.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds declared more than $10 million in debts when he filed
for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in 1996. Under the plan
approved recently by Judge Paul G. Hyman Jr. in West Palm Beach,
Reynolds will pay creditors 10 percent of his film income up to
$500,000 over the next two to three years. He would keep his $1.17
million Hobe Sound home but most likely lose his BR ranch in
Jupiter Farms.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds' show-business resurgence and prospects for increased
income, which followed his Oscar nomination for Boogie Nights,
helped push through the agreement, lawyers for both sides said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that it was believed that his career was on the
upswing again was a factor,'' said Bob Gilbert, a West Palm Beach
attorney for unsecured creditors _ those who aren't holding any
assets they can seize. Unsecured creditors are in line behind two
mortgage holders and the tax collector, who are owed about $3
million, Gilbert said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, creditors will see less than 20 cents on the dollar,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds has the right to match any sales offer on his $4.6
million, 160-acre ranch and tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.3 million second mortgage on the ranch was in the name of
actress Loni Anderson. In the settlement, $300,000 of that debt is
moved to Reynolds' Hobe Sound home.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson and Reynolds divorced in 1994. Reynolds will continue
$10,000-a-month child support payments for son Quinton, now 10.
</P>
<P>
   In the deal, Reynolds paid creditors $308,000 for personal
effects in the home and ranch. CBS received rights to syndication
of the ``Evening Shade'' television series. And properties Reynolds
owns in Hawaii and Utah will be sold to help pay creditors.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
