<SLUG> BC-ULTIMA-ONLINE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ultima Online's success better than expected
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Which is more perilous _ navigating the swamp in
the computerized, fictional sword-and-sorcery world of Britannia or
answering questions from a roomful of business journalists about
your company, which creates that sword-and-sorcery world?
</P>
<P>
   Richard Garriott, co-founder of Austin's Origin Systems, seemed
equally at ease in both roles as he addressed a Society of American
Business Editors and Writers conference at the Renaissance Hotel in
Austin, recently.
</P>
<P>
   While Origin Systems' Ultima Online game, based on the fantasy
world of Britannia, may be treacherous, it's also more successful
than the company expected, Garriott said.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of the few online games, if not the only one, making
money from game sales as well as monthly subscriptions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The game has 90,000 users who hunt and fish, fight monsters,
talk to each other and train virtual pets to guard their virtual
homes when they leave Britannia to crawl into their real beds to
dream virtual dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists reacted with audible suprise when Garriott told them
the average time an Ultima online user spends with the game is 3
1/2 hours a day. An earlier speaker said that Web surfers stay at
even the most popular Web sites for less than 10 minutes a day on
average.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are playing way longer than we anticipated,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Garriott _ tall, sandy-haired, dressed in jeans and an Austin
essential blue workshirt bearing an Origin logo _ is considered a
legend and old-timer in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   For 20 years, Garriott has been the creator and guiding force of
Ultima, a series of games that go back to the early days of Apple's
first computers. After selling Origin to Electronic Arts Inc., a
public company based in San Mateo, Calif., Garriott became more
involved in business strategy than in developing games. With Ultima
Online and the Wing Commander series, Garriott thinks more about
distribution methods, brand management, cultivating and keeping a
strong team _ in short, the boring business stuff that's far from
the virtual world of Britannia.
</P>
<P>
   He said he doesn't mind working for a big company _ with the
complexity of games (for one game: the average cost, $10 million;
time, two to five years; staff, up to 50 workers), he says it's
necessary to be sizable.
</P>
<P>
   That's changed from the days when he made $150,000 for a few
weeks' work after his first game was published in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   He likens the current state of the game industry to Hollywood's
film eras _ experimentation, the rise of a studio system and the
breakout of the independents. Successful games, he said, make more
money than most movies.
</P>
<P>
   And it may go further: ``My goal is to create the first
completely virtual (reality) world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
