<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ There are two struggles going on in the House
Judiciary Committee. One, arguably the lesser, is over the fate of
William Jefferson Clinton. The other struggle, arguably the larger,
is over the cultural disposition of the nation. (Teepen, Cox News
Service) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ There will come a day when a challenge will
be made to the stipulation that presidents be native-born. It may
not be in the next few decades but certainly it will come.
(Kleinberg, Cox News Service) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-COLUMN _ PARIS _ It's Sunday, 4 p.m., and tea time for
Americans in Paris who gather at George Whitman's famed bookstore,
Shakespeare &AMP; Co., just across the River Seine from Notre Dame
Cathedral. Unfortunately, they're all talking about Bill and
Monica. (Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ Personal character, a sage once
said, is how you behave when no one is looking. We already know
that, as a private person, Bill Clinton has flunked his character
test. What we do not know as yet is whether Congress will see fit
to remove him for his bad acts. (Glass, Cox News Service) MOVED
THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ With all the paid-for lies and distortions
running on television this political season, I was heartened to
read something Roy Barnes said on a campaign trip to Jesup,
population 10,000 more or less, deep in southeast Georgia. ``It's
going to be a close election, and I think it's going to be decided
south of Macon,'' he predicted. (Minter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ It's far too hot for an October night,
especially inside the Nacogdoches Expo Center, where there's not a
hint of a breeze. I soon realize I've overdressed for the
Superstars of Wrestling
</P>
<P>
   Extravaganza about to take place. (Borders, Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel) MOVED.
