<P>
   These feature stories for release Oct. 10, 1998, are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-DEMOCRATS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ In 1992, Ohio voters helped
elevate Bill Clinton to the presidency by going to the polls in the
greatest numbers of the past two decades. Six years later, Clinton
is mired in scandal, the public seems more disinterested than ever
in politics and some experts fear turnout in the Nov. 3 election
will mark an all-time low. (Dempsey, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ULTIMA-ONLINE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Which is more perilous _
navigating the swamp in the fictional sword-and-sorcery world of
Britannia or answering questions from a roomful of business
journalists about your company, which creates that
sword-and-sorcery world? Richard Garriott, co-founder of Austin's
Origin Systems, seemed equally at ease in both roles, recently.
(Gallaga, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GANG-PLEA _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Vowing to place Texas at the
forefront of curbing prison gangs, state prison officials are
developing new programs to entice convicts to renounce their gang
membership and to reduce gang violence. (Ward, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WASTE-SITE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ A delegation of Mexican officials
urged the Bush administration and state lawmakers recently to block
a proposed disposal site for low-level radioactive waste.
(Haurwitz, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EYMAN-ON-BOOKS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Surfing San Onofre to
Point Dume: 1936-1942 (Chronicle, $24.95) is a superlative
collection of photographs by the late Don James, who was in at the
inception of the coming of surfing to Southern California in the
1930s. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-B/O _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ BUILDING A COMPANY: Roy O.
Disney and the Creation of an Entertainment Empire, by Bob Thomas.
Hyperion; 359 pages; $24.95. At one point in this resolutely
interesting biography of the other Disney, someone speculates that,
without his brother, Walt Disney would have been a mediocre
cartoonist for somebody else's company. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   SWITZER _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Barry Switzer, easy rider and former
football coach, is a busy man. When he isn't riding his
Harley-Davidson on scenic highways, he is visiting Hollywood movie
sets, opening restaurants and making cameo appearances on an
Oklahoma City TV station. (Cantu, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-OPENHAND _ Project Open Hand, the remarkable meal
delivery program for AIDS patients, celebrates its 10th anniversary
in September. Everything, from preparation of meals to their daily
delivery to clients, is done in house, largely through volunteers.
A look at the operation, its impact, and some of the volunteers
(100 per day) who make it possible. (Henry, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   FILMS-HEAVEN _ Heaven may be wonderful to dream about, but it
sure is hard to capture on film. Such a problem, however, hasn't
stopped filmmakers from trying. With the recent release (Oct. 3) of
``What Dreams May Come?'' yet one more producer is attempting to
sell his idea of heaven. (Blake, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA
8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   HOME &AMP; GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   PIANOS _ Suzy Berliner and Sandy Hartman may not play the piano,
but their elegant white grand does far more than collect dust _ it
makes a nice backdrop for cat hair. That's because their large
black and white Himalayan, Rhett Butler, is the only one in their
house who uses the piano _ for a snooze under the top. Pianos are
in harmony with a growing number of middle-class Americans and are
performing a new role _ as decoration. And that's not such a sad
note as the musical instrument celebrates 300 years. (Flanders,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   W/PIANO-TIPS _ Tips for buying a piano. (Flanders, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
