<HEADLINE>
CHANGES HAP PEN AS COYOTES SHAKE UP ROSTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, ARIZ. - The opening day of Coyotes' training camp
this fall looked more like a White House reception line than a
hockey practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, I'm Greg Adams.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, nice to see you. I'm Keith Carney.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, I'm Jyrki Lumme. I'm looking forward to playing with
you this season.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, thanks. By the way, I'm Louie DeBrusk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's up, man? My name's Jim Cummins. They call me Kong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey there, Kong. I'm Mike Sullivan. The pleasure's mine.''
</P>
<P>
   After that initial workout, right wing Dallas Drake remembers
walking over to his locker and looking around the room. Players
were still greeting each other, shaking hands and getting to know
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I know half these guys,'' Drake said at the
time. ``I knew there were going to be a lot of changes this year,
but I had no idea we were going to see so many news faces. There's
a ton of 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 38 players who appeared in at least one game last season
for Phoenix, 14 are gone. In their place are 13 new players who
weren't with the club when it opened the season a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   No other team in the NHL made as many roster changes as the
Coyotes did in the offseason. It was by design, according to
General Manager Bobby Smith, who had his hands full with just
trying to re-sign a herd of his own free agents, let alone scanning
all of pro hockey to find a bunch of others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we significantly improved our team in the past year,''
Smith said. ``It wasn't easy, but I'm convinced the team we put on
the ice for opening night, 1998, will be far better than the one we
had on opening night, 1997.''
</P>
<P>
   Time will tell, but do all the changes guarantee the Coyotes of
advancing beyond the first round of the playoffs for only the third
time in the fracnhise's 20-year history?
</P>
<P>
   Captain Keith Tkachuk, who ended what could have become a
season-long holdout by agreeing to a restructured contract two
weeks into camp, seems convinced this is the group that can finally
get the job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really addressed some key areas and I think this will be
the strongest team we've put on the ice in years,'' said Tkachuk,
whose 205 goals are the third-most among any NHLer in the past five
seasons. ``The important thing is to go out, get a good start, get
some wins, and hopefully, when it comes down to the stretch drive,
we'll have the players to get us to that next level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows for sure? But I'm really happy with this team. I
love this team. We've got some balanced scoring now, a solid D, and
a great goaltender. Now we've just got to put it together.''
</P>
<P>
   It starts Sunday, when the new-look Coyotes open their third
season in the Valley against the Ottawa Senators at America West
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Just getting Tkachuk back into the fold was a change many
players weren't exactly counting on. Had Smith not decided to make
one last contract pitch to the power forward midway through camp,
the chances were very real the Coyotes wouldn't have their leading
scorer from each of the past three seasons around anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   But he's back, and the left wing brings with him 40 to 50 goals
the team can count on. It more than balances out the 45 goals
Phoenix lost by purging the 14 players from last season.
</P>
<P>
   The main substractions were Tkachuk's personal play-making
center, Craig Janney, 700-goal scorer Mike Gartner, defenseman
Murray Baron, enforcer Jim McKenzie, left wing Darrin Shannon, and
center prospect Chad Kilger, who was dealt to Chicago in March for
defenseman Keith Carney and right wing Jim Cummins.
</P>
<P>
   The additions of Carney and Cummins were only the beginning.
Smith landed perhaps the best defenseman on the free-agent market
in July by signing Vancouver's Jyrki Lumme to a four-year deal. He
will start the season on the No. 1 defensive unit with fellow Finn
Teppo Numminen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a solid, two-way defenseman,'' Numminen said of Lumme, a
10-year pro who plays power play, kills penalties and four times
has reached the 40-point mark. ``He does everything well.''
</P>
<P>
   With Numminen and Lumme, Oleg Tverdovsky and Carney, and Gerald
Diduck and players such as Deron Quint, Michel Petit and Sean
Gagnon, the Coyotes' defense is as strong as it ever has been,
according to Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like our defense, too,'' said Diduck, a 14-year
veteran. ``It's definitely an improvement over last year. Oley and
Q are younger and better. Carney really came on last year. We've
got lots of guys who can move the pu ck and know the game and where
to be in your own end. We work well with the sys tem, work well
with the forwards, and we're getting a raport going with Niki
(Khabibulin) in net, where we're using each other as three guys in
that zone and we can shut a lot of things down.''
</P>
<P>
   If there's a knock on the blueline, it's that the defense may
lack some size and toughness. Diduck, though disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teppo's not a punishing checker, but he throws hits,'' Diduck
said. ``Carns hits guys. So does Jyrki. ... Look, the game has
changed now. You can be a punishing checker, but the way they've
changed the rules around, if you're missing your hits, you can't
get that extra grab on a guy. So it's a higher risk play now to be
an aggressive, body-checking defenseman. You've got more
opportunities for things to go wrong now.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was starting out, you could chase guys around all day
and battle guys without the puck all over the place. They're
getting away from that. What you want now are guys who can move,
know where to be on the ice, and be their ahead of time. If you
look at our defense, I think that's exactly what we have.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes also finally have some goal-scoring depth at left
wing behind Tkachuk. Smith solved that problem by signing Greg
Adams of Dallas as a free agent. The former standout at Northern
Arizona University, Adams, 35, is capable of a 25-goal season by
skating with the likes of Jeremy Roenick or Cliff Ronning. He's had
injury problems the past few seasons, but Adams has looked great in
the preseason and he has been healthy so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``With what they've been able to add this year, there should be
no more excuses,'' Tkachuk said. ``There should never be any
excuses for any team,'' Drake said. ``You do your best, you play
hard, and you should win a lot of hockey games. That doesn't just
go for us, but for every team in he NHL. We're no exception. But
yeah, definitely, there are no more excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   If there are, there could be even more changes next year. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
