<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-NEW-DIVISION-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGES: COYOTES WELCOME NEW RIVALS IN NEW DIVISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. - For a guy who isn't particularly excited
about flying in airplanes to begin with, Coyotes defenseman Oleg
Tverdovsky took about one nanosecond to explain what he likes most
about playing in a new division this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Less travel, a lot less travel,'' the fifth-year pro from
Moscow said. ``Those long, three- to five-hour flights are going to
be almost cut in half, and that's the best part of it, no question
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the NHL's realignment for this season, the Coyotes
moved out of the Central Division, where they were paired with
Toronto, Detroit, Chicago and St. Louis, and joined Dallas by
transferring to the Pacific Division with its three
California-based teams, Los Angeles, Anaheim and San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 45-minute flight to a place like Anaheim or LA,'' Tverdovsky
said, ``beats a 3{-hour flight to Detroit or Chicago in a
heartbeat. . . . I couldn't stand those long, long trips all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes still will make the occasional jaunt to the Midwest
and East Coast, but instead of playing teams such as the Red Wings
and the Maple Leafs at least three times away from home, that will
usually happen only once. In some circumstances, they won't even
travel to certain Eastern Conference cities.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Phoenix plays the Carolina Hurricanes only once
this season _ and it's at America West Arena. Next year, Pittsburgh
could be left off the road list. Or maybe Washington or Boston or
Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   In the Pacific, the Coyotes will play divisional foes six times
apiece. That accounts for 24 games out of the 82-game schedule _
and probably tens of thousands of reduced miles aboard a cramped
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really going to be the most beneficial thing for us,''
Coach Jim Schoenfeld said. ``We had very tough travel last year.
And it really wears on you after a while. It affects you in a lot
of ways, and it alters your routine. Among other things, you don't
always get good practices on the road because of it.''
</P>
<P>
   When the change was announced before last season, it was widely
thought the Coyotes would be putting themselves in a much greater
position to challenge for a division championship by moving into
the Pacific. Sure, Dallas was seen as a visible threat, but Los
Angeles, San Jose and Anaheim weren't exactly viewed as Stanley
Cup-contending material.
</P>
<P>
   It had to be better than slugging it out against Central rivals
such as Chicago, St. Louis and Detroit _ the pure essence of what
used to be the old black-and-blue Norris Division.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld, though, doesn't buy into that theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``On any given night, you can get beat (in the Pacific), so you
have to be at your best,'' he said. ``I don't think we're any
better or worse off that way. With players changing teams as
rapidly as they do and coaches changing teams as rapidly as they
do, it's hard to identify a division as the skating division or the
black-and-blue division anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at one year, when the high-flying Pittsburgh Penguins
became a great defensive team with great goaltending and a
different coaching staff. It happens all the time now. I think you
have to be careful when you start labeling one division as this and
another division as that because it's always changing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes aren't the only team moving to a new division. The
NHL abandoned its two-division format in each conference and went
to a three-division lineup, creating a Southeast Division in the
East and a Northwest Division in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, Florida in Tampa Bay are leaving the Atlantic
Division for the Southeast, where they will be joined by Carolina,
which leaves the Northeast. Pittsburgh also leaves the Northeast to
join Philadelphia, New Jersey and the Rangers and Islanders in the
Atlantic. Toronto, meanwhile, has switched conferences altogether,
leaving the Central for the Northeast to join Boston, Buffalo,
Montreal and Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   In the Western Conference, Calgary, Edmonton, Vancouver and
Colorado leave the Pacific to form the Northwest Division. And
joining Chicago, Detroit and St. Louis in the Central is the
expansion Nashville Predators, the first of four expansion clubs
that will be unveiled by 2000-2001.
</P>
<P>
   Next season, Atlanta will join the Southeast. In two years,
Columbus will join the Central and Minnesota will join the
Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be great not having to play Detroit five, six
times a year,'' Coyotes forward Dallas Drake said, ``but it doesn't
get any easier having to play a team like LA or San Jose, who both
are better hockey teams this year. There's so much parity in the
league now. I don't know if it makes that much difference where you
play.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
