<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 11:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8234 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     10-09 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, Oct. 9, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Saturday and Sunday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DEBARTOLO (Baton Rouge, La.) _ Pleading guilty to a felony in
federal court was a doubly humiliating experience for Eddie J.
DeBartolo, Jr. Not only did he admit to a crime, he also had to
tell the whole world that he was not a stand-up guy and would spill
the beans on an old friend in exchange for lenient treatment. By
ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   POLICE-TRAINING (San Francisco) The fatal shooting of a
prominent advertising executive in his car _ the latest in a series
of similar incidents _ has prompted San Francisco Police Chief Fred
Lau to order specialized training to help cops handle or avoid such
confrontations. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA and RAY DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   BLUE-ANGELS (San Francisco) _ When you are flying upside down at
500 mph and a problem comes up, it's always nice to have a soothing
presence nearby. For the Blue Angel pilots who will be flying the
Navy's F-18 Hornets over the Bay this weekend, ``Betty'' _ or
rather her voice _ provides such a presence. By JACOB H. FRIES.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ROUGH-RIDER-COLLECTION (Albany, N.Y.) _ As politician, writer,
naturalist, hunter, war hero and rugged adventurer, everything
about Teddy Roosevelt was outsize, and so is the TR collection at
its new home in the New York State Library. The library paid a
private collector $200,000 for the estimated 300,000 items _
including teddy bears. By PAUL GRONDAHL. (For release Sunday, Oct.
11)
</P>
<P>
   BEAUTIFUL-TABLES (Great Barrington, Mass.) _ Setting a beautiful
table can be half the fun of creating a great dining experience. In
her latest book, ``Modern Antiques for the Table'' (Penguin),
author Sheila Chefetz takes the novice and seasoned collector
through the paces of gracious table settings with tableware
antiques from 1890 to 1940. By FRANCES INGRAHAM. (For release
Sunday, Oct. 11)
</P>
<P>
   SNUFF-BOTTLES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Creating a collection is fun,
especially when you've collected bibelots and find they have
appreciated in value over time. Some items, of course, can also
turn into gold mines. For example, snuff bottles. By FRANCES
INGRAHAM. (For release Sunday, Oct. 11).
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ Direct buying is putting the
manufacturers of personal computers on alert. Increasingly, those
who have owned PCs are buying direct, a trend that has alarmed
computer makers who push their goods through retailers. By DWIGHT
SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ Mail servers provide a safe home
for e-mail when your computer is down. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-DEVIL (Undated) _ There's a scene in ``Love Is the
Devil,'' the shockingly real film subtitled ``study for a portrait
of Francis Bacon,'' in which Derek Jacobi, who plays the celebrated
British painter, starts to paint a picture. By DAVID BONETTI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-COP (Undated) _ Enjoyment of ``One Tough Cop,'' the
new film directed by Bruno Barreto and starring Stephen Baldwin in
a fictionalized account of real-life New York policeman Bo Dietl,
is entirely dependent on the expectations the viewer brings to the
movie. If you want some gritty mean streets drama about a loner cop
bucking the system, kicking tail and throwing televisions out of
tenement windows _ Bingo, you're there. By CRAIG MARINE.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-MANNERS (Undated) _ An academic couple and their
house guests have a long, boozy encounter filled with verbal
sparring, sexual tension, shifting alliances, humiliations and
revelations. ``Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?'' _ right? But it's
also a spot-on summary of ``Bad Manners,'' Jonathan Kaufer's new
dark comedy. By WALTER ADDIEGO.
</P>
<P>
   SPECTOR-MUSIC-PROFILE (Houston) _ Before the Spice Girls and
Madonna, before Courtney Love and Chrissie Hynde, before Diana Ross
and the Supremes and Martha and the Vandellas, there was Ronnie
Spector. As the lead singer of the '60s-era Ronettes, Spector
defined a sound and a look that had a profound influence on
subsequent generations of female rockers. By RICK MITCHELL.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SPORTS-NIGHT (Albany, N.Y.) _ ``Sports Night'' stands out in
style from every other sitcom on television. But its uniqueness
wasn't enough for the ABC, which decreed that this show about a
fictional sports cable network must have a laugh track. The
producers of the show didn't want it, but, as is the case in most
of these battles, the network won. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   ANTZ-FILM-ANIMATION (Undated) _ In the battle of the bugs, the
popular movie ``Antz'' leads the way in computer animation. By
BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-FIRELIGHT (Undated) _ Ever wonder what ``Jane Eyre''
might have been like if Charlotte Bronte had watched too many
soaps? Wonder no longer, because here we have ``Firelight,'' a
well-meaning, sufficiently well-acted but ultimately lachrymose
cross between chest-heaving Victorian melodrama and ``As The World
Turns.'' By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-HOLY (Undated) _ Eddie Murphy and Jeff Goldblum, two
actors one doesn't usually associate with low energy, star in a
living retread, ``Holy Man.'' Part ``Network,'' part ``Truman
Show'' and fully boring, ``Holy Man'' asks us to believe that a
spiritual man can help sell products on a home-shopping channel by
telling the viewers not to buy products. By G. ALLEN JOHNSON.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-PROFILE-OPRAH (BOSTON) _ When Oprah Winfrey breezed into
Beantown on a press tour for her new film ``Beloved,'' she greeted
reporters with an easy, unaffected familiarity. She made eye
contact. She memorized names. Articulate, quick-witted,
self-deprecating and smart, she answered questions with candor and
heat, discussing the film and the Toni Morrison book on which it's
based in impassioned bursts of talk. By AMY BIANCOLLI. (For release
Sunday, Oct. 11.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Linda Pershing is annoyed. She
gets calls from public opinion pollsters who want to ask her
questions. But when she asks them questions, such as who is
sponsoring the poll, she gets cut off. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
</TEXT>
