<HEADER>
A8256 &Cx1f; tab-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUXURY-ON-THE-SLOPES-     10-09 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUXURY-ON-THE-SLOPES-TRAVEL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARMING HOTELS ON THE SLOPES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers. HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A
FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW
IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR PAGES!)
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By EVERETT POTTER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Now is the time to start planning this season's ski vacation.
For skiers in need of some pampering, here are eight of the most
atmospheric places on the slopes. Rates are based on double
occupancy in January.
 &HT;    Taos might seem like a high desert mirage of purple skies and
snow-white powder. But that miraculous Southwest powder that
inspired Georgia O'Keefe is no mirage. Here in laid back Taos, the
Inn at Snakedance (Box 89, Taos Ski Valley, N.M. 87525;
800-322-9815) counts as high fashion. The rooms are comfortable but
simple, the fireplaces welcome, a television the only hint of
luxury.
 &HT;    Skiers don't come here to watch CNN, however, but to earn their
stripes among moguls the size of adobe pueblos. Rates from $175,
including breakfast.
 &HT;    Aspen has four extraordinary mountains, the best restaurants in
ski country and a wallop of glitterati. It also has more than its
share of places that would qualify as a romantic retreats.
 &HT;    But the sybarites' choice has to be The Little Nell (675 E.
Durant, Aspen, Colo. 81611; 800-525-6200). As smooth as hazelnut
gelato, the last word in subtle, this slope-side hotel compares
favorably with the best in the world.
 &HT;    From impeccable service to marble baths and Frette robes, the
Little Nell attempts to give its guests the feeling of being the
most important person in the world. Rates from $475.
 &HT;    The Spring Creek Resort (P.O. Box 3154, Jackson Wyo. 83001
800-443-6139) has views of the snowcapped Tetons and grazing elk
herds. The hotel is a cozy place where wood-paneled bedrooms come
with a wood-burning fireplace.
 &HT;    The Granary restaurant offers a bountiful skiers breakfast, just
the thing for negotiating Corbet's Couloir on a pair of K-2s or
heading down one of the less intimidating runs at Jackson Hole.
Rates from $190 including breakfast.
 &HT;    Adjacent to Spring Creek is the newly opened Amangani (P.O. Box
15030, Jackson Wyo. 83002; 800-443-6139), which offers sybarites a
totally different kind of pleasure.
 &HT;    The first resort in this luxury chain to open in the continental
United States, the rooms have a sleek, quasi-oriental design,
drop-dead views and a quiet demeanor that suits a chain whose best
known properties are in Bali. Rates here start at $400.
 &HT;    At Sundance (RR4, Box A1, Sundance, Utah 84604; 800-892-1600),
there are few lights, no cameras and all of the action is on the
slopes.
 &HT;    An hour from Salt Lake City, Sundance is actor Robert Redford's
retreat at the base of Mount Timpanogos, the highest peak in the
Wasatch Range. The accommodations at Sundance are an idealized
version of what a cabin should be, with pine interiors, stone
fireplaces and rustic furniture with just the right amount of
cowboy chic. Cap the night at the screening room, which has
Hollywood-quality sound and vision. Rates from $195 and includes
breakfast.
 &HT;    Take the most dramatic mountain scenery in North America, add a
Relais &AMP; Chateaux property, and position it five minutes away from
Lake Louise, Canada's largest ski area. That's why the cognoscenti
cozy up at the Post Hotel (P.O. Box 69, Lake Louise, Alberta,
Canada, T0L 1E0; 800-661-1586) in Lake Louise.
 &HT;    Swiss brothers George and Andre Schwarz run this alpine
chalet-style property, which features rooms paneled with Canadian
pine, whirlpool tubs and fieldstone fireplaces. That same decor is
featured in what is arguably the best dining room in the Canadian
Rockies.
 &HT;    The cooking is by Chef Wolfgang Vogt, the award-winning 15,000
bottle wine cellar is a treat and the dinnertime pianist isn't bad
either. Call it north woods rustic meets European civilization at
discounted Canadian prices. Starting in January, rates will begin
at about $110 U.S.
 &HT;    Visitors are know to hum ``Edelweiss'' on their horse-drawn
sleigh ride around the 2,200-acre Trapp Family Lodge (42 Trapp Hill
Road, Stowe Vt. 05672; 800-826-7000). The ``Sound of Music'' family
bought this farm outside of Stowe Village in 1940 because it
reminded them so much of Austria.
 &HT;    Rebuilt and updated, the Tyrolean-style rooms come with a duvet
and a balcony with an Alpine-style view of the mountains.
 &HT;    Johannes von Trapp, the youngest of the 10 children of Maria and
the Baron, not only runs the lodge but laid out the resort's 100
kilometers of cross-country trails back in 1968, the first
dedicated Nordic center in North America.
 &HT;    The lodge is a few minutes from the prototypical mountain
village of Stowe, the downhill pleasures of Mt. Mansfield and the
headquarters of Ben &AMP; Jerry's. Rates from $140.
 &HT;    The Peaks Resort &AMP; Spa (P.O. Box 2702, Telluride, Colo. 81435;
800-789-2220) Facials, massage and a yoga class are the perfect way
to unwind after a day in San Juan Mountain powder.
 &HT;    The 42,000-square-foot spa at the Peaks lays claim to being the
best spa at any ski resort. Think of this as a contemporary
mountain chateau, with good-size rooms, terry-cloth robes and
generous bathrooms. Not to mention terraces with views of 14,000
foot peaks.
 &HT;    The hotel is a gondola ride away from the heart of the
Victorian-era mining town of Telluride, perhaps the most beautiful
ski town in America. Rates from $405.
 ---- 
 &HT;     (Everett Potter is a New York-based free-lance writer.)  
