<HEADER>
A8314 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GREENSPAN-EUROPE-HNS &LR;      10-09 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN-EUROPE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEANS ARE CHILLED BY GREENSPAN'S WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ When Federal Reserve chief Alan Greenspan said this week
that in 50 years as a financial analyst he had never seen anything
like the recent turbulence that has struck financial markets, he
sent a wave of cold apprehension through Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan is not, to put it mildly, known as someone who
over-dramatizes events. His speeches have in the past drawn stifled
yawns of boredom from his audiences. The Fed chairman has built his
reputation as a cautious and balanced analyzer of economic trends.
He is widely regarded as the most asute central banker of the
world's top industrial nations, partly because of his usual care
not to say something he might later regret.
</P>
<P>
   So when even he publicly ackowledged he was caught by surprise
by the speed of the markets' sharp dip and the downward movement of
the dollar, his foreign peers became seriously concerned. Le
Figaro, France's biggest newspaper, said it was surprised at his
pessimistic tone.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he has declared several times in recent months that the
continuing Wall Street bull market might not be justified by the
hard economic facts. But he always cushioned his statements by
adding that the economy was still in fine shape. This week, the
cushion was nowhere to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   His latest remarks were interpreted here as signaling that
Asia's year-old credit crunch _ a polite way of saying banks won't
lend you any money _ has now struck the United States and that
business executives have become shy about further expansion.
</P>
<P>
   There appeared to be little evidence of any of this as recently
as late summer. U.S. banks, unlike many in Japan and elsewhere in
Asia, are stable and, as far as we know, mainly profitable. And
hardly a day went by without the announcement of some multi-billion
dollar industrial or financial institutional merger.
</P>
<P>
   Now, suddenly, investors are quitting the American market in a
strategy of ``risk aversion,'' London's Financial Times reports. It
quotes one financial adviser as explaining that ``everybody is
rushing for the exits ... not just those involved in so-called
hedge funds.''
</P>
<P>
   The near crash last month of Long-Term Capital Management, L.P.,
a leading hedge fund, is blamed by many for the change in the
economic outlook. Hedge funds make money _ or lose it _ essentially
by betting on changing values between different currencies.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the storm, the dollar, previously the world's
strongest currency, took the heaviest hammering. The dollar's most
spectacular losses were against the yen. But most experts said this
had virtually nothing to do with the respective economies of the
United States and Japan. ``There has been no upward reassessment of
the Japanese economy,'' said French banker Emil Miller.
</P>
<P>
   He and other specialists said the dollar fell largely as a
result of hedge funds being forced to cash in to cover their losses
in the emerging markets of Asia and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   As Greenspan might have said, but didn't: It's a crazy world.
And there is likely to be more to come.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 1242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
