<HEADER>
A8422 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-LETOURNEAU-EUROP     10-09 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-LETOURNEAU-EUROPE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK DETAILS RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN BOY, FORMER TEACHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KIMBERLY A.C. WILSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Betrayal is the first sensation 15-year-old Vili Fualaau recalls
feeling when he learned that Mary K. Letourneau, his former grade
school teacher, was pregnant with his second child.
</P>
<P>
   In a tell-all book released in Europe this week, the teen
Letourneau was convicted of raping last year reveals his shock at
learning that he had fathered another child.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the impression that she had wronged me, or lied,
something like that,'' Fualaau recalls in the 300-page paperback,
``Un Seul Crime, L'Amour'' _ French for ``Only One Crime, Love.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really overwhelmed because I didn't really feel ready
for another baby. I already had problems with the first,'' Fualaau
says.
</P>
<P>
   The book, written by Letourneau, 36, and Fualaau with the help
of a ghostwriter, is not yet available in the United States or in
English.
</P>
<P>
   It was released in French this week at a book fair in Frankfurt,
Germany. A French publisher offered the most money for the book _
and French readers may more easily accept the tale as a love story.
</P>
<P>
   While Fualaau receives most of the $250,000 advance, sources
close to the deal say, Letourneau will not get a cent. Her share
will be awarded to Fualaau, their 18-month-old daughter and their
unborn child.
</P>
<P>
   The publishing house, Laffont, would not confirm particulars.
</P>
<P>
   The book details the illicit affair that cost the former
Shoreline Elementary School teacher her career, her marriage, her
freedom and custody of her five children, and thrust her favorite
sixth-grade pupil into teen fatherhood and notoriety.
</P>
<P>
   The book _ and the baby, when it arrives _ could end up being
used as evidence against Letourneau, who is in prison in Gig
Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   One or more new criminal charges could be filed after the birth
of the latest child if it turns out Fualaau is the father, said Dan
Donahoe, a spokesman for King County Prosecutor Norm Maleng.
</P>
<P>
   Each chapter of the book is written from the perspective of
Letourneau, Fualaau, or his mother, Soona. Irish writer Bob Graham
wrote the book from tape-recorded interviews with Letourneau at the
Washington State Corrections Center for Women, and the Fualaaus at
their home in Burien.
</P>
<P>
   With its cover photograph of baby Audrey cradled in Letourneau's
arms, much of the book dwells on protestations by Letourneau and
Fualaau that love cannot be outlawed.
</P>
<P>
   But there are revelations, as well:
</P>
<P>
   _ Though ordered to have no contact with Fualaau after she was
arrested and charged with raping him in 1997, Letourneau asked the
boy to drive her to the hospital for the birth of Audrey, now 18
months old. The teen, then 13, did not have a driver's license and
hadn't learned to drive a manual transmission. Though he managed to
drive part of the way, Letourneau, in the midst of contractions,
was later forced to take the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   _ Released from jail on Jan. 2 after serving six months in the
King County Regional Justice Center on two counts of second-degree
rape of a child, Letourneau immediately resumed contact with the
teen, speaking by phone, communicating by pager and meeting late at
night.
</P>
<P>
   _ During her month of freedom in January, while she was under
close monitoring and treatment as a convicted sex offender,
Letourneau hid Fualaau in the Seward Park home where she was
staying. For two nights _ without the knowledge of her hostess _
they slept together in a bed and on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shortly before a police cruiser knocked on the steamy window
of Letourneau's gray compact car early on Feb. 3, Letourneau
threatened to kill herself, according to Fualaau. In response, he
promised to do the same, to fulfill a ``Romeo and Juliet scenario''
they had previously discussed. She was rearrested that night for
violating the terms of a suspended sentence by having contact with
Fualaau.
</P>
<P>
   Soona Fualaau, who has given her blessing to a future union
between Letourneau and her son, describes in the book how she came
to accept the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a simple woman. I understand simple things,'' she says in
the book's prologue. ``The court says she committed a crime. The
rape of my son ... I know, myself, that it wasn't a rape, and God
knows it, too. Yes, it was adultery, that I don't dispute, but not
a rape. They don't know my son.''
</P>
<P>
   A worldly-sounding Vili Fualaau, who entered the ninth grade
this fall, said his his attraction to Letourneau was
``inexplicable, love. You feel it, that's all and you know what it
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Letourneau asks for understanding:``We took, I know, a road
different from others, the road less traveled, but we're no longer
in the Middle Ages, when they burned women, the unfaithful, the
witches, who dared to love outside their marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Letourneau nor Fualaau would comment on the book.
</P>
<P>
   Fualaau left Seattle for Paris on Wednesday for a book tour with
his lawyer, Bob Huff.
</P>
<P>
   Letourneau's estranged husband, Steve, also would not comment
about the book. He once told a reporter he was considering his own
book deal, as were a British physicist who befriended Letourneau, a
Puget Sound crime writer and the two attorneys who have represented
both Letourneau and Fualaau. But in a brief telephone interview
Thursday, there was both relief and exhaustion in Steve
Letourneau's voice when he said, ``No,'' afterall, he doesn't plan
to write a book.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
