<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'TIS THE SEASON FOR POLL-VAULTING 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Linda Pershing is annoyed. I can't blame her.
</P>
<P>
   She teaches at the State University of New York at Albany. She's
on sabbatical. She's working at her home in the Albany suburb of
Guilderland. Her husband works nights for an airline. And, while
she's trying to work and he's trying to sleep, her phone is ringing
with disturbing regularity.
</P>
<P>
   Who's calling? This is an election year. So the callers are
pollsters, naturally.
</P>
<P>
   Pershing said: ``They just kept calling the house over and over
again ... What they do is start out with this spiel, `We just want
to ask you a few questions. It'll just take a few minutes time.'
And they talk so fast that you can't get a word in. And before you
can say boo, pretty soon the person starts rattling off questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed real clear to me that they were trying to figure out
how voters were feeling about some political issues ... When I
asked for information about who was sponsoring this _ I asked for
an address, a phone and a name _ I got hung up on. The second time,
I said, `Do not hang up on me. I want to talk to your supervisor.'
</P>
<P>
   ``This person put me on hold, and I eventually talked to his
supervisor. And this man who was the supervisor refused to give me
that information ... he explained to me that that's not public
information, and that he could not give it to me ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Well, that's interesting. You're going to bother
me in my home and ask my opinion, and you're not going to tell me
who you are.' ... And then that's when I thought, `Gee, there's
something wrong going on here.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' I explained to Pershing. ``They never give you that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope. They don't want you to know who's calling because
they're afraid that if you're an activist and you have a point of
view hostile to their candidate that you'll lie. You see, it's my
own personal belief that anybody, when contacted by a pollster, has
a duty to lie through his or her teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I say that is that too much of government is run by
polls and too much of the political process is dictated by polls.
You've got all these sniveling cowards in public office who're
afraid to act on the dictates of their consciences.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I think that everybody should lie on every single political
polling question.''
</P>
<P>
   And, you know, that really is the way to fix things. Politicians
are so attentive to polls for a perfectly rational reason. They're
tremendously effective mechanisms for measuring public sentiment at
a precise moment in time. Professionally conducted polls produce
remarkably accurate snapshots of public opinion at that moment.
Politicians well understand that you can obtain a snapshot like
that on a statewide or even a national basis with calls to maybe
800 people. It's relatively cheap, and the science is definitely
for real. This stuff works.
</P>
<P>
   Now you might not believe that. You might be one of those people
who sneer at poll results because you have never been called and/or
because you can't conceive that so few people could share your view
of the world.
</P>
<P>
   You are wrong, though. For evidence, just take a look at how
many political dollars are spent on this stuff _ and how many
commercial dollars, too, by companies doing market research.
</P>
<P>
   Lying to commercial pollsters would be a mistake _ unless, of
course, you want to see a lot of cars on the road with three
wheels.
</P>
<P>
   But lying to political pollsters? Hey, that's no mistake. That's
patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   And ethical, too. It's perfectly OK to lie in what you believe
to be a just cause, even under oath.
</P>
<P>
   Thats what the polls say, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
