A8448 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-HOUSE-BOS &LR;      10-09 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HOUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE VOTES TO LAUNCH CLINTON IMPEACHMENT INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WASHINGTON _ A divided House embarked Thursday on an American
odyssey, launching a full-scale investigation into whether
President Clinton should forfeit his office over charges he tried
to cover up his sexual affair with a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   In a dramatic moment in presidential history, the House voted
258-176 to conduct an open-ended probe into Clinton's possible
impeachment, only the third such inquiry since the nation was
founded.
</P>
<P>
   Despite widespread concerns about the potential consequences for
the presidency, Congress and the country, 31 Democrats joined the
united Republican majority in approving the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an onerous, miserable, rotten duty, but we have to do it
or we break faith with the people who sent us here,'' said
Representative Henry J. Hyde, chairman of the House Judicicary
Committee, which will conduct the impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get this behind us and behind the country and move
on,'' Hyde said near the end of a three-hour debate marked by
flourishes of impassioned eloquence, accusatory rhetoric and what
one lawmaker described as ``a cacophony of catcalls.''
</P>
<P>
   The passage of House Resolution 581, the first impeachment
inquiry approved by Congress since the Watergate crisis in 1974,
authorizes the Judiciary Committee to ``investigate fully and
completely whether sufficient grounds exist for the House of
Representatives to exercise its constitutional power to impeach
William Jefferson Clinton, president of the United States of
America.''
</P>
<P>
   The resolution places no limits on the scope of the inquiry,
although Hyde said he plans to focus on allegations involving
Clinton's affair with Monica S. Lewinsky unless other possibly
impeachable charges arise.
</P>
<P>
   By partisan turns, Republicans portrayed the resolution as the
framework for a solemn, constitutional review of Clinton's conduct,
while many Democrats assailed the plan as a prologue to a long,
lurid soap opera with a plot designed to drive the president from
office.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, the vote clears the way for high-profile
impeachment hearings, with Clinton and Lewinsky high on the list of
possible witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's aides immediately began planning the inquiry, saying they
expected to spend the next month conducting a separate review of
independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr's investigaton of Clinton.
They said they hoped to hasten the inquiry by reaching an agreement
with Democrats and Clinton's lawyers on accepting as many of
Starr's findings as possible as true.
</P>
<P>
   Committee investigators also are expected to interview many of
Starr's witnesses ``to see if they have changed their testimony,''
said Paul McNulty, the panel's communications director.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said he will hold hearings after the Nov. 3 elections in
the hope of concluding the inquiry by Jan. 3, 1999, when the
impeachment resolution expires.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of Democrats argued in vain to limit the inquiry's scope
to the Lewinsky matter and permit a full investigation only if the
Judiciary Committee first determined that the allegations meet the
standards for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all profoundly hurt by what the president has done,''
said House Minority Leader Richard A. Gephardt of Missouri. ``He
has deeply disappointed the American people, and he has let us all
down. But this investigation must be ended fairly and quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   The House rejected the Democratic proposal, 236-198, with every
Republican opposing the plan except for Representative Jay Dickey,
from Clinton's home state of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Ten Democrats voted against their party's alternative, several
because they favored the GOP plan and others because they believe
Clinton's conduct does not warrant an impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president betrayed his wife. He did not betray the
country. God help this nation if we fail to recognize the
difference.'' said Representative Robert Wexler, a Florida Democrat
who serves on the Judiciary Committee and supported the Democratic
alternative.
</P>
<P>
   The White House and Democratic leaders had subtly lobbied House
Democrats to oppose the Republican-sponsored plan in an effort to
portray the inquiry as a partisan vendetta aimed at negating
Clinton's victory in the last election.
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton, the strategy is vital to his survival plan. But to
many rank-and-file Democrats, the effort is geared less to
protecting Clinton than to regaining control of the House in
November. Democrats need to pick up 11 seats to seize what they
lost four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   With House Speaker Newt Gingrich presiding over the debate, his
fellow Georgian and Democratic foe, Representative John Lewis said,
``Republicans want to do what they could not do in the election,
defeat Bill Clinton. Well, the American people are watching. Beware
the wrath of the American people, Mr. Speaker. Beware.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the 31 Democrats who defected were fewer than the
White House had feared and Republicans had desired. ``I would have
liked 40,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Democratic defectors are Southern conservatives who
quickly abandoned Clinton over the Lewinsky spectacle. Others, such
as Representative James H. Maloney of Connecticut, are locked in
tight election races and feared they would be attacked as
apologists for Clinton if they did not support a full inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Still others were moderates from Midwestern states where
Clinton's popularity is flagging. ``There are states like
Massachusetts and New York that strongly support the president,''
said Representative Tim Roemer, an Indiana Democrat who voted for
the Republican-sponsored inquiry. ``But there are states like
Indiana and Nebraska that are deeply divided. The country needs a
full and fair inquiry so we can can start to move toward some kind
of healing.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most partisan moments of the debate, Democrats
accused Republicans of holding Clinton to a different standard from
Gingrich, who was reprimanded by the House and fined $300,000 last
year after he admitted providing the ethics committee inaccurate
information during its investigation of his political finances.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Representative Nancy Pelosi, a California Democrat, reminded
Gingrich he received the reprimand shortly after the GOP majority
reelected him speaker last year. ``How inconsistent, Mr. Speaker,
for the same Republican majority to move to an impeachment inquiry
of the president for lying about his personal life,'' Pelosi said.
``We all agree that lying is wrong. But why the double standard?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; At issue throughout the proceedings Thursday was a two-hour
limit on the debate. Democrats had asked for eight hours. But
Republicans, citing House rules that permitted only one hour for
debate on the special resolution, would agree only to the two-hour
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; At one point, so many Democrats wanted to speak that 13 women
lined up at a microphone to ask, in the few seconds allowed, for
permission to insert their written comments into the Congresional
Record.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; When several of the women tried to voice their views at the
microphone, they were shouted down by Republican members.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, lawmakers in both parties invoked the words
of dozens of American heroes, from Benjamin Franklin to Frankin D.
Roosevelt. And one member alluded to a setting from a work of
American fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Gary Ackerman, a New York Democrat, decried the
impeachment inquiry as a witch hunt by saying: ``Mr. Speaker, I
move that when the House adjourns, we do so to Salem, a quaint
village in the Commonwealth of Massachusetts, whose history beckons
us thence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
