<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-FIRELIGHT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FIREFLIGHT': A SOUP THAT BOILS BUT NEVER COOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever wonder what ``Jane Eyre'' might have been like if Charlotte
Bronte had watched too many soaps? Wonder no longer, because here
we have ``Firelight,'' a well-meaning, sufficiently well-acted but
ultimately lachrymose cross between chest-heaving Victorian
melodrama and ``As The World Turns.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie aims for subtle eroticism but misses, mostly because
it's stuffed to the cheeks with woozy sentimentality. The whole
thing would be more affecting _ more romantic _ if it had, in the
end, less romance. How's that for irony?
</P>
<P>
   ``Firelight'' marks the directing debut of William Nicholson,
who penned the radiant script for ``Shadowlands'' (from his own
stage play) and has a proven affinity for eros. And there are
moments in this film that stand on their own as snapshots of
frustration or desire _ lovers who share a furtive caress, a child
who sits in a lonely lake house, a woman who gazes at her daughter
with distant maternal longing. But Nicholson gets tripped up by his
own itch for closure, shoving his lovers toward the finish line
while they're still tying their shoes at the start. The pair in
question are Elisabeth (Sophie Marceau, best known as the fiery
princess in ``Braveheart'') and Charles (Stephen Dillane, of
``Welcome to Sarajevo''), a promisingly ill-matched 19th-century
duo.
</P>
<P>
   Charles is the son of a decadent English lord (Joss Ackland) and
the husband of a comatose woman who's been out cold since a riding
accident early in their marriage. But Charles wants an heir, so he
arranges, anonymously, for a three-day tryst with the impoverished
Elisabeth and pays her for their baby.
</P>
<P>
   An infant girl arrives and departs, swept away by nurses. The
years pass. Elisabeth is haunted by the absent child. And although
Elisabeth hasn't a clue to Charles' identity or the whereabouts of
her daughter, she tracks them both down to an austere stone manse
in England, where the lost baby is now a bratty 7-year-old named
Louisa (Dominique Belcourt) with an indulgent father, a kind maiden
aunt (Lia Williams) and a silent lady staring at the ceiling in an
upstairs bedroom. Elisabeth becomes Louisa's governess, despite the
fact that Louisa is a spoiled snotnose who knows nothing about her
teacher's maternity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're poor, I suppose,'' the kid fumes. ``I don't have to do
what you say.''
</P>
<P>
   Here the movie splits off into two directions: into ``Jane
Eyre'' territory (the wife in the attic), and into the land of the
von Trapp Family Singers, where obnoxious urchins need to be tamed
and clueless fathers need to be chided. Let's hear it for
wisenheimer governesses, particularly wisenheimer governesses who
inspire quivering lust in their employers.
</P>
<P>
   The main drawback to these and other plot turns is their
abruptness everything unfolds too quickly, too exaggeratedly, with
a score (by Christopher Gunning) that's far too heavy on bathetic
violins. Forbidden love is a fair subject, but forbidden love
pinned on bawling string solos and awkward dialogue (``I am not a
servant! I am a prisoner, just like you!,'' yelps Elisabeth to
Louisa, ripping into a speech on the oppression of women) is too
much of a not-so-good thing. And Nicholson chews too hard on the
title image, a reference to the ``magic time'' created in a room
lit solely by firelight. Explains Elisabeth: ``You can do what you
want, say what you want, be what you want.'' And the viewer thinks:
don't.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Anderson, who played the worldly priest in ABC's doomed
series ``Nothing Sacred,'' shows up as a pony-tailed American sheep
farmer who makes a flaccid stab at wooing Elisabeth. Like almost
everything else in the film, Anderson's character feels contrived,
a stock ingredient in a soup that boils but never cooks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
