<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-GOV-POLL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI HOLDS SMALL LEAD IN GOVERNOR'S RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH   AND FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Acting Governor Paul Cellucci and Attorney General
Scott Harshbarger are locked in a tight race for governor, with
Cellucci holding a small lead but drawing strong support from swing
voters, a new Boston Globe/WBZ-TV poll shows.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, taken Tuesday and Wednesday, gives Cellucci a 46
percent to 40 percent lead with 10 percent undecided. It also shows
that his themes are working better with voters than those
Harshbarger has pushed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the poll's finding that Harshbarger trails the Republican
incumbent by only a few percentage points should come as a boost to
the Democratic nominee, who has been off balance and on the
defensive in the first few weeks of the general election campaign.
Election Day is Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Harshbarger has struggled to overcome a
perception among even his supporters that he is slipping behind
Cellucci, a feeling accentuated by his poor showing in a debate on
Monday. The poll, done by KRC Communications Research of Newton,
has a margin of error of plus or minus 5 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news for Harshbarger is that despite a few bad weeks,
he is still in the hunt,'' said Gerry Chervinsky, president of KRC
Communications Research Inc., the Newton firm that conducted the
survey. The pollster said Harshbarger's continuing strength stems
from the fact that the state's voter registration is heavily
Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   But Chervinsky said the numbers suggest Cellucci seems better
positioned to attract more support as the campaign progresses.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Cellucci holds a strong lead, 59 percent to 27
percent, among a key voting bloc, independents.
</P>
<P>
   Undecided voters, who make up 10 percent of the sample, also
tend to select Cellucci when asked to choose between the two on a
number of economic and fiscal issues.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 400 likely voters also suggests that Cellucci has
struck a chord with voters by making a no-new-tax pledge, which he
has taken and Harshbarger has declined, a central issue in the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   When respondents were told that Cellucci had taken the pledge
while Harshbarger had not, 44 percent said it made them more likely
to back Cellucci, compared to 20 percent who said the news made
them more inclined to support Harshbarger. Twenty-seven percent
said it had no impact.
</P>
<P>
   And among a smaller sample of independents, the issue played
even more strongly, with half of the respondents saying the
anti-tax issue made them more likely to vote for Cellucci, and only
12 percent saying Harshbarger's anti-pledge position would help win
their support.
</P>
<P>
   ``People seem to have gotten used to all the years of holding
the line on taxes,'' Chervinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Harshbarger's attempt to use his rival's switch of
position on several major issues over the years to paint him as
untrustworthy does not appear to move voters. Forty-nine percent
rejected that argument, while 24 percent agreed with it.
</P>
<P>
   Although Harshbarger has scoffed at the notion that Cellucci
deserves any credit for the state's healthy economy _ something the
acting governor cites as a reason he should be elected _ likely
voters were more charitable.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-four percent said Cellucci deserved all the credit he has
taken, with 15 percent saying he deserved more kudos than he has
claimed. Only 26 percent thought Cellucci had overstated his role
in the state's economic success.
</P>
<P>
   When voters were asked who they thought cared more about people
like them _ typically a question on which Democrats score well _ 39
percent chose Cellucci, and 34 percent said Harshbarger.
Significantly for Cellucci, among independents, he beats his
Democratic rival 48 percent to 21 percent on this question.
</P>
<P>
   One ominous sign for Harshbarger came among the 31 percent of
the sample who watched the first televised debate between the two
men on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Of that subsample, 47 percent said what they had seen in the
debate made them more likely to back Cellucci, while only 21
percent said the debate had pushed them toward Harshbarger. Two
more live televised debates are scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   But Harshbarger can find comfort in two other findings. One is
that voters tend to &UR;  &LR; discount Cellucci's assertion that the
attorney general is a big-spending Democrat. Some 40 percent
rejected that charge, while 36 percent agreed with it.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Cellucci should not get much traction from his claims that
Massachusetts needs a Republican chief executive to keep the Beacon
Hill Democrats in check. Although 32 percent agree with that view,
35 percent said they would prefer an all-Democratic government and
24 percent said it would make no difference. Independents, however,
wanted divided government by a margin of 37 percent to 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Cellucci is benefiting from Democrats who have broken with
Harshbarger to support him, as well as from the perception that
Harshbarger is getting only lukewarm support from some factions of
the Democratic Party. Among independents, 46 percent said that made
them more likely to vote for Cellucci, with 14 percent saying it
made them more inclined to vote for Harshbarger.
</P>
<P>
   During their Monday debate, Harshbarger, tired of Cellucci's
references to the Dukakis-era fiscal crisis, accused Cellucci of
trying to run against former governor Michael S. Dukakis. The new
poll suggests Cellucci's strategy might work.
</P>
<P>
   Although respondents split about evenly when asked whether they
recalled the Dukakis years negatively or positively, 35 percent
said their memory of that era made them more likely to vote for
Cellucci, compared with 18 percent who said it made them more
likely to back Harshbarger.
</P>
<P>
   On teacher testing, voters were slightly more inclined to
support Cellucci's position that a teacher who failed a competency
test should be fired, than Harshbarger's somewhat more lenient
stand, which would give them two chances to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-six percent said that teachers who fail the test should be
fired, while 36 percent said they opposed firing.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to identify the greatest problem facing them and their
families, 19 percent of those polled said education, 17 percent
taxes, 13 percent health care, and 10 percent crime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
