<SLUG> BC-ANTZ-FILM-ANIMATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE BATTLE OF THE BUGS, `ANTZ' LEADS THE WAY IN COMPUTER
ANIMATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Antz,'' a new computer-animated movie, battle lines are
drawn between armies of ants and monstrous termites.
</P>
<P>
   In the real world of making such films, the battle lines are
between Pacific Data Images and Pixar.
</P>
<P>
   Both are computer-animation firms in Northern California, and
both are aligned with major studios: PDI with DreamWorks and Pixar
with Disney.
</P>
<P>
   Both also have new insect films: PDI's ``Antz,'' out now, and
Pixar's ``A Bug's Life,'' due Nov. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Their rank-and-file animators are probably too busy to worry
about competition. But their parent studios are big rivals _
perhaps even bitter ones.
</P>
<P>
   It all began at Disney, when Jeffrey Katzenberg was ousted as
production chief by company president Michael Eisner. Katzenberg
hit back by forming DreamWorks with Steven Spielberg and David
Geffen.
</P>
<P>
   That studio now has a traditional, hand-drawn animated film,
``The Prince of Egypt,'' ready to steal Disney's thunder during the
holiday season. It's due in theaters Dec. 18.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, bug wars _ and computer animation _ can mean big
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antz'' opened at No. 1 last weekend, earning $17.2 million.
That's an all-time record for an October weekend, and industry
analysts expect Antz to become the highest-grossing non-Disney
animated film ever.
</P>
<P>
   As for critics, some believe that this second computer-animated
film has surpassed the first: 1995's ``Toy Story,'' from the
Richmond, Calif.-based Pixar.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is that sense that if you go back and look at `Toy
Story', it won't look the same, because we've raised the bar,''
said former Houstonian Eric Salituro, who works at PDI.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Antz,'' his job was lead technical director for production
and engineering, building software to bind elements together.
</P>
<P>
   Salituro doesn't think the two bug movies symbolize a war
between studios.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disney vs. DreamWorks doesn't mean anything to us,'' he said.
``It may mean something to certain people at those companies, but
it's not what drives us.''
</P>
<P>
   PDI's Tim Johnson, who directed ``Antz'' with Eric Darnell,
agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their rivalry doesn't carry over from our point of view down
in the trenches,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just concentrate on making our movie. Folks on the upper
end may have a different story. But frankly, we've got lots of
friends and even people dating between the two companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said PDI's animators ``were not very conscious of `Toy
Story' while making `Antz,' which is not to say we weren't huge
fans. `Toy Story' opened a lot of doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``But computer animation is a broad spectrum of looks and feels
and aesthetics, and we knew our story was different. The world of
insects is a very natural, organic world compared to that in `Toy
Story.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As for ``A Bug's Life,'' ``We knew nothing about it, the story
or the look,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   No one seems sure who resolved to make a computer-animated bug
film first.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he conceived of such a film in 1991, when PDI was
focusing on graphics and commercials. In 1995 he pitched the idea
to the new DreamWorks.
</P>
<P>
   When ``Toy Story'' hit big that year, PDI got the green light.
</P>
<P>
   Although PDI was responsible for ``Antz's'' story and character
development, Katzenberg often provided input.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's good at looking with fresh eyes,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   It took 2 { years to make the movie. DreamWorks financed it,
thereby gaining 40 percent ownership of Palo Alto, Calif.-based
PDI.
</P>
<P>
   At the production's start, PDI had 80 employees. Now it has 240,
and 190 of them worked on ``Antz,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was part of that hiring surge,'' said Salituro, who lived in
Houston from 1982 until joining PDI in early 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Salituro graduated from Houston's Rice University in 1986 with a
degree in computer science, then worked at Rice for a decade,
mostly in the computer department.
</P>
<P>
   Salituro had been aware of PDI and other computer-animation
firms. When he heard about ``Antz,'' he applied and was hired.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has been at PDI for 10 years. Before ``Antz,'' he was
animation director on a Halloween program for ``The Simpsons,''
placing Homer Simpson in a three-dimensional, computer-animated
world.
</P>
<P>
   Creating computer animation starts with traditional methods:
drawings with pencil and paper.
</P>
<P>
   But these concepts are soon fed into computers, with characters,
backgrounds, movements and lighting programmed in intricate detail.
</P>
<P>
   ``You spend a long time just preparing,'' Johnson said. ``You
gradually work toward building this fantastic world on a computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the fun of animation: creating an entire world. It's
fun to take moviegoers someplace they've never been.''
</P>
<P>
   As in traditional animation, voices are recorded early in the
process. For ``Antz,'' the first actor cast was Woody Allen as
voice of Z, an ant who has adventures with a princess, voiced by
Sharon Stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voice actors were inspiring,'' Johnson said. ``We didn't
actually make the character look like Woody, but because of the
animators' ability to capture the essence of the voice, you end up
thinking these characters look a lot like the actor.''
</P>
<P>
   Since all of ``Antz's'' visual information is now programmed
into PDI computers, a sequel would be ``much simpler, cheaper and
faster to make,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You easily spend 50 percent of your time and money just
getting ready _ getting characters built into the system. There are
over 300 controls just to move Z's face, and somebody had to
program all that.''
</P>
<P>
   While ``Antz'' has brought computer animation to new heights,
Johnson doesn't think it will take the place of traditional
animation, even though the latter sometimes uses computer-generated
shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an animation purist,'' he said. ``Nothing will ever beat
the beauty and expressiveness of drawn animation.''
</P>
<P>
   PDI's next film will be ``Shrek,'' which is about a troll trying
to find his place in the world. Like ``Antz,'' Johnson believes it
will be a departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I knew what computer animation was,'' he said. ``But
`Antz' is entirely different.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge was humanizing the bugs' faces ``while
keeping them bugs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted the characters to have a lot of heart, which meant
they needed to be expressive in ways we're used to seeing faces be
expressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether using computers or drawings, Salituro thinks the key to
success is in a strong story and talented artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got nothing to do with the technology,'' he said. ``None
of this is automatic. The heart of any animated movie still comes
down to animators creating. All the technology in the world can't
supply the heart.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 1407EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
