<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPECTOR-MUSIC-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCK 'N' ROLL ROSE, RONNIE SPECTOR, BLOOMS AGAIN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICK MITCHELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before the Spice Girls and Madonna, before Courtney Love and
Chrissie Hynde, before Diana Ross and the Supremes and Martha and
the Vandellas, there was Ronnie Spector.
</P>
<P>
   As the lead singer of the Ronettes, the ultimate girl group of
the early '60s, Spector defined a sound and a look that had a
profound influence on subsequent generations of female rockers. The
Ronettes' classic recordings with producer Phil Spector, who became
Ronnie's husband, include ``Be My Baby,'' ``Baby I Love You'' and
``Walking in the Rain.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie Spector will be singing these songs and other favorites
Saturday at Compaq Center in Houston, when she appears with Three
Dog Night, Ben E. King, Jan &AMP; Dean and America in the 17th annual
Whataburger Lovin' Feelings concert.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love doing the oldies-but-goodies shows,'' she said. ``I do
six or seven a year. It keeps me rooted.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect her to run through abbreviated versions of her
hits, as is the case with so many oldies acts. She brings her own
band and puts on a real show, just like she does in the hippest
nightclubs in New York and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people come to my shows, I give them their money's worth.
I don't do medleys. I do `Be My Baby' all the way through, maybe
even longer than the record, because that's what the people came to
see.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie Spector was a 12-year-old kid named Veronica Bennett when
she fell under the musical spell of Frankie Lymon &AMP; the Teenagers.
Lymon was only 13 himself, but he was already a star.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was like a god to me,'' she said. ``He came to my 13th
birthday party. He lived just 10 blocks away from me in Spanish
Harlem. My mother was a waitress, and he used to come into the
restaurant where she worked. She told him she'd give him free
hamburgers if he came to my party.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by Lymon's example, Ronnie put together a group with
her sister, Estelle Bennett, and their cousin Nedra Talley. The
group cut a couple of singles for the Colpix label, then Ronnie
became intrigued with a hot young producer from Philadelphia named
Phil Spector.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that song `Spanish Harlem' came out, I thought they wrote
it for me, because I was a rose in Spanish Harlem'' she said. ``I
said to my sister, `I'd like to meet that Phil Spector guy, who
wrote a song about me, and he doesn't even know me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Spector heard the Ronettes sing at the Peppermint Lounge
and signed them to his Philles label. His first single with the
group, ``Be My Baby,'' hit No. 2 in 1963. With its majestic ``wall
of sound'' production and Ronnie's sexy, yearning vocal (``for
every kiss you give me/I'll give you three ... ''), ``Be My Baby''
remains one of rock 'n' roll's most glorious moments.
</P>
<P>
   As successful as they were in the United States, the Ronettes
were even more popular in Great Britain. When they toured England,
the Rolling Stones and the Yardbirds opened shows for them. The
Beatles, in preparation for their first American tour in 1964,
wanted the Ronettes to fly back across the ocean with them so they
all could get off the plane together in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil insisted that we come home a couple of days earlier,''
said Ronnie. ``Then, when the plane landed in New York, who gets
off the plane with them? Phil Spector. That's when I realized that
he wanted to be the star; he wanted all the credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Ronnie and Phil fell madly in love.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we did was make love and make music,'' she said. ``We were
so much in love with each other. As a matter of fact, I think he
loved me a little bit too much. He didn't want me to be a star. He
wanted me to be his star alone.''
</P>
<P>
   After they married in 1968, Phil made Ronnie quit performing.
Except for a session with the Beatles, none of the recordings they
worked on together ever came out. As Phil's hit-making career
declined, he became ever more reclusive. Ronnie felt like a
prisoner in her own house. She left him in 1972, although it was
another two years before their divorce was final.
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie attempted to resume her career, but the momentum was
gone. Still, her peers recognized her lasting contribution to rock
'n' roll. In 1976, Billy Joel wrote a tribute to her called ``Say
Goodbye to Hollywood,'' which she recorded with Bruce Springsteen's
E Street Band.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Ronnie recorded a hit duet with Eddie Money _ ``Take Me
Home Tonight'' _ that proved her voice had lost none of its
evocative power. She also made an unforgettable appearance in the
video for the song, which contained a strong echo of ``Be My
Baby.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past 16 years, Ronnie has been happily married to her
manager, Jonathan Greenfield. They live in Connecticut with their
two teen-age children. A lengthy court case against Phil Spector
and Allen Klein, who manages the Spector song catalog, is nearing
its conclusion. Greenfield expects to receive some sort of
settlement for unpaid royalties and lost opportunities, although he
adds that ``it will never undo what's been done.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie Spector documented her life before, during and after Phil
Spector in the book ``Be My Baby: How I Survived Mascara,
Miniskirts and Madness'' (Crown Publishers, 1991). Now, she's
looking forward to the release of her first new recordings in more
than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me a long time, but I wanted to make sure I had the
right material and the right producers,'' she said. ``I wouldn't do
anything if it wasn't to my liking. I'd rather stay home and play
with my kids.''
</P>
<P>
   She has finished an EP-length recording for the British Creation
label, which boasts such contemporary artists as Oasis and the
Jesus and Mary Chain. The sessions were co-produced by Daniel Ray
and Joey Ramone and include covers of the Ramones' ``She Talks to
Rainbows'' and Johnny Thunders' ``You Can't Put Your Arms Around a
Memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect to hear either song at Compaq Center. But there's
another cover Ronnie definitely plans on singing: the Beach Boys'
``Don't Worry, Baby''. Brian Wilson wrote the song for her
immediately after hearing ``Be My Baby,'' but Phil Spector refused
to let her sing it because he didn't control the publishing rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``That song kept me alive during the time when I was divorcing
Phil,'' she said. ``I always loved Brian Wilson and the Beach Boys'
version of it. I'd come home from court and listen to those lyrics.
When it came time for me to make another record, I thought, I must
do `Don't Worry, Baby.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Still a rose at 55, Ronnie Spector is finally free to pursue her
dreams of 30 or 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a real life now,'' she said. ``I'm a mother, and a
wife, and a performer in rock 'n' roll. And that's everything for
me.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
