<HEADLINE>
NO COMPARISON BETWEEN NIXON AND THIS FARCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sword of impeachment, a deft instrument skillfully employed
in the surgical removal of the Nixon cancer 24 years ago, returned
as a clumsy mallet, a blunt, partisan tool wielded by smaller
people than the members of Congress who showed Nixon the door.
</P>
<P>
   History's wheel, grinding first as tragedy, then as farce, takes
another turn in the House of Representatives. The ``high crimes and
misdemeanors'' of the Founding Fathers' high-minded framing of our
nation's laws are ratcheted down to the low conduct of Clinton and
Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Can there be a better word than ``squalid'' for Clinton's
entanglement and his trying to wriggle off the hook? And does not
``squalid'' also encompass the actions of the House in bringing
down upon our collective heads the totally unnecessary and
potentially disastrous consequences of this foolish partisan
overreaction?
</P>
<P>
   There is a different feel to this political dumb show compared
with the gravity, awe, and genuine sense of duty evident 24 years
ago, when the House last weighed impeaching a president. I covered
the House Judiciary Committee's impeachment inquiry in 1974 for the
Globe. Both the process and the politicians of both parties
participating were several cuts above this present pathetic
performance in preelection propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Peter Rodino, Speaker Carl Albert, and majority leader
Tip O'Neill were fair and sincere in their respect for
bipartisanship. That's what convinced the Republicans, then in the
minority, that the process was fair. The fact that six of the 17
GOP members voted to recommend impeachment was what sealed Nixon's
deserved doom. But it was the courting of the Republicans and
Southern Democrats whose constitutents sympathized with Nixon that
carried the day.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Henry Hyde does not demonstrate sufficient independence
from Speaker Gingrich to merit similar respect across the aisle.
This is a far more partisan House under rule-or-ruin Gingrich. Bill
Cohen, the present secretary of defense, was a young lawyer from
Bangor, Maine, in those days, a junior House member, but eloquent
in sizing up the stakes and then voting to take down his party's
president.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon's crimes, concluded Cohen then, ``raise the specter of an
American `Gulag Archipelago,''' a reference to the just-published
revelation of Soviet labor camps by Alexander Solzhenitsyn. ``The
rattle of the chains that can bind up our own Constitution can be
heard,'' said Cohen 24 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast that with Henry ``Homewrecker'' Hyde's dismissing
revelations of his extramarital dalliance with a married mother of
three as ``a youthful indiscretion'' committed when he was in his
40s and you get an idea of how the debate has deteriorated. The
process then was too important for politics of a low order. But not
so now. Twenty-five days in advance of elections for Congress and
state offices, the Republicans slash at Clinton's neck. The
process? It reeks of partisanship and cheap electioneering. The
fact that the nation's newspapers do not denounce such
grandstanding is due principally to their role in profiting from
the president's embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   Editorialists pose as high-minded moral arbiters safeguarding
the tender ears of the nation's young while sales depend on
stuffing each edition with more prurience slicked up as news. In
the Department of Hypocrisy, the media pack takes the cigar.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's committee, stacked to vote impeachment, dumped the
now-infamous Starr report on the public without even reading it.
The committee's ``deliberations'' are a joke. The House vote is a
mere formality.
</P>
<P>
   It all gets real the morning after the congressional elections
are tallied. If the Democrats lose, say, only half the 44 seats the
party of the White House typically loses in the sixth year of an
administration, the GOP brass will conclude that the public wants
this charade to end. But if the GOP picks up enough Senate seats to
make the upper chamber filibuster-proof (60), or if Gingrich wins a
heady addition of 30 to 50 congressmen, a two-thirds vote to
impeach Clinton in the Senate becomes a real possibility, though
perhaps still not a probability.
</P>
<P>
   They will have to dynamite Clinton's fingers off the Oval Office
door jambs. I cannot conceive of this political survivor yielding
to his enemies over an unconsummated romantic dalliance that
stopped short of intercourse. It is ludicrous that it got even this
far. But the mendacity of the Republicans, the timidity of the
Democrats, the stupidity of Clinton, the incompetence of his
lawyers and handlers, and the rapacity of the news media combined
to land us where we are.
</P>
<P>
   I remain convinced that Clinton will be neither impeached nor
forced to resign. His job approval ratings are around 60 percent.
In July 1974 Nixon's job approval rating in the Gallup poll: 24
percent. That is a huge differential. Every poll shows that a
majority of Americans do not want Clinton removed via impeachment.
But in '74, Gallup's number had 47 percent saying Nixon should be
ousted as opposed to 34 who said no. Absent that kind of sentiment,
this week's House action is purely an exercise in preelection
posturing for political gain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
