<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAIL SERVER PROVIDES A SAFE HOME FOR E-MAIL WHEN COMPUTER'S DOWN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Where does e-mail go that I get when my computer is off? Do
those little guys hang out in a room somewhere until I turn it back
on and somebody yells ``Showtime!''? And how long can you leave
your computer off before your e-mails get tired and go home? If
someone trashed an old computer, seems like spam would pile up
until it covered the world.
</P>
<P>
   A. Actually, your speculation about what happens with your first
question is not bad. Except the ``little guys'' aren't waiting on
your computer.
</P>
<P>
   When someone sends you an e-mail, it travels across the Internet
and lands on a computer at your Internet service provider. That
computer, called the mail server, is designed to receive, sort and
then dispatch incoming mail. You can think of it as a kind of
digital mail room.
</P>
<P>
   When you log on to the Net through your provider and launch your
e-mail software, it sends a message to the mail server requesting
that it deliver all your unread mail. The server checks your
in-box, finds your mail and sends it to your system.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a direct connection to the Net, it's possible for
you to run your own mail server on your computer, so that e-mail is
sent directly to your machine. But this setup is rare for most home
users.
</P>
<P>
   As to your second question, the answer depends on how your
Internet provider has configured the mail server.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, unretrieved e-mail is removed after a specific
period of time. In other cases, it may be removed when your in-box
on the mail server gets too full. Or, there may be a combination of
the two. In that case, older messages go first.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I just started getting into computers, so forgive me if this
question is too basic. But what's Windows NT? Do I want it instead
of Windows 98, which is what came on my first computer?
</P>
<P>
   A. To paraphrase an old joke: If you have to ask what Windows NT
is, you don't need it.
</P>
<P>
   But the chances are you're going to get it, eventually.
</P>
<P>
   Windows NT is Microsoft's industrial-strength operating system.
It's aimed at businesses and those users who require a
crash-resistant, high-security system that runs over a network.
</P>
<P>
   Windows NT is not a good choice for the home user, particularly
someone who is new to computers. It doesn't run older programs _
particularly MS-DOS software _ very well. It lacks many of the
features that make Windows 95 and 98 relatively friendly, most
notably Plug and Play _ the ability to install new hardware and
have the system recognize it. Trying to get Windows NT _ even 4.0,
the latest version _ to recognize a sound card can be a Herculean
feat.
</P>
<P>
   That will change soon. Shortly after the release of Windows NT
5.0, which is scheduled for early next year, Microsoft will merge
the underlying architecture of NT and the Windows 9x series of
operating systems. You'll then have Windows NT for Business and
Windows NT for Consumers. They'll share the same internal
structure, but with different features for home and work.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have installed Windows 95 and created the start-up disk.
Can you tell me what command to type in at the A: prompt when you
want to reboot using the start-up disk?
</P>
<P>
   A. No command is necessary. Just insert the disk into your
floppy drive and leave it in there when you reboot your computer,
or power it down and fire it back up.
</P>
<P>
   When a PC begins the boot-up process, it first checks the floppy
drive for the operating system. If it doesn't find it on the
floppy, then it moves to the hard drive. If you've got a floppy
disk in place with the OS on it, it will boot from there. You need
to do nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Got a question? Maybe Computing columnist Dwight Silverman can
help. Send e-mail to dwight.silverman at chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
