<HEADLINE>
ASSAULT ON AFFIRMATIVE ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Far from laying claim to fairness in the Boston Fire
Department, a handful of angry white people would rather torch the
city with wasted emotion, pour ignorance over the flame, and howl
in celebration as the ashes of progress waft into the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday the City Council held a hearing on affirmative action.
The hearing was called by the council's president, James Kelly, who
is already immortalized as a foe of school busing in South Boston
in the 1970s. Kelly has contended that thousands of white police
and fire candidates have been passed over for jobs by people of
color who have lower test scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of unfair treatment to people who take the
test, pass it, but because of their race they are being denied the
opportunity,'' Kelly has said. Kelly's view is shared by Councilor
Peggy Davis-Mullen. She has said, ``There are poor white males that
are not being hired anymore in the traditional jobs they are
looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those bearing kerosene is Larry Mackin. Mackin, a white
man, claimed he was rejected several times by the Fire Department
throughout the late 1970s and '80s despite having high civil
service test scores, including a 100 in one case.
</P>
<P>
   Mackin sued all the way up to the Supreme Court. But whatever
meritocracy Mackin thought should be in place in Boston, the court
did not see the merits of his own case.
</P>
<P>
   The conservative court, which has already badly singed
affirmative action, declined to hear Mackin. Mackin's bitterness
has driven him to claim, fatuously: ``I have really been able to
see how the marchers in the civil rights movement must have felt,
being American citizens and being denied.''
</P>
<P>
   For all their flame and fuel, for all their access to city
statistics, these angry white souls have no hard evidence of a
wholesale denial of opportunity to white people.
</P>
<P>
   Affirmative action has lifted the percentage of Boston
firefighters of color from less than 1 percent in 1968 to 29
percent today. But white firefighters still make up 71 percent of
the force in a city that is now 56 percent white.
</P>
<P>
   Mackin cannot point to wholesale denial even in his own family.
Two of his brothers have made the force. More important, several
studies have torn apart the implication by Mackin, Kelly, and
Davis-Mullen that test scores should be the highest proof of a
candidate's qualifications.
</P>
<P>
   Last year a study published in the Journal of the American
Medical Association found that 94 percent of medical school
students of color admitted under affirmative action graduate from
the University of California at Davis. That is nearly equal to the
97 percent graduation rate of rest of the student body.
</P>
<P>
   Affirmative action students received fewer A's than regular
admissions students, but once graduated, 82 percent of both
affirmative action graduates and regular admissions graduates
completed their postgraduate residency training. Affirmative action
graduates received nearly the same percentage of honors evaluations
in residency as graduates from regular admissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time they had completed residency,'' the study said,
``the practice characteristics of the two populations were nearly
identical.''
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 study of corporate affirmative action in Atlanta, Boston,
Detroit, and Los Angeles by two Michigan State University
economists found that African-Americans entered the work force with
an average of one year less schooling than white colleagues at
identical jobs. But African-American men hired under affirmative
action received performance ratings equal to white men and
African-American women actually earned job performance ratings that
were slightly higher than for white women.
</P>
<P>
   Authors Harry Holzer and David Neumark said that while critics
of affirmative action may choose to focus narrowly in the fact that
African-Americans often enter jobs with less educational
qualifications, the study revealed a more profound truth. They
found that ``ultimately, the most important measure'' of job
qualification is ``job performance.'' Once hired, they said, ``Our
results suggest that most women and minorities hired under
affirmative action make up in some way.''
</P>
<P>
   The struggle of people of color to make up ground lost to racism
is lost on Kelly, Davis-Mullen, and Mackin. Given the history of
Police and Fire Department hiring, affirmative action is the only
known way to assure fairness. Kelly and company have been curiously
slow to suggest that white performance on fire and police tests may
have less to do with native intelligence and potential for bravery
than the benefits of growing up in insular white neighborhoods
where it was assumed that police and fire jobs could be handed down
for generations.
</P>
<P>
   Boston could not stop Kelly from holding his hearings. It can
stop him from doing what he wants. Kelly, Davis-Mullen, and Mackin
hold a torch lit only with grumbles of white superiority and
accusations of black inferiority. A Boston that does not care to
rekindle its inflamed past should douse this arson squad with a
fire brigade of facts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
