<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STRATEGY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT CAN ONLY HOPE FOR SPEED, FAIRNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He has lived for years in a universe of independent
counsels, grand jury investigations, sexual harassment suits and
criminal task forces, but at no point in the presidency of Bill
Clinton has he faced a threat to his survival as dire and
unpredictable as this, aides and allies conceded Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, mostly grimfaced, Thursday issued a personal plea for
an impeachment inquiry that will be fair and fast, telling
reporters after the vote, ``It is not in my hands. It is in the
hands of Congress and the people of this country, ultimately in the
hands of God.''
</P>
<P>
   As his fate is now left to others, Clinton is characterized by a
complex emotional mix of frustration and relief, friends said. He
is at once infuriated that congressional Republicans insist on
making -- quite literally -- a federal case out of his affair with
Monica Lewinsky and his subsequent efforts to deny and conceal it.
But he has appeared unburdened by his dramatic series of public
confessions these last two months, his mood, his psyche, lightened
by his admissions of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were in his shoes and walk by a TV set and see `House
Impeachment Vote,' that's unsettling,'' said Doug Sosnik, a White
House counselor who spends considerable time with Clinton. ``How
could it not be? A person has to be weird not to be unsettled by
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But on another level, anyone in his situation would feel much
more liberated,'' Sosnik added. ``No one is carrying around the
secret anymore and wondering if today's the day it comes out. For
months, everyone's been chasing rumors, and now we know what we're
dealing with.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton himself seemed to echo that sentiment Thursday, offering
reporters a small smile at a Cabinet Room photo opportunity and
saying, ``Personally, I am fine. I have surrendered this. This is
beyond my control. I trust the American people. They almost always
get it right, and have for 220 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, White House officials have taken to repeating the
mantra that Clinton will not be impeached, almost as if they are
trying to will their words into reality. The public is behind them,
the officials say, and in the Senate, where a two-thirds majority
is needed for removal and the Democrats now hold 45 seats, simple
arithmetic points to his survival.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the emotion and the fear and the unprecedented nature of
their predicament, Clinton and his aides have tried to cobble
together a strategy that takes him back to his most successful
roots as a moderate policymaker scratching at issues crucial to
everyday Americans, like health care reform and the minimum wage.
The idea, some aides said, is to position the president as a voice
of reason amid what they will portray as an inquiry propelled by
partisanship that could stretch well into next year.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after Thursday's House roll call which launched the
full full impeachment inquiry, White House officials began looking
towards the next crucial vote -- the November 3 congressional
elections -- as the key to the president's future.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's strategists have already mapped three potential
scenarios: A Republican landslide, which would embolden the GOP
leadership and could prove ruinous to Clinton; a Democratic
comeback, which would serve as some vindication and may inspire a
GOP retreat from impeachment to a compromise outcome, like a
censure vote. The third possibility, and perhaps the most likely,
is an election day result somewhere between the two extremes,
providing a muddled message for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will assume his role as the policymaker immediately;
indeed, it is the posture he has adopted from the day last month
that he reluctantly conceded to an improper relationship with
Monica S. Lewinsky. Thursday, he began with a declaration that the
most important item on his agenda is the passage of a federal
budget that will preserve the surplus to protect Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm working in a way that I hope will restore their trust in
me by working for the things that our country needs,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, Clinton will immerse himself into the business of
state, pondering possible NATO-sanctioned bombing runs in Kosovo
and brokering a potentially breakthrough summit on Thursday between
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestine leader
Yasser Arafat on the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were president, I would get the focus on the issues, get
out and campaign for candidates,'' said Representative Martin
Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat and a member of the Judiciary
Committee. ``I would take his arguments directly to the American
people. The republican members of the Judiciary Committee will all
vote for impeachment. The only thing that can change that is
Democratic victories in November.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House plans to heed the advice. For the next month,
Clinton will make at least one campaign trip a week, including a
visit next week to Miami where he will highlight his plan to reform
the Social Security system, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This vote was a political event 26 days before the election,''
said Ann Lewis, Clinton's communications director. ``This was their
only campaign strategy to crowd issues off the front page. They
don't care about you. They want to play their own games, and all
the while the president will talk about issues that people care
about.''
</P>
<P>
   White House aides predict a volatile election period, followed
by the hearings -- whose tenor and outcome it seems too early to
predict. If Democrats hold their own in the elections and lose
fewer than a dozen House seats and just a Senate seat or two, the
nature of the inquiry remains unclear. Should the GOP gain
significant numbers of seats in both chambers, they will likely
seek to broaden their investigation to encompass Whitewater and the
wholesale firing of the White House travel office. Conversely,
almost any Democratic gains at all will signal to Republicans to
retreat from the probe.
</P>
<P>
   In November, as the Judiciary Committee convenes a hearing,
Clinton is due to fly off to Asia for a protracted trip, including
stops at an economic summit in Malaysia during which the worldwide
financial crisis will be the dominant issue, followed by likely
stops in South Korea and Japan, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   During the holiday season, White House officials said they plan
to follow their script from years past and make little news while
huddling to put together an agenda for the State of the Union
address in January. Some aides are already conceding that the House
will vote for an impeachment, leaving the president's fate in the
hands of the Senate and a possible policy agenda early next year
obliterated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The House will come back and we go through a 60-day, America
held hostage hearing on impeachment,'' said one senior White House
adviser. ``It rolls down the track toward the Senate, and depending
on the appetite, the Senate will take it up and he will not be
impeached and America will scream to get on with life.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, for now, is left to plead for brevity and impartiality.
``I hope that we can now move forward with this process in a way
that is fair, that is constitutional and that is timely,'' he said.
``The American people have been through a lot on this, and I think
that everyone deserves that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
