<HEADLINE>
SUPPORTERS PUSH EFFORT FOR CONTRACEPTIVE REFUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Armed with a threat of a Senate filibuster and the
pledge of White House support, backers of a measure to provide
federal workers with insurance coverage for prescription
contraceptives braced Thursday for another round in what has been
an unexpectedly tough fight for passage.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Harry Reid, a Nevada Democrat, threatened Thursday to
hold up the Treasury Department spending bill and tie up the Senate
with a filibuster unless the contraceptive-coverage amendment,
which was dropped from the bill on Tuesday, gets reattached.
</P>
<P>
   The White House spokesman, Joe Lockhart, said the administration
favored the measure and pledged to ``continue to make the fight for
this provision'' in negotiations with Congress over a host of
appropriations bills that will probably be rolled into one large
spending package to fund the federal government through the next
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   The contraceptive-coverage amendment passed with bipartisan
support in the House and Senate this summer. But on Tuesday, GOP
leaders abruptly dropped it from the fiscal 1999 Treasury-Postal
spending bill, saying it was one of several measures blocking the
bill's passage. The House passed the stripped-down spending bill on
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the measure, which would extend insurance coverage
to an estimated 2 million federal workers, were furious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is just outrageous the way the Republican
leadership bowed to its extreme right wing and thwarted the will of
the people,'' said Kate Michelman, president of the National
Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League, a private group.
``It makes me wonder what kind of democratic process we really have
when something like this can happen in the dead of night.''
</P>
<P>
   The contraceptive-coverage amendment has become a lightning rod
for antiabortion groups, lawmakers, and the US Catholic Conference.
The opponents argued heatedly Thursday that most prescription
contraceptives are abortifacients, or abortion-inducing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are ecstatic. We didn't expect Congress to show the courage
to take this language out,'' said Judie Brown, president of the
American Life League, an antiabortion group. ``We have been working
for over a year to prove that prescription contraceptives have
nothing to do with a woman's health and well-being but are
recreational drugs that prevent fertilization and abort children.''
</P>
<P>
   Women's-rights activists say they took advantage of the
agreement by some insurers to pay for the impotence drug Viagra to
press the issue of contraceptive coverage. Groups such as Planned
Parenthood for years have complained that women are shortchanged
because half of all private insurers do not pay for the Pill and
other prescription contraceptives.
</P>
<P>
   The attempt to mandate the benefit for federal workers who are
covered for other prescriptions was aimed at getting private health
plans to provide substantially more coverage for contraceptives,
backers said.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Nita Lowey, a New York Democrat who authored the
House version of the amendment, said Thursday that she was
optimistic about its prospects because White House officials
assured her `they would stand very firm for it'' in ongoing
spending-bill negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Campanella, a spokewoman for Reid, said Senate leaders had
delayed debate on the Treasury spending bill Thursday ``to see if
they could work something out'' and avoid a filibuster. The most
likely outcome, she said, is that the Treasury bill will be rolled
into the omnibus spending package, with the contraceptive-coverage
amendment attached.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans who handled the Treasury spending bill insisted they
had not killed the amendment to punish Democrats who favored it,
but were fighting an unrelated GOP-backed provision.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a good example of what happens when a spending bill
gets bogged down with too many pet items,'' said a spokeswoman for
the House Appropriations Committee. ``The leadership did what it
had to do to get this train out of the station.''
</P>
</TEXT>
