<HEADLINE>
BROWN HAS MADE HIS PITCH; CAN ATLANTA? 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Had a great history teacher once. He had many
wonderful expressions, but one of his favorites to describe the
inexplicably woebegone state of once haughty powers was this: ``Oh,
how the mighty have fallen!''
</P>
<P>
   A. Graham Down was a Brit whose knowledge of American sport was
pretty much confined to an awareness that Joe Louis had once packed
a tremendous punch. But those of us whose business it is to monitor
the game of baseball might be inclined to adopt A. Graham's maxim
in reference to the Atlanta Braves, who have just lost the first
two games of a rather important playoff series at home.
</P>
<P>
   They dropped the opener of the National League Championship
Series, 3-2, in the wee small hours Thursday morning, and they
dropped the second game, 3-0, Thursday night. Let's just say that
the 42d anniversary of Don Larsen's perfect game will not be a
featured day on any Atlanta Braves calendar.
</P>
<P>
   It now falls to the $10 million man to rescue the proud
perennial rulers of whatever division the ever-changing National
League sees fit to insert them in. Greg Maddux gets the start in
San Diego Saturday, and if he can't beat Sterling Hitchcock, the
Braves can start thinking about tee times and vacation itineraries.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Hitchcock lived up to his first name with 11 strikeouts in
six-plus innings last time out against Randy Johnson and the
Houston Astros. But if he is aptly named, then what can we say
about Kevin Brown? Should his name be Cy? Christy? Grover
Cleveland? Sandy? Zeus?
</P>
<P>
   Right now he is the best pitcher in baseball, at least among
those whose teams are still playing. He's not going to win the Cy
Young Award, which will go to either Thursday night's rival, Tom
Glavine, or teammate Trevor Hoffman. He doesn't have the historic
reputation of Mr. Maddux, or even the Big Unit. But at the moment,
Kevin Brown is the towering figure in the 1998 postseason. He is
compiling the most intimidating postseason resume since Orel
Hershiser pitched the Dodgers to the 1988 title.
</P>
<P>
   In three 1998 postseason starts, he is 2-0. He has given up
seven hits and one run in 23 2/3 innings. They always said he had
``nasty'' stuff. Now he is more than just nasty. He has become
ruthless.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a great start in Houston (when he struck out 16 in
eight innings) and he had great stuff tonight,'' said San Diego
manager Bruce Bochy. ``He is as tough as any pitcher in baseball.
He is as great a competitor as I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   You really can't pitch a whole lot better in the circumstance
than he did Thursday night, when he threw a three-hit shutout
during which the Braves hit exactly one (1) ball hard, that being a
390-foot fly to the center-field fence off the bat of Chipper Jones
in the sixth, when it was still a 1-0 game. The three hits were
singles, none distinguished. He walked three, fanned 11, and was in
trouble only once.
</P>
<P>
   The closest Atlanta came to scoring was in the fourth, when a
single, walk, and wild pitch put men on second and third. But Brown
got Javy lopez on a routine fly, and that was that.
</P>
<P>
   He also helped himself with two hits (love that National League
ball), figuring in both scoring innings. No radio or TV station had
to look too far in order to find what a more sports-minded A.
Graham Down might refer to as the Man of the Match.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves always count on their superb starting pitching to be
their trump card in all matters, but once you get to the
postseason, you discover that the Other Guy often has pretty good
starting pitching, too. John Smoltz didn't pitch a bad game
Wednesday night/Thursday morning, and Glavine didn't pitch a bad
game Thursday night, either. The two combined to surrender three
runs in 13 innings. Not bad. But not good enough, either. As good
as Messrs. Smoltz and Glavine were, Andy Ashby and Kevin Brown were
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought both our guys pitched brilliant games,'' sighed a
glum-looking Braves manager Bobby Cox. ``But their two guys did,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   When pitching is this good, it is often difficult to dissect
individual hitters. But it is increasingly obvious that Atlanta has
some major offensive problems, which, if not solved immediately
(i.e., by Saturday afternoon), will result in an embarrassingly
abrupt ending to another routinely fine Braves season (106 wins).
The Braves need something from cleanup man Andres Galarraga, for
example. The Big Cat hasn't hit a home run since Sept. 7, and his
lack of production is killing the attack.
</P>
<P>
   In vivid contrast to the Red Sox' woes during the Cleveland
series, just about all the damage done by the Braves this
postseason has been done by the bottom four spots in the order. The
only RBI among the top four is a solo homer by Chipper Jones.
Leadoff man Walt Weiss is in a complete fog, and you've got to
wonder how long Cox can stay with him.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all that, be careful. Don't assume the Braves are dead.
Any reasonable person likes their chances in the next two pitching
matchups (Maddux vs. Hitchcock and Denny Neagle vs. Joey Hamilton).
This is a team that came from 3-1 down two years ago to defeat St.
Louis. Baseball is not really a momentum sport. It is, and always
will be, an execution sport.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres have enough veteran players to be aware of this, and
in case anyone is unclear on the matter, Bochy will be only too
happy to remind him. ``We know it's the best of seven,'' Bochy
said. ``We know there is a lot of baseball left. It was nice to
take two here, but we have to go home and keep playing the same
kind of baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, Saturday's game is everything to the Braves, and they
have the acclaimed Mr. Maddux going. If they lose that one, then
OK, feel free to quote my esteemed history mentor. Until then, the
mighty haven't fallen. They've just stumbled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
