<SLUG> BC-BEAUTIFUL-TABLES-$ADV11-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRESS UP A TABLE SETTING WITH ANTIQUES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 11)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREAT BARRINGTON, Mass. _ Setting a beautiful table can be half
the fun of creating a great dining experience.
</P>
<P>
   In her latest book, ``Modern Antiques for the Table'' (Viking,
240 pages, $39.95), author Sheila Chefetz takes the novice and
seasoned collector through the paces of gracious table settings
with tableware antiques from about 1890 to 1940.
</P>
<P>
   ``An empty table is like a blank canvas awaiting the touch of
the painter's brush,'' Chefetz said in a recent interview at her
store that specializes in table settings, The Country Dining Room,
in Great Barrington, Mass. ``Don't forget that many of the great
hostesses often spent days supervising the setting of their tables
with hundreds of pieces from their fabled tableware collections.
You can too, by using your imagination and an artistic eye. You
don't need to be an heiress or a great decorator to dine with
antique tableware.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example of how Chefetz coordinates different settings, she
mixes several periods in her book. For one setting, she combines
glass Art Nouveau celery vases as flower vases and a mix of silver
and ivorine flatware, solid yellow basket-weave scallop-edge plates
and a Chintz coffee set in yellow, green, orange and white.
</P>
<P>
   You better shop around. Chefetz advised the best way to add to
your existing table settings is to shop around at garage sales,
auctions, antiques shops and specialty stores, where you can find a
myriad of buys, from a separate set of salad plates to cups and
saucers and serving pieces. Mixing and matching is what makes a
table interesting and come to life, she said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the popularity of Chefetz's first book, published in
1993, ``Antiques for the Table,'' that inspired her latest book. It
depicted memorable table settings for every occasion using 18th-,
19th- and 20th-century china, glass and silver, along with the
history of each piece and customs for using them.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Modern Antiques for the Table,'' Chefetz covers the four
principals of modern design _ Art Nouveau, Arts &AMP; Crafts, Beaux
Arts and Art Deco. She does so through two cities she considered to
be the ``pulse points'' of America: Detroit for its industry, and
Los Angeles for its fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good design can harmonize with and enhance well-designed
tablewares of any era,'' Chefetz said. ``Never try to re-create
history, but rather bring your own personality to the mix to create
a melange of your favorite accessories and table service.''
</P>
<P>
   Chefetz suggests thinking about setting a dinner table in the
same way one would accessorize a model. This is a comparison
Chefetz has had firsthand experience with, having been a fashion
director for Gimbles in New York City years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``To make the dress stand out, you need the right jewelry, shoes
and purse,'' she said. ``Setting the table utilizes the same
principal. A friend once told me that silver is a table's or a
room's jewelry. An outfit is never complete without jewelry. Silver
and jewelry provides the glow or shine to make other things stand
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever you do, don't be afraid to mix and match,'' Chefetz
said. ``A table setting should always be a mix of the unexpected to
create a conversation piece.''
</P>
<P>
   Chefetz said that the best route to table setting is to start
with what you have or like to use.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always best to bring a few pieces of your table service
with you when shopping,'' she said. ``You should also bring a
sample of your wall color, paper or fabric and measure the space on
the table that you plan to fill.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In English porcelain dinner sets, dating up to the 1920s, there
were always separate dessert services, according to Chefetz, as
well as separate sets for breakfast, fish courses, tea and coffee.
The latter two, were more or less an American invention, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A really early set of fine china, for middle- to upper-class
homes, would never have had bread-and-butter plates,'' Chefetz
said. ``An early set would have had a set of crescent-shaped dishes
in which to discard fish or meat bones from your dinner plate.
People are buying these crescent-shaped dishes today and using them
as salad plates. Demitasse cups are perfect for serving sorbet.''
</P>
<P>
   Early sets of china also came without matching cups and saucers.
There would be a separate dessert set that was placed after all of
the dinner dishes were removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun to mix teacups, as many of the decorative ones tell a
little story,'' Chefetz said. ``These can start as low as $20 to
$30 and up to the $200 range for one cup and saucer. It's easy to
start a set of your own by carefully mixing color and designs.''
</P>
<P>
   Tea also required its own service. The small plates that
accompanied a tea service were for sweets or finger sandwiches.
``Today, these make very nice plates for salad, which Americans
serve as a first course,'' Chefetz said. ``Tea and dessert services
were always more decorative than the dinner plates, to show off the
dessert. It's always nice to pre-set and start with the prettier
plate, because that's what people see first.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Modern Antiques for the Table,'' Chefetz notes that the
beauty of china made during the Arts &AMP; Crafts period, is in its
subdued patterning. That allows it to mix with contemporary pieces
without fear of clashing. Its predominantly subtle colors work well
with today's tableware, affording an opportunity to combine the
best of the old with the new.
</P>
<P>
   Antique silver and glass are also able to meld well with
contemporary settings, Chefetz said.
</P>
<P>
   The richly decorated silver from the Arts &AMP; Crafts period can be
used for a special dinner party or be interspersed with new pieces
for a Sunday brunch or luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   The rich colors that were used in stained glass windows and
showed up in the table glass of the period are particularly
appealing, Chefetz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, what could be lovelier than a luncheon table set with
Depression-era glasses of pink and green, maybe set off with a
centerpiece of complementary roses?'' she said. ``The mix and match
possibilities are endless, and Depression glass still remains
well-priced, making it particularly attractive to young people with
a lifelong love of collecting vintage glass. You see many of
America's greatest financial titans choosing reproductions for
their American manor homes, because of the new pride in
machine-made goods.''
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1920s, Arts &AMP; Crafts and Art Nouveau gave way to the
modern look of Art Deco. Exotic designs associated with Art Deco
were lavishly used on both tables and decorative glass by almost
all of the major china, silver and glass manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   As styles changed and more and more women entered the work
world, fine china, crystal and silver flatware were commonly left
in their cases and cabinets. These ornate and delicate settings
were replaced by the more functional and gaily colored plates made
of Bakelite (the first synthetic plastic, developed in 1907) and
Depression glassware.
</P>
<P>
   ``The variety of plates changes as each decade progresses,''
Chefetz said. ``For instance, the geometry of some of the china
made during the 1920s and '30s was so it was possible to wedge
pieces together to conserve needed space in the trunk or rumble
seat of the Model T car. Many china companies responded to the rage
for traveling by car by designing attractive breakfast, bachelor,
tete-a-tete, or tea-for-two sets that were easily packed.''
</P>
<P>
   All kinds of services were made for travel by public and private
train cars and water on yachts and passenger steam ships. Chefetz
said these pieces make wonderful accents.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the holidays at hand, it's great fun to search for
holiday motifs on tableware,'' Chefetz writes in her new book.
``There is an abundance of turkeys, evergreens, rabbits, cherubs
and reindeer to be found on tableware made between 1880 and 1940.
... Pine cones were particularly popular during the Arts and Crafts
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be argued that for a table to be truly spectacular, it
must be placed in a truly spectacular setting _ and yet, a
thoughtfully planned table, lovingly set with treasured heirlooms,
is very much a world unto itself, much like a stage set, conjuring
up an exotic ambiance that transcends even the plainest environs,''
she added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
