<HEADLINE>
VA. TECH LEAVES BC HIGH AND DRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Tom O'Brien knew the deluge was coming. The Boston
College football coach had the television in his office tuned all
week to the Weather Channel. With each update, the forecast for
Thursday night's game against Virginia Tech grew more ominous: 100
percent chance of rain. Sheets of rain. Torrents of rain.
</P>
<P>
   What O'Brien never figured was that his team would be inundated
by a deluge of turnovers (three interceptions, including one for an
85-yard touchdown, a questionable fumble, and two blocked punts), a
blown goal-line scoring opportunity in the third quarter, and, oh
yes, Virginia Tech's defense, a force of nature that lived up to
its billing as the best in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   On a night when BC would have been better off suiting up Doug
Flutie and Mike Ruth instead of retiring their numbers at halftime,
the Eagles put a damper on the festivities by suffering a 17-0 Big
East loss to the 17th-ranked Hokies in an ESPN matchup before an
Alumni Stadium crowd of 37,628.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech's defense, which has not yielded a rushing
touchdown this season, dealt BC _ owner of the conference's most
potent offense _ its first blanking since a 21-0 loss at Navy in
1980. It was BC's first shutout loss at home since 1972, a 10-0
setback against Tulane.
</P>
<P>
   One bit of BC consolation: The Hokies (5-0, overall, 3-0 Big
East) were roughed up by senior running back Mike Cloud, who
carried 32 times for 186 yards, including a long of 65 yards. They
were gaudy numbers when you consider Virginia Tech's rushing
defense was allowing just 58 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I think we need to build an ark,'' said O'Brien,
managing a weak smile and a weaker quip in his postgame remarks.
``It was a tough night out there. I think that Virginia Tech did a
great job. They're a great defense. They cause so many problems
with their quickness. Obviously, throwing a couple of
interceptions, they returned one for a touchdown, that's a killer.
I think that our defense played well. They, for the most part, gave
us an opportunity to win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   It was BC's offense, senior quarterback Scott Mutryn in
particular, that wound up costing the Eagles. Mutryn (10 for 20,
116 yards) was sacked three times and committed four costly errors
when he threw three interceptions _ one that Pierson Prioleau
returned for an 85-yard touchdown that gave the Hokies a 7-0 lead
in the first quarter _ and fumbled a wet ball on a critical
fourth-and-goal play from the Virginia Tech 1.
</P>
<P>
   On the latter play, Mutryn regained possession but was dropped
for an 11-yard loss by defensive end Corey Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the key moment of the game came when it's 14-0 and
we're on the 1-inch line and can't get in,'' O'Brien said. ``You
put the ball in the end zone there and it's 14-7, and who knows
what's going to happen?''
</P>
<P>
   Mutryn, who fumbled on second and goal as well, concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to get into the end zone there and we didn't, and
that's totally on me,'' he said. ``That's two quarterback sneaks
we've got to get in there, and that fourth-down play, that's my
fault, too. We've got to punch that ball in there. It's
disappointing for me to come out and play as poorly as I did. It
really hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   It nullified a valiant effort by BC's defense, which held
Virginia Tech's sputtering offense to 236 yards total (72 passing)
and forced six turnovers (four fumbles, two interceptions).
</P>
<P>
   Because of injuries, Virginia Tech coach Frank Beamer started
his third quarterback in as many conference games _ redshirt
sophomore Nick Sorensen, who served as Al Clark's backup last
season before switching to free safety. Sorensen was pressed into
service in a 27-7 victory at Pittsburgh two weeks ago when
sophomore backup Dave Meyer suffered a separated shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I've ever been around a game where there were
more big plays,'' Beamer said. ``They've got a great offensive
line, but we have some guys who are fighting their heart out.''
</P>
<P>
   Unable to muster much offense, the Hokies relied on their
special teams to come up with their second touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Davis blocked a Jason Malecki punt at the Virginia Tech 48
and recovered for the Hokies at the BC 16 in the third quarter.
Four plays later, Lamont Pegues crashed in from the 2, giving
Virginia Tech a 14-0 lead with 6:23 left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles threatened on their next drive when Cloud ripped off
a 65-yard run before he was dragged down from behind by Loren
Johnson at the Virginia Tech 23. Two plays later, Cloud had BC
knocking on the door when he carried for a 10-yard gain to the 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was right there; I should've got in,'' Cloud said. ``But a
guy from the back side came and clamped down on my legs and I
couldn't get enough drive to punch it in.''
</P>
<P>
   There the Hokies stymied the Eagles, including the last-gasp
play that was supposed to be a play-action pass to Cloud in the
right flat until Mutryn mishandled the ball.
</P>
<P>
   After the teams exchanged possessions, the Hokies converted
another BC turnover into an easy score. Ricky Hall recovered a
muffed punt by Jermaine Walker, who appeared to regain possession
when he stripped the ball from Hall's hands. However, officials
ruled the play dead when Hall recovered at the BC 18.
</P>
<P>
   Shayne Graham, who missed a 26-yard chip shot wide left in the
first quarter, put the game out of reach when he tacked on a
29-yard field goal with 8:38 to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that we played extremely hard and I think it's a great
measuring stick for where we are,'' said O'Brien, whose team now
must prepare for a visit from Syracuse a week from Saturday. ``We
can compete. As long as we stay healthy and we don't turn the
football over and do some of the things that I think we can, we can
be a heck of a football team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
