<SLUG> BC-FBC-HOLLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOUD IS SILVER LINING FOR BC 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ You almost had no reason to watch it. No one watches a
game with 10 fumbles and five interceptions if they can help it.
And don't forget the rain. There were times you looked out at the
Alumni Stadium field and wondered if someone were dishing out
buckets of water, just like they do during those fake torrential
rain scenes in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   No, you had almost no reason to watch Boston College's 17-0 loss
to Virginia Tech Thursday night. Almost no reason.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Grier was watching. A few seats away from him, Bill Polian
was watching, too. These men make their living by evaluating
football players for the Patriots and Colts. So they were here to
see what players on either team possibly could help them in the
NFL. Sometimes professional football observers can make you dizzy
with their breakdown of the game. It is as if they are saying,
``This is why I get paid for this and you don't.'' But then there
are days when all football fans are equal, days when you all look
at a player and simply say, ``He's very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Grier said that Thursday night about Mike Cloud. Polian said it.
More than 37,000 people probably said it a few times as they peered
through raincoats and watched Cloud run for 186 yards on 32
carries. That performance would have been impressive enough on a
normal day. But when a ball is constantly sloshed through water and
you have to carry against one of the fastest defenses in the
country, falling 14 yards short of 200 is other-worldly.
</P>
<P>
   This is all fitting, isn't it? On a night when BC coach Tom
O'Brien said he was watching the Weather Channel to see what was
coming next; and on a night when you swore you could hear countless
echoes of Johnny Gill's baritone on ``Can You Stand The Rain,'' a
young man named Cloud ran through the rain. That doesn't
necessarily blunt the pain of BC's first home shutout loss since
1972. And it won't stop the skeptics from saying that the Eagles
can count on only two more wins this season (Pittsburgh and Navy).
It also didn't make O'Brien sleep any easier knowing that his team
was inches from a touchdown, had four shots to get in the end zone,
and didn't do it. But even O'Brien, an ex-Marine who doesn't throw
around praise easily, had to give Cloud his props.
</P>
<P>
   Long after the stadium had cleared, O'Brien approached Cloud as
he was doing an interview. ``I thought he was going to yell at me
or something,'' Cloud said. ``I thought I had done something
wrong.'' Not at all. O'Brien touched Cloud on the shoulder and held
out his hand. ``Good job,'' the coach said. ``That was a hell of a
job.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach was right. BC has a huge offensive line, a line whose
members told Cloud before the season that they wanted to see him
get 2,000 yards. They are a talented line, but you have to be a
very good back to break 2,000. Cloud is very good. You could argue
that every great runner is motivated by something powerful,
something that flashes across his mental screen each time he
touches the ball. Cloud is no exception. The BC athletic department
lists him as 5 feet 11 inches and 201 pounds. The weight is not in
question. But Cloud goes somewhere between 5-9 and 5-10 (maybe) in
bare feet. But he runs hard for many reasons.
</P>
<P>
   One is his brother, Kevin. A few years ago, Kevin Cloud broke
three vertebrae in his neck and had bone chips in his spinal cord.
That ended Kevin's football career. Now he has an academic
scholarship at the University of Hartford ``and has a 3.9
grade-point average,'' a smiling Mike Cloud said. Mike used to
idolize Walter Payton and wear No. 34 because of him. But when
Kevin was injured, he switched to his current No. 21 and began to
have even more respect for his brother.
</P>
<P>
   You could also point to Cloud's studies. He is the ultimate
student-athlete. He already has a degree in sociology and is
currently working on one in marketing. ``I'd like to take the money
I make in the NFL and use it to open my own business,'' he said.
``A nightclub-restaurant. Something laid-back.''
</P>
<P>
   Cloud's mention of the NFL is not unrealistic. ``He's a good
back; there are no two ways about it,'' Polian said Thursday night.
``These aren't the best conditions to be running in, but he's doing
a great job.'' Grier, the man who drafted Curtis Martin and Robert
Edwards, also was intrigued by Cloud. ``I've seen him a few times
now,'' Grier said. ``He's a good back.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there were a few downers. Cloud did have one of those
10 fumbles (he recovered it). And personnel men get kind of antsy
when they see an offense drive inches from an opponent's goal
without coming away with a touchdown. But that's just nitpicking
when you compare Cloud's 186 yards to the frequent bobbles and
fumbles going around the rest of the field. It wasn't fun to watch.
A man named John Valente at least helped make it a listenable game.
Announcing play-by-play in the press box, Valente unleashed a
Seinfeldian ``Hello, Newman'' after a fumble recovery by BC
linebacker Adam Newman. A few people laughed. They had to. It was
almost better than the alternative, which was watching.
</P>
<P>
   Almost better. That's because Mike Cloud was in the building,
carrying the ball over and over. BC may not be good enough to go to
a bowl this year. But the Eagles are worth watching as long as
Cloud is running.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
