<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-FLUTIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLUTIE'S NUMBER IS UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They have a special place for their awards.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Flutie, he of the fabled Hail Mary pass that beat Miami,
47-45, the day after Thanksgiving 14 years ago, has a spot in the
front room of his home with lighting focusing on the 1984 Heisman
Trophy he won as the nation's finest college football player.
</P>
<P>
   And Mike Ruth has created a space of honor in the middle of his
recreation room for the 1985 Outland Trophy he earned as the
nation's best lineman.
</P>
<P>
   Now the two Boston College legends have something else. At
halftime of Thursday night's game against Virginia Tech, their
uniform numbers _ Flutie's 22 and Ruth's 68 _ were retired. They
took their place on the Wall of Fame at Alumni Stadium, next to
those of Mike Holovak, Charlie O'Rourke, Luke Urban, and Tony
Thurman.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was recruited by Boston College, I was told that BC
hadn't gone to a bowl game in 40 years but that we had a 5-10
player who would bring us to another one, and he brought us to
three bowl games in a row,'' said former nose guard Ruth, noting
that Flutie was that player.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Heisman and The Pass have stood the test of time,'' Flutie
said. ``And this will stand the test of time. It's something that I
can be proud of the rest of my life. This is a great achievement,
what BC is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flutie gang's last bowl was the best _ the 1985 Cotton, in
which BC belted Houston, 45-28. The other postseason trips ended in
losses _ to Auburn in the 1982 Tangerine Bowl, 33-26, and to Notre
Dame in the 1983 Liberty Bowl, 19-18.
</P>
<P>
   Before that run, BC hadn't been to a bowl game since the 1943
Orange.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now people can look at the wall and you get a great feel as to
who 22 and 68 were,'' said Flutie, the Buffalo Bills reserve
quarterback who had two teammates with him for the trip. ``Fame is
fleeting, and this is something that will last forever, including
with the guys who played with me, like Gerard Phelan (who caught
the TD pass against Miami).''
</P>
<P>
   Flutie is still playing football, 14 years after leaving
college. Many of the young fans in the stadium Thursday night were
just 4 or 5 years old when Flutie was performing his exploits at
the Heights, but they saluted him vigorously.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the only Division 1-A offer, and I thought I'd take
advantage of the university,'' Flutie said. ``I didn't have any
expectations of myself.''
</P>
<P>
   All Flutie and Ruth have to do now is point to their numbers.
They will be up there forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my wife, Judy, here with my two kids,'' said Ruth, ``and
they can see the wall, and I can lose all my hair and I now have a
pot belly, but the numbers on the wall will last for a long, long
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 1418EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
