<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8501 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-ANA     10-09 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS SHOW HAS MUCH HAPPIER PLOT LINE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLLEGE-ANALYSIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ Prime time at the Heights. Prime-time national
television exposure. Reporters from USA Today and the New York
Times. Boston Mayor Thomas M. Menino on hand. All the attention
focused on Boston College athletics.
</P>
<P>
   And not a scandal or controversy in sight. No talk of
point-shaving or gambling. No disgruntled coaches or players. No
harried BC officials attemping to put a positive spin on a negative
story.
</P>
<P>
   How refreshing. If progress is best measured in tiny steps, then
what happened at Alumni Stadium Thursday night must be considered
significant at the very least.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, consider the crowd of 37,628 who came to watch a
game _ available on television _ on a miserable evening in a
driving rain.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time certainly in the memory of the current senior
class, the focus on the Eagle football program was directed at was
happening on the field, not off it.
</P>
<P>
   With Thursday night's ESPN special against Virginia Tech, the
Eagles were in the spotlight for all the right reasons.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, it was not classic football. Not with all those
turnovers hampering the offenses. And nothing more than bragging
rights in the Big East was at stake.
</P>
<P>
   You have to understand where the BC program was two years ago to
appreciate Thursday night. Saddled with losses, embarrassed by a
gambling scandal that put the football program on the nightly news
and ultimately brought down coach Dan Henning and his staff, the
Eagles were in the most negative situation imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's negative _ a sloppy 17-0 loss to No. 17
Virginia Tech _ was frustrating for coach Tom O'Brien and his staff
since all of the Hokies' points were almost direct gifts from
turnovers deep in Eagle territory. But it pales in comparison to
events of a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's team might have taken something positive out of that
kind of loss.
</P>
<P>
   These Eagles have gotten past the point of moral victories.
Forget about how BC basically outplayed Tech all evening, shutting
down the Hokie offense and moving the ball fairly well itself.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles were genuinely angry that they lost because they knew
that were it not for the turnovers, they had a chance _ a good
chance _ to win. Such was not the case two weeks ago when
Louisville simply blew the Eagle defense off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Two blocked punts, three interceptions, one fumble, and a
failure to score with a first and goal on the opponent's 1-yard
line will make all but the very best teams losers on any given
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our chances,'' said O'Brien, who now must put his
team's pysche back together in the 10 days remaining before
Syracuse comes to town. ``But I think this shows we can compete.
It's a measuring stick where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   For Virginia Tech, which has been a Big East and quasi-national
power for several years, it was just another step along the highway
to what coach Frank Beamer hopes will be a spot in the Bowl
Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Eagles, it was something different. The memory of
the stain caused by the gambling scandal two years ago is fading
fast. O'Brien, who surely has the Eagles headed in the right
direction despite their second loss in succession, has brought
stability and pride to a program that needed them as much as any in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake about it _ lots of people are rooting for
O'Brien and BC.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Fiesta Bowl (and insight.com Bowl) head man John Junker
about the Eagles and you hear a plea for them to get bowl-eligible
sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd love to have BC,'' said Junker the other day from his
Phoenix office. ``They would be a very attractive team.''
</P>
<P>
   Junker was speaking about the insight.com Bowl, which will
select the third-place (or choice) team from the Big East for the
game in Tucson Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Junker also knows that the Eagles still have a rough road to
reach the six-win minimum requirement for bowl eligibility and the
seven wins likely necesssary to play in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   But it's obvious that BC _ which Thursday night unveiled some of
its past greatness, honoring former stars Mike Ruth and Doug Flutie
_ is in demand again.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the Eagles' program is still fragile. They have
barely reached the stage where they can beat the teams they are
supposed to beat, much less pull off an upset of a nationally
ranked team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of our growing process as a football team,'' O'Brien
said. ``We'll get better. And we'll play our hearts out against
Syracuse.''
</P>
<P>
   And after that come Navy, Miami, Notre Dame, Pitt, and West
Virginia, none of them _ with the possible exception of Navy _
anything close to a sure W.
</P>
<P>
   To become bowl-eligible and get to Tucson over the Christmas
holidays will take some luck as well as skill.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's loss will make finishing above .500 a struggle
_ the Eagles will need to pull off some major upsets to do it.
</P>
<P>
   But even if this turns into another sub-.500 season, it seems
clear that the Eagles under O'Brien are flying north, not south.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 1419EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
