<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8503 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-PADRES-BRAVES-BOS     10-09 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PADRES-BRAVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES DOUBLE UP BRAVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Can the nightmare be recurring for the Atlanta Braves?
They are the acknowledged class of the National League, playing for
the pennant a record seventh straight time. But they are on the
verge of being denied a chance to advance to the World Series for a
second straight year by a nemesis named Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Brown beat the Braves twice in the NL Championship
Series for the Florida Marlins, who eventually won the World Series
with a team that was almost immediately disbanded for financial
reasons. Now Brown has chance to inflict damage on the Braves while
representing the opposite coast. And that's just what he did
Thursday night, hurling a three-hitter, striking out 11, and
getting hits that figured in both scoring rallies as the San Diego
Padres silenced the Braves, 3-0, and seized a 2-0 advantage in the
best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's on to San Diego for three games, with Brown looming
like a thunderclap in Game 5, if necessary. Maybe by then, the
Braves will have figured out a way to get to him, because they sure
haven't so far. In his career against Atlanta, Brown is 6-0 with a
1.85 ERA; in the playoffs, he's 3-0, 2.63.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 24 hours after Ken Caminiti's 10th-inning homer won
the rain-delayed opener, 3-2, Braves hitters again struggled.
</P>
<P>
   They mustered only three singles, an output Brown nearly matched
by himself. Tom Glavine, the NL's only 20-game winner, allowed just
one run in six innings but wound up throwing 121 pitches and
issuing six walks to go with six strikeouts. That is not a
blueprint for beating Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying like crazy to win a ballgame,'' said Braves
manager Bobby Cox, ``and we just couldn't hit the guy. I don't know
if any team would have hit him tonight. The Houston team has as
good a hitting lineup as there is in the National League, and they
couldn't touch him'' _ when Brown struck out 16 Astros in the
opener of last week's Division Series. ``We have a good-hitting
lineup and we couldn't, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown wasn't as sharp as he had been in throttling the Astros,
but then again, that's comparing degrees of excellence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I had quite the stuff I had that night,'' said
Brown. ``But from the standpoint of just making adjustments as the
game went along and trying to use what was working at that moment,
I was pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Braves are a team that can hurt you from top to bottom.
You've got to minimize your mistakes against them. I think I threw
everything at them but the kitchen sink.''
</P>
<P>
   If he had, that probably would have been a strike, too. It was
one of those nights for Brown.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he made just one mistake _ and that was while running
the bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``What an idiot,'' he said about being nailed at third in the
sixth inning after an overthrow following a single by Quilvio Veras
that brought in San Diego's first run _ the only one Brown needed.
``I misread the play. I thought the throw home got further past
him. Glavine picked it up and threw me out. Obviously, it was
misjudgement on my part. It could have cost us the ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Not really. The Padres come to life each time Brown pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin Brown is as tough a competitor as I've ever seen,'' said
manager Bruce Bochy. ``He's just locked in. When you have somebody
like Kevin Brown, it gives you a tremendous sense of confidence.
When he's out there, you feel you're going to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Kevin would make a difference in our club. But I didn't
think he'd make this big an impact.''
</P>
<P>
   He got the support he needed on Veras's hit _ one of three he
had for the night _ which followed base hits by Chris Gomez and
Brown, ground balls all.
</P>
<P>
   For insurance, the Padres scored two in the ninth off lefthander
Odalis Perez.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was in the middle of this rally, too. After a leadoff
single, he moved to second on Veras's single. Atlanta tried to pick
him off second, but the throw by catcher Javy Lopez went into
center field and Brown wound up on third. From there, he scored on
an infield single by Steve Finley. Wally Joyner's bases-loaded
single brought in the last run, window dressing for Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``What more could we want at this point?'' said Brown. ``It's a
huge victory, a moral victory coming in here and facing this
caliber of team.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are sick of facing Brown's caliber of pitcher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
