<SLUG> BC-POLICE-TRAINING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE CHIEF CALLS FOR MORE TRAINING AFTER FATAL SHOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA and RAY DELGADO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The fatal shooting of an advertising executive
who had gunned his car at two patrolmen has prompted San Francisco
Police Chief Fred Lau to order specialized training to help
officers handle such confrontations.
</P>
<P>
   Of 12 shootings involving the police this year, seven have
involved officers firing at cars during traffic stops or attempted
arrests. Two, including the latest, resulted in death.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to learn from all of these incidents,'' Lau said
Thursday. ``We need a comprehensive training program to reduce the
number of these kinds of incidents. ... You can never predict the
behavior of suspects, but we can improve the safety for officers.
This is the kind of thing we need to address in training.''
</P>
<P>
   John M. Smart Jr., 46, an executive for New York-based
Interbrand, was shot dead late Tuesday when the two officers fired
as many as 13 rounds at his 1996 Mercedes convertible. The police
say the officers fired as Smart drove at them, minutes after they
interceded in a struggle between Smart and a woman.
</P>
<P>
   Homicide investigators said the officers believed their lives
were in danger and had no choice but to shoot as the car bore down
on them. Smart was not armed, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Under departmental rules, officers are not to fire at suspects
fleeing in cars, but are allowed to shoot in cases of self-defense
or to protect the lives of others.
</P>
<P>
   But Lau said the department needs to offer its patrol officers
better training. He said, ideally, officers should avoid firing
their weapons. But, he added, ``We need to protect the public and
allow officers to protect themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very concerned about these incidents. I don't want to
second-guess (the officers') right to defend themselves and other
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The department's weapons policy has been heavily scrutinized
since May 13, when 17-year-old Sheila Detoy was shot dead by
officers as she rode in the car of a man the police said was
fleeing a drug bust.
</P>
<P>
   The police homicide unit, the district attorney and the Police
Department's Management Control Division have launched separate
investigations into the Smart shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The incident began when the officers saw Smart involved in an
apparent quarrel with a woman in his car. The officers stopped the
argument and separated the two for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   When Smart was allowed to re-enter his car, he gunned it into
reverse, pinning one officer, who was standing on the curb, between
the open passenger door and a parking meter, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The officer pulled away from the meter and ran into the street
where the other officer joined him. With their guns drawn, both
officers ordered Smart out of the car, but he shifted into drive
and headed at them, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   They started shooting as the car approached them, the police
said. The car swerved across the oncoming lanes of traffic and
crashed into a building on the eastern sidewalk. Smart was
pronounced dead at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   The woman fled and the police are seeking her for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want her to come in voluntarily and talk to us,'' homicide
Lt. David Robinson said Thursday. ``This woman is a witness. ... We
do not see her as someone who committed a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson confirmed that at least 13 shell casings were found at
the scene.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 1421EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981009.0122 </DOCNO>
