<HEADLINE>
PACIFIC DIVISION
</HEADLINE>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... and one forward.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
ANAHEIM MIGHTY DUCKS &QL; 
(FR)Coach: Craig Hartsburg &QL; 
(FR)Record: 26-43-13 (sixth) &QL; 
(FR)Key personnel changes: Acquired LW Stu Grimson and D Kevin
Haller from Carolina for D David Karpa and a 2000 fourth-round
draft pick; signed D Fredrik Olausson and D Scott Ferguson; lost RW
Scott Young as a free agent. &QL; 
(FR)Outlook: The disappointing Ducks have only one change that
matters: superstar Paul Kariya is back with his head clear, his
'97-98 season ended when he was crosschecked by then Blackhawk Gary
Suter just prior to the Olympics. Kariya and Teemu Selanne are two
of the most talented and exciting players in the game. Once past
that super duo, however, these are lame ducks. GM Pierre Gauthier's
mandate will be to fill out the picture, make it a competitive
squad without giving up either of his super shooters. The place to
start will be defense, where the Ducks have youth on their side but
little else. There is no power-play quarterback, which severely
impacts what either Kariya or Selanne can do on the man-advantage.
The option of putting Scott Young (now in St. Louis) back there is
gone. Add the right player or two, and it could get interesting in
a hurry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DALLAS STARS &QL; 
(FR)Coach: Ken Hitchcock &QL; 
(FR)Record: 49-22-11 (first in Central) &QL; 
(FR)Key personnel changes: Signed D Brett Hull and RW Brent
Severyn; lost LW Greg Adams, LW Benoit Hogue, and C Bob Bassen as
free agents; acquired C Tony Hrkac from Nashvile for future
considerations. &QL; 
(FR)Outlook: This is the one club out west that could give Detroit
a real tickle in the ribs. They handed Brett Hull $17 million for
the next three years and he'll team with Mike Modano for one
frightening line, with Jere Lehtinen the lead checker. Hull will
start the season at left wing, a switch he made voluntarily,
knowing that Lehtinen's preferred side was the right (company guy
to the end, Hull). Hitchcock's crew is deep up front and big on
defense. Holdout Jamie Langenbrunner finally signed a new deal at
the start of the week, and he'll help fill out a second line with
Pat Verbeek and, eventually, Joe Nieuwendyk (back from knee
surgery). They realized last year that they needed to toughen up
some and went out in the offseason and signed Brent Severyn away
from the Ducks, a move that should take care of yet another missing
piece. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
LOS ANGELES KINGS &QL; 
(FR)Coach: Larry Robinson &QL; 
(FR)Record: 38-33-11 (second) &QL; 
(FR)Key personnel changes: Acquired D Doug Bodger from New Jersey;
signed D Steve Duchesne; lost D Jan Vopat as a free agent. &QL; 
(FR)Outlook: Still waiting for that big, franchise-saving Eric
Lindros trade. The Kings are getting better, slowly, but they're
still recovering from the lingering Wayne Gretzky hangover. The
Kings could find it difficult to improve much on last year, when
their two top scorers were former Bruins Jozef Stumpel and Glen
Murray. The picture on offense is about the same, unless one or two
kids (Olli Jokinen? Don MacLean?) can come in and deliver a
legitimate second line. The key off-season hurdle was getting
heavy-hitting defenseman Rob Blake, the Norris Trophy winner, under
contract, which GM Dave Taylor did for more than $5 million a year.
Until further notice, it's a .500 team in need of a marquee forward
to take charge, ergo the rumors about a megaswap for Lindros. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PHOENIX COYOTES &QL; 
(FR)Coach: Jim Schoenfeld &QL; 
(FR)Record: 35-35-12 (fourth in Central) &QL; 
(FR)Key personnel changes: RW Mike Gartner and D Jim Johnson
retired; signed D Jyrki Lumme, LW Greg Adams, and C Mike Sullivan;
sent C Craig Janney to Tampa Bay; lost D Murray Baron and C Mark
Janssens as free agents. &QL; 
(FR)Outlook: For around $11 million, the Coyotes got Keith Tkachuk
to agree to bump his contract out one more year, through 2001. He
should come in and play with a revived passion, which could
translate to another 50-goal season (he dipped to 40 last year
after a pair of 50s). What the Desert Dogs now need is for Jeremy
Roenick to come back and play with his signature fire. First,
they'll have to put him in a position to perform. If the Coyotes
ever really are going to light it up it will be with Roenick
dishing to Tkachuk, allowing them to open up the ice. On defense,
Oleg Tverdovksy should be a more valuable contributor. Teppo
Numminen, if allowed some freedom to create, could be a force. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SAN JOSE SHARKS &QL; 
(FR)Coach: Darryl Sutter &QL; 
(FR)Record: 34-38-10 (fourth) &QL; 
(FR)Key personnel changes: G Kelly Hrudey retired; signed D Bob
Rouse and D Gary Suter; lost RW John MacLean and D Marty McSorley
as free agents. &QL; 
(FR)Outlook: There is plenty of upside here, with some real voids
filled through free agency the last couple of years. Mike Vernon
arrived last year to secure the net. Now Gary Suter is in from
Chicago, adding instant respectability to the defense, which
already included hitman/terrorist Bryan Marchment. But what about
up front? The day will come, everyone says, when Patrick Marleau
(the No. 2 draft pick to Joe Thornton's No. 1) develops as the
club's franchise center. But that won't happen this year. Sutter
will have to coax some badly needed points out of what amounts to a
below-average bunch of shooters and passers _ the Stephane
Matteaus, Shawn Burrs, and Murray Cravens of the world. The one guy
he could lean on is Owen Nolan, but it just seems that Nolan never
blossoms (41 points last season). &QL; 
 &QL; 
NORTHWEST DIVISION &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Calgary Flames &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
(FR)Coach: Brian Sutter &QL; 
(FR)Record: 26-41-15 (fifth in Pacific) &QL; 
(FR)Key personnel changes: Acquired C Bob Bassen from Dallas;
acquired D Phil Housley off waivers from Washington; dealt LW
German Titov to Pittsburgh; D Steve Smith came out of retirement;
signed G Ken Wregget. &QL; 
(FR)Outlook: For now, Theo Fleury remains the centerpiece of the
franchise. But the Flames are so small-market, it may be impossible
to keep paying him, and he could be worth far more in overall
roster enhancement than, say, another 90- or 100-point season.
Meanwhile, former Bruins coach Sutter has to keep force-feeding
kids. Not a pretty prospect after last season's collapse. To help,
aging blueliners Housley and Steve Smith have been added to the
mix. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Colorado Avalanche &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
(FR)Coach: Bob Hartley &QL; 
(FR)Record: 39-26-17 (first in Pacific) &QL; 
(FR)Key personnel changes: Signed C Chris Drury from Boston
University; lost D Uwe Krupp and C Tom Fitzgerald as free agents;
RW Jari Kurri retired. &QL; 
(FR)Outlook: Exceptional forwards and highly respectable at defense
and in goal. So what's wrong? That's left for rookie coach Hartley
to answer. GM Pierre Lacroix has gone from acquiring Patrick Roy in
a brilliant swap to letting the likes of Krupp and Young, Mike
Ricci and Mike Keane leave without getting much, if anything, in
return. He also watched Marc Crawford walk (or was he fired?) in
the offseason. But there is still a lot here for Hartley to
kickstart, beginning with forwards Peter Forsberg, Joe Sakic,
Valeri Kamensky, and let's not forget lovable Claude Lemieux. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Edmonton Oilers &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
(FR)Coach: Ron Low &QL; 
(FR)Record: 35-37-10 (third in Pacific) &QL; 
(FR)Key personnel changes: Acquired G Mikhail Shtalenkov and C Jim
Dowd from Nashville; signed D Marty McSorley and RW Pat Falloon;
lost G Curtis Joseph as a free agent; D Kevin Lowe retired. &QL; 
(FR)Outlook: Doug Weight spent training camp on the sidelines,
asking for about $4 million a year, and unless he pulls on a
sweater, the Oil might not have anyone to put the puck in the net.
Edmonton does have a talented and exciting defense, ex-Boston
University blueliner Tom Poti only adding to the mix that already
included Roman Hamrlik and Janne Niinimaa. GM Glen Sather let
Curtis Joseph walk and now will entrust the net to journeyman Bob
Essensa and ex-Duck backup Mikhail Shtalenkov. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Vancouver Canucks &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
(FR)Coach: Mike Keenan &QL; 
(FR)Record: 25-43-14 (seventh in Pacific) &QL; 
(FR)Key personnel changes: Signed D Murray Baron; lost D Jyrki
Lumme, G Arturs Irbe, and F Brian Noonan as free agents. &QL; 
(FR)Outlook: Brian Burke gave up his cushy seat at NHL headquarters
for the hot seat as GM here, where superstar Pavel Bure says he'll
never again wear the Canucks uniform. About the only thing the
Canucks might have going for them is that Mark Messier is back with
something to prove. Wrentham's Garth Snow is the No. 1 netminder,
but that could change if Bure gets swapped for a franchise
netminder (hello, Felix Potvin?). &QL;
