<HEADLINE>
NHL 1998-1999: WESTERN CONFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT AND NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 
WESTERN CONFERENCE 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CENTRAL DIVISION &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHICAGO BLACKHAWKS &QL; 
(FR)Coach: Dirk Graham &QL; 
(FR)Record: 30-39-13 (fifth) &QL; 
(FR)Key personnel changes: Acquired G Mark Fitzpatrick and a 1999
fourth-round draft pick from Tampa Bay for D Michal Sykora; sent G
Chris Terreri to New Jersey for a 1999 second- or third-round draft
pick; signed C Doug Gilmour, C Mark Janssens, D Paul Coffey, and RW
Ed Olczyk; lost D Gary Suter and C Greg Johnson as free agents. &QL; 
(FR)Outlook: They passed on Brett Hull and instead lavished their
money ($6 million per year) on Gilmour, who'll have to wring a lot
out of those 35-year-old legs to help the goal-challenged Hawks.
They didn't have anyone with a point per game last year (Tony
Amonte was tops with 73 in 82 games). Coffey fell off the map in
Philadelphia. He's 37 and not the kickstart this team needs.
Remember when Alexei Zhamnov was going to step in and be the
statistical equivalent of Jeremy Roenick? It's been two years and
Zhamnov looks forever to be in that almost-but-never-quite
category. Jeff Hackett will handle most of the load in net after 58
games last year and Graham no doubt will try to tighten the game
plan even more around him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DETROIT RED WINGS &QL; 
(FR)Coach: Scotty Bowman &QL; 
(FR)Record: 44-23-15 (second) &QL; 
(FR)Key personnel changes: D Viacheslav Fetisov retired; signed D
Uwe Krupp; lost D Dmitri Mironov and D Bob Rouse as free agents. &QL; 
(FR)Outlook: Bowman, recovering from an offseason heart procedure,
will make it back sometime in the first half. There is no real
hurry. The Wings will be back in the hunt, their lineup spiced a
little with the heavy-shooting Krupp, acquired from Colorado. The
Wings pull on that postseason face that make guys like Doug Brown,
Darren McCarthy, and Kirk Maltby invaluable Cup performers. Who
heard of Tomas Holmstrom until it really became time to play? In
other words, they're rich in talent (Steve Yzerman, Brendan
Shanahan, Sergei Fedorov) and deep, too. Could they have won it all
without handing Fedorov the $28 million over 100 days? No one
knows, but their blend of depth and discipline would not have made
it a surprise. A third straight Cup should be no surprise, either. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NASHVILLE PREDATORS &QL; 
(FR)Coach: Barry Trotz &QL; 
(FR)Record: First season &QL; 
(FR)Key veteran players: Acquired D Bob Boughner, G Mike Dunham, C
Greg Johnson, and RW Blair Atcheynum in expansion draft; acquired
RW Vitali Yachmenev from Los Angeles for future considerations;
acquired RW Sergei Krivokrasov from Chicago; signed C Tom
Fitzgerald and D Rob Zettler as free agents. &QL; 
(FR)Outlook: The ever-growing,
team-in-every-town-bigger-than-Biloxi NHL now brings Game On to the
Big Guitar. The good people of Nashville will have to be patient
(witness the suffering souls of San Jose, who've had little more to
cling to than a wicked cool logo for seven years). Ex-Caps GM David
Poile has remained true to his initial plan. He wants speed and
grit. He even brought in ex-Panther Tom Fitzgerald and instantly
made him captain. They hope they've got a franchise player in
waiting with pivot David Legwand. With the likes of Fitzgerald,
Atcheynum (St. Louis), Zettler (Toronto), Boughner (Buffalo), there
is at least the fabric of an enthusiastic squad. Dunham has waited
since the '94 Olympics to get a real big league shot in net. It's
all his now, with all the rubber he can handle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ST. LOUIS BLUES &QL; 
(FR)Coach: Joel Quenneville &QL; 
(FR)Record: 45-29-8 (third) &QL; 
(FR)Key personnel changes: Signed RW Scott Young; lost RW Brett
Hull and D Steve Duchesne as free agents. &QL; 
(FR)Outlook: OK, everything here is the same, except with former
Boston University winger Young plugged in as one of the ways to
fill the Hull void. Oh boy and uh-oh. Not to mention the Blues also
saw Duchesne pack bags for LA and the developing Blair Atcheynum
get gobbled up by the Predators. If this club can hope to play
around .600 again (.598 last year), a lot more of the load is going
to fall to Pierre Turgeon, Geoff Courtnall, and even Jim Campbell.
They'll tighten up on defense without Hull, and that's an emerging
Blue strongsuit with the talented Chris Pronger back there. And,
oh, they gave Al MacInnis $15 million over three years to stick
around. He's the type to earn every penny, and he'll be asked to do
just that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NORTHWEST DIVISION &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CALGARY FLAMES &QL; 
(FR)Coach: Brian Sutter &QL; 
(FR)Record: 26-41-15 (fifth in Pacific) &QL; 
(FR)Key personnel changes: Acquired C Bob Bassen from Dallas for C
Aaron Gavey; acquired D Phil Housley off waivers from Washington;
sent G Rick Tabaracci to Washington for a conditional 2000 seventh-
or ninth-round draft pick; sent LW German Titov to Pittsburgh; D
Steve Smith came out of retirement; signed G Ken Wregget; lost LW
Todd Hlushko, G Dwayne Roloson, and C Jim Dowd as free agents. &QL; 
(FR)Outlook: For now, Theo Fleury remains the centerpiece of the
franchise. But they're so small-market, it may be impossible to
keep paying him, and he could be worth far more in overall roster
enhancement than, say, another 90- or 100-point season. Meanwhile,
former Bruins coach Sutter has to keep force-feeding kids. Not a
pretty prospect after last season's collapse. To help, aging
blueliners Housley (out of Washington) and Steve Smith (out of
retirement) have been added. If they're at their best, Housley will
help move the puck _ especially on the ravaged power play _ and
Smith should help ex-Penguin Ken Wregget on the defensive end. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
COLORADO AVALANCHE &QL; 
(FR)Coach: Bob Hartley &QL; 
(FR)Record: 39-26-17 (first in Pacific) &QL; 
(FR)Key personnel changes: Signed C Chris Drury from Boston
University; lost D Uwe Krupp and C Tom Fitzgerald as free agents;
RW Jari Kurri retired. &QL; 
(FR)Outlook: Exceptional forwards and highly respectable at defense
and in goal. So what's wrong? That's left for rookie coach Hartley
to answer. General manager Pierre Lacroix has gone from acquiring
Patrick Roy in a brilliant swap to letting the likes of Krupp and
Young, Mike Ricci and Mike Keane leave without getting much, if
anything, in return. He also watched Marc Crawford walk (or was he
fired?) in the offseason. But there is still a lot here for Hartley
to kickstart, beginning with forwards Peter Forsberg, Joe Sakic,
Valeri Kamensky, and let's not forget lovable Claude Lemieux. The
loss of Krupp's big shot from the point will hurt, but the talented
Sandis Ozolinsh makes up for a lot of that on the power play. Don't
be surprised in BU's Chris Drury gets regular second-line duty. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
EDMONTON OILERS &QL; 
(FR)Coach: Ron Low &QL; 
(FR)Record: 35-37-10 (third in Pacific) &QL; 
(FR)Key personnel changes: Acquired G Mikhail Shtalenkov and C Jim
Dowd from Nashville; Signed D Marty McSorley and RW Pat Falloon;
lost G Curtis Joseph as a free agent; D Kevin Lowe retired. &QL; 
(FR)Outlook: Doug Weight spent training camp on the sidelines,
asking for about $4 million a year and unwilling to come in for $3
million. Unless he pulls on a sweater, the Oil might not have
anyone to put the puck in the net. Edmonton does have a talented
and exciting defense, ex-Terrier Tom Poti only adding to the mix
that already included Roman Hamrlik and Janne Niinimaa. GM Glen
Sather let Curtis Joseph walk and now will entrust the net to
journeyman Bob Essensa and ex-Duck backup Mikhail Shtalenkov. If
there are some goals to be found, they'll likely come from Bill
Guerin, Todd Marchant, Dean McAmmond, or perhaps the disappearing
Andrei Kovalenko. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
VANCOUVER CANUCKS &QL; 
(FR)Coach: Mike Keenan &QL; 
(FR)Record: 25-43-14 (seventh in Pacific) &QL; 
(FR)Key personnel changes: Signed D Murray Baron; lost D Jyrki
Lumme, G Arturs Irbe, and F Brian Noonan as free agents. &QL; 
(FR)Outlook: Brian Burke gave up his cushy seat at NHL headquarters
for the hot seat as GM here, where superstar Pavel Bure says he'll
never again wear the Canucks uniform. About the only thing the
Canucks might have going for them is that Mark Messier is back with
something to prove. . Wrentham's Garth Snow is the No. 1 netminder,
backed by Corey Hirsch, but all that could change if Bure gets
swapped for a franchise netminder (hello, Felix Potvin?). The
Canucks tried to convince former Bruin Andy Moog to come out of
retirement, an indication that Snow comes in needing to do some
convincing. The ultimate franchise saver here would be a
Bure-Alexander Mogilny swap to bring in a pair of young, character
forwards or a franchise netminder and one forward. &QL; 
 &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
