<HEADER>
A8516 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROUGH-RIDER-COLLECTIO     10-09 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROUGH-RIDER-COLLECTION-$ADV11-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBRARY SNARES A VAST COLLECTION ON THE `ROUGH RIDER' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 11)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The chair, wide of girth and squat of stature,
seems a good fit for its famous occupant, Theodore Roosevelt, who
described his strength as that of a bull moose.
</P>
<P>
   The dark stain on the chair's curved ladder back has been rubbed
off down to the golden oak's natural grain, presumably by the
kinetic energy of the man known as ``The Rough Rider.'' Similarly,
the rush seat apparently took plenty of abuse and is tattered and
sagging.
</P>
<P>
   Surveying the chair from all sides within inches of its carved
legs and low-slung muscularity, the sensation is magical.
</P>
<P>
   One can imagine the 26th president of the United States summoned
back to life. With a slap of his brawny knee, a flourish of his
spectacles and a ``Bully!'' muttered from beneath his walrus
mustache, you can picture Roosevelt launching his fireplug frame
out of the chair and lighting out for another adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bit of a spar,'' perhaps, as TR liked to call military
battles.
</P>
<P>
   As politician, writer, naturalist, hunter, war hero and rugged
adventurer, everything about Teddy Roosevelt was outsize, and so is
the chair and the collection where it now resides, in its new home,
the New York State Library in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   The State Library paid a private collector $200,000 _ a record
amount for a single collection acquisition in the state's history _
for this Roosevelt collection, which contained an estimated 300,000
items ranging, including books, letters, photographs, campaign
buttons, official papers and teddy bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``The State Library has wanted to have this collection for a
long time because of the tremendous importance of Teddy Roosevelt
to New York state,'' State Librarian Janet Welch said.
</P>
<P>
   The only other public collections to rival it are TR's personal
archives at Harvard University and his presidential papers at the
Library of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt's home at Sagamore Hill, near Oyster Bay, N.Y., is a
historic site, but does not contain much in the way of manuscript
material.
</P>
<P>
   Born Oct. 27, 1858, in New York City, Roosevelt was elected at
age 23 to the state Legislature in Albany, where he built a
reputation as a blunt-spoken, reform-minded Republican. Roosevelt's
swagger is captured in an 1892 oil painting by William Bengough
titled ``New York State Senate'' that hangs today outside the
Senate floor in the state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Riding a wave of immense popularity for leading the Rough Riders
in the battle for Cuba's San Juan Hill in 1898, Roosevelt was
elected governor of New York later that year.
</P>
<P>
   During his brief stay at the governor's mansion, TR wrote the
book ``Rough Riders'' and was a dynamo of legislative and literary
output.
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt won election to the vice presidency under William
McKinley in 1900. McKinley was assassinated on Sept. 14, 1901 in
Buffalo. Roosevelt, who was hiking in the Adirondack High Peaks at
the time, rushed to Buffalo, where he was sworn in as president at
age 42 _ the youngest to hold that office.
</P>
<P>
   The collection came to the State Library only after years of
gentle coaxing of Lyall Squair, a Syracuse collector known far and
wide as a TR omnivore.
</P>
<P>
   Squair, 68, a retired librarian, decided it was time to part
with the tonnage of a four-decade obsession that threatened to
overtake his large home near the Syracuse University campus.
Besides, his wife needed more room for her doll collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Squair's entire living room, the bedrooms, a study, the
basement, every inch of his house was crammed with TR material,''
said James Corsaro, associate librarian and special collections
expert for the State Library.
</P>
<P>
   Corsaro hauled away four vanloads packed tight with TR stuff and
Squair's Syracuse house still wasn't completely emptied of
Teddydom.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the bargain, Squair threw in dozens of boxes of
material for free, Corsaro said, appraised at tens of thousands of
dollars. Squair turned down lucrative offers from dealers and
collectors and refused to sell his TR collection piecemeal.
</P>
<P>
   Squair typed his own catalog to the collection. Its 21 sections
run to more than 200 pages.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every item has a story. Take the chair, for instance. TR brought
it to use when he visited his sister, Corinne Roosevelt Robinson,
at her home _ Henderson House, also known as Cruger Mansion _ in
Jordanville. ``I got the chair at auction near Jordanville many
years ago,'' Squair said. ``I paid $850 for it and outbid members
of the Roosevelt family.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a large bronze bust of TR by the sculptor James Fraser
that once dominated Squair's living room. ``I got that out of
Fraser's studio in Connecticut,'' Squair said.
</P>
<P>
   Squair was a relentless TR tracker. It took him a decade, for
instance, to run down a 1902 limited edition, specially bound
volume by TR titled ``The Deer Family.'' There were just 100 copies
of TR's biological study of deer, and Squair snared No. 16.
</P>
<P>
   Books were where Squair's TR obsession began. As a library
science student at Syracuse University, Squair picked up a copy of
``The Life of Theodore Roosevelt,'' by William Draper Lewish, that
his wife, Linda, had picked up for a dime at a church rummage sale.
``I read it, got interested in TR, followed the bibliography to
other books and kept going,'' said Squair, who made his first
purchases in 1960. ``The next thing I knew, I had a whole house
full of TR books.''
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt was a prolific writer whose published books number in
the dozens, along with hundreds of essays and articles. ``Squair
collected not only every book by TR, but every edition, along with
every book with an introduction or foreword by TR, as well as every
biography and history book about TR,'' Corsaro said. The books
alone in the collection total thousands of volumes.
</P>
<P>
   There are many notable books, including a poetry collection
titled ``Sea and Shore.'' TR gave it to his sister as a Christmas
present in 1874. An inscription penned in a light, controlled
cursive reads: ``To Corinne from her brother. Thee Jr.''
</P>
<P>
   Squair's catholic collecting habits can be seen in odd items of
tangential interest: a half-dozen different bottles of TR barbecue
sauce, thousands of TR postcards, TR china and TR beer trays, even
a bag of jasmine incense sticks (``Carry A Big Stick'') that
purport to burn for three hours.
</P>
<P>
   The list of teddy bears _ named for Roosevelt _ and teddy bear
accoutrements goes on for pages. There are never-before-published
letters, glass negatives and photographs of TR, as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
