A8517 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     10-09 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE IMPEACHMENT TRAIN IS LEAVING AS SCHEDULED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You couldn't really call it a debate. The word ``debate''
implies competition, and Thursday's House vote to initiate
impeachment proceedings against President Clinton was a no-contest
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans rule Congress these days, and the decision to
undertake an open-ended impeachment inquiry was a no-brainer. Any
mystery that existed involved the question of how many Democrats
would join their GOP colleagues in the final vote to launch the
constitutional procedure that could eventually lead to Clinton's
removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   That number turned out to be 31, meaning that 31 Democrats were
either brave enough to defy their party's president or simply
scared stiff of the Clinton-haters back home. All 435 House members
face re-election Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to proceed with impeachment proceedings was a done
deal after Monday's party-line vote by the House Judiciary
Committee, which will conduct impeachment hearings and vote on any
articles of impeachment that result before sending them to the full
House for consideration. If the House votes for impeachment, a
trial will be held in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   A two-thirds vote for conviction in the Senate _ 67 senators _
would oust the president from office.
</P>
<P>
   But we're getting ahead of ourselves, as did some House
Democrats when they argued Thursday that the president should face
some punishment for his reprehensible conduct but that the
punishment should come in the form of a censure or a rebuke or a
reprimand _ something, anything, other than impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   A plea bargain, in other words.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, of course, a plea bargain might be just the ticket
for resolving all this. The pundits are saying that even if the GOP
picks up as many as five additional Senate seats on Nov. 3, there
won't be 67 votes to convict Clinton in an impeachment trial. And
if there's no hope of driving Clinton from office, his enemies in
Congress might be willing to settle for raking him over the coals
with some sort of official reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   Which raises an interesting question: If there is no chance of
convicting Clinton in the Senate, why is the House trying to
impeach him?
</P>
<P>
   The Republican majority in the House insists that it has a
constitutional responsibility to investigate and act upon
allegations of impeachable offenses by the president. House
Democrats, Clinton loyalists and certain nonpartisan cynics insist
that the Republicans will do anything to embarrass and discredit
Clinton _ even it means subjecting the country to the trauma of
impeaching the president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Impeachment,'' don't forget, refers only to the House's
``grand jury'' function of charging the president with ``treason,
bribery, or other high crimes and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   So. The experts believe that Clinton won't be removed from
office. Most Clinton-watchers believe that he will never resign.
Polls show that most Americans don't want him to resign or be
impeached.
</P>
<P>
   What the heck is going on here?
</P>
<P>
   It's called politics. The pols who are pushing impeachment keep
saying that they are concerned about justice and the ``rule of
law,'' but in fact they are concerned about the ballot box.
Republicans and some Democrats are guessing that anti-Clinton
voters will punish them Nov. 3 if they are perceived as soft on
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   They're right. But here's a prediction: If the anti-impeachment
vote comes up bigger than the anti-Clinton vote, the House's zeal
for impeachment will suddenly recede.
</P>
<P>
   And it might be time for a plea bargain after all.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 1425EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
