<SLUG> BC-SNUFF-BOTTLES-$ADV11-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUE SNUFF BOTTLES CAN FETCH A KING'S RANSOM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 11)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Creating a collection is fun, especially when you
have collected bibelots and find they have appreciated in value
over time.
</P>
<P>
   Some items, of course, also can turn into gold mines.
</P>
<P>
   Consider these examples: In the 1994 auction catalog from
Sotheby's on fine Chinese ceramic, furniture and works of art,
snuff bottles were valued at between $600 for a carnelian agate
melon-form bottle all the way up to $70,000 for a rare Imperial
painted Peking enamel bottle.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, an enameled glass miniature double-gourd snuff bottle
from the Qian Long period (1736-1795) in China sold at Sotheby's
for $1.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   These snuff bottles could have been purchased for under $20 as
late as the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the humid climate of East Asia, snuff bottles were
more practical than snuff boxes, in which the powdered tobacco
caked when exposed to moisture. They were used in China for
centuries to hold cosmetics and medicines. Snuff was considered a
medicine, aiding in dispelling colds, provoking sweating, curing
pain in the eyes and teeth, easing throat ailments, asthma,
constipation and helping digestion.
</P>
<P>
   Snuff bottles that are considered to be antiques were
manufactured in China from 1644 to 1912 during the Manchu period or
Ch'ing dynasty. The bottles, with their richly carved or painted
surfaces and in some cases interiors, seldom exceed 2 inches to 3
inches in height. Their beauty comes from the material from which
they were made and the artistry employed to create these small
works of art. The art form includes telling legends and folklore.
</P>
<P>
   Early bottles were made of incised bronze, but as the demand
grew for snuff bottles, materials would grow to include carved
layers of colored glass, cloisonne, enamel, porcelain, coral, jade,
ivory, amber, soapstone, amethyst, turquoise, carnelian and white
jade. New snuff bottles continue to be made today in Hong Kong and
mainland China at affordable prices.
</P>
<P>
   These tiny embellished bottles, corked with a domed cap that's
attached to a slender spoon, are no longer intended to hold
tobacco, but they continue to be prized for their beauty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 1428EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981009.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8528 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      10-09 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN BRUINS LIVE UP TO HIGHER EXPECTATIONS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A year ago at this time, the Bruins had just finished
auditioning a group of young and largely unknown commodities,
hoping they would develop into a competitive, cohesive unit.
</P>
<P>
   When the club departed for its annual journey west in October,
coach Pat Burns, in his first year behind the Boston bench, was
holding his breath, crossing his fingers, and wondering what he had
on his roster.
</P>
<P>
   After a 1-1 start at home, the Bruins impressed with a 6-2 trip,
playing those eight games in 15 nights. There were little in the
way of lofty expectations for Boston, which had missed the playoffs
for the first time in 30 seasons the previous spring. If there was
such a thing as rock bottom, the Bruins had found it.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, with a promising prospect named Jason Allison, an
exciting first-round pick named Sergei Samsonov, a previously
underused goalie named Byron Dafoe, and a living legend named Ray
Bourque, the Bruins rebuilt their fortunes. They finished with 91
points, 30 more than the year before, and were on their way. The
Bruins lost to Washington in the first round of the playoffs, but
the far more experienced Capitals went to the finals. It was a
first-round loss, but it was a jumping-off point.
</P>
<P>
   When the Bruins came to training camp to prepare for the 1998-99
season, it was in some ways a repeat of the previous fall. Allison,
Kyle McLaren (whose worth isn't as quantifiable but is substantial
nonetheless), Ted Donato, Steve Heinze, and Anson Carter were
missing. Heinze re-signed in short order. Allison and Donato
returned much later but were big shots in the arm to a team
composed of players many of whose first names were ``Who?''
</P>
<P>
   So, the season starts Saturday and what do we know? Are the
Bruins better? Have the contract squabbles hurt the camaraderie?
Have other teams improved more than Boston?
</P>
<P>
   The truth is the Bruins were able to sneak up on teams last
season, especially in the first half when more powerful clubs
viewed them as little more than a fly at the company picnic. Except
these guys wouldn't, didn't buzz off.
</P>
<P>
   This year, teams will see the Bruins coming. But the $64,000
question is: What will they be able to do about it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody on the team feels like they are an
established contending player in the league,'' said
president/-general manager Harry Sinden. ``For instance, I feel
Jason's line feels it can operate with the top lines in the league.
I think Tim Taylor's line feels it is as good a checking line as
there is in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most impressive results of last season was that the
players bought into Burns's system, with help from assistant
coaches Jacques Laperriere and Bobby Francis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took the whole season to really get it perfectly in tune,''
said Heinze. ``But everybody talked about the first long road trip
and how we jelled. I don't know if that's because the system was
totally understood or guys started to get along and we had a better
team atmosphere. The system took a good third of the season to get
down pat where (Burns) wasn't yelling at a different guy each
night, saying, `Don't lose it at the blue line,' `Cover the middle
on the forecheck,' things like that. It just ended up being, `Work
harder,' by the end of the year. The system was understood.''
</P>
<P>
   There was insecurity last season, partly because of the poor
finish the year before, partly because there were so many new
faces, partly because no one knew what to expect. That insecurity
was wiped away by modest success, and now there are, lo and behold,
real expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year they were kind of in a developmental stage,
mentally, as to were they any good or were they terrible or did
they belong,'' said Sinden. ``I think now they feel they can
compete, once we get them back together, with the best teams.
That's why I think they're going to be better. I don't think
they're going to stand for poor performances as a team. Pat
wouldn't let them do it last year, but I think they're going to
help Pat this year that way. I don't think this team, if we get it
together like I hope we will, is going to say, `Well, it's the
Detroit Red Wings. We played a good game against them.' I think
they're going to say, `Damn it, we should beat this team.' They
should have that, which they certainly couldn't have had last year
because they were just put together.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns, because of his personality and the circumstances, is
conservative in his thinking about this season. ``There are a lot
of things we still have to work on,'' he said. ``This has been a
different training camp than I've ever been involved in. I still
don't know who is going to start the year. It's been an up-and-down
camp. We're trying to fit players in places where we don't really
know if they're going to be there on a permanent basis. We tried
some guys, then we take them out, then we tried some other guys.
It's almost like a new type of training camp again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until I know who's going to be here, and who we're going to
play with on a regular basis, it's really tough to gauge how we're
going to start off. When you start the season, we're still going to
have to go through stuff on a weekly and daily basis. That's how we
did it last year, too. With the drop of the puck, it's not like I
don't have to say anything anymore. It's all starting over again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 1428EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981009.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8533 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-PROFILE-OPRAH-$A     10-09 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PROFILE-OPRAH-$ADV11-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAR OF `BELOVED' IS BELOVED HERSELF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Refiling due to garbled text)  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 11)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ You know Oprah Winfrey. We all know her: She's
everyone's best buddy, the lady down the street with the warm-bread
voice and the infectious belly laugh. What's more, she knows we
know her _ she seems to understand that wherever she goes, she'll
be treated as a longtime friend. She is our crowned queen of
amiability.
</P>
<P>
   So when Winfrey breezed into Boston on a press tour for her new
film ``Beloved,'' she greeted reporters with an easy, unaffected
familiarity. She made eye contact. She memorized names. Articulate,
