<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8534 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOURQUE-BO     10-09 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOURQUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOURQUE AN ENDURING PRESENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When Ray Bourque was pondering how long he wanted his
playing career to last, 20 years sounded like a nice, round number.
He has since negotiated a contract extension that will take him one
year beyond that, but for now he is one of three National Hockey
League players entering their 20th seasons, with Rangers center
Wayne Gretzky and Canucks center Mark Messier the others.
</P>
<P>
   To put into perspective how remarkable that is, consider that of
all the players in the league's history, only 20 prior to this
season had played as many as 20 years. Larry Robinson, now coach of
the Los Angeles Kings, had done it most recently, playing his final
season in 1991-92.
</P>
<P>
   ``There haven't been that many 20-year guys in the history of
the league, so to have three in one year, a lot of that is a credit
to the players of today who really train a lot harder,'' said
Bruins president/general manager Harry Sinden. ``They maintain
their physical fitness at a level necessary to play in this league
a lot longer than they used to. Training camp is shorter now. Guys
used to come in in horrendous shape and play their way into shape.
We would have to take 10-15 pounds off 80 percent of the players in
training camp and we had six weeks to do it, but that doesn't
happen today. If you show up like that, you might not even get on
the ice.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque has been committed to fitness throughout his career,
working out in the summers with friend and trainer Ben Leduc.
However, as much as conditioning plays a part in the longevity of
players such as Bourque, Messier, and Gretzky, it goes beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say our passion is probably the same as it's always
been,'' said Gretzky, who was in Boston last week for an exhibition
game against the Bruins. ``Your excitement level changes. Things
that energize you and get you ready and get you excited about games
obviously change over time. I think the biggest thing of all, for
the three of us, is we truly have a love for the sport and we truly
respect the sport. We've never taken this game or this league for
granted.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as Gretzky and Messier have been public ambassadors for
the sport, Bourque has gone about his career in a more subdued
fashion. Where Messier is the most outspoken of the three, Gretzky
has learned to deal with the spotlight in large part because of the
success he's had individually as well as on Stanley Cup-winning
teams. Bourque, while always cooperative and accessible to the
media and fans, has preferred to let his game do the talking for
him. All three are captains of their teams and have served in those
positions with dignity and class.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all three of us have the same philosophy,'' said
Gretzky. ``Your preparation and your habits and your training
become even that much greater because you want to succeed. I think
that's why the three of us have the success to be able to keep
playing _ and not just playing but contributing to our teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruins coach Pat Burns said Bourque has been invaluable both in
the dressing room and on the ice. He has tutored a boatload of
youngsters in his career, most recently second-round draft pick
Jonathan Girard, who is 18. Last year, Bourque helped Hal Gill
become a bona fide NHL player, and he is also part of the reason
Kyle McLaren came along so quickly in his rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   ``His presence is very, very important for younger players,''
said Burns. ``It can be intimidating for a young player playing
with him. You can see Girard sometimes, he feels like he has to
give the puck to him. Sometimes you don't have to. You can give it
to somebody else and Ray won't be mad at you. That's one of the
things, when you're playing with a 20-year veteran it can be
intimidating. I've seen a lot of guys play with Gretzky do the same
thing. Instead of giving the puck to the winger, they'll look for
him right away and sometimes that's not the proper play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Ray settles everybody down, tells everybody to relax.
He just likes to be treated like one of the boys. He's the type of
player everyone would like to have on your hockey club. I feel
blessed just to be able to have him for the amount of time I'll be
here or he'll be here. I think he might be here longer than I am.
He might decide to sign another contract.''
</P>
<P>
   When Bourque came into the league, fans and media were comparing
him with one of the greatest players of all time _ Bobby Orr. After
Orr's career was cut short by injuries, Bruins devotees were hoping
for another superstar. Bourque said he never worried about the
comparisons because he knew there was only one Orr.
</P>
<P>
   Sinden argues that as great as Orr was and Bourque is, the two
couldn't be more different. ``They're absolutely totally different
people,'' he said. ``I don't say that in a negative way; they were
just totally different. They were in different eras. In a lot of
their good points, both of them are similar. But Bobby was much
more high strung than Ray.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray holds a lot inside him. He contains his emotions and his
temper. He contains them very well. He doesn't have to let it out
to perform well. Some players have to get mad at the coach or
management or yell at somebody or go fight somebody or yell at the
referee. Ray doesn't have to do any of those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of what makes Bourque so special is that he has never made
a misstep since becoming a Bruin. When the Bruins were mired in
contract squabbles with several free agents at the start of
training camp, Bourque quietly went in to the team's offices with
his agent, Steve Freyer, and within 90 minutes had a new two-year
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just doesn't stop with Ray from the day he came here until
the other day when he signed,'' said Sinden. ``The example he sets
and the things he does always reconfirm and reassure that he is
what he really is. This hasn't been some kind of an act.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque contends he will keep playing as long as he's having
fun. ``I'm still looking at it like a little kid,'' he said. ``I
still feel like I've got something to prove. Every day you've got
to prove yourself, and that's how I've played this game my whole
career.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
