<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-KOSOVO _ MOSCOW _ In the United States' bid to convince
it's NATO allies of the need for military airstrikes against
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic over the fighting in Serbia's
Kosovo province, persuading Russia has been the toughest task.
Although U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and other U.S.
officials have said if a decision is taken to strike the Serbs the
Russians will not be able to stop it, most point to Russia's
outspoken resistance as a key reason the strikes have not happened
-- despite repeated warnings they could happen within days. A
longtime ally of the Serbs, Russia is butting heads with the U.S.
much in the same way it did with Iraq. Why? What does Russia stand
to gain? (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 4 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SHARON _ Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu says he will
appoint Ariel Sharon as his new foreign minister. The conservative
hardliner is known as a great military leaders but a poor diplomat
and politician. He has a good reputation among Arabs, but not with
Palestinians. Analysts believe this is Netanyahu's way of placating
the right wing as he heads to Washington next week to meet with
PalestinianNational Authority President Yasser Arafat and President
Clinton. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 3 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-TITOV _ MOSCOW _ As Ohio Sen. John Glenn prepares to go
back into space, we profile former Russian cosmonaut German Titov.
Titov was Russia's second man in space. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-TESTS _ WASHINGTON _ As thousands of students across the
country suffer sweaty brows and churning stomachs during the SAT
exam today, a debate is raging over whether the test should
continue to play an important role in college
</P>
<P>
   admissions. While one advocacy group says the test is unfair to
minorities and should be de-emphasized, the College Board argues
that the SAT greatly helps colleges gauge a student's ability to
handle college work. (Monroe, Cox News Service 700).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving Friday.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ENVIRONMENT-TALKS _ Hundreds of environmental journalists from
around the country are meeting in Chattanooga this weekend to talk
about how the media covers issues like sprawl, transportation and
the environment. Ted Turner, who is funding a foundation to examine
issues of sprawl in metro Atlanta, will give a speech to kick off
the conference. And one of the first topics (on friday) will be the
plans for a high-speed train from Atlanta to Chattanooga. (Soto,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15-18.
</P>
<P>
   EAGLES _ Legendary military aviators ranging from astronauts to
the Tuskegee Airmen gather today and Saturday at the US Air Force
Museum for a Gathering of Eagles
</P>
<P>
   We talk to Joe Engle, shuttle astronaut on Columbia and
Discovery and Tom Stafford, NASA astronaut on Gemini and Apollo.
(Gaffney, Daytona Daily News). WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   HOLBROOKE _ The University of Dayton is giving U.S. Ambassador
Richard Holbrooke, architect of the Dayton Peace Accord, an
honorary degree. Holbrooke, along with other experts on the
Balkans, will be in Dayton on Nov. 21-22, the third anniversary of
the talks that ended the civil war in Bosnia. (Dempsey, Dayton
Daily News). 7-8.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS _ Georgia's task force on AIDS probably will decide Friday
whether to keep track of HIV infections by using names or whether
to track cases by coded numbers. Activists want numbers, because
they fear breaches of confidentiality; health officials want to use
names, to ensure accuracy of reporting. (Kim, Atlanta
Jurnal-Constitution) 15-20.
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-DEMOCRATS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ In 1992, Ohio voters helped
elevate Bill Clinton to the presidency by going to the polls in the
greatest numbers of the past two decades. Six years later, Clinton
is mired in scandal, the public seems more disinterested than ever
in politics and some experts fear turnout in the Nov. 3 election
will mark an all-time low. (Dempsey, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GANG-PLEA _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Vowing to place Texas at the
forefront of curbing prison gangs, state prison officials are
developing new programs to entice convicts to renounce their gang
membership and to reduce gang violence. (Ward, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WASTE-SITE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ A delegation of Mexican officials
urged the Bush administration and state lawmakers recently to block
a proposed disposal site for low-level radioactive waste.
(Haurwitz, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
