<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS DEFENDS WILLIAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT THE ALCS _ I was in my New York hotel room when the phone
rang at 9 a.m. yesterday. Ted Williams was responding to a week-old
message I'd left when our crack sports staff was assembling a
massive Red Sox-Yankees, American League Championship
Series-Armageddon preview. Our special section would have been
longer and jucier than the Starr Report but ... the Red Sox didn't
hold up their end.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, there was no need to revisit the golden days of
Sox-Yankees when Ted called, but the greatest hitter who ever lived
was on the phone ready to talk. So I listened.
</P>
<P>
   Ted was wound up. Calling from Hernando, Fla., he hardly needed
a telephone to be heard in Times Square. Like all baseball fans,
this is his time of year _ playoff games every day, sometimes two
in one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is still the game,'' he said. ``I love to watch it
and I have three of my best friends here right now and all we're
doing is talking about the Braves and what happened last night and
the Yankees _ whether the guy was out of the base line going to
first. And they're all becoming experts, just like the Boston
writers. They don't know much, but they're experts.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Ted can say the word ``writers'' and make it sound like a
profanity. The Kid wasn't happy about the treatment Sox manager
Jimy Williams got from Boston sportswriters during the ill-fated
Cleveland series.
</P>
<P>
   ``The manager did a stupendous job, and the thing I can't
understand is, how can the Boston writers second-guess what a great
manager like Jimy Williams does with his starting pitchers and his
closer? That is bush league. I'd have to take the manager's
expertise far and away over any of those writers. How they can even
look him in the eye if they wrote some of that crap when they know
nothing about it ... it just amazes me. I can't hardly get over it.
Boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted wasn't buying into the disappointment that engulfed Red Sox
Nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched 'em on TV and I pulled like hell for 'em,'' he said.
``I think they did a hell of a job. Nobody picked the Red Sox to
win, and still, they were right there at the end. I think they
probably did as well as any club in the league with what they had.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that last game, I thought everything worked out exactly the
way they wanted it to work out. The kid starter pitched a hell of a
game and then they had as good a reliever as there is in the game
... and he gets beat. But how you can second-guess Jimy Williams?''
</P>
<P>
   The Kid still calls Nomar Garciaparra ``one of the greatest
hitters to come along in the last 20 years.'' He didn't know much
about Mo Vaughn's contract status but said, ``I'll just bet you he
stays with the Red Sox. That's just a wild guess from a tired old
ballplayer. I don't know how much money they've got to give him,
but he's a hell of a player and a good first baseman. He has
improved as a hitter and learned how to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Bob Feller and other old-timers, Williams does not live
in the past. He's never claimed the game was better in his day.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my lifetime of looking at baseball _ 70 years now _ I've
never seen more talent, more strength, more speed than I do in the
present array of players. But you guys don't realize that. You'll
be talking about it in 25 years.''
</P>
<P>
   He loved watching Mark McGwire's march toward 70 homers (``He's
about as devastating as anybody I ever saw''). And, contrary to
popular opinion, Ted says it's possible to hit a home run when you
are trying to hit one out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure. You try once in a while. The only time I tried to pull
the ball and hit a long one was when I had a count where I'm ahead
and a pitch where the ball looks like a watermelon. You take that
extra swing. But any time you got for a home run, you're hurting
yourself a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   If he had tried to hit only homers, he said he'd have hit 50-80
points lower and added about 20 percent more homers. Williams said
he was going for the fence on about 21 of 521 career homers.
</P>
<P>
   And what about the Sox' ill-timed batting slump against
Cleveland?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said this for 50 years. It's harder to hit in the fall.
Like it is now. The weather's colder. The sun's lower on the
equator. The shadows are longer. The ball doesn't carry quite as
well and some of these pitchers are kind of revived by the cooler
weather. And the colder it is, the slower you can get the bat
around.''
</P>
<P>
   That was it. He was done talking, done ripping the Boston
writers. But he was back in front of his TV last night to watch the
Braves and Padres. Too bad he can't be in Boston tonight to throw
out the first ball of Game 3 of that Red Sox-Yankees series.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The Internet address for Ted Williams Family Enterprises is
www.hitter.com; for Hitter Communications, it's www.hitter.net.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
