<HEADER>
A8537 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      10-09 1417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THERE A STORM AHEAD FOR THE BRUINS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Word from the West Coast has it that UCLA will make a decision
in the next few days on whether to reschedule its canceled game
against the University of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   What decision? Play the game. It's that simple. But of course,
it really isn't that simple.
</P>
<P>
   The game was scheduled to be played Sept. 26 in Miami, but then
Hurricane Georges came calling and the game was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Miami officials say they would love to play the game on the
first available date, which would be the weekend of Dec. 5.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA? Well, there's a problem. It seems the Bruins' regular
season ends two weeks earlier against Southern California. It seems
that the team banquet is scheduled for the week of Dec. 5. It seems
that it would hurt the Bruins in recruiting and that it would cut
down on the players' Thanksgiving vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Fine. Let the Bruins duck out and finish with a 10-0 record
instead of 11-0 or, heaven forbid, lose a game and finish 9-1. Then
let the computer spit out the numbers that will deterimine who will
play in the Fiesta Bowl Jan. 4 for the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Let it compare UCLA's 10-0 or 9-1 with the potential 11-1 record
of a Florida State, which plays as tough a schedule as anyone in
the country and will play all of the games on its schedule.
</P>
<P>
   And then let's drop UCLA like a boulder in the polls. Don't want
to play a potentially tough Miami team at the Orange Bowl? Fine.
Then there's no reason for the Bruins to play for the national
title in the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Let them stay home and play in the Rose Bowl against someone
like Virginia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA athletic director Peter Dalis said he will make his
decision perhaps as soon as Friday, no later than Monday.
``Ultimately, it's my decision,'' he said. ``I'm certain I'll
disappoint people one way or another.''
</P>
<P>
   Disappoint? If Dalis chooses to duck the Hurricanes _ and that's
how this would be perceived _ he'll do more than disappoint.
</P>
<P>
   On a weekend when teams from the Southeastern, Big 12, and
Western Athletic conferences are putting their records on the line
in an attempt to win league championships, the prospect of an
unbeaten UCLA team staying home and digesting turkey leftovers is
simply outrageous.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the point may be moot. The Bruins travel to Tucson
Saturday night for a game against unbeaten Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   A UCLA loss will make the matter of whether the Bruins want to
play in December meaningless. But if they win and run the table,
then the final game of the regular season should be against Miami,
not USC.
</P>
<P>
   If UCLA is worried about television, forget about it. CBS, which
owns the rights to the game, could schedule it in prime time as
part of a sports tripleheader that would include the Army-Navy game
and a college basketball regional package involving Connecticut,
Kentucky, and Michigan State, all of whom will be in the Top 10 in
the preseason polls.
</P>
<P>
   Even better, CBS could switch it to prime time Friday night or
let ESPN pick up the game and show it Thursday night in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   When you look at all the factors, there is no good reason not to
play the game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Poll position
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State has been No. 1 in the Associated Press poll since the
preseason. Since the AP began a preseason poll in 1950, no team has
gone wire to wire at No. 1 ... South Carolina coach  &UR; Brad Scott  &LR; is
going through a rough year. Not only are Scott's Gamecocks off to a
miserable 1-4 start, but his wife,  &UR; Daryle &LR; , &UR;  &LR; broke her left ankle
and sprained her right ankle while leaving the stands following
last week's 30-28 loss to Mississippi. Said Scott, ``She's probably
out for the season.'' Unless South Carolina turns it around, in all
likelihood, so is Scott ... UCLA has not beaten Arizona in Tucson
since 1988 ... The first poll of the Bowl Championship Series
(which will decide who will play in the Fiesta Bowl) will be
released Oct. 27 or Nov. 3 ... It's been quite a recent few weeks
at Prairie View. Two weeks ago, the Panthers broke their record
80-game losing streak with a win over Langston. Then the program
was suspended by the Southwestern Athletic Conference after the
Prairie View adminstratrion ignored a two-week suspension issued to
the band, which was involved in a brawl with the Southern band
Sept. 19. Earlier this week, however, the SWAC backtracked and
lifted the suspension, saying it will take the matter under
consideration ... Nebraska, which barely survived an upset bid by
Oklahoma State last week, must travel to Texas A&AMP;M Saturday with a
huge question mark at quarterback. Both starter  &UR; Bobby Newcombe
 &LR; and backup  &UR; Eric Crouch  &LR; are hurt. ``You'd like to have your No. 1
guy ready to go,'' said coach  &UR; Frank Solich &LR; . ``You'd like to have
your No. 2 guy ready to go. We'll just see how that develops.''
Worst-case scenario? Former walk-on  &UR; Monte Christo &LR;  ... If Notre
Dame can get past Arizona State Saturday, the Irish could roll into
a bowl game. After the Sun Devils, who are off to a 1-3 start, the
Irish face Army, Baylor, Boston College, and Navy in the next four
weeks. The Irish should be favored in all of those games, and wins
would put them at 8-1, with a home game against Louisiana State and
a game at USC topping off the season. A loss against Arizona State
would put the Irish back where they were last month after getting
blown out by Michigan State ... Added to the Irish uncertainty is
the sore shoulder of starting quarterback  &UR; Jarious Jackson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; which
could leave freshman  &UR; Arnaz Battle  &LR; as the starter ... The
quarterback experiment is over at Florida _ for the time being.
 &UR; Jessie Palmer  &LR; has the job after alternating all season with  &UR; Doug
Johnson &LR;  ... UCLA must face Arizona without its rushing and scoring
leader. Tailback  &UR; Jermaine Lewis  &LR; was suspended for a week by coach
 &UR; Bob Toledo  &LR; because of his involvement in a fight at a party over
the weekend ... Syracuse is 2-2 and barely in the Top 25 after its
loss last weekend to North Carolina State. So how do the Orangemen
feel about their plight? ``We've watched film and are pretty
disgusted about how horrible we played,'' said safety  &UR; Jason
Poles &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tough question
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Want to know who has the toughest schedule? According to the
NCAA, it's Auburn. Based on last season's records of opponents on
this year's schedules, the Tigers are said to have the toughest
road in Division 1-A, followed by Florida, Alabama, Washington, and
Southern California. Interestingly, the only team in the Top 10 in
both this week's polls and the toughest-schedule ranking is
Georgia, which is No. 7 in the polls and has the sixth-toughest
schedule ... This week's sleeper team to watch is Wisconsin, which,
as predicted because of a cupcake schedule, is unbeaten and rising
steadily in the polls ... Some people don't learn _ or don't want
to learn. During last week's Ohio State-Penn State game, Buckeyes
quarterback coach  &UR; Joe Salem  &LR; inadvertently punched out the window
in the coaching booth, showering reporters below with glass. One
reporter,  &UR; Kim Jones &LR; , &UR;  &LR; was slightly cut. Jones, who covers Penn
State, is still waiting for an apology from Salem or another Ohio
State official. The response has been not only silence but
arrogance. Salem told  &UR; Bruce Hooley &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who covers the Buckeyes for
the Cleveland Plain Dealer, ``I'm going to start off by saying that
for every person who asks me about this glass-punching incident,
I'm going to make sure the next three home games you're sitting in
front of our damn booth. So if you've got a question, just be
prepared to sit in front of us for the next three games.'' Asked if
he would do it again, Salem said, ``That will just keep you alert,
that's all I know.'' Maybe Salem would think differently if Ohio
State officials put the families of the coaching staff in the row
beneath him. Then again, maybe not ... College football doesn't
have many legends in New England, but one of them, former Brandeis
athletic director and coach  &UR; Benny Friedman &LR; , &UR;  &LR; will be honored Oct.
16 at the Hall of Fame dinner held in conjunction with the
university's 50th anniversary. Brandeis's first athletic director
and football coach, Friedman, who died in 1982 at age 77, first
gained fame as a football player at the University of Michigan in
the 1920s ... Bryant, which is in its first season of football,
will try to go 3-0 vs. Pace Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
