<HEADLINE>
STAR OF `BELOVED' IS BELOVED HERSELF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Refiled due to garbled text)  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 11)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ You know Oprah Winfrey. We all know her: She's
everyone's best buddy, the lady down the street with the warm-bread
voice and the infectious belly laugh. What's more, she knows we
know her _ she seems to understand that wherever she goes, she'll
be treated as a longtime friend. She is our crowned queen of
amiability.
</P>
<P>
   So when Winfrey breezed into Boston on a press tour for her new
film ``Beloved,'' she greeted reporters with an easy, unaffected
familiarity. She made eye contact. She memorized names. Articulate,
quick-witted, self-deprecating and smart, she answered questions
with candor and heat, discussing the film and the Toni Morrison
book on which it's based in impassioned bursts of talk. Here,
clearly, was a woman with zeal for her subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``The book spoke to me. The book deepened me in a way that I do
not have words to express,'' said Winfrey, wearing a simple brown
sweater with slacks. For ``Beloved,'' she earned two credits, one
as star (her first role in a feature film since ``The Color
Purple''), the other as a producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It opened me up to the experience, the humanity, of people who
every day reconstructed their lives and had the faith to love in
spite of their pasts. ... I wanted to create a movie where people
would feel the same thing. So when people come away feeling numbed,
they feel dumbfounded, staggered, they feel devastated,
overwhelmed, all of that _ I felt all of that when I read that
book.''
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Jonathan Demme, ``Beloved'' examines the tortured
past and conflicted present of Sethe (Winfrey), an ex-slave haunted
by the ghost of her dead baby. When an old friend (Danny Glover)
becomes Sethe's lover, the apparition leaves. But the ghost
rematerializes in the form of an enigmatic young woman named
Beloved (Thandie Newton), and Sethe is forced to confront the past:
her life in slavery, her bloody escape and her role in the baby's
death. The story of Sethe and Beloved ``connects to all
experiences, all human experiences. The denial of your past, the
denial of your true existence, is the real death. To deny who you
really are is the real living death, and that's part of what Sethe
understood,'' Winfrey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The past does have a life of its own ... and it will walk into
your house and sit at your table and call (itself) something else,
unless you're willing to look at it in truth. It just bleeds into
the future all the time. You can't deny it,'' she said. ``You can't
deny it. So free yourself. So free yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Winfrey has championed a movie version of Morrison's book for
years, jumping through endless hoops in the search for the right
director. Demme, best known for ``The Silence of the Lambs'' and
``Philadelphia,'' was not her first or most obvious choice. She
considered foreign directors (``I thought: foreign ... sensitivity
...''), African-American directors, female directors. She even
asked Jodie Foster, who had written a thesis on the novel at Yale
and replied with ``a lovely `no' letter saying she didn't think it
could be on the screen _ that she thought this was a piece that
worked best as a piece of literature.''
</P>
<P>
   With razor timing, Winfrey stopped for a moment and smiled.
``She has changed her mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those she interviewed was director Peter Weir, who
questioned Winfrey's ability to play the main character. Winfrey
was adamant: She told him she just needed to lose weight, that
Sethe ``is here, inside me somewhere.'' Weir suggested she give him
the rights to the book, ``and then we can decide.''
</P>
<P>
   A reporter in the group wryly noted the ``parade'' of directors
that had failed to make the cut. ``I never heard it described as a
parade,'' Winfrey replied, then started humming a spry little
circus tune. ``Peter Weeeirrrrr ... Jane Campionn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 1434EDT &QL; 
