<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV11-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECK TAX EFFECTS BEFORE SELLING VANGUARD POSITION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, October 11, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I retired this past year. I am 69 and my wife is near 65.
Soon we will be receiving Social Security benefits totaling $12,500
a year. We have had the following portfolio for about 10 years. It
totals about $650,000. IRA accounts consist of $67,600 in Fidelity
Puritan, $40,000 in Fidelity Low-Priced Stock, and $22,000 in
Fidelity High Income. Our taxable accounts consist of $203,000 in
Fidelity Cash Reserves, $42,000 in Fidelity High Income, $79,000 in
Vanguard GNMA, $76,000 in Vanguard Short-Term Corporate Bond, and
$76,000 in Vanguard LifeStrategy Conservative Growth. Finally, we
have $44,000 in Janus fund. I plan to buy property in Florida for
$130,000 and to realign the portfolio as follows: $123,000 in
Vanguard GNMA, $124,000 in Vanguard Short-Term Corporate Bond,
$120,000 in Fidelity High Income, $67,600 in Fidelity Puritan,
$40,000 in Fidelity Low-Priced Stock, and $44,000 in Janus. With
Social Security, I would like to pick up an income stream close to
$40,000 a year, while being pretty conservative and staying in the
15 percent tax bracket.
</P>
<P>
   P.D., Norwood, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think you've thought this out pretty carefully, and the
portfolio you suggested should, combined with Social Security,
deliver an income stream a couple of thousand dollars in excess of
your $40,000 target. If I read correctly between the lines, you
plan to leave the IRA accounts as they are, selling the entire
positions in Fidelity Cash Reserves and Vanguard LifeStrategy
Conservative Growth. After taking the $130,000 for your real estate
purchase, the remaining proceeds would be used to build the
positions in Vanguard GNMA, Vanguard Short-Term Corporate Bond, and
Fidelity High Income funds. This is fine as far as it goes; there
are no tax implications of selling the Cash Reserves position.
</P>
<P>
   But I wonder about what might happen upon the sale of the
Vanguard fund. You report the portfolio is about 10 years old, but
that certainly can't be the case with Vanguard LifeStrategy
Conservative Growth, which was launched only in the fourth quarter
of 1994. My suggestion is that you analyze the tax effects of
selling that $76,000 position before you make a move.
</P>
<P>
   Most notably, there would be no immediate tax implications if
you were to sell the shares in Fidelity Puritan and use the
proceeds to build your positions in the fixed-income funds.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, in a perfect world I would rather hold Fidelity Puritan
than Vanguard LifeStrategy Conservative Growth. But the first thing
I think of when contemplating the imperfection of the world is the
existence of the IRS. And what's the difference between the two
funds? Both balance investments between stocks and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Puritan's portfolio is usually about 60 percent stocks
and 40 percent fixed income; the portfolio of Vanguard LifeStrategy
Conservative Growth typically is the opposite _ 60 percent
fixed-income and the rest equities. Over three years the results,
as reported in the latest Morningstar Mutual Funds report, are very
similar _ 12.32 percent average annual returns for the Vanguard
offering versus 12.24 percent for Puritan. Over the long haul, the
heavier stock position in Puritan should make it the better fund,
but for the moment, I think I'd sell the Puritan, simply to avoid
the tax consequences. One tactic you might adopt if you agree with
me about the merits of Puritan would be to sell small parts of the
Vanguard LifeStrategy Conservative Growth position each year,
keeping the amount of the sale small enough so that it wouldn't
cause you great grief on April 15. You could then use the proceeds
of the sales to rebuild a taxable account in Puritan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 50 and would like to retire at age 63. At that time I
will have Social Security and a company pension based on 22 years'
service. My 401(k) account is currently worth $124,000, and is
divided among these Vanguard funds: Windsor II, 30 percent,
Institutional Index, 25 percent, Primecap, 20 percent, Asset
Allocation, 15 percent, and International Growth 10 percent. I am
maximizing my contributions to the plan, and my employer adds 4
percent, so the annual contributions come to $12,000. What will my
401(k) grow to in 13 years? Am I too diversified? The other options
in the 401(k) are Vanguard's LifeStrategy Conservative Growth,
LifeStrategy Moderate Growth, and LifeStrategy Growth funds. In
addition to the 401(k) I have a $21,000 deductible IRA invested in
Fidelity Growth and Income, and another deductible IRA invested in
zero-coupon government bonds, which will mature in the year 2016,
at which point they will be worth $102,000. What do you suggest for
an investment for a Roth IRA, into which my wife and I will each
contribute $2,000 a year for the next 10 to 12 years?
</P>
<P>
   J.D., Murrieta, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Let's start with the good news _ if you achieve 10 percent
average annual portfolio growth over the next 13 years, and
continue contributions at current levels, your 401(k) should grow
to $735,839. I'm not particularly enamored of the options on the
401(k) menu; with the exception of the international fund, these
eight options limit your stock market exposure substantially to the
large-cap universe, giving you no choices in the mid- cap or
small-cap arenas, and no other attractive options such as Vanguard
Specialized Health Care. Given the limited menu, I think you've
done as good a job of allocating the portfolio as you can, but
you're certainly not overdiversified. My suggestion would be to
lobby your company's officers for a broader menu of options,
including Vanguard Health Care, its Small-Cap Stock Index fund, and
(for selection as you get closer to retirement) its GNMA,
High-Yield Corporate Bond, and other fixed-income funds.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, since it's likely to take some time to get a
change there even if you are successful, I would make my selection
of investments for Roth IRAs serve to fill some of those gaps.
Since you won't be limited to Vanguard for those investments, I
suggest a good value-oriented small-cap stock fund such as Fidelity
Low-Priced Stock, and a health care fund focusing on
pharmaceuticals and medical equipment stocks, such as Vanguard's
Health Care fund or Fidelity Select Health Care.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
