<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8546 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      10-09 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRISBY HAS MOVED UP BY STAYING PUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ If you haven't noticed, there's a Vincent
Brisby revival going on.
</P>
<P>
   The six-year veteran, who came into the NFL with Drew Bledsoe,
has been to the valley and now is beginning to climb back to the
peak he reached in 1995 when he caught 66 passes for 974 yards, a
14.8-yard average. The strong season as one of Bledsoe's favorite
targets earned him a long-term deal with the Patriots through 2000
that averaged more than $1 million per season.
</P>
<P>
   But Brisby became a virtual nonperson in Bill Parcells's
thinking when he missed most of the '96 season with a hamstring
pull. He made it back last season and had one of the best training
camps of any receiver. In fact, his first four games of 1997 were
very impressive _ 11 catches, including a 31- and a 24-yarder. But
after that, he disappeared. When Terry Glenn was injured, Troy
Brown emerged as the top receiver, while Shawn Jefferson had one of
his best years.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding his plight, Brisby was openly scolded by Bledsoe for
not getting open while the quarterback was running for his life
against Jacksonville. Quarterback and receiver exchanged heated
words on the sideline, and confrontation seemed to get Brisby
going. Bledsoe went right back to him as Brisby caught four passes
for 58 yards in that game.
</P>
<P>
   But after that, he disappeared again, not resurfacing until the
7-6 playoff loss at Pittsburgh, where he caught three passes for 37
yards.
</P>
<P>
   During the offseason, Brisby and his agent, Michael George, had
extensive conversations with the Patriots about a trade. The
Patriots permitted George to discuss Brisby with other teams. There
was interest, but no team was willing to give up a second- or
third-round draft pick, which the Patriots wanted. So Brisby stayed
with New England, committed himself to the offseason training
program, and became an intriguing part of Ernie Zampese's new
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Zampese and the Patriots had been searching in the offseason for
a big, physical receiver, as the offensive coordinator had with
Dallas in Michael Irvin. The Patriots drafted Tony Simmons, who is
6 feet 2 inches, but they knew he was a longer-range solution.
</P>
<P>
   So they decided to look no further than their own backyard _ to
the 6-3 Brisby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just needed an opportunity to be involved,'' he said
Thursday. ``As a player, you want to see that you're in the game
plan. So right now I probably have more motivation because I see
that I'm in the game plan every week and that they have a role for
me and a need for me.''
</P>
<P>
   In training camp, Brisby wanted more than a role, he wanted to
start. Coach Pete Carroll told him he would get the chance to
compete and he was in the starting lineup for a couple of
exhibition games, but once the season began, Jefferson was back in
his starter's role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both situations were tough,'' said Brisby. ``I think family,
players, and friends were all helping me believe in myself when
other people weren't. People were telling me that regardless of
what was going on, `you're a better player than how they're
treating you. Just keep going and keep praying you'll overcome it.'
That's what I did. I just kept working hard, and then when I had
the opportunity to voice my opinion, I did. I just let everything
else take care of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said not playing after he was healthy was tougher than
having his masculinity questioned by Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like when you're able to perform and you're not being
put in a situation to do it, that hurts even more than when you're
injured,'' said Brisby. ``Even though you want to be out there when
you're hurt, you can't be. It's physically impossible, and there's
nothing you can do about it. To be able to perform and not being
put in the position to make plays, that's tough, so I think last
year was tougher than the year before.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Parcells, ``Bill had his ways,'' said Brisby. ``Some of
them were based on negative criticism. As a player, I had the
experience with Bill, so I knew his style. I didn't make a big fuss
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll made it clear that Brisby would be part of a four-man
rotation in which the receiver with the hot hand would play. Last
week against New Orleans, Brisby made two key catches _ a 6-yard
touchdown on a diving grab of a low ball in the end zone in the
second quarter and a 27-yarder on which he faked inside, went
outside, and got knocked out of bounds as he held the ball high,
away from the defender.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way the system works,'' Brisby said of the
rotation. ``When the opportunity presents itself, I have to make
the most of it. You can't be selfish about it, because we figure
all of the other guys deserve to play, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Brisby said his rapport with Bledsoe has never been better. They
seem to know one another as well as Bledsoe and Ben Coates do.
There are times now when Brisby will tell Bledsoe if there's a
certain route that works best in a given situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say, `Drew, the curl route is going to work,''' said
Brisby. ``When I speak, I just tell Drew something that I think
would be good to run because of what I see out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm in there, Drew has indicated that he'll go to me if I
get the job done. If somebody is making plays, Drew is going to get
you the ball. I'm just trying to be consistent and not only catch
the ball but block for the other guys also.''
</P>
<P>
   Brisby is expected to play a bigger role Sunday against the
Chiefs because Kansas City's two cornerbacks _ Dale Carter and
James Hasty _ are very physical and he has the strength to
outmuscle them. Such was the case in October 1995, the last time
the Patriots faced the Chiefs, when Brisby had a day that KC coach
Marty Schotteheimer mentioned during his press conference
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember it was a real physical game and Dale and Hasty were
playing a lot of bump,'' said Brisby. ``The first play of the game,
I was trying to be physical with them just to let them know that
they weren't going to be able to take advantage of me physically.
We just battled all game. I made some plays. I felt like I won the
battle that day.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Schottenheimer's laudatory words, Brisby said, ``When I
play, I do my best. When I'm involved in a system, I do the best I
can. That's probably why he has high praise.''
</P>
<P>
   Brisby is putting personal considerations aside for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to make the most of it,'' he said. ``I'm
putting the team first. Any time I get the opportunity to do
something, I'm there for the team. I'm not really worried about it.
At the end of the season, then I'll look back and see what I did
personally and how did I take advantage of the opportunities I
had.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
