<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8548 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMA-CASE-BOS &LR;      10-09 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMA-CASE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUIETLY, VIRGINIA BATTLE ENDS OVER COMATOSE MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WASHINGTON _ The Bible-waving protesters outside the nursing
home have all gone away, the governor of Virginia has made and lost
his case in state Supreme Court, and the media have retreated.
</P>
<P>
   Only Hugh Finn's family now is holding vigil in Manassas, Va.,
since his feeding tube was removed last week, waiting for the
moment that will bring an end to anguished attempts to wake him
from three years of life without consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Since the middle of the summer, the family has battled over the
fate of Finn, a 44-year-old former newscaster and father of two who
emerged from a car accident three years ago in a persistent
vegetative state. Their private agony has become a pitched battle
that has pitted in-laws, sisters, brothers, and parents against one
another, galvanized the public, and resulted last week in a
last-ditch court manuever by the governor of Virginia to delay the
tube-removal.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a federal judge rejected an emergency request by a
state legislator to have the tube reinserted.
</P>
<P>
   The case revisits the life-and-death question of who has the
right to decide whether to remove a feeding tube that is the
lifeline for people in a vegetative state. That question was
supposed to have been settled by a US Supreme Court ruling in the
Nancy Cruzan case in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   It also underscores the moral and emotional conflicts that roil
families whose loved ones are saved _ and perhaps also cursed _ by
medical technology that keeps them sitting upright, eyes open,
mute, physically alive but mentally and emotionally frozen. And it
is but a harbinger of the struggles to come, medical ethicists say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is nothing compared to how difficult it is going to be in
10 years to make these kinds of decisions,'' said Dr. Ron Cranford,
a Minnesota neurologist and expert witness in the Cruzan case.
``Hugh Finn is completely unconscious. What will happen when we
start to see people who are just outside the vegetative state,
severely brain-damaged with a little bit of consciousness?''
</P>
<P>
   The conflict erupted publicly this summer after Finn's wife,
Michele, 39, received confirmation of his diagnosis from a sixth
doctor: that he was paralyzed in a persistent vegetative state. Dr.
Robin Merlino, Hugh's attending physician at Annaburg Manor in
Manassas, said Finn was unable to respond to pain, feel thirst or
hunger, or ``communicate in any meaningful manner'' since his
accident.
</P>
<P>
   Finn had told his wife and his laywer, who had drawn up a living
will, that he prefered to die rather than persist in a vegetative
state. Without the hope of recovery, and in accordance with his
wishes, Michele decided it was time to remove his artificial
feeding.
</P>
<P>
   But members of the family, including Finn's parents and
siblings, as well as Michele's own sister, protested.
</P>
<P>
   They refused to accept the diagnosis, saying he was not dead to
the sensory world but had in fact communicated with them and others
by blinking in agreement, following individuals visiting him with
his eyes, speaking words and shedding tears. They also disputed his
wishes to die.
</P>
<P>
   The courts sided with Michele, determining that he would not
recover consciousness, that Michele had taken every measure
possible to rehabilitate her husband, and that she should remain
his legal guardian with the power to make health-care decisions for
him.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Michele's sister Elaine Glazier wrote to state
Delegate Robert G. Marshall, a conservative Republican in the
district of Finn's parents.
</P>
<P>
   Her brother-in-law, she wrote, ``has been speaking
intermittently since and before leaving Moss Rehab in Philadelphia,
began to develop a gesturing system for yes and no. ... Hugh's
feeding tube will be pulled on August 19, 1998, and he will be
allowed to starve to death by order of his guardian, and in keeping
with the Virginia Health Decisions Act.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia is one of a few states with a law specifically stating
it is legal to remove feeding in such cases. Massachusetts has no
such law.
</P>
<P>
   After Michele had won her case, the family agreed not to appeal.
After weeks of turmoil and anguish, the family reluctantly decided
to remove the feeding tube.
</P>
<P>
   But Virginia Governor Jim Gilmore, having been alerted by
Marshall, stepped in. Only days before Finn's feeding tube was to
be removed, the state announced it would appeal the case in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job as governor and my role is to protect those people who
are most frail in society and cannot necessarily protect
themselves,'' Gilmore said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors, politicians, and lawyers around the country accused
Gilmore of exploiting a family tragedy to score points with social
conservatives, while antiabortion groups and others lauded his
actions.
</P>
<P>
   In its appeal, the state argued that removing the tube amounted
to euthanasia. The state's own examining physicians, however, had
ruled Finn to be in a vegetative state, and the Virginia Supreme
Court immediately rejected the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But the question persists of why Finn's family and friends
insisted he showed signs of consciousness. Doctors like Cranford
explained that it is ``very typical'' for people to mistake signs
and gestures for consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say the person is interacting with their environment,
their eyes move about and they randomly blink and look perfectly
normal,'' he said. ``It takes families weeks, months, years,
sometimes forever to see the person is in a vegetative state. Some
can never bring themselves to admit it.''
</P>
<P>
   There are only three known cases in the world where people who
suffered injuries like Finn's emerged from unconsciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Cranford says that it is difficult to misdiagnose a persistent
vegetative state.
</P>
<P>
   For some members of the Finn family, this explanation may never
be acceptable. And for Michele, and those who supported her, the
bitterness toward the state may never fade, said her lawyer,
Gregory L. Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said Michele was ``absolutely devasted and emotionally
torn apart'' by having to fight the state for the right to remove
the feeding tube.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Gilmore and Delegate Marshall &UR;  &LR; have put me through
sheer hell,'' Michele said in a public statement after the state
Supreme Court ruled against the state. ``I don't see where they can
run roughshod over the law.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
