<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8552 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-TITOV-$ADV10-C     10-09 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-TITOV-$ADV10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE RUSSIAN RIGHT STUFF: VETERAN COSMONAUT COVETS GLENN'S
MISSION
 &HT;    With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, Oct. 10 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ As American John Glenn prepares for his return to space
later this month aboard the U.S. space shuttle, no one is watching
with more interest or envy than German Titov, Russia's second man
in space and the retired dean of the cosmonaut corps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am jealous of him. I would also like to fly again,'' Titov
said in a recent interview at the Memorial Museum of Cosmonautics
in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Like Glenn, Titov is the senior surviving space traveler from
his country. And like Glenn, his space glory led him to a career in
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that when I am as old as John Glenn I'll also be able
to fly in space again,'' quipped Titov, now 63 and a member of the
Russian parliament. But his smile faded as he added: ``I don't
think that is going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russian space program has been plagued by cash shortages and
technical glitches. Its troubled space station Mir, is scheduled to
end its service and plummet to earth next year. Amid the country's
economic crisis, Russia cannot afford to meet its obligations under
the planned international space station.
</P>
<P>
   But the Right Stuff lives on in Titov. He dismisses critics in
his own country who criticize public spending on space exploration.
``These people don't understand the critical importance of science
and explorations. It is what being human is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Titov followed Russian Yuri Gagarin, and Americans Alan Shepard
and Gus Grissom to become the fourth human to travel in space.
After Gagarin's sensational first flight, Titov gave the Russians
yet another coup over the fledgling U.S. space program.
</P>
<P>
   Then 25, Titov was the first man to spend a full day in space in
prolonged weightlessness, orbiting the earth 17 times on August
6-7, 1961. The experience also gave Titov the dubious bragging
rights as the first human to suffer the seasickness-like effects of
zero-gravity.
</P>
<P>
   Titov and Glenn met first in 1962, the year after each of them
flew in space. It was the first close encounter of an American
astronaut and Russian cosmonaut during the Cold War. (The two last
met in the summer of 1997 at the Smithsonian's Air and Space Museum
in Washington to promote an exhibit on Russian space exploration.)
</P>
<P>
   A scientific conference brought them together in Washington,
each man reflecting his country and the times. Glenn hosted the
Russian at an impromptu cookout at his home in suburban Virginia;
Titov brought the vodka.
</P>
<P>
   They have met several times since. But neither Glenn nor Titov
could have imagined in 1962 that they would each end up in politics
-- Glenn in the U.S. Senate and Titov as a Communist Party member
elected to the Duma, the lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought our space careers would end with a trip to Mars.
The space programs were evolving that rapidly. But the end was
somehow different,'' said Titov.
</P>
<P>
   Titov and Glenn's path to space began much the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty Soviet military pilots were selected to train as
cosmonauts at a secret base, now known as Star City, outside Moscow
in 1960. By the end of the year the group was pared down to six,
including Titov and Gagarin.
</P>
<P>
   Titov was the backup for Gagarin's mission. The diaries of a
Soviet space administrator published in 1995 recalled that Titov
was perhaps more qualified than Gagarin -- but in the end Gagarin
was picked because of his easy smile and everyman appeal as the son
of peasants.
</P>
<P>
   Gagarin, who died in a 1968 jet crash, is a legend. He is buried
within the Kremlin walls and his name adorns streets and parks in
cities throughout Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Titov went on to become an air force general and was elected to
the Duma in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have two birthdays -- Sept. 11, 1935, when my mother bore
me, and August 6-7, 1961, when the entire world knew there was this
person called Titov,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet his fame never came close to the hero status reached by
Gagarin in Russia and Glenn in America.
</P>
<P>
   In those early meetings with Glenn and other American
astronauts, Titov recalls comparing notes about weightlessness and
the mechanics of eating, drinking and sleeping in space.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cold War was among politicians and military planners and
speechmakers. Cosmonauts and astronauts -- we had no problems. We
have a special bond,'' Titov said.
</P>
<P>
   But the years may have colored his recollections.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference with Glenn during their 1962 meeting in
Washington, Titov was guarded in answering questions about his
Vostok-II spacecraft and would discuss space cooperation only in
the context of disarmament, the Washington Star newspaper reported
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   NASA's historical summary of the early years of the space
program reflects the anxiety Americans felt over Titov's flight in
an age that fueled fears of the Soviets lobbing warheads from their
capsules in space.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people admired the Soviet's technological proficiency but
were concerned by the strategic implications. The fact that Titov's
orbital track in a near-polar plane carried him over the United
States three times was alarming to some people,'' the NASA history
says.
</P>
<P>
   Titov hopes Glenn's shuttle flight will renew interest in space
exploration, both in America and Russia, and that cooperation
between the two countries will continue.
</P>
<P>
   But he notes with sadness that his own nine-year-old grandson
has no interest in Russia's efforts in space.
</P>
<P>
   He also has grown weary of politics and does not plan to seek
reelection to the Duma next year. Instead, Titov plans to write his
memoirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still resourceful and I need to write them while I'm
young,'' said Titov with a grin. ``Before my mind goes and I start
telling everybody that I was the first man in space, not Gagarin!''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
