<HEADER>
A8554 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-PROFILE-OPRAH-2N     10-09 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PROFILE-OPRAH-2NDTAKE-$ADV11-HNS </SLUG>
  
 BOSTON: x x x circus tune.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finally, the long line of aspirants led to Demme. She knew from
the first meeting. ``And I never, ever regretted it, even when I
disagreed,'' Winfrey said. ``You know, there were some days when I
had disagreements, but he was always right I have to tell you. He's
always been right, and that's really not an easy thing for me to
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would have been a different movie without him,'' she
continued. ``Because, if I'd had a director I could have pushed
around, I would have played (Sethe) with a greater sense of
sentimentality _ and I would have ruined the movie. It would have
ruined the movie for her to be sentimental, because she isn't.
That's what makes her what she is _ there's not a moment's sympathy
she has for herself.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, Winfrey shed tears while uttering some of Sethe's most
painful dialogue _ including an agonizing recollection of white men
sucking milk from her breasts. Winfrey couldn't speak the lines
without crying. So Demme corrected her. And corrected her: Sethe
would not weep for herself. ``So he said to me, `Listen. Go empty
yourself. Do whatever you need to do.' So I cried in the corner,
just boo-hooed in the corner, then I came back. I was clean. I did
it his way _ the best way, actually.''
</P>
<P>
   She played the scene without tears.``I've always wanted to be an
actress, and my father didn't want me to be,'' said Winfrey, who
received an Oscar nomination for her performance in Steven
Spielberg's ``The Color Purple.'' ``My father said: `No daughter of
mine ...,' and, `How do you think a negro girl's gonna get a job
acting?' To my father, acting is synonymous with stripping your
clothes off and running nude around a room.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Winfrey would allow his daughter to teach acting,
however, so she majored in speech and drama with an eye toward a
career in education. She was a student (and radio broadcaster) at
Tennessee State University when a local news director phoned and
offered her a job in television. So began one of the most
extraordinary _ and fruitful _ careers in broadcasting, culminating
in last month's decision to extend her daytime talk show through
2002. She'll wear the producer's hat again for ``Tuesdays with
Morrie,'' a film version of Mitch Albom's best-selling book. Her
goal, she said, is ``finding something that speaks to me. ... It
takes a lot of work to do this well. It really does. And it takes
as much time to do it poorly as it does to do it well. If you take
the time off to do a movie, for me, it needs to speak to you or be
meaningful in a way that it's going to speak to other people
because it's a lot of your energy. I think acting is the ultimate
in compassion, and empathy, because you've got to step into
somebody else's life.''
</P>
<P>
   Winfrey, it turns out, is a profound believer in art and its
power to change lives. ``That's what art does for you,'' she said.
``That's what real art does for you. You know, you hear a beautiful
pianist, and even though I can't play a note on the piano, I feel
like it touches something inside me, and I can be a better person.
... When I saw `Phantom of the Opera,' I heard those voices, and I
went out thinking, `I'll do my own theme song.' She laughed. Only
kidding. ``No, I went out thinking, `Tomorrow's gonna be better for
me. I'm gonna do better,' she said. ``And isn't that what art
does?''
</P>
</TEXT>
