<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S THE GREAT WHITE WAY, CHARLIE BROWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; It is a little-known fact, but the most-produced American
musical of the past quarter-century is ``You're a Good Man, Charlie
Brown.'' Why? Mainly because high schools, community theaters, and
summer-stock companies can mount the 6-person show cheaply _ it ran
for years in New York's Greenwich Village with a two-piece
orchestra and virtually no set _ and fill the house. The animating
spirit of Charles Schulz's comic strip characters, and the music,
lyrics, and book by Clark Gesner have delighted millions of
theater-goers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 31 years after its debut, a ``Charlie'' revival is headed
for Broadway. But the new ``Charlie'' ain't the old ``Charlie.''
The producers are promising an ``ethnically diverse,'' grandiosely
designed show by hot Broadway director Michael Mayer. Schroeder is
an African-American. B.D. Wong of ``M. Butterfly'' is playing
Linus, and Anthony Rapp, the original Mark Cohen from ``Rent,''
will be Charlie. ``It's going to be a `Charlie Brown' for the
90s,'' says Michael Leavitt, an executive for the show's
co-producer, Chicago-based Fox Theatricals.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Gesner hadn't paid much attention to the
revival. He spent the summer acting at the Weston Playhouse in
Vermont, and producing his own cabaret show in New York, called
``The Jello is Always Red.'' But when he learned that Fox had
booked the show into Broadway, and that Matthew Broderick was being
wooed for the lead, he started to get nervous. ``I've said no to a
Broadway revival for 30 years,'' says Gesner, who must approve any
script or song changes for the new, megabucks ``Charlie.'' ``What I
heard about it made me uncomfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Mayer _ who once acted in ``Charlie'' _ is planning
some changes. He may re-name one of the six characters, and add at
least one new song to the show. The show's backers emphasize that
the proposed changes are copacetic with Peanuts creator Charles
Schulz, and with Arthur Whitelaw and Gene Persson, who produced the
1976 original. Says Persson: ``Obviously we want Clark to be part
of the process. We expect him to be happy with the changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Gesner and Mayer sat down for lunch about a month ago, and it
came off amicably. Says Gesner: ``We did agree about keeping the
core of the show.'' Gesner is the world's last gentleman and will
go to extraordinary lengths to avoid a conflict with ``Charlie'''s
new friends. On the other hand, he notes: ```Charlie Brown' is such
a delicate and small thing, I don't want them to ruin it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
