<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8568 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIAN-GAMBLING-2TAKE     10-09 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-GAMBLING-2TAKES-$ADV11-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIAN-GAMBLING-2TAKES-$ADV11 
 
NEVADA GAMBLING GROUPS BATTLING CALIFORNIA'S INDIAN GAMING
INITIATIVE WITH BIG MONEY 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 11) 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KIM COBB 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMECULA, Calif. _ Turn on a television anywhere in California
these days and you're going to get an expensive earful on the
state's Indian gaming initiative.
</P>
<P>
   With the vote still weeks away, the massive amount of airtime
being bought by both sides virtually guarantees that Proposition 5
will break the state's previous $58 million record for spending on
a ballot measure _ thereby setting a national record as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before all is said and done, I think Proposition 5 is going to
do like Mark McGwire _ not just break the record but shatter it,''
said Mitch Zack, a spokesman for California Gov. Pete Wilson's
political office.
</P>
<P>
   The issue before voters is whether the state's Indian tribes
will be allowed to operate legally the slot machines they have had
in their casinos for years.
</P>
<P>
   But a huge amount of money is at stake: how much more the Indian
tribes stand to earn from this already-lucrative industry, and how
much neighboring Las Vegas stands to lose at the hands of their
nascent competitors.
</P>
<P>
   For the campaign reporting period that ended Sept. 30, the
coalition of Indian tribes supporting Proposition 5 had raised
$42.7 million. The opponents report contributions of $15.5 million
- which means the two sides raised a combined amount of money equal
to the 1996 spending record with five weeks until the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their history of poverty, the tribes are outspending
their moneyed opponents - a Las Vegas coalition whose big donors
have been Hilton Hotels Corp. with $ 4.3 million, Circus Circus
Enterprises with $4.4 million and Mirage Resorts with $4.3 million
</P>
<P>
   Proposition backers, who call themselves Californians for Indian
Self-Reliance, have spent about $36 million to date, said spokesman
Dan Pellissier.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us the spending issue is driven in large part by what we
have to do to compete with the misinformation being spread by our
opponents,'' Pellisier said. ``The burden of proof is on us to
educate the voters. We've been largely successful in that.''
</P>
<P>
   The state government has been quarreling with the tribes for
years over what kind of gaming is legal in the Indian casinos, all
of which sit on reservation lands. The federal Indian Gaming
Regulatory Act of 1988 restricts the tribes to types of gaming
already legal in the state, and requires the tribes to sign
compacts with the state government.
</P>
<P>
   The casinos, many of which started as bingo parlors, evolved
into rather large-scale, highly profitable operations over the past
decade without compacts. And while California law allows a lottery,
bingo, off-track betting and card clubs, the state's constitution
specifically prohibits ``casinos of the type operating in Nevada
and New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   The major sticking point is the thousands of video slot machines
which proliferate in the Indian casinos. U.S. attorneys in
jurisdictions throughout the state have in recent months threatened
to seize the machines as illegal, because players were ``betting
against the house,'' as in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Pete Wilson, saying he would only deal with tribes who were
not breaking the law, negotiated a restrictive compact for a
limited number of slot machines with the Pala Band of Mission
Indians, who do not have a casino. He also forced a handful of
other tribes to accept the agreement with threats of seizing their
illegal machines. But some of the wealthier gaming tribes called
the deal unworkable and began seeking signatures to force the
referendum.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And legal observers still predict a court fight even if
Proposition 5 passes.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents' advertisements hope to convince the average
Californian that a vote for Proposition 5 will fuel a huge boom in
unregulated, untaxed gambling, turning the state into a place where
no residential neighborhood is safe from a casino.
</P>
<P>
   But the Indian tribes backing the gaming initiative have the
clear public relations advantage, both in terms of the real poverty
still experienced by many non-gaming California tribes (who would
receive a percentage of the casino tribes' profits under
Proposition 5), and a reservoir of public guilt over the tribal
history of mistreatment at the hands of the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   One brochure distributed by the Pechanga Band of Luiseno Indians
features an illustration of what looks like Custer's Last Stand,
and advises, ``The old way to steal from the Indians was to send in
the Cavalry. Today it's Las Vegas casinos, politicians, slick
lobbyists.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls indicate a majority of California voters intend to
vote for Proposition 5.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pechanga casino in Temecula, a voter registration booth
sits prominently in a courtyard that players pass while moving from
one gaming room to another. One volunteer said they have registered
about 2,000 people to vote at the casino in recent weeks - many of
them people in their 50s and 60s who say they have never voted
before.
</P>
<P>
   In a small office up the hill from the casino, surrounded by
boxes of Proposition 5 support material and brochures, tribal
members and Proposition 5 organizers Jill Sherman and Donna Baron
said there is no reason to believe passing the initiative would set
off a boom in Indian casinos. A lot of the reservations are in
areas that are just too remote to support a casino, Sherman said.
``So it's an Indian issue. It's not going to up the ante for anyone
else,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits of gaming are obvious, according to tribal council
member Andrew Masiel. ``Tribal members have been able to buy mobile
homes, fix their homes, purchase better vehicles. We've been able
to build a fire station, a playground, a park, a government
center.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventy-five percent of our business will be gone if
Proposition 5 doesn't pass, because they'll force us to shut down
those (non-lottery style) slot machines,'' Sherman said. The tribe
estimates it would cost about $13 million to buy the kinds of game
machines described in the Pala compact that have not yet been
designed.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue goes beyond the money. ``They said they'd close
the door before they'd sell our sovereignty,'' Sherman said,
referring to the tribal council.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, the Indian casinos in California are no match
for the glitz of Las Vegas. But studies show that Las Vegas draws
about 35 percent of its clientele from neighboring California.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Eadington, director of the Institute for the Study of
Gambling and Commercial Gaming at the University of Nevada at Reno,
explained that growth in Las Vegas has been ``soft'' for the past
two years, both in terms of visitors and gaming revenues. Air
carriers have reduced the number of flights to and from Las Vegas
in favor of more profitable cities. And casinos have noticed a
measurable drop in high end players because of the Asian economic
crisis, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Adding fuel to panic, five major hotel projects will be
completed next year, adding 20,000 more hotel rooms to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Mulhal, spokesman for the Nevada Resort Association, said
despite his state's obvious financial stake in the outcome of
Proposition 5, Nevada gaming companies also know from their own
cities' history that tight regulation of gaming is necessary _
something he says is absent under Proposition 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the claims by proponents of Proposition 5, the clear
reality is the federal government has not yet dedicated the
resources ... to come anywhere near the levels of scrutiny and
diligence the New Jersey gaming control or Nevada gaming control
operations have,'' Mulhal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You add to that the tribes are not taxed, don't have any of
the community obligations, they don't have to provide workers
compensation _ you can see how unfair the competition would be,''
Mulhal said. ``Because make no mistake about it, the competition in
the gaming industry is there and it's growing because gaming has
proliferated around the country. There's no doubt Las Vegas is up
to the challenge, but if it's unregulated and untaxed, that's
tilting the playing field.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
