<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8572 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     10-09 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CRIME' DOESN'T PACK ENOUGH PASSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Well, well. A network known for crashing asteroids and other
supernatural wonders takes on a classic novel, one of literature's
most memorable characters and an intricate premise that remains
rich even by today's standards.
</P>
<P>
   The result for NBC is a handsome-looking and well-acted, if not
somewhat tedious, adaptation of Fyodor Dostoevsky's ``Crime and
Punishment'' with Patrick Dempsey as the young, guilt-ridden
student Rodya Raskolnikov. Those who labored through the novel
won't be satisfied that due reverence has been paid, but I can't
remember when a film adaptation, let alone a TV movie (even from
the well-respected Hallmark, as here) lived up to its literary
source.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the major problem with ``Crime and Punishment'' (8 p.m.
CDT Sunday, NBC) is that the core issue of Dostoevsky's novel _ do
extraordinary people, because of their greatness, have the right to
commit any crime and remain unpunished? _ goes practically
unexplored.
</P>
<P>
   We are left with dream sequences and ever-too-brief exchanges
between Raskolnikov and Magistrate Porfiry (Ben Kingsley), who
suspects Raskolnikov in the killing of a corrupt pawnbroker and her
sister, an innocent bystander returning home while Raskolnikov was
still in the apartment rifling through his victim's valuables.
</P>
<P>
   Raskolnikov is a brilliant but impoverished student, and Dempsey
portrays him as a mixture of upper-crust snob and liberal
revolutionary. No wonder that immediately after the murders,
committed with an ax, he suffers debilitating pangs of conscience.
This is, after all, a man who rushed into a burning home to save
small children, and verbally scolded his sister for marrying for
money. Unable to keep his tortured soul from taking over his
exterior, Raskolnikov attracts the attention of the magistrate.
</P>
<P>
   This is where the psychological wars ensue, though ``Crime and
Punishment'' doesn't exploit that, either. Magistrate Porfiry is
convinced that people who get away with crimes become tortured
souls begging for forgiveness, and even before he lets Raskolnikov
know that something is amiss, we can see that he is merely waiting
for Raskolnikov to burst.
</P>
<P>
   As Raskolnikov says shortly after the murders: ``I'm not ashamed
of what I've done. I will not let guilt betray me.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of Dostoevsky's book lies in its recognition of the
fact that we all may have a murderous side, and of how committing
such a crime could make one confess, if only for the sake of a
peaceful soul.
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey is magnificent as Raskolnikov. In fact, by the film's
end, he doesn't look like a recognizable human being.
</P>
<P>
   While their scenes are far too brief, there is also instant
chemistry between Raskolnikov and his love, played by Julie Delpy,
who is well-cast here. I can't think of anyone with a more perfect
European face.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   One of the many insanely preposterous fight scenes in ``Dollar
for the Dead'' is when Emilio Estevez, as a young gunslinger with
no name and little patience, is trapped inside an upstairs room.
With bars on the window and a dozen gun-wielding bad guys fast
approaching, he pulls out two large pistols, points them at the
floor and starts firing, spinning in a circle.
</P>
<P>
   As the bad guys burst in, Estevez smiles, then conveniently
drops through the punctured floor. Waiting for him on the ground
floor are a half-dozen others, guns drawn. As they fire countless
rounds, a running Estevez raises his pistols and fires, hitting
them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Mister, you're sure pretty good at killin','' an
impressed stranger tells him at one point.
</P>
<P>
   Quips Estevez in an almost apologetic tone. ``Not a talent I
wish for.''
</P>
<P>
   The tawdry pleasures of B-moviedom don't get much better than
``Dollar for the Dead'' (7, 9 and 11 p.m. CDT Sunday, TNT), which
bills itself as a movie about a treasure hunt played out during the
chaotic, almost lawless badlands of the post-Civil War era. But it
does so with such a decided wink of the eye that it's enjoyably
digestible.
</P>
<P>
   William Forsythe is Estevez's partner, and Howie Long is one of
the many in pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   Executive Producer Stanley M. Brooks wants so desperately to
usher the ``spaghetti western'' into the '90s that he shot this
film on the Almeria, Spain, sets where ``The Good, the Bad &AMP; the
Ugly'' and ``Once Upon a Time in the West'' were filmed.
</P>
<P>
   From what I can see, writer/director Gene Quintano has no
interest in developing characters beyond a comic-strip level. And
yet, like Sergio Leone, the filmmaker who obviously inspired this
project, Quintano succeeds in letting the characters use their
bullets like words, creating a dusty, stylized universe of sheer
mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Vietnam: The Soldiers' Story'' (8 and 9 p.m. CDT Sunday
through Tuesday, TLC) isn't a political or social analysis of the
war; it's the ``human'' story of soldiers' experiences. In six
parts, ``Soldiers' Story'' features accounts of POWs and medics,
cameramen and pilots, making good use of archival film from ABC
News (a co-producer), the U.S. military and North Vietnamese
footage. ...
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise that if God picked someone to play a
contemporary Noah in a family film he'd go for the durable Tony
Danza. ``Noah'' (6 p.m. CDT Sunday, ABC) is a sweet, modern-day
version of the biblical patriarch chosen to build an ark and fill
it with animals before a flood threatens their existence. Perfect
for ``Wonderful World of Disney.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   What could possibly bring the world's fastest city to a
standstill? A cab strike? Greg Evigan and Cynthia Gibb find out in
``Earthquake in New York'' (7 p.m. CDT Sunday, Family Channel), a
so-called disaster thriller that even tosses in a ruthless serial
killer. ...
</P>
<P>
   How plausible is it that a judge would order strangers (Jane
Seymour and James Brolin) fighting over custody of a child to get
married? It happens in ``A Marriage of Convenience'' (8 p.m.
Sunday, CBS) and, lo and behold, they fall in love! Hey, at least
CBS calls it a romantic ``fantasy.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
