<DOCNO> NYT19981009.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8577 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEBARTOLO-HNS &LR;      10-09 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBARTOLO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 DeBARTOLO'S LEGAL ORDEAL MAY BE JUST BEGINNING  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. _ Pleading guilty to a felony in federal court
was a doubly humiliating experience for Edward J. DeBartolo Jr. It
showed on his face and in his hangdog demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did he admit to a crime, he also had to tell the world
he was not a stand-up guy and would spill the beans on an old
friend in exchange for lenient treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Living with that decision may prove painful for DeBartolo when
he is cross-examined by lawyers for former Louisiana Gov. Edwin
Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   They will try to define him as a snitch _ the exact opposite of
the public persona DeBartolo has cultivated as a resolute man's
man, a business tycoon with linebacker eyes.
</P>
<P>
   And if the characterization of DeBartolo as a victim of Edwards'
extortion scheme crumbles in court, the National Football League
may be less sympathetic to DeBartolo's effort to regain control of
the San Francisco 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo is regarded as a vital witness in the public
corruption case against Edwards, and for that reason had leverage
in working out a deal with federal prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Had he chosen to proceed to trial in a joint defense with the
Edwards team, he would have been taking the risk of a hefty prison
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo, 51, pleaded guilty to the obscure crime of misprision
of felony _ the failure to report an alleged extortion attempt by
Edwards arising from DeBartolo's efforts to obtain a riverboat
gambling license in Louisiana. He was sentenced to probation for
two years and fined $1 million _ on condition that he cooperate
with the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Misprision is ``a charge that is used a lot when you get
individuals that you want to flip and they want to negotiate an
agreement,'' said John Volz, the former U.S. attorney in New
Orleans, who prosecuted Edwards in 1985 and 1986 on charges of
illegally selling hospital permits.
</P>
<P>
   ``You charge them with the lesser offense. You could get them
for a bigger offense, but to get their cooperation you have to give
them something,'' Volz said. ``Not only did he (DeBartolo) get a
much lesser felony than he would've been charged with, but he was
facing RICO, and that's 20 years in the pen.''
</P>
<P>
   RICO is the acronym for Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt
Organizations Act, the federal statute under which Edwards, his son
Stephen and at least one associate are expected to be indicted by a
Baton Rouge grand jury as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   Volz also noted that in allowing DeBartolo to plead guilty to a
minor criminal offense, the prosecution ``makes him a much better
looking witness'' than if he had been let off. ``You can't just let
him go. That would destroy him (as a witness),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Volz noted, ``defense lawyers are going to ask, `How
many years did you get?' And he says, `I didn't get any,' so they
say, `So you had an incentive to lie, didn't you?' and he'll have
to take his lumps on that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Portman, a federal public defender in San Francisco, said
the prosecution appears to be trying to create the image of
DeBartolo as ``Red Riding Hood who didn't yell `wolf.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you believe the spin being given (to DeBartolo's plea), it
is that `I am being sentenced because I, as a victim of a wicked
extortion plot, didn't tell the government soon enough of my sad
plight.' But that obviously did not happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Portman said U.S. District Judge John V. Parker hit the nail on
the head in a comment from the bench when he accepted DeBartolo's
guilty plea Tuesday: ``The criminal justice system rewards the
fellow who gets to the courthouse quickest, and (DeBartolo attorney
Aubrey) Harwell has secured you a prime seat on the train that
seems to be leaving the station. In fact, you may have a private
car.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an unfortunately very accurate statement about the
nature of the criminal justice system and the use of informants
these days,'' Portman said. ``It was striking because of its
candor.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, a Democrat, has made light of the damage DeBartolo
could inflict on him as a witness. ``If he told the truth, it
certainly would not hurt me,'' he said. ``Anybody who jumps to the
conclusion that he's a victim ... ought to listen to the tape of
our telephone conversations.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the allegation that he victimized DeBartolo by insisting
on a wad of cash for using his influence to secure the riverboat
casino license, Edwards said, ``If I had victimized him, I would
have done it for a lot more than $400,000.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
