A8603 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FERAL-CATS-2TAKES-$AD     10-09 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FERAL-CATS-2TAKES-$ADV11-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FERAL-CATS-2TAKES-$ADV11 
 
TEXAS A&AMP;M STUDENTS INTENT ON HUMANELY SOLVING PROBLEM OF FERAL CATS
PROWLING UNIVERSITY  
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 11) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ By day, the sprawling Texas A&AMP;M
University campus almost buzzes with excitement as more than 43,000
Aggies hotly pursue their dream of higher education.
</P>
<P>
   But when darkness falls and students retreat, the cats appear.
</P>
<P>
   From basement, window sill and drain pipe, they come. Three
hundred of them, by best estimate. Howling, prowling, without
pedigree or permanent home, they do what vagabond cats do _ fight,
scavenge and make more kittens.
</P>
<P>
   It's been this way for decades. And, although some have agonized
over the animals' welfare or fretted that they might spread disease
or kill too many birds, for the most part the situation has been
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, comes the Aggie Feral Cat Alliance (AFCAT), a
volunteer group of students and professors intent on humanely
solving A&AMP;M's stray cat problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some view these cats as just carnivores out in the wild,''
said AFCAT faculty sponsor Margaret Slater. ``They're satisfied
that their population will just wax and wane with the food supply,
as with foxes. My personal perspective is that this is a domestic
species and we have a responsibility for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Slater, an associate professor at A&AMP;M's College of Veterinary
Medicine, said AFCAT's goal is to reduce the number of on-campus
stray cats by neutering them. To that end, as many as 12 cats a
month are being trapped and sent to the vet school's small animal
clinic on the edge of campus for an operation that will change
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   While there, they are tested for fatal diseases, vaccinated,
implanted with information-laden computer chips and fitted with
special radio collars for later tracking.
</P>
<P>
   Healthy kittens are ``rehabilitated'' for adoption. The adults,
which are skittish, hostile and hardly can be handled, are released
into the wilds of the A&AMP;M campus, now the site of 12 cat-feeding
stations monitored by student volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M's approach _ modeled after a similar effort at California's
Stanford University _ is a dramatic step away from the standard
method of dealing with colonies of stray animals: trapping and
destroying.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some other institutions, A&AMP;M never has destroyed large
numbers of feral cats. In fact, the cat problem officially came to
light only when traps set for marauding skunks or raccoons snagged
an occasional kitty.
</P>
<P>
   While a smaller neutering program is in place at the University
of Texas in Austin, it is the College Station effort that has drawn
regional and national attention. Earlier this month, a Discovery
Channel video crew visited campus to document the group's efforts.
Financial support for the $50,000, two-year program, which began in
August, has come from foundations and vaccine and cat food
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is every indication that these types of programs can be
successful,'' said AFCAT founder Dawn Fradkin, a first-year
veterinary medicine student. ``But the critical element for our
success is educating the public. As long as there's a source for
more cats, we can neuter all we like and we're still going to have
this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Local animal advocates noted that A&AMP;M is not unique in its
homeless cat problem.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Bice, executive director of the Brazos Animal Shelter,
which serves 10 Texas counties, said her agency receives 10,000
animals a year, roughly two-thirds of them strays. The phenomenon
of ``throw away pets'' leaves the normally placid Bice apoplectic.
``It cheapens life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem of stray animals, though, isn't limited to cats.
Packs of feral dogs have been reported in rural Brazos County.
Often, though, they are quickly corralled. Cats, leading lives of
stealth and inconspicuousness, are another matter. And, Dawn
Boothe, vet school associate professor and AFCAT adviser, noted
that many people simply view the lives of cats as unimportant.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Dogs are working animals,'' she said, ``and you can see a role
for food animals. That makes sense. But there's not a real role for
cats in society. They've always been an extra.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many people say, `Ugh! I don't like cats.' or that cats
are aloof?''
</P>
<P>
   At A&AMP;M, Slater, Fradkin and others associated with AFCAT,
believe many of the campus cats were abandoned by students, who had
brought the animals into their dormitories in violation of
university policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students can be idealistic,'' Fradkin said. ``They aren't
knowledgeable about the cost _ vaccinations and so forth _ involved
in being responsible pet owners.''
</P>
<P>
   Other cats were dumped on campus by townsfolk who concluded the
animals would be cared for by kind-hearted college kids.
</P>
<P>
   While feral cats usually fall victim to their environment within
three years _ house cats can live 15 years or more _ a fertile
female can deliver several litters annually.
</P>
<P>
   The strays' presence on campus has stirred passions among cat
lovers and those who fear their impact on birds and other ``urban
wildlife,'' but most students probably aren't aware they are there.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd see a few cats hanging around,'' Slater said, ``but
they never thought about it.''
</P>
<P>
   A nocturnal stroll through the nearly deserted campus with Sara
Ash, a wildlife and fisheries graduate student working with AFCAT
to track neutered and radio-collared cats, is revealing.
</P>
<P>
   Equipped with an oversized flashlight and antenna, Ash, 26,
combs the campus nightly to document their lives and travels. On
one recent outing, she found collared cats in window sills, hidden
in shrubbery around campus buildings and just skulking about in the
shadows.
</P>
<P>
   Led to each subject by the beeping of her monitor, she
spotlighted the cat, then meticulously noted the details of its
location. Such data should help AFCAT judge the success of its
efforts as well as lay the groundwork for future studies.
</P>
<P>
   Passing students good-naturedly greeted the young woman and her
cumbersome apparatus. ``Some of them ask me if I've got cable,''
she said. ``They meow at me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ash said she has been struck by the affection many on campus
feel for the strays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had one woman tell me that she was worried that one cat's
radio collar was on too tight,'' she said. ``She said she thought
the cats had `sweet faces.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ash, though, is not among the cats' admirers.
</P>
<P>
   Contending that studies have shown even well-fed cats will prey
on birds and other wildlife, she dispassionately admitted her
sympathies lie not with the strays, but with their meals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two parts of a cat's brain,'' she said. ``One that
addresses hunger and one that deals with hunting. Even when a cat's
hunger is satisfied, it will still hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   AFCAT officials conceded that ``if anything moves fast, cats
will try to catch it,'' but countered that the rampant growth of
A&AMP;M _ the campus now encompasses more than 5,000 acres _ likely has
done more damage to wildlife than the cats.
</P>
<P>
   At the Sterling Evans Library in the heart of the main campus,
the stray cats for years have had a home away from home. Each
morning, the cats queue up for a free breakfast, emerging from the
shrubbery as staff opens the building for the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been feeding them for two years,'' said one employee, who
asked not to be identified. ``There are four or five people here
feeding them. You just feel so sorry for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just get started and you can't stop.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
