<HEADER>
A8605 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-CHEAP-BOS &LR;      10-09 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CHEAP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVVING UP TO THE '70S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the annals of rock 'n' roll no band has toured this way:
Twenty-one years after its album debut, the band, still intact and
rocking, is revisiting its first three studio albums by playing
each album, in its entirety, in order, on successive nights in the
same city.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, Cheap Trick plays Boston's Paradise, where it made
its area debut two decades ago. On Thursday, the band plays its
eponymous first album; Friday, it's album two, ``In Color''; the
group wraps it up on Saturday with ``Heaven Tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, many of the songs on these albums were included on
the 1979 live album breakthrough, ``At Budokan,'' when singer Robin
Zander became a young girl's pop dream and goofball guitarist Rick
Nielsen became ... well, America's uber-guitar geek with hot licks.
Fleshing out the Trick experience were handsome bassist Tom
Petersson and pudgy, chain-smoking, alleged Venezuelan drummer Bun
E. Carlos. (He's actually Brad Carlson and hails from the same
Rockville, Ill., parts as the others.)
</P>
<P>
   So, what have we here in 1998? A retro thrill? A flashback to
the late '70s? An acid-damaged casualty trip?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah, I think all of those,'' says Nielsen. ``I don't know. It's
just we're playing real good and this is the soup du jour of the
week. See, we never did these albums like that then, so it's still
new and fun with us, not like some drudgery we're going through.
When we did them we meant them to be played like this (the songs in
order). We wanted each record to stand alone _ there are highs,
lows, fast, slow, a whole bunch of different stuff. Now, we when we
get done with the first side, we turn all of the equipment around
and flip over.''
</P>
<P>
   A little joke there from the band's main songwriter, who has
pumped many a Cheap Trick song with both sly jokes and strong
melodies, bright hooks, and double-edged lyrics. Nielsen always has
been a hyperactive guitarist-foil to the classically styled rock
singer Zander. Says Nielsen: ``People used to say to me, `Whatever
Rick's on, I'd like to get some.' Now, they say, `Whatever Rick's
on, I don't want any.' Actually, I'm on the same thing every night
I play: I actually like people and I like to play. I don't always
feel like a million dollars, but I try not to let anybody know.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Carlos, of this club tour: ``It's weird to look back and
celebrate a little bit. When those albums came out, we were living
in a motor home or on the bus on the road. There was more struggle,
just to keep your head above water. ... (Playing these songs) is
like going to your high school reunion, where some of the people
you're glad to see again, and then you remember why you haven't
seen some of them in 20 years. Occasionally, some of the lyrics
might be dated, but luckily Rick wrote three great albums in the
first place, so they hold up real good.''
</P>
<P>
   The tour has a practical and promotional purpose, too:
Sony/Legacy has remastered, remixed, and re-released those first
three albums (with bonus tracks) as well as an expanded, complete
version of ``At Budokan.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, an album a night does not a concert make. Albums _ 12
inches round, two sides of polyvinyl chloride _ tended to clock in
under 45 minutes. So, Carlos explains, Cheap Trick plays the album
that is the soup du jour and ``a couple of hits and whatever.'' The
band will spread about 50 songs over three nights. There will be
some obvious repeats but not that many. ``Surrender,'' the big,
early rock-as-generational-bonding hit, will likely be played
twice. ``The Flame'' _ a treacly power ballad not written by Cheap
Trick but played and sung by them, a 1988 song that reached No.1. _
will not make an appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is part of our history,'' says Nielsen, of ``The Flame.''
``Whether we care to do it or not ... It left a bad taste in our
mouths. But, like I say to people in my own family, if there is
something buggin' you, get over it. So I say, `Hey, Rick, get over
it.' Having something go to No.1 is not something many people get a
chance to do. I wish it would have been with `Dream Police,' but it
wasn't and everything's cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheap Trick has gone through peaks and valleys, weathering the
lows spots by working through them, and, occasionally, connecting
with whatever direction the mainstream is headed. ``I don't have a
clue,'' says Nielsen, as to when or why that happens. As to the
glow that surrounds pop stardom, Nielsen says, ``Once you start
believing all that baloney you read, it's like, `Yikes! I'm not
like that.'''
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen and company are planning a new live CD; they'll be
recording new songs this spring. Having parted company with their
last label, Red Ant, which released ``Cheap Trick,'' (yes, their
second eponymous disc), they're looking for a new deal.
</P>
<P>
   Cheap Trick has played with big hip bands like Smashing Pumpkins
and big unhip bands like Heart. It has some underground cachet. Its
early song, ``He's A Whore,'' was covered by Steve Albini's Big
Black. Band members are unabashed Beatles fans, having covered
``Magical Mystery Tour.'' Cheap Trick has played tiny clubs and
cavernous arenas. Self-described road dogs, they've played 200
shows a year for 20 years. ``More than any other American band,''
says Nielsen. ``Maybe more than any band anyplace, as for a
traveling band. I mean Wayne Newton's played more shows than
anybody ever, but he just crawls out of bed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin sidebar) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't be shocked when you hear Cheap Trick playing on ``I'm
Losing You,'' the lead track from the upcoming John Lennon
boxed-set anthology. Don't be stunned when today's video wizardry
allows for a ``new'' video that combines the guys in Cheap Trick
with the late Beatle's visage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Nat Cole and Natalie Cole,'' says a bemused Rick Nielsen,
guitarist for Cheap Trick.
</P>
<P>
   You see, Cheap Trick _ minus singer Robin Zander _ recorded some
backing tracks to Lennon's last album, 1980's ``Double Fantasy,''
and they just got word that Yoko Ono, the arbiter of all things
Lennon _ has decided to use their backing on ``I'm Losing You,''
despite the fact that it was initially scrapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took us off and now, here, 18 years later, it's coming
out,'' says Nielsen. ``Maybe, it wasn't so bad after all. What they
told us back then was the reason they didn't use it was because we
sounded too heavy compared to the rest of the album.''
</P>
<P>
   Drummer Bun E. Carlos recalls meeting Lennon, who first said,
```Oh, you guys are in Cheap Trick. They told me your names, but
they didn't tell me what band you were in.' That felt good.''
</P>
<P>
   Memories of the five-hour session? Carlos says he was sitting in
the recording booth with Lennon watching Nielsen blister through a
solo. ``We were smoking a doobie,'' says Carlos, ``and he was
jumping up and down going like, `Boy, we could have used this guy
when we did `Cold Turkey.' Clapton was all stoned out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
JIM SULLIVAN &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
