<HEADER>
A8606 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-DEVIL-HNS     10-09 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-DEVIL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPERATE BEAUTY IN PORTRAIT OF ARTIST'S LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID BONETTI  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a scene in ``Love Is the Devil,'' the shockingly real
film subtitled ``study for a portrait of Francis Bacon,'' in which
Derek Jacobi, who plays the celebrated British painter, starts to
paint a picture.
</P>
<P>
   Alone in his studio, no music to accompany him, he approaches a
blank canvas, fiddles around with his brushes, finds a photograph
to use as an aid, traces a circle on the canvas using a trash can
cover _ taking his time to do all of it _ and then, ready at last,
attacks the canvas with a brush laden with paint the color of
coagulated blood.
</P>
<P>
   Fury shaped and controlled by deliberation equals art _ at least
an art as emblematic of mid-century existentialism as Bacon's _ and
it has probably never been captured on film with such sympathy.
Usually the director, not really understanding creativity, overdoes
it. The actor grimaces, spouting nonsense as music swells. He might
as well be portraying constipation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love Is the Devil'' is the best film I've ever seen about an
artist's life. It is also one of the best I've ever seen about gay
life and homosexual relationships. To pile on the praise, it is
also one of the most honest movies I've ever seen about the effects
of alcoholism and drug addiction.
</P>
<P>
   Bleak and depressing, it is relieved by outbursts of great
humor, and it is also desperately beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   The film, written and directed by John Maybury, his first
feature, tells the story of the tortured but strangely tender
relationship between Bacon (1909-1992) and his lover George Dyer
(Daniel Craig).
</P>
<P>
   It opens in 1971 with Bacon returning to his squalid London flat
after the opening of his retrospective in Paris, the first British
artist since Turner to have been so honored. He approaches an
unmade bed, picks up a pillow, sniffs it and then begins to sob
into it.
</P>
<P>
   Dyer, who had almost literally fallen into Bacon's arms while
breaking into his house in a bungled attempt at burglary a number
of years earlier, had died messily of an overdose of pills and
alcohol while Bacon was receiving the press at his opening (in
fact, his suicide occurred a couple of nights before).
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the film is a flashback detailing Bacon's and Dyer's
attempts to forge a relationship across the chasms of class and
personal philosophy. It is dazzlingly edited, the narrative
intercut with subliminal images, for instance of a naked man
covered in blood howling before he topples over into the void, that
capture variously Bacon's blood-steeped philosophy and the horror
of Dyer's mind.
</P>
<P>
   The Colony Room, the Soho drinking club where Bacon and his
cronies hang out, is the setting of much of the action, which is
heavy in bitchy repartee. (Example: Bacon, as he pours champagne
over the head of his dutiful photographer, John Deakin, ``Champagne
for my real friends; real pain for my sham friends.'') Tilda
Swinton gives another memorable performance as Muriel Belcher,
Colony Room proprietor and resident harpy.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of obtaining the rights to reproduce Bacon's images of
screaming popes, of naked men wrestling, of people vomiting into a
sink or sitting on a toilet was prohibitive, but Maybury turned the
disadvantage to his favor. He filmed with distorting lenses that
capture a sense of Bacon's own smeared images without being
literal.
</P>
<P>
   The events surrounding Dyer's death are brilliantly filmed to
simulate the triptychs Bacon subsequently painted of the horrific
event, some of his greatest ever. The scenes in which Maybury
shoots the inebriated Colony Room drinkers apparently through
bottles gives a real sense of what it's like to be drunk and
sparring verbally with similarly lubricated and witty friends (and
enemies).
</P>
<P>
   Jacobi gives an astonishing performance. Visually, he is Francis
Bacon, and he plays the aging ponce with a taste for leather
brilliantly. The bluntly handsome Craig, a sort of Cockney James
Dean, perfectly captures the confusion and desperation of an
uneducated, neurotic, petty criminal more at home with boxers than
with artists.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure authenticity, the rest of the cast includes London art
world figures, both from Bacon's day and the present.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, voice-overs of Bacon's existentialist personal
philosophy structure the film. (Example: ``Is my lover to be my
assassin, or I his?'') In an age when mood-enhancing drugs are
prescribed for every minor depression, it all seems long ago and
far away. ``Love Is the Devil,'' however, brings it all vividly
back to life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 1500EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
