<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-VIETNAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMBITION KILLS INDIVIDUAL TALES IN `VIETNAM' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
VIETNAM: THE SOLDIERS' STORY 
Produced by: Lisa Zeff and Ed Hersh 
On: The Learning Channel (TLC) 
Date: Sunday-Tuesday, 9-ll p.m. and midnight-2 a.m. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``You're covered in blood all day,'' says Army pilot Wayne Coe
in the documentary miniseries, ``Vietnam: The Soldiers' Story.'' At
19, Coe flew support missions in Vietnam. So profuse was the
arterial blood pumping from the wounded, rescued men in his
helicopter, that it had to be hosed out every night.
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of tough, evocative testimony you expect to
hear in a documentary like this six-parter created by ABC News
Productions and airing on the TLC cable channel, beginning Sunday.
(Two hour-long segments run nightly at 9 and again at midnight,
through Tuesday.)
</P>
<P>
   After all, why call it ``the soldiers' story'' if it doesn't
honor the voices and closely, sympathetically detail the harshest
experiences, deepest fears, and innermost thoughts of individual
combatants?
</P>
<P>
   But oddly, whatever its other virtues, this ``Vietnam'' isn't
really driven by the voices of the many veterans interviewed on
camera. This judgment is based on viewing three of the series' six
hours. Despite a few riveting recollections like Coe's, too many of
the interviews seem tamely factual, and all of them exist to
personalize larger, sweeping narrative segments like ``War in the
Skies'' rather than as stories on their own terms.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly a whole fine segment could have been drawn from the
experiences of the series' host, ABC correspondent Jack Smith,
himself a decorated Vietnam veteran. Smith was a 20-year-old
rifleman when he fought in the war's first major battle in 1965.
After being wounded in what he calls ``a massacre,'' he was taken
for dead by North Vietnamese regulars, who then used him and the
corpse of another American soldier as sandbags for their machine
gun. He felt the hot casings of their shells falling on him as they
fired at his fellow soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Even material as powerful and disturbing as this is somehow
diminished if not overwhelmed by its context. Smith's recollections
are only a small part of the much larger story covered in Part 1,
called ``Ambush: The Battle of Ia Drang,'' a bloody, several days'
long action with complex ramifications.
</P>
<P>
   This documentary tries in vain to be two generally incompatible
things at once: deeply personal and historically panoramic. While
it often manages to survey major operations or themes quite well _
the broad ``War in the Skies'' segment is a good example _ the
intimate stories tend to get lost in the epic subject matter.
</P>
<P>
   There are other problems with the interviews, the gravest one
being the lack of leisurely introspection that would almost
certainly have made many of them unforgettable. Senator John
McCain, for example, is given remarkably short shrift in ``The War
in the Skies'' segment, which merely sketches the experiences of
POWs like him, rather than painting full-blown portraits. It
doesn't help that most of the uniform-looking interviews were
filmed in a studio, where the participating veterans couldn't feel
entirely at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vietnam: The Soldiers' Story'' is not without interest and
flashes of intensity, but its hidebound refusal to let the
interviews expand to tell more of this war story in intimate human
terms severely limits its achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the series takes explicit pains to detach its treatment of
the Vietnam War from politics, which of course is impossible, and
it does no such thing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 1501EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981009.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8609 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CRIME-BOS &LR;      10-09 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CRIME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RUSSIAN CLASSIC AS CLIFF NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
CRIME AND PUNISHMENT 
Starring: Patrick Dempsey, Ben Kingsley, Julie Delpy 
Directed by: Joseph Sargent 
On: NBC 
Time: Sunday at 9 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Feodor Dostoevski and Patrick Dempsey _ it's not often you'll
find those names in the same sentence. But a lightbulb went off at
NBC at the idea _ Dempsey is Raskolnikov _ and so Sunday night at 9
we have ``Crime and Punishment'' network-style, with that tormented
ax-murdering Russian dude swigging shots of ``wadka'' and
submitting guiltily to that wise Columbo of a police inspector,
Porfiry Petrovitch. And with the requisite touch of British class,
also known as the Honorary Vanessa Redgrave Casting Coup, we have
Ben Kingsley (and _ whew! _ not Patrick Stewart) Shakespearing it
up as the baldheaded magistrate.
</P>
<P>
   And you know what? It's not half bad, this Cliff Notes of a
Cliff Notes of ``Crime and Punishment.'' Partly that's because it's
always a happy moment whenever network TV aims higher than its
usual
a-woman-murders-her-stalking-ex-who-looks-like-her-abusive-father
story lines, for something low in the exploitation department.
Truly, you can't choose too many classics that are more high-minded
than ``Crime and Punishment'' if you're looking for a cerebral,
barely filmable property that just screams ``Do Your Homework!''
</P>
<P>
   But NBC's ``Crime and Punishment'' is also a fairly engaging two
hours of drama, with a committed performance by Dempsey, authentic
settings filmed in Budapest, and an idea-driven script that more or
less encapsulates Dostoevski's story. Certainly the TV movie is not
going to hold up against comparisons to the novel, not just because
characters and subplots have been dropped, but because it's a
mainstream version of a complex story. The grayer, more
intellectual aspects of its hero's thinking about ordinary versus
extraordinary men have been dulled into simplistic terms, and the
motives behind his actions are given a decidedly conventional
twist. Still, the NBC movie is driven by a few literary ideas _
about society, about conscience, and about redemption.
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey's Rodya Raskolnikov is a poor scholar who kills a
miserly pawnbroker and her sister for money. He is physically
sickened by his guilt, but refuses to turn himself in to the
patient but knowing Porfiry, even after an innocent man claims
responsibility. He is drawn to Sonia (Julie Delpy), whose poverty
and familial trials have led her to prostitution, and she tries to
offer him moral guidance. Meanwhile, his governess sister is
victimized by the wealthy family she works for, and may need to
marry a despicable man for security.
</P>
<P>
   When the script of ``Crime and Punishment'' tries to re-create
Raskolnikov's interior process, it is most awkward. ``This is the
only evidence there is,'' he says out loud to himself. ``I'll throw
it in the river. ... No, no, no, if I throw it away what is the
point of what I have done?'' The writers should have protected
Dempsey from having to spell it all out in this manner, and saved
the lead-footed narration for Books on Tape.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 1502EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981009.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8610 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-HUNGER-BOS &LR;      10-09 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-HUNGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMMIGRANTS' `HUNGER' LEAVES THEM STARVED OF PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
HUNGER 
By Lan Samantha Chang 
Norton, 191 pp., $22 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Some people just live in the past, spewing story after story
to anyone who will listen. Others, like many of the characters in
Lan Samantha Chang's new story collection, ``Hunger,'' refuse to
discuss their past lives at all.
</P>
<P>
   As immigrants, Chang's characters want to focus on achievement,
not family history. But through her six stories, Chang reveals
(among other things) how this culture of silence can drive a wedge
between parent, child, and spouse, creating feelings of
misunderstanding, resentment, and rejection. The book also unveils
how, in turning away from their past, some immigrants place unfair
and unwise expectations on their greatest future hope _ their
children.
</P>
<P>
   The book, through its many characters, is moving and
thought-provoking. While it primarily focuses on the Chinese
immigrant experience, ``Hunger'' could really be a group of stories
about any race or nationality. The desire for love, prosperity,
parental approval, and strong family ties is universal.
</P>
<P>
   Chang begins her first story, which bears the same title as the
book, with the recent arrival of Min in New York City from Taiwan
in 1967. A hostess in a restaurant, Min soon meets her future
husband, Tian Sung, a violin instructor.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's relationship is strained from the beginning. Min
believes it's more important to please Tian than to understand him.
So she never questions why he insists on keeping chopsticks in a
certain drawer or why he has a plan for where each piece of
furniture is placed.
</P>
<P>
   Only after Min confronts Tian about his indifference to her
pregnancy does he briefly reveal some of his demons _ that he'd
been raised to become a scientist and support his family in Taiwan.
When his love for music drew him to the United States, his family
disowned him, telling him he had no right to ever think of them
again. ``I began to see that all of Tian's specifications _ the
chopsticks, ... the placement of lamps _ were slips of willpower,
signs of a forbidden loyalty to this other house that he had been
barred forever from entering,'' Min says.
</P>
<P>
   Tian's mechanism for forgetting his pain, it seems, is his
music. With the birth of daughters Anna and Ruth, Tian forces his
music on them as the one and only means for them to get to know
their father and earn his love and attention. Childhood memories
are never discussed. But when the children discover they don't have
their father's passion for the violin, their relationship with him
dissolves. Why, they're left wondering (as Tian's family did before
them), is music so consuming? Isn't family more important?
</P>
<P>
   The story ``The Unforgetting'' has a similar theme. Ming and
Sansan Hwang move to Iowa from China in 1967 with the great hope
that their son Charles might have a better life in the United
States. ``We're getting old. How will we make the space in our
minds for everything we'll need to learn here?'' Sansan asks early
in the story. Ming responds, ``We will forget.''
</P>
<P>
   And forget they do: that Ming had really wanted to be a
scientist, not a photocopy machine repairman. That Sansan loved
reading Chinese classics, not watching TV to practice her English.
That stored in their house are six rice bowls once used in the
emperor's household. Rather than display them with pride, the
Hwangs store them in the basement, with their red-bound Chinese
history text. When a schoolteacher suggests the Hwangs speak less
Chinese at home so that Charles can learn English faster, they
comply.
</P>
<P>
   With less Chinese culture in the home _ Sansan even cooks
sometimes using Betty Crocker recipes and canned and frozen foods _
it's no surprise that Charles grows to become a typical American
teenager: He locks his bedroom door, cuts short conversations with
his parents, and becomes alienated from his culture. In the end,
Ming and Sansan realize that while they've achieved their American
dream, they've lost their identity and perhaps their son as well.
</P>
<P>
   Chang's stories open up readers to a world of sadness and
regret. So often, her characters can't break barriers of silence
with one another to uncover true feelings. The end result is that
sometimes well-meaning parents, despite all their sacrifices, can't
give their children what they need the most: a firm foundation of
cultural and family history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 1503EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981009.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8616 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-TOUGH-BOS &LR;      10-09 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TOUGH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE PREDICTABLE NYPD PLOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
ONE TOUGH COP 
Directed by: Bruno Barreto 
Screenplay by: Jeremy Iacone, based on Bo Dietl's autobiographical
novel 
Starring: Stephen Baldwin, Chris Penn, Mike McGlone, Gina Gershon,
Paul Guilfoyle, Amy Irving, Victor Slezak 
Running time: 91 minutes 
Rated: R (strong violence and language) 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Authentically gritty street settings and characters are
undermined by melodramatic contrivance in ``One Tough Cop.''
Although based on the specific experiences of retired New York City
detective Bo Dietl, who lives up to the film's title, it comes
close to flattening them into cliche. Too bad, because in doing so,
it wastes what could have been Stephen Baldwin's breakthrough
performance as Dietl, who was more concerned with results than with
career politics. He comes across as the kind of cop you like to
know is out there on the streets _ smart, tenacious, solving most
of the crimes he investigates, even if it sometimes meant turning a
blind eye to due process.
</P>
<P>
   Vigilante cops have been meat and drink to the movies long
before Dirty Harry ever fired a shot from his block-long revolver,
and Baldwin's taciturn Dietl persuades us that he has developed a
world view that allows him to do things his own way as long as he
lives up to his code of honor. Essentially, it's the old
Love-Your-Friends-Crucify-Your-Enemies code, which means he's
thrown into conflict with his police colleagues because he insists
he can do his job without compromising himself while still
remaining close with the rising mafia underboss who had been his
friend since childhood.
</P>
<P>
   The film takes a dim view of the workings of the justice
establishment, which puts the squeeze on him when he refuses to
wire his mafia buddy. He's also unswervingly loyal to his
self-destructive partner, Chris Penn, in another of the
good-hearted, slow-thinking lug roles into which he's been
pigeonholed for too long. Specifically, the cop Penn plays is
lumbered by severe alcohol and gambling addictions, which of course
make him vulnerable to his superiors, to say nothing of his mob
creditors.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Baldwin and Penn play cops under the gun, but
brave all the same, and so effective that they embarrass their
politically-oriented bosses, who would love to can them, but can't
because they keep breaking big cases and maintain impressive arrest
and conviction records. They're tough, they're tenacious, and they
succeed because they throw out the rulebook, hit hard and worry
about the legalities later. Baldwin at least underplays
convincingly and never shows any sign of sadistically reveling in
the tough-guy stuff.
</P>
<P>
   The film goes off the track, however, when it plays out a
triangle involving Dietl, his mafia buddy and the latter's mistress
(Gina Gershon), who transfers her affections from the married crime
boss to the unmarried cop. Throughout, mob stereotypes undercut the
streetwise flavor, which peaks in the cops' bulldozing through the
ghetto and breaking heads until they collar a couple of thugs who
break into a convent, rape a nun and leave her for dead. Given the
flawed script, it takes more directorial savvy than Bruno Barreto
can deliver to move ``One Tough Cop'' away from genre cliche. TV
cop shows do this stuff better every week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 1505EDT &QL; 
