A8624 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-LIMITS-BOS &LR;      10-09 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-LIMITS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LIMITS' GOES ALL OUT ON LIFE OF AN ATHLETE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
WITHOUT LIMITS 
Directed and written by: Robert Towne 
Starring: Billy Crudup, Donald Sutherland, Monica Potter, Jeremy
Sisto, Billy Burke, Matthew Lillard, Dean Norris, Gabe Olds, Judith
Ivey, William Mapother, Adam Setliff 
Running time: 118 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You don't have to be a runner to get caught up in Robert Towne's
``Without Limits,'' although the running world is likely to know
everything about the film's subject, Oregon runner Steve
Prefontaine, going in. He was a naturally gifted athlete who ran
with a fierce purity, he set a handful of world records by rushing
to the front of the pack and staying there, and he died at 24 when
a logging truck demolished his sports car.
</P>
<P>
   So why, then, should ``Without Limits'' be so gripping? Apart
from the fact that Towne, the writer and director, draws an
electrifying performance from Billy Crudup as Prefontaine, the
answer is that while Towne is much better known as a writer than as
a director, the film grabs you less with its dialogue than with its
sheer physicality _ not only the running, but the suspension of
time as the camera serves up speed in slow motion and the sight of
thousands of screaming spectators recedes and we breathe the highly
charged air barely separating the runners on the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Limits'' makes us realize that Towne is something of a
long-distance runner, too, having conceived it 10 years ago for Tom
Cruise, who now serves as its producer. The irony in the title of
course is that, like Prefontaine, we are being confronted with
limits at every turn. It is with more gallantry than hubris that
Prefontaine refuses to accept them, even though he's well aware
that the ultimate limits against which he and all runners compete
are the limits of the human body, pumping blood to furiously
pounding muscles as they try to chip a few hundredths of a second
off the best previous time.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the concentration that turns ``Without Limits'' into
such a heart-racing rush is the very concentration that made its
subject the phenomenon he was. To Towne's credit, and Crudup's, the
Prefontaine we get is uncompromising in his all-out approach to
running. Off the track, too, he's a cocky, refreshingly unplacating
hotdog, and even though he's right to seethe at the blatant
injustices of the Amateur Athletic Union, he's hard-headed and
difficult to reach.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally breaking through his star runner's stubbornness
gives Donald Sutherland's coach, Bill Bowerman, something to do
when he isn't tinkering with the waffle-soled running shoe he
invented on Prefontaine's foot, the shoe that became the Nike.
Sutherland superbly expresses the canny long view of an old head as
he fights Prefontaine's nothing-held-back insistence on being a
front-runner instead of saving a last burst for the finish. The
weight of Sutherland's presence enables the film to avoid seeming
an exercise in iconography and turn it into an ongoing tug-of-war
between seasoned experience and raw impulse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Limits'' gives us the achievement and the disarmingly
unpremeditated Prefontaine's flaws alongside his considerable
appeal, and makes us feel the abruptness of his death. Nor do
Crudup's focus and concentration preclude the occasional glint of
sly humor and masochistic drive (at one point he tells Bowerman he
can beat anybody because he can endure more pain than anybody).
``Without Limits'' is miles beyond the previous film,
``Prefontaine,'' which earnestly gave us the same information.
</P>
<P>
   Towne surpasses it with nuances and details that nail down a
world that could easily seem generic. But there's nothing
stereotyped or simplistic about ``Without Limits.'' I had no idea I
could become so engrossed in a film about running. But as ``Without
Limits'' easily carried me across its finish line, I realized that
it worked because it made running seem a subdivision of being
maniacal about something in which you've held nothing back. Nothing
works better in a movie. Or as an approach to moviemaking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
