<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLIM-REVIEW-COP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S ONE TIRED `COP' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CRAIG MARINE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Enjoyment of ``One Tough Cop,'' the new film directed by Bruno
Barreto and starring Stephen Baldwin in a fictionalized account of
real-life New York policeman Bo Dietl, is entirely dependent on the
expectations the viewer brings to the movie.
</P>
<P>
   If you want some gritty mean streets drama about a loner cop
bucking the system, kicking tail and throwing televisions out of
tenement windows _ Bingo, you're there.
</P>
<P>
   If you expect the deeper tale of loyalty, friendship, betrayal,
love and justice promised by the film's publicists, you'll likely
be disappointed. The script by Jeremy Iacone is just too
predictable, and the audience is asked to take too much for granted
about Baldwin/Dietl's righteousness as he stomps people in the name
of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Dietl was a highly decorated New York City cop who amassed more
than 1,400 felony arrest before his retirement in 1985 at the age
of 35. He also had a conviction rate of 98 percent, which is even
more impressive. Dietl is also a relentless self-promoter who
always courted crime writers, wrote his own book on his exploits
and now runs his own private security business.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin's Dietl gives no hint of self-promotion. He has his own
code of the streets, which involves solving crimes by his own
methods, maintaining his friendships with both a boyhood pal who
grew into a major Mafioso and a drunken partner whose $10,000
gambling debt is exceeded only by his $11,000 parking ticket debt.
I don't know about you, but I wouldn't want to be hunting thugs
with a cop partner who doesn't even know how to get out of a
parking ticket.
</P>
<P>
   The plot revolves around an actual case, the vicious rape and
beating of a nun. In real life, Dietl beat the bushes to find the
bad guys. That pretty much also happens in the movie, except
differently.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the police brass don't want Dietl near the case and form a
task force and look like peckerwoods who don't much care about the
victims and would rather keep Dietl down than solve the case.
</P>
<P>
   Toss in some FBI types who also want to nail Dietl because he
won't rat out his mob buddy Richie La Cassa (played by Mike
McGlone), Gina Gershon as La Cassa's mistress Joey who gets to walk
around being Gina Gershon, partner of the year Duke (Chris Penn)
and assorted pimps, players and junkies, and you have a decent cop
movie, a step up from video fare.
</P>
<P>
   But it gets so heavy-handed as we're preached to about morality
and all that stuff _ time better spent killing people or at the
very least smashing their heads against the bar _ and ``One Tough
Cop'' starts to become One Tough Hour-and-a-half.
</P>
<P>
   Barreto, the Brazilian director twice nominated for Oscars for
``Dona Flor and her Two Husbands'' and ``Four Days in September,''
earns his pay by capturing the intensity and feel of the tough New
York streets _ no small feat since most of the movie was filmed in
Toronto.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
