<HEADER>
A8633 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV1     10-09 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV11-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEVERAL CURES FOR BATH WINDOW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, October 11, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have a window in the tub area of my bathroom. I hate
plastic curtains, which seem to be the only solution for keeping
that window from getting soaked during showers. Is there any other
solution that would work?
</P>
<P>
   KEITH DINSMOOR, Braintree, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There are certainly solutions, but not necessarily ones that
would work for you. But what the heck, here they are:
</P>
<P>
   1. Take out the window and wall in the opening. Properly done,
this walling in is invisible. But it will work only if you install
an exhaust fan venting to the outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   2. Take out the windows and put in one with glass blocks. It
will provide light and be watertight, but this installation would
also require an exhaust fan.
</P>
<P>
   3. Paint the window and frame with Zinsser's Perma-White
Mildew-Proof bathroom paint. It claims to resist mildew for up to
five years and to go over virtually any old painted surface.
</P>
<P>
   4. Despite your aversion to plastic curtains, consider a new one
anyway. The new shower curtains and curtains are quite soft and
remain that way; they can be quite attractive, some with patterns,
and are not the old-fasioned plastic that gets stiff and
unmanageable with age.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My black walnut trees are staining my concrete steps. I tried
bleach on without success. How can I clean the steps and keep them
clean?
</P>
<P>
   EDWIN GRAB, Newton
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Try the bleach again, but this time leave it on the steps for
several minutes before scrubbing and rinsing. Wear skin and eye
protection when working with bleach. Or, make a strong solution of
Spic and Span and water, add a cup of bleach, apply this solution,
let it sit a while, then scrub and rinse.
</P>
<P>
   Or, try muriatic acid. This usually does nothing for stains, but
will etch off a very thin layer of concrete, possibly taking the
stains with it. Mix one part acid with one part water, and always
pour acid into water. Paint this solution on the stains, let it sit
a few minutes, then scrub and rinse. Wear skin and eye protection
when working with acid.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever cleans the concrete, you can then seal it with masonry
sealer, which will make the concrete resistant to water and stains.
The sealer must be renewed every year or so.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How can I fill holes in vinyl siding left when wires and
small pipes were removed?
</P>
<P>
   ROBERT LOUT, Holyoke, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Almost any short plug will work: a round-headed stainless
steel bolt, or a plastic toilet bolt will do. You may have to cut
them short so they will fit in the small space behind the siding.
You can also seal the bolts with caulking. Paint them to match the
siding; a round-headed bolt might show as a slight bump, but
otherwise will be invisible.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. All the cedar shingles on my daughter's neighbors' houses in
Hingham have turned black over time. She is concerned about the
white cedar shingles on her new house. How can she prevent that
blackness?
</P>
<P>
   DONALD RUSSELL, Needham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The black is a natural aging and weathering process,
aggravated by mildew. The same could happen to your daughter's
white cedar shingles, designed to turn to an attractive, fairly
even silver color, without treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Painting or staining them is is not the answer. I suggest she
apply a coat of Cabot's bleaching oil, which will provide a light
gray color and enhance the weathering process, making the color a
little more even and the shingles a little more resistant to
mildew.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Piana of Canton, Mass. was another homeowner plagued by
little black dots that appeared on her siding. They did not respond
to bleach, so they were not standard mold or mildew but were rather
sticky dots, like tar.
</P>
<P>
   This is what Cynthia Piana did: ``I replaced a lot of wood chip
mulch around my house with crushed stone, going about two feet from
the foundation outwards. Then I took the dots off with a nylon
scrubber dipped in paint thinner, finally wiping with a dry
cloth.''
</P>
<P>
   You did right, Cynthia Piana; those black dots were probably
spores fired by a particular fungus lurking in that wood chip
mulch. Get rid of the mulch, and the fungus will leave.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I ordered a solar-powered pathway light for my back yard. Now
I am wondering if it will work in New England. It needs several
hours of charging from the sun in order to provide a few hours of
light. It was not expensive so I am not out a lot of money, but
with our overcast days in winter, I wonder if I will be without
light on occasion.
</P>
<P>
   J.S., Belmont, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You probably will, but that is a chance you have to take. All
you can do is try; there are plenty of sunny times in New England
winters, and if you locate it so it gets as much sun (when it is
shining) as possible, you'll get adequate light.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
