<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-HOLY-MAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HOLY MAN' CAN'T PROFIT FROM PROPHET PREMISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
HOLY MAN 
Directed by: Stephen Herek 
Screenplay by: Tom Schulman 
Starring: Eddie Murphy, Jeff Goldblum, Kelly Preston, Robert
Loggia, Jon Cryer, Erin McCormack 
Running time: 114 minutes 
Rated: PG (some language) 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's all the difference in the world between a great premise
and a great screenplay drawn from that premise. Sometimes the
difference turns into a yawning gap, as in ``Holy Man,'' the new
Eddie Murphy vehicle. On paper, it seems a case of a movie long
overdue, as a guru stumbles into a home shopping network and turns
out to be a dynamite pitchman without trying to be. The link
between religion and consumerism, perfected by TV, has begged to be
skewered. But ``Holy Man'' doesn't do it.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise is that Murphy's beatific guru in his long white
tunic is no con man. His mile-wide smile is the real thing. Which,
of course, is what makes his character such a hot salesman. He goes
on camera knocking materialism, and obviously meaning it. But just
when the people in the control booth start going crazy, wondering
what kind of loose cannon they're dealing with, the phones start
ringing and the merchandise starts flying off the shelves because
he has neutralized people's guilt about buying it.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good. But the film doesn't know where to go with
Murphy's spiritual pilgrim. Or even that it ought to go with him,
and tell us more, or at least give him more screen time. What we do
see of him intrigues us, especially after a few party tricks with a
disappearing Rolex watch convince us that he could have been, or
was at one time, a very efficient scam artist. But now, for
whatever reason, the mysterious stranger who calls himself G has
genuinely seen the light.
</P>
<P>
   Fatally relegating G to catalyst status, the film bores us with
a dully earnest struggle for the soul of Jeff Goldblum's TV exec,
who exploits G's selling skills to save his own skin when Robert
Loggia's results-hungry shark buys the station. Goldblum's exec has
another incentive after falling for marketing specialist Kelly
Preston, who pertly but unconvincingly draws the line at selling
one's soul after it dawns on him that his unscheduled house guest,
G, is a human sales machine.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle for the nerdy executive's soul is frankly less than
compelling. The film spins its wheels with predictable prefab
moves, including the usual romantic complications between Goldblum
and Preston, while Murphy's G beamingly looks on, following his
bliss. Too bad he didn't have more of a script to follow. He
certainly shows up ready to do a job, and does what he can with the
stunted material he's offered. But the Murphy comeback express into
family films stalls with ``Holy Man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 1509EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981009.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8639 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-POPS-BOS &LR;      10-09 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-POPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPS RING THE SEASON IN WITH SPIRIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Keith Lockhart's fourth CD with the Boston Pops pictures the
conductor in a Santa Claus suit in front of a Christmas tree
decorated with lollipops. But there is no other acknowledgement of
Christmas on the outside of the album, although nearly all the
music is specifically associated with the sacred or the
department-store window, cash-register aspects of the season.
BMG/RCA Victor has followed the Pops on its misguided journey onto
the thin and slippery ice of political correctness. The outside
appearance of this album eliminates Christmas from ``Holiday
Pops.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately the performances do not, and Lockhart's first
Christmas CD can keep company with its celebrated (and
best-selling) predecessors recorded under Arthur Fiedler and John
Williams, although it's short as an LP, clocking in at 55 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   As in Symphony Hall, one notes and regrets the absence of
anything festively baroque, but there is some very good music of
religious inspiration here, including Bizet's ``Farandole,'' which
incorporates an old French carol; the ``Shepherd's Chorus'' from
Berlioz's ``L'Enfance du Christ,'' tenderly sung by the Tanglewood
Festival Chorus; and Vaughan-Williams's ``Fantasia on Christmas
Carols,'' which features Metropolitan Opera baritone Mark Oswald as
a warm-voiced soloist. The ``Gloria'' by Randol Alan Bass has
become a Lockhart favorite; it sets out to be effective and it is,
but one wishes it had set out to be distinguished as well. Another
Lockhart favorite has been an arrangement of ``Mary's Little Boy
Child'' by Jester Hariston; this song was a hit for Harry Belafonte
30 years ago, and Lockhart learned it from a record by the Harry
Simeone Chorale that was in his father's Christmas-album
collection. A perennial favorite is the choral version of
Leontovich's ``Carol of the Bells.''
</P>
<P>
   From the Pops repertory comes a collection of traditional
wassails arranged by Patrick Hollenbeck (which includes his own
neighborhood contribution, the ``Westland Avenue Wassail,'' and a
nifty episode for early instruments); ``Christmas Time Is Here''
from ``A Charlie Brown Christmas''; ``Good Swing Wenceslas'';
``Frosty All the Way!'' (an arrangement that combines ``Frosty the
Snowman'' and ``Jingle Bells''); Leroy Anderson's ``Sleigh Ride''
(recorded by the Pops for the first time in an arrangement for
chorus and orchestra that uses the lyrics fashioned for the piece
by Mitchell Parish), and ``Merry Christmas, Merry Christmas'' from
John Williams's score for the movie ``Home Alone 2.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the album avoids Symphony Hall's most
frequent seasonal lapse of taste: there are few collisions of
sacred and secular, as if they were the same thing, or equivalent.
``Silver Bells'' may not be the best possible introduction to
``Carol of the Bells,'' but there's a worse blot in the arrangement
that includes the greatest hit from Bob Hope's movie ``The Lemon
Drop Kid'' _ a rather peculiar medley ``Christmas Waltzes'' which
includes ``My Favorite Things'' from ``The Sound of Music,'' which
is not a Christmas waltz; a bit of ``It Came Upon a Midnight
Clear'' incongrously wanders in.
</P>
<P>
   Many Christmas albums are recorded in the summer for seasonal
release; this one was made last Dec. 30 and 31 following a full run
of ``Holiday Pops'' concerts. A personnel list in the album makes
it evident that many members of the Boston Pops chose not to work
on New Year's Eve; their places were confidently taken by freelance
members of the Boston Pops Esplanade Orchestra. Cellist Martha
Babcock contributes an eloquent cello solo to the Vaughan-Williams
work. Lockhart contributes a high energy level and assures a high
level of polish; everything sounds well played and sung, and
producer Shawn Murphy's recorded sound is sumptuous. There's also a
sense of occasion that you don't get at each and every concert in
the ``Holiday Pops'' season. The Tanglewood Festival Chorus, which
records less often than the orchestra, clearly did not view this as
a routine assignment; the chorus sounds wonderful. So does the
children's chorus PALS (Performing Artists at Lincoln School) which
sings the ``Charlie Brown'' selection. (Like Oswald, PALS receives
no credit on the outside of the album; you have to buy it to find
out they're there).
</P>
<P>
   The formula represented by this album clearly works; a ``Holiday
Pops'' tour takes Lockhart and the Esplanade Orchestra to arenas in
17 cities; the Symphony Hall dates are Dec. 15-24 and 26-30.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart contributes breezy notes written in the style of a
family Christmas letter, with lots of exclamation points. He refers
directly to Christmas at least a dozen times, so at least he knew
what kind of album he was making.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
