<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-MANNERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BAD MANNERS' JUST AN ACADEMIC EXERCISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WALTER ADDIEGO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An academic couple and their house guests have a long, boozy
encounter filled with verbal sparring, sexual tension, shifting
alliances, humiliations and revelations. ``Who's Afraid of Virginia
Woolf?'' _ right? But it's also a spot-on summary of ``Bad
Manners,'' Jonathan Kaufer's new dark comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Both movies offer a curdled view of academia, lots of nasty
personal gamesmanship and the pleasure of watching talented casts
at work. But the likeness ends there. If ``Virginia Woolf'' is a
dissertation on the woes of modern marriage, ``Bad Manners'' is
more of an undergraduate essay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manners'' is based on David Gilman's ``Ghost in the Machine,''
which debuted at Chicago's Steppenwolf Theater in 1993 and also ran
off-Broadway. Gilman adapted the play for director Kaufer, whose
only previous feature was the 1982 picture ``Soup for One.''
</P>
<P>
   I haven't seen the play, but Kaufer's notes say the film's
producers wanted the movie to have ``more humor,'' and that it was
decided the picture would resolve a key question the play left
unanswered. These are not encouraging signs.
</P>
<P>
   The set-up: Nancy (Bonnie Bedelia) is a successful professor
living in Cambridge, Mass.; her husband, Wes (David Strathairn), a
teacher of comparative religion, is upset at having been denied
tenure. He's in no mood for guests, especially one of his wife's
old boyfriends, Matt (Saul Rubinek), a musicologist lecturing at
Harvard. Upping the ante is the presence of Matt's young paramour,
the sexually provocative Kim (Caroleen Feeney), a computer expert.
</P>
<P>
   Matt says he's discovered a quotation from a Martin Luther hymn
in the middle of a recent computer-generated musical composition, a
finding he expects to stun the music world. The acerbic Wes
suspects a hoax, and isn't shy about saying so. Meanwhile, Kim adds
to the strains on her middle-aged hosts' marriage by toying with
Wes, and suggesting that Nancy might enjoy a fling or two with
handsome young students. But the real fun begins when Wes finds a
$50 bill missing from his wallet, and is convinced Kim took it.
</P>
<P>
   The characters jockey for dominance, fret about the missing $50
and flirt with betrayal. There's plenty of trouble to go around,
and much seems to lead back to sultry Kim. But dramas of this sort
continually tease us: Who is actually doing what to whom?
</P>
<P>
   Bedelia (``Heart Like a Wheel,'' ``Die Hard''), who hasn't had
the parts she deserves, is fine here. Strathairn, probably best
known for his early roles in John Sayles' movies, offers a sharp
portrayal of a conflicted and vulnerable academic. Canadian actor
Rubinek, star of Kaufer's ``Soup for One,'' is good as an arrogant
type begging to be taken down, while Feeney is a convincing sexual
troublemaker.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Kim voices a professional interest in meta-games
(games about games), which suggests Kaufer is shooting for
something ambitious that he can't really pull off. ``Bad Manners''
has its moments, and the characters get off a few wicked zingers,
but it seems secondhand. Besides the watered-down Albee, there are
distant (and I stress ``distant'') echoes of Pinter, especially
``The Homecoming.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a particularly challenging kind of drama, with its
emphasis on verbal power struggles and strategic withholding of key
information. It surely doesn't help that the director felt
constrained to lighten things up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 1512EDT &QL; 
