<HEADER>
A8645 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-VOLLENWEIDER-BO     10-09 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-VOLLENWEIDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARPS OF MANY VOICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Swiss harpist Andreas Vollenweider is starting his first solo
tour, but he's bringing enough instruments to supply a large
orchestra. He'll move around to play gothic harp, Celtic harp, kora
(African harp), cheng (Chinese harp), wind chimes, gongs, piano,
accordion, flute, soprano saxophone, and, yes, tuned salad bowls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have more stuff on the road than ever before, because of all
these custom-made instruments,'' says Vollenweider, the New Age
pioneer who headlines Jordan Hall in Boston Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he's calling it his ``naked tour.'' He explains: ``I just
finished an extensive tour with a 90-piece orchestra and a lot of
guest musicians. So this is a kind of naked tour.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also his attempt to be a musical troubadour who can still
connect with the ancient art of storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm trying to do is not just play a solo concert but have
people create stories in their mind,'' he says. ``I'm following the
ancient history of storytelling, because by listening to
storytellers is how people had their imaginations trained. The
listener is still the key element.''
</P>
<P>
   Vollenweider, who has been a New Age icon since his 1989 album
``Dancing with the Lion,'' has so far only brought his solo tour to
a few opera houses in Europe and to a theater inside a volcanic
cave on the Canary Islands. If you get the impression this man is
an adventurer who eschews boundaries, you're right.
</P>
<P>
   The new tour ``is more of a theatrical project, actually, so I
also need some theatrical lights to make it work,'' he says. ``And
I have sound effects to tie the pieces together. I have pedals and
triggers all over the stage for that. And sometimes I could be
triggering something very subtle, like you might hear people
walking or hear a door closing.''
</P>
<P>
   Vollenweider also has a MIDI (computerized) setup on his harp to
color the sound and add more sonic shadings. And the instruments
will range from a classical harp to an African kora, which is a
gourd covered with goatskin that has 24 strings. ``It sounds very
raw,'' he says. ``And I also play a Chinese harp, which is
horizontally played. You can even play blues on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The night's repertoire will come from past Vollenweider albums,
as well as his new one, ``Kryptos,'' which is designed to be a
musical journey into mythological lands, exemplified by the song
titles ``Morgana's Place,'' ``Herme's Wedding,'' and ``Trigon.''
The album includes guest appearances from South African vocal group
Ladysmith Black Mambazo and from singer/violinist Mindy Jostyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stories are there in the music, but it's not my job to
make things clear,'' says Vollenweider, sounding more mystical as
the interview goes along. ``I want to confuse people. It's like
Surrealism, to make people see things from another angle. To me,
nothing is clear and it gets less clear every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to look at the undefinable,'' he adds. ``We destroy so
many things by trying to describe them. I want to step out of the
restrictions of reality, and start with the imagination to expand
our vision and our culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all sounds very intellectual, but it's not meant to be,''
he says with a laugh. ``It's meant to be one flowing experience.
... It's like a movie without a picture. I want it to be a 3-D
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Vollenweider has been known to American audiences for the
past decade (Carly Simon became one of his biggest boosters and
helped gain him national attention), he's been touring in Europe
for more than 20 years. He has often played up to 250 concerts a
year with his regular band, so stepping out on his own marks quite
a departure. He'll rejoin his band in the future, but for now, he's
relishing the solo tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm enjoying it immensely,'' he says. ``I feel totally free.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 1513EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
