<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8650 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-UNMADE-BOS &LR;      10-09 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-UNMADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
URBAN SINGLES ALONE IN THE BIG CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
UNMADE BEDS 
Directed and written by: Nicholas Barker 
Starring: Brenda Monte, Aimee Copp, Michael De Stefano, Mikey
Russo 
Running time: 105 minutes 
Unrated 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It won't do to denounce the voyeurism that drives Nicholas
Barker's ``Unmade Beds'' because the truth is that it hooks us from
the start. It's not quite fact, not quite fiction. British
documentarian and anthropologist Barker found four veterans of the
New York City singles scene, taped hours of interviews with them,
then fashioned for each a script of their lives and had them play
themselves on camera. You keep hoping they won't meet one another
and ruin with contrived interaction the isolation they have in
common. Mercifully, they don't. Not for nothing does the film take
its visual cue from an Edward Hopper reproduction on a wall. It's
attuned to a similar world of urban loneliness, never losing a
chance to portray the solitary confinement the city's grids impose
upon us.
</P>
<P>
   What the four have in common is the conviction that it's the
world that's failing them, never the reverse, that if they just
hang in there and keep doing the same things, sooner or later life
will click for them. Two, a former lapdancer named Brenda Monte and
a recently fired security expert and unproduced screenplay writer
named Mikey Russo, proclaim themselves highly desirable. Voluptuous
Brenda, who needs money to catch up with the mortgage payments on
her condo, wants an old man to dish out the cash she needs and
excpect nothing in return. In the film's comic high point, she
examines her scantily-clad body in a full-length mirror and doesn't
like the changes beginning to arrive, but is bluntly honest about
confronting them.
</P>
<P>
   She perhaps protests too much. Her world consists of men
inflamed with sexual longings for her, to which she remains
scornfully aloof. She loves her pet dog, announces that it's going
to have to wait for an operation it needs until she raises the $400
to pay for it, but blithely rationalizes that it's OK to steal dog
food from the supermarket because God imposed her dog's appetite on
her. As she tools around the city in her car, being photographed
from the passenger seat, she's a bawdy mix of candor and
unapologetic self-interest. Utterly without self-pity and bristling
with survival skills, she steals more than Alpo. She also steals
the film.
</P>
<P>
   Russo, who at 54 refuses to bring up to the conscious level the
fact that his cool swinger routine is looking more than a little
sad and desperate, is very much into role-playing and
self-dramatization. The rejected screenplays he writes all involve
the romantic capers of thinly disguised versions of himself. He's
no Redford or Newman type, he says, telling us nothing we haven't
already grasped. He sees himself more as a Nicholson or Harvey
Keitel kind of guy. For him the world is divided into babes and
mutts. And he prides himself on never suffering mutts for long.
When a blind date doesn't meet his standard, he has himself beeped,
and skips out.
</P>
<P>
   Aimee Copp and Michael De Sefano harbor no illusions about their
attractiveness. Aimee, 28, is under pressure to marry before she's
30. She's funny, self-deprecating, and bright. She also weighs 225
pounds, a fact that brings her to tears when her thinner girlfriend
accuses her of being in denial about the need to lose weight. All
she can find are men who want to fetishize her because of her size.
Michael, pushing 40, is increasingly unable to keep the lid on his
bitterness over being rejected because he's five-feet-four. Tired
of deflecting queries about whether he's gay, he lapses into
homophobic remarks about women hanging around gay choreographers
and make-up artists instead of throwing themselves to heterosexual
companions. Yet he comes across as an essentially decent guy who's
just been turned down too many times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unmade Beds'' leaves unanswered the question of when clarity
becomes cruelty and whether Barker's exploitation of the four
singles becomes acceptable in view of their complicity in inviting
several kinds of exposure, or unacceptable in view of the film's
highlighting tendency to present them as freaks. At times their
yearnings seem pathetic and self-deluding; at other times, they
seem spunky and vigorously resilient. We never see the presumably
disastrous dates they go on. We see only the selves they present to
the camera. In the end, the knowledge that Barker has manipulated
the four is likely to prove more unsettling than anything any of
them say or do. Either way, ``Unmade Beds'' is a brash, vigorous,
sometimes surprisingly moody study of four strikeout artists
ensnared by their hangups, more alone than they want to be in the
big city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
