<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETER WOLF REDISCOVERS HIS SOUL IN R&AMP;B 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At long last comes a Peter Wolf album that does justice to his
J. Geils Band legacy and to his disciple's love of classic soul.
Wolf's new album, ``Fool's Parade,'' is without a doubt the best
and most personal of his solo records since Geils broke up 14 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is just a beginning for me,'' says Wolf. ``I
worked into something that was always in front of me, but I never
realized it until I started `Fool's Parade.' It comes out of a
great love for the R&AMP;B tradition, but is an attempt to make it
relevant to the present time.''
</P>
<P>
   The album comes out Oct. 20, while the first single, ``Turnin'
Pages,'' has just been released. Sings Wolf: ``My life's going on,
turnin' pages.'' Welcome to the future _ and it's an uncanny
updating of the past. Just as Keith Richards did on his solo album,
``Talk is Cheap,'' Wolf brings fresh energy to the tight-knit
ensemble sound born in Memphis and Muscle Shoals. It's also a sound
perfected from his days in the Geils Band and from such past highs
as singing with Aretha Franklin and serving as MC on this summer's
``Royal Soul Revue'' tour, featuring Percy Sledge, Carla Thomas,
and Lloyd Price.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned from the masters,'' Wolf says of that tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I started to make the record, I also went back to listen to
a lot of Stax records (from Memphis) and Muscle Shoals (Alabama)
records. I listened to Arthur Alexander, who did `You Better Move
On,' which the Stones did, and `Anna,' which the Beatles first did.
And I listened to a lot of Al Green and Aretha and Don Covay. And
then I came across this Dan Penn record _ he wrote `I'm Your
Puppet,' `Dark End of the Street,' and `The Letter.' I started
re-reading Peter Guralnick's book, `Sweet Soul Music.' It was all a
revelation _ and I wanted to create that vibe for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf succeeds admirably. His new album opens confessionally with
the disarming ``Long Way Back Again,'' in which he sings, ``I spent
my whole life chasing rainbows/I just hope there's something
left.'' There's at least plenty of funk left, witness ``The Cold
Heart of the Stone,'' a reminiscence of Cambridge in the '60s when
buddy Van Morrison lived on Green Street and the two men shared
inspiration and craziness.
</P>
<P>
   As the song goes: ``Green Street full of memories/wild hearts
doing what they please ... every night was a fool's parade/we'd get
so lost in the plans we made/we were cracking up, we were breaking
down/ we were filled with fire, burning up the town/we lived it
all, right down to the bone/to the cold heart of the stone.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar themes are espoused in the songs ``All Torn Up''
(``nobody wants to be alone at closing time''), the rocking ``Ride
Lonesome, Ride Hard'' (``you got to go where the road is taking
you''), and the mid-tempo funk of ``Roomful of Angels'' (``I need a
roomful of angels to see me through tonight'').
</P>
<P>
   To make the record, Wolf gathered a close ensemble that includes
musician friends Kenny White (who co-produced the record with him),
Boston guitarist Duke Levine (who tours with Mary Chapin
Carpenter), keyboardist Leon Pendarvis (who has played with Stevie
Wonder), background vocalist Ada Dyer (who also does a great duet
on ``Pleasing to Me''), and the Uptown Horns, who had toured with
the Geils Band and Rolling Stones.
</P>
<P>
   An eerie irony came when Wolf realized the studio he used _ Sear
Sound in Manhattan _ was formerly the Hit Factory, where the Geils
Band recorded ``Give It to Me'' in the early '70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had changed the studio around and I didn't realize it,''
says Wolf. ``But there was something very rewarding that, after all
these years, I was still in the race, fulfilling my passion. And I
felt exactly the same as when the Geils Band was in that studio
doing `Give It to Me.' We were trying to take some roots music _
Titus Turner songs and reggae songs and blues songs and R&AMP;B songs _
and make it work in a way that made sense to us. And that's exactly
what I was trying to do now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to take a vibe and a mood and use the knowledge that I
had to create a new sensibility,'' adds Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through trials and tribulations like many people,
and through numerous loves and heartbreaks, and many a sleepless
night. And I've gotten to travel and see the world and meet some of
the greatest artists from Tennessee Williams to Harold Pinter to
Muddy Waters to Howlin' Wolf to Don Covay. I've spent hours and
hours drinking with Sam Phillips or sitting in a hotel room with
Van Morrison and Freddie Hubbard. All those people and those
midnight drives sort of ended up on `Fool's Parade.' For me, it's
just the beginning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
