<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-HOLY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HOLY MAN' DOESN'T HAVE A PRAYER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By G. ALLEN JOHNSON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eddie Murphy and Jeff Goldblum, two actors one doesn't usually
associate with low energy, star in a living retread, ``Holy Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Part ``Network,'' part ``Truman Show'' and fully boring, ``Holy
Man'' asks us to believe that a spiritual man can help sell
products on a home-shopping channel by telling the viewers not to
buy products, and this works so well that in a matter of weeks he
is on the cover of Time, Newsweek, USA Today and featured on
television shows.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy plays the enigmatically named G, a man on an unspecified
religious pilgrimage who is sidetracked by the two top executives
of the shopping channel, Ricky (Goldblum) and Kate (Kelly Preston).
They have a flat tire; G strolls across the highway, magically
avoiding the crowded, on-rushing traffic. He's so loving and
positive, he thanks a group of rednecks who pelt him with a paper
cup full of soda for not using a can.
</P>
<P>
   G decides to stick around because he senses Ricky, a
self-absorbed egotist, needs spiritual assistance. In order to save
Ricky's soul, G decides to sell his soul _ hawking products to keep
Ricky's boss (Robert Loggia) from firing him.
</P>
<P>
   Writer Tom Schulman, who won an Oscar for writing ``Dead Poets
Society,'' and director Stephen Herek (with a resume as diverse as
``Bill and Ted's Excellent Adventure'' and ``Mr. Holland's Opus'')
obviously see G as the cure for an ailing, materialistic society.
He becomes the anti-Howard Beale: He's happy as hell, and he's not
going to take it anymore. Yet if he's truly making a connection,
how can the network's sales skyrocket?
</P>
<P>
   It's also troublesome that Murphy, a generally charismatic
actor, is downright dull here. He and Goldblum are curiously flat
in their line readings; they don't seem convinced by the story
they're asked to act out, and with good reason.
</P>
<P>
   The problems stem from an overall softness of the picture.
Because the filmmakers want to appeal to a broad section of the
audience, they never explore the spirituality or religious
philosophy of G. In fact, never does he mention God or any other
type of deity. During a montage examining the G phenomenon,
priests, rabbis, imams and other religious leaders try to claim him
as their own, as if he were an enigma like Chance in ``Being
There.''
</P>
<P>
   He looks like a Buddhist, with his shaved head and flowing white
robe, but all he ever says to his viewing public are variations on
the ``Look around you, take time out to enjoy life'' spiel.
Occasionally, he bends down to smell the grass.
</P>
<P>
   To make sure we get it, Herek gives us villains _ Loggia as the
greedy, cutthroat network owner and Erik McCormack as a conniver
after Ricky's job _ as one-note as Snidely Whiplash, and a damsel
in distress in Preston, who's one more woman in a Hollywood film
waiting for her man (Ricky) to come around.
</P>
<P>
   And when that man does come around, he gives the most
self-serving, ridiculous speech that's hardly the embodiment of
selflessness _ one more example of a film that tries to have it
both ways.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
