<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8674 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV11-BO     10-09 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV11-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONDA REINVENTS THE MINI WITH THE 1999 ODYSSEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  
 (For release Sunday, October 11, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R.WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ There has been considerable discussion over just who
invented the minivan. Some would credit the Germans _ remember the
Volkswagen Microbus? It was not exactly a mini, about the size of
some standard American vans of the time, and with seats for seven
or so, but its underpowered rear-mounted engine was mini easy on
gas.
</P>
<P>
   Others favor the Japanese who shortly after the end of World War
II had mini delivery vans, rear-drive little boxes suitable for
narrow Japanese streets, later exported to the United States as
pasenger vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   But the front-drive, carlike mini was a Chrysler idea and a
Honda executive cheerfully credited Chrysler Corp. with the
invention of the minivan _ on the occasion of Honda's introduction
of its reinvention of the mini, the 1999 Odyssey, a ``no
compromise, take-no-prisoners vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Odyssey is very different from the old Odyssey _ which
isn't exactly old in the grand scheme of things. In some ways the
new Odyssey is different from anything else on wheels. It is the
largest vehicle ever produced by Honda and, unlike the old Odyssey,
it is built on this side of the world, in a new plant in Alliston,
Ont., an hour's drive from downtown Toronto. Honda marked the
occasion of the birth of the new van by showing off the birthplace
and the vehicular infant. The plant is impressive and Toronto is a
beautiful city, but for this columnist the real lure was the chance
to drive the new Odyssey across Canada and back to the Globe. The
resulting 1,000 or so miles behind the wheel of an Odyssey lends
support to the Honda claim that it is the ``new standard'' in vans.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the Odyssey is a 3.5-liter ``variable'' horsepower
V-6 mated with a 4-speed automatic transmission. Variable? With
premium-grade fuel, the new engine puts out 210 horsepower; with
regular grades, the horsepower drops to 205 _ believe me, you can
live with that.
</P>
<P>
   But the new Odyssey isn't a van body with sedan doors like the
old model, which, by the way, Honda will continue to build and sell
in Japan. On the basic $23,200 LX, sliding doors on each side offer
passenger access; on the $25,800 EX (same price as the '98, but
with ``more stuff,'' Honda says), both doors are powered, operated
by a pair of switches on the left side of the dash or by pulling
the handle. But wait, there's more _ the seats.
</P>
<P>
   Up front is a pair of buckets with a folding tray table between
_ when folded it allows access to the rear. Behind that is a pair
of seats separated by aisle, with another folding tray table
between. You prefer a bench? Unlatch one seat and push it over; you
now have a two-passenger bench with aisle space on the side. Either
seat is easily removable by an average person (or a slightly
arthritic auto columnist). In the rear is what Honda calls the
``magic seat,'' a three-passenger bench that folds and disappears
into the floor leaving a flat cargo area suitable for hauling
4(MUL)8 sheets of plywood inside the van. Folding eliminates the
need for removal to convert to cargo, a three-passenger seat is a
handful for two.
</P>
<P>
   When it's in use, there is a well behind the rear seat _ what it
folds into _ that increases cargo area available for luggage. So
where's the spare? Inside the van under the floor between the front
and second rows.
</P>
<P>
   Moving the seats requires no fussing with seatbelt anchors;
there are shoulder belts for seven and head rests for all. Storage?
The glove box isn't much but there are drawers, bins and plenty of
places to fit stuff. And enough cupholders for a convention.
</P>
<P>
   So, after a day of tooling around Toronto in each of the two
models, visiting the factory, and listening to the spiel, it is
finally time to venture forth for home in an Odyssey EX _ north on
Route 11A to Highway 401, the longest stretch of freeway in a
single political enclave stretching 510 miles from the shadow of
Detroit across Ontario to the Quebec border. It is excellent
roadway, divided, with a 100 kilometer (62 miles) per hour speed
limit. The Canadians make me feel right at home by totally ignoring
that despite frequent signs announcing horrendous fines.
</P>
<P>
   The routine is: Drive 100 miles, then stop and get out of the
car to walk around, eat, etc. In the middle of nowhere in
particular, with traffic highballing at around 80 _ that's miles _
I spot this guy in a suit on a bridge. Why does a man in a suit
hang around bridges in the boondocks? Answer: Speed trap. I
instinctively let off the gas approaching the bridge; a quarter
mile beyond are police cruisers and officers pulling people over.
</P>
<P>
   A good part of the way runs along the north shore of Lake
Ontario, close enough to see that inland fresh-water sea. At the
Quebec border, the good road gives way to the Canadian version of
Route 1 and the Big Dig _ and it is rush hour in Montreal. Creep,
crawl and discover that Quebecois in cars are a lot like Boston
area folk _ that is to say, nutballs at the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Approaching Sherbrooke, I miss the road best taken, find myself
in a strange city as night falls, somewhat uncertain of my route
... I violate the adult male driving handbook and enter an auto
parts store seeking navigational aid. They speak French here; I do
not. But they are friendly, helpful and a gentleman in a white coat
gives me precise directions through town to Route 212. From there
it is a plasant romp through little villages to the customs post at
Coburn Gore in northwest Maine, 498.2 miles from downtown Toronto.
The customs agent climbs in, pretends not to be looking around in
search of smuggled five-gallon toilets, checks my passport, asks my
business and bids me good night.
</P>
<P>
   From here it is south along Route 27 with lakes shimmering in
the moonlight on my right, tall spooky pines on my left; 52 miles
later I pull into Kingfield, Maine _ enough driving for one day, I
think.
</P>
<P>
   It is another 143 miles home, then 86 miles to the Globe, and
... the driving continues. For 850 miles checked, the van, EPA
rated 18 miles per gallon city, 26 highway, is delivering 22.47
m.p.g.
</P>
<P>
   The '99 Odyssey is a lot of classy van, nice handling, quick
enough and easy on gas; Chrysler and Ford have real competition
here.
</P>
<P>
   I like this van _ I like it a lot. What took these guys so long
to do this?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
