<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUE-ANGELS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVY'S BLUE ANGELS RELY ON `BETTY' AND STRICT TRAINING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JACOB H. FRIES  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When you are flying upside down at 500 mph and a
problem comes up, it's nice to have a soothing presence nearby.
</P>
<P>
   For the Blue Angels pilots who are flying the Navy's F-18
Hornets over the San Francisco Bay this weekend, ``Betty'' _ or
rather her voice _ provides such a presence.
</P>
<P>
   Betty is a computer-generated female voice that soothingly
informs pilots of any major problems, such as low altitude or an
engine fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be a grumpy old man talking, but no one liked
that,'' said Petty Officer 2nd Class Rick Boswell, a Blue Angels
crew chief. ``The designers felt that men would rather listen to a
woman tell them what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty is just part of the on-board computer system that runs the
Navy's premier jet, the first to fill both the fighter and attacker
roles equally well.
</P>
<P>
   The $18 million Hornet redefined what pilots are able to do in
the air and how they do it, Boswell said. Compared with past Blue
Angels planes _ the Hellcat in 1946 and, later, the Skyhawk _ there
really is no comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's night and day,'' Boswell said. ``If you go back 30 or 40
years, people would have thought this plane wizardry.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hornet reaches speeds of more than 1,200 mph and can roll
over in a second, Boswell said. Every part of the plane was
constructed to create more lift, enabling the plane to fly for
extended periods with its wings vertical to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco's Fleet Week shows this weekend, the aerobatic
planes will approach the sound barrier, about 700 mph at sea level,
but will not break it.
</P>
<P>
   What makes these planes so special is what they have inside,
said Master Chief Petty Officer Scott Carmean. In the past, a
pilot's controls relied on cables to activate hydraulics in the
wings and tail. Now, a computer runs interference between the pilot
and rudders, making adjustments almost simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   When a pilot wants to fly up and to the right, it is the
computer that decides which rudder adjustments would best do that,
said Capt. George Dom, lead pilot for the squad.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Betty, who shows up during serious in-flight
problems, a diagnostic computer tells mechanics what is wrong on
the ground and monitors how hard a landing is, Boswell said.
Mechanics then just have to refer to the manual.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually more like fixing a Volkswagen than you might
think,'' Boswell said. ``This plane was designed to be
maintenance-friendly. It's really quite self-sufficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the Hornet, if mechanics replaced, say, a rudder, they
had to rely on trial and error to align it, Boswell said. Now, like
so many other components, the computer takes care of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Funny thing is that this is '70s technology,'' Boswell said.
``This plane, one of the best in the world, is actually slower than
a 286 computer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Angels have been flying Hornets since 1986 and will
continue using some version of the supersonic plane for at least 30
more years, Carmean said. The Navy uses a newer version of the
Hornet and is testing two others.
</P>
<P>
   But do not get the idea that these planes fly themselves, Dom
said. Technology changes, but demands on pilots do not.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots often bring their planes closer than 2 feet to one
another, Dom said, and that takes extraordinary eye-hand
coordination, as well as a great knowledge of the technology.
</P>
<P>
   Also, all Blue Angels pilots must be physically fit, because
they are exposed to extreme G-forces with each twist and turn, Dom
said. The flights are so demanding that a G-suit, which prevents
blood from leaving the pilot's head, is not completely effective.
</P>
<P>
   `We fly six days a week and nothing we do becomes routine or
normal,'' Dom said. ``One single moment of inattention could be
disastrous. Flying like this is very unforgiving of complacency. We
respect that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The six Blue Angels pilots use a stationary reference point to
precisely coordinate their maneuvers, Carmean said. Commands given
by Dom are the only communication with pilots while they are in the
air, Carmean said. It takes weeks of flying together for the pilots
to become familiar with the rhythm of each syllable in Dom's
orders.
</P>
<P>
   But while in formation, all the planes have an escape plan,
Carmean said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something goes wrong, the pilots have to resist their
natural instinct, which would be to bank up and away,'' Carmean
said. ``Here, that's dangerous. They're so close that the pilot
would run the wing of his plane into the tail of the lead plane.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Angels' last fatal crash was in 1985 during a
performance at Niagara Falls. The cause of the crash was not
determined.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two pilots have died in the 52-year history of the Blue
Angels. No spectators have been injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to our safety is that we never forget what we're
doing,'' said Dom, who has been flying for 20 years. ``There's no
such thing as an average day at work. We don't fear it, though. You
couldn't fly like that. But still, we can't forget the
possibilities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
