<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEAP-TRICK TV TEASERS RILE VIEWERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Notes and quotes, this and that:
</P>
<P>
   TV news folk call it ``teasing.'' E-mailer Annie Blanco labels
it ``pure laziness.'' I call it simply a clever tool of
manipulation.
</P>
<P>
   It begins with a grim-faced anchor delivering a nugget from the
usual bag of 10 o'clock tragedy: murders, drug busts, fires,
suicides, the vegetable oil that kills, you know the drill. This
instance: An anchor on Dallas-Fort Worth's NBC station, KXAS, pops
up between commercials to tell us about ``a missing boy in
Denton,'' and say we'll be provided with ``the latest at 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, no. You stay tuned only to see that KXAS doesn't even lead
with the missing kid story. (They go with Troy Aikman instead.) The
missing boy? Turns out to be no story at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boy came home,'' Annie writes. He'd been there since 7
that evening, in fact. KXAS airs footage of the ``reunion,''
telling us that, well, the kid was just next door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the bottom line is ratings, but what about respect?''
writes Annie, who says she felt embarrassingly duped. ``All Channel
5 did was pat themselves on the back (in their report) for covering
their frivolous story earlier and prompting a neighbor to phone the
family saying the kid was over at her house. This is no more a
story than someone missing a cat.''
</P>
<P>
   If it weren't so troubling, if we didn't rely so heavily on
local news for our information, it would be comical. According to a
media survey conducted by Dallas-based Audience Research &AMP;
Development, viewers tune in to local TV an average of 3.8 times
per week. Radio and newspapers tied for second at 3.2 times,
followed by network news programs at 3, cable at 2.2, TV
newsmagazines at 1.4, print news mags at 0.6, and the Internet,
0.6.
</P>
<P>
   TV news teasers are merely the way to keep us from flipping
channels, even if it means stretching the truth and playing on our
worst fears.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad but true, parents are constantly worried about their
children and often act quickly when they feel their child is
missing,'' Annie says. ``But this is just pure laziness. We deserve
more.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   $565,000.
</P>
<P>
   That's what it costs for a 30-second commercial on NBC's ``ER.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Caller Cathy Riner ``hates ``Martial Law.'' ``Just hate it. I
can't think of anyone who would want to watch that trash.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS can. Admittedly, the desperate network is going after more
males and a more ``urban'' audience this season. Which means more
shows like ``Martial Law,'' a campy drama with lots of kung-fu
fighting, and fewer like ``Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Quinn'' simply didn't fit into CBS' long-term plans. In
ratings, ``Quinn'' matched ``Early Edition,'' which now occupies
its time slot. But ``Early Edition'' is set in Chicago and recently
added sex appeal (Kristy Swanson) to the cast.
</P>
<P>
   CBS makes it clear that older adults or female viewers are
passe. But give them time. TV programming decisions are based on
fear. Change comes with that fear. In January, CBS chief Les
Moonves told critics how happy the network was to ``embrace its
baby boomers.'' And if the other networks didn't want 49-year-olds,
``we'll happily take you.''
</P>
<P>
   Moonves six months later: ``We need to get younger.''
</P>
<P>
   Get your Jane Seymour fix from ``Quinn'' reruns at 8 p.m. CDT
weekdays on Pax TV/Channel 68.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   E-mailer B.J. Graham on the gay guy/straight gal sitcom ``Will &AMP;
Grace'': ``Either they sent you the wrong tape, or you're in dire
need of a permanent vacation. It was awful.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   E-mailer Natalie Hernandez on ``Will &AMP; Grace'': ``Were you right
on. This is the funniest thing I've seen in years.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   And this from Susan Geist about Pax TV, the new family-friendly
network.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for (Pax TV's) hidden agenda, I think (your criticism) may
be a little unfair,'' she writes. ``I am far from a regular
churchgoer, but I have become tired of some of the daily offerings
by some of the other networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``So please give this new network a fair chance and realize that
there are many of us without cable (and I bet there are more than
you realize) who are looking forward to an alternative. We are not
all twentysomethings.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
