<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-GROWTH-$ADV11-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO-GROWTH-$ADV11 
 
SPARKED BY NEW AUTO PLANT, MEXICO FARM TOWN LEADS BOOM IN
GUANAJUATO STATE 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 11) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SILAO, Mexico _ With scores of new factories planned in the next
few years, this once-quiet farm town prepares to rocket into the
global industrial future.
</P>
<P>
   New sheet-metal buildings that will hold some of those
manufacturing plants sprout amid the corn and bean fields on the
southeast edge of town. Construction crews pave roads, lay sewer
and water lines and build houses for middle-class managers. Several
business hotels are in the works.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost our tranquility, perhaps,'' says Nicolas
Villagomez, a burly 36-year-old builder who has been Silao's public
works director since January.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we see a great future here,'' he says as he pores over
diagrams of a city arising.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its location deep within Mexico, 600 miles from the
Texas border, Silao has joined the mostly northern Mexican
communities being pulled to prosperity by the North American Free
Trade Agreement, or NAFTA, which within another decade will tightly
bind the economies of Mexico, the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Five years into the onset of the trade pact, few regions of
Mexico have been transformed as quickly as Silao and the
surrounding industrial corridor in the central state of Guanajuato.
Blessed with good highways, rail lines and a new international
airport, the region's prospects contrast with those of impoverished
states of Mexico's South.
</P>
<P>
   Within the next four years, Villagomez says, the population of
this run-down farm city will double to about 300,000. Some 150 new
factories will set up shop to serve the General Motors plant here
and a Nissan assembly plant in the nearby city of Aguascalientes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect there to be a new Silao existing right next to the
old one,'' says Villagomez as he outlines the planned route of a
beltway around the city.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,000 people already work at the GM plant, which
exports about 80 percent of the light trucks and sport utility
vehicles it produces to the United States. Another 8,000 jobs will
be created in the new factories expected to open, Villagomez says.
</P>
<P>
   ``There never was much opportunity in Silao before,'' says
Alfredo Gomez, 24, as he trudges home from his $10-a-day shift at
the GM plant. ``Now there are a lot of jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Silao itself only recently began to industrialize, the
community anchors a burgeoning 75-mile industrial corridor that
cuts across the flat plains of Guanajuato. The shoe manufacturing
center of Leon holds the northwest corner, with the
textile-producing city of Irapuato at the center, and the
agricultural-industrial hub of Celaya in the southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Still, by many measures, Guanajuato (Gwahn-nah-HWAHT-o) remains
as backward as anywhere in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The state's average education levels rank below the national
average of six years and more than half of its adult population
never finished primary school, according to the Mexican
government's census bureau. Per capita income of $2,600 in 1996,
the latest year for which statistics are available, stood at just
70 percent of Mexico's national average, about equal to that of
Guerrero state in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Guanajuato has long been a major source of illegal immigration
to the United States, with as much as 10 percent of its work force
living north of the border.
</P>
<P>
   To the state's advantage, more than half of Mexico's 95 million
people live within 250 miles of its major cities, giving its
industries access to domestic consumers. Irrigation on huge
stretches of flat land make agriculture more productive than in
more mountainous states in the South and the deserts farther north.
</P>
<P>
   But state officials have decided that the global economy holds
Guanajuato's future and are scrambling to boost exports.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Vicente Fox, who hopes to run for president of Mexico on
the center-right National Action Party ticket in 2000, has made the
global economy a key theme of his 4-year-old administration. Fox
has led business delegations to the United States, Europe and Asia
seven times so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been able to take good advantage of NAFTA,'' says Arturo
Sanchez Castellanos, 32, an accountant and business leader from a
politically powerful family who heads the Leon chapter of Coparmex,
Mexico's premier business council. ``There are many companies that
had never exported before and now are.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the case in Leon, which has been Mexico's footwear
capital for more than 60 years, producing half the country's 200
million pairs of shoes annually.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the shoes made in Leon are sold in Mexico. But exports,
primarily to the United States, have increased from 5 million pairs
a year before NAFTA took effect in 1994 to an estimated 30 million
pairs this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trade agreement has brought a lot of opportunities but we
haven't yet taken full advantage of it,'' says David Gonzalez, the
president of the footwear manufacturers association, whose own
company makes and sells women's dress shoes. ``We could be
exporting twice as much as we are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(But) I think there is a dawning realization among businesses
that they should look for markets elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   As Guanajuato pushes into foreign markets, analysts and local
business owners say, the state relies on a tradition of
self-reliance and resourcefulness often lacking in other parts of
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   For example, almost all of Leon's shoe manufacturers, which sell
under their own names or produce for international brands such as
Rockport and Dexter, are small family businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here say that there is an entrepreneur inside every
worker,'' says Sanchez, the Leon business council president.
</P>
<P>
   Before General Motors came to Silao, the town was a shabby
market center serving the surrounding farm communities. Now, with
two shifts working in its off-yellow plant sprawled on a grassy
rise a few miles east of town, the community has been transformed.
</P>
<P>
   A constant stream of cars washes through Silao's main street; GM
workers walking to and from the plant jam its sidewalks. New
factory buildings and residential neighborhoods are going up
everywhere on the edges of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Silao Now'' gushes a billboard in English on the lawn of the
new Century 21 real estate office on the highway outside of town.
</P>
<P>
   Still working off production bottlenecks caused by last summer's
strike in the United States _ &UR; t &LR; he unionized U.S. workers were
protesting the loss of jobs to places like Silao _ the GM plant is
surrounded by thousands of trucks, both lined in neat rows and
parked haphazardly in the grass.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of large automobile transport trucks queue along the road
running past the plant, waiting for loads to carry to the border.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the industrial boom brought by GM has been a limited
financial blessing for Silao. Boosts to town coffers have been
offset so far by the tax breaks and other incentives given to the
new factories.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the factory workers commute from Irapuato, Leon and
other nearby cities because Silao's poorly educated and unskilled
workers have been unwilling or unable to fill the jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here aren't used to this kind of work,'' Gomez, the GM
worker, says. He notes that working on the truck line is cleaner
but also more monotonous than his old job in a Leon shoe factory.
``It takes some getting used to.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
