<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SHUTDOWN (Washington) _ Working against the clock to
avert a government shutdown, Congress and the White House struggle
to wrap up several appropriations bills and other contentious
business as lawmakers prepare to head home to campaign. By GREG
McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-MARIJUANA (Washington) _ Four Republican senators and
former national drug policy director William Bennett urge voters
not to approve state ballot initiatives that would follow the 1996
California and Arizona measures legalizing marijuana for medicinal
uses. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   CAPITOL-SHOOTINGS (Washington) _ A federal grand jury indicts
Russell Weston Jr. on murder and other charges in connection with
the shooting deaths of two police officers last summer in the
crowed U.S. Capitol. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLENN-NASA (Cape Canaveral) _ Mercury astronaut John Glenn,
flanked by a half-dozen younger space travelers, scrambles aboard
the shuttle Discovery to rehearse the actual launch countdown that
is scheduled for them late this month. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTIST-LEADER-PROFILE (Undated) _ We profile Richard Land, a
Southern Baptist leader and a member of the committee that wrote a
controversial family amendment for the church. One part of the
amendment _ stating that wives should submit to their husbands _
has created dissent. By RICHARD VARA.
</P>
<P>
   NASA-TECH (Undated) _ NASA will display more than 200
technological developments and exhibits to business, education and
community representatives during Inspection 98 next week. The goal
is to put NASA technology into general use. By LAURA E. GOLDBERG.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN-EUROPE (Paris) _ When Federal Reserve chief Alan
Greenspan said this week that in 50 years as a financial analyst he
had never seen anything like the recent turbulence that has struck
financial markets, he sent a wave of cold apprehension through
Europe. By BERNARD D. KAPLAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (undated) _ What happened to the Houston Astros? They
were the hottest team in baseball over the last half of the regular
season. They were the team everybody feared heading into the
playoffs. Then for the second consecutive year, the lineup went
belly-up in the postseason. By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ President Clinton is sitting out
much of the most important election of his life, largely foregoing
the barnstorming that presidents usually undertake in midterm
elections. With the threat of impeachment hanging over his head, he
plans stops in only seven or eight states in this campaign. By
STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-GAMING (Temecula, Calif.) _ It's expected to be the most
expensive ballot proposition in California history. At stake is the
future of Indian casino gaming, which operates illegally in a state
where Las Vegas has traditionally drawn 35 percent of its business.
Nevada gaming interests will spend millions to try to defeat the
proposition, but ironically, the once impoverished Indian tribes
will probably spend the most to defend it. By KIM COBB. (Already
filed)
</P>
<P>
   FERAL-CATS (College Station, Texas) _ By day, the sprawling
Texas A&AMP;M University campus almost buzzes with chaos and excitement
as more than 43,000 Aggies fly to classes and meetings, pursuing
their dream of higher education. But when darkness falls and the
students retreat, the cats appear. From basement, window sill and
drain pipe, they come. Three hundred of them, by the best estimate.
By ALLAN TURNER. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLICIES (Tierra Colorada, Mexico) _ The billion-dollar
highway here was praised when it opened in 1993 as an engineering
and cultural marvel. But its $80 tolls proved too steep for most
and its lack of exits excluded the local farmers and business
people. Now, bankrupt, the toll road embodies all that is wrong
with Mexico's economic policies. By DUDLEY ALTHAUS.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-GROWTH (Silao, Mexico) _ With scores of new factories
going up here to supply a GM truck plant, Silao, a northern Mexico
city of 100,000, is undergoing a rapid transformation due to the
global economy. ``We've lost our tranquility, perhaps,'' says the
public works director. ``But we see a great future here.'' By
DUDLEY ALTHAUS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SHELL-TECH (Undated) _ Shell is waking up and realizing it had
been giving away some of the most valuable technology in the world.
The challenge for the huge company, however, has and will continue
to be that it thinks like a bureaucracy. And while it has done a
great job at developing technology, it has been lousy at making
money with it. By HILLARY DURGIN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ With acrimony running high in
Washington over the Clinton impeachment probe, it might be a good
idea for the key players on each side to remember how President
Harry Truman and his adversaries settled their differences _ by
sitting down together and having several shots of good bourbon. By
ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Filed Wednesday.)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: The following stories on the growing political power of
Hispanics were sent Wednesday for release starting Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-CLOUT (Washington) _ Republicans and Democrats are
making an unprecedented effort to win Hispanic support, not only
for next month's election but for 2000 and beyond. Strategists for
both parties are amazed at Hispanics' zooming population growth and
believe that Latino voters are willing to switch party allegiance,
depending on candidates and issues. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   With graphics on the Wieck database slugged HISP-LOGO,
HISP-GROWTH, HISP-REGISTERED, HISP-VOTERS and
HISP-PRESIDENTIAL-ELECTIONS.
</P>
<P>
   With HISP photos available on Wieck.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-HISTORY (Washington) _ 1stLd-Writethru _ For Hispanics,
the long march to political power began shortly after World War II.
We trace the effort, looking at such leaders as Cesar Chavez, who
won national attention with his efforts to organize migrant farm
workers in California, and Dr. Hector Garcia, who stirred outrage
across the country at the refusal of a Texas town to bury an Army
private killed in World War II in the local cemetery because he was
Mexican American. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   With HISP photo of the Arlington National Cemetery grave of the
Hispanic soldier available on Wieck.
</P>
<P>
   For Monday, Oct. 12:
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-GOVERNORS (Del Rio, Texas) _ Texas Gov. George Bush
gets a warm welcome in Hispanic communities. Some Latinos say he is
more sympathetic to their concerns than other Republicans,
especially Gov. Pete Wilson of California, who has taken harsh
stances on immigration and affirmative action. The men's
differences illustrate the mixed messages the party sends to
Hispanics. By LAURA TOLLEY. With HISP-LOGO graphic.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-TEXAS (San Antonio) _ A look at the rising power of
Hispanics in various cities including San Antonio and Corpus
Christi, where Hispanics have city council majorities, and El Paso
and McAllen, which have Hispanic mayors. We also look at the
campaigns of Mexican Americans running for statewide offices. By
LAURA TOLLEY.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic on the Wieck database slugged HISP-TEXAS.
</P>
<P>
   For Tuesday, Oct. 13:
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-CONTESTS (Washington) _ From the streets of Salt Lake
City to the lake lands of Minnesota, Hispanic candidates are
running for office in state and congressional races that would have
seemed almost impossible for them to enter only a few years ago.
The development comes at a time when more Hispanics are running for
national and statewide posts generally. By MARK HELM and STEWART M.
POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   With HISP-LOGO graphic.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-DIFFERENCES (Washington) _ Republican and Democratic
politicians are learning that they cannot regard Hispanics as a
monolith. We look at the cross-currents between certain groups and
within the groups themselves. Republicans believe they have a
chance to take many Hispanic votes away from the Democrats. By MARK
HELM.
</P>
