<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8812 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERVIEW-COLIN-POWEL     10-09 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERVIEW-COLIN-POWELL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWELL FAVORS AFFIRMATIVE ACTION, SAYS CLINTON SHOULD NOT RESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ With his hands formed in a cat's cradle, giving direct
and lucid answers to questions, retired Gen. Colin Powell comes
across as the kind of guy with whom you'd want to share a foxhole
or as a White House office mate in the politely savage political
battleground of Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Powell is a man at ease, whether meeting with school kids in
Seattle or soliciting support for volunteerism from corporate
pooh-bahs.
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, he was the perfect
cool counterpart to hot-tempered, headstrong Gen. H. Norman
Schwarzkopf in directing the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, Powell is at ease with himself. Perhaps that is why
he has no compulsion to become a full-time candidate for president
of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't choose that course and I don't choose that course,''
Powell said during an interview Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party's most famous recruit _ and the party's
most outspoken moderate _ was about to inaugurate the 1998-99
season of the Seattle Celebrity Forum. He was also talking
excitedly about the achieving youngsters he met earlier in the day
when he saluted Seafirst Bank's Youth Job Program.
</P>
<P>
   ``One kid said something that struck me: `What we try to do is
not just get the super-volunteers, but all kids involved, so what
we are doing becomes important to each of them,''' Powell
recounted.
</P>
<P>
   Powell is a believer in bootstraps. But while he is, for many, a
symbol of the American dream _ the first African American to chair
the Joint Chiefs, a college ROTC man rather than an academy
graduate _ Powell has refused to put a soft, gauzy focus on his
achievements.
</P>
<P>
   Nor will he tailor the cloth of his conscience to conform with
the increasingly conservative fashions of his political party.
</P>
<P>
   He is a believer in affirmative action. In his best-selling
autobiography ``An American Journey,'' Powell freely acknowledged
that race played a role as he was tapped for coveted assignments,
but that in each case he was up to the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The experience has turned Powell him into a passionate critic of
measures _ such as Initiative 200 on Washington's November ballot _
that would ban any preferences based on gender or race.
</P>
<P>
   Powell called the measure ``diabolical'' and challenged its
intellectual underpinnings, saying: ``Nothing in affirmative action
says to admit people who can't do the work.''
</P>
<P>
   In language reflective of his three decades in the military,
Powell said he believes the United States has made tangible,
step-by-step progress toward the objective of what he calls ``a
second emancipation'' _ when minorities and women will participate
fully, not only in American citizenship but in the economic
opportunities of American life.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (progress) didn't happen by market forces, it didn't come
about from a spontaneous change of attitude, it happened because
people took risks _ yes _ and put their lives on the line to break
down barriers in our society,'' Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   Powell thinks that, if anything, it is time to accelerate
movement toward a more inclusive American economy because of
changes in the complexion of American society.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are becoming a more diverse people,'' he argued. ``We have
to speed up the process of finding qualified people, giving them
training and putting them into the workplace.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1995, the great America publicity and promotion
machine put Powell under the spotlight. He was urged to run for
president by people ranging from historian Stephen Ambrose _
biographer of Dwight Eisenhower as well as Lewis and Clark _ to
Mississippi's good-old-boy Democratic Rep. Gene Taylor. The
``Conventional Wisdom'' column in Newsweek put a seemingly
permanent upward arrow beside Powell's name.
</P>
<P>
   The attention served Powell's economic interests. ``An American
Journey'' became an instant best seller.
</P>
<P>
   But the glare seemed to re-enforce the desire of Powell's wife,
Alma, for privacy and _ after years of moving from one base posting
to another _ a house she didn't have to share with the American
people.
</P>
<P>
   The political right also reared its head. Just before Powell
decided not to run, leaders of the Christian conservative movement
as well as fund-raisers from the Republican right held a press
conference, declaring they would do everything in their power to
block him.
</P>
<P>
   Their reasons: Powell's moderate pro-choice stand on abortion,
and his support for government programs designed to enhance equal
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, Powell is still visibly irritated at the
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult to escape the ideological pinnings of both
right and left,'' he said. ``If you are an economic conservative,
as I am, rather than a social conservative, having your candidacy
validated by the powers that be is more and more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1952, a moderate Dwight Eisenhower was pushed to the GOP
presidential nomination over furious opposition from
isolationist-minded Republican conservatives. The argument that
Eisenhower could win the election was barely enough to win the
tolerance of his party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be far more difficult to do that now than in
Eisenhower's days, particularly in the Republican Party,'' Powell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Powell worries that the base of the Republican Party has moved
so far right that even the most superbly qualified moderate _ he
lists New Jersey Gov. Christine Todd Whitman and former
Massachusetts Gov. Bill Weld _ would find it prohibitively
difficult to get the party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The hostility of the hard right is hard to comprehend, because
``An American Journey'' revealed Powell to be in many ways a very
conservative man.
</P>
<P>
   He is a devout, traditional Episcopalian who recoiled at the
``genderless and ordinary'' God that liturgical reformers are
foisting on the faith. He is a man of order and purpose who was put
off by the college bull-session atmosphere of the White House early
in Bill Clinton's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Mixed feelings are apparent when Powell is asked about Clinton.
He obviously admires the president's brains and determination, but
not his personal conduct and the Monica Lewinsky mess.
</P>
<P>
   Among retired military officers, Powell said _ indicating it is
a view he shares _ ``there is unease and disappointment that the
person at the top of the military structure would find himself in
this position, and lying about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We live by a different code,'' Powell added, referring to the
Uniform Code of Military Justice. He gracefully sidestepped a
question about what would have happened to Clinton had his affair
with Lewinsky been subject to that code.
</P>
<P>
   Powell sees no way out of a prolonged impeachment process.
Having survived previous firestorms, Clinton will not leave office
voluntarily, the general believes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He isn't going to, nor do I think he should,'' Powell added.
``I am not going to comment on the psychology of Bill Clinton, but
he is a man who believes in what he is doing and is extraordinarily
strong-willed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which means we are in for a long ride. Now that the process
has begun, the country is simply going to have to ride it out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
