<DOCNO> NYT19981009.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8822 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-TORN-2TAKES-$A     10-09 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-TORN-2TAKES-$ADV11-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO-TORN-2TAKES-$ADV11 
 
MEXICO ECONOMICALLY TORN ALONG GEOGRAPHIC LINES BETWEEN BURGEONING
NORTH, IMPOVERISHED SOUTH 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT, 11) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIERRA COLORADA, Mexico _ What his government calls progress has
all but ruined Eligio Santiago.
</P>
<P>
   Santiago and other business owners in Tierra Colorada, a market
town that once thrived on a steady stream of tourists and truckers
winding down a two-lane road toward the resort city of Acapulco,
were whipsawed five years ago by the opening of a toll highway that
Mexican officials said was a path to the future.
</P>
<P>
   The billion-dollar road, the ``Autopista del Sol,'' or Highway
of the Sun, now whisks motorists to their beach holidays right past
Tierra Colorada. Although the town, a 40-minute drive north of the
Pacific coast resort city in Guerrero state, possesses one of the
toll road's scarce exits, few stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no traffic here, no nothing,'' says Santiago, whose
30-table restaurant less than two miles from the exit often goes
days without a customer. ``We are sometimes here until two or three
o'clock in the morning, hoping for a customer so we have enough
money to eat on the next day. That's the sad truth of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Built mostly with private money, the 250-mile ``autopista'' was
praised when it opened in 1993 as an engineering and cultural
marvel. The road, officials crowed, marked a new free-enterprise
vision for Mexico's economy and signaled the country's sure-footed
climb to the global winners' circle.
</P>
<P>
   But the road's tolls _ at first about $80 each way for cars, up
to $225 for trucks _ proved too steep for all but the most
affluent. A lack of exits excluded local drivers. Except for Mexico
City's weekend rush to and from the beach, there has never been
much traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Now, bankrupt and under government management, the toll road
embodies all that is wrong with Mexico's economic policies, critics
say, and all that those programs have wreaked upon the country's
impoverished and violent South.
</P>
<P>
   In a region stymied by a lack of public investment, one of
Mexico's best and most costly highways stands idle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did the `autopista' wrong,'' Santiago says with the
resigned shrug that is the reflex of southern Mexico's poor. ``We
have had no improvement because of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly five years after the onset of the North American Free
Trade Agreement, which will merge the economies of this country
with those of the United States and Canada over the next decade,
Mexico has become an ever more fractured and fractious land.
</P>
<P>
   As trade pulls production and power toward the U.S. border, this
nation of 95 million people finds itself ever more divided between
promise and penury, between North and South.
</P>
<P>
   Many in northern Mexico, long contemptuous of the economic and
political clout surrounding Mexico City, have added the South to
their list of resentments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The North works, the Center thinks and the South rests,'' said
Felipe Gonzalez Gonzalez of the conservative National Action Party
after winning the governorship of north-central Aguascalientes
state in August.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not everyone in southern Mexico is poor, nor is
everyone in the North rich. Oceans of poverty and pools of almost
unimaginable wealth plague the country.
</P>
<P>
   But the breach between the developing North and the moribund
South offers a stark reflection of the widening disparities in a
society that has been transformed by 15 years of free-market
economic policies.
</P>
<P>
   Those differences already are dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   Nuevo Leon state, which borders Texas and includes the
industrial city of Monterrey, posted per capita income of about
$6,000 in 1993, the latest year for which figures are available.
That was almost twice the national average of $3,600, according to
researchers at Banamex, Mexico's largest private bank.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, per capita earnings that same year in the three
states that generally define the South were much lower: about
$1,700 in Chiapas, $1,800 in Oaxaca and $2,100 in Guerrero.
</P>
<P>
   In Monterrey, where 1993 per capita income stood at $7,000,
about 15 percent of the workers earned more than $13 a day,
Banamex's cutoff between the working class and middle class. In
Acapulco, just 5 percent of employees earned or exceeded that
level.
</P>
<P>
   The changes now sweeping Mexico because of the trade agreement,
known as NAFTA, and other economic policies promise to widen the
divide, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Many northern and central states will become more prosperous as
international trade and investment bring new and better jobs, these
experts say. The South, heavily weighted with Indians and peasant
farmers widely seen as anachronisms, will fall behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does NAFTA offer one of these peasants who lives where
there are no roads, no development?'' asks Alberto Diaz, an expert
on Mexico's regional economies. ``It offers them nothing. NAFTA is
going to create more regional differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Northern Mexico's dependence upon trade and foreign investment
comes at a time of extreme uncertainty in the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   Many Mexicans have yet to recover from the December 1994 peso
devaluation, which set off the country's worst recession in memory.
Despite the risks, international trade remains the best hope for
the North, many say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things only now are getting better and we have another crisis
approaching,'' says Jose Luis Cabrera, the city treasurer of Silao,
a farm town in central Guanajuato state that is quickly
industrializing for the export market.
</P>
<P>
   ``But agriculture is being wiped out,'' Cabrera says. ``We had
to find some other way to live.''
</P>
<P>
   In the South, where as many as half the people live on the land,
the trade-based prosperity promised by a succession of Mexican
presidents for the past 15 years remains a mirage.
</P>
<P>
   Imports from the United States have ravaged grain prices, and
the land no longer supports the millions of families who live on
it. Jobs are scare, and most of them pay less than $5 a day.
Hundreds of thousands of villagers continue to leave for Mexico's
cities or the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Guerrero needs is work,'' says 21-year-old Ruben
Terrazas, who recently returned from a five-year stint laboring
illegally in the United States, He used his savings to open two
small pharmacies in villages along the toll road.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are jobs, but not enough for everyone. And they pay
miserably. That's why people leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite southern Mexico's immense natural resources _ Chiapas
alone provides half the country's hydroelectric power and a large
percentage of its natural gas _ federal economic policies that
favor the more populated and politically powerful North keep the
South at a disadvantage, critics say.
</P>
<P>
   ``How is it possible that Chiapas is one of the principal grain
producers (of Mexico) and has the highest levels of malnutrition?''
asks Enoch Araujo, the outgoing mayor of Tuxtla Gutierrez, Chiapas'
capital. ``More than 50 percent of the electricity from
hydroelectric plants is produced in Chiapas and we are the most
backward state in terms of electrification.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thousands of families lack drinking water, (yet they) live in
a state with important quantities of the liquid.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, armed rebellion in the rural South has rocked
Mexico since the January 1994 uprising of Maya farmers in Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
