<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8825 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-SHARON-1010-CO     10-09 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SHARON-1010-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NETANYAHU NAMES CONTROVERSIAL HARDLINER SHARON AS FOREIGN
MINISTER
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 400 words.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ As he prepares for high-level summit talks next
week, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu Friday appointed
Ariel Sharon, warrior, hard-liner and frequent Netanyahu critic, to
be the country's new foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
   The 70-year-old former general is known as a brilliant military
tactician but is reviled by many Israelis and Palestinians alike,
for his actions in 1982 that led to the massacre of 700
Palestinians by pro-Israel Lebanese troops.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment to the third highest post in the Israeli
government, behind prime minister and defense minister, is the
culmination of Sharon's long effort to rehabilitate his standing
since Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu may see Sharon as insulation from right-wing members
of his administration, who have repeatedly threatened to topple his
government if he goes along with an American-backed plan to give 13
percent more of the occupied West Bank to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon, currently in Netanyahu's cabinet as infrastructure
minister, has in the past been among those threatening to revolt.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu and Sharon are headed to Washington next Thursday
(Oct. 15) for summit talks with President Bill Clinton and
Palestinian President Yasser Arafat. The meetings are meant to nail
down the 13 percent deal and get commitments by Palestinians to
crack down on anti-Israel terrorists within their ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon's appointment came a couple of days after visiting U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright spoke of a new cooperative
spirit between Netanyahu and Arafat. But, Israeli troops killed a
Palestinian man Thursday during riots in Hebron, and a Palestinian
man stabbed and killed a 19-year-old, unarmed Israeli female
soldier Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The elevation of Sharon added a new element to the tense mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``His experience is wide ranging,'' Netanyahu spokesman David
Bar-Illan(CQ) said. ``He's been through the horrors of war and seen
the fruits of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians decried the appointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has shed more Palestinian blood than any other Israeli,''
chief Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat said.
</P>
<P>
   Erekat said a deal could still be made in Washington, but
Sharon's appointment will make impossible to settle the more
important issues that remain in the Oslo peace process.
Palestinians want those final issues to leave them enough land to
form a nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Netanyahu has to choose between the right wing and peace,
and with the choice of Mr. Sharon he has chosen the right wing at
the expense of peace,'' Erekat said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story c an end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Sharon has been on the front lines of many of Israel's most
heroic and shameful moments.
</P>
<P>
   He received accolades when commanding troops in the wars in 1967
and 1973. Also, he has the respect of Jordan's King Hussein, who
insisted on meeting only with Sharon when diffusing a crisis last
year.
</P>
<P>
   But Sharon is most well known as the defense minister who
launched the unpopular 1982 invasion of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign's scope stretched far beyond what Sharon had
pledged to Israelis in the beginning -- presented as a quick sweep
to clear out PLO terrorists. The Lebanese count more than 17,000 of
their people killed in the invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon was forced to resign after an Israeli commission found
that he had approved the entrance of pro-Israel Lebanese militia
into two Palestinian refugee camps in Beirut, named Sabra and
Shatila.
</P>
<P>
   Over about two days, while Israeli soldiers viewed from lookout
positions, the militias massacred about 700 Palestinian civilians,
including children.
</P>
<P>
   Efraim Inbar, political scientist at Bar-Ilan(CQ) University,
said that despite his hawkish stands, Sharon is a ``pragmatist.''
He noted that although they were from opposing parties, former
Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin used to secretly consult with Sharon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a bulldozer. If he takes on a job, he can complete it.
He just really moves people,'' Inbar said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
