<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8826 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-KOSOVO-1010-CO     10-09 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-KOSOVO-1010-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DOWN AND OUT, RUSSIA PLAYS ITS DIPLOMATIC HAND AT THE KOSOVO
TABLE
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In the debate over Kosovo, Russia already may have
scored a success simply by being in the diplomatic game.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Russia's vigorous diplomatic efforts will have
little bearing on the decision of the United States and its allies
over whether to punish Yugoslavia with air strikes to halt the
ethnic conflict in Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts in Moscow believe the Kremlin has achieved its
primary goal of re-establishing a measure of credibility on the
world stage at a time of deep economic and political distress at
home.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin said on Friday that Russia remained
firmly opposed to strikes against Serbian targets by the 16-nation
North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Other Russian officials have implied that a new Cold War could
result from military action by the West, severing the post-Soviet
security partnership between Russia and NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must defend a political, peaceful road of negotiations
without the use of military force,'' Yeltsin told reporters Friday
before meeting with Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev.
</P>
<P>
   Russia objects to the violent methods Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic has used against the separatist Kosovo province,
but says the conflict should be settled through talks.
</P>
<P>
   If the diplomatic tone sounds familiar, it is.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Russia has increasingly asserted its diplomatic
role to forestall U.S. strikes against Iraq over Saddam Hussein's
failure to yield to U.N. weapons inspections and other sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   With Russia's economy a wreck and its military severely
weakened, the Kremlin has little real clout with its former Cold
War adversaries in NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Its limitations as a faded superpower were illustrated plainly
on Friday when the government in Moscow formally asked the European
Union for humanitarian food aid to get Russia through the long
winter ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Its stand against NATO comes amid growing anti-Western hostility
in Russia. Many poor Russians blame the country's economic problems
on Western-style reforms since the demise of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomatic bearing on Kosovo, however weak Russia's hand may
be, plays well at home, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our national and strategic interests do not lie in the
Balkans,'' said Lilia Shevtsova, an analyst with the Carnegie
Moscow Center, a think tank. ``This is a diplomacy motivated by the
feeling of lost vanity of a former superpower.''
</P>
<P>
   Sergeyev visited Belgrade on Sunday with Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov for talks with Milosevic. Sergeyev warned on Friday that
NATO strikes could lead to ``full-scale warfare. Yugoslavia is
fully resolved to fight to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia is a traditional ally of the Serbs -- both are Slavic
people, sharing a common Orthodox Christianity and a kinship of
communist rule before the breakup of the Soviet Union and the
Warsaw Pact.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Russia's threat to use its veto power in the
U.N. Security Council effectively precluded a vote there on
sanctioning military action against the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   But if Moscow's diplomatic efforts have encumbered the
deliberations over the use of military force, there are also signs
that Russia has played the role of dispassionate arbiter in trying
to convince its ally in Belgrade to back down.
</P>
<P>
   When the Russian officials visited Milosevic last Sunday to try
to convince him to make concessions, they reportedly were supplied
by NATO with some details the pain the U.S. and its allies are
prepared to inflict.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, Russian politicians and analysts are increasingly
concerned over a perception that the United States is prepared to
act militarily without regard for the kind of international
consensus building that took place before the 1991 Gulf War against
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, air strikes could cause more domestic political problems
for Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov as he struggles to deal with
the Russian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-Yeltsin chairman of the Duma's defense committee, Roman
Popkovich, said Friday he would not rule out providing Russian
military aid to Serbia in the event of a war.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the lower house of parliament, the Duma, unanimously
passed a non-binding resolution calling on Russia to sever all
relations with NATO if it strikes the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Pavel Felgenhauer, defense and security editor for the newspaper
Sevodnya, predicts that NATO strikes could have a long-lasting
negative impact on Russia's relations with the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia will be engulfed by a genuine wave of mass
anti-Western, anti-NATO hatred,'' he commented, fueled in part by
``a suppressed mass hysteria'' of frustration over the collapse of
the economy in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
