<HEADER>
A8827 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANIMALS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-09 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMALS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROWS: GIFTED BUT CRANKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The phrase ``stupid birds!'' may spring to mind when you first
hear those loud, scolding caws at sunup.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing could be further from the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Crows, surprisingly classified as songbirds, are among the most
intelligent birds.
</P>
<P>
   And we are approaching the best time of year to appreciate them,
as they gather by the thousands in fall and winter nighttime
roosting areas across the state (the largest such area being high
on the Jordan's Furniture hill overlooking Route 9 in Framingham).
</P>
<P>
   The crow family is found in most of the world and its numbers
are on the rise. Yet crows remain poorly understood and little
studied.
</P>
<P>
   Still, anyone who has been reprimanded by an enraged
neighborhood crow for putting a lid on a trash can knows that they
have plenty of personality. And those who have had close encounters
with canny crows have remarkable stories to tell.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Craighead George, the Newbery Medal-winning author of such
children's books as ``My Side of the Mountain'' and ``Julie of the
Wolves,'' has lived with crows as pets. (That is illegal now.)
</P>
<P>
   Take Crowbar, one of George's favorites. Her children found him
on the ground, a naked, orphaned nestling. He was soon a member of
the family, gobbling down scrambled eggs at the breakfast table and
dropping to the ground to walk the kids to the school bus stop. He
could mimic George's voice and shout ``Hello!'' from treetops. He
even figured out a way to join the kids on the slide, using a
coffee can lid like a surfboard.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Mertz, director of the New England Wildlife Center in
Hingham, Mass., treats about 60 crows a year _ mostly nestlings
tossed out of trees being trimmed or adult birds hit by cars. What
impresses Mertz is how determined these birds are to escape. ``You
can wrap up a red-tailed hawk with its face covered, and it will
just lie there,'' Mertz says. But a crow similarly bound ``will
take about 17 seconds before it's figured out how to get out of the
wrapper.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin McGowan, curator of the ornithology and mammalogy
collections at Cornell University, has studied American crows
around Ithaca, N.Y., for a decade, tagging about 750 birds out of a
population of about 125,000. McGowan is skeptical about the way we
define intelligence in animals but nonetheless finds his study
species astonishing.
</P>
<P>
   In laboratory tests of ``reversing habit'' behaviors _ the
pellets suddenly stop coming from the green lever and will come
only from the red, for example _ crows score as high as monkeys in
figuring out the switch.
</P>
<P>
   Crows are omnivores and opportunists. They live in large
extended families in which, often, several generations of crow kids
help out around the nest of the breeding parents (a rare behavior
for birds and, come to think of it, for humans, too).
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes offspring will leave for weeks or months or even a
year and be recognized and welcomed on their return. (Many of us
have been recognized upon returning to the nest but not necessarily
welcomed.) Unlike most other birds, a 7-year-old crow might still
be hanging around the nest. As with many intelligent species, crows
have a fairly long lifespan and a long time in childhood to learn.
The oldest wild crow known was 30 (a crow crone?); the average crow
usually lives to age 13.
</P>
<P>
   Like us, it appears crows began moving to the suburbs and cities
in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   They mate for life, or as scientists prefer to say, they form
``long-term pair bonds,'' with cases of crow divorce recently being
reported from a researcher in _ where else? _ California.
</P>
<P>
   Crows have a huge vocabulary and varied vocalizations. They seem
to enjoy play, and young crows have been observed chasing each
other with feathers.
</P>
<P>
   So, if crows are so much like us, why have we hated them? They
have been known to be agricultural pests (though their impact is
now believed minimal, while we are just discovering some of the
positive things they do for farmers, ecologically). They are loud.
On the ground, a crow has the menacing gait of _ as author Thomas
McNamee described another bird _ a ``bar bully.'' They scatter our
trash. They eat the nestlings of cuter birds. They appear dressed
for a funeral. And they have been known to feed on corpses.
</P>
<P>
   But as we are finally getting to know them, their image is
changing. What does researcher McGowan see when he looks at a crow?
``I see a big, beautiful, intelligent, and fascinating bird,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   We have mostly American crows around here, with a few of the
smaller fish crows. Ravens, about four times the size of crows, are
making a comeback, with some in Western Mass. and very few east of
Worcester. McGowan says crows and ravens are as different as lions
and leopards.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's amazing to see thousands of the black birds filling
the sky as they gather to roost evenings from October to February,
there is good crow viewing in your own back yard too.
</P>
<P>
   Crow families have territories, so your neighborhood crows
really are your crows. If you want to befriend these birds, you
can. Though they all look alike to us, crows can distinguish
individual humans, even out of context.
</P>
<P>
   McGowan says you can toss some peanuts to the ground when you
see the crows _ don't look directly at them or throw the nuts at
them. In time, the crows will know you and greet you.
</P>
<P>
   And then you may have stories such as the one Jean George tells
about Crowbar. The bird was stealing milk money from school kids
and hiding it. She happened to discover one day that he was
depositing the coins in the drainpipe of the building next door.
Which just happened to be a bank. Coincidence?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 1645EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981009.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8828 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-TORN-2NDTAKES-     10-09 2298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-TORN-2NDTAKES-$ADV11-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO-TORN-2NDTAKES-$ADV11 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  TIERRA COLORADA, Mexico: in Chiapas.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although the political violence in Chiapas has largely subsided,
the Zapatista rebels there continue to resist, calling for greater
rights for Mexico's indigenous farmers.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a less publicized but far more violent
rebellion seethes in Guerrero, Oaxaca and adjoining states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economic and social backwardness (in the South) lies at the
root of this problem,'' says Mauricio de Maria y Campos, a Mexican
official who recently completed a five-year stint in Geneva,
Switzerland, as the director-general of the United Nations agency
that promotes industrialization.
</P>
<P>
   De Maria y Campos and other economists cite studies that show
the economic gulf that narrowed in the 1960s and 1970s has expanded
since the early 1980s when the Mexican government began opening the
country to trade and international investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within Mexico we need to think more in terms of regional
development,'' he says. ``If not, we are going to have problems,
not only the social and economic ones, but with the whole
integration process (of the North American trade zone).''
</P>
<P>
   The clash between bureaucratic vision and the South's unrequited
needs is nowhere as jarring as along the ``Autopista del Sol.''
</P>
<P>
   A sleek black ribbon, the four-lane divided highway climbs the
high pass south of Mexico City, winds into the breathtaking valley
that holds the city of Cuernavaca, then rips into the jumbled
mountains of Guerrero.
</P>
<P>
   Rains have painted the normally parched brush a brilliant
emerald. Rivers pregnant with topsoil roil brown and angry through
gorges beneath the highway's suspension bridges.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical downpours, frequent earthquakes, occasional rockslides
and stretches of shoddy construction require workers to patch the
roadway constantly.
</P>
<P>
   Still, cars can, and do, zoom along at 80 mph or better, their
drivers unhindered by the heavy traffic, predatory patrolmen or
yawning potholes common to Mexico's public roads.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, the ``autopista'' is a source of pride in a
country that 10 years ago had less than 600 miles of expressways.
Yet, with its few exits and prohibitive tolls, the road is of
little benefit to the impoverished communities that it skirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't use it,'' says Mario Castillo, the top elected
official in Dos Arroyos, a cluster of tile-roofed adobe that
huddles along the side of the highway 25 miles north of Acapulco.
``We just watch the traffic go by.''
</P>
<P>
   From its beginnings, the highway was never meant to be more than
a means of carrying Mexican tourists to the beach hotels,
restaurants and discotheques of Acapulco. Foreign tourists have
been scared off, first by Acapulco's polluted bay and its crowded,
noisy streets and later by news of hurricanes and guerrillas.
Business leaders and government officials hoped to fill the void
with regular visitors from Mexico's capital and other cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Acapulco basically is the beach resort of Mexico City,''
explains Amin Zarur, Guerrero's secretary of economic development
who served as mayor of Acapulco in the early 1980s. ``(It) needed a
faster and safer roadway.''
</P>
<P>
   It took seven hours of hot, hectic, hazardous driving to travel
the old two-lane highway from the Mexican capital. With the
``Autopista del Sol,'' people in Mexico City can set out after
breakfast and be swimming in the ocean by lunch.
</P>
<P>
   While Mexico's public and private planners focused on pumping
life into the resort, economic development schemes for the rest of
Guerrero stagnated.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to make choices,'' Zarur says. He recites a litany of
failed or postponed projects elsewhere across the state. Not enough
water, he says of a small industrial zone. No good roads, he says
about another area where farmers' produce rots on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Neighboring states are far ahead of Guerrero, he says. ``It's
difficult to compete with them,'' he explains. ``They are closer to
Mexico City and have better services.''
</P>
<P>
   Zarur acknowledges that access to the toll road could enhance
the economic fortunes of Guerrero's poor villages. But he says the
highway does not figure in the immediate future of the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we have a plan for economic development, they can build
exits,'' he says. ``It doesn't make any sense to do it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Even access doesn't count for much along the toll road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you think I am just sitting here?'' asks Estelina
Morales Vela, the 60-ish owner of a once-bustling restaurant and
motel in Tierra Colorada. ``There is no one to buy anything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All the buses passed through here, all the cars,'' Morales
says as she gazes from her shady lobby out to the now-empty old
highway that cuts through town. ``There was a lot going on, a lot
of life. Now, it's dead. Just dead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to work to eat,'' she says. ``and I am just sitting
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Morales waves over a friend, Gloria Muiz, who is carrying a
stack of homemade pizzas draped with a clean cloth.
</P>
<P>
   Muiz owned a highway restaurant for 30 years in Tierra Colorada.
More than 25 people worked for her, she says, but it all ended with
the toll road. With her restaurant shuttered, Muniz makes ends meet
selling pizza.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought of selling out,'' Muniz says with a weary smile
and a shrug. ``But no one is buying. We never thought that it was
all going to completely die. We were foolish''
</P>
<P>
   ``They killed us with the `autopista,' '' she says. ``They made
us into the living dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty miles closer to Acapulco, the toll road dominates Dos
Arroyos, running along a high embankment and across one of the
streams that gave the village its name.
</P>
<P>
   The growl of passenger buses and the whine of cars mix with the
braying of donkeys and snorting of pigs rooting through the
village's garbage. Women wash clothes in the river, laying them to
dry on the concrete skirt of the highway's bridge. Children splash
naked in the swift, shallow current.
</P>
<P>
   Denied use of the toll road, the many people in Dos Arroyos who
work in Acapulco have to take a bus to the resort along the old
highway, a two-hour journey that costs about $2 each way. Many of
those people earn only about $100 a month at their construction or
hotel jobs, so most of them live in Acapulco, returning home on
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   And because the toll road cleaves Dos Arroyo's fields and
pastures, villagers are forced to make circuitous detours across
bridges or through tunnels to tend their corn or herd their
livestock.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't pay attention to us,'' says Juan Zapata, who joins
a half-dozen other Dos Arroyos farmers on a shady porch for early
afternoon beers and complaints about the government. ``They always
treat peasants with disregard.''
</P>
<P>
   Such resentments have helped nurture the People's Revolutionary
Army, or EPR, which surged two years ago in the mountains near the
highway following the state police's massacre of 17 unarmed farmers
on the way to an anti-government protest.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, the Mexican army killed 11 alleged guerrillas, many
of them also apparently unarmed, in a village not 50 miles from Dos
Arroyos. In August, suspected rebels ambushed a state police patrol
in another nearby village, killing two officers. And last month,
army troops hastily mobilized near Dos Arroyos itself after a
passing motorist reported seeing a dawn patrol of uniformed men,
presumably guerrillas, walking along the ``autopista.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the political violence, armed robberies have
multiplied, with bandits sometimes setting up roadblocks on the
toll road or attacking drivers who have stopped to rest.
</P>
<P>
   State police squads, armed with automatic rifles and riding in
the back of pickup trucks, have become a common sight along the
``autopista.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a lot of thieves in this town,'' admits Eligio
Santiago, the restaurant owner in Tierra Colorada. ``It's for the
same reason. There is nothing else to do, no other way to make
money to eat on.''
</P>
<P>
   With the state mired in guerrilla violence, highway banditry and
feuds between marijuana- and heroin-producing families, attracting
investment money for anywhere outside of Acapulco is nearly
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Zarur, the state's economic development czar, says it's all
about cycles. And the cycles in Guerrero are particularly vicious.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as there is no development, there is no security,''
Zarur says, almost wistfully. ``As long as there is no security,
there is no development.''
</P>
<P>
   Government and business have bet Guerrero's future on Acapulco's
fortunes. From the look of things, the bet grows riskier all the
time.
</P>
<P>
   The toll road splits just north of Acapulco into a branch
leading to the flashy development of ``Punta Diamante'' south of
the main bay and another that trudges into the maddening urban
quagmire known as ``Renacimiento,'' or Rebirth, on the backside of
the resort's coastal mountains.
</P>
<P>
   With few opportunities elsewhere, people from across Guerrero
keep pouring into Acapulco. They scrounge for work, build their own
houses in sprawling slums, hustle to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many who come from the countryside can't read or write. There
is little good work for them,'' says Rodolfo Benardis, the owner of
a small company that sells bottled water in Acapulco. ``(But) they
keep coming from the villages, because it's even worse there.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials say more than 1.25 million people, most of them
poor, now pack into the once-tranquil port. Local businessmen,
concerned about the city's threatened tropical-paradise image,
insist that the population is closer to 750,000.
</P>
<P>
   The road bogs down into the chaotic traffic of ``Renacimiento.''
A dearth of stoplights means bottlenecks, even in sparse traffic.
Pedestrians skitter among the speeding, swerving cars, buses and
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The trip over the mountains to the beach from ``Renacimiento''
used to take at least a half-hour on these city streets. But a new
toll tunnel blasted through the rock saves, to those who can afford
it, the time and the bother of seeing how most of Acapulco lives.
</P>
<P>
   Acapulco exudes the sultry charm of an aging madame. Wealthy
enclaves on the south rim of the bay still offer the stunning
views, warm breezes and radiant sun that made the city popular. But
downtown is decaying. Teen-age prostitutes ply their trade on some
of the beaches and hang out in the plazas. Vendors clog the
sidewalks. Traffic noise drowns the sounds of the waves.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism is seasonal. And this isn't the season.
</P>
<P>
   Occasional groups of foreigners on package tours fly in from the
United States, Canada or South America. People still drive down
from Mexico City on the weekends.
</P>
<P>
   But business has melted with the hard rains. The beach hotels
and restaurants that anchor Acapulco's economy echo emptily. The
few tourists who meander from the beach are assaulted by hordes of
hawkers, taxi drivers and time-share salespeople scrambling for a
few pesos or dollars.
</P>
<P>
   With Christmas' tourist boom approaching, crews are busy
repairing the wide bay-front avenue where the better hotels are
located. They are still cleaning up the damage from last October's
murderous hurricane, Pauline.
</P>
<P>
   That storm turned the streets on the slopes above the hotel
strip into torrents, sluicing away houses, churches and businesses.
Hundreds died. But residents say little repair has been made in the
working-class neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never come to see how the neighborhoods above are
doing,'' says Crystal Armenta, who lives with her husband, children
and four other families in a small two-story house on the back
slope of the coastal mountains. ``They just take care of the
tourists.''
</P>
<P>
   But Armenta's family lives off the tourist trade. The incomes of
her taxi-driving husband and brothers-in-law drop sharply in the
off-season.
</P>
<P>
   With few manufacturing jobs or other sources of income, business
and government leaders insist, taking care of tourists is the only
way to ensure Acapulco's prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the efforts to spruce up the city and improve its image,
tourism has been dropping for years. Foreign visitors, preferred by
business owners because they spend more than Mexicans, now make up
just 20 percent of the tourism, economists say.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign tourism this past winter dropped by 7 percent, draining
$100 million from Acapulco's economy, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Retail sales, an indicator of economic health, have declined 27
percent in the past four years, twice the rate for Mexico overall,
according to Banamex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Acapulco is very beautiful. We just don't know how to sell
it,'' says Cesar Bajos, the son of a prominent merchant family in
the resort who now heads the local chapter of Coparmex, a national
business council. ``But I'm an optimist.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was born, all the streets here were dirt,'' the
42-year-old says. ``Now look at it. We are much better off.''
</P>
<P>
   Bajos and other business leaders have teamed with local, state
and federal officials to produce Acapulco's first detailed
development plan.
</P>
<P>
   Their proposal calls for adding and improving streets and sewers
and building industrial parks near where the toll road enters the
city. The projects would provide jobs for the thousands of
newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a problem, the first step is recognizing it,''
Bajos says. ``We have a great future if we know how to plan it.
People may want to do a lot of things, but no one knows where to
start.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the new plans prove effective remains an open question,
Bajos concedes. But rescuing the resort cannot be more urgent, he
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Acapulco declines,'' Bajos says with a shrug, ``the whole
state declines.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
