</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LEAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWERFUL, LYRICAL, INTIMATE `LEAR' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
KING LEAR 
Produced by: Chestermead Production for BBC-TV and WGBH-TV. 
Directed by: Richard Eyre 
On: Masterpiece Theatre 
Date: Sunday, 9 p.m. 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The common assumption in adapting a play for movies or
television is that you either record it as is, putting the viewer
in the proverbial front row, or you open it up, treating the action
more like a movie than a play.
</P>
<P>
   Director Richard Eyre finds a third, extremely satisfying way of
adapting his Royal National Theatre production of ``King Lear,''
featuring Ian Holm, for the BBC and ``Masterpiece Theatre.'' Rather
than opening the production up, Eyre closes it in. Except for the
scenes in the storm, the action is bordered in a plain room and
corridor tinted red in the first act and green in the second.
</P>
<P>
   This might sound as visually inviting as ``The Nightly Business
Report,'' but don't be fooled. Eyre gives us just enough to keep
the production from getting visually boring through smart cutting
and tight editing. Meanwhile, the starkness of the visuals keeps
the focus on the intensity of the action and the beauty of the
poetry. Almost every line bounds off the screen with such clarity
that ``Lear'' seems no more distant linguistically or thematically
than the average ``NYPD Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that has a lot to do with the superlative acting as
well as Eyre's aesthetic choices. The underrated Laurence Olivier
version of a decade ago for Granada Television featured an actor at
the end of the line. This one features an actor at the top of his
game. Now in his 60s, Holm has suddenly emerged as one of the
finest English-speaking actors, but even his amazingly
multidimensional performance in ``The Sweet Hereafter'' didn't
prepare us for the accolades he received as the National's Lear
last year.
</P>
<P>
   They're deserved. In interviews Holm has downplayed his
portrayal, saying that he just went with the text. If so, he's a
better reader than most anyone else as he stalks the stage with a
ferocity more closely associated with Richard III and an energy
level more closely associated with men half his age. From drumming
on the desk to staring down people twice his size, Holm is every
inch a tornado. One might wonder how his ungrateful daughters would
ever have the nerve to stand up to such a person, but one is too
busy marveling to care.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, like Olivier, Holm isn't surrounded by shrinking
violets. Almost every performance is a gem, chief among them Finbar
Lynch's slashing Edmund, David Burke's heroic Kent, and Michael
Bryant's witty Fool. The cast takes full advantage of the freedom
of not needing to reach the back row with modulated performances
that go from whispers to shouts and from profound pity to
heaven-shaking rage. Holm doesn't literally strip Lear naked as he
did onstage, but there is such raw emotion in the performance that
he could be doing ``Lear'' in Russian and you'd know almost all you
have to know about the play.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, though, that Shakespeare's English has rarely
sounded so accessible. It's as if an old friend revealed secrets
that made his character seem fully coherent. Just as we never know
the whole truth about another person, we never know the whole truth
about a Shakespeare tragedy. But in this ``Lear'' the falls from
grace, the inabilities to look truth in the face and their tragic
consequences, the micro and macro family issues, the spirals of
evil, stand in splendid relief from the action.
</P>
<P>
   Eyre was after the same intimacy he reportedly achieved at the
National. He gets that and a lot more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
