<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPLOYEES NEED CONSIDERATE HAND 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Working for a company for a long time is a lot like being
married. If you're not on your toes, a certain lack of
consideration &UR;  &LR; can creep in.
</P>
<P>
   Like spouses who take each other for granted, assuming the
laundry will be washed and dinner will be cooked every night,
bosses often assume that their employees will hang around forever
doing the same old thing.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes when a spouse gets fed up and says she's got a more
attractive offer _ even if it means living alone _ then he suddenly
gets worried and comes bearing gifts of roses, champagne and
chocolate to woo her back. It's the same at work, except the tokens
of affection are typically better job titles, more responsibility
and more money.
</P>
<P>
   One Houston marketing manager pushed for a director-level job
for more than a year. It was promised when she was hired and she
kept getting hints that it would come soon.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, another company came courting with a director-level job
that offered a sizable increase in pay, a sign-on bonus and more
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Her current employer went crazy, offering to match everything on
the table including the sought-after director's title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has been very nice, including calling frequently to
ask how I'm doing,'' said the marketing manager, asking not to be
identified.
</P>
<P>
   All that courting is intoxicating, which is blurring her ability
to make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   She said she likes her current job but it does linger in her
mind why she didn't get that director's title earlier.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Supervisors often neglectful &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's a sad situation that's not uncommon, said Greg Nakanishi,
president of GN Resources, a human resource consulting company.
Often out of neglect, supervisors don't let their employees know
how valuable they are to the organization and don't take the steps
to get them a promotion, a raise or a pat on the back.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing employees for their good work isn't that difficult,
he said. A nice note, a nice comment or a nice bulletin board
notice goes a long way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We focus on the negative _ this went wrong, we made this
mistake,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And not recognizing the contributions of those already at work
sometimes makes bosses look right past them when it comes time to
fill a new job.
</P>
<P>
   The corporate communications manager at a Houston company found
out accidentally about several new openings in her department at
the director level, then discovered she wasn't being considered for
any of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that since I was with the company that they didn't have
to court me or do anything for me,'' she said, asking not to be
identified. She said she pushed and pushed her own candidacy and
was finally elevated to the director level.
</P>
<P>
   She said she believes she would never have been promoted if she
hadn't pushed. You watch people with fewer qualifications get hired
in at a higher level but you're left behind, she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, there's not a `fit' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes when a boss doesn't promote a subordinate, it's
because the employee may not be seen as the ``right'' person for
the job, Nakanishi said.
</P>
<P>
   Employees may not be good team players, or have the right
``fit'' with the organization, or not be results-oriented enough to
move to the next level, but they're doing a perfectly good job in
the job they've got, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's easier to avoid the issue, he said, than rock the boat.
Bosses figure: ``I've got a lot of things to do. Why spend time on
tweaking?''
</P>
<P>
   But the tragedy is that the employee doesn't get any feedback on
what she needs to do to move to the next level, yet she's doing a
good job so she isn't counseled on how to improve, Nakanishi said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just sit there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Clifford isn't in the business of giving out promotions,
but she does help companies show appreciation for their employees.
She finds that many times the effort backfires.
</P>
<P>
   Clifford, president of Celebration Productions, which plans
special events for corporations, said she gets calls from companies
that say they want to celebrate a big milestone at the company, yet
instruct her to serve employees a lunch of barbecue and potato
salad in the company lunchroom.
</P>
<P>
   They don't understand that they're saying they really don't care
about their employees, said Clifford. And yet those same companies
put on huge spreads for their clients, complete with fancy
restaurant dinners, complimentary valet parking and lavish goodie
bags.
</P>
<P>
   Employees see that disparity and they get the message of where
they fit into the organization, she said. Even if the bosses don't
see it, employees pick right up on that insincerity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Send e-mail to lm.sixel at chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
