<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-WATCH-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUNDS WATCH: JUST HOW LOW CAN FEES GO? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Oct. 11)  
 (bl)  
 By ABBY SCHULTZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With equity markets on the skids, investors may soon notice the
bite that fees take from their mutual-fund returns. But a new fund
family with big-name outside advisers hopes to attract investors by
reining in these costs.
</P>
<P>
   In rolling out four funds earlier this month, Forward Funds, a
San Francisco firm, pledged only that expenses would never be more
than the average of all funds in its peer group. In a filing with
the Securities and Exchange Commission, expenses for the Forward
Equity fund, for example, are estimated at 1.4 percent for the
initial fiscal year, just below the 1.41 percent average expense
ratio of domestic equity funds.
</P>
<P>
   But Ronald Pelosi, the group's president, said he expected to
``be able to deliver lower expenses'' _ and still make a profit _
by applying institutional-style pricing to retail funds.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Lallos, a senior analyst at Morningstar Inc., the
financial publishing firm in Chicago, said the group's success
would depend on how big it becomes. As assets grow, fund companies
can realize economies of scale on fees. Unlike most fund companies,
Forward plans to pass on those savings, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Bobroff, a fund industry consultant in East Greenwich,
R.I., was cautious in assessing the group's prospects. ``Cost isn't
the only factor,'' he said. ``If it were, Vanguard would have all
the assets,'' he added, referring to the low-cost fund giant.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, if Forward Funds succeeds, it could face a flood of
competition, even from its own subadvisers, which could match its
pricing very quickly, Bobroff said.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Equity is managed by Barclays Global Fund Advisors. The
other funds are International Equity, managed by Templeton
Investment Counsel; Global Bond, managed by Pacific Investment
Management, and Small Capitalization, managed by Hoover Capital
Management. A fifth fund, Global Asset Allocation, is managed by
Webster Investment Management, the fund family's investment
adviser, by distributing assets among the four other funds.
</P>
<P>
   The group will get a head start with a $100 million cash
infusion from Sutton Place Associates, a group of private investors
also in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Rogers, a principal at Barclays, which manages $563
billion, said its agreement with Forward Funds was an ``Intel
inside'' strategy that allowed Barclays to have someone else sell
its product.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Funds investors pay an upfront purchase fee of 0.25
percent, which is not a load because it goes directly into the
fund's net asset value _ and not to the management company _ to
cover the costs of buying securities. Vanguard employs similar
``transaction'' fees ranging from 0.25 percent to 1 percent on some
of its index funds to defray the costs of buying and selling, a
Vanguard spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Mutiny in the Markets
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, when investors lose money they become restive,
even mutinous. But would shareholders make even the vaunted Dr. J.
Mark Mobius, captain of seven Templeton funds with a total value of
more than $13 billion, walk the plank?
</P>
<P>
   No. Dissidents at the $448 million Templeton Dragon fund, which
is intended for investors seeking long-term capital appreciation by
investing in companies in China, proposed that the board consider
converting from a closed-end fund traded on the New York Stock
Exchange to an open-end fund. But Franklin Resources, Templeton's
parent company, reported that shareholders had rejected the
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Templeton Dragon, which reached a 52-week high of $15.75 a share
a year earlier, closed Thursday at $6.25, up from a low of $5.25 on
Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that drubbing, Mobius, perhaps the leading apostle of
emerging-markets investing, voices optimism. In an article from
Hong Kong, Dow Jones recently reported that Mobius was advising
investors ``to be patient.'' He added, ``We have seen a tremendous
over-correction in the markets.''
</P>
<P>
   But not every manager has Mobius' sway with shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   At Clemente Global Growth, an $80.4 million fund that has seen
its share price shrink from a 52-week high of $13.125 on July 22 to
a close of $8.5625 on Thursday, a group of dissidents gained
control of the board. The dissidents, led by Phillip Goldstein of
Opportunity Partners and Ronald Olin of Deep Discount Advisors,
triumphed over Lilia Clemente, the fund's manager, who was not
re-elected to the board.
</P>
<P>
   Fly, Fly Away  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To paraphrase an ad for a rival marketing combination, , was it
the fund or was it the miles?
</P>
<P>
   Warburg Pincus Asset Management Inc. and Northwest Airlines
announced that they had agreed to create and market mutual funds _
initially, two money market funds _ through which Warburg Pincus
investors can earn Northwest World Perks frequent-flyer bonus
miles.
</P>
<P>
   Investors can earn one bonus mile for each $4 invested on an
annual basis, plus up to 1,200 bonus miles; accounts opened during
the first six months of the program, which began Oct. 1., can earn
200 a month.
</P>
<P>
   And just think, if the market really turns south, you can too.
Just take a nice holiday and get away from it all.
</P>
<P>
   Two New Acorns
</P>
<P>
   Acorn Investment Trust, managed by Wanger Asset Management LP,
announced two new no-load mutual funds. Acorn 20 will invest in 20
to 25 American companies; Acorn Foreign 40 will invest in 40 to 60
foreign companies. Both will seek long-term capital growth. John
Park and Mark Yost manage Acorn 20, while Marcel Houtzager and Leah
Zell manage Acorn Foreign Forty. Each fund has a minimum investment
of $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gabelli Sticks to Its Guns  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With storm clouds over the world's financial markets, both
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. and Neuberger &AMP; Berman have decided this is no
time to go public. But the intrepid Mario Gabelli is pushing ahead
with an initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   In an amended Securities and Exchange Commission filing this
week, Gabelli Funds said a group including Merrill Lynch and
Salomon Smith Barney would manage the offering, but gave no hint of
when the sale might occur, or how many shares would be sold,
Bloomberg News reported.
</P>
<P>
   The firm, based in Rye, N.Y., managed about $15.8 billion of
assets as of June 30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 1703EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
