<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-SHOOTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY INDICTS SUSPECT IN SHOOTING OF 2 OFFICERS AT CAPITOL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal grand jury Friday indicted Russell E.
Weston Jr. on two counts of murder in the shooting of two U.S.
Capitol Police officers in the building they swore to protect.
</P>
<P>
   The six-count indictment also accuses Weston, 41, of attempted
murder on a third officer and using a firearm in the three violent
attacks July 24. He could be sentenced to death if convicted of
killing a federal officer.
</P>
<P>
   Weston, scheduled to be arraigned Wednesday, remains in custody
without bond at D.C. General Hospital as he recovers from gunshot
wounds he sustained outside the office of House Majority Whip Tom
DeLay, R-Texas. During the attack, Weston killed Officers Jacob J.
Chestnut, 58, and John M. Gibson, 42, who was assigned to guard
DeLay, federal prosecutors say.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Douglas B. McMillan was injured along with 24-year-old
Angela Dickerson of Virginia, who was visiting the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Weston's deadly march began about 3:30 p.m. when he stormed
through a metal detector at the East Front entrance to the Capitol
and fired a .38 caliber revolver point blank at the back of
Chestnut's head as the officer was giving directions to a tourist,
prosecutors allege.
</P>
<P>
   Weston then ran down the first floor hallway toward DeLay's
office, firing on McMillan before engaging Gibson in a short-range
gun battle that left the officer dead and the assailant seriously
wounded, accord to law enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   Weston, bandaged and in a wheelchair, made his first appearance
before a federal judge Sept. 23. He said he understood that he was
being held on charges of killing two federal officers but declined
to enter a plea.
</P>
<P>
   The accused, who has been diagnosed as a paranoid schizophrenic,
wrote several letters to federal agencies before the Capitol
attack, complaining that government officials had planted land
mines on the grounds of his Montana cabin, prosecutors stated in
court papers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he once drove up to a guard station at the Central
Intelligence Agency's headquarters in Langley, Va., and rambled on
about President Clinton, Marilyn Monroe and cloning, prosecutors
added.
</P>
<P>
   Weston's lawyers have received permission from the U.S. District
Court in Washington, D.C., to have their client evaluated by
psychiatrists. The evaluations might form the basis for an insanity
defense, but the attorneys have not publicly discussed their
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have also asked the court for permission to evaluate
Weston's mental health but have not yet received judicial
clearance.
</P>
<P>
   Weston, a native of Valmeyer, Ill., could present an insanity
defense at his arraignment Wednesday. A judge then would likely
permit government psychiatrists to evaluate him.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also would decide whether Weston is competent to stand
trial. If an insanity defense is presented, the court would have to
determine if Weston was sane enough to understand the difference
between right and wrong at the time of the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Weston's parents, who testified before the grand jury in August,
have spoken publicly about their son's 20-year history of mental
illness and his fear of the federal government. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
