<HEADLINE>
CLINTON FIGHTS MID-TERM ELECTIONS FROM THE SIDELINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 11)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton is sitting out the most important
election of his political career.
</P>
<P>
   Although the new Congress that convenes in January is expected
to decide whether to impeach him, Clinton is planning campaign
visits to only seven or eight states in the weeks before the Nov. 3
mid-term congressional election.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, he campaigned in 14 states in the final 25 days of
the 1994 mid-term congressional elections, appearing with dozens of
candidates at open air rallies, closed-door fund raisers and
policy-oriented events staged to highlight Democrats' political
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Clinton plans to use a White House-based ``Rose
Garden'' strategy that will give him greater control over his
public agenda. He is planning White House events to spotlight
efforts to protect the Social Security system, boost federal
investment in public education and efforts to protect the rights of
medical patients in the era of managed health care.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats hope the tactic will overshadow any Republican efforts
to make the mid-term congressional election a referendum on
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Staying at home also will shield him from hecklers and
protesters carrying signs urging his impeachment or resignation in
connection with the White House sex and coverup scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the strategy is to gain Democratic seats in the
House, where the 206 Democrats are outnumbered by 228 Republicans.
A House vote to impeach a president requires a simple majority. All
435 House seats are up on Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Republicans outnumber Democrats, 55 to 45. A
two-thirds vote _ or 67 senators _ would be needed to convict a
president and remove him or her from office. There are 34 Senate
seats up on election day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing the president can do _ especially given the
common agenda we have with Democrats _ is to do his job,'' says
White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart. ``It's a case of where
good policy is good politics.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton may be bucking history if he hopes to boost
Democrats' strength.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Romer, chairman of the Democratic National Committee and
governor of Colorado, says the party of an incumbent president has
never boosted its total of House seats in the sixth year of a
presidential term.
</P>
<P>
   The party in power in the White House typically loses 35 seats
in the House in the sixth year of a presidency, Romer says.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are hoping to hold losses below that level in order to
claim that voters are standing by Clinton in the face of GOP-led
impeachment efforts.
</P>
<P>
   When he does travel, Clinton is opting for carefully staged
political events featuring invited guests and closed-door fund
raisers in private homes rather than the boisterous open air
campaign rallies designed to ignite voter turnout and spark local
media coverage,
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will continue to raise money for Democrats, flying to
Chicago on Friday to help Sen. Carol Moseley-Braun, D-Ill., and to
St. Louis later Friday to raise money with House Minority Leader
Richard Gephardt, D-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has not scheduled any open air campaign rallies
for the president before Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that going from town to town and from rally to
rally is what helps most Democrats around the country,'' Lockhart
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's last major overnight campaign swing is a scheduled
two-day trip to California on Oct. 20-21 to help raise campaign
funds for Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif. The latest polls in the
state show Boxer and Republican challenger Matt Fong locked in a
close race.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials deny that Democratic candidates are shying
away from appearances with the embattled president.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland Gov. Parris Glendening, who shunned Clinton at a
campaign appearance in his state in late September, has now
appealed for a joint appearance with the president in hopes of
forestalling a formidable challenge by Republican Ellen Sauerbrey.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will campaign in Maryland on behalf of Glendening and in
New York on behalf of the Senate campaign of Rep. Charles Schumer,
D-N.Y., locked in a tough fight with three-term Sen. Alfonse
D`Amato, R-N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
