<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-ONLINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN E! FOR EFFORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ She's 25, an Encino native and engaged. And no,
she didn't really get a master's degree in Must-See TV from the
University of California at Burbank.
</P>
<P>
   But Wanda, the campy TV maven at E! Online who hosts a weekly
chat attended by hundreds, has proven a huge hit in the year since
her oh-so-modest debut.
</P>
<P>
   Wanda in fact is the !ital!nom de net!off! of one of E! Online's
editors, a true TV junkie who really does follow the ins and outs
of Bailey and Claudia on ``Party of Five,'' Amanda and Billy on
``Melrose Place'' and numerous other characters on numerous hits
and cult faves.
</P>
<P>
   What she doesn't like to do, however, is give out her real name.
Being an Internet star can be an uncomfortable experience in some
ways for an attractive young personality who still has pretensions
to a private life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wanda has stalkers, one or two,'' the editor said of her alter
ego. ``Sometimes you get strange e-mails that freak you out. One of
the strange things on the Internet is you can have such intimate
relationships with people and not know who they are.''
</P>
<P>
   The editor originally wanted to create an online character who
took television much less seriously than do many critics, she said.
Wanda was the result.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea I had is that I love fan sites where they're dishy,''
Wanda said. ``I love TV so much. All my friends would always call
me because I know what's going on on all the shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, her bosses agreed to let her create an online
persona dishing the latest dirt to far more extended group of
``friends'' on the Internet. In September 1997, the weekly chat
debuted with just 10 participants. But her bosses were patient with
the new feature, and it blossomed quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Wanda talks with hundreds of followers in the 3 p.m. Monday
chats, with thousands more people reading the transcripts that are
posted afterward at the site. Oh, and she kept her day job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still an editor, but this has obviously become much more
of a prominent role,'' Wanda said. ``I spend more time on it then
my bosses will ever know.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes personally answering an eye-straining 200 or so
e-mails a day from fans. She even got some hundred e-mails from
people concerned about her whereabouts when she recently took a
week off for vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people write three times a day,'' Wanda said. ``A lot
think I'm their personal entree to Hollywood. The reality is, I
guess I am for them.''
</P>
<P>
   In between working her regular job, handling the Wanda load and
carrying on a regular life, the editor still manages to watch a
remarkable amount of television.
</P>
<P>
   Wanda attributes her TV fixation to ``growing up in the 1980s in
the Valley,'' where she loved watching ``thirtysomething,'' her
all-time fave, which she still catches regularly on the Lifetime
Network.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like angst, I like drama, I like human emotion and family,''
Wanda said. ``And dysfunction, obviously. It's dysfunction that got
me where I am today. My mom will be happy to read that.''
</P>
<P>
   GAMES WE LIKE: A decade and a half after Flight Simulator
debuted, Microsoft added the one thing critics always clamored for:
guns.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Combat Flight Simulator is fully compatible with
Flight Simulator 98 planes and will convert the thousands of other
plane models created by third-party companies and enthusiasts since
Flight Simulator 5.0 came out.
</P>
<P>
   You can even add guns and bombs to the civilian models, so that
747 isn't defenseless when it drops into a dogfight between U.S.
P-51 Mustangs and German Me-109s.
</P>
<P>
   Clever graphic tricks make the backgrounds look smashing.
Incredibly detailed physics models take into account such details
as the declining weight of ammo and fuel during a mission and the
resulting effects on performance.
</P>
<P>
   Run the game with a force-feedback joystick and accelerator card
and you'll be in ready-room heaven.
</P>
<P>
   The game is confined _ in this iteration _ to U.S., English and
German fighters in the European theater of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   But the great thing about the Flight Simulator has been its
expandability, allowing that game's millions of rabid fans to add
their own planes, scenarios, landscape, even such complements as
air traffic control packs. Expect way more of that when this hits
the shelves Nov. 5.
</P>
<P>
   FIGURES AND NUMBERS: So, just how big IS the Intenet these days?
Depends on who you're asking. The Industry Standard, a fine
technology-oriented news weekly, recently asked nine different
prominent consulting firms, and got, well, nine different answers.
</P>
<P>
   The highest estimate came from a Nielsen Media
Research/CommerceNet study conducted in June that estimated 70.5
million U.S. Internet users aged 16 and up. Intelliquest was right
behind, at around 67 million users in a somewhat earlier study.
</P>
<P>
   On the other end of the scale, Simmons and MRI respectively
estimated 48.2 million and 49.1 million users over the age of 18.
Three other studies, with massive sample sizes ranging from 35,000
to 50,000 people, pegged the total somewhere between 56 million and
60 million users each.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say, at least one in six Americans probably is an
Internet user _ and perhaps as many as one in four.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
