<DOCNO> NYT19981009.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8938 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BACHARACH-CD-TEX     10-09 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACHARACH-CD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CD WITH ELVIS COSTELLO INTRODUCES BACHARACH TO YET ANOTHER
GENERATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Painted From Memory,'' the new album by Elvis Costello and
Burt Bacharach, is dedicated to children in the two artists'
families. This is fitting. Not only is Costello, despite his long
and largely mythical connection to punk-rock, a musical child of
Bacharach, but Bacharach's music has a timelessness about it, which
should be passed on from generation to generation.
</P>
<P>
   Should be. It was surprisingly difficult to find this
much-anticipated CD in stores, but it was even more astonishing to
encounter blank stares from salesclerks after asking about it.
</P>
<P>
   You kids these days. Don't you know that Bacharach has left a
legacy that's stretched from pre-''Casino Royale'' to post-''Austin
Powers,'' from Marty Robbins singing ``The Story of My Life'' to
Rupert Everett leading a sing-along of ``I Say a Little Prayer'' in
``My Best Friend's Wedding''? That alt-rockers such as Stereolab
and R.E.M. have sung the praises of his songwriting?
</P>
<P>
   Bacharach's music has been part of the pop culture for 40 years,
but although modern rockers such as Oasis and soul singers such as
Tevin Campbell have covered his songs, we only found one Web site
dedicated to him. He deserves better _ let's hope that when Rhino
Records releases the three-CD ``The Look of Love: The Burt
Bacharach Box'' on Nov. 3, it'll be a lot easier to find.
</P>
<P>
   My affection for Bacharach comes from my own father-son
connection. My dad owned a copy of ``Make It Easy on Yourself,''
which included many of Bacharach's '60s hits with lyricist Hal
David. Its soft, melancholy music was the perfect mood-setter for
those quiet times between Sunday Mass and Sunday lunch, back in the
late '60s and early '70s, when the family actually ate lunch at the
table. You didn't want to turn up the volume on this record; it
would spoil the almost subliminal melancholy.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about the Costello collaboration is how it evokes
that mood. Bacharach is known primarily as a songwriter, but his
true strength lies in his arranging skills. Bacharach rarely went
over the top _ his songs were more often matters of subtle
punctuation rather than loud exclamation points. The softly
bleating flugelhorns on ``Toledo,'' one of the best songs of the
new CD, echo Herb Alpert's guy-with-a-hopeless-crush trumpet on
1968's heart-tugging ``This Guy's in Love With You''; the female
choruses sprinkled throughout ``Painted From Memory'' recall the
``whoa-whoa-whoa'' chorus that introduces Dionne Warwick's ``Do You
Know the Way to San Jose?,'' also from '68. There's no denying how
affecting these songs are. Bacharach's subtle arrangements put you
in a lonely place, but in a good lonely place _ one that,
oxymoronically, makes you not feel so alone. Misery loves company,
and for all the gentle swing of Bacharach's music, lyricist David
sure could reach for the sorrow: In ``Walk on By,'' Warwick told a
lost love to ignore her if he saw her on the street, because the
pain would just be too much if they met again. In the Fifth
Dimension hit ``One Less Bell to Answer,'' a dumped woman tries to
look on the bright side of a breakup, only to be reduced to tears.
</P>
<P>
   Bacharach's music always responded elegantly to these words, as
it did to David's more upbeat, swingin' '60s side (''The Look of
Love''; ``What's New, Pussycat?''). A poor singer, Bacharach always
attracted the right muses to sing his and David's songs. His
favorite was Warwick, but he had big hits with Jackie DeShannon
(''What the World Needs Now''), the Carpenters (''Close to You''),
B.J. Thomas (''Raindrops Keep Falling on My Head'') and a host of
others.
</P>
<P>
   Like many prolific songwriters, however, Bacharach hit a slow
period; he was quiet for much of the late '70s, and the early '80s
found him mostly writing for movies, usually with then-wife Carole
Bayer Sager. Although he produced a few hits (''Arthur's Theme,''
``That's What Friends Are For''), the pop landscape had subdivided.
The guy who once shared the airwaves with the Beatles and the
Stones couldn't be found on the same stations with disco dollies
and hair-metal bands. Those who preferred harder-edged rock stopped
paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   But during the '90s, we've been rediscovering our parents' (and
grandparents') music. Frank Sinatra performed with U2's Bono, Tony
Bennett appeared on MTV, and swing is hot again. Yet Bacharach,
till the Costello collaboration, has seemed relatively quiet. Until
you remember that Mike Myers used him as an epitome of '60s cool in
``Austin Powers.'' Or you discover that Bacharach worked with
Warwick again in this decade, as well as with James Ingram and
Earth, Wind &AMP; Fire. He has even performed with Oasis' Noel
Gallagher.
</P>
<P>
   And now he's working with Costello, who at 43 roughly belongs to
my generation the same way the 69-year-old Bacharach roughly
belongs to my father's. The songwriters are kindred spirits:
musically eclectic, seeking new challenges, obsessed in many ways
with the misfires of love. At its best, this music tugs at your
heart even before you realize that you're humming along with it.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the sort of stuff that will get easy radio exposure;
you'll have to seek the album out. It's worth the hunt, not just
because it's a good CD, but because it provides a gateway to
Bacharach's REALLY good older stuff. And with that Rhino set due
out next month, it's the perfect time to reopen the door to
Bacharach's world.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
