<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVICE TO THE NEW PARENTS: ENJOY HER WHILE YOU CAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two of my colleagues became parents for the first time Sunday
night. Husband and wife both work at the newspaper, and it was a
hoot watching the progress of the pregnancy and the excitement in
the daddy-to-be's eyes when he would speak of the impending arrival
of his child, and hearing the elation in his voice several days
after his daughter's birth as he recounted the details of her
delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever close friends have a new baby, there's a desire to pass
along some truly significant piece of advice that will stick with
them forever. All I could think of was, ``Enjoy the early years,
'cause once she hits puberty she won't be worth killing _ although
you'll give it serious thought from time to time.''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly words to warm the cockles of a new parent's heart,
but true nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Nature's cruel joke on the parents of girls is called puberty.
That delightful bundle of love who used to crawl up in your lap at
every opportunity, who would run as fast as her little legs would
carry her to greet you when you arrived home, turns into a
venom-spewing, hormone-spawned creature from some dark, evil place.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, she looks like your child, and at times can still display
hints of her former sweet self _ usually when she wants something
that only you can provide. But the mood swings are instantaneous,
and the degree of anger and frustration almost inexplicable in its
intensity.
</P>
<P>
   What in a teen-ager's life can evoke that kind of rage?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is just about anything. Life is a tremendously
desperate experience for a 12-year-old girl. And 13-, and 14-, and
15- ...
</P>
<P>
   But fear not, new parents. The ultimate revenge cometh. It's
called grandchildren. If you're lucky, it will be several decades
in the making, but eventually you'll get to sit back and enjoy the
show.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Bob and Lisa, revel in the joy and fascination
that your new baby girl will bring. As Elizabeth Leland Davis
learns the ways of her new world from you, so too will you learn
from her. Cherish each moment of discovery that she makes _ from
the first time she really notices her perfect little fingers to her
growing affection for that favorite plush-toy companion _ or an
imaginary friend.
</P>
<P>
   My mother loves to tell the story of my sister's make-believe
friend, a turkey she named Murder. I kid you not. That might
forebode a twisted adulthood, but Kristi grew up to be a highly
intelligent, extremely talented teacher. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   As for Baby Libby, save every art project, every letter home
from camp, every photograph that documents the milestones of her
life _ birthdays, holidays, her first mud pie. You'll want to share
them with her when she is grown.
</P>
<P>
   Be sure to capture the obligatory
naked-child-getting-into-the-bathtub photograph. It will be great
leverage for when she starts to date.
</P>
<P>
   You're probably spending a good deal of your time scrutinizing
every fold of skin, every fuzzy strand of hair on her head, the
length of her eyelashes, the way her mouth looks like a tiny,
upside-down butterfly, how she smells so ``new.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether she's 2 weeks or 20 years old, you will never tire of
tiptoeing to the door of her room to stand silently by, just to
watch her sleep. Enjoy it while you can.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and a columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Her e-mail address is
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com and her phone number is (817)
390-7599. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
