<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8948 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSERVANCY-CELEBRATI     10-09 1791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSERVANCY-CELEBRATION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATING 20 YEARS OF SERVICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL BIDWELL 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They had to plead for donated postage stamps to
get out their message, but the dozen people who banded together in
crowded living rooms 20 years ago were determined to save the Los
Angeles Central Public Library from the wrecking ball.
</P>
<P>
   Their fight took two years, and they won.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with a $900,000 annual budget and a paid staff of seven,
the 6,000-member Los Angeles Conservancy is the largest historic
preservation group on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   The group's track record speaks for itself: nearly three dozen
preservation successes, a more-than-90 percent win record.
</P>
<P>
   Even developers who do battle with the conservancy on a regular
basis can't deny it: That struggling group of a dozen has become a
power in the fabric of Los Angeles politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly we never anticipated the evolution this far down the
line,'' said Margaret Bach, the group's founding president. ``We
never could have seen what we'd be in 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The mission of the conservancy is simple: to preserve valuable
old buildings and neighborhoods, tangible storehouses of our city's
history and guides to Los Angeles' future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just a sentimental, knee-jerk reaction: `It's old,
it's worth protection','' Bach assured. ``We continue to applaud
the sensible growth and development of the city. But we need to
have a sense of the past, too.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not enough to save a building only to let it stand empty,
conservancy officials say.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really want to keep the buildings in use as a vibrant part
of an urban landscape,'' Bach said.
</P>
<P>
   In fighting to preserve the library, for example, the
conservancy didn't object to demolition of a part of the building
so a new addition could be built.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because we want to have the best buildings saved, that
doesn't mean we want to put them all under glass,'' said Linda
Dishman, the conservancy's executive director. ``Sometimes change
is part of life.''
</P>
<P>
   In its campaign to save the remnants of Los Angeles history, the
conservancy hasn't always made friends. Some developers have
complained that the group's demands would interfere with the use of
their property, or that preservation would be too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   And some city officials, wanting to shepherd projects to
fruition, have griped that the conservancy is too demanding, too
willing to drive up the cost of development to preserve features of
doubtful historic value.
</P>
<P>
   But John Molloy, head of the city's Redevelopment Agency, said
that while the agency and the conservancy have faced off many
times, they do not see themselves as enemies or even as permanent
adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time we are partners,'' Molloy said.
``Occasionally, a development opportunity will come along with
which we'll not see eye to eye on some aspect of historical
development, and we have to respectfully disagree. But that goes
with the territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Differences of opinion prevail over one of the conservancy's
latest causes, St. Vibiana's Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   The church at Second and Main streets was built in 1876 as the
Archdiocese of Monterey and Los Angeles' first cathedral. But when
the 1994 Northridge Earthquake took its toll on St. Vibiana's, the
archdiocese started laying the groundwork for demolition.
</P>
<P>
   That is, until the conservancy stepped in.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Redevelopment Agency and Mayor Richard Riordan's
support for Cardinal Roger Mahony's decision to tear down the
cathedral and build anew on the same grounds, the conservancy's
four-year campaign to preserve the church has made headway.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, the Catholic Archdiocese of Los Angeles agreed
to build a new cathedral elsewhere and to let the conservancy try
to find a buyer who will preserve the old structure _ perhaps as a
hotel or an office building. But Molloy doubts the group will be
successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the cost involved, I don't know if we'll ever be
able to see anything there that's economical (to develop),'' Molloy
said.
</P>
<P>
   Archdiocese spokesman Father Gregory Coiro _ who characterized
the archdiocese's relationship with the conservancy as alternately
``adversarial'' and ``amicable'' _ is equally doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   ``They very much want that building to be preserved _ and in the
meantime, it's standing there red-tagged,'' Coiro said. ``It's not
a healthy thing to remain there.''
</P>
<P>
   Dishman acknowledges that the Conservancy has sometimes raised
hackles but said the group simply wants the city and developers to
adhere to preservation guidelines set down for communities
nationwide by the U.S. Department of the Interior.
</P>
<P>
   And, she said, while one issue may provoke a spirited fight,
another issue may find the conservancy on the same side as an
earlier foe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have good relationships with the city, with a number of
developers, and I think much of being able to accomplish things in
this city is relationships,'' said Dishman. ``We don't want to
alienate anybody. We just want to save buildings, and I think we
have a good history of compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   Some former adversaries even become fans.
</P>
<P>
   Philip MacDonald of Irvine, owner of the Bob's Big Boy
restaurant on Riverside Drive in Burbank, was one of the
conservancy's biggest enemies in 1992, when the group forced
historic-site status on the 1949 eatery. The restaurant was failing
economically, and MacDonald was considering tearing it down and
selling the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt they were telling us what to do with our property, and
nobody likes being told what to do,'' MacDonald said. ``But in
retrospect, (the decision) forced us to deal with the property in a
more aggressive manner.''
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald terminated a 20-year lease with Marriott, hired a
Marriott defector to run the hamburger joint and remodeled inside
and out, adding weekend car hops and enticing local car clubs to
use the restaurant as headquarters for Friday cruise nights. Last
year, more than 600,000 customers chowed down on burgers and fries
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I owe it all to the L.A. Conservancy,'' MacDonald said
with a laugh. ``They got me in the restaurant business. Right now,
there's nothing I could do that would even compare to the
restaurant. Business is off the charts. It's been a real success
story.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of victory the conservancy relishes.
</P>
<P>
   But if the group can't win compliance any other way, it's
prepared to go to court, as it has three times in its 20-year
history.
</P>
<P>
   A 1988 courtroom challenge to a Redevelopment Agency policy on
transfer of development rights was settled short of a trial,
resulting in rules that encourage developers to preserve old
buildings rather than tear them down.
</P>
<P>
   In its 1989 fight to save the Ambassador Hotel, site of the 1968
assassination of presidential candidate Robert F. Kennedy, the
conservancy forced the Los Angeles Unified School District to
prepare a new environmental impact report that has so far halted
plans to build a new high school on the site.
</P>
<P>
   And its most recent court battle over the fate of St. Vibiana's
Cathedral, has, for the time being, succeeded in preventing
demolition.
</P>
<P>
   For a group that started as a dozen conservationists in a city
notoriously _ but erroneously _ known for having little history,
the Conservancy has been a busy bunch. And they say their work's
not nearly done yet.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the city's earliest buildings _ adobe structures,
made of mud bricks _ ``just sort of melted away'' with age and
disuse, many buildings erected from the mid-1860s to the 1930s
still stand, Dishman said.
</P>
<P>
   And often, they stand on a spot where a developer wants to put a
parking garage or strip mall.
</P>
<P>
   So the conservancy keeps watch over the old buildings _
including more than 400 city-designated landmarks _ determined to
hang on to these structures that document Los Angeles' growth from
desert town to worldwide icon.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen of the old landmarks were felled by the
wrecker's ball before the conservancy took root in 1978. Among the
lost ones are the 1929 downtown Richfield Building, considered the
greatest example of art deco architecture in the city, demolished
in 1968, and the Dodge House, a 1916 private West Hollywood home
considered a design masterpiece, demolished in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   But once the 1926 Central Library building had been saved from
demolition, the handful of historic-minded people decided to stick
together to tackle other preservation issues.
</P>
<P>
   The group, whose members pay from $20 (for students) to $2,500
(for corporations) to belong, is now ranked as one of the top
preservation organizations in the nation, said Elizabeth Goldstein,
director of the Western Office of the National Trust for Historic
Preservation.
</P>
<P>
   But the conservancy isn't resting on its laurels.
</P>
<P>
   It's joined South Pasadena and El Sereno residents in fighting
the extension of the Long Beach Freeway (710) through their quiet
neighborhoods. And it's working to convince the developer of a
strip of Sunset Boulevard to preserve historic features of the
Cinerama Dome theater.
</P>
<P>
   Later this month, the conservancy will be at City Hall promoting
a City Council resolution that would prohibit property owners from
tearing down old buildings until a plan for a replacement is
approved.
</P>
<P>
   And in late November, the conservancy plans to release a
detailed proposal for the revitalization of a three-mile strip of
the Broadway Theater District, urging development of loft
apartments above the theaters and, in between theaters, more retail
shops.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's always St. Vibiana's to try to sell to a compliant
developer.
</P>
<P>
   The conservancy is also looking outside downtown for future
preservation projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the Valley is going to be an important part of our
future,'' Dishman said. ``So much has happened in the Valley since
World War II. And you need some distance to provide a context for
evaluation. We're just beginning to see what's worth preserving
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Among structures ripe for saving are the Valley Municipal
Building on Sylvan Street in Van Nuys, an early Cadillac
dealership, some historic homes, some strip malls along Ventura
Boulevard reminiscent of early streamlined design, and some old
businesses with early neon signs.
</P>
<P>
   So, as the conservancy plans to mark its 20th anniversary Sunday
at the Memorial Coliseum in Exposition Park, its members are
reflecting on the past but looking toward a busy future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a big agenda,'' said Dishman. ``We're not done yet. In
a perfect world, we would never have to fight to save a building,
but I don't see that happening in the near future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
