<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-NASA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLENN, DISCOVERY ASTRONAUTS REHEARSE LAUNCH COUNTDOWN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ Mercury astronaut John Glenn, flanked by
a half-dozen younger space travelers, scrambled aboard the shuttle
Discovery on Friday to rehearse the launch countdown scheduled for
late this month.
</P>
<P>
   The 77-year-old U.S. senator was alert and eager despite the
early hour. Glenn and his colleagues awoke before sunrise to don
bulky pressure suits for the 10-mile ride to the launch pad aboard
NASA's gleaming Astrovan, just as they are slated to do Oct. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, who became the first American to orbit the Earth on Feb.
20, 1962, as part of a Cold War-era moon race with the former
Soviet Union, is preparing for a mission aboard Discovery. The
three hours spent strapped aboard their spacecraft closed out a
week of launch drills for the shuttle crew and marked one of the
final milestones in an eight-month training regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really looking forward to this,'' Glenn assured the dozens
of news reporters who gathered at Kennedy to follow the seldom
covered exercises required of all shuttle crews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, I was scared to death I might catch a cold or
something and might be replaced,'' Glenn said of the
suspense-filled weeks leading up to his Mercury mission. ``I feel
that same way right now.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, NASA shuttle managers will gather in Florida for a
thorough review of Discovery's launch and mission preparations.
They are likely to formally approve the Oct. 29 launch date
established when Glenn was named to the flight crew in January,
said agency spokeswoman Lisa Malone.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn was the sixth of Curt Brown's crew to board Discovery
following the commander, pilot Steve Lindsey, mission specialist
Steve Robinson, European Space Agency astronaut Pedro Duque and
Japanese astronaut Chiaki Mukai. Flight engineer Scott Parazynski
was the last.
</P>
<P>
   Though a national hero, Glenn ranks low in the shuttle's chain
of command, a point he attempts to stress each time he is
questioned about his flight.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn was seated on the shuttle's lower deck, below and out of
the view of the flight deck. He has no window. Other than to
confirm to ground controllers that his communications systems are
working, Glenn has been instructed to say little during the
countdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payload specialist 2, loud and clear,'' Glenn barked on the
occasions he was asked for a voice check of his communications
gear.
</P>
<P>
   Payload specialists are considered as non-professional
astronauts, experts who fly on the shuttle to participate in
research efforts that NASA would rather not ask its own shuttle
corps to undertake.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn will serve primarily as a subject in a range of medical
experiments designed to investigate similarities between the
stresses of space flight and aging.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn will furnish medical specimens and data that may furnish
new insights into bone and muscle deterioration that occurs in
astronauts. Other experiments will look into balance, sleep and
immune system disorders that bother the elderly and that astronauts
experience temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   As Friday's mock countdown lapsed into its final moments,
Brown's crew rehearsed the escape procedures they would follow if
the shuttle's explosive fuel system ruptures or a fire starts.
</P>
<P>
   The fliers scrambled from Discovery's hatch when informed by
launch controllers their unfueled rocket engines had ignited then
shut down abruptly with three seconds until lift off.
</P>
<P>
   Once outside the shuttle, the astronauts marched 100 feet across
the metal gantry of their launch pad to seven metal baskets 200
feet above the ground. Though not required to do so Friday, in a
real emergency the astronauts would dive into the baskets for a 21
second slide down a 1,200 foot long cable to the base of the launch
pad.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the nature of an actual emergency, escaping
astronauts would either sprint into a concrete reinforced
underground bunker or hop into an armored personnel carrier to
drive to one of the surrounding helicopter pads for final
evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   The cage-slide portion of the escape has not been used in 91
previous shuttle launches.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn is deemed by NASA to be physically qualified for such an
escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are physical requirements that every one has to pass,
regardless of age. John has passed all of those with flying
colors,'' said Rick Linnehan, a veteran astronaut who serves on
NASA's shuttle crew support team at Kennedy. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
