r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSERVANCY-TOURS-LAD     10-09 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSERVANCY-TOURS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOURS TAKE IN ORNATE, HISTORIC BUILDINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL BIDWELL 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Downtown Los Angeles isn't all modern
glass-and-steel buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Look up and you'll see terra cotta angels, art deco entryways,
Greek columns and rococo cornices carefully decorating a downtown
that was built largely between the 1880s and the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, the Los Angeles Conservancy organized its first tour to
spread awareness of the architectural features that abound
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Saturday walkabouts draw as many as 100 people.
Tourists are among them, but surprisingly, more than half the
tour-takers are Southern California residents who marvel at the
ornate structures so close to home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their reaction is surprise,'' said docent Joe Spencer of West
Los Angeles, who has been leading tours for 15 years. ``We have a
lot of people who were afraid even to go downtown. They go (on
tours), and they come out alive and they see that it's beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   The Conservancy currently offers 10 tours focusing on
neighborhoods or architectural themes downtown. Tour reservations
are required a week in advance. Except for the hourlong Biltmore
and Union Station tours, walks generally last two to 2{ hours. Cost
is $5 per person, free for Conservancy members. For more tour
information, call (213) 623-2489 between 9 a.m. and 5 p.m.
weekdays.
</P>
<P>
   The tours are:
</P>
<P>
   PERSHING SQUARE: Covers landmarks around the park named after
World War I Gen. John ``Black Jack'' Pershing, including the
Biltmore Hotel, the Bradbury Building, the Oviatt Building and the
Grand Central Market. Begins at 10 a.m. every Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   TERRA COTTA: Visits to the Wurlitzer Building, Palace Theatre,
Clifton's Silver Spoon and other downtown sites spotlighting the
use of clay molded and fired into different shapes and forms.
Begins at 10 a.m first Saturday of every month.
</P>
<P>
   MECCA FOR MERCHANTS: Rediscover downtown's first department
stores in the Seventh Street shopping district, a hotspot in its
heyday between 1909 and 1929. Other landmarks include the downtown
Pantages Theatre, the Los Angeles Athletic Club and the Fine Arts
Building. Begins at 10 a.m. fourth Saturday of every month.
</P>
<P>
   LITTLE TOKYO: A historic look at the Japanese community that
established this area, plus sites that include the Japanese
American Cultural Community Center, Noguchi Plaza, the First Street
North Historic District and the Higashi Hongwanji Buddhist Temple.
Begins at 10 a.m. first Saturday of every month.
</P>
<P>
   UNION STATION: Built in a combination of Spanish colonial
revival and streamline moderne styles; tour includes a visit to the
Fred Harvey Restaurant, closed to the public for nearly 25 years.
Begins at 10 a.m. third and fourth Saturdays of every month.
</P>
<P>
   BILTMORE HOTEL: Tours of the 1923 hotel include the kitchen, the
health club and _ if nobody's staying there _ the Presidential
Suite. Begins at 11 a.m. second Saturday of every month.
</P>
<P>
   MARBLE MASTERPIECES: Explores the use of marble in historic and
new buildings, from the One Bunker Hill Building built in 1931 to
the postmodern Coast Savings Building. Begins at 10 a.m. second
Saturday of every month.
</P>
<P>
   PALACES OF FINANCE: Spring Street Historic District, once known
as the Wall Street of the West, includes stops to see the glass
dome of the Banco Popular, the art deco lobby of the Title
Insurance Building, the Palm Court of the Alexandria Hotel, and the
Los Angeles Theater Center. Begins at 10 a.m third Saturday of
every month.
</P>
<P>
   ART DECO: Late 1920s modernistic style can be seen in the Oviatt
Building, the Sun Realty Building, the Garfield Building and the
Eastern Columbia Building. Begins at 10 a.m. every Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   BROADWAY THEATERS: Interiors of the largest concentration of
opulent pre-World War II movie houses in America, including the
Orpheum. Begins at 10 a.m. every Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
