<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-LASSOTHEWIND-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EGAN TACKELS `TRUE WEST' WITH SKILL, ENTHUSIASM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The task would daunt a less energetic, ambitious or cocksure
reporter: To somehow sum up the state of the American West today,
in all its frustrating and contradictory complexity, and accomplish
this formidable task in a serious, thoughtful book of less than 250
pages.
</P>
<P>
   But Timothy Egan of Seattle is not daunted by the size of a
story or what it takes to capture it. As readers of his 1990
Northwest classic, ``The Good Rain,'' and his prominent journalism
in The New York Times have come to learn, Egan is a reporter from
the REI School of Journalism, an intrepid and relentless news-hound
in hiking boots and Gore-Tex who is eager to ford any stream, climb
any peak, hike any trail, track down any interview subject, no
matter how reclusive, to get what he needs onto the page.
</P>
<P>
   Egan again demonstrates his considerable skills in getting the
story and telling it, too, in his new book, ``Lasso the Wind: Away
to the New West.'' This is an immensely entertaining and
informative tour through the 11 contiguous states west of the 100th
meridian, a fast-paced mix of ground-pounding reporting today and
often-overlooked Western history.
</P>
<P>
   It is also vintage Egan, or at least vintage book-version Egan,
filled with engaging first-person narrative that displays
unrestrained enthusiasm for what he sees as the delights of nature
(backpacking, fly-fishing, climbing) and of humankind (zinfandel,
baseball, cigars, Eric Clapton, Walla Walla sweets).
</P>
<P>
   As touched upon in his brief introduction, Egan's goal is to
uncover the ``true West'' (a phrase borrowed from playwright Sam
Shepard). His method is to devote each chapter to a Western place,
to sample its nature, highlight its history, to meet its people, to
examine its present conflicts and to offer a few conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Egan's training in objective news reporting (at the
Post-Intelligencer before The New York Times), however, seems
somewhat of a handicap when it comes to book-writing. He has a
dazzling ability to capture a place or a person in telling words
and details. But Egan, 43, seems less comfortable at interpreting
his material in much depth or spinning continuing narrative threads
throughout the book.
</P>
<P>
   So the chapters in ``Lasso the Wind'' read more like stand-alone
essays than connected sections of a whole.
</P>
<P>
   Some common themes do emerge, as Egan immerses himself in such
varied locales as Las Vegas; the Grand Canyon; Butte, Mont.;
Sunnyside, Wash.; Joseph, Ore.; and Escalante, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic struggle,'' Egan writes, ``is between the West of
possibility and the West of possession.''
</P>
<P>
   For too long, the West and its abundant wonders have been abused
as if there is no tomorrow (which too often came true). Forests
were wasted, resources squandered, animals slaughtered, rivers
dammed, unsuitable animals (cattle) introduced. And groups of human
beings, when they have encountered each other in the West over the
past four centuries, often have exhibited their absolute worst
behavior _ lying, stealing, pillaging, hating, murdering.
</P>
<P>
   No example of this may be more blood-chilling than Egan's
account of a long-covered-up 1857 massacre of California-bound
wagon train families by Mormons in Mountain Meadows, Utah. All
told, 157 men, women and children were tricked into believing they
were being saved from Indians but soon were set upon and executed
at point-blank range.
</P>
<P>
   Egan is an optimist by nature, shunning gloom and doom in a time
when many others see the West as astride the direst of straits,
with the remaining unspoiled land imperiled by runaway growth.
</P>
<P>
   Among Egan's most surprising observations is that the West is
now ``the most urban area in the country'' since ``86 percent of
all Westerners live in the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Egan remains encouraged about the West and its future,
seizing on such developments as the rebound of the American River
in California, the reintroduction of wolves and bison into open
spaces, the return of the Nez Perce Indians to their homeland in
Oregon, the growth of a multicultural society in central
Washington's agricultural country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The corrective is under way,'' Egan concludes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lasso the Wind'' is an impressive response to a daunting
assignment, perhaps not quite the book it might have been, but a
solid and welcome addition to Western writing nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, it is sad to note that Egan's accomplishment is
undermined by the carefree editing and fact-checking too prevalent
in publishing today. These shortcomings include nagging matters of
style and voice, but also more serious errors of fact (Terry
Tempest Williams writes non-fiction not poetry).
</P>
<P>
   Most inexcusable of all is Egan's assertion that Ernest
Hemingway shot himself with a pistol. It was a shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   Lasso the Wind. By Timothy Egan. Alfred A. Knopf. 247 pages. $25
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981009.0264 </DOCNO>
