<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SHARON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL'S NETANYAHU TO APPOINT SECURITY HAWK SHARON AS FOREIGN
MINISTER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In a move that sent conflicting signals about
prospects for peace with the Palestinians, Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu Friday said he would appoint security hawk Ariel
Sharon as his new foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon, now minister of national infrastructure, would start his
new job after the Cabinet votes on the appointment next week,
Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
   He characterized Sharon as ``the most appropriate man'' for
foreign minister. Netanyahu himself has held the post since
January, when David Levy resigned in protest over the slow pace of
peace negotiations with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings a wealth of experience, creativity and a proven
track record,'' Netanyahu said. ``And I think he knows well the
damage of war and the fruits of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the West Bank town of Hebron, violence continued
for a second day between Palestinian stone throwers and Israeli
soldiers as hundreds of Arab mourners gathered for the funeral of a
21-year-old protester killed in clashes on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   And in the Jordan Valley, a 19-year-old female Israeli soldier
was stabbed to death while standing outside a Jewish settlement.
The assailant, a Palestinian, was shot by setters and taken to a
hospital in Jerusalem. His motives were not known, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon's appointment to the foreign ministry was lambasted by
Israel's left-wing opposition and by some Palestinians as a sign
that Netanyahu doesn't want to make strides in peace talks with
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Others were more positive.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon's move comes only days before Israelis and Palestinians
are expected to make their first progress toward peace in months.
The negotiations have stumbled for 19 months, but now appear to be
on the brink of a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, Netanyahu is set to meet Palestinian Authority
President Yasser Arafat at the Wye Plantation outside Washington to
discuss a land-for-security deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps it means Netanyahu has made up his mind to go along
with this withdrawal,'' said Aryeh Naor, who was Israeli cabinet
secretary under former Prime Minister Menachem Begin twenty years
ago. He was referring to the Israeli troop pullback from 13 percent
of West Bank territory that will be on the table at next week's
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   A self-styled warrior-politician who raises sheep on a ranch in
the Negev desert, Sharon has wielded considerable behind-the-scenes
power in Netanyahu's right-wing government since it came to power
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   As foreign minister, Sharon would move out of the shadows of
power and into direct negotiations with the Palestinians on a final
peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   A leading critic of the peace accords signed with the
Palestinians and a vocal opponent of the proposal for a pullback of
Israeli troops from 13 percent of the West Bank, analysts suggest
Sharon may be a bigger threat to Netanyahu if he is left out of the
decision-making process than if he is let in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Sharon is the most dangerous politician for Netanyahu in
the coming elections,'' Naor said.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment caps a remarkable comeback for a man who was
disgraced and ousted from politics 15 years ago after an internal
government probe found him indirectly responsible for a Christian
Lebanese massacre of Palestinians during his tenure as defense
minister.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he has slowly moved back into politics with the
support of security hawks and religious Jews, particularly those
living in settlements in the West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime champion of the settlements, Sharon maneuvered to
create a new ministry of national infrastructure under Netanyahu
that would allow him to help the controversial communities grow.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, some Parliament members praised his appointment as a
step that would strengthen settlements. But skeptical settlers said
the move was meant to appease them just before Israel made
territorial concessions that would endanger their existence.
</P>
<P>
   When rumors of his appointment began, Sharon said that he would
not shake Arafat's hand during negotiations because he considered
the Arab leader a ``terrorist'' and a ``war criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, he said through a spokesman that he would work to
further Israel's platform of peace with security.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that in my role as foreign minister, I can assist in
advancing Israel's policy which is striving towards peace while
maintaining and protecting Israel's national and security
interests,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Palestinians say privately that Sharon may be the only one
capable of delivering Israel's vociferous right-wing, which is
vehemently opposed to any further territorial compromise.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one characterization of Sharon suggests they may
not relish the thought of working so closely with a man they
consider to have more blood on his hands than any other Israeli
leader.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian negotiator Mahmoud Abbas wrote that the former army
general was the ``cruelest and most hostile of Israelis'' in his
book ``Through Secret Channels,'' a chronicle of the peace
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sharon is a personality in search of a leadership role,''
Abbas wrote. ``His ambitions greatly outweigh his personal and
political abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Sharon will help or hinder agreements with the
Palestinians, events in Hebron on Friday underscored the fact that
peace is still elusive here five years after initial peace accords
were signed.
</P>
<P>
   In the midday heat, hundreds of Palestinians marched through
this divided city on their way to bury Amjad Natshe, a Jordanian
citizen shot by soldiers during violent demonstrations on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Hooded youths, some with machine guns, protested for a a second
day, chanting slogans opposing Jewish settlements and the peace
accords their leaders signed with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat's pro-peace Fatah party had called the march to protest a
curfew clamped on Palestinians living in the Israeli-controlled
part of the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fatah is fed up with the situation in Hebron,'' said Abdallah
Hishami, a 20-year-old Fatah supporter. The march, the first one of
its kind called by Fatah, was seen as a sign that peace agreements
were being questioned even by Arafat's most ardent followers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fed up with an agreement that puts thousands of us under
curfew for days,'' Hishami said. ``How can we have peace when there
are settlers in the city and the army continues to kill our
people?''
</P>
<P>
   Since January 1997, Palestinians have ruled 80 percent of
Hebron, where most of the city's 120,000 Arabs live. Israeli rules
the other 20 percent, where some 400 militant settlers are lodged
in five tiny enclaves.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Palestinian youths gathered at the border dividing
the Jewish and Arab sides of the city, where they pelted Israeli
soldiers with stones. The soldiers sat outside a security fence
that leads to the Jewish enclaves and shot back with rubber bullets
and tear gas.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the Israel-controlled sector, some 20,000
Palestinians seethed under a curfew for the tenth day. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Horan is a free-lance journalist based in Jerusalem. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
