<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TOYOTA TACOMA PRERUNNER IS ONLY HALF A TRUCK
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by CARS-GLANCE) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If it looks like a duck, walks like a duck and quacks like a
duck, the old saying goes, then it must be a duck.
</P>
<P>
   Not so with the Toyota Tacoma PreRunner.
</P>
<P>
   This compact pickup looks like a serious four-wheel-drive, with
knobby tires, high ground clearance, a bold grille, large front
bumper and other off-road styling cues.
</P>
<P>
   But underneath, it's just half a truck. Yep, two-wheel drive.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose you can get away with that in Texas and some other Sun
Belt states that have no really lousy weather and no really cool
places to go four-wheeling. This truck wouldn't sell well in
Denver, but it probably will do OK in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   My impression, though, is that it's more for show that action,
designed for the urban cowboy-wannabe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at me in my cool new truck with the off-road tires and
suspension,'' it screams out to other motorists on the freeway
during the rush-hour commute. Just don't force me into a showdown
on the dusty trail, pardner. I won't make it as far as your real
four-wheeler will go.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this little truck has a lot going for it, especially if
you have no real need for four-wheel drive. I found the high ground
clearance a plus during last week's storms as I negotiated some
deep puddles.
</P>
<P>
   The price is certainly right: $17,238 plus $447 transportation
buys the basic extended-cab truck, complete with four-speed
automatic transmission (I told you it was citified), 2.7-liter
four-cylinder engine, air-conditioning, power steering and brakes,
styled steel wheels, deluxe AM/FM/cassette stereo, front bench
seat, front-facing rear jump seats and dual air bags.
</P>
<P>
   In press material provided with the PreRunner, Toyota explains
that the vehicle is designed to look like its four-wheel-drive
counterpart, the Tacoma SR5.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 1998 PreRunner combines the rugged styling and off-road
performance of Toyota's four-wheel-drive pickups with the
affordability of a two-wheel-drive,'' the Toyota literature says.
That's a bit of a stretch, since the PreRunner doesn't really offer
all the performance of a four-wheel drive.
</P>
<P>
   A pre-runner is a ``class of vehicle used to pre-run an off-road
race course and preserve the race vehicles from damage,'' Toyota
says, and the Tacoma PreRunner, introduced as a 1998 model, was
developed in conjunction with Toyota's desert racing-truck program.
</P>
<P>
   I've driven four-wheel-drive vehicles all over Baja, and I'd be
hard-pressed to take a two-wheel-drive over most of the routes I've
covered.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm not making fun of this truck. I actually liked it, and I
know that most people who buy four-wheel drive never really use
that option. If you're among that group and you want a truck that
looks really cool but doesn't cost a bundle, then the PreRunner
might be just the thing.
</P>
<P>
   The four-cylinder engine cranks out a respectable 150 horsepower
and 177 foot-pounds of torque. It's slightly more powerful than the
142-horsepower, 2.4-liter four-banger that comes in the base
two-wheel-drive Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   This truck is so light that the four-cylinder offers plenty of
power for urban freeway driving as well as most light off-road
situations.
</P>
<P>
   I think, however, that if I were to buy a PreRunner, I would opt
for the 3.4-liter, 24- valve, twin-cam V-6, which brings 190
horsepower and 220 foot-pounds of torque. It's not really the extra
power I would be seeking with the V-6, however; you have to buy the
six-cylinder option to get a driver-controlled locking rear
differential, which could help you get through the muck in the
absence of four-wheel drive.
</P>
<P>
   The off-road suspension of the PreRunner includes Bilstein shock
absorbers, progressive-rate front coil springs, rear leaf springs
and a large front stabilizer bar. Included are 15-inch Goodyear
off-road tires. The ride wasn't as rough as you would expect from a
pure off-road design; this is a comfortable and smooth-riding
commuter vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Our test model came with some extras that I could live without,
such as the aluminum-alloy wheels ($995), a convenience package
($710) that added tilt steering wheel, cruise control and
tachometer (who needs a tach with automatic transmission?), and
custom pinstripes ($66).
</P>
<P>
   Other options were welcome, including the power windows and door
locks for $470 (well, it is a city vehicle), bucket seats to
replace the three-across front bench ($70), and a $299 hard-plastic
bedliner, a real necessity to protect the finish of the bed if you
do much hauling.
</P>
<P>
   Total sticker was $20,414.95, including transportation.
</P>
<P>
   For 1998, the PreRunner was offered only in the extended-cab
version, but for '99, a regular-cab model is available. Most pickup
buyers prefer the extended models, though.
</P>
<P>
   Like most pickups these days, the PreRunner has a cut-off switch
for the passenger air bag, which allowed me to put a tiny tyke up
front in a rear-facing child seat. I did have the child seat in the
rear for a while, too, but that limits how far back you can slide
the front seat.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel economy was a respectable 20 miles per gallon in the
city and 24 on the highway. The tank holds 18 gallons of gas,
plenty for a week of urban commuting.
</P>
<P>
   The PreRunner is built at Toyota's plant in Fremont, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   JAG TO OFFER SMART CRUISE: Jaguar's new S-type sedan, which goes
on sale next spring, will be the first car in the United States to
offer a ``smart'' cruise control, which uses doppler radar to
measure the speed and distance of vehicles ahead.
</P>
<P>
   This system judges the relative position of the vehicle ahead
and adjusts your acceleration and braking to maintain a safe
distance between you and it. If there is no one ahead of you, the
car will cruise at the speed you set.
</P>
<P>
   The system will be built by General Motors' Delphi Automotive
Systems, and will initially be available only in a few markets,
Jaguar officials said. No price tag has been announced.
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III writes on transportation issues for
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Contact him at 3201 Airport Freeway,
Suite 108, Bedford, TX 76022; telephone (817) 685-3810; e-mail
chambers &LR; star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 1734EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
