<HEADLINE>
DICKINSON THEATRES CONSIDERING BUYOUT OFFERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MISSION, Kan. _ The owners of Dickinson Theatres will decide
soon whether to accept any of several offers to buy the movie
exhibitor or whether they even want to sell, a company spokesman
said this week.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Downs, spokesman for the family-owned company based in
Mission, wouldn't identify the bidders. He did say at least one is
a competing exhibitor and at least one is an investment group.
</P>
<P>
   Two investment firms that have been buying movie chains are
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts and Hicks Muse Tate &AMP; Furst. Those two
earlier this year bought Regal Cinemas, based in Knoxville, Tenn.,
and combined it with another chain, Act III. A similar deal to buy
Denver-based United Artists fell through.
</P>
<P>
   Other parties rumored to be interested are CineMark USA and
Carmike Cinemas.
</P>
<P>
   Downs wouldn't say why the Dickinson family was considering
selling the chain of 30-plus theaters with more than 200 screens.
But industry observers say that it might have stretched its
finances too tight in a competitive environment.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kansas City area, Dickinson has experienced brutal
competition, particularly from AMC Entertainment Inc., which is
based in Kansas City. On one day alone last December, AMC opened
three megaplexes with a total of 74 screens. That increased the
number of first-run screens in Kansas City by 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Act III opened an 18-screen megaplex last year at Station
Casino Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Herb Buchbinder, an analyst with George K. Baum &AMP; Co. who
follows the movie exhibition industry, said anyone considering
buying Dickinson might be trying to get it at a fire-sale price.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a good time to try to sell anything, but if
(Dickinson) is hurting financially, they might take what they can
get,'' Buchbinder said. ``It just makes some sense that someone
might try to steal this thing away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
