<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASINO-REFERENDUM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPENDING IS LOPSIDED ON MISSOURI GAMBLING AMENDMENT CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ When it comes to lopsided political
campaigns, look no further than the Nov. 3 boats-in-moats contest
between gambling proponents and opponents in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   According to Missouri Ethics Commission reports, spending
through Sept. 30 by the casino industry's election committee,
Missourians for Fairness &AMP; Jobs, already had topped $5.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The tally for the anti-gambling group, Show Me The River Inc.,
is $34,505.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, in the statewide election to legalize slot
machines, the industry spent more than $12 million. The
anti-gambling group spent $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a top-down effort that has all the money it needs,''
said Mark Andrews II, Show Me's chairman who also led the 1994
opposition campaign. ``We are a grass-roots effort that is an
effort of the heart.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, however, Show Me's grass roots don't appear to grow much
deeper than Andrews' own pocketbook.
</P>
<P>
   To date, the retired manufacturing company executive has
personally donated to or lent the committee $32,000 of its $34,000
bankroll, according to Ethics Commission financial disclosure
reports made public this week. Ten other persons have contributed
amounts ranging from $30 to $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the numbers, Andrews insists his organization isn't a
one-man show.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew early on that in order to finance a little bit of
activity, somebody had to loan some money to the campaign,''
Andrews said. ``We had to get a start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're about people, not about money. This is not a documented,
big-time campaign like they're running. This is hundreds of
beehives of activity all around the state.''
</P>
<P>
   The Show Me group has aligned with several church organizations
opposed to gambling on mostly religious grounds that are working
against Amendment 9.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed constitutional amendment would retroactively
legalize riverboat casinos moored in man-made lagoons. The Missouri
Supreme Court last year outlawed games of chance, including slot
machines, aboard those boats in moats.
</P>
<P>
   Unless voters approve Amendment 9, effectively nullifying the
court's ruling, nine of the state's 15 casinos could be forced to
close or operate without the slot machines, which typically
generate about two-thirds of casinos' revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Show Me's largest expenditure to date is $11,300 to its campaign
management company, Topline Corp. of Ballwin, Mo. It has also paid
about $5,800 to the Spangler Group of Camdenton, Mo., for campaign
work.
</P>
<P>
   Huge campaign spending by gambling companies _ which have 10,000
employees and more than $1 billion invested in the jeopardized
casinos _ should surprise no one, said Don Poston, spokesman for
the industry-financed committee.
</P>
<P>
   Harrah's Entertainment Inc. and Station Casinos Inc. have each
contributed $2.3 million to date. Harrah's has four threatened
casinos in North Kansas City and Maryland Heights. Station has four
casinos in the state, but only two _ in Kansas City _ that are
classified as boats in moats.
</P>
<P>
   The Flamingo Hilton Casino, with one riverboat in Kansas City,
has contributed $506,600. Players Services Inc. in Atlantic City,
N.J., which operates the Players Island casinos in Maryland
Heights, has contributed $282,800 to date.
</P>
<P>
   Poston said Thursday that he wouldn't characterize the campaign
as David vs. Goliath.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got built-in (church) organizations all across the
state,'' said Poston of the opponents. ``We've got to get to people
nobody has touched. It's a costly process.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 3.5 million voters in Missouri in more than 2
million households. We have to buy mailings, phone banks,
television advertising or whatever we have to get to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee clearly is doing just that.
</P>
<P>
   Its reports show 10 paid staff members and a raft of
consultants, pollsters, advertising firms and others.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the campaign's chain of command is Winner//Wagner
&AMP; Mandabach, a national campaign consulting group.
</P>
<P>
   Counting significant television advertising costs that are paid
through the company, Winner//Wagner to date has received $2.57
million from the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous Kansas City consulting firms are also working for the
riverboat committee, including SGB Communications, where partner
Scott Burnett is unopposed in November for a seat on the Jackson
County Legislature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 1744EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
