</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTIST-LEADER-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN BAPTIST LEADER RICHARD LAND CHALLENGES CONSCIENCES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD VARA 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Richard Land challenges consciences _ whether his audience is
fellow Southern Baptists or national radio listeners.
</P>
<P>
   He has called on the Southern Baptist Convention to repent for
past racism. He calls for President Bill Clinton, a Southern
Baptist, to resign because he has lost the ``moral authority'' he
needs to be president. He calls for husbands to love their wives
and for wives to obey husbands.
</P>
<P>
   Land, a former Houstonian, is the high-profile president of the
convention's Nashville-based Ethics and Religious Liberty
Commission. It is the convention's watchdog on national religious
liberty issues such as school prayer, as well as social and moral
issues such as abortion and gambling. The Princeton- and
Oxford-educated Land voices the convention's biblically
conservative stance.
</P>
<P>
   He is an example of the media-savvy evangelicals who have
sparked the growing conservatism in the 16 million-member
convention. His flexibility has earned him some begrudging respect
from opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are out to confront the culture,'' Land said. And confront
he does.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the national convention amended its doctrinal
statement, the Baptist Faith and Message, to define family
relationships. ``A husband is to love his wife as Christ loved the
church,'' the amendment stated. ``A wife is to submit graciously to
the servant leadership of her husband even as the church willingly
submits to the headship of Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   It was written by a seven-member committee that included Land.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment drew applause from the floor but incredulity from
the media, as well as many Baptists and mainstream believers. In
response, the First Baptist Church of Raleigh, N.C., voted Sept. 25
to leave the national convention.
</P>
<P>
   It's the latest convention action to draw national attention. In
1997, the convention launched a boycott of the Walt Disney Co.,
arguing that Disney promoted immoral attitudes in some of its
movies and company policies. Disney denies the charges.
</P>
<P>
   The convention has taken staunch anti-gay rights stands and
anti-gambling stands. The leadership has opposed the ordination of
women. These are stands that Land has no problem defending.
</P>
<P>
   ``What fascinates the press,'' Land said in a recent Houston
visit, ``is that it is not used to people willing be so politically
incorrect. They are fascinated by this largest of Protestant
denominations in the country that really doesn't seem to be overly
concerned about acquiescing to the late-20th-century prejudices of
secular America.''
</P>
<P>
   First Baptist of Raleigh voted 264-23 to leave the convention
after a membership of 153 years. The church elected its first
female deacons in 1874, and half of the 48-member deacon board is
female.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very sad we were in a position that we had to make a
decision,'' the Rev. Daniel Day, senior pastor, said. ``The mood of
regret and sadness was heavy within the room.''
</P>
<P>
   Land, never at a loss for words, argues that the American family
is in crisis. ``In 1963, 83 percent of American children were
reared in intact homes,'' Land said. ``Today less than half of
children are reared in intact homes and that is a severe crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Land, like the Southern Baptists now in national convention
leadership, says that social problems, from family breakdown to
abortion, can be remedied by adhering to traditional scriptural
interpretations such as maintaining chastity prior to marriage. He
shares such views on his daily, half-hour national radio talk
program, ``For Faith and Family.'' It airs on 180 stations,
including Houston's KTEK (1110 AM), at 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   His conservatism resonates with Southern Baptists, said Bill J.
Leonard, dean of Wake Forest University's new divinity school.
Land's views reflect the views of the convention's current leaders,
and ``Baptists either agree with those views or seem willing to
accept them in order to stay Southern Baptist,'' Leonard said,
adding that his own ideas differ. He sees the convention's outlook
as close to the views of the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Parham of the independent Baptist Center for Ethics in
Nashville was a former staff member of the convention's Ethics &AMP;
Religious Liberty Commission. He left in 1991, but respects Land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard and I disagree significantly on theological, cultural
and strategic issues,'' Parham said. ``But I find him to be an
opponent and not an enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard sees the options for Christian faith as either
capitulation to the current culture or retrenchment of the culture
of the 1950s,'' Parham said. He charges fundamentalists who want to
use the Republican Party to bring national political change have
lost sight of the church's call to transform the culture through
spiritual means.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Land says he thinks he should voice the convention's views to
secularized press and a similar society.
</P>
<P>
   But he admits that Southern Baptists are not a monolith. While
opposed to abortion in principle, he said, some conservative
Southern Baptists will accept abortion to save the life of the
mother, while others will oppose it except in cases of incest or
rape.
</P>
<P>
   Land rejects the criticism that he is following a ``right-wing
agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We spend as much time taking about environmental stewardship
as we do talking about a lot of issues dear to right-wing groups,''
Land said. ``When right-wing groups agree with our positions, I
applaud their good tastes.''
</P>
<P>
   Land also spearheaded the convention's 1995 resolution
apologizing to African-Americans for the convention's racist past.
The Southern convention split with their Northern Baptist
counterparts over slavery before the Civil War.  &UR;  &LR; ``When we went to
Atlanta (for the 1995 meeting) and celebrated our sesquicentennial,
we couldn't do it without apologizing for racism, for slavery, for
segregation,'' Land said.
</P>
<P>
   It is Land's willingness to listen to opposing views that earns
the respect of critics at the opposite end of the theological and
political spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   It is a flexibility that was formed during his childhood in
Houston. The son of Leggette and Mary Lee Land, he grew up in South
Park, attending South Park Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Religion was always very important, and the church was very
important in my family's way of life,'' he said. Land was intent on
becoming a career military officer but felt a call to the ministry
at age 14. ``I resisted for a couple of years because I wanted to
go to West Point,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Preparing for seminary, Land decided to attend Princeton
University, where he graduated magna cum laude in 1969. He said
that school was hostile to religion, and he often found himself the
lone evangelical in a class.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I found it exciting and challenging,'' he said. ``I
learned a whole lot more about why I believed what I believed.''
</P>
<P>
   To help maintain his faith during the summers of his college
years, Land attended a Bible study at the home of Paul Pressler, a
Baptist who would later become a leader in the convention's
conservative movement. After Princeton, Land attended New Orleans
Baptist Theological Seminary, where he met Paige Patterson, then a
graduate student. Patterson, now convention president, and Land
shared a concern for what they considered ``liberal'' biblical
teachings at the seminary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several of my professors had real questions about whether Adam
and Eve were real people,'' he said. ``I had a professor in
religious education who basically was no longer certain of the
supernatural.''
</P>
<P>
   He met his wife, Rebekah, a psychotherapist, at the seminary.
The couple has three children.
</P>
<P>
   Land, who wanted to become an educator, went to Oxford
University and graduated in 1975. He was reunited with Patterson
when Land taught at Criswell College. Patterson was president of
that Bible school in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Land was in the leadership of the conservative movement when it
began controlling the convention in 1979. In 1981, he joined the
Christian Life Commission, the forerunner of the Religious Liberty
Commission, which he now leads.
</P>
<P>
   Land said Baptists' national battle over biblical views was
costly. Several Baptist colleges and universities, such has Baylor
University in Waco, have become autonomous to avoid conservative
control.
</P>
<P>
   Several churches have loosened ties to the convention by
redirecting moneys to other groups such as the Cooperative Baptist
Fellowship. A few, such as the Raleigh church, have left. Parham
points out that state conventions like Texas, Virginia, North
Carolina and a few others are distancing themselves from the
national convention.
</P>
<P>
   But Land is satisfied with the results. ``We have turned our
seminaries back to where they once were,'' he said. ``We have
turned our agencies back to where they should have been.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
