<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9057 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHELL-LAYOFFS-$ADV11-     10-09 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHELL-LAYOFFS-$ADV11-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHELL-LAYOFFS-$ADV11 &HT;    
 &HT;    SHELL UNIT WILL LAY OFF 20% OF WORKERS 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 11) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HILLARY DURGIN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Shell Oil Co. has notified employees at its exploration and
production unit that the company plans to lay off 740 workers, or
20 percent of its staff, as part of a larger cost-cutting effort.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston-based oil company employs 3,700 workers at its Shell
Exploration &AMP; Production Co. unit.
</P>
<P>
   Shell also said it is reviewing its portfolio of oil and gas
properties to determine which are not essential.
</P>
<P>
   The action comes on the heels of a warning by the chairman of
its parent company, Royal Dutch/ Shell Group, that earnings in the
current and next quarters would be depressed. Royal Dutch/Shell
also said it would shutter four large European offices.
</P>
<P>
   As oil prices remain depressed at levels 35 percent below
year-ago highs, other major oil companies said they are either
studying layoffs or already have announced them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know many executives today who are very positive,''
said Carol Freedenthal, a principal with Jofree Corp., a Houston
energy consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the way through the industry we're detecting a very
pessimistic view (from executives) that the low prices are not
going away, that they really have to compete to sell their goods,
and that we don't have much control of what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   A Texaco spokeswoman said Thursday that the company was
reviewing ``all operations, which may lead to some changes.'' The
company has approximately 3,000 employees in Houston, most of whom
are affiliated with its exploration and production business.
</P>
<P>
   Texaco said earlier this year that it plans to defer up to 10
percent of its 1998 capital spending budget of about $4.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Amoco Corp. is expected to lose jobs as part of the company's
pending acquisition by British Petroleum.
</P>
<P>
   And last month, Atlantic Richfield Co. said the company plans to
cut employment to avoid being taken over by another oil company
during this period of low prices.
</P>
<P>
   At Exxon Company U.S.A., a spokesman said no layoffs had been
announced. He noted that the company's capital spending budget for
the first six months of 1998 had increased 7 percent to $771
million.
</P>
<P>
   The layoffs at Shell are not a surprise. A month ago, the
company said it was considering layoffs as part of an effort to cut
its 1999 budget for worldwide deepwater exploration. At the time it
said layoffs in the Gulf of Mexico were not likely as part of that
effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are also reviewing our assets to determine those that are
not strategic to our portfolio,'' a Shell spokeswoman said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The spokeswoman said that the company's exploration and
production business had been holding meetings with employees at its
different divisions for some time regarding the possible work force
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Employees received a memo via e-mail Tuesday detailing the
specifics of the cuts, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The company said that it will undertake an employee severance
program soon and expects to have completed the layoffs by year-end.
</P>
<P>
   No details were available on what sort of positions or which
divisions would be most affected by the cuts. Shell's joint
ventures are not going to be affected, the spokeswoman said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
