A9063 &Cx1f; var-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      10-09 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Oct. 11, will move Saturday in the `a' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-REVIEW (Washington) _ At the crisis-wracked annual
meetings of the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank _
the institutions built 53 years ago to create global stability out
of the wreckage of World War II _ the 21st century village was
termed the ``new international financial architecture.'' President
Clinton insisted said it would be designed ``to tame the pattern of
boom-bust on an international scale.'' Unfortunately, the
groundbreaking ceremony is years away. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-REVIEW (Washington) _ If the House votes to impeach
Clinton, the matter goes to the Senate, which must decide, by a
two-thirds majority, whether to convict him and, thus remove him
from office. So the Lewinsky matter has suddenly injected a new
order of disruptive force into the Senate contests. Voters, even
those who support Clinton, expect their political leaders,
Republican or Democratic, to renounce Clinton's behavior and
morals, and candidates have been doing that. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   MERGER-REVIEW (Undated) _ As banks, brokerage firms and
insurance companies combine into huge new conglomerates, and with
legislation wending through Congress to make such mergers even
easier, there is increasing concern about the amount of personal
financial and medical data that can be collected under one roof. By
Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-REVIEW (Moscow) _ The world watched tens of thousands of
Communists and their allies march on the Kremlin last week,
demanding the removal of Boris Yeltsin and his lackeys, and a
telegenic protest it was. What it wasn't was a good gauge of
Russian discontent. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   GIRLTALK-REVIEW (Undated) _ When Monica Lewinsky poured her
heart out to Linda Tripp, she was clearly looking for girl talk.
Girl talk runs deep. By Jenny Lyn Bader.
</P>
<P>
   HALLOWEEN-REVIEW (Undated) _ It's not easy being Monica _ even
for one night. Th nation's major mask makers have taken a pass on
Monica Lewinsky masks this Halloween, worried about possible
lawsuits over the use of her likeness. So revelers will have to
improvise with wigs and berets, and many plan to do so. Party
stores and costume makers report that this season's best-selling
spooking gear is all about Ms. Lewinsky, President Clinton and
Hillary Rodham Clinton, Linda Tripp and even Kenneth Starr. By Mike
Allen.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-REVIEW (Shanghai) _ So many of China's neighbors in Asia
are mired in financial wreckage that economists and international
traders fear that China may be the last and heftiest domino getting
ready to fall. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   BIZTALK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Wall Street loves jargon, which makes
its business sound mysterious and important and serves as a sort of
secret handshake. By Leslie Eaton.
</P>
<P>
   GEOPOLITICS-REVIEW (Undated) _ If there is a worldwide canard
about political correctness, it is that it's an American disease.
Geopolitically  &QL; 
speaking, though, that is wildly incorrect. Every country has its
own strain. &QL; 
By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   BABE-REVIEW (Johannesburg) _ In South Africa a woman is a babe
first, last and foremost. The better-looking she is, the easier
life is. By Suzanne Daley. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
