<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FANTASY-FOOTBALL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL COULD USE MORE FANTASY, LESS OF REAL THING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   into a fantasy world, this would be a good time.
</P>
<P>
   The No Fun League was especially so Sunday. In Phoenix, where
our TV games are chosen by sadistic network weasels, we were
treated to the Dolphins-Jets punt-a-thon and the ultimate atomic
stink bomb: Philadelphia at Denver.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not saying the Eagles gave up in the second half. They gave
up in the first half. At one point, the Philadelphia secondary was
actually playing hacky sack.
</P>
<P>
   But in all fairness, I noted that the Eagles were careful never
to actually touch the hem of Terrell Davis' garment.
</P>
<P>
   Other rotten match-ups: Giants-Bucs, Chargers-Colts and, of
course, Seahawks-Chiefs, which was halted for 54 minutes because of
heavy rain and lightning _ the only fireworks during a dismal NFL
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   For the average fan, this turn of events might lead to dire
consequences _ yardwork, baby-sitting or, horror of horrors, a
Sunday afternoon cooking show.
</P>
<P>
   While braising pork chops might seem more appealing than
watching Danny Kanell impersonate an NFL quarterback, this isn't a
problem for fantasy leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some might argue that fantasy leagues are saving the
NFL from itself.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the league. Five weeks into the season, there are three
winless teams (Washington, Carolina and Philadelphia) and seven
teams with one victory. Other teams with slightly better records
(Arizona, New Orleans and Atlanta) just don't have the legs to
last.
</P>
<P>
   Quick quiz. The Dallas Cowboys' next three opponents have how
many wins among them? Answer: one.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, two of them are actually tied with Bye Week.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the bad football, fantasy owners always have a
reason to watch the games.
</P>
<P>
   Without fantasy football, the Eagles-Broncos might have seemed a
little, ah, dull. Don't tell that to the guy who started John Elway
at quarterback, only to watch Bubby Brister get the privilege of
whacking out the Eagles. (By the way, it's really hard to pry a
shoe out of a big-screen TV.)
</P>
<P>
   This game featured a slew of fantasy favorites besides Elway.
With Denver, you had Davis, wide receivers Rod Smith and Ed
McCaffrey and tight end Shannon Sharpe. As for the Eagles, some
poor souls were rooting for receiver Irving Fryar and running backs
Duce Staley and Charlie Garner.
</P>
<P>
   News that the Falcons were blowing out the Panthers was fine
with fantasy owners who started Falcons quarterback Chris Chandler,
running back Jamal Anderson or receiver Tony Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Purists argue that fantasy leaguers don't watch the games for
the right reasons, that we should be more interested in wins and
losses than statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Well, this weekend, the winless Eagles play the winless
Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   The purists can have my ticket. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tip of the week &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't be fooled by the performance of Panthers quarterback Kerry
Collins against Atlanta. He ran up his numbers after Carolina was
behind, 38-3, and this week he benched himself in favor of backup
Steve Beuerlein. I think Pittsburgh quarterback Kordell Stewart
will have a bounce-back game against Cincinnati. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Waiver wire &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Look for Miami rookie John Avery to find his way into the
lineup. Coach Jimmy Johnson never has been enamored with starter
Karim Abdul-Jabbar. In Kansas City, Rashaan Shehee looked good in
relief of Donnell Bennett on Sunday, but Bennett should be back
this week despite a bruised hand. Don't expect Cowboys running back
Chris Warren to score two touchdowns every week, but he will get
significant time spelling Emmitt Smith. Running back Gary Brown
appears to have the starting job for the Giants, such as it is. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
One-hit wonder &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This week it's Detroit receiver Johnnie Morton, who had two
catches for 138 yards and one touchdowns. Morton is good, but he's
not going to catch too many more 98-yard bombs. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bill Muller can be reached at bill.muller(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
