<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9075 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLLEGE-TESTS10-COX     10-09 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-TESTS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOME SAY SAT FAILS THE TEST OF FAIRNESS
 &HT;    310&AMP;add.
 &HT;    BY NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As thousands of high school students sweat over SAT
exams Saturday, a debate is raging over whether colleges and
universities should continue making the test such an important
factor in the admissions process.
</P>
<P>
   While one advocacy group says standardized tests are biased
against minority students and should be downplayed, the College
Board contends the SAT is fair and greatly helps gauge a student's
readiness for college.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the National Center for Fair and Open Testing
(FairTest) released a study claiming that some U.S. colleges and
universities have moved away from using the SAT to evaluate
students, partly because high school grades are better at
forecasting success in college.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colleges that have de-emphasized standardized admissions tests
have found that these reforms promote equity and excellence,'' said
Charles Rooney, assistant director of FairTest. ``Applicant pools
have become more diverse without any loss in academic quality
because a focus on test scores deters many otherwise qualified
minority, low-income and female students.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, College Board spokesman Jeffrey Penn said that if
certain groups do poorly, it doesn't mean the test is biased. Some
students may have difficulty because their schools just didn't
prepare them as well, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We contend that it is not unfair to minorities and women,''
Penn said. ``I think part of what FairTest and other test critics
in general assume is that everyone would get the same score.
They're disappointed that some groups fare worse than others on the
test. This is not an IQ test to measure aptitude, it measures
learned reasoning.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn said college admissions directors already place more weight
on grades, class rank and course work, although 82 percent of all
four-year colleges still require SAT scores.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The three-hour SAT, which measures a student's verbal and math
skills, is a rite of passage the average American high school
student endures at least once. Nearly 2 million students take the
test each year.
</P>
<P>
   Attacks on standardized tests have gained increased attention as
affirmative action programs are being dismantled across the
country. One college system highlighted in FairTest's survey was
the University of Texas, which now admits all applicants who are in
the top 10 percent of their class regardless of test scores.
</P>
<P>
   That policy was instituted after the landmark Hopwood federal
court ruling banned colleges in some states from considering race
as a factor in admission. It was ordered not by the University of
Texas system but by the state Legislature, where its backers hoped
it would lead to a rebound in the number of minority applicants at
the schools, which has dropped since the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The new policy itself has proved controversial. Some say that
students whose schools grade more leniently gain an unfair
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Muhlenberg College in Allentown, Pa., was also examined in the
FairTest study. After two years of research, faculty and board
members of the private four-year college voted in 1996 to make
standardized tests an optional part of the admissions process for
five years.
</P>
<P>
   In place of test scores, students must submit a graded academic
paper and be interviewed. Counselors say they have seen an increase
in minority, female and low-income applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the SAT say Muhlenberg's practice is good because
it gives students an option for how they will be evaluated and
increases their comfort with the college. Although Muhlenberg has
not seen an increase in minority enrollment, officials believe the
policy works as a hedge against student assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the wake of all the anti-affirmative action stuff that's
been going on, one might be able to argue that this SAT-optional
policy has allowed Muhlenberg to maintain a consistent African
American and Latino population,'' said Christopher Hooker-Haring,
the school's dean of admissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been some evidence that these students are assuming
an inhospitable climate at all predominantly white universities and
these schools have seen their numbers drop,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
