<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVES WARN VOTERS AGAINST APPROVING POT FOR MEDICAL USE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Four Republican senators and former national drug
policy director William Bennett urged voters Friday not to approve
state ballot initiatives that would legalize marijuana for
medicinal uses.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Gordon H. Smith of Oregon, Jon Kyl of Arizona, Wayne
Allard of Colorado and Frank Murkowski of Alaska joined Bennett at
a Capitol Hill news conference to warn that such ballot measures in
their states would, in the words of Allard, ``send the wrong
message to youth.''
</P>
<P>
   Initiatives to legalize the drug for debilitating diseases such
as cancer, glaucoma or AIDS are also on the November ballot in
Nevada and Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, who was drug policy director under President George
Bush, said that ``marijuana is not medicine. It is a serious drug
that leads to a lot of problems. A doctor who tells you to smoke
marijuana is a lousy doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   But R. Keith Stroup, executive director of the National
Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws, a Washington
advocacy group, said later that opponents of the initiatives ``are
confusing a medical issue with the war on drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Stroup insisted that ``there is no connection between a doctor's
being able to prescribe a medication to relieve pain and suffering
and what kids use on the street. Our opponents are holding sick and
dying patients hostage to the war on drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference Smith predicted that Oregon voters will
``overwhelmingly'' approve a measure that would allow people
suffering from ``debilitating medical conditions,'' to use
marijuana, but said he wanted ``to make a plea'' for state
residents to ``think twice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will unreasonably complicate the efforts of law enforcement
to do their jobs if we allow people to grow marijuana in their
homes even if it is held up as (being for) medicinal use,'' Smith
said. He added that any vote to legalize the drug ``should be made
based on science, not on popularity.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyl warned that an initiative on the Arizona ballot that would
legalize drugs such as marijuana and heroin for medical use ``is a
first step toward the total legalization of (illicit) drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, voters in California and Arizona approved measures to
legalize marijuana for certain medical uses. Since then, the
Arizona legislature passed a law nullifying the state's Proposition
200 initiative. In California, the Justice Department has sued in
federal court to invalidate the state's Proposition 215, arguing
that federal law, which bans marijuana, supersedes any local law.
</P>
<P>
   Some cannabis clubs in the state, set up to dispense marijuana
to people who are ill, have been shut down, and the federal
government is seeking to shut down the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Allard warned that a proposed amendment to Colorado's
constitution that would legalize medicinal marijuana could have
``grave'' consequences because it would grant a drug panel power to
add other illegal drugs to the list. However, the amendment is in
limbo because a recount has been ordered of signatures on petitions
backing the proposal to determine whether there are enough to place
the issue on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Murkowski said a ballot initiative to legalize so-called medical
marijuana in Alaska contains major loopholes that ``would
effectively weaken laws against marijuana.''
</P>
<P>
   He called the measure ``very dangerous,'' charging that it would
shield medical marijuana users from criminal penalties if they
cause an accident under the influence of the drug.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
