<HEADLINE>
SKIP AWAY COULD REACH $10 MILLION PLATEAU AT BREEDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Horses don't race for the practice. This is a money
game, and Skip Away can become the first horse to win $10 million
in purses if he captures the $1 million Jockey Club Gold Cup at
Belmont Park Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Cigar holds the record, which includes Europe and Japan, with
$9,999,815. Skip Away stands at $9,506,360 and will soar past the
mark if he takes his third Gold Cup in a row. But Skip Away, who
has won nine graded stakes in a row, seven this year, must win
because the $200,000 place purse won't get the job done. The big
gray, certain to be Horse of the Year, is scheduled to race once
more after Saturday, in the $4 million Breeders' Cup Classic at
Churchill Downs Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along that this is a generous horse who has done
so much for a lot of people,'' said Sonny Hine, who trains Skip
Away (career record 36-18-10-5) for his wife, Carolyn. ``If I can
get him the money title and do it in a race that only Kelso has won
more than twice (five consecutive times, 1960-64), well, I think
that would give Skippy his place as one of the greatest horses of
all time. He doesn't have to convince me that he's one of the
greatest, but this would be a nice thing to get for him. We've been
trying to get these little milestones all along, so people will
take notice of what he's accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kelso was great. He was Horse of the Year five times, and
nobody's going to beat that. But I want to see the money record
broken for the horse and my wife. It's also nice to say that I
trained the money-winningest horse in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away will face five foes in the Gold Cup, but it would
appear that only Gentlemen really stands in his way as the other
four seem hopelessly overmatched. Gentlemen, winner of an
impressive $3,408,598, beat Skip Away in last year's Pimlico
Special and ran a strong second to him in the Woodward Stakes at
Belmont Sept. 19. The Gold Cup, at 1 1/4 miles, is an eighth of a
mile longer than the Woodward, which will be to Skip Away's
advantage, but Gentlemen will wear blinkers for the first time in
his career (22-13-2).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're putting blinkers on him trying to find a way to win,''
said Richard Mandella, who trains Gentlemen for R.D. Hubbard,
chairman of the board of Hollywood Park. ``It is an attempt to get
him to focus more. Not to say that he isn't focused, but I'm
desperate to find a way to get 110 percent out of him. And
sometimes blinkers help do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gentlemen signaled that he enjoys the blinkers, going 5 furlongs
in :58 3/5 at Belmont Monday, the first time he had worked with the
help of the rogue's badge.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still pumped up from his work the other day,'' said
Mandella. ``I'm happy with the way he's training, but I also know
what I'm up against. Skip Away is a great horse; you don't need to
tell me that. But the thing is, Gentlemen is a great horse, too.
It's true that he's older now (6), and I feel that I haven't had
the same horse at any time this year that I had in the past. When
he was the best, I wouldn't have traded him for any other horse. I
haven't had that this year, so now I'm grasping at straws trying to
find that one thing that will get him over the hump.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It poured Friday, and the Belmont surface was turned into a sea
of slop. The forecast for Saturday calls for showers, but it should
be of little concern to Skip Away and Gentlemen if the track is off
for the Gold Cup. Skip Away is 3 for 3 on a wet track in his
career, while Gentlemen is 2 for 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``The track won't bother us if it comes up wet,'' said Hine.
``The last Jockey Club Gold Cup win and his Blue Grass win were
both over wet-fast tracks. Skippy won by more than 6 lengths in
both.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gentlemen can run on anything,'' said Mandella. ``Being able
to run on fast tracks, off tracks, and on turf are admirable
traits. Those are things breeders will be attracted to.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are four other Grade I races on Saturday's Breeders' Cup
preview card. The $400,000 Frizette Stakes, for 2-year-old fillies
at 1 1/16 miles, is headed by Things Change, listed at 6-5. Sharp
Cat is even money to take the $400,000 Beldame Stakes, for filles
and mares 3 years old and up at 1 1/8 miles. Buck's Boy, at 2-1, is
the horse to beat in the $500,000 Turf Classic, for 3-year-olds and
up at 1 1/2 miles. And the $400,000 Champagne Stakes, for
2-year-old colts at 1 1/16 miles, is wide open, with Tactical Cat
the lukewarm choice at 5-2.
</P>
</TEXT>
