<HEADLINE>
JONES-JOHNSON MATCHUP MAY BE IN THE CARDS  
 TIME NEARING FOR TEBUCKY JONES TO SHOW WHAT HE CAN DO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ It's not easy for a rookie to start in the
NFL, but sometimes it's necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Edwards has been forced into the fire, and each week the
running back from Georgia seems to douse the flames that once
seemed to be burning around him.
</P>
<P>
   That time has not quite come for Tebucky Jones, but one must now
wonder, is it around the corner? After all, when the Patriots
drafted the 6-foot-2-inch, 216-pound Syracues defensive back as
their second pick in the first round (22d overall) and decided he
could be a bump-and-run cornerback, the idea was to have him go
against big receivers _ like Keyshawn Johnson, who will be in town
with the Jets Oct. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Will that be Jones's baptism?
</P>
<P>
   ``All along, I've thought about that as a key matchup,'' said
Patriots coach Pete Carroll. ``We'll see how it goes this week and
next. We don't have to throw him into the fire. Ty Law is having a
great year and Chris Canty has done a nice job. The urgency to do
it isn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans are eager to see more of Jones, a high-profile pick. The
Patriots passed up a chance to take defensive lineman Vonnie
Holliday, who is now starting for the Packers. New England paid
Jones $5.375 million over five years, including a signing bonus of
more than $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Such an investment has to be put to use sometime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm anxious, sure,'' said Jones. ``But patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones says he understands that all of Patriots Nation is
awaiting his arrival at right cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go home (to New Britain, Conn.) and stuff ... and
everybody's wondering,'' he said. ``My wife's wondering. She leaves
the games early every week.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears that Jones is aware of the timetable that has been
established for him, though neither he nor Carroll will say what it
is.
</P>
<P>
   Right now he's limited to special teams. He still hasn't broken
into the substitute packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had a big week in practice,'' said Carroll. ``Ty missed
Wednesday's practice, so he had a chance to play that spot. He's
also played on our scout teams and he did a fine job. He's
progressing.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether he played the role of the Chiefs' James Hasty
or Dale Carter against Terry Glenn in practice, Jones said, ``I was
Tebucky Jones.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, who will face Carter Sunday when Kansas City visits
Foxboro Stadium, thinks there are a lot of similarities between
Carter and Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not exactly Dale Carter because he doesn't have that type
of experience yet, but he can be in that mode,'' said Glenn.
``Tebucky is strong and he's fast. He has to work on getting
himself in and out of his sets a little more and he'll develop into
a nice player.
</P>
<P>
   As for Jones's situation, Glenn _ a former top draft choice _
said, ``Usually when you're a No. 1 pick, they throw you into the
fire, but they've done a good job not throwing him in. I think in
the long run that's going to help his confidence a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   This might be a good week for Jones to get his baptism, and
don't bet against him seeing some playing time. Jones's case is
slightly different than Edwards's because Edwards is playing the
position he's accustomed to while Jones has had to shift from
strong safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Ditka told me last week that he would have loved the
chance not to throw some of his young kids into the fire so quickly
but he had no choice,'' said Carroll. ``In this case, we haven't
had to do that to Tebucky. He's been learning his game and position
slowly. When he does get out there, he's going to have had the time
to really study the position he's about to play. We know he's going
to be a superb athlete and a guy we can grow with in the future. We
have to be careful on when we decide the time is right.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll likes to reward good play with more playing time. He has
praised the work of Steve Lofton all season. He's been trying to
get Steve Israel back on the field. When Jones assumes a bigger
role, the roles of both veterans will be reduced or eliminated.
When Jones is ready, last year's No. 1 pick, Canty, will likely
have to spend more time on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   There are many personnel decisions Carroll must deal with, but
the bottom line is that Jones needs to be on the field if he's as
good as the Patriots think he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's getting better and better every day,'' said secondary
coach Ron Lynn. ``He's a joy to be around because he wants to play
so badly and he's receptive to everything we tell him. He has so
much enthusiasm that we can't wait until he gets out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn said the staff has often been tempted to just throw Jones
into action, especially against the bigger receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tempted from day one,'' said Lynn. ``Here's a big guy who can
run fast. Hopefully, we're getting close to that day. At some
point, he's going to line up against Keyshawn.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, who haven't allowed a deep ball this year, don't
want to ruin Jones's confidence by exposing him to getting burned.
But they'll have to pull the trigger soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when I'm standing there on the sidelines, I think
back to when I was a running back and picture myself running with
the ball up and down the field,'' said Jones. ``I'm playing
(special teams) but I'm not playing corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are people who want to see me, but I want to see
me, too. They'll probably break me in in the nickel at first and
then increase it gradually. I go up against Terry Glenn and the
rest of our receivers every day. When I see some other receivers
and compare them to Terry, I say to myself, `I can cover them,'
because there aren't many that compare to Terry. I think I'm as
anxious as anyone to see how I'd do out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
