<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GIANT STEP FOR THE BAY AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- Their experience is broad and deep, from the
Atlanta Hawks, the Portland Trail Blazers, the San Jose Sharks, the
Carolina Panthers, and the Kansas City Chiefs. The sales staff
comes from basketball, hockey, and football, but at the China Basin
Ballpark Company, they're selling baseball.
</P>
<P>
   For baseball, the most reluctant of big league sports to market
itself, the future of the grand old game may be as bright as its
present. The home run odyssey of Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa, the
continuing work-ethic elegance of Cal Ripken Jr., and close playoff
contests have rescued baseball from the sour aroma lingering from
1994, a season with no World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's upsurge of renewed fan interest coincides with a
construction boom. Nearly every team has built or is building a new
ballpark, that doubles as destination entertainment center and
family-fun emporium.
</P>
<P>
   Its foundation is built, the girders are up and Pacific Bell
Park will likely be ready for Opening Day for the 2000 season of
the San Francisco Giants. It hasn't been easy, financially or
politically, which is why it may be a model for other cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first privately financed ballpark since Dodger
Stadium in 1962,'' says the team's executive vice president, Larry
Baer. ``An all-private plan is not for everyone. We're not martyrs
here. We had to take a creative approach to raise money and we're
not suggesting that for every city, but the days of 100 percent
public funding seem to be numbered. Every deal now is a hybrid,
with every team contributing.''
</P>
<P>
   In a city where most issues are decided by referendum, the
nation's foremost left-wing constituency supports many social
services, but subsidizing baseball is not one of them. Four times
the Giants asked for taxpayer help in referendums; four times, they
struck out. Finally, in 1996, 67 percent of the voters allowed the
Giants to build a privately financed ballpark closer to downtown
than chilly, windswept Candlestick Park, where they have played
since 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate sponsorship, even $50 million in naming rights, pours
only so much concrete. The team asked fans to pony up $4,500 for
each charter seat. ``You have legal title in perpetuity to that
seat, and it is fully transferable,'' says R. Michael Patterson,
director of sales, meaning it can be willed or sold. So far, 14,000
charter seats have been sold. Last week, 15,000 regular season
tickets went on sale and sales are brisk, reinforcing the law of
supply and demand for the rest of the 41,000 new seats.
</P>
<P>
   At cavernous Candlestick (now known as 3Com Park), only 8,500
full season tickets were sold this year. When Patterson escorts
potential buyers through his exposed-brick offices here, he points
to pictures of Camden Yards in Baltimore, Jacobs Field in
Cleveland, and Coors Field in Denver, saying, in cadence,
``All-sold-out!'' In luxury suites, 50 of the new park's 65
skyboxes have been rented.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco is not a great baseball town. The success of
football's 49ers has created a fandom of front-runners. The Giants,
who have not won a World Series since moving here from New York in
1958, share northern California with the Oakland A's, who have won
four.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing, therefore, is a must. The team is thinking of
occasional 4 p.m. starts, ``since so many people work on an East
Coast schedule,'' according to Baer. This plan would draw
money-managers on Montgomery Street and flex-time telecommuters
from Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Front-runners feed on pennants. ``There clearly is a correlation
between a team in a new ballpark and success on the field,'' says
Baer. ``But the Baltimore Orioles, who had the biggest payroll, did
not fare well on the field this year. There's no guarantee.''
</P>
<P>
   Pro basketball is torn by labor strife while pro football is
saddled with sagging dynasties and so-what games. Baseball's moment
is here, but the game on the field is still more important than
luxury suites.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
