<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALANGER'S FIELDING SHOULD EARN HIM HONORED STATUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Mark Belanger, a .228 lifetime hitter, belongs in
the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Do we not agree that Mark McGwire will someday be inducted into
the Hall because he is classically representative of the impact
sheer power has on the game of baseball? Fine. Then consider this:
The late Mark Belanger was the Mark McGwire of fielding. It's true.
I looked in the dictionary the other day, and under the word
``fielding,'' it said, ``What Mark Belanger did better than anybody
else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of years after I left the Orioles,'' says San Diego
Padres coach Merv Rettenmund, ``I was playing against him. I was
thrown a breaking ball that I should have been able to pull and I
hit it up the middle. Mark Belanger was there to throw me out. What
was he doing there? Next time up, I was thrown a fastball that I
shouldn't have been able to pull and I hit it deep into the hole.
Mark Belanger was there to throw me out. What was he doing there?
But that was Mark Belanger. He was the greatest shortstop I ever
saw.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Martinez discovered the joy of being Mark Belanger's
teammate very early in his career. ``In my very first game,''
recalls the venerable Nicaraguan righthander, ``I had the bases
loaded with nobody out in Detroit. Both Brooks Robinson and Mark
came over to me. They said, `Calm down. Just throw the way you did
in Triple A to get yourself here. Make them hit it and we'll catch
it.' As it turned out, I struck out the side. But in the next
inning, someone hit the ball into the hole and Belanger made the
same kind of play (Derek) Jeter made the other night against
Cleveland (i.e., plant hard on the left leg and make the jump-pass
throw to first). I thought, `Hey, life's gonna be pretty easy up
here.'''
</P>
<P>
   We are living in the Golden Age of shortstops, 'tis true. Never
before in baseball history have we been blessed with such a
collection of two-way threats at this key position. Alex Rodriguez,
Jeter, and Nomar Garciaparra are all sensational hitters who make
all the plays at short. But I have little doubt that if any of the
above trio were to come up with Baltimore while Earl Weaver was
managing, he'd have been advised to learn a new position. Earl
would have wanted the bat, but Belanger was going to be his
shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   In his fine tribute in these pages after Belanger's death from
lung cancer at the age of 54 Tuesday, Dan Shaughnessy spoke of the
teeny-tiny glove Belanger used and how he would just about go
postal if anyone else tried to stick his hand in it. Mention of
that glove brings a smile to Rettenmund's face. ``Absolutely,''
Rettenmund says, ``he didn't want anyone to touch it. That glove
was amazing. Just having a catch with him was fascinating. It would
seem as if the ball never even went into his glove at all, that he
could transfer it to his throwing hand before you even realized it.
He would say, `I don't catch the ball; I just redirect it.'''
</P>
<P>
   The tiny glove wasn't his only quirk. He was renowned far and
wide in baseball for his refusal to wear a protective cup inside
his athletic supporter (jock, to you macho guys). ``I've never
known another infielder who wouldn't wear a cup,'' says Rettenmund.
``He always said, `If I have to wear a cup, I can't trust my
hands.'''
</P>
<P>
   What level of offense would it have taken for Belanger to have
gotten more attention from the so-called experts with the notebooks
and computers when Hall of Fame balloting time rolled around? .240?
.270? .290? Ozzie Smith turned himself into a pesky .290/.300 type
of slap hitter. Belanger never did that. He stuck in one weird .287
season, but the .228 lifetime summed up his hitting prowess, though
not necessarily his offensive prowess. ``He was a very good
bunter,'' Rettenmund points out. ``He was a good baserunner, too,
and there were guys he could hit.'' One of them, interestingly
enough, was Nolan Ryan, whom he owned (just as Doug Griffin had a
lease on Jim Palmer).
</P>
<P>
   But why should it be necessary to state, or perhaps even
overstate, his offensive credentials when his calling card was
defense? Shortstop is a defensive position. Year after year,
baseball insiders preach the value of pitching and defense to
winning teams, and year after year, writers print their stories
extolling said values. Don't they believe it? Is it just lip
service? Don't the eight Gold Gloves count for something at the
most demanding defensive position save, perhaps, catching?
</P>
<P>
   Mark Belanger wasn't just a little bit better than his
contemporaries. He was The Man. He completely mastered the
position. But his heyday was before ``SportsCenter'' and even
before ``This Week In Baseball.'' And even if it hadn't been, he
wasn't a highlight kind of guy like, say, Ozzie Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``They talk about Ozzie, and he was great with the flips and
acrobatics and dives,'' points out Rettenmund. ``But in seven years
as his teammate, I never saw Mark dive for a ball because he never
had to. He was always in the right place.''
</P>
<P>
   Belanger had expertise in areas where most shortstops don't even
enter into the discussion. ``I played both left and center with
him,'' says Rettenmund. ``When the situation calls for you to hit a
cutoff man, most shortstops just run where they're supposed to, and
what happens happens. But Mark Belanger was able to go out and take
every relay throw chest-high while he was turning to make the throw
to the plate. I never saw him take a throw at his ankles or
anywhere else. I don't know how he did that.''
</P>
<P>
   Middle infielders are woefully underrepresented in the Hall,
anyway, and middle infielders such as Belanger and Bill Mazeroski,
men whose defensive dominance was just as pronounced, and
important, as the numbers put up by slugging types, are shamelessly
ignored. Their continuing absence from Cooperstown is an
embarrassment to the voting body.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps someday the Veterans Committee will rectify the wrong
and get Mark Belanger in. Until then, how about one more story from
Merv Rettenmund?
</P>
<P>
   ``After I had played with Mark in 1968 and 1969, I went to
winter ball,'' he says. ``I was playing center one day and I was in
my defensive position when someone hit a ball up the middle. I
guess I was slow to react, and the ball got by me. I couldn't
understand what the ball was doing there. I thought if a ball was
hit up the middle, the shortstop would catch it. But I had
forgotten. I was used to playing with Mark Belanger.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
