<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GA-TENN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL THE FIXIN'S FOR AN OLD-FASHIONED SOUTHERN FEUD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Back in the days when Georgia football was a Top
10 fixture, big games used to come through Sanford Stadium with the
regularity of a midsummer thunderstorm.
</P>
<P>
   It was a big deal, of course, when teams came to play Between
the Hedges, and the Dawgs would show folks what Georgia football
was all about. The likes of Alabama, Auburn, and LSU would fill
coach Vince Dooley's dance card, making this place one of the
meccas of college football.
</P>
<P>
   That changed in the late '80s and '90s. Oh, the Dawgs still won
their share of games, but Dooley, ending a 25-year reign as Top
Dawg, moved up to the athletic director's chair and the really big
games gradually disappeared as his successor, Ray Goff, won more
than six games only twice in seven seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But the passion for Georgia football remained, which is why
there is an old-time feeling around here surrounding this
afternoon's Southeastern Conference matchup with Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Big? Why, it's so big that the folks from ESPN's ``College
Football Game Day'' will set up shop here Saturday, making their
first appearance ever.
</P>
<P>
   You have to go back to the early post-Herschel Walker days to
find a more intriguing battle than the meeting between the
unbeaten, seventh-ranked Bulldogs and the unbeaten, fourth-ranked
Volunteers; in fact, you have to go all the way back to 1983 to
find the last game played here between two Top 10 teams.
</P>
<P>
   If that weren't enough, you also have the fixin's for an
old-fashioned Southern feud.
</P>
<P>
   Now if you listen to Georgia coach Jim Donnan and Tennessee
coach Phil Fulmer, it's not a big deal.
</P>
<P>
   That's flat out wrong. It is still big stuff and it will add an
even bigger edge to a game that will establish the front-runner not
only in the SEC East race but also in the quest for the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   The animosity stems from last year's game in Knoxville, a 38-13
spanking by the Vols that the Georgia folks felt was unduly harsh
because Fulmer chose to keep starting quarterback Peyton Manning in
the game long after the outcome had been decided.
</P>
<P>
   The situation became even more tense when Manning wrapped up the
Volunteers' scoring for the day by throwing a touchdown pass with
1:44 left.
</P>
<P>
   Donnan, who was brought in two years ago to replace Goff,
thought that was a bit much and told Fulmer so privately in their
postgame midfield meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer responded by making Donnan's remarks public, which
incensed the Georgia coach even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't regret what I said,'' said Donnan, who has steadily
rebuilt the Georgia program into a national power _ the Dawgs have
lost only once in 10 games since falling to Tennessee. ``What I
regret is the fact that he made it public after I whispered it in
his ear.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnan, who has more weapons than ever before in his three years
at Georgia _ most notably freshman quarterback Quincy Carter and
all-around talent Champ Bailey, who plays offense and defense and
is making a Charles Woodson-type run at the Heisman Trophy _ says
it is time to move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any disagreements with him,'' Donnan said. ``He's
got to coach his team. I've got to coach mine. That happened and
it's over with and we're playing this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer is also saying it's best to let sleeping Dawgs lie. When
asked about Manning's pass, Fulmer said, ``I don't think that has
any place in this ballgame. He's not going to pay a down and
neither am I.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Fulmer, neither is his best player, tailback
Jamal Lewis, who is out for the year with a knee injury. That could
end not only the Vols' national championship hopes but also their
domination of Georgia, a winning streak that dates back to 1988.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
