<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9118 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-CENSUS-NYT &LR;      10-09 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-CENSUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT TO HEAR ANOTHER SUIT ON CENSUS SAMPLING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Conn., Mass., Minn., Mo., Pa., Wis.)   (bl)  
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Friday added a second census
case to its calendar for argument next month, an action that could
substantially increase the odds of producing a definitive and
relatively quick ruling on whether the Clinton administration can
proceed with its plan to use statistical sampling to correct an
expected undercount in the next census.
</P>
<P>
   The latest case is an appeal by the administration from a ruling
two weeks ago by a special three-judge U.S District Court in
Richmond, Va. That court ruled, in a suit brought by 16 individuals
and by Cobb County, Ga., that federal law bars the use of sampling
for the purpose of apportioning congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   A separate three-judge panel here issued a nearly identical
ruling in August, in a suit brought by the House of
Representatives. But while the Supreme Court agreed last month to
hear the administration's appeal of that decision, doubts about
whether the House was the proper party to bring the suit remain an
obstacle to the justices' ability to decide the merits of the
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is vigorously disputing the House's legal
standing, arguing that it will continue to have 435 members and to
exercise the same constitutional authority no matter how the census
is conducted.
</P>
<P>
   While the administration also plans to dispute the standing of
the plaintiffs in the new case, Clinton vs. Glavin, No. 98-564, the
court's precedents put this case on firmer procedural ground. The
16 plaintiffs live in six states that the lower court found are
``substantially likely'' to lose a seat in the House if the census
is adjusted through the use of sampling, because population would
be shifted through the statistical adjustment to other states.
Consequently, the lower court found, these individuals' claim to
standing is based on an allegation of prospective ``vote dilution''
of the sort the Supreme Court has recognized in the past as a basis
for challenging an apportionment plan.
</P>
<P>
   The six states are Connecticut, Massachusetts, Minnesota,
Missouri, Pennsylvania and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to claiming vote dilution at the federal level, the
plaintiffs maintain that with sampling they will suffer in the
state redistricting that follows the 2000 census and that their
states will get less than their rightful share of money under
various federal grants and programs that are based on population.
The traditional census head count misses millions of people, and
misses them differentially, with urban residents, the poor and
members of minority groups uncounted more frequently than others.
</P>
<P>
   In agreeing Friday to hear the case, the justices granted a
request filed jointly by the administration and the plaintiffs to
handle the appeal on a highly expedited basis. The argument will
take place Nov. 30 in a time slot already reserved for the earlier
case, Department of Commerce vs. U.S. House of Representatives, No.
98-404. The court set aside 90 minutes instead of the usual hour to
hear the arguments, which will cover both cases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 1825EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
