<HEADER>
A9138 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATL-MOVIES-MINIREVIEW     10-09 4061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS09 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of current movies
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel and Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Reviewer's initials appear at end of review). Grades range from
A to F.
</P>
<P>
   Air Bud: Golden Receiver G
</P>
<P>
   If you're younger than 8, this ``Bud's'' for you. In this sequel
to ``Air Bud,'' Buddy, the hoop-shooting Golden Retriever, and his
boy, Josh (Kevin Zegers) trade basketball for football. Scriptwise,
it's little more than a glorified after-school special, but there
hasn't been much around for younger kids recently and it handles
its messages well. And so what if the movie is essentially a series
of Stupid Pet Tricks? In his K-9 jersey, pads and helmet, Buddy
looks more athletically heroic than Bruce Willis. 1 hour, 31
minutes. (ER) Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Antz G
</P>
<P>
   A visual picnic, a so-so script. This computer-animated feature
tells of worker ant Z (voice of Woody Allen) whose love of Princess
Bala (Sharon Stone) lands both of them in the scary world outside
the ant colony. It's fun, but the story is as predictable as the
spectacular visuals are not. 1 hour, 23 minutes. (SM) Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Armageddon PG-13
</P>
<P>
   While ``Deep Impact'' treated a similar let's-save-Earth story
with sobriety, ``Armageddon'' never lets the threat of global
annihilation get in the way of fun. It's a space-cowboy movie, with
Bruce Willis and Ben Affleck saving the world for Liv Tyler. As a
summer popcorn movie, it's more enjoyable than that big-lizard
flick ``Godzilla.'' And you'll see the reported $165 million budget
onscreen in the impressive effects and mammoth sets. But is the
movie good for you? Probably not. Rated PG-13 for sci-fi disaster
action, implied sex and profanity. 2 hours, 24 minutes. (SM) Grade:
C
</P>
<P>
   The Avengers PG-13
</P>
<P>
   Visually, this update of the '60s TV series pays witty homage to
the original's vein of Carnaby Street surrealism. In between sips
of champagne and civilized quips, agents John Steed (Ralph Fiennes)
and Mrs. Emma Peel (Uma Thurman) foil criminals plotting against
the British government. But there are two problems: a half-baked
script and Thurman, who's trumped by the cool, feline memory of
Diana Rigg, who originated the role. (SM) Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Blade R
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't cut it. Wesley Snipes stars as the half-vampire,
half-human hero who can handle sunlight but also has a taste for
blood. Armed with an arsenal of sci-fi gadgets, a really cool
leather coat and Kris Kristofferson (a kind of high-tech Gabby
Hayes), Blade is devoted to wiping out all vampires. Especially a
strutting bloodsucker played by Stephen Dorff. Alas, all the
non-stop slash 'n' gnash action becomes more repetitive than
anything else. Rated R for extreme violence and strong language. 2
hours. (ER) Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Clay Pigeons R
</P>
<P>
   A good indy cast, including Joaquin Phoenix as a framed,
small-town everyman, Janeane Garofalo as a dry FBI agent, and
especially Vince Vaughn as a giggling, psycho good ol' boy can't
save this arch, overplotted ``Fargo'' wannabe. 1 hour, 44 minutes.
(SM) Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Dance With Me PG
</P>
<P>
   A guilty, quick-stepping pleasure. Vanessa L. Williams plays a
Houston dance instructor who hopes to recapture past dance
competition glory with the help of a Cuban newcomer (Latin music
star Chayanne). Original it isn't, but ``Dance'' is great fun. It's
the first film that lets Williams show off her knockout dancing,
and in his first Hollywood flick, Chayanne goes for the summer's
heartthrob title. 2 hours, 6 minutes. (SM) Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Dead Man on Campus R
</P>
<P>
   Some passable laughs, but it doesn't make the honor roll. Two
college students (Tom Everett Scott and Mark-Paul Gosselaar) hope a
kamikaze frat boy (Lochlyn Munro), will share their dorm suite.
And, preferably, kill himself in one of his misadventures. That's
because an odd clause at their college gives students an automatic
4.0 average if their roommate offs himself. Rated R for drug use,
language and crude sexual humor. At metro theaters. 1 hour, 36
minutes. (SM) Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Deep Impact PG-13
</P>
<P>
   The impact here is human, which is pretty gutsy since, going in,
we all know this is about a comet hurtling toward Earth. Showing at
area discount theaters, director Mimi Leder's thriller shows that
catastrophes can be measured one life at a time. The strong cast
includes Tea Leoni as an ambitious reporter and Robert Duvall as an
aging astronaut sent to blow the comet to bits. 2 hours, 3 minutes.
(ER) Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Disturbing Behavior R
</P>
<P>
   Disturbingly lame. This teens-in-peril flick is a high-concept
pitch with zero follow-through _ it's ``The Stepford Teens'' with a
touch of ``Invasion of the Body Snatchers.'' James Marsden plays a
newcomer to a small-town high school who encounters a band of
frighteningly clean-cut students. With the help of the school
psychiatrist (Bruce Greenwood), these fascist Archies ``recruit'' a
new classmate into their group every few days. Rated R for
profanity, violence and sex. 1 hour, 23 minutes. (SM) Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dolittle PG-13
</P>
<P>
   This raucous but uninspired Eddie Murphy vehicle has almost
nothing to do with the old Rex Harrison musical. Murphy is John
Dolittle, a busy doctor who has neglected his wife (Kristen Wilson)
and his two daughters. One day, all kinds of animals start
pestering him vocally. Despite the zing of some nuttier moments,
the lame plot keeps dragging the movie to the ground. 1 hour, 30
minutes. (SM) Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Ever After PG-13
</P>
<P>
   Happily, this ``Ever After'' proves you can teach an old doll
new tricks. Re-inventing the Cinderella story in a way that targets
``Titanic''-loving teens more than Barney grads, the movie stars
Drew Barrymore as its spirited heroine, Anjelica Huston as her
scheming stepmother and Dougray Scott as a prince who's more than
just another trophy husband. Jeanne Moreau, doyenne of the French
New Wave, contributes a classy cameo. Rated PG-13 for emotional
situations (death of a father) and some violence. 2 hours. (ER)
Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Everest NR
</P>
<P>
   Breathtaking. Even filmgoers accustomed to the five-story IMAX
format may gasp at the unearthly scale of ``Everest.'' This
44-minute documentary was filmed at the same time as the 1996 storm
that killed eight mountain climbers, memorialized by Jon Krakauer's
best-selling book ``Into Thin Air.'' Cameraman David Breashears
fills the screen with awesome vistas, but discreetly avoids the
piles of discarded oxygen tanks, human waste and frozen bodies that
now litter the trails of the mountain. This is a film whose cruel
beauty manages to celebrate the spirit of the climbers, while
making you question their sanity. 44 minutes. (SM)
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Fakin' da Funk R
</P>
<P>
   A message movie that's weakened a bit by heavy reliance on
stereotypes and a predictable plot. An adoption agency mistakenly
gives Ernie Hudson and Pam Grier a Chinese baby. (Their last name
is Lee). They keep it. And he, in turn, adopts the notion that he
is black. But when the Lees move from Atlanta to South Central Los
Angeles the boys in the hood are quick to tell Dante Basco he's
``Fakin Da Funk.'' 1 hour, 29 minutes. (Sonia Murray) Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Firelight R
</P>
<P>
   This Gothic romantic drama set in the 1830s could use a little
more fire and a lot lighter touch. Still, it burns with
intelligence, craft and psychological resonance. A Swiss governess
(Sophie Marceau) agrees to bear a child for an aloof English
aristocrat (Stephen Dillane), then disappear from his life. But
their ``business'' arrangement is complicated by feelings both
romantic and maternal. A quiet, emotionally assured film that
respects its characters and its audience. 1 hour, 44 minutes. (ER)
Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Godzilla PG-13
</P>
<P>
   He's back. He's big. He's boring. There was probably no way this
extravagant update of ``Godzilla'' could live up to its yearlong
hype. What's depressing is how far it falls short of being even
solid summer escapism. Bikini atoll resident Godzilla comes to nest
in Manhattan when it's time to think of family matters. Matthew
Broderick is a biologist on the monster's trail. 2 hours, 19
minutes. (SM) Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   The Holy Man PG
</P>
<P>
   A mild comedy-drama that wastes Eddie Murphy's talents as a New
Age drifter who brings big sales and enlightenment to home shopping
producer Jeff Goldblum and media analyst Kelly Preston. It's
Hollywood's latest reduction of spiritual values to ``give somebody
a hug.''1 hour, 53 minutes. (SM) Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Hope Floats PG-13
</P>
<P>
   This movie never flies, but never sinks, either. Sandra Bullock
teams up with director Forest Whitaker (``Waiting to Exhale'') for
this affecting story of a woman who goes back to her small-town
home to lick her wounds after her husband has an affair. 1 hour, 54
minutes. (ER) Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   How Stella Got Her Groove Back R
</P>
<P>
   The screen version of Terry McMillan's novel tries to distract
us from its lack of plot with visual opulence. Angela Bassett plays
a fortysomething investment banker who takes a trip to Jamaica with
her best pal (Whoopi Goldberg), where she falls for a 20-year-old
local (Taye Diggs). Luckily, Bassett roots the picture with a
glowing performance, sharing with us Stella's unexpected moments of
emotional rediscovery. Rated R for sexual situations, nudity,
language. 2 hours, 4 minutes. (SM) Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   The Impostors R
</P>
<P>
   Flawed as it is, this slight, silly film is impossible to
dislike. It's too full of talented funny people such as Lili
Taylor, Campbell Scott, Dana Ivey and Steve Buscemi. Stanley Tucci
and Oliver Platt star as two out-of-work actors who stow away on a
luxury liner. The '30s setting reflects the movie's screwball
aspirations, which it never quite achieves. 1 hour, 38 minutes.
(ER) Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Knock Off R
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Claude Van Damme returns in _ surprise! _ an action movie
about an American salesman working in Hong Kong who becomes aware
of a terrorist conspiracy. Directed by Hong Kong action auteur Tsui
Hark. Not reviewed. Grade: NR
</P>
<P>
   Lethal Weapon 4 R
</P>
<P>
   The latest in director Richard Donner's cheerfully chaotic
blow-'em-up series re-pairs Mel Gibson's hothead cop Riggs, and
Danny Glover's long-suffering partner Murtaugh. Shaggy and amiable,
Number 4 hardly bothers to get its real plot going for its first
hour. More than ever, the film is an excuse to give its crack
supporting cast, including Joe Pesci and Chris Rock, a series of
comic riffs. Rated R for violence and profanity. 2 hours, 5
minutes. (SM) Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Lolita R
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Lyne's version of Vladimir Nabokov's acclaimed novel
about a grown man (Jeremy Irons) sexually obsessed with a
pre-pubescent girl (Dominique Swain) is neither a triumph nor a
travesty. It's just okay, which, given the source, suggests that
the director had little affinity for the material besides its name
value. The result is an overlong, sometimes sluggish film that opts
for Victoria's Secret gauze over the black comedy of Stanley
Kubrick's 1962 version. 2 hours, 5 minutes. (ER) Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Madeline PG
</P>
<P>
   This is a faithful and fun adaptation of the series of
children's books about a precocious redheaded orphan living in a
girls' school. Set in the relatively uncomplicated 1950s and
breathtakingly filmed in Paris, it's fast-paced enough to appeal to
kids (even boys should take to the scooter-riding rascal Pepito)
and nostalgic enough for adults. 1 hour, 29 minutes. (Jill
Vejnoska, c. 1998 Cox News Service) Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   The Mask of Zorro PG-13
</P>
<P>
   Derring-do done right. Our men in black are Anthony Hopkins and
Antonio Banderas, who double our swashbuckling pleasure and double
our fun as dual Zorros, saving California and Hopkins' beautiful,
spirited daughter (Catherine Zeta-Jones) from the evil schemes of
one Don Rafael (Stuart Wilson). It's an expert blend of panache,
romanticism and supple, tongue-in-cheek humor. 2 hours, 16 minutes.
(ER) Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Mulan G
</P>
<P>
   The best Disney animated feature since ``Beauty and the Beast''
and ``The Lion King.'' Based on a 4th-century legend, it's about a
young girl who pulls a National Velvet, i.e., disguises herself as
a boy and goes to battle in her elderly father's place. This isn't
just a grand family film; it's a grand film, period. As Eddie
Murphy's little red dragon says, ``Mulan, you the man!'' 1 hour, 28
minutes. (ER) Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   The Negotiator R
</P>
<P>
   In this crisply acted thriller, Samuel L. Jackson plays a
hostage negotiator for the Chicago police department who is framed
for embezzlement and murder. Desperate to clear his name, he takes
four members of the department hostage, then asks another
negotiator (Kevin Spacey) to act as a mediator between himself and
his fellow officers. The film's main kick is the engrossing duel of
bluffs and counterbluffs between Spacey and Jackson. They make us
believe in the high stakes of the situation. Rated R for violence
and profanity. 2 hours, 15 minutes. (SM) Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Next Stop, Wonderland R
</P>
<P>
   A small wonder in its own modest way. This charming low-budget
romantic comedy about the relationship travails of a Boston nurse
(Hope Davis) is stronger on character nuance than on plot; in fact,
filmmaker Brad Anderson loads it with too much plot. But by
applying a naturalistic independent-film sensibility to a vintage
glossy-Hollywood predicament, he comes out ahead. Think of a film
where John Cassavetes shares pillow talk with Doris Day. Rated R
for vulgar language and sexual situations. 1 hour, 36 minutes. (ER)
Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   A Night at the Roxbury PG-13
</P>
<P>
   Those head-bopping, nightclubbing brothers from ``Saturday Night
Live'' are out in a full-fledged story. Well, as full-fledged as
you can get when your central characters are a couple of clueless,
would-be coolsters whose dream is getting into, and then owning,
the hottest club in town. Lots of groaningly funny lines and a
surprisingly coherent story line make this a fun, thankfully
concise viewing experience. 1 hour, 23 minutes. (Jill Vejnoska, c.
1998 Cox News Service) Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Nights of Cabiria NR
</P>
<P>
   Carefully restored version of Fellini's 1957 Oscar winner,
starring his wife, Giuletta Masina, as a downtrodden yet
indomitable hooker wandering through the streets of Rome cloaked in
a ratty fur and unquenchable optimism. The current print hasn't
just been spruced up; an entire section _ ``the man in the sack,''
about a Good Samaritan who feeds the poor _ has been re-included.
Note to Fellini fans: This is early Fellini. Simple. Toned down.
Lovely. 1 hour, 57 minutes. (ER) Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   One True Thing R
</P>
<P>
   Strikes too many false notes. Renee Zellweger plays a career
journalist who goes home to care for her dying homemaker mother
(Meryl Streep). Streep's performance is terrific, but the movie
suffers from generic slickness. 2 hour, 7 minutes. (SM) Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   One Tough Cop R
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Baldwin stars as a NYPD detective torn between duty to
his badge or to a childhood pal (Mike McGlone) who is now a member
of a crime family. This solid cop procedural is fact-based, but
plays like a dozen fictional flicks you've seen before. 1 hour, 30
minutes. (SM) Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   The Parent Trap PG
</P>
<P>
   Wisely, deviates little from the plot of the 1961 Disney film
that made 15-year-old Hayley Mills a star. This time Lindsay Lohan
plays the dual role of separated-practically-at-birth twins who
meet and switch identities in the hopes of reuniting their divorced
parents. Young kids may fidget at the length and several kissing
scenes. (Jill Vejnoska) 1 hour, 45 minutes. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Pecker R
</P>
<P>
   Edward Furlong plays a Baltimore kid whose grainy photos bring
him New York art scene fame in John Waters' new comedy. Like all
Waters' films, it's a very mixed bag of raunch and sweetness, smart
satire and dumb comedy. 1 hour, 27 minutes. (SM) Grade C+
</P>
<P>
   A Perfect Murder R
</P>
<P>
   Not Perfect, this ``Dial M for Murder'' remake is still a guilty
pleasure, a slick B-movie jazzed up with great clothes, art
direction and decent plot twists. Michael Douglas plays a business
shark whose boom is going bust, so he attempts to hire his wealhy
wife`s lover to kill her. 1 hour, 47 minutes. (SM) Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Ronin R
</P>
<P>
   The title suggests a close friend of Rodan or Godzilla, but it
actually refers to shamed samurai who, having lost their master,
are for hire. Robert De Niro and Jean Reno lead some modern-day
``ronin'' _ Cold Warriors without a war _ hired to snatch a
mysterious suitcase. Director John Frankenheimer (``The Manchurian
Candidate'') and an unbilled David Mamet (``The Spanish Prisoner'')
bring a cool professional touch to this crackling
action-suspense-thriller that's fun and smart. 1 hour, 58 minutes.
(ER) Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Rounders R
</P>
<P>
   Director John Dahl (``The Last Seduction'') has a couple of very
hot aces up his sleeve _ Matt Damon and Edward Norton _ in this
nifty movie about the addictive lure of high-stakes poker. Damon is
a former card sharp who's managed to kick the habit and concentrate
on his law studies. Norton is his old friend, fresh out of jail,
who lures him back. A pungent, character-rich picture that's a lot
less about where it goes than how it gets there. Rated R for nudity
and language. 2 hours. (ER) Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Rush Hour PG-13
</P>
<P>
   Kung Fu king Jackie Chan and fast-talking comedian Chris Tucker
play two cops whose clashes go way beyond cultural differences.
Thrown together by FBI agents who don't want either mucking up
their search for a kidnapped child, the pair drive each other
crazy, at first. You'll howl as Chan and Tucker learn to work
together, in part by imitating (sometimes badly) how the other one
works. 1 hours, 37 minutes. (Jill Vejnoska) Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Saving Private Ryan R
</P>
<P>
   Part gung-ho heroism, part in-your-face horror show, Steven
Spielberg's superb film shows us World War II as we've never seen
it before. Tom Hanks leads a courageous squad (and excellent
ensemble cast) on a mission to find a private (Matt Damon) whose
three brothers have already been killed in combat. Hanks'
performance is a miracle of decency and subtle emotion, but kudos
all around here. And the opening D-Day sequence is the most
powerful combat footage ever created on film. Rated R for extreme
violence and some vulgar language. 2 hours, 50 minutes. (ER) Grade:
A
</P>
<P>
   Simon Birch PG
</P>
<P>
   A little movie with big problems. In the early 1960s, a
pre-adolescent dwarf named Simon Birch (Ian Michael Smith) is
convinced he will one day be a hero while his best pal (Joseph
Mazzello) tries to solve the mystery of his real father (Ashley
Judd is Mazzello's closemouthed mom). The movie is clearly a labor
of love; alas, it's also a labor to sit through. Rated PG for
violence (a scary bus accident) and sexual innuendo. 1 hour, 50
minutes. (ER) Grade: D-
</P>
<P>
   Six Days, Seven Nights PG-13
</P>
<P>
   Think ``Romancing the Stone'' only without the romance or the
adventure in this movie. Harrison Ford is a gruff charter pilot and
Anne Heche is a New York magazine editor. They wind up stranded on
an island near Tahiti _ an abandoned place, except for some
pirates. The pair bicker, bond and kick some pirate butt. 1 hour,
41 minutes. (SM) Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Slums of Beverly Hills R
</P>
<P>
   A vivid, very funny look at coming of age on the fringes. Vivian
Abramowitz (Natasha Lyonne) is the odd girl out in a post-divorce
family led by a father (Alan Arkin) who, every three months or so,
skips out on rent and moves his brood to another fleabag on the
edge of Beverly Hills. Director Tamara Jenkins re-creates the daily
humiliations of adolescence with wince-inducing accuracy. And
Lyonne is terrific at navigating the waters of teen angst. Rated R
for nudity, profanity, sexual situations. 1 hour, 31 minutes. (SM)
Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Small Soldiers PG-13
</P>
<P>
   Action- and violence-packed movie is heavy on computer-generated
effects but woefully light on plot twists or interesting characters
(either flesh-and-blood or plastic). Borrowing liberally from too
many other movies, action figures come alive, start warring with
each other (and any human who gets in their way) and destroy an
idyllic small-town neighborhood. 1 hour 49 minutes. (SM) Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Snake Eyes R
</P>
<P>
   Oscar winner Nicolas Cage and Brian De Palma are always worth
gambling on; while they don't come up total winners here, they're
hardly losers either. Cage plays a crooked Atlantic City cop who
finds himself in the middle of an assassination plot during a
heavyweight boxing match. Part detective story, part
action-thriller, the picture loses steam near the end, but De
Palma's wired camerawork and Cage's strutting energy help hold it
together. Rated R for violence and language. 1 hour, 42 minutes.
(ER) Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   A Soldier's Daughter Never Cries R
</P>
<P>
   Family matters and more are examined in this thoughtful
adaptation of Kaylie Jones' semi-autobiographical book about
growing up in the '60s and '70s (her father was writer James
Jones). The scattered, vignette-ish approach may bother some _ the
movie is like a personal memoir divided into three separate but
equal short stories _ but the film's sense of memory as an
emotional tapestry made up of many people and incidents rings true.
2 hours, 4 minutes. (ER) Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   There's Something About Mary R
</P>
<P>
   Rude, crude and hilarious. Ben Stiller plays Ted, a nerdy high
school senior who suffers a bathroom mishap that keeps him from
attending his prom with the class golden girl (Cameron Diaz).
Thirteen years later, the still-obsessed Ted hires a gumshoe (Matt
Dillon) to track her down. The movie is liberating in its
scatological, slapstick way. But the easy-to-offend should find
something more polite to watch. 1 hour, 58 minutes. (SM) Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Touch of Evil NR
</P>
<P>
   Orson Welles' 1958 cult classic about corruption and lust in a
small Mexican border town has been re-created as the filmmaker
originally envisioned it. Small changes and some technical tweaking
render the film more coherent without losing its nightmarish,
B-movie edge. Charlton Heston and Janet Leigh star as newlyweds
whose honeymoon is interrupted by murder. Welles is decadence
incarnate as Capt. Quinlan, the lawman gone wrong. 1 hour, 51
minutes. (ER) Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   The Truman Show R
</P>
<P>
   Jim Carrey's excellent performance is the centerpiece of this
provocative social satire. It's about a cheerful insurance salesman
who slowly realizes his entire life has been a TV show and all the
people he knows are actors. Peter Weir directs this dazzlingly
executed concept and the strong cast includes Laura Linney and Ed
Harris. 1 hour, 44 minutes. (ER) Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Urban Legend R
</P>
<P>
   Alicia Witt and Jared Leto star in the latest knockoff of
``Scream'' and ``I Know What You Did Last Summer.'' The
college-campus, teen-kill thriller is slickly made, well played,
instantly forgettable. 1 hour, 39 minutes. (SM) Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   What Dreams May Come PG-13
</P>
<P>
   Imagine ``Ghost'' directed by Terry Gilliam and you'll have some
idea of this tear-jerker phantasmagoria. Robin Williams stars as a
doctor exploring aspects of the afterlife after he's killed in a
car crash. Annabella Sciorra is his widow; Cuba Gooding Jr., his
spiritual guide. The movie is emotionally and visually stunning, a
little simplistic story-wise. But sometimes simplistic can be
startlingly close to primal. Check your cynicism at the door and
bring a box of Kleenex. 1 hour, 46 minutes. (ER) Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Why Do Fools Fall in Love R
</P>
<P>
   This dark, dramatic biopic stars Halle Berry, Vivica A. Fox and
Lela Rochon as the women who were married to doo-wopper Frankie
Lymon, and whose court fight over his royalty ``estate'' clues us
to the singer's sorry life. Boasting some great late '50s and early
'60s rock sounds, this film, unfortunately, spins back and forth
narratively. Rated R for language, sex scenes and drug use. 2
hours, 3 minutes. (The Hollywood Reporter) Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Your Friends and Neighbors R
</P>
<P>
   Neil LaBute, who did the lacerating ``In the Company of Men,''
suffers a sophomore slump of sorts in this black comedy about sex
games and power plays among six thirtysomething urbanites. Rated R
for sex and language. 1 hour, 45 minutes. (ER) Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
