<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFE-FILM-REVIEWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BOOK OF LIFE' AND `LIFE ON EARTH': TWO VIEWS OF THE MILLENNIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes at end of review.)  
(lb) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is the morning of Dec. 31, 1999, and who should
breeze into John F. Kennedy International Airport just in time for
the apocalypse but a bland, dapper Jesus (Martin Donovan).
Accompanying him is his assistant and gal Friday, Magdalena (P.J.
Harvey), a witchy-looking vixen wearing knee-high black boots and
toting a backpack. The pair head straight for Manhattan, where they
check into a hotel, consult with their lawyers and make final plans
for the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a SoHo bar, Satan (Thomas Jay Ryan), a cynical,
loudmouthed crank, is knocking back drinks and chatting about final
things with Dave (Dave Simonds), an atheist and ne'er-do-well. At
one point, Satan proposes a deal: If Dave buys a lottery ticket for
his ``terminally good'' girlfriend, Edie (Miho Nikaido), who works
in the bar, Satan promises it will win. But in exchange the Devil
gets Edie's soul. Without realizing with whom he's dealing, Dave
goes for it.
</P>
<P>
   Whimsical yet deeply serious, Hal Hartley's ``Book of Life''
loosely translates the Book of Revelation into a hip religious
fable that begins facetiously and becomes steadily more reflective.
Shot on digital video blown up to 35-mm film, pastel-hued and
filled with feathery digital afterimages, the movie has a floating,
ethereal look that oddly matches its lofty subject.
</P>
<P>
   The one-hour film _ one of two millennially themed movies being
shown together Saturday evening at Alice Tully Hall as part of the
New York Film Festival _ could be taken as a companion piece to
``Henry Fool,'' the director's full-length pop fable, which opened
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, who played the title character in that film, brings the
same mixture of self-deluded grandiosity and bitterness to Satan;
he's a familiar type, a chronic complainer and compulsively
contrary.
</P>
<P>
   So what will happen at the stroke of midnight? Does the world
end? Or does Jesus, who begins to have second thoughts about his
father's insistence on punishment, take a more sympathetic and
relativistic view of human folly and decide to call off the
apocalypse? Let's put it this way: Hartley's mild-mannered Jesus
turns out to be a nondoctrinaire liberal humanist with the mind of
a science-fiction writer.
</P>
<P>
   Abderrahmane Sissako's film ``Life On Earth'' looks at the
millennium from a less affluent perspective. The movie follows
Sissako, a Mauritanian living in Paris, back to Sokolo, his
father's village in Mali, to film a portrait of life in this
impoverished area of western Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the film, Sissako forcefully editorializes about
Europe's destruction of Africa, blaming ``industrial leaders
without scruples'' for creating ``the highest pile of corpses in
history.''
</P>
<P>
   But from this point on, the film draws back to paint a
dispassionate, almost lyrical portrait of the village, whose meager
livelihood is threatened by swarms of birds that have been
devouring the rice crop. We visit the rudimentary local radio
station and the post office, which has the only telephone in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   It is Dec. 31, 1999, and the news emanating from the few radios
in Sokolo is all about the millennial celebrations around the world
and the crowds at the Eiffel Tower in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life on Earth'' doesn't offer the disquieting images of
poverty, disease and starving children that have become standard in
Third World documentaries. Instead, it compiles a picture of a way
of life that is so primitive and detached from the material
abundance and technological sophistication of Europe that you are
left with the sinking feeling of having visited a country that has
been forever left behind, literally in the dust.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE BOOK OF LIFE'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Hal Hartley; director of photography,
Jim Denault; edited by Steve Hamilton; produced by Pierre
Chevalier, Carole Scotta, Caroline Benjo, Simon Arnal, Thierry
Cajianut and Matthew Myers.
</P>
<P>
   With: Martin Donovan (Jesus), P.J. Harvey (Magdalena), Thomas
Jay Ryan (Satan), Dave Simonds (Dave), Miho Nikaido (Edie) and D.J.
Mendel (Lawyer).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 63 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   `LIFE ON EARTH'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Abderrahmane Sissako; written (in Bambara and
French, with English subtitles) by Sissako; director of
photography, Jacques Besse; edited by Nadia Ben Rachid; produced by
Pierre Chevalier, Carole Scotta, Caroline Benjo, Barbara Letellier
and Simon Arnal.
</P>
<P>
   With: Abderrahmane Sissako (Dramane), Nana Baby (Nana), Mohamed
Sissako (Father), Bourama Coulibaly (Photographer), Keita Bina
Gaousso (Postman) and Mahamadou Drame (Telephone Employee).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 61 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night at 6 at Alice Tully Hall as part of the 36th New
York Film Festival. These films are not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
