<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9145 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-SPECIES-NYT &LR;      10-09 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPECIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON CAPITOL HILL, INTRICATE MANEUVERS ON ENDANGERED SPECIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Calif., R.I., Idaho)   (bl)  
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate authors of a bill to overhaul the
Endangered Species Act are trying to persuade House leaders to
attach the measure to a catch-all spending bill, a step that would
fundamentally rewrite one of the nation's most important
environmental laws without either the full Senate or House taking a
separate vote on it.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration supports the overhaul, which would
codify many of the innovative approaches to protecting imperiled
species that Interior Secretary Bruce Babbit has adopted over the
years. But the White House has said it opposes putting this or
other new environmental policy measures on the omnibus spending
bill.
</P>
<P>
   The species bill would authorize landowners like big timber
companies to develop comprehensive habitat conservation plans
protecting many species at once. In exchange, they then may receive
permits for some degree of harm to endangered species on the land.
The federal government promises that there will be no future
demands for them to spend money or set aside additional land for
the covered species.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the existing law often allows environmentalists to
block development that harms even a single endangered species or
its habitat, a power that they have used with great success for
years, and has made it difficult for Babbitt to carry out the more
flexible approach that he prefers.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republican environmental proposals that the administration
opposes may also be attached to the omnibus bill as Congress leaves
town for the elections, and the administration has threatened to
veto the omnibus bill if it contains those.
</P>
<P>
   The endangered species measure has broad bipartisan support in
the Senate, but in the House it is opposed by many liberal
Democrats and conservative Republicans, for different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Most major environmental organizations oppose it, saying it does
not do enough to guarantee that endangered species recover from the
destruction of their habitat.
</P>
<P>
   Many other groups, who advocate the rights of property owners,
especially small landowners, over the preservation of species, also
oppose the bill.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sens. John Chafee of Rhode Island and Dirk Kempthorne of Idaho,
the Republicans who co-authored the bill, have been lobbying hard
to get House budget negotiators to include it on the omnibus
spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would support that,'' said Chafee, one of the Republican
Party's leading environmentalists. ``It seems to be a catch-all for
all kinds of legislation that have not been considered in great
depth by one body or another. But as far as the Senate goes, we
worked extremely hard on it, had a whole host of hearings, a
markup, and reported it out. And it has been on the calendar for a
year, so it isn't unknown to the House of Representatives.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the House, conservatives from western states may save the
day for their arch-rivals in the environmental movement. Led by
Rep. George Radanovich, R-Calif., the vice-chairman of the Western
caucus in the House, they are working hard to get House leaders to
keep the proposal off the omnibus bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We in the House have certainly not had a look at the bill, or
had the opportunity to amend it,'' said Radanovich.
</P>
<P>
   Although he said the situation remains fluid, he said that
``right now, the leadership is opposing putting it on the spending
bill, primarily because of the opposition that has been voiced'' by
conservative Western lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   But the Western Governors Association is supporting the
legislation's passage.
</P>
<P>
   Several interest groups, from environmental organizations to
homebuilders, were working hard to influence the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Home Builders circulated a letter in
the House saying that the revisions to the Endangered Species Act
are ``long overdue and the provisions included in the omnibus
package are important improvements.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Competitive Enterprise Institute, a conservative
research organization, called on Republican leaders to reject the
bill, calling it ``anti-property rights and anti-landowner.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups said that they expected the legislation to
die, more because of the opposition of House conservatives than
because of opposition from their own allies, like Rep. George
Miller, D-Calif., and Rep. Jim Saxon, R-N.J., both of whom wrote
congressional leaders asking for the bill to be killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this bill has more enemies than friends,'' Melinda
Pierce, endangered-species lobbyist at the Sierra Club. ``We seem
to be linking our arms with the property-rights caucus. Whatever it
takes, we will link arms.''
</P>
</TEXT>
