<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRIDE-RITE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRIDE RITE BACKS AWAY FROM LEVI STRAUSS LICENSING PACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stride Rite Corp. said Friday it will stop marketing a footwear
line made under a licensing agreement with Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. and
take a fourth-quarter charge of $3.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   While Levi's accounted for only 3 percent of third-quarter
sales, Stride Rite looked to licensing agreements with such fashion
companies as Levi's, Tommy Hilfiger, and Nine West to augment sales
of its core brands _ Keds, Stride Rite children's shoes, and Sperry
Top-Siders.
</P>
<P>
   Ending the relationship with Levi's ``was a difficult decision
for us,'' said Stride Rite chairman and chief executive Robert C.
Siegel, 61, a former Levi Strauss executive who plans to step down
shortly from his Stride Rite jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Launched just three months ago, the Levi's footwear line did not
meet sales expectations, Siegel said.
</P>
<P>
   Levi's may be a powerful brand name, but in recent years, its
denim apparel has lost cachet with younger consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Stride Rite, sales for Keds have been booming,
and Wall Street analysts don't expect the Levi's decision to have a
major impact on the Lexington, Mass. company.
</P>
<P>
   Keds account for about 35 percent of the company's 1997 sales of
$515.7 million. The Stride Rite children's shoes accounted for
another 35 percent of 1997 sales.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Marotta, an analyst with Wasserstein Perella Securities,
hailed Stride Rite's decision to end its relationship with Levi's.
Sometimes the best thing, he said, is ``to cut your losses
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's insignificant,'' Morgan Stanley Dean Witter analyst
Josephine R. Esquivel said of the decision to pull the plug on the
Levi's line. ``The real story is the turnaround of Keds.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Stride Rite said third-quarter sales were up 17
percent and profits were up 56 percent to $12.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   But uncertainty over future sales for the licensed shoe lines
prompted Tucker Anthony analyst Steven A. Richter to lower some of
his estimates for Stride Rite's future performance.
</P>
<P>
   In a report dated Sept. 25, Richter shaved 5 cents off his 1999
earnings-per-share estimate, from 80 to 75 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, after Stride Rite's announcement about the Levi's shoe
line, Richter indicated that he may revise his 1999 estimate
slightly downward again.
</P>
<P>
   After losing money in 1995, Stride Rite has bounced back. Even
so, its stock price has languished, in part, analysts say, because
the entire shoe industry is in disfavor on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, company stock shares rose 15/16
to close at 7 13/16 after hitting a 52-week low earlier in the
week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 1842EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
