<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Saturday, Oct. 10. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SHARON (Jerusalem) _ Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
appointed Ariel Sharon, a hawkish former defense minister, to be
foreign minister in a bid to placate the far right wing as he moves
closer to turning over more West Bank land to the Palestinians. By
Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-AID (Moscow) _ Rocked by a poor harvest and a plummeting
ruble, Russian appealed for humanitarian aid from the West. By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHAN-AID-GROUPS (Kabul, Afghanistan) _ Nearly three months
have passed since 23 international aid groups left this country
rather than obey a command to move their non-Afghan employees into
a decrepit and abandoned row of college dormitories at the
capital's edge. The international agencies had been supplying clean
water and fresh bread and medical necessities _ services that
benefited 400,000 people, a third of the city's population. There
is no one to take their place. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-HEALTH (Washington) _ Legislation to protect patients'
rights died Friday, a casualty of heavy lobbying by the insurance
industry and of the sex scandal that has enveloped President
Clinton. But supporters and opponents said similar legislation
would be back next year. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IMPEACH (Washington) _ Settling the question of what
kind of impeachment investigation the House of Representatives
wants did nothing to settle the partisan squabbling about how it
should be conducted, and Judiciary Committee members immediately
began arguing about a range of issues, including whether to call
Kenneth Starr to testify. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-RELIGION (Washington) _ Congress unanimously approved
legislation Friday that would require the government to punish
countries that persecute its citizens for their religious beliefs.
By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-PRODI (Rome) _ By only one vote, the center-left prime
minister of Italy, Romano Prodi, lost a confidence vote in
parliament and was toppled from power. The collapse of his
government after two and a half years, making it the second-longest
to hold office since World War II, suggested that the chronic
political instability that marked Italy for decades has sprung back
to life. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   NY-GOV-RACE (New York) _ Although many Democratic candidates
across the country are uneasily keeping their beleaguered president
at arms' length, Peter Vallone, the Democratic candidate for
governor, is politically embracing Bill Clinton _ and his high
approval ratings _ head on.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ The stock market rallied Friday, with the
technology heavy Nasdaq index jumping almost 5 percent and the Dow
Jones industrial average climbing 2 percent. By Jonathan
Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-INDIANS-YANKS (Cleveland) _ Game 3, Yankees-Indians. By
Buster Olney.
</P>
</TEXT>
