<SLUG> BC-BELARUS-CHILD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTIM OF CHERNOBYL BACK IN THE US 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GLORIA NEGRI  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In late September, as autumn was turning to winter in
north central Europe, Alexei Anatolevich Saponchikov, a victim of
the Chernobyl nuclear fallout, returned to the orphanage for
disabled children in Belarus that had been his home for so long.
</P>
<P>
   When they heard his car approaching, the 130 children who live
at the orphanage rushed to the windows to welcome their friend back
from America. Some on crutches hobbled out to greet him.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen-year-old Alexei, who is called ``Alosha'' and still
struggles with the juvenile arthritis and severely stunted growth
that plague him as a result of the radiation spread across Europe
by the Chernobyl explosion in the Ukraine in 1986, cried with
excitement to see his old friends.
</P>
<P>
   But his joy was mixed with pain over the realization that he
might, again, be back for good at the orphanage where he was taken
a dozen years ago after his mother abandoned him when he was 11
months old. After 15 months in the United States, Alosha's
immigration papers had expired.
</P>
<P>
   The boy _ who weighs about 40 pounds and stands just 38 inches
tall _ held firmly to the hand of Daniel Joyce, the man who had
become his surrogate father and accompanied him to Belarus.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce made the bittersweet journey with Alosha not only because
he loves him, but to see Belarus and US officials about remedying
insufficient documentation to allow Alosha to stay in the states
permanently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing was certain when we started out,'' Joyce said this
week about their trip to Belarus. ``Alosha knew we were trying our
best to get him to come back, ``but that it was a chance and he
accepted that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chernobyl Children Project in Hingham, Mass. paid for their
flight to Belarus. At first, Joyce and Alosha stayed with Alosha's
doctor in Gomel, about an hour's drive from the orphanage. Alosha
visited with his girlfriend, Lena, and with Max, a Chernobyl victim
with thyroid cancer, who had stayed with the Joyces with him. Then,
the orphanage director drove them to the only home Alosha had known
until last year.
</P>
<P>
   For 13 days, Joyce, 39, the director of systems support at
Fidelity Investments in Boston, stayed at the orphanage with
Alosha, sleeping on a couch and making two 16-hour overland
journeys to Minsk, the Belarus capital, to see Belarus and US
officials about Alosha's documentation.
</P>
<P>
   He returned with a six-month medical visa for Alosha to return
to this country and said that a more permanent arrangement will
take ``anywhere from two to three months.''
</P>
<P>
   Alosha's apprehension at returning to Belarus was not that the
people at the orphanage treated him badly. On the contrary, they
cared for him well, allowing him to come to Boston in the summer of
1997 for respite and medical treatment with 83 other Chernobyl
victims under a program sponsored by the Chernobyl Children
Project.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the orphanage and the governments of Belarus and the
United States gave permission for Alosha to extend his stay for
medical treatment for his many orthopedic ailments related to his
arthritis, unavailable in Belarus. He also had dental surgery for
seriously rotted teeth.
</P>
<P>
   For the last 15 months, Alosha has been living just outside
Boston, at the Milton home of Dan and Janet Joyce and their three
sons, Dan, 15, Doug, 12, and Ryan, 8. There, he has experienced a
sense of family for the first time in his tragic life.
</P>
<P>
   With an impish smile almost as broad as he is, Alosha has stolen
the hearts of all who've met him. His ailments and severe joint
deformities have prevented him from growing beyond his 38-inch
frame.
</P>
<P>
   What was to have been a summer's stay in 1997 was extended after
the Joyces and doctors at The Floating Hospital for Children at New
England Medical Center, which gives free medical treatment to the
Chernobyl children, convinced the governments of Belarus and the
United States how vital such treatment was for Alosha.
</P>
<P>
   Bordered by Russia, Latvia, Lithuania, and Poland, Belarus won
independence from the former Soviet Union in 1991. It is still a
very poor country with medical supplies in short supply. Joyce was
stunned at what he saw at the orphanage, ``badly burned children,
some with birth defects, broken legs, epilepsy.''
</P>
<P>
   On his recent return there, Alosha was knocked down by children
rushing to a meal and the femur of his left leg was broken. ``They
don't have any facilities there,'' Joyce recalled this week. ``So,
we made a splint with sticks and clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Alosha is back in Milton now and waiting for the next chapter of
his life to unfold.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he is in a cast and on crutches, he continues to go
on a bus to the Glover School, working at a fifth-grade level.
While he needed an intrepreter when he first arrived, he now speaks
English without a trace of a Russian accent, and has forgotten some
of his native language.
</P>
<P>
   Tiny as Alosha is, he horses around with the Joyce sons as if he
were 6 feet tall. Now, the brothers vie over who is going to carry
him around the house while he wears the cast.
</P>
<P>
   The other night, in anticipation of Halloween, Alosha donned a
magician's top hat and hammed it up for a photographer. Around his
neck he wore a cross that the Joyces had given him. He will always
love them, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the time he has been here, Alosha has had his first-ever
birthday party at 13, grew to love chicken, and sang Russian folk
songs at karaoke nights. He is an extrovert.
</P>
<P>
   Though his diminutive size first attracts, it is Alosha's blue
eyes that arrest. Even while he is trying to be a flippant
teenager, they harbor a deep melancholy.
</P>
<P>
   With his major physical problems, Alosha knows his medical
future is uncertain. His medications, alone, Joyce said, cost about
$235 a month. The Joyces are planning a fund-raiser on Nov. 14 to
help meet Alosha's needs.
</P>
<P>
   But, Alosha still flashes his dimpled smile that moves so many
to tears. The Delta Air Lines crew that flew him and Joyce free
from New York to Boston last week were among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing Alosha has given us,'' Dan Joyce said, ``is
the sense of hope and love he has, in spite of the fact that he
grew up in such poverty and hardship.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Those wishing to contribute to a fund for Alosha's medical
needs may do so sending checks to The Alosha Fund: US Trust, Box
25, Milton, MA 02186).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
