<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SOUTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO MODERATE DEMOCRATS FACE TOUGH CHOICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One is a black Democrat representing a
majority-white district in rural southwest Georgia. The other is a
white Democrat who hails from a sprawling South Carolina district
where blacks are more than 30 percent of the voting-age population.
</P>
<P>
   Both are moderates facing tough reelection battles that may turn
largely on the strength of black voter turnout. And the question
facing them was the same: Would they vote for an open-ended
impeachment inquiry against a president who is popular among
African-Americans?
</P>
<P>
   For Representatives Sanford D. Bishop Jr. of Georgia and John M.
Spratt Jr. of South Carolina, the answers turned out to be
different. Spratt voted Thursday with the Republican majority to
launch only the third presidential impeachment inquiry in US
history; Bishop voted against the GOP plan.
</P>
<P>
   Their decisions underscored more than just the dilemma that
confronts many congressional Democrats who represent districts that
are both black and white, rural and urban. While black voters are
more united around Clinton and tend to vote Democratic, polls show,
whites are split in their attitudes about the president and in
their vote.
</P>
<P>
   As lawmakers try to wrap up their work this weekend and return
home to campaign for the Nov. 3 elections, they will find how their
votes on impeachment are playing among the voters. In districts
where candidates need the support of both black and whites, any
action in the impeachment process could simultaneously attract and
alienate important constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue for a lot of Democrats is how many white voters do
they have in their districts for whom not only is this inquiry a
big deal for them, but who are anti-Clinton and will vote solely on
the basis of how their member of Congress votes in terms of the
impeachment proceedings,'' said David Bositis, senior political
analyst at the Joint Center for Political and Economic Studies, a
black think tank in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop, the most conservative member of the Congressional Black
Caucus, joined his 35 black colleagues in the House in voting
Thursday against the Republicans' unrestricted probe of Clinton
that could go beyond his relationship with former White House
intern Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   All but two of the caucus members voted for the Democratic
alternative that would have placed more limits on the inquiry.
Those two _ Representatives John Lewis and Cynthia McKinney of
Georgia _ opposed any type of inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   While Spratt may face the wrath of blacks voters who may
perceive his vote in favor of an impeachment inquiry as a vote
against Clinton, for Bishop, his vote may turn out to be the bigger
political gamble.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his other black colleagues, who conspiciously rallied on
the House floor against an open-ended inquiry, Bishop was low key.
He had refused to reveal how he would vote in advance.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued after the vote, Bishop said: ``After
prayerful consideration and thoughtful deliberation in consultation
with my constituents,'' he decided against voting for the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have been politically expedient, and voted for the
Republicans resolution, but I could not in good conscience put my
personal and political interests ahead of the well-being of the
people'' of his district and the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He went on, ``The president's conduct was wrong, it is
indefensible, and he should be punished. But it is the president
who should be punished, not the country.''
</P>
<P>
   By voting against the inquiry, Bishop could face a backlash from
white and rural voters, who are in the majority in his heavily
agricultural district and who are less enamored with Clinton than
Bishop's black constituents.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Bishop's is the only one among the 11 congressional races in
Georgia considered up for grabs, said Bill Shipp, the publisher of
a popular political newspaper in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before Bishop cast his vote, Shipp said the ``best
politics'' for Bishop was to vote for the inquiry. ``It doesn't
matter much with the black vote, but it will matter a lot with the
white vote,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shipp said Bishop's opponent, a conservative businessman from
Albany, Joe McCormick, is likely to use a ``no'' vote against
Bishop. ``He will beat him over the head with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Silas Lee, a political pollster and sociologist at Xavier
University in New Orleans, said that Spratt's vote also contained
risk. He ``alienated 30 percent of his electorate, or a majority of
that 30 percent,'' Lee said. ``That that is not a good position for
anyone seeking reelection.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ron Lester, a Democratic pollster, said that ``even among
African-American voters, it's difficult for them to make the case
that there should not be any action taken by Congress against the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Brent Weaver, executive director of the South Carolina
Democratic Party, said Spratt's Republican challenger, Rock Hill
businessman Mike Burhold, had already begun ``trying to connect him
with the president and make them much closer than they may be.''
</P>
<P>
   He conceded Spratt's vote may not sit well with black voters in
his district. ``There's a fine line to tow in regard to this issue
_ not upsetting African-Americans who are in support of the
president and those Democrats who are,'' he said. Although Spratt's
and Bishop's vote could cause problems among some constituents, the
impeachment drive may stay on the margin of issues voters care
about in their districts, said Bositis at the Joint Center.
</P>
<P>
   The key for them and similarly situated Democrats will be voter
turnout, he said. ``The Democrats main problem in regard to turnout
is there is a big proportion of people in the country, maybe a
majority, who really don't care about this scandal at all,''
Bositis said. ``The problem is that a lot of those same people
don't care about politics either, and so they don't vote.''
</P>
</TEXT>
