<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GORE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE WARNS THAT MAJOR ISSUES BEING IGNORED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Vice President Al Gore, in his first public remarks on
the House vote to launch an impeachment inquiry of President
Clinton, Friday warned that the hearings have stirred partisanship
that threatens to derail progress on key economic and policy
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers have been totally distracted from issues such as a
patients' bill of rights, environmental protection, and saving
Social Security, said Gore, who arrived in Boston Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, who used his visit to announce a major
environmental accord between chemical producers and the
Environmental Protection Agency, did not defend the president's
actions in the Monica S. Lewinsky matter. Instead he took a long
view at the Clinton presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people place'' Clinton's actions ``in a larger
context and balance them against all the great things he has done
as president of the United States,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why the overwhelming majority of people in both parties
and independents want to see this over quickly,'' Gore said, adding
that he hopes Congress handles the impeachment process ``fairly and
as speedily as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   As the House proceeds with the impeachment investigation, Gore
said he hopes ``that no matter what party we're in, we're all
Americans first; let's not let partisanship get in the way of
progress of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeting Gore at Logan International Airport Friday was EPA chief
Carol Browner, and Mayor Thomas M. Menino.
</P>
<P>
   The Chemical Manufacturers' Association signed an accord with
the EPA to set up a schedule of tests of chemicals the public
commonly encounters to determine their health risks.
</P>
<P>
   Browner credited Gore's attention to the issue and his belief
that better decisions result from parties who collaborate rather
than lock horns as adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Weber, head of the manufacturers' association, said the
industry was agreeing to an ambitious and expensive, voluntary
program rather than having the EPA mandate tests and enforce fines.
</P>
<P>
   The chemical industry expects to spend $700 million by 2002 to
conduct the tests on 3,000 chemicals and to then make the results
available to the public. The chemicals include common water
additives such as chlorine as well as solvents and petrochemicals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
