<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-GREECE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREECE AWARDS RAYTHEON $1.45B PACT FOR PATRIOT MISSILES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raytheon Co. Friday said it won a long-awaited contract to
supply Greece with $1.45 billion worth of Patriot missiles and
other military equipment _ welcome relief for Raytheon's
Massachusetts workers, who have been fretting about layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriot missile, made famous during the Gulf War for
intercepting Iraq's Scud missiles, is built at Raytheon's Andover,
Mass. plant, which just this week announced 400 new job cuts, on
top of several earlier cutbacks.
</P>
<P>
   While the Greek missile order won't reverse those layoffs,
Raytheon spokeswoman Toni Simonetti said, ``What we we hope this
will do is help us stabilize our employment in Andover.''
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon currently has 2,952 employees in Andover, but many have
been idle for months, because of a lack of new orders for Patriot
and Hawk missiles, which are also assembled there.
</P>
<P>
   ``There just hasn't been enough work to keep them all busy,''
said Simonetti. In fact, Raytheon in August announced 261 layoffs
in Andover because several hoped-for missile orders from foreign
countries were delayed because of global economic uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big contract,'' Simonetti said of the Greek Patriot
business. ``We're very happy about it. It's an important win for
the Andover operations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Andover plant is already operating well below historical
levels because production of another major missile, the AMRAAM, was
moved to Tuscon earlier this year. The shift was part of Raytheon's
consolidation efforts following its buyout of the defense units of
Hughes Electronics Corp. and Texas Instruments Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the plant will benefit from Raytheon's decision to
consolidate all of its circuit card assembly work in Andover, but
that shift has yet to occur.
</P>
<P>
   The union that represents Raytheon's manufacturing workers in
Andover welcomed news of the Greek missile order.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something we've been waiting for for a long time,''
said Michael Zagami, business manager of Local 1505 of the
International Brothers of Electrical Workers in Waltham.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had had this news sooner, maybe we might not have had
the layoffs,'' said Zagami, who blasted Raytheon officials earlier
this week for reneging on commitments to keep jobs in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The order for at least four, and possibly, six Patriot missiles
is the largest element of the Greek military contract. Raytheon
said the Patriot business could be worth as much as $1.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Greece will become the ninth country to buy the Patriot system.
The others are the United States, Israel, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia,
Germany, the Netherlands, Japan and Taiwan. Raytheon is also
targeting the United Arab Emirates, Egypt and South Korea for
Patriot sales, but analysts fear that economic and political
turmoil in those countries will likely delay any new orders.
</P>
<P>
   Greece will also buy 45 of Raytheon's new T-6A Texan II military
trainer aircraft. The planes, built in Wichita by Raytheon's
aircraft subsidiary, are valued at $200 million. Deliveries start
in July 1999 and extend through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The nation also awarded a $145 million contract to upgrade its
Hawk air-defense system to HKV, a joint venture between Raytheon
and Norway's Kongsberg Gruppen ASA.
</P>
<P>
   The Greek military is undertaking a major five-year
modernization that will cost nearly $16 billion, said Achilles
Paparsenos, a Greek Embassy spokesman in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon had been expecting the Greek order for months, but
despite finally claiming it, the company still expects slower
growth in the next few years as economic weakness causes nations to
scale back their military purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Raytheon cut its sales growth forecast and
said it would cut its defense workforce 16 percent _ 5,300 more
jobs than planned _ to cope with slumping demand overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it now expects annual sales growth of 6 percent
to 8 percent, compared with an earlier estimate of 10 percent. By
stepping up cost reductions, however, Raytheon said it expects
profits to grow at a faster 10 to 12 percent rate.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon also took a $284 million charge against earnings,
mostly to cope with weakness in its engineering unit.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon's Class B shares closed at 55 1/8, down 1 7/8.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Aaron Zitner of the Globe Washington bureau contributed to this
story.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
