<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9210 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHELL-TECH$ADV11-HNS &LR;      10-09 2639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHELL-TECH$ADV11-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHELL-TECH-$ADV11 
 
SHELL ATTEMPTS TO FOSTER NEW TECHNOLOGIES, CAPITALIZE ON THEM 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 11) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HILLARY DURGIN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of Dr. Harold Vinegar's most promising inventions had a
three-year coating of dust when a colleague stopped by his
laboratory at Shell Oil Co. and stunned him with a seemingly casual
question:
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have any ideas?''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his file cabinet were photos and vials of treated
soil, evidence of a technological breakthrough capable of cleaning
up the dirtiest of industrial sites, transforming tar-contaminated
soils into clean, white beach sand.
</P>
<P>
   What really amazed Vinegar was that someone inside Shell saw a
business opportunity in an idea that the oil company's top
executives repeatedly had rejected. Not even inquiries from
potential customers such as General Electric Co., anxious to use
Vinegar's technology to clean up their polluted sites, could pique
their interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just unbelievable,'' Vinegar says. ``The argument had
always been, `We're not interested in that business _ we're in the
oil business.' Suddenly, here was a group of people that were both
scientists as well as entrepreneurs and eager to take a new idea
and look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   What Vinegar and others now call ``revolutionary'' was a radical
new venture for the fiercely secretive company. Shell was quietly
forming a business to uncover cutting-edge technology buried deep _
and all too often lost _ inside its maze-like bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been some Shell-sized businesses created from
Shell's technologies in the past where Shell got virtually no
profit,'' says Bill Dirks, leader of the effort called Shell
Technology Ventures. He conceived and sold the idea of creating a
company to commercialize discoveries made in Royal Dutch
Shell/Group's labs.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, short-sighted policies that allowed other companies
to license Shell-authored technologies enabled them to profit from
the oil company's innovations. Shell, whose exploration and
production research lab has a $500-million-a-year budget, had made
discoveries that led to such breakthrough ideas as the floating
drilling rig, and a computer chip design that was the precursor to
random access memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal _ I have a hard time getting our employees to believe
it some days _ our goal is to be a Fortune 500 company in 10
years,'' says Dirks, president and chief executive officer of Shell
Technology Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for Shell _ and Dirks _ is to create an
environment within the world's largest public oil company where
entrepreneurs can thrive and build a start-up company. In the past,
Shell, and other big oil companies, have done a great job
developing technology and a miserable job of marketing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're doing is dramatically different,'' says Fred
Lowther, chairman of the Washington, D.C., law firm Dickstein,
Shapiro, Morin, and Oshinsky, which specializes in launching
start-ups at energy companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly countercultural to energy companies,'' says John
Griffin, partner in the Houston office at Heidrick &AMP; Struggles, the
executive search firm, referring to the concept behind the unit.
``Energy companies are so driven to be proprietary. What Shell
(said) is, `We've got a machine in here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Griffin and Lowther are both members of a four-person advisory
board Dirks set up to help guide the venture.
</P>
<P>
   For Vinegar and his fellow researchers, the new company has
created for the first time at Shell a forum for discussing and
selling ideas, unleashing a wave of entrepreneurial energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly people are taking things off their shelves,'' Vinegar
says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Research cut back industrywide &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shell's new venture comes at a time when researchers at oil
companies feel a bit like an endangered species. The oil industry
dramatically scaled back research and development spending in the
late 1980s and early 1990s. And today's low oil prices intensify
pressure to cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   A common worry within the industry is that this bottom-line
focus will stifle innovative ideas and the entrepreneurial culture
necessary to foster them _ the lifeblood of an effort such as
Shell's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice idea but it depends on how it's managed,'' says
Ronald Robinson, president of Texaco Technology, referring to
Shell's new venture.
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming pressure to deliver strong profits could
discourage scientists from embarking on new, risky ideas that hold
out an equal promise of breakthrough and a failure, Robinson warns.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage innovation, Robinson has set aside 7 percent to 10
percent of his research and development budget for scientists to
pursue the projects of their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't use it,'' he says incredulously. ``The pressures on
them to produce things that are incremental is so great at the
price of oil we have today,'' Robinson explains. ``We need a
different culture.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem industrywide is that when researchers devote their
efforts to sure things, the results only yield relatively minor
improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mindset is such that when the price of oil is $13 or $14,
the opportunity to stick your neck out _ the culture's just not
there,'' Robinson says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Products give business boost &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite such industry pressures, Shell unveiled its new
technology venture in August, and the business is off and running
with two new products.
</P>
<P>
   Vinegar's invention had already spawned a 2-year-old company,
TerraTherm Environmental Services, which specializes in removing
hazardous waste from the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The second business idea is being developed through a joint
venture with Halliburton Co. It involves a process that expands
pipe casing in oil wells drilled in difficult to operate places,
such as mile-deep waters.
</P>
<P>
   This approach solves the problem that forced companies to use
progressively smaller diameter pipe as a well got deeper. By
expanding the pipe, oil companies can drill smaller holes while
drilling deeper, greatly reducing the cost.
</P>
<P>
   In the next two years, Shell Technology Ventures hopes to sell
technology that produces heat from natural gas without a flame.
This could enable industrial plants to substantially reduce
hazardous emissions and could someday allow the development of
flameless industrial or home furnaces.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another technology promises to lower infrastructure costs
and operating expenses at natural gas processing plants by
stripping liquids from natural gas more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   While Dirks has the backing of one of the world's richest
companies, the launch of the group is something of a high-wire act.
He has to balance the uncertainty of any one technology's success
with the need to deliver profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to tell, even when you have the right new market and
the right financing ... which new business is going to be a billion
dollar business and which is going to be a flop,'' Dirks says.
</P>
<P>
   Shell Technology Ventures has ``got to show very rapid
profitability,'' he notes. He predicts it will meet that point in
three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to find a way somehow to pay back the corporation.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getting ahead of the curve
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Shell's budding business opportunities often never
saw the light of day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our philosophy in Shell for decades has been, `Our technology
is for our beneficial use only,''' Dirks says. ``We never
purposefully in Shell have had a philosophy of sharing our
technology with the commercial marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   That began to change in 1994 with an initiative launched by
Philip Carroll, then Shell Oil's chief executive officer. The
high-level effort sought to develop new ventures outside Shell's
core oil and gas business to provide new and better sources of
future earnings.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Dirks, then a 37-year-old geologist who'd been with
Shell for 13 years, was on a conventional career track involved in
U.S. exploration. He saw change engulfing the industry and he
wanted to be ahead of it.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll's effort provided an opportunity for Dirks, who held
what he describes as ``an interesting conversation'' with Jack
Little, then president of Shell Exploration &AMP; Production Co. Dirks
told him he didn't want to be onshore exploration manager anymore
and asked Little, now CEO of Shell Oil, for the chance to lead the
team developing growth opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Little didn't grant Dirk's wish, but left him an opening by
providing some time, a few workers and a small budget to work on
the initiative. Dirks and his team began asking for ideas from
researchers and even set up a ``Wild Ideas'' Web site on Shell's
in-house computer network.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we'd get a response, it kept being from somebody in
the labs, and they'd pull open a drawer, and out would come a
patent or out would come a document that had been buried and it
would be fabulous,'' Dirks recalls.
</P>
<P>
   After months of culling through ideas from Shell's labs in
Houston, Dirks' team had a stack of about eight or 10 ideas to
choose from.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became very clear: Shell was a Fortune 500 company with a
lot of R&AMP;D that could be leveraged,'' Dirks says. ``To me, there
was no reason why we couldn't become a competitor to Lucent
Technologies in our own industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The geologist-turned-entrepreneur now had to become a political
strategist as well to garner support within this global company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to market the idea to parts of Shell that I didn't even
know existed,'' Dirks said.
</P>
<P>
   To guide his campaign, Dirks drew a map of what he called
``company stakeholders,'' listing likely backers and critics, and
he embarked on an eight-month campaign for support.
</P>
<P>
   Over and over he made that argument that if Shell invested in
marketing its technologies, it could create billion-dollar
businesses. At the same time, it would maintain control of its
technologies for Shell and other users.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with business plans for both the new venture and a new
company based on Vinegar's technology, Dirks won approval from Jack
Little to launch Shell Technology Ventures as a U.S. effort in the
spring of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The unit moved quickly to act on Vinegar's invention and
established a new company to launch it called TerraTherm
Environmental Services. It quickly set up a marketing plan, hired
an employment agency to staff TerraTherm, and set up TerraTherm
offices in The Woodlands.
</P>
<P>
   At a Shell test facility in southwest Houston, which Vinegar
calls his ``playground'', Shell has tested Vinegar's equipment for
removing contaminants from the soil, as well as tools for
underwater seismic surveys and well logging exercises.
</P>
<P>
   While showing a visitor around the site, which looks like a
miniature golf course of oil-field contraptions, Vinegar lingers
almost lovingly at the TerraTherm equipment. It includes a sort of
industrial electric blanket that heats the ground to temperatures
of 1,000 degrees Celsius, literally boiling out harmful
contaminants such as PCBs, the acronym for Polychlorinated
Hydrocarbons. This process is sold as odorless, noiseless and
doesn't require disturbing the ground.
</P>
<P>
   It has been used in six jobs in the past two years, including
the cleanup of a former drag strip Superfund site in New York owned
by General Electric and a U.S. Army Corps of Engineers job on the
island of Saipan, where the carcinogenic chemical leaked out of
transformers islanders used to decorate their homes and family
gravesites.
</P>
<P>
   While Vinegar says the technology is effective, he admits the
price of doing the jobs will limit the market. To create a mass
market among industrial operators, they'll need to reduce the cost
enough to make this type of cleanup competitive with the price of
capping a polluted site and walking away from it.
</P>
<P>
   TerraTherm also is examining options to use the technology in
such situations as cleaning up chemical plant sites, railroad yards
and even sterilizing the soil in farm fields to get rid of harmful
pests.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Partnership takes shape &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just as the discovery and development of Vinegar's technology
helped garner support for the new venture from Shell, Dirks logged
another milestone in reaching a joint venture agreement with
Halliburton.
</P>
<P>
   The pact with the oil-field service and supply giant to market
Shell Technology's other big product helped sell the concept of the
new business unit to the powers that be at Shell's parent, Royal
Dutch/Shell in July.
</P>
<P>
   From that point on, Shell Technology Ventures went from being a
domestic organization to become a global organization with
deep-pocketed support.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, this second venture also demonstrated that marketing
new ideas in the oil service business is a tricky sell. Shell
Technology realized that, to commercialize its inventions, it would
need help from the companies that control access to oil company
customers.
</P>
<P>
   But convincing big oil-field service companies, such as
Halliburton or Schlumberger, to join in a Shell-led venture
represented a new way of doing business.
</P>
<P>
   It took a year for Halliburton and Shell to overcome mutual
suspicions prior to forming the latest of Shell Technology
Ventures' businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants an extra competitor, particularly when that
competitor is as large as Shell,'' notes Dirks.
</P>
<P>
   That venture represented a change from the traditional
relationship in which oil-field service companies traditionally
have licensed technology from oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   Halliburton officials say they were concerned that they would be
blamed if the joint venture failed, potentially antagonizing one of
their best customers. Shell executives feared that Halliburton
would not work hard to sell a technology that might compete with
some of its existing products.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those soft issues are very, very important,'' says Ali
Daneshy, vice president of integrated technology products at
Halliburton Energy Services in Houston. ``Today we are very
comfortable with each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``This technology will make a difference,`` he notes.
</P>
<P>
   Called Enventure Global Technology, the tool uses a device,
called a pig, made of secret materials crafted with special angles,
that expands the width of the pipe casing like a hand pushing
through a tight sock. It allows the operator to drill deeper, using
fewer strings of casing to complete a well while also taking less
time.
</P>
<P>
   Shell is still working on convincing other oil-field service
companies that it is not a competitor. And if Dirks keeps up the
dogged persistence and sensitive politicking that already have
changed so many minds, he may just end up being successful.
</P>
<P>
   For now, he's not content.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long term, the track record has yet to be proven,'' he
says. And while there are pressures to succeed, &UR;  &LR; Dirks says the
greatest challenge is to deliver on the promises he has made to his
colleagues who, like him, have left promising careers to pursue
this vision of Shell Technology Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to do anything that's going to cost them their
jobs because we couldn't get this profitable,'' Dirks says.
</P>
<P>
   Oil prices now are a major worry in the business _ slowing
exploration and triggering thousands of layoffs. Earlier this week,
Shell said it would cut 740 jobs, or 20 percent of its work force
at its exploration and production unit. But Dirks argues the
technologies he is developing will end up cutting costs, and
ultimately changing the way the energy industry _ and possibly
other industries as well _ do business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's big money to be made _ if I can find one big-hit
technology, we can start a Shell-sized business,'' Dirks says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It only takes one semisubmersible drilling rig venture to do
that, which is why I think we're going to make it.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
