<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS-HEAVEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Filmmakers say portraying heaven is one of their trickiest tasks
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Angels playing harps. Gates of pearl. People wearing crowns as
they float blissfully about a golden city nestled in the clouds.
</P>
<P>
   It might be heaven, but it's hell for filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Images of heaven have inspired people of faith for ages, but the
subject is a major pain for filmmakers. The problem? A
conflict-free existence with no nasty villains may be great
theology, but produces boring movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you say, 'We all live in peace and harmony and worship
God,' you don't have much of a plot after that,'' said Fritz Boger,
a minister who teaches a course on film and faith at Columbia
Theological Seminary in Decatur.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Ward disagrees. He's the director of ``What Dreams May
Come,'' a multimillion-dollar movie released last weekend that
focuses on the afterlife and stars Robin Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Ward departs from the traditonal view of heaven. In his vision,
each person experiences a different version of heaven. And his
angels aren't winged, celestial creatures. They curse; one cranky
angel even challenges another to a fight.
</P>
<P>
   Ward said he had to do something different because he was
tackling a subject that filmmakers dread.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen paradise or heaven depicted in a compelling
fashion,'' Ward said during a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   Blame some of that on Christian theology.
</P>
<P>
   In the book of Matthew, Jesus declares that romantic
relationships are dissolved in heaven _ ``For in the resurrection
they neither marry nor are given in marriage but are like angels in
heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Filmmakers, however, know that audiences love a good love story.
That's why the most memorable films on heaven spend more time in
their movies developing romantic relationships than exploring
ephemeral theological themes.
</P>
<P>
   In ``What Dreams May Come,'' Williams' character discovers that
heaven is hell without his soulmate and romantic love.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Defending Your Life,'' director/actor Albert Brooks has to
go to heaven before he can finally meet the perfect woman; ``Made
in Heaven,'' with Timothy Hutton and Kelly McGillis, focuses on a
heaven filled with gardens and bucolic countryside, where they make
love.
</P>
<P>
   Many film critics and directors agree that it's a mistake to
attempt to portray heaven literally. It's better, they think, to
hint at the afterterlife symbolically.
</P>
<P>
   As examples, they point to the startling communion scene at the
end of ``Places In the Heart,'' and the joyous banquet in the
enchanting Danish film ``Babette's Feast.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're (working) with some spiritual themes, all you can
do is infer,'' said the Rev. Timothy McNulty, a Presbyterian
minister who publishes ``Visual parables,'' a newsletter that
examines religious values in film. ``Any attempt to photograph or
pin it down doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Such films also bog down when filmmakers make heaven too
sentimental. That's one of the problems Nancy Dixon of
Lawrenceville had with ``What Dreams May Come.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was overdramatic,'' Dixon said. ``It seemed kind of silly
that the family's two kids would die, then the dog, then the wife _
everybody's dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Filmmakers have been much more successful capturing the
netherworld on film.
</P>
<P>
   Torment is a much easier concept to grasp than bliss, said
Barbara DeConcini, an Emory University professor who is an
authority on religion and film.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know what it means to be utterly miserable,'' DeConcini
said. ``What makes eternal damnation horrifying is the notion that
the worst you've ever felt is going to be your state forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
