<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-LMAY10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Garden will have to roll with The Rock
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MCCAYSVILLE, Ga. _ Like archaeologists on a dig in ancient
lands, Lyn and I began uncovering The Rock that sits majestically
on the hillside sloping to Fightingtown Creek.
</P>
<P>
   This adventure, started a couple of weeks ago, must be done in
stages, as it requires both patience and strength. Patience to weed
out the myriad plants, some tiny, and strength to dislodge the
bigger trees and shrubs that long ago took up residence on the big
stone, spreading tenacious roots deep and wide.
</P>
<P>
   The uncovering launches my gardening on the creek side of the
cabin, coming after months of clearing and digging and planting on
the road side. There, hundreds of excavated rocks form borders and
designs around dozens of plants, creating a kind of mountain
symphony, bearing witness to one more effort to garden against the
odds.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on the creek side, the land had remained untouched.
</P>
<P>
   Now the touching begins. Fitting that it should start with what
arguably is the most impressive part of the landscape. This huge
outcropping, this gigantic piece of gray stone inspires awe; it is
a focal point that no amount of shrubbery can equal in this wild
garden.
</P>
<P>
   I always knew The Rock had presence, but only after we cleared a
bit of its surface did I know just how much presence. Less obscured
by brush, it is much larger than I had thought. Also, looking down
at it from the porch, I was surprised at its clearly defined shape,
a half-moon, with ruffled edges resembling flower petals on the
curved side. It must measure 20 feet across and 10 feet deep.
</P>
<P>
   On the straight side of The Rock, toward the cabin, several
stones just the right size for sitting are lined up. Sit on those
stones and face the big half-moon, and you feel as if you are part
of an audience looking down at a stage. It is easy to imagine
Cherokee elders sitting on these rocks, addressing a group of
council members on The Rock below.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever uses this massive piece of rock has had, it always has
had respect, I know.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone who sees it stops and stares in much the same way that
we all stare at Fightingtown Creek, at the ocean crashing against
rocks, rolling onto sandy shores. There is power in all these
marvels of nature _ a seductive, mesmerizing power.
</P>
<P>
   Uncovering The Rock is, in a sense, freeing it, unleashing its
power.
</P>
<P>
   First, I collected the mosses growing on its surface, anchored
in years of leaf mold. With trowel and pruners, I loosened huge
sheets of these tiny plants, cutting away roots from surrounding
shrubs. With the mosses bedded down in the roadside garden, I
returned to pull out briars and weeds and little pines and laurels.
</P>
<P>
   Lyn raked the leaf mold, pulled weeds and held on to my overalls
to keep me from falling overboard when I leaned over the front of
the stone to prune some shrub from a crevice. Every 20 minutes or
so, we rested on the rocks, looking down at the gray half-moon,
marveling at its change.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly in silence we stared, discovering mottling of charcoal,
light and dark grays on the newly uncovered surface, crevices we
did not know existed. No longer absolutely flat, it bulges gently
here and there.
</P>
<P>
   What else will we discover? Artifacts from other lives, other
times?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, maybe not. That won't matter. The Rock, big, beautiful,
powerful, this first and foremost feature in the garden by the
creek, soon will be free.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: leemay(at)bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
