<SLUG> BC-PIANO-TIPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What to look for before you tickle the ivories
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When shopping for a piano, don't be intimidated by the number of
options. Some key points to remember:
</P>
<P>
   -- Tone. For most, it's the most important feature. Play, or
have a salesperson play, the same short piece on every piano you
consider.
</P>
<P>
   -- Touch. Make sure the keys travel smoothly and quickly,
allowing a full range of expression.
</P>
<P>
   -- Tuning. Ask a technician about the tuning stability of the
various brands you consider.
</P>
<P>
   -- Beauty. Examine the luster and finish of the cabinet. Does it
invite touch? Is it smooth? Is the finish durable?
</P>
<P>
   -- Value. Ask around for brands that have reputations for
quality and durability.
</P>
<P>
   -- Image. Ask the dealer how well the manufacturer is
established and if it has a reputation for quality and integrity.
</P>
<P>
   -- Life. Ask the dealer about its service policy.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Yamaha Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
