</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIANOS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Decorator pianos,' idle or high-tech, can fine-tune rooms
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suzy Berliner and Sandy Hartman may not play the piano, but
their elegant white grand does far more than collect dust _ it
makes a nice backdrop for cat hair.
</P>
<P>
   That's because their large black and white Himalayan, Rhett
Butler, is the only one in their house who uses the piano _ for a
snooze under the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took piano lessons as a kid but only practiced right before
the lessons,'' Berliner said. ``That was the extent of my
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, when she and Hartman built their new home in Buckhead last
spring, its two-story living room screamed for something with some
scale _ and not necessarily the musical kind _ so a grand fit the
bill. ``We bought it just for the look,'' Berliner said. ``But when
someone comes around who can actually play it, it's great!''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, however, the piano is in harmony with a
growing number of others across middle-class America that are
assuming a new role _ as decoration. And that's not such a sad note
for an instrument celebrating almost 300 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the right space, a beautiful piano becomes sculpture,''
said Charles Gandy, an Atlanta interior designer. ``For a lot of
people, the grand is a symbol that they've arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   But not every ``decorator piano'' sits idle. After decades of
relying on sales to moms and dads bent on tapping their kids'
musical talents, piano retailers can vouch: The piano's gone
high-tech. Among their hottest sellers are computerized acoustical
players that offer thousands of songs using compact discs for hours
of continuous music.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have Rachmaninoff playing in your living room while
you're giving a party,'' said Barbara Kirby of Piano Gallery in
Atlanta _ without hiring anyone to tickle the ivories.
</P>
<P>
   The trends reflect the buying habits of consumers who can afford
such a luxurious decoration. ``It used to a real bread-and-butter
thing with kids and lessons,'' said Lori Morse of Baldwin Piano &AMP;
Organ Co. in Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   Decorator and automatic player pianos are a far cry from what
Italian harpsichord maker Bartolomeo di Francesco Cristofori had in
mind when he invented the piano around 1700. Although it would
assume various forms over the next three centuries _ grand, square,
upright, spinet, console _ and finishes, including ebony, walnut,
mahogany, rosewood, ivory and white _ the basic instrument remains
the same.
</P>
<P>
   Grand pianos typically boast better tone than common uprights,
so they cost more; the tilt-top models, therefore, bring more class
to interiors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up in a little town in Ohio in the '40s, I thought
anyone who had a grand was a millionaire,'' Kirby said.
</P>
<P>
   Today's models start at about $10,000 and can reach $150,000 or
more.
</P>
<P>
   And though some buyers have good intentions, others buy grands
with no plans for learning to play. ``I think prestige is what
they're after,'' said Al Rich of Jim Scott Organ &AMP; Pianos in
Marietta, Georgia. ``A grand piano adds an element of elegance to a
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Rich, who estimated some 5 percent of his sales are decorator
pianos, gets a lot of business from designers shopping for
furniture in a specific size and price. ``Quality doesn't come into
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it's the ``piano-shaped object'' their clients are
after. ``They'll say, 'We don't care if it plays' because their
decorator's told them it will look good in their home,'' Morse
said.
</P>
<P>
   One driving force is today's popular house designs. Builders, in
devoting most living space to the great room, have shrunk the less
popular formal living room. Buyers, in turn, have turned to
alternative uses for the living room, such as home offices and
music rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Patty Powers of Atlanta chose the latter. ``I wanted something
that looked like a nice piece of furniture when you walked in the
house,'' she said. So she bought a Baldwin grand _ a white one for
making the room look more contemporary.
</P>
<P>
   Gandy had a client with an even bolder idea. ``We refinished the
piano in Chinese red to match other things in the house,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Decorating magazines also have taught consumers how to use the
piano as a grand display for accessories. ``People love the idea of
grouping silver-framed pictures on top of one or a nice vase of
roses,'' said Linda Westbury, an Atlanta interior designer.
</P>
<P>
   Gandy takes the opposite approach in his Atlanta condo with the
80-year-old grand he acquired from a friend's estate _ one he
actually plays. ``It's a beautiful thing to look at, so I don't
decorate it,'' said the award-winning designer, who takes lessons
every week. ``I cherish the piano too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if they don't play, some buy pianos for entertaining,
whether the player is human or digital.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin's ConcertMaster has a built-in hard drive that can play
almost 10,000 songs using a floppy or compact disc and provide up
to 20 hours of continuous music. The player, which sells for about
$7,000, also can be wired into the home's sound system. ``The piano
is activated, but you have accompaniment playing behind it,'' Morse
said.
</P>
<P>
   For about $5,000, even standard uprights and grands can be
retrofitted for players.
</P>
<P>
   Such advancement has made the piano, the third largest household
investment, appreciate in value even more than it has throughout
time.
</P>
<P>
   Powers knew that when she went shopping for her grand, but she
had an ulterior motive. ``I played growing up, participated in
talent shows, recitals,'' she said. ``It was a big part of my life,
so I wanted to make sure my kids would learn, too.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, she's content to use the white piano as decoration. But
she's pulled out some of her old sheet music from childhood _ just
in case.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
