<DOCNO> NYT19981009.0349 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9217 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEATTLE-COX     10-09 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEATTLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Savoring Seattle: Pack an appetite with your poncho
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL OCTOBER 11: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE_First you notice the baby. All pink cheeks, she is
gnawing on a bright blue potato. Then there's the dude squatting
beside his bicycle, packing a case _ a whole case! _ of peaches
into the side pouches of his two-wheeler. By the time you see the
man ambling around with a bunch of red-veined Swiss chard sprouting
from his backpack, you don't give it a second thought _ even though
it kind of reminds you of van Gogh's lost ear.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Seattle. Everything you've heard is true.
</P>
<P>
   The salmon is redder. The berries are bluer. The greens are
greener. No wonder people here are literally becoming attached to
their food. They are the counterparts of Parisians who wander the
streets with baguettes under their arms. Already known as a mecca
of earth-loving, bike-riding, coffee-drinking individualists, this
city is blossoming into a full-blown food lover's paradise, a
veritable Eden by the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Roll over, James Beard. Au revoir, Alice Waters.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle is creating an exciting culinary vocabulary that is
uniquely its own. Unlike the South, which boasts a mythic cuisine
some 300 years in the making, this 150-year-old food culture
continues to evolve even as it flourishes. Think of foragers
gathering wild blackberries and chanterelles, fishermen catching
black cod and halibut, Asian immigrants disseminating their own
techniques and ingredients, and farmers planting exotic produce
beside their native stands. Think of hippies who stashed homemade
beer under their beds in the 1960s, then built the microbreweries
and vineyards of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise, then, that along with the Space Needle, the
harbor and the aquarium, one of the town's top tourist magnets is
its open-air produce stall. Founded on Puget Sound in 1907, Pike
Place Market is one of the world's great markets _ a sensual
overload that crushes with the perfume of flowers and food. You
know the 16th-century Italian artist Arcimboldo, the one who
painted images of the human face made up of various fruits,
vegetables, flowers or fish? One can only imagine what he could do
with this cornucopia of lobster mushrooms, Dungeness crabs and dewy
raspberries.
</P>
<P>
   In this nine-acre historic district with some 300 commercial
tenants, there are hole-in-the-wall oyster bars, a pirogi stand, a
Latin grocery, a Turkish fast-food joint, the original Starbucks,
an Italian food shop that stocks 100 brands of olive oil, and a
gardening center with seeds for things you've never heard of: 12
different basils, 68 kinds of tomatoes, even Baby Boo Mini
Pumpkins. Louis DeLaurenti, proprietor of the Italian place, slices
into a wedge of pecorino cheese and reminisces about the days when
he used to stack salt cod on the counter _ naked. These days, you
get your fish packed on dry ice to take home or you can nibble
smoked salmon straight off the counter.
</P>
<P>
   Or you go out.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco's got better restaurants, but we don't worry
about it,'' says seafood expert Jon Rowley, who taught local
fishermen the quality-control measures that have put the region's
oysters and salmon on the global map.
</P>
<P>
   Why worry, indeed, when you can order corned-beef hash and a
poached egg for breakfast, fried razor clams and wild blackberry
cobbler for lunch, then slurp oysters and wine all night long.
That's the real-people food.
</P>
<P>
   If there's a trend, it's pan-Asian. Blowfish, Wild Ginger,
Etta's Seafood, Flying Fish: These are the restaurants where some
of the city's top talents are fusing Asian and indigenous flavors.
This means peanut noodles twirled with pea vines and
ginger-barbecued pork, Alaskan spot prawns fired with chile
peppers, skewers of scallop satay.
</P>
<P>
   But to see what the locals are eating, you must get out and
wander _ to the organic markets, ethnic groceries and neighborhood
P-Patch where residents grow their own stuff.
</P>
<P>
   At the Japanese grocery Uwajimaya, there are tanks of oysters,
abalone and long-schnozzled geoduck clams. Also rice cookers, sushi
trays, an entire sake department and the tiniest six-packs of beer
you've ever seen: 4 1/2-ounce Sapporos.
</P>
<P>
   Just north of downtown, you'll find the University District
Farmers Market, a showcase for the organic bounty of the land. On
Saturdays from May through October, you see home cooks and chefs
loading their bicycles and knapsacks with currant tomatoes,
butterscotch melons and purslane.
</P>
<P>
   Potatoes? Bet you can't eat just one. One vendor has 10 kinds,
including Ruby Crescents, Russian Banana fingerlings, German
Butterballs and blues. At the sprout stand, there are radish
sprouts, mustard sprouts, corn sprouts, cilantro sprouts, arugula
sprouts _ 10 varieties in all. This is the place to fill a vase
with tufted ``Teddy Bear'' sunflowers and giant dahlias, dip into a
pot of buckwheat honey or muse over the umpteen greens sold by the
region's Southeast Asian farmers, from bok choy to pok choy to baby
bok choy.
</P>
<P>
   If these earthly delights inspire you to get a little closer to
nature, pick a P-Patch garden and wander through it. This
25-year-old model of urban neighborhood gardening includes 38
public sites around the city. The Belltown patch, just north of
Pike Place Market, is all done up with tile mosaics, wrought iron
sculpture, sunflowers and garlic blossoms. In a sculpted metal
chalice over the entrance, somebody has added a bunch of plastic
grapes. Somewhere, Bacchus is smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Down at the Interbay P-Patch, Starbucks executive Ray Schutte is
putting in his winter crop of greens, and Rowley, the seafood
expert, is turning piles of compost. So what's with this town?
``Until you have gone through 40 days of gray, you don't understand
sunshine,'' Schutte says.
</P>
<P>
   Get Rowley going and he'll wax elemental about the Pacific
Northwest cuisine, how it all comes from earth, compost, salt, sea.
``Copper River king salmon with fresh morel mushrooms _ life
doesn't get any better than that,'' says this man with cheeks like
dappled peaches. ``Unless you have room for strawberry shortcake
made with old-fashioned drop biscuits and red, sweet, juicy
June-bearing strawberries picked that morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
