<HEADER>
A9222 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-OPENHAND-COX     10-09 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-OPENHAND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Project Open Hand provides meals to AIDS patients _ men, women,
children
 &HT;    By Derrick Henry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_If it weren't for Project Open Hand, Ed Cross wouldn't
be living in Atlanta. He might not be living at all.
</P>
<P>
   Cross, 32, diagnosed as HIV-positive more than a decade ago,
moved to the metro area in 1994 after hearing about the innovative
food delivery program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went on disability, and I had no money left for food,'' says
Cross, who now lives in Chamblee with his partner, Paul N. Walker.
``In Florida, we had a food pantry, but not meals already prepared.
Here, we just have to warm up the food.''
</P>
<P>
   Since its founding _ it celebrated its 10th anniversary last
month _ Project Open Hand has served 6,000 men, women and children
more than 2.75 million free meals. The organization now has a $1.8
million operating budget, 20 staff members and more than 1,000
active volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Such was not always the case. In the late '80s, founder Michael
Edwards-Pruitt, 49, was delivering meals for AID Atlanta. The
organization managed to feed 14 people one meal five days a week.
The food was gathered from shelters and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't enough,'' Edwards-Pruitt says. ``I saw people in
desperate condition, people alone, dying of malnutrition. So I
decided to start a program to deliver two meals a day, seven days a
week, and cook the meals myself.''
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, Project Open Hand was totally volunteer-run.
Stephen Woods, 42, was an early volunteer. ``I did everything here
at first _ shop, cook, pack, deliver,'' he says. ``I'd be at Cub
Foods at 6 a.m. and volunteers would be waiting for me when I got
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who himself has been living with HIV for a decade, made
himself so indispensable that when Open Hand received its first
grant in 1989, he was hired as the first paid staff member. He took
over as executive director in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, Project Open Hand has never missed a delivery in its
10-year history, although the aftermath of Hurricane Opal in 1995
proved a challenge _ meals were cooked on a single gas burner and
packaged by flashlight.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Woods oversaw the organization's most far-reaching
change, a shift from ready-to-eat hot food to a cold-food delivery
system. Freshly prepared meals are quickly chilled to below 40
degrees to prevent bacteria growth, then packaged into microwavable
containers for next-day delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 160 degrees, food continues to cook for six hours, so by
the time the client got it, the food had less nutritional value,''
Woods says. ``Delivering the meals cold not only preserves
nutrition, but it gives clients a choice when to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, volunteer nutritionists from Georgia State University and
Grady Memorial Hospital analyze the menus, planned on a 28-day
rotation to ensure variety and palatability.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter how nutritious the meal is if the client
doesn't eat it,'' says Development Director John Fritchie.
Everything is prepared from scratch. Favorite dishes include baked
ham with orange sauce and roasted sweet potatoes with lime and
coconut.
</P>
<P>
   To deliver two meals a day dependably (Saturday's delivery
includes Sunday's meals), Project Open Hand has become a model of
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, volunteers can be found preparing, packaging
and sorting meals at the organization's headquarters in Midtown. As
the lunch hour approaches, drivers arrive to pick up the meals and
begin their routes, mapped out so carefully that Fritchie says a
volunteer ``could fly into Atlanta without knowing the city'' and
not get lost.
</P>
<P>
   For many of the volunteers, who come from across metro Atlanta
and as far away as Rome and Athens, working at Project Open Hand
has become a highlight of their week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It starts the weekend off right,'' says Michelle Yablin, 38,
of Roswell, who's been packing food at the facility for nearly five
years. ``I started coming because I had a lot of AIDS deaths among
my friends,'' she says. ``Working here truly makes me feel good,
and everyone here is warm and welcoming.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Wasil, 40, has been driving in from Lithonia weekly for
more than a year, partly because she enjoys the camaraderie of the
food assembly line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to seeing the regulars every Saturday,'' she
says. ``I know I'm doing something good.''
</P>
<P>
   Project Open Hand primarily serves people inside the Perimeter,
unable for logistical reasons to reach outside I-285.
</P>
<P>
   But the need is great and Woods is hopeful his organization can
work with other groups outside its target zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to partner with local schools and religious
institutions to establish satellite drop-off sites where they would
deliver to clients,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   One satellite distribution route has already been started in
Gwinnett County, run by AID Gwinnett, and another in Cobb County at
St. Ann Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   The need for expansion is urgent, says Woods. ``There is much
more AIDS in outlying communities now.''
</P>
<P>
   Information: 404-872-8089.
</P>
<P>
   To volunteer: 404-872-2707.
</P>
<P>
   Web: http://www.projectopenhand.org
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
