<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Saturday, Oct. 10 and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   ON-ASSIGNMENT-SHARES (Los Angeles) _ Shares of On Assignment
Inc. have dropped 33 percent in the last 10 trading days, a
precipitous drop even in the recent bear market. Analysts speculate
On Assignment is being hurt because investors think the job
placement company won't be able to do place many applicants in this
uncertain work environment. By Ben Sullivan. (Will move in the
``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SIMBA-RELEASE (Los Angeles) _ Walt Disney Co., in an effort to
squeeze more dollars out of one of its key characters, will release
its direct-to-video ``Lion King'' sequel into European and Latin
American theaters next spring. By Dave McNary. (Will move in the
``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TOXIC-SCHOOL (Los Angeles) _ LAUSD officials said Friday that
the soil and air at Jefferson New Middle School is safe _ it's the
parents and activists that present a health risk. As district
officials held a meeting Friday morning to declare the school built
on a former toxic site is safe for the students attending classes
there, parents were turned away from the meeting by uniformed and
plain-clothes officers. By Peter Hartlaub. (Will move in the ``n''
California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LA-CITYHALL-DEFENSE (Los Angeles) _ Three years after Los
Angeles officials spent $10,000 to buy metal detectors for City
Hall, the devices remain in storage, never having been put into
use. The inaction outrages some City Council members who say
they're concerned about safety in government offices, just a few
days after a gunman opened fire on members of the Riverside City
Council. By Patrick McGreevy. (Will move in the ``n'' California
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
