<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9246 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-APATHY-BOS &LR;      10-09 1348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-APATHY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS NUMBED BY CLINTON CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Three weeks after Seattle radio station KJR-FM
declared itself Clinton free, the ``swear jar'' that benefits a
children's charity has maybe $200 in it.
</P>
<P>
   At $10 a pop, that means callers have mentioned the president's
name on air no more than 20 times in as many days. The station's
disc jockeys and newscasters haven't had to pay up once.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not indifference that has engulfed KJR's employees and
audience, said program director Gary Bryan. It's exhaustion. Like
much of America, he said, they simply can't stand to hear any more
partisan haggling over whether to impeach President Clinton.
They're both bored and embarrassed by the process, rather than
riveted by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's becoming like the O.J. Simpson case: What more is there
to say?'' said Bryan, whose station's '70s music format attracts
largely female listeners ages 30 to 50, a key constituency of
Clinton's. ``We're just picking this thing over in minute detail
and watching it devolve into a political food fight...It's just not
entertainment anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with dozens of people from around the country found
many no longer amused by the daily doings in Washington D.C., or
even interested in them. The sex scandal is no must-see soap opera,
several noted, since there are villains but no heroes, developments
but no real drama, a congressional investigation but no
cliffhanger. Few, after all, said they expect Congress to impeach
the president for lying during a deposition in a civil case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel apathetic, I feel disgusted,'' said Noreen
McCracken, a Venice, Calif., hairdresser. ``I try to keep up with
it to a point, but then I get so angry I don't pay as much
attention as maybe I should...There's no chance he'll be impeached
anyway, but, hey, the Republicans have a majority so we'll have to
wait until the elections to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Neal, an executive secretary in Atlanta, is happy there is
a GOP majority, and would like to see Clinton impeached, too.
Still, she conceded she hasn't been watching Washington with glee
-- or even at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was a Republican president, I'd probably pay more
attention,'' she said. ``I'd feel like I had a more vested
interest. But I didn't vote for the guy and I say let's get rid of
him.''
</P>
<P>
   This blend of anger and inattention is driven, for some, by a
sense that the major steps in the scandal have been hugely
overhyped. To Chris Kelly, head writer for the TV show
``Politically Incorrect,'' each of this month's climactic events _
from the release of the Starr report to Thursday's vote to begin
impeachment proceedings _ comes to seem like another installment in
the ``Friday the 13th'' horror movie series, where the killer
appears to die only to return again and again.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always say, ``This time, Jason's really going to get
his,' `` said Kelly, whose Los Angeles-based show has been making
an effort to open on other topics but inevitably wends its way to
Clinton. ``After awhile, it gets hard to get people in the
theaters...A great story needs change, and with this one the
suspense level is very low.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, suspenseful or not, the seriousness of the charges
against Clinton -- and the fact that he is the third president in
US history to face impeachment proceedings -- demands America's
attention, several of those interviewed said. New York photographer
Gwendolen Cates said she watches and listens and reads about each
development because she should, although she'd rather not. She also
said that she finds the entire process demeaning and demoralizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sort of feel like it's my responsibility to know what's
going on, but it's also discouraging. . .,'' said Cates, a
self-described liberal Democrat who does not want to see Clinton
punished further. ``Congress supposedly represents the people, but
it seems like they have absolutely no concern for what the people
want, if you look at the polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, poll after poll has shown that support for Clinton
remains high while his impeachment is a low priority for most
voters. Pollsters and voters alike say those numbers reflect the
economy's continuing strength despite turmoil in the financial
markets and, particularly among women, a belief that White House
policies have benefitted them.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, their lack of vocal outrage over Thursday's
congressional vote to hold impeachment hearings may have indirectly
empowered Congress to ignore the will of the people, many voters
conceded. Several added that they believe the latest vote, largely
along partisan lines, was based purely on politics. After the
November elections, they expect the issue to be dropped quietly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised it got this far. I thought Congress would have
gotten the message by now...,'' said Dan Dimendberg, co-president
of the Ridgefield High School Young Democrats in Ridgefield, Conn.
``There's no real chance he'll be impeached, though that doesn't
make it less interesting to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Cindy Wunsch, who manages country music singers in
Nashville, ``I was paying attention at the height of it, but I'm
completely apathetic now. It's almost pointless to talk about it
anymore. It seems absurd. He's not going to get impeached, so why
bother?''
</P>
<P>
   Wunsch compared the current situation to the season of
``Dallas'' that ended with Bobby Ewing waking up and declaring it
all a dream. As she noted with a laugh, ``That took up a whole lot
of time and energy for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Another turnoff has been what many voters consider manufactured
outrage among congressmen. As Larry Doyle, who writes for ``The
Simpsons'' TV show noted, Democrats would be calling for
impeachment if the president was a Republican while Republicans
would be demanding an end to the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``People look at it and say no one has any moral authority,''
Doyle said. ``Their opinions are meaningless, and I'd bet a lot of
people feel the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Coral Quiet, who practices medicine in Phoenix, went so far
as to say she actively tries to ignore updates from Washington
because she considers Clinton's personal life irrelevant to his
professional one. She also said the current situation bears no
resemblance to Watergate, when solemnity surrounded Richard Nixon's
impeachment hearings and Congress rose to the occasion with an
almost unprecedented level of bi-partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a reflection of our current political environment that
they'll only be going ahead with (the hearings) after the next
round of elections,'' said Quiet. ``I think it's cowardly and it
assumes the American people are a bunch of morons.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Buchanan, a contract administrator for a San Francisco
area construction company, said the point is that Clinton lied to
the court in a civil case and then again to the American people. He
also said that he expects more citizens to keep closer tabs on the
case -- and clamor for impeachment -- if the US stock market
continues its downward slide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that I think it's a business decision, but I do
believe that a lot of people are just inherently selfish and they
have been willing to overlook a whole lot of things in a good
economy,'' said Buchanan, who chose not to vote for any
presidential candidate in the last national election. ``When they
get disappointed, they'll get pissed and there just happens to be a
fairly easy vehicle right before their eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Allan Landau, a Chicago-based photographer who doesn't
follow politics regularly, said he will take notice once the actual
hearings are under way. For now, however, he said the case is not
holding his attention because it lacks tension.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the impeachment part will get people's attention again,''
said Landau, a native of Canada who has lived in the United States
since 1977. ``No one thinks he will be impeached. But no one really
thought we'd be where we are now two weeks ago. So they'll probably
watch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
