<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLDOUT   WOES TRIM BRUINS' SEASON HOPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Step 2 in the Bruins' long crawl back to respectability
begins Saturday night with the start of their 1998-99 season. After
going bust the year before, when it finished dead last in the
Original 26, the once-proud franchise found its way back to the
dinner table last year, qualifying for the playoffs and even
winning two postseason games against the Capitals.
</P>
<P>
   What's in store for '98-99?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we'll be a great team,'' said resident realist
Pat Burns, ready to take his charges into his second season as the
Makeover King on Causeway Street. ``We'll be a good team. You'll
have to work hard to beat the Bruins.''
</P>
<P>
   The reality is that the Bruins will start the season, and
perhaps go well into the 82-game schedule, minus holdouts Kyle
McLaren and Anson Carter. Part of the reason this is not a great
team is that the Bruins, like many NHL clubs, have been hit with
their share of the payroll blues. The defense will have to go
forward without McLaren, one of its key components the past three
years. The front line will have to move ahead without Carter, whom
the Bruins acquired in hopes that he would develop into an impact
player. His impact right now is the void he leaves at left wing.
</P>
<P>
   The new edition of the Bruins that will be unveiled this evening
against the St. Louis Blues will be much like last season's club.
</P>
<P>
   To wit:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; They'll be honest at both ends of the ice and prone to
clogging up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Ray Bourque, their old man in the ``C,'' will be back on the
blue line, beginning his 20th season as the anchor of the defense.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Jason Allison and Sergei Samsonov, the 1997-98 rookie of the
year, will team up on their top line, most likely starting with
newcomer Antti Laaksonen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Bryon Dafoe will be the No. 1 netminder, looking to build on
his impressive 30-25-9 season and erase the memory of the long
Brian Bellows softy that beat him to end the playoff run.
</P>
<P>
   When Bruins fans first come to Causeway Street, the most
noticeable difference will be the absence of the old Garden. The
proud old barn was in its initial stages of demolition when the
Bruins' '97-98 season ended. It since has been swept away, every
last seat, girder, and gummy linoleum tile, and the sterile,
behemoth FleetCenter finally has been revealed for all the sporting
world to see. A large field of asphalt, what amounts to a parking
lot, sits hauntingly vacant where the Garden once stood.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Vault, Bruins fans will see a few wrinkles here at
the dawn of a new season.
</P>
<P>
   To wit:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; There has been a European enhancement of the Boston lineup.
Laaksonen, via the University of Denver, hails from Tammela,
Finland. Another new forward, Peter Nordstrom, was born in
Munkfors, Sweden, and played the last three seasons in his
country's Elite League. They join Samsonov, Dmitri Khristich, and
P.J. Axelsson in the club's United Nations division. The Bruins
arrived late in the race to acquire international talent. By the
time they jumped into the Russian market, making the long-forgotten
Dmitri Kvartalnov their top pick in the '92 draft, the best of
Mother Russia's skating sons already had been acquired by other NHL
clubs (Example: Sergei Fedorov got grabbed at No. 74 by Detroit in
'89 and was in the October 1990 Red Wings lineup).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Don Cherry is in the house. The flamboyant and at times
bombastic former Bruins coach will participate in pregame
festivities, handing Burns the Jack Adams (coach of the year)
Award. Grapes and Boston boss Harry Sinden parted as, shall we say,
less than amiable partners in the spring of '79. Much has happened
in the years since. The Berlin Wall is gone. The WHA is gone.
Cherry even once has complimented a European player during his
wildly successful Canadian TV gigs (the ``I Love All Things
Canadian And Nothing Esle Hour''). Grapes is older now. Look for
the white-haired guy dressed in a shirt that has a starched 8-inch
collar with a giant red maple leaf on his back.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Bobby Orr is in the house. The great No. 4, joined by former
teammate/broadcaster Derek Sanderson and Bourque, will present
Samsonov with the Calder (rookie of the year) Trophy in the pregame
show. Four Calders in the same cauldron _ Orr in '67, Sanderson in
'68, Bourque in '80, Samsonov in '98. The joint still jumps when
Orr comes walking down the runway. Samsonov was born in October
1978, when Orr was about to begin his fourth year of retirement. If
that makes you feel old, bunky, cheer up, because sideburns are
back and you'll be able to pull on those psychedelic bellbottoms
again any day now.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Speaking of follicle fashion, Burns has a far more
conservative haircut this year. The long locks are gone. He looks
even more like the cop walking the beat now. If he trims an equal
amount every year, he'll look like Kojak by the time he enters year
No. 4 of his deal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; The ice surface holds a couple of significant changes.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1: The ``wings'' have been clipped off the blue-tinged
crease area in front of the net, allowing attacking players to move
closer to the cage. Had the wings been clipped last year, Tim
Taylor's controversial goal against Washington would not have been
wiped from the scoreboard. Who knows what would have happened after
that? And if there hadn't been too many men on the ice in Montreal
...
</P>
<P>
   No. 2: The net has been moved an extra couple of feet away from
the end boards. The Lords of the Boards did this in hopes of
opening up the game, allowing more playmaking. If Cam Neely were
still playing (and who says he won't someday?), this change would
allow Claude Lemieux less of a chance to play hide 'n' turtle. That
alone might take Neely's rehab up a notch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; And for the first time in nine-plus seasons, the Blues will
come to town without Brett Hull. The Golden Brett ran off to Dallas
in the offseason, signing on with the Stars for a three-year deal
worth some $17 million. In his best days, Hull was the league's No.
1 sniper. In his worst days, he was still a frightening factor in
the St. Louis offense, even with that ``One Way'' sign stapled to
his helmet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
