<HEADLINE>
THREE YET TO RETURN FROM TRIP TO FLORIDA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM F. DOHERTY PATRICK FLAHERTY   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTLEBORO, Mass. _ As family members set up a web page and
posted a reward for three missing Attleboro men, police in Orlando,
Fla, where they were last seen nearly two weeks ago were turning up
scant clues in the mysterious disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're waiting and watching,'' said Catherine Ryder, sister of
Scott Renquin, one of the missing men, who had gone to Renquin's
time-share condominium in Orlando for vacation and disappeared in
that city Sept. 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a licensed pilot and a certified SCUBA diver so we never
worried about him going off on side trips,'' said Ryder. ``This is
highly unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Orlando Police have reached what is very nearly a
dead end in their search for 35-year-old Renquin and his friends
Daniel Nelson, 32, and Roger DesVergnes, 31.
</P>
<P>
   Det. Barbara Bergin, lead investigator for the Orlando Police
Department, said police aren't ruling out anything, but there is no
evidence of foul play.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no evidence of anything whatsoever, except that they
didn't go home,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes people orchestrate their own disappearances, but we
don't think that's the case,'' said Bergin. ``These men had
families and responsibilities to return to and we have no reason to
think that wasn't what they wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryder said the web page was set up by her husband and a friend.
The DesVergnes family has posted a reward of up to $5,000 in the
case, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The men were expected home Oct. 2 and when relatives contacted
police, investigators went to the time share condo and found a
refrigerator stocked with food and beverages worth about $200 and
$500 in cash in a floor safe. Toothbrushes and razors, were all in
place.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that is still unaccounted for, however, is their
rented GMC Jimmy with four-wheel drive.
</P>
<P>
   Bergin said that the three men came to Orlando to hang out, play
some pool and relax. They wanted to get outdoors, Bergin said. They
told Renquin's childhood friend, Kevin Kennedy, who lived in nearby
Longwood, that they might do some fishing and barbecuing.
</P>
<P>
   That was Sept. 28. Kennedy made plans to meet them at a downtown
nightclub complex two days later, but they didn't show. Staff at
Orlando's Sunshine Resort, where Renquin shared ownership of unit
105, saw them the afternoon of Sept. 28, but not after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thinking they may have gone four-wheeling in the truck
they rented and somehow driven into a swamp or a lake,''
DesVergnes' cousin David DesVergnes said Friday. ``We got a call
from a woman today who said she remembered a similar missing person
case where a person accidentally drove into a hidden lake and the
body wasn't found until the lake was dredged.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the men were reported missing, police have searched the
woody, rural areas around Orlando but have turned up nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities also have kept the names and photographs of the
three men on television and in the local paper for more than 48
hours. If any of the men had used a driver's license or credit card
to rent a boat, airplane or dirt bike, police would know it by now,
Bergin said.
</P>
<P>
   DesVergnes, who works at DesVergnes Construction Company in
Attleboro, has three children. Renquin has owned Renquin Unlimited
Auto Body Shop in Attleboro for the past five years. Nelson is the
father of a 5-year-old boy who he left with relatives while he went
on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a home on Lindsey Street, David DesVergnes said his
cousin, Roger, loves the outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several family members live on this street.'' DesVergnes said.
``We have a lot of land here and he would take his hovercraft-type
vehicle out on the pond in the backyard. He loved outdoor sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Ryder, who is from Windham, Maine but is staying with
her parents in Attleboro during the search, said her brother is
``rough on the outside but he has the biggest heart of anyone. He
would give you the shirt off his back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One good thing to come out of this is the stream of people who
have called to to say how he touched their lives,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Correspondent Brad Liston contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
