<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP BEGINS PLANNING IMPEACHMENT STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One day after an historic vote to launch an
impeachment inquiry of President Clinton, some GOP members were
suggesting that the hearings would focus mostly on whether Clinton
was engaged in a coverup, rather than his sexual relationship with
Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans on the House Judiciary Committee met privately
Friday to begin developing their strategy for hearings to be held
after the Nov. 3 elections. While no decisions were made Friday
about how to proceed, there were signals that the
Republican-controlled committee is trying to avoid details on the
physical nature of the Clinton-Lewinsky relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is absolutely a no-brainer that they will focus on
obstruction of justice as opposed to a lying about sex,'' said
Representative Christopher Shays, a Connecticut Republican. Shays
said the committee might try to broaden its scope by examining
whether Clinton tried to obstruct justice on an array of issues,
including campaign finance and the use of FBI files.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is clearly where they are going,'' former federal
prosecutor Joseph diGenova said about focusing on the alleged
coverup. ``It makes a lot of sense. The coverup stuff is easier to
understand, and it gets away from the unseemly and distasteful
aspects of the story.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of that strategy, Republicans would like Clinton to
``stipulate'' that he does not dispute some key facts in the case.
This would allow the committee to narrow its focus considerably,
looking only at areas in which Clinton disputes the report by
independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear, however, whether Clinton wants to stipulate to
any facts in the case. While Clinton has admitted having a
relationship with Lewinsky that was ``not appropriate,'' he denies
committing perjury when he claimed he had no sexual relations with
her. There has been speculation that Republicans want the president
to agree that he had a sexual relationship with Lewinsky, which
would enable the GOP to avoid interrogating Lewinsky about the kind
of sex she had with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans cringe at the thought that they would have to
ask Lewinsky about such matters in a nationally televised hearing.
Indeed, Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry J. Hyde, an Illinois
Republican, has played down the possibility of subpoenaing Lewinsky
and said Friday he won't ask Clinton to testify. The president
hasn't ruled out voluntarily testifying.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, some GOP members prefer that the impeachment proceeding
focus on whether Clinton and Lewinsky conspired to cover up their
relationship. The clearest sign of this strategy came, according to
diGenova, when the committee's Republican counsel, David P.
Schippers, announced his list of 15 possible impeachable offenses
and added the allegation that Clinton and Lewinsky conspired in
what amounts to a coverup.
</P>
<P>
   Focusing on an alleged coverup also would help Republicans draw
parallels with the Watergate case in 1974, in which former
President Nixon was forced from office largely because of a
coverup.
</P>
<P>
   There are also questions about whether Republicans will find it
worthwhile to pursue allegations that Clinton committed perjury.
Democrats in the last several days have said that any attempt to
impeach Clinton for perjury would prompt them to focus on the fact
that House Speaker Newt Gingrich was allowed to remain in office
after he was reprimanded for &UR;  &LR; making false statements to the House
ethics committee.
</P>
<P>
   In the Gingrich case, the ethics committee found that the
speaker misused a tax-exempt organization for political purposes,
namely to build a Republican majority in Congress. The committee
also found that Gingrich made false statements about the tax-exempt
work to the committee. Gingrich wound up being reprimanded by a
395-28 vote in the House and required to pay a $300,000 fine, but
he was allowed to remain in office.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Barney Frank, the Massachusetts Democrat and the
only other sitting House member to be reprimanded for false
statements, said in an interview Friday it would make no sense to
impeach Clinton for lying, because he and Gingrich were accused of
a similar violation and allowed to remain as House members. Frank
was reprimanded in 1990 for writing a misleading memo in an attempt
to end a male prostitute's probation and using his House privileges
to waive parking tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Frank, a member of the House Judiciary Committee, said the
comparison between the Gingrich and Clinton cases was valid.
``Although Gingrich wasn't under oath, it was still a lie to a an
official body,'' Frank said, referring to the ethics committee.
``It is a crime of making false statement to government
officials.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans prefer to point to parallels in another case,
the ouster of Senator Bob Packwood, an Oregon Republican. The
Senate ethics committee voted unanimously to expel Packwood on
Sept. 7, 1995, prompting him to resign the following day before the
full Senate took a vote. The committee charged Packwood with sexual
misconduct, misuse of office and obstructing the committee's
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The committee sent its recommendation of expulsion to the Senate
after determining that Packwood in his own version of a coverup,
altered diaries that contained information about his relationships
with various women.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Bob Smith, a New Hampshire Republican who served on the
ethics committee, said his vote to expel a fellow GOP senator shows
that House and Senate members take such responsibilities seriously
and won't make a partisan vote on Clinton. As for the parallel
between the Packwood and Clinton cases, Smith said, ``Yes,
(Packwood) did make an attempt to keep certain diary entries from
us that would have been incriminating to him. So in terms of
obstruction, there is a parallel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
