<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9279 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV11-B     10-09 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV11-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON OVERSHOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, October 11, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was one of the shabbiest and most alarming episodes of the
decade: a president hounded from office by the congressional
majority, abetted by an angry press.
</P>
<P>
   David Baltimore's forced resignation as president of Rockefeller
University in 1991 is worth considering, and not just because there
has appeared an exquisitely well-informed and fair-minded account
of the path that led to it. The story casts some light as well on
events that led to the impeachment inquiry for President Clinton.
It even offers a glimpse of where we might go from here.
</P>
<P>
   We owe a good deal to Daniel Kevles. He is one of the nation's
most distinguished historians of scientific politics, a professor
of the humanities at the California Institute of Technology, the
author of a memorable portrait of the scientific community that is
modern physics, and of another study of the early 20th century
quackery that was the eugenics momenent.
</P>
<P>
   He also is a man of no discernible politics aside from good
science. ``The Balitimore Case: A Trial of Politics, Science and
Character'' is not an easy read, for it goes to great lengths to
lay out the biochemistry underlying the experiment at the heart of
the affair. Nor have I read and understood every word of its 509
pages. But Kevles' conclusions carry great weight.
</P>
<P>
   Let me remind you of the broad outlines of the story.
</P>
<P>
   It began with a beguiling young whistleblower named Margot
O'Toole. She had been hired as a post-doc by a cellular
immunologist named Thereza Imanishi-Kari in 1985, and introduced
into a lab at the Cancer Center of the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, where the usual fear and loathing among anxious
graduate students prevailed _ perhaps slightly more than the usual.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to duplicate the results of an experiment that required a
series of demanding techniques, the younger woman became convinced
that Imanishi-Kari had fabricated some data. Writes Kevles,
``O'Toole's dogged insistence that she was right and her supervisor
was wrong lay at the heart of the affair.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Toole complained. Nobel laureate David Baltimore defended
Imanishi-Kari (he was her co-author on the paper in question), and
in due course, O'Toole's complaint boiled over and out of the
university. When it fell into the hands of a pair of self-styled
``science cops'' at the National Institutes of Health, it began to
attract a national audience. Walter Stewart and Ned Feder,
freelance students of scientific misbehavior, were tipped to the
issue by another disaffected student.
</P>
<P>
   That Baltimore, director of MIT's Whitehead Institute, was one
of the most senior &UR;  &LR; figures in all of biology added charm. Stewart
and Feder in turn succeeded in interesting a pair of staffers who
worked for US Representative John Dingell, powerful chairman of the
House Energy and Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Dingell was no stranger to science _ he had been a chemistry
major as an undergraduate at Georgetown University, a scientist
brother was working at the NIH. But he nevertheless had declared a
kind of war on the universities in the late 1980s. Staff leaks and
one-sided hearings his principle weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Thus it was that Dingell hauled Baltimore before his committee
and provoked a memorable confrontation in the spring of 1988. A
year later, Baltimore was tapped to become president of Rockefeller
University in New York City _ once the nation's premier center of
molecular biology, but in need of a turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, egging on federal investigators and the news
reporters covering their proceedings, were perhaps the most
important actors in the drama: a handful of rival Harvard
professors, who professed to be shocked by their MIT colleagues'
science.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation escalated. Imanishi-Kari's notebooks were sent
to the Secret Service and pronounced to have been doctored.
Preliminary reports were leaked. Criminal referrals were made.
James Watson, discoverer of the structure of DNA (and former
Harvard professor), urged that Baltimore be stripped of his Nobel
Prize. Those resisting reorganization at Rockefeller University dug
in their heels against his attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, The New York Times pursued the story with
prosecutorial zeal. And when Baltimore finally stepped down in 1991
_ ``Nobelist Caught Up in Fraud Case Resigns as Head of Rockefeller
U.'' _ a reporter described the ``spectacle'' of his downfall as
seeming ``larger than life, with an effect greater than any case of
scientific fraud in memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevles' findings? That Imanishi-Kari was innocent. That her
Harvard foes didn't make a good-faith attempt to replicate the
crucial experiment, though all the necessary help repeatedly had
been offered. That the Secret Service investigation of the lab
notebooks had been thoroughly discredited. That without Baltimore's
defense, Imanishi-Kari, a Brazilian-Japanese better at tracking
antibodies than at defending herself in English, likely would have
been railroaded out of science. That the press by and large didn't
care.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great injustice was perpretrated in the name of scientific
integrity and the public trust ... '' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing Kevles' book, Roy Porter, an English historian of
medicine, wrote, ``Where else (but America) would this storm in a
teacup _ after all, it wasn't such an important paper in the first
place _ get blown up into a megascandal, involving the expenditure
of goodness knows how many manhours and dollars and the venting of
such acrimony?''
</P>
<P>
   Where indeed?
</P>
<P>
   Here's the point of the story. Imanishi-Kari got tenure at
Tufts. David Baltimore got a good job as president of the
California Institute of Technology. (Kevles had been teaching there
for 30 years.) Scientists still get to take their notebooks home at
night. And John Dingell got dumped; his overreaching contributed to
the Republican landslide of 1994. Though he remains in office, the
Republican majority that swept to office stripped him of his
power &UR;  &LR; _ its leaders even tried to compel his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   No excess John Dingell ever committed, however, compares to the
arrogance and roughshod bullying of the current GOP congressional
leadership. Forty years out of power and the first thing they do is
shut down the government. Next they attempt to impeach the
president, after he balances the budget. (Can you remember the
other nine items of the famous ``Contract With America.'') It is
absurd.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; What will happen to Bill Clinton and the presidency? Great
injustices will be done. But before long, the Republicans will lose
their power. Just like currency traders, the political leadership
has overshot.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)nws.globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
