<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The kick: When it leaves the foot, it leaves the mind
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Falcons kicker Morten Andersen has set seven NFL
records, but there's one he wants more than any other _ George
Blanda's career scoring mark of 2,002 points.
</P>
<P>
   In his 17th season, the native of Denmark has 1,668 points,
fifth in history, and Sunday night he'll get a chance to close the
gap when the Falcons play the Giants in East Rutherford, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Giants Stadium can be tough on a kicker,with tricky winds common
this time of season. Andersen, 38, spoke with the
Journal-Constitution about the job of kicking.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you change your approach kicking outdoors, especially in a
place like Giants Stadium?
</P>
<P>
   A: You try not to let the wind or any element control your
thought process, but if there's a crosswind, you've got to give it
credence. You never give up the goal post or completely (aim) a
ball outside, but you change (the aim) just a little bit.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You're second in NFL history with 383 career field goals, 13
behind Minnesota kicker Gary Anderson, who also is second in NFL
history with 1,731 points. Do you keep tabs on him?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't look at the stats much. I used to all the time. I
know my points (27 this season) ... but I don't know where
everybody else is. I know he has more than me and more
opportunities (Anderson is leading the league with 52 points,
including 11-of-11 field goals; Andersen has hit 5-of-5 this year).
But that's one of those things I can't control.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's your biggest goal?
</P>
<P>
   A: I've said for the last year and a half that I want to break
Blanda's record. It's certainly not unrealistic that Gary would do
it, too.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When you miss a kick, or go in a slump, do you focus on
correcting the mistakes you made? Or do you shut them out of your
mind and just concentrate on the positive?
</P>
<P>
   A: I look at every kick objectively every Monday, analyze it and
keep a very detailed diary of every kick in my career. I have a
seven-step checklist for every kick. I confront the mistake head-on
and try to make improvements. But I try not to dwell on it too
long, just like I try not to dwell on a good kick too long. I've
always said when it leaves the foot, it leaves the mind.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Have you ever picked up a fumble and run, thrown a pass, or a
block?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. No. No. I have made a couple tackles ... I say tackles;
I've pushed a couple people out of bounds, using the sideline to my
advantage. I can't say I've boned somebody, I haven't laid wood, I
haven't crushed somebody. I mean, look at my (scrawny shoulder)
pads.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
