<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-LEMANS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Proven Porsche captures pole at Road Atlanta
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ To the surprise of no one, the No. 26 Porsche GT1 that
won the 24 Hours of Le Mans took the No. 1 position for Friday's
Petit Le Mans at Road Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Porsche, the only GT1 in the top seven, had a top lap of
124.95 mph, turning the 2.6-mile circuit in 1:13.754.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the leaders _ including the fourth qualifier, the
Atlanta-sponsored No. 7 Lease Plan Ferrari 333SP are in the World
Sports Car or the similar Le Mans Prototype Class, which also isn't
surprising, because those cars generally are faster and easier to
handle.
</P>
<P>
   The top five includes two Porsches (one LMP) and three Ferraris,
bringing back memories to some fans of days past when the two
battled on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   The Lease Plan Ferrari, driven by Wayne Taylor, Eric van de
Poele and Emmanuel Collard ran the course in 123.65/1:14.531.
</P>
<P>
   The Petit, a 1,000-mile or 10-hour version of the famous French
endurance race, starts today at 11 a.m. and finishes at 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be like Le Mans but with a little more intensity,'' said
No. 26 co-driver Yannick Dalmas of France.
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Allan McNish of Scotland said the winner will have to
have a ``great deal of dedication, commitment and a good car,''
because the Road Atlanta circuit is so demanding technically.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the best I've ever seen,'' McNish said, but it is
demanding as many learned, especially in the ``esses'' at the top
of the hill after Turn 1. That area had a good collection of
fiberglass and headlight pieces scattered around it after
qualifying was over.
</P>
<P>
   Luck is a big factor at Road Atlanta, too, as Team Panoz
learned. The No. 5 Panoz GT1 won't be in the race because of some
bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   Driver Johnny O'Connell of Phoenix was blazing downhill into the
final turn on his first lap of qualifying, hit a patch of oil on
the track and skidded into the wall beneath the press tower. It's
doubtful that No. 5 will be in the starting grid.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no flag warning us to slow down,'' O'Connell said.
It went up shortly thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   There are still two Team Panoz cars competing. The No. 4 GT1,
driven by David Brabham, Andy Wallace and Scott Pruett qualified
10th with a best lap of 119.76 mph/1:16.951.
</P>
<P>
   No. 07 Panoz Q9 GT1, the hybrid V8/electric motor tandem, driven
by Doc Bundy, John Nielsen and Christophe qualified 12th at 117.52
mph/1:18.415.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-built No. 63 Kudzu Mazda with owner/driver Jim
Downing, Yojiro Terada and Howard Katz qualified 14th at 112.13
mph/1:22.190. The Kudzu is the only rotary engine-powered car in
the race.
</P>
<P>
   Missing from the race are teams from BMW and Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   BMW actually had a team with three cars at Road Atlanta, but
technicians weren't satisfied with the performance of the cars' new
engines.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercedes team had a conflicting schedule with FIA races at
Homestead, Fla., and Laguna Seca, Calif., in the next three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
