<P>
   TAIWAN-PUBLIC-RELATIONS (Taipei, Taiwan) _ Deep in the corridors
of Taiwan's Mainland Affairs Council, faceless bureaucrats have
been busily tabulating lists of insults and injuries, faxes and
phone calls, homicides and other hostilities _ for use in a
simmering public relations war with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   They've determined, for example, that while Taiwan approved 205
separate measures over the past decade aimed at relaxing tensions
with the mainland, the communists broke 25 promises, rejected 114
pleas for cooperation and failed to answer 14 phone calls and 11
faxes from Taipei officials. In addition, Taipei's statisticians
found that Taiwanese businessmen on the mainland were the victims
of 27 murders, five accidents, 44 assaults, 28 kidnappings and 29
disappearances. These and dozens of other seemingly arcane
statistics and analyses are part of a Taiwanese public relations
offensive in advance of a resumption of high-level contacts between
Taipei and Beijing beginning Oct. 16 in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   By Ron Redmond. (story will move in the ``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-HUSKIES (Seattle) Huskies' beleaguered defense finally gets
a chance to right itself after an opening diet of Arizona State,
BYU, Nebraska and Arizona. Utah State, Saturday's opponent, begins
the UW's softest part of the schedule.
</P>
<P>
