<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN MOUNTS PR OFFENSIVE ON EVE OF TALKS WITH BEIJING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RON REDMOND  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ Deep in the corridors of Taiwan's Mainland
Affairs Council, faceless bureaucrats have been busily tabulating
lists of insults and injuries, faxes and phone calls, homicides and
other hostilities _ for use in a simmering public relations war
with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   They've determined, for example, that while Taiwan approved 205
separate measures over the past decade aimed at relaxing tensions
with mainland China, the communists broke 25 promises, rejected 114
pleas for cooperation and failed to answer 14 phone calls and 11
faxes from Taipei officials.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Taipei's statisticians found that Taiwanese
businessmen on the mainland were the victims of 27 murders, five
accidents, 44 assaults, 28 kidnappings and 29 disappearances.
</P>
<P>
   These and dozens of other seemingly arcane statistics and
analyses are part of a Taiwanese public relations offensive in
advance of a resumption of high-level contacts between Taipei and
Beijing beginning Friday in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's top political envoy, Koo Chen-fu, chairman of the
Straits Exchange Foundation, will meet in Shanghai with his Beijing
counterpart, Wang Daohan. It will be their first meeting since
1993. The 1993 talks, held in Singapore, were the first open
contact between Taipei and Beijing since the communists won control
of the mainland in 1949 and drove the Nationalists into exile on
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Koo and Wang were preparing for a second meeting in mid-1995
when Beijing froze all talks and launched a year of war games in
the Taiwan Strait in retaliation for a high-profile visit to the
United States by Taiwan President Lee Teng-hui.
</P>
<P>
   Relations have improved in recent months, leading to the
agreement to meet next week. But the two sides have different
expectations for the meeting. Beijing is pressing Taiwan to agree
to political negotiations on reunifiction and wants an agreement to
inaugurate direct postal, shipping and air services.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan officials, however, say there will be no political
discussions and are portraying the first meeting as more form than
substance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will warm up and improve the atmosphere,'' said Chong-Pin
Lin, vice chairman of the Mainland Affairs Council in Taipei. ``The
very act of meeting will have that affect.''
</P>
<P>
   Lin dismissed Beijing's calls for political talks on
reunification, saying the two sides first had to determine how to
handle issues that had been agreed upon for discussion in the
previous talks. Those issues included fishing disputes, joint
efforts to combat crime, and the protection of Taiwanese business
people working in the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hope is that the meeting will regularize normal
communications,'' Lin told a small group of visiting American
journalists. ``We hope this will set in motion preparations for
future consultations.''
</P>
<P>
   If Beijing wants to make progress in the talks, Lin added, it
should renounce its longstanding policy of refusing to rule out
force for the recovery of Taiwan. Beijing, which considers the
island a renegade province, says it will invade if Taiwan tries to
declare independence.
</P>
<P>
   The mainland government has become increasingly alarmed over the
rising popularity of the pro-independence Democratic Progressive
Party in Taiwan. In local elections last November, the DPP for the
first time outpolled the Kuomintang Party, which had ruled the
island since Gen. Chiang Kai-shek and his forces fled there in
1949. It is also expected to mount a strong showing in legislative
elections in December.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the party's growing popularity was a major factor
in Beijing's decision to return to the talks and to mount a
full-court press against Taiwan's efforts for more international
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The DPP won 12 of 23 positions in the local elections and it
scared the life out of them in Beijing,'' said Julian Baum, Taipei
correspondent for the Far Eastern Economic Review. ``Beijing is
getting more sophisticated and now wants to win diplomatically and
politically what it failed to win by war in 1949.''
</P>
<P>
   For its part, President Lee's government says Taiwan's destiny
must be determined by its 21 million people. Polls show most are
opposed to reunification with China until the mainland becomes
democratic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great majority of our people support maintenance of the
status quo,'' said foreign ministry spokesman Roy Wu. ``Status quo
for the time being means we will decide later _ either toward
independence or toward reunification.''
</P>
<P>
   Wu dismissed Beijing's proposal for a Hong Kong-style ``one
country, two systems'' reunification policy for Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people in Taiwan will not accept one country, two
systems,'' he said. ``We prefer one country, one good system. That
means freedom, democracy and respect for human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Wu and other officials said, Taiwan will
continue its uphill struggle for international recognition and
respect.
</P>
<P>
   But it can expect strong opposition from Beijing, which views
any effort by Taiwan for international recognition as one more step
toward independence.
</P>
<P>
   During the more than three years since the last cross-strait
talks were suspended, Beijing cranked up its international campaign
to further isolate Taiwan diplomatically and to portray the island
as obstinate and uncooperative.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, at least eight countries have broken diplomatic
relations with Taiwan in favor of Beijing, Wu said. Taipei now has
official ties with only 27 nations.
</P>
<P>
   Correspondent Baum said Beijing is exerting tremendous pressure
on governments and organizations that have ties with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Top Taiwan officials can't go anywhere,'' he said. ``China is
really playing hardball and it's been very tough on Taiwan's
international status.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
