<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS, CONSUMER MEASURES GET SHORT SHRIFT IN 105TH CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite a Republican Congress and a president who
often embraces corporate America, many of business's top priorities
are headed for the graveyard as Congress winds up its work for the
year.
</P>
<P>
   The latest likely casualty: a sweeping overhaul of banking,
brokerage and and insurance laws, which would have updated
Depression-era regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Business lobbyists considered it a huge accomplishment to line
up the major players from all three industries behind the bill.
Squabbling among banks, brokerages and insurance firms had killed
similar measures about a dozen times over the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, the Senate returned the bill to committee and
declared it all but dead, due to opposition from Senator Phil
Gramm, Republican of Texas. ``It's mostly dead,'' said David Pratt
of the American Insurance Association. ``There's one `Hail Mary
pass' left that might work, one 100-yard bomb play.''
</P>
<P>
   Defeat of the financial services bill would not be the only big
loss by big business this session. The Senate Friday approved
legislation that would encourage the United States to take action
against countries that engage in religious persecution. Businesses
fear the bill would lead to economic sanctions against more
countries, which they say are ineffective and harmful to US
companies.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton seems likely to veto a bill that would make it
harder for consumers to escape their debts by filing for
bankuprtcy. Credit card companies, department stores and other
lenders had ushered the bill through both the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, lawmakers are considering a tax bill that is far
smaller and far less beneficial to business than many lobbyists had
hoped. And just three weeks ago, lawmakers denied President Clinton
so-called ``fast track'' powers to negotiate new trade treaties,
which most big businsses say are vital to opening new export
markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I have a pro-business Republican majority, I don't
have enough votes to get done what I'd like to get done,'' said
Bruce Josten, chief lobbyist for the US Chamber of Commerce, one of
the largest business lobbies. ``I need more votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups, who oppose big business on may issues, said the
105th Congress did little for them, either. ``This was not a
consumer-friendly Congress, not at all,'' said Frank Torres,
legislative counsel at Consumers Union.
</P>
<P>
   In short, both business and consumer groups said their biggest
victories in the two-year session came by playing defense, killing
off proposals that their opponents had proposed. Amid the Monica
Lewinsky scandal and talk of impeachment, both sides found it hard
to go on the offensive and push big new initiatives through
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups, for example, mourned the death of the ``Patient
Bill of Rights,'' which would have imposed broad new regulations on
health-maintenance organizations. Business lobbyist Josten,
meanwhile, said blocking the health bill was one of his top
accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   And while Josten was sorry that the bankruptcy bill faced a
likely veto, Consumers Union considered that prospect a big win for
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, business claimed its accomplishments in the 105th
Congress. An increase in the number of skilled, foreign workers
admitted to the United States each year seems likely to become law.
High-tech firms said they needed more foreigners because the tight
US job market made it hard to find skilled computer workers, but
unions and other worker groups said the measure would merely
depress US wages.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses also supported a moratorium on new taxes on goods
bought or sold over the Internet, which the Senate approved
Thursday. A similar version has passed the House, and President
Clinton has said he would sign it.
</P>
<P>
   Several major business issues are not yet resolved, though their
fate will likely be known by the end of the weekend. Congress is
scrambling to finish work on major legislation so that lawmakers
can return home for the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   In an odd twist of timing, the new hurdles to the financial
services overhaul arose only one day after the merger of Citicorp
and Travelers Group Inc. became final.
</P>
<P>
   That merger, which formed the world's largest financial services
company, created momentum for the financial services bill when it
was was announced last April. The new company, called Citigroup
Inc., brings banking, securities, insurance and other financial
services under one roof. But under current law, which dates to
1933, no single company can offer all those services.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Congress said that the merger showed that the market
has moved faster than the lawmakers. The said Congress must update
the banking laws so that US companies could form the same kind of
financial-service supermarkets that are common in Europe and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   To comply with existing law, Citigroup could divest of insurance
underwriting businesses or seek to be regulated under a different
type of bank charter. The company has five years to comply with
existing laws _ enough time, perhaps, for Conress to change the
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Morris, a Citigroup spokesman, said the company had no
comment Friday on the bill, ``certainly not about its demise,
because it is not dead.'' The financial services overhaul could be
revived if Gramm removes his opposition. Gramm has said he wants
the bill to limit the scope of the Community Reinvestment Act,
which requires banks to meet the credit needs of communities where
they do business, because he believes community groups abuse the
law.
</P>
<P>
   Also yet to be resolved is whether Congress will agree to $18
billion in funding for the International Monetary Fund, and whether
it will approve a package of tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Material from Globe wire services was used in this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
