<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-AID-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA REQUESTS FOOD AND OTHER HUMANITARIAN AID 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic depicting Russian wheat and grain harvests is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Rocked by its worst harvest in 45 years and a
plummeting ruble, Russia appealed Friday for relief aid from the
European Union. It has also approached the United States and Canada
for help.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov broached the question of relief
at a meeting Friday with Jacques Santer, the president of the
European Union. ``There has been a request for humanitarian aid,''
a spokeswoman for Santer said. ``There are no details yet.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.S. official said the Russians had begun to sound out
the United States and Canada about arranging shipments of food.
``They have told us they want to talk to us about what is
possible,'' the official said. ``They are looking at the
acquisition of grains and other commodity supplies.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Russian officials are still trying to figure out how much
help they need, there is no mystery about why the Kremlin is
asking. Russia is being pushed to the brink, anxiously facing a
harsh winter and fearful that it may lack the food, medicine and
power to get by.
</P>
<P>
   Food is a big worry, a result of bad luck, bad agriculture and a
collapsing economy. Western experts say Russia may have enough to
survive the winter but that the country's reserves will be
dangerously depleted by the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's production of grain is way down, mainly the result of
this summer's drought in the Volga River and Ural regions.
</P>
<P>
   But the downturn also reflects the nation's sorry experience
with agriculture, which has been slow to reform since the breakup
of the Soviet Union. Outdated farm equipment, the result of a lack
of investment, as well as inadequate supplies of fertilizer and
deficient storage have also contributed to the bad harvest.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's grain harvest this year will reach about 52 million
tons, down from 88 million tons last year, according to a new
projection by the U.S. Department of Agriculture. That would make
it the worst harvest since 1953.
</P>
<P>
   Cattle inventories and other livestock have also declined, a
consequence of shrinking supplies of feed grain.
</P>
<P>
   Aggravating the problem, Russia's financial crisis has led to
sharp cutbacks in food imports. Russia has imported about half of
the food it has consumed in recent years, making the recent falloff
in imports especially serious.
</P>
<P>
   For example, about 15 ships full of frozen poultry from the U.S.
have delayed unloading their cargo because payment has not been
made and Russia's creditworthiness is now in question.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, the Russian government has issued assurances that
there will be sufficient food to get through the winter. A senior
Agriculture Ministry official said Friday that he did not
anticipate the need for emergency imports of grain.
</P>
<P>
   ``With last year's carry-over of 20 million tons, the grain
balance is such that there will be no need for centralized
purchases,'' Vyacheslav Chernoivanov, the deputy agriculture and
food minister said.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, however, Russian officials have already begun to
discuss food shipments.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. official said that the Russians had talked informally
about obtaining 3 million tons of wheat, 1.5 million tons of corn,
500,000 tons of soy meal and 100,000 tons of meat. Speculation
about U.S. food shipments to Russia has driven up commodity
futures.
</P>
<P>
   Other U.S. officials said, however, that the total size of the
Russian request is unclear and that the Kremlin is still trying to
figure out what it may need.
</P>
<P>
   It is far from clear how the shipments would be financed or how
much the cash-poor Russians can afford to pay for themselves. U.S.
officials are considering a number of ways to help, including soft
loans and outright grants of food.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Closer to home, Russia has suggested that Belarus and Ukraine
repay their debts for shipments of Russian natural gas by providing
food instead of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of replenishing hard currency reserves Russia will be
receiving foodstuffs and will eat them up,'' the newspaper
Kommersant observed wryly.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov and his new coalition government have promised other
steps, as well. To ease the way for imports, Russia is considering
abolishing import duties on meat, butter, grain and other food.
</P>
<P>
   It is giving the agricultural industry five years to repay debts
to the state budget. It is also allowing Russian regions to pay
some of their debts with deliveries of food.
</P>
<P>
   Russia consumes about 70 million tons of grain a year, of which
22 million tons is used for food products. The rest is used largely
for cattle feed and seed.
</P>
<P>
   Grain, however, may play an increasingly larger role in the
Russian diet as Russians substitute bread for high-priced meat.
</P>
<P>
   A paradoxical result of Russia's disastrous harvest is that the
quality of the grain has improved. Experts say the dry summer made
the grain more suitable for milling.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's looming food shortage is hardly the only humanitarian
issue here. The financial crisis has also interfered with the
import of medicines, many of which are produced abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``The socioeconomic crisis has hit all aspects of the health
system, stopping us from doing our job,'' Vladimir Starodubov, the
new health minister, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the general problem that is crippling all aspects
of the society: a debilitating shortage of cash.
</P>
<P>
   Tax collection is down, and Primakov acknowledged Friday that he
had no idea where the money would come from to fund the
government's budget for the rest of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is still holding out hope that it can persuade the
International Monetary Fund to distribute billions in more aid.
</P>
<P>
   But the IMF does not give money on humanitarian grounds. It is
looking for signs that Primakov is prepared to advance market
reforms. And the government's absence of an economic program and
its talk of printing money to pay back wages has not comforted the
fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the sources will be for financing the
government program which is being worked out,'' Primakov said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
