<SLUG> BC-MARKET-595&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW AND NASDAQ RALLY TO END A TURBULENT WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The stock market rallied Friday, with the
technology-heavy Nasdaq index jumping 5.2 percent and the Dow Jones
industrial average climbing 2.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But that rebound only added to the lore of the week that was _
five days of trading frenzies in stocks, bonds and dollars that
will be the talk of Wall Street for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, what was so striking was that it was not just one market
that went wild this week: The dollar plunged 13.8 percent against
the Japanese yen, its biggest decline in 27 years; the yield on the
30-year bond, after falling to a 31-year low of 4.72 percent on
Monday, hammered bonds by surging back to 5.12 percent. And then
there was the stock market. The Nasdaq dropped 7.6 percent despite
Friday's rally. The Dow moved in a 450-point trading range during
the turbulent week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sit in awe at it,'' said Charles Clough Jr., chief
investment strategist at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., of the week's
volatility. ``We've never had moves like this.''
</P>
<P>
   And Abby Joseph Cohen, the market strategist at Goldman, Sachs &AMP;
Co., admitted that the volatility added to the jitters that had
left many on Wall Street walking on eggshells. When prices ``jump
around quite a bit and jump out of their normal pattern, people get
nervous,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   There are always winners and losers in markets, but the focus in
this time of global financial uncertainty is going to be on the
losers.
</P>
<P>
   One, according to people familiar with the fund, is Tiger
Management LLC, the hedge fund run by Julian Robertson, which is
said to have lost nearly $2 billion when the yen rallied against
the dollar and the Tokyo stock market rose. Tiger Management had a
large bet that both the Japanese yen and some Japanese stocks would
fall. But his fund is still up about 10 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Another loser may be the U.S. economy. It is clear already that
this volatility is contributing to the decisions of thousands of
investors to cut back on riskier companies. Bankers are also
talking about becoming more cautious, making it harder for
businesses to grow.
</P>
<P>
   In trading Friday, the Dow rose 167.61 points, to 7,899.52,
finishing the week up almost 115 points, or 1.5 percent. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 stocks rose 24.95 points, or 2.6
percent, to 984.39, down 1.8 percent for the week. The Nasdaq index
jumped 73.37 points, to 1,492.49.
</P>
<P>
   The rally was led by the stocks that had been pummeled earlier
in the week and were now seen as bargains to many investors.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign stock markets also rallied, with the Financial Times 100
index up 2.7 percent in London, the CAC 40 index up 4.5 percent in
Paris and the DAX 30 index up 2.3 percent in Frankfurt, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   In the U.S. bond market, government securities sold off for the
fourth consecutive day, with the yield on the 30-year bond jumping
from 4.99 percent on Thursday to 5.12 percent. The price, which
moves in the opposite direction, fell 1 29/32, to 105 23/32.
</P>
<P>
   In the foreign exchange market, the dollar continued to fall
against the yen, dropping 1.8 percent, to 116.95 yen from 119.05
yen. That was a big drop for a normal day, but almost stabilizing
after the 8.1 percent plunge on Wednesday. The dollar was little
changed against the German mark, slipping to 1.6363 marks from
1.6375.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market was led higher Friday by Microsoft, up 5 11/16,
to 96 7/8; Intel, up 5 3/8, to 83 13/16; Dell Computer, up 4 3/8,
to 52 13/16; and Cisco Systems, up 3 3/8, to 50 1/16. The four
stocks accounted for about half of the rise in the Nasdaq index.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Money center banks rose for the second day. That sector has been
among the hardest hit since the stock market reached its peak in
July. Despite the cumulative 8 percent rally in the last two days,
the S&AMP;P index of big banks is off 40 percent since July 17. J.P.
Morgan, which was one of the Dow leaders, rose 4}, to 84 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Johnson, the chief investment officer of First Albany
Corp., said the rally on Friday, after all the volatility, added up
to ``a modestly positive week.'' But he quickly checked his
optimism: ``It may be a head fake,'' he said. ``We have had so many
before.''
</P>
<P>
   The selloff in the foreign exchange market, traders said, was
caused by hedge funds and other institutions as they reversed
trades that had been originally based on the idea of borrowing
money cheaply in Japan to put at work at higher rates in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   That unwinding, spurred by fears that a higher yen would make
many of those deals unprofitable, accelerated this week as the
dollar fell through the 130 level and turned a lot of positions
into losses.
</P>
<P>
   That helter-skelter rush for the exits also pushed bond prices
down. To pay off their yen loans, traders had to sell U.S. bonds,
pushing both bond prices and the value of the dollar lower.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor in the bond market was the reversal of trades by
funds owning mortgage-backed securities. For several weeks, as
interest rates fell, managers of funds owning mortgages abandoned
those securities because they feared that lots of homeowners would
refinance at lower rates. When that happens, fund managers rush to
buy 10-year Treasury notes to keep their cash invested.
</P>
<P>
   But when interest rates began to rise this week, fund managers
reversed those positions, selling 10-year Treasuries to buy higher
yielding mortgage-backed securities.
</P>
<P>
   Given all the wild swings, it is no surprise that some investors
just threw up their hands and put their money in three- and
six-month Treasury bills. ``Everyone is shifting into the short
end,'' said Michael Cloherty, market strategist at Credit Suisse
First Boston. That's ``where the real haven is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
