<HEADLINE>
ON A ROLL, ARMSTRONG GEARED UP FOR WORLDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While one American _ Bobby Julich _ decided to pull out of this
week's world championship race in the Nethlerlands, another _ Lance
Armstrong _ was raring to go. Which reflects the way the racing
season has gone for the two riders. Both had successes, but they
peaked at different times.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, who missed all of the 1997 season when he was
diagnosed with testicular cancer and subsequently underwent
chemotherapy, got back on this bike &UR;  &LR; last spring, not sure how he
would fare. He was hot at first but then dropped out of a European
race on a wet and windy day in March, and when he came back, he
``didn't unpack my bike for four weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he did unpack it, he was on a roll. Armstrong finished
second in the national road race in Philadalphia in early July, won
the Cascade stage race in Orgeon later that month, and was on his
way. By late summer, when he returned to Europe, he finished fourth
in the Tour of Holland stage race and fourth in last month's Tour
of Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Julich, on the other hand, geared his spring racing to getting
in shape for the Tour de France. It worked, and he placed third in
the three-week race, the best finish by an American since Greg
LeMond won his third title in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he acknowledged, he's tired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just been a long season,'' he said by phone earlier this
week in a conference call. ``I'm tired, since I've just been going
nonstop; I think I'll go home (to Philadelphia) and take a break.''
</P>
<P>
   The worlds, he said, ``are something that you want to be 100
percent top form, and I've not been feeling so good, so I've
withdrawn myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the event, Armstrong, who won the world road race in
1993, said he was ready for tomorrow's 162-mile road race and the
time trial, in which he placed fourth, although he does wish the
championships were earlier in the season. ``It's really an event
that shouldn't be in October,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, 27, has been as surprised as anyone with his success
this season. ``I had no idea,'' he said. ``If somebody were to tell
me at the beginning, I would have said you were crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   But now he's certain he's back on track. ``I feel like a
professional cyclist again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he's determined to keep biking in a perspective that he
didn't have before. ``It's a good balance I have now; before, it
wasn't quite there,'' he said. ``Before, I was putting too much
pressure on myself. Now the emphasis is just on doing my best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to look at things anymore in terms of winning;
that's too lofty. I just want to look at it as just being there and
contending.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, who plans to ride the Tour de France next year, also
hopes to ride some mountain bike races in 1999 and might try out
for the Olympic team for mountiain bikes as well as road bikes in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Armstrong, the men's road race team for the world
championships includes pro champion and Killington stage race
winner George Hincapie, Trent Klaska, Chann McRade, Chris Horner,
Christian Van de Velde, Chris Homer, Dylan Casey, David Clinger,
and Jonathan Vaughters.
</P>
<P>
   The women's team will include Dede Demet, Mari Holden, Karen
Kurreck, Elizabeth Emery, Emily Robbins, Pam Schuster, Kendra
Wenzel, and Julie Young.
</P>
<P>
   The men's under-23 team includes two New Englanders _ Tom Davis
from Mashpee, Mass. and Justin Spinelli from Nashua, N.H.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
