<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE CYBER DONALD  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK RICH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   No trophy wives. No gaudy Rolexes, Julian Schnabel paintings or
custom-made Armani suits. No Gordon Gekkos, Sherman McCoys, Donald
Trumps. The 1990s model of high-flying self-made zillionaire, we've
been repeatedly told, is as different from his 1980s predecessor as
a fully loaded Jeep is from a Porsche. Instead of vulgar Reagan-era
barbarians at the gate, we're getting dressed-down microgeeks who
don't know or care how much money they have and are so busy
dispensing utopia to the entire globe through technology that they
don't have time to lord their good fortune over us peons who can't
install a printer without crashing Windows.
</P>
<P>
   But as I stood in front of a glass cabinet at Draeger's in San
Mateo, just south of San Francisco, recently, I wondered. Draeger's
is the lush Silicon Valley supermarket where you can buy not only
all the healthy foods you want but choose from a dizzying array of
brandies and cigars to finish off that abstemious meal. In this
locked cabinet were small bottles of balsamic vinegar that cost
more than those vials of coke Wall Street traders were snorting in
the '80s. Is it progress that our new rich can turn salad dressing
into a status symbol?
</P>
<P>
   Standing there with my nose pressed against the glass, I
realized it was only a matter of time before the culture would stop
lionizing our '90s tycoons and turn on them, much as it did on
their prototypes of the go-go '80s. All it takes to grease the
skids is a steep decline in the stock market (both Tom Wolfe's
``The Bonfire of the Vanities'' and Oliver Stone's ``Wall Street''
took off in post-crash '87) and an ugly, protracted battle between
the government and a corporation synonymous with the era's
accumulation of money and power (Drexel then, Microsoft now).
</P>
<P>
   It also helps if some celebrity member of the freshly minted
zillionaire class presents himself to the public as the
personification of arrogant, self-infatuated plutocracy _ and last
week the '90s may have finally got just the cyber-Trump it's been
asking for. The Wall Street Journal revealed that Nathan Myhrvold,
the 39-year-old chief technology officer of Microsoft, is not only
starring in ads promoting the joys of owning a private Gulfstream
jet but is also the ``Anonymous'' who wrote a lengthy firsthand
account in Vanity Fair of spending $12 million for his own first
Gulfstream.
</P>
<P>
   The piece and ad both ran in October's ``New Establishment''
issue, in which Myhrvold, often described as Bill Gates'
intellectual guru, was rated No. 23 in the list of top moguls of
the Information Age. ``At the Davos, Switzerland, powerfest,'' the
magazine notes, ``the organizers put him on a panel with Elie
Wiesel and Desmond Tutu.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's hard to imagine Wiesel or Tutu touting their Nobel
Prizes _ as Myhrvold does his advanced degrees from Cambridge and
Princeton in the Gulfstream ad _ to endorse so much as a Subaru.
But the ad is just a warm-up for Myhrvold's article, a New Age
hybrid of consumerist pornography and let-'em-eat-cake memoir.
``I've bought a lot of big-ticket items in my day, from real estate
to publicly traded companies,'' the author writes while coyly
introducing us to such pals as ``one famously parsimonious
billionaire'' and `` `C,' a billionaire known for his Zen-like
affinity for solitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Lest we think Myhrvold is frivolous, he sternly warns us that
``your life is on the line'' when shopping for this particular
big-ticket item: ``Buy a bad plane and you could be dead.'' Lest we
think a $12 million jet is a wasteful extravagance, he points out
that ``in bulk,'' jet fuel ``is actually cheaper than Diet Coke,''
and adds up how much of his precious time he'll save once he need
no longer cool his heels waiting for connecting commercial flights
in first-class lounges. Lest we confuse him with '80s-style
potentates like investment bankers _ whom he labels ``high-rent,
hired-gun slimeballs'' _ he pours on Princeton-Cambridge literary
allusions unknown to Nasdaq: Virgil and Dante and ``The Remains of
the Day.''
</P>
<P>
   But actually Myhrvold's prose resembles no writer's so much as
that of Sinclair Lewis _ minus, alas, the irony. Rhapsodizing over
his new plane, the Microsoft mogul writes in dead earnest: ``Each
tiny detail _ the satin chrome finish on the cabinet latches, the
edge work in the lavatory, the memory foam in the seats _ reveals
fresh marvels.'' He might as well be Babbitt, the go-getting
real-estate man of Zenith, a fictional 1920s equivalent to our
Seattle and Silicon Valley, as he hyperventilates over every
fixture in his ``altogether royal bathroom of porcelain and glazed
tile and metal sleek as silver.'' Though separated by decades, both
are bloated products of a boom on the eve of a bust.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
