<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9331 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIVENT-DRABINSKY-ART-     10-09 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVENT-DRABINSKY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STRANGE LAST DAYS OF A THEATER IMPRESARIO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Garth Drabinsky watched the world premiere of
``Fosse: A Celebration in Song and Dance'' in August, he knew the
stakes were high. The entertainment company he had founded _ Livent
Inc., based in Toronto _ had struggled for months to pay its bills.
Its credit was so poor that its bonds were considered junk.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian impresario didn't just need a hit; he needed a
megahit. Drabinsky had spent three years working out the details
for the opening of ``Fosse'' that Sunday night in Toronto, pushing
himself, he said later, to his physical limits.
</P>
<P>
   And for a few hours, at least, his work seemed to have paid off.
Roy Furman, Livent's new chief executive, told Drabinsky at the
premiere that ``Fosse'' would be ``a spectacular asset'' for the
company.
</P>
<P>
   What Drabinsky did not know was that at a secret meeting earlier
that evening, Furman and Livent's corporate directors had planned
Drabinsky's ouster, suspecting that he had helped inflate profits
by millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, locksmiths would change the lock on his office,
where he kept not only Livent documents but also piles of private
papers. And newly hired security guards would memorize his photo
and take up stations at the company's entrances with orders to keep
him out.
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky's famously lavish spending had suddenly caught up with
him and the company he created in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   In June, cash troubles had forced him to turn over control of
Livent to Michael Ovitz, former president of Walt Disney Co., in
return for a $20 million investment.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Robert B. Webster, one of the new executives hired by
Ovitz, was startled when he found the Livent accountants reluctant
to talk to him. In a court affidavit, Webster said he became
``greatly concerned'' when some of the accountants told him that
Drabinsky had warned them not to provide certain financial
information until the producer had reviewed and approved it.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Thursday, Aug. 6 _ three days before the ``Fosse''
premiere _ five accountants gave Webster details that, he said,
``cast doubt upon the veracity and accuracy'' of the company's
books.
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky has refused repeated requests for an interview, and
Ovitz and his team have provided little information on what they
call ``accounting irregularities.'' But details about the dispute
have emerged in papers that are part of a lawsuit Drabinsky filed
last month against KPMG, the giant accounting firm, which is
conducting a forensic investigation into the accounting
irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky won a small victory in the case this week when the
judge said the producer might review the accountants' investigative
report before they gave it to Ovitz. Livent's new managers have
said the suit is a desperate attempt to delay the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to Livent's board have said privately that
Drabinsky kept two sets of books for expenses like advertising _
hiding, in the official set, some of his extravagant spending by
shifting it to other accounts. He kept a separate list, they said,
of the actual advertisements for each show.
</P>
<P>
   After the ``Fosse'' premiere on Aug. 9, the cast and company
employees celebrated at an opening-night party. Drabinsky, by his
account, left early to help edit a television commercial for the
show, which he did until 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky had been home only a few hours when Furman called at
5:30 a.m., telling him he was suspended and summoning him to an
8:30 a.m. meeting at the offices of the company's lawyers. There,
Furman and other executives warned him to stay away from Livent's
premises. Drabinsky's partner, Myron Gottlieb, was also suspended.
</P>
<P>
   According to Webster's affidavit, Drabinsky admitted at that
meeting that he was aware of the accounting irregularities, but
said he thought they were balanced out by the tens of millions of
dollars that Livent had written off in late 1997 and early 1998.
Webster said, however, that those write-downs had no connection to
the irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   Webster said in the affidavit that the irregularities ``will
ultimately be shown to have been known to and directed by''
Drabinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky has said through his spokesman that he did nothing
wrong, and has questioned why Ovitz and his team have only now
brought up the accounting problems. Ovitz had hired KPMG Peat
Marwick to review the company's books before he took over. But KPMG
found nothing that caused Ovitz to find another place to invest his
$20 million.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday a spokesman for Drabinsky said that the producer would
not comment further on the ``vague assertions'' made by Webster and
others. ``He'll address these issues in court at the appropriate
time,'' said David Weiner, the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky also successfully argued to the judge that many of
Webster's statements on his reputed role in the accounting
irregularities, including many of those detailed here, were
irrelevant to his case against the KPMG accountants and should be
struck from the court record.
</P>
<P>
   Gottlieb's lawyer did not respond to repeated requests for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second time that Drabinsky, 48, a man long known for
his artistic vision, abundant confidence and high-spending ways,
has built a sprawling entertainment company, only to be tossed out
when questions arose about his accounting.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Drabinsky, a former entertainment lawyer, founded
Cineplex Odeon, building it from an 18-screen theater company in
Toronto to an 1,800-screen chain sprawling across the United States
and Canada. MCA, one of the company's big investors, dismissed him
in 1989 amid questions of aggressive accounting.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next decade, Drabinsky built Livent in much the same
way. He and Gottlieb bought a Toronto theater from Cineplex in
1989, and then expanded rapidly by building new theaters and going
deeply into debt.
</P>
<P>
   Livent now owns five theaters in four cities _ New York;
Toronto; Vancouver, British Columbia; and Chicago. On Broadway,
Drabinsky, with much bravado, opened ``Ragtime'' in Livent's new
$22.5 million Ford Center for the Performing Arts on Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
   But soon after that the producer's unrestrained spending on
sets, cast, costumes and advertising caught up with Livent, and not
even $76 Broadway tickets covered the bills. When Ovitz came to the
company's aid, the big-talking producer lost his position as
chairman and chief executive. He continued as chief creative
director, earning a salary of $700,000.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ovitz and his team were aware of the cash problems,
they say they did not expect the financial fiasco they soon
discovered.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
