<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-MOUNTAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNOWLESS SLOPES JUST RIGHT FOR MOUNTAIN BIKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KILLINGTON, Vt. _ The 1,000-space parking lot outside the base
ski lodge is packed with cars, but there are no ski racks on their
roofs. The people waiting in line for the gondolas aren't wearing
wool hats or mufflers. And there's not a ski or a ski boot in
sight.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, you'll see a bike rack on every car, a helmet on every
head, and yes, a mountain bike next to almost every person in line.
</P>
<P>
   Never let it be said that skiers ignore the slopes just because
there's no snow on them. Both the athletes and the mountian
managers realize that the terrain and gondolas can be put to good
use in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   So on a recent cloudless, 55-degree day, with trees along Route
4 in central Vermont bursting with red, yellow, and green leaves,
it was no surprise that some bikers decided to leave the
exhaust-filled roads and head up the mountain, along with tourists
who ride the gondola just for the view.
</P>
<P>
   Next weekend, Killington will begin making snow in full force
and remove from the gondola cars the hooks from which to hang
bikes. But for now, two wheels substitute for two skis.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the bikers go straight down the Cascade or Double
Dipper ski trails _ even the boldest realize that a steep mountain
with no snow can be more treacherous than a mountain with snow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Killington did a good job cutting single-track trails just for
bikes,'' said Bob Rebolledo, getting ready for his second run of
the day. ``You don't want to go down these Alpine slopes because
there are a lot of hidden rocks that are dangerous and it's steep
and you're just on your brakes all the time, so it's no fun.''
</P>
<P>
   His friend Burl Amsbury had some dried blood on one leg as
evidence that even on the special trails, you can still take a
spill.
</P>
<P>
   But Amsbury shrugged it off, saying, ``You've got to pay your
dues, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   While the blanket of colors covering the mountains might not be
as blazing as last year (``Too much rain early in the season,'' is
the diagnosis from hiking guide Walt Gropar), most bikers said the
scenery is a main attraction on Killington.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Hardy, who drove up from Newport, R.I., with his friend
Sarah James, said things can be a blur as he's making his way down
the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I buzz down, but you have to stop every now and then,'' Hardy
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Smollen, who came from Chicago to ride down the mountain,
put the scenery in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I'm not looking at the leaves on the way down,'' he
said with a laugh. ``Just on the way up. So yeah, I see the foliage
on the ground after it's fallen.''
</P>
<P>
   The bikes that are either brought up by their owners or rented
(350 were rented at Killington last Sunday) are better suited for
mountainous terrain than ever before. In addition to the thick,
knobby tires and flat handlebars that are better for maneuvering,
the bikes can have up to 24 speeds. Some have cantilever instead of
side-pull brakes, and shock absorbers on the front, back, or both.
</P>
<P>
   As for garb, Killington biker Damian Stowell explained that
aesthestics are not the issue when it comes to mountain biking;
safety is.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try not to crash, but it's inevitable,'' said Stowell,
sporting a well-worn helmet and arm pads,
</P>
<P>
   His friend David Hess was equipped with plenty of protection. He
wore his soccer chin pads and had a full-coverage helmet that made
him look like Darth Vader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like my teeth the way they are,'' he said matter-of-factly.
</P>
<P>
   The two, who came up with two other friends from Boston, said
they are prepared to ``go up and shoot down the mountain until they
quit running the lift'' at 5:45 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Scott, who mans the gondola that goes up to Killington Peak,
said, ``Mountain bikers are a very reliable crowd for us. They're
out here in the pouring rain, and as soon as I get snow, they'll be
skiing for me as well.''
</P>
<P>
   And if the conditions are right, when the nights are cold enough
to keep the man-made snow on the ground and the gondolas are still
taking bikes up, the skiers/bikers will do both in one day.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Elles, who owns the First Stop/Board Barn on Route 4, has
seen the crossover firsthand. He started his shop 19 years ago,
renting skis and selling small accessories.
</P>
<P>
   When he began renting bikes 12 years ago, he opened a shop right
next door but with a separate entrance ``because bikers and skiers
didn't see eye to eye. There was no respect for a ski shop that
carried bikes.'
</P>
<P>
   Now he sells both skis and bikes and wants to connect the two
buildings since ``everything is starting to blend together.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott stressed that the bikers don't have to be hard-core to go
down the mountain. Although some come down in 15 minutes, others
can take up to two hours.
</P>
<P>
   And there are plenty of bikers in the leisurely category. Two
fathers, Rusty Williams and David Osborne, and their 7-year-old
sons were headed out to ride down the mountain while their wives
and other children took the gondola back down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a beautiful day, and if you walk around up here, you can
see the whole area,'' said Williams, of Wayland, Mass. ``The kids
are really good bikers, and we're going to go really, really slow
and meet the others at the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   Still others say they don't need the gondola at all to enjoy the
mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Bud Alpert, a dentist in Stamford, Conn., who has a house near
Killington, makes the drive up north every weekend to either ski in
the winter or bike in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   But like a cook who disdains a microwave, Alpert said he prefers
to use human energy to power his way both up and down the mountain
and through the surrounding woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like saying, `Let's go for a beautiful ride in the
country,' and then getting on Interstate 91,'' he said. ``For me,
part of the reward going downhill is earning it coming up.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHERE ELSE TO RIDE BEFORE THE SNOW FALLS ...
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Many downhill and cross-country ski areas in New England have
mountain bike trails and offer rentals. Others, like Wachusett and
Butternut mountains in Massachusetts, are state reserves, and
biking is not allowed on the trails, although it is permitted on
the fire roads and surrounding areas. &QL; 
In addition, here are some of the resorts that offer lift or
gondola services to bikers: &QL; 
 &QL; 
Vermont: Mount Snow, Stowe, Stratton, Sugarbush
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire: Attitash, Loon, Snow
</P>
<P>
   Maine: Sunday River
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts: Jiminy Peak
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
