<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9333 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIVENT-DRABINSKY-ART-     10-09 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVENT-DRABINSKY-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: soon discovered.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After he was dismissed in August, Drabinsky battled with
Livent's lawyers for weeks to try to get piles of personal papers
he had kept in his office.
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky had also decorated his office walls, the adjoining
hallway and the boardroom with his private artworks. But Livent now
demanded that he produce proof that he owned the art, which he
eventually recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky even had his own personal bookkeeper, Lorraine
Valentine, at Livent. Ms. Valentine kept the financial records for
the producer's personal tax returns. Livent officials would not say
whether the bookkeeper's salary was paid by the company or by
Drabinsky.
</P>
<P>
   For days, investigators from the Canadian affiliate of KPMG
sorted through thousands of documents in the offices of Drabinsky,
Gottlieb and Ms. Valentine, deciding which belonged to Livent and
which were personal.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Drabinsky's objections, the KPMG investigators have kept
items like his personal diary, papers on a Toronto art gallery he
owns, and architectural drawings for a weekend home he had wanted
to build in Uxbridge, Ontario, but later abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say that the diary includes details pertinent to
their accounting inquiry and that they have evidence of business
dealings between the gallery and Livent. It is not clear why the
architectural drawings were retained.
</P>
<P>
   On the night of Aug. 13, the investigators let Drabinsky enter
Livent's headquarters, with KPMG security guards escorting him to
his office, which was then almost devoid of documents. ``The
atmosphere was highly intimidating,'' Drabinsky wrote in court
papers.
</P>
<P>
   According to the court papers filed by KPMG investigators,
Drabinsky grew angry during his visit. He was ``verbally abusive
and swore several times,'' wrote Gary Gill of KPMG Investigation
and Security Inc. ``I also heard him shout and yell several times
at his bookkeeper, Ms. Valentine,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   When Drabinsky filed suit against KPMG, he said the firm should
be dismissed from the investigation because it had several
conflicts of interest. For almost two decades, KPMG's tax
accountants have prepared Drabinsky's personal tax returns and
often provided advice on matters related to Livent.
</P>
<P>
   KPMG investigators have argued that they avoided Drabinsky's tax
documents during their investigation, and that they have not talked
to the firm's tax accountants about Drabinsky or tried to get
information from them. They say they have used none of Drabinsky's
personal information in their investigation and have followed all
ethical rules.
</P>
<P>
   This week, a judge said that KPMG, which has completed its
report, must allow Drabinsky to see it to ensure that none of his
personal tax information has been used by the investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Since they were suspended, both Drabinsky and Gottlieb have
tried to stay out of the public view. Drabinsky has been handling
his legal predicaments from an office in his home, but his art
gallery _ the Drabinsky-Friedland Gallery in Toronto _ is still
open.
</P>
<P>
   Neither man now receives a salary. And much of their personal
wealth is tied up in Livent stock, which cannot be sold. Both U.S.
and Canadian exchanges suspended trading in it on Aug. 10, when the
company announced the discovery of the accounting irregularities
and officially suspended Drabinsky and Gottlieb.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators say they will not allow trading until the company
releases more information on the severity of the accounting
problems, which the company says date back to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky says he owns ``directly and indirectly'' 2,167,875
shares, which, based on the stock's last price of $6.75, would be
worth more than $14 million. But the shares are no doubt worth much
less now.
</P>
<P>
   In his court affidavit, Drabinsky said he feared his reputation
would soon ``be completely destroyed'' with the aid of his ``own
accountants.''
</P>
<P>
   The impresario, once so full of bluster, says the days following
the premiere of ``Fosse'' ``were the worst two weeks of my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
