<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHROEDER TELLS CLINTON HE BACKS ACTION BY NATO IN KOSOVO  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN ERLANGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ _ The German Chancellor-elect, Gerhard Schroeder,
told President Clinton Friday that he would support a decision by
the caretaker German government to authorize NATO to use force over
Kosovo if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   But Schroeder made it clear, German officials said, that any
authorization for German troops and airplanes to participate in any
NATO action should wait for the newly elected parliament, which
will take its seats on Oct. 26. That parliament is expected to
elect Schroeder as chancellor on Oct. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said they were relieved that
Schroeder and his prospective foreign minister, Joschka Fischer of
the Green Party, would not block the use of force by NATO or
undermine the effort to increase the pressure on the Yugoslav
president, Slobodan Milosevic, to take NATO's threats seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The officials have told the Germans that their forces _ the
Germans have offered some 14 fighter jets and up to 500 troops _
would not be crucial in the early stages of any NATO action in any
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one, and above all the Yugoslav president, should hope that
we will take a less decisive approach'' than the current government
of Helmut Kohl, Schroeder said Friday morning. ``He must fulfill
the U.N. resolutions completely, and we will do all we can to
ensure it is fulfilled. The U.S. knows that is our view.''
</P>
<P>
   Fischer said: ``Nothing has changed in the basic position of
Germany with respect to Milosevic. Milosevic should not think that
the new government will take a less firm position than the old
one.''
</P>
<P>
   While ``we agree with the positions of the Western alliance that
there must be a serious pressure on Slobodan Milosevic,'' Fischer
said, ``in this transition situation, the Americans have to
understand that our possibilities for action are very limited.''
</P>
<P>
   After their White House meeting, Clinton emphasized the
importance of the NATO authorization of force _ a vote that may not
take place until Tuesday or even Wednesday, officials said Friday.
There is a desire to see the results of talks in Belgrade between
U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke and Milosevic, the officials said, and
the Italians need to sort out a new government after the coalition
of Prime Minister Romano Prodi collapsed earlier Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first issue is whether Germany will support NATO issuing
the action order to make sure that the plans are in place and
authorized if NATO action should be needed,'' Clinton said. ``That
is what he said yes to today.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added: ``I am convinced it is important that we
authorize NATO to act. That's where the agreement is.'' German
officials say the current Cabinet is expected to vote on Monday to
authorize the use of force by NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder said that Germany ``does not have a vested interest in
going into war in Kosovo,'' but said, with his usual vagueness: ``I
find it very important to reveal a certain degree of decisiveness
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, at a news conference later at the German Embassy here,
Schroeder said, ``I don't even want to think about what happens if
the U.N. resolution is not fulfilled'' by Milosevic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
