<SLUG> BC-NASA-TECH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA SEEKS PRIVATE FIRM TO MAKE HABITATION MODULE AVAILABLE AS
EMERGENCY SHELTER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  with NASATECH-CHART 
 
By LAURA GOLDBERG 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASA's Johnson Space Center thinks technologies in its TransHab,
a large inflatable ``habitation module'' could be put to good use
in places other than space _ maybe for some type of emergency
shelter.
</P>
<P>
   What's needed is a private company willing to take the
techniques used to make the Transit Habitat into commercial
products.
</P>
<P>
   NASA just might find a company poised to do so at its three-day
Inspection98 program beginning Wednesday. Johnson Space Center will
display more than 200 technologies and exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to put NASA's technology into general use. At the
program, Johnson's third, NASA may also find a company or person
who can partner with on research or projects.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of business, industry and education, and
community leaders are invited. More than 4,000 people, including
those from outside the country _ especially those outside the
aerospace community _ are expected to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we hope is people will find technology that they can use
in their businesses or take home and turn into commercial
products,'' said Kathy Jurica, who is chairing Inspection98.
</P>
<P>
   There are different ways to get NASA technology. Some of it is
in the public domain and available free. In cases involving
patented technology a licensing agreement may be needed. NASA would
receive a licensing fee and royalties that could be based on a
percent of sales.
</P>
<P>
   A partnership with NASA could also be set up. That's what
happened with Robert Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, who has a doctorate in anatomy, went to Inspection96
searching for technologies that would help him teach anatomy and
physiology.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a place to go see what I would have not otherwise
known about,'' he said. ``I was looking for educational application
of technologies.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice, an adjunct professor at University of Houston and a
professor at Montgomery College in Conroe, had an idea to create a
virtual reality human body as a teaching tool. He was hoping NASA
had developed the technology that would allow him to do so.
</P>
<P>
   He found it had not. But he also found that NASA was interested
in partnering with him to create that technology, which also has
applications for space use. NASA, he said, is interested in the
effects of microgravity, which means virtually no gravity, on
people; and in using a virtual body to design the next generation
of spacesuits.
</P>
<P>
   At the Inspection in 1996, Rice met Anthony Bruins, a NASA
systems engineer. Bruins, Rice said, had immediate enthusiasm for
Rice's idea and has sheparded him through the NASA process.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1997, Rice set up in the Institute of Somatic
Sciences at the Houston Advanced Research Center in The Woodlands
north of Houston. Somatic refers to bones, muscles and nerves. By
the time the next Inspection rolled around, Rice had developed a
prototype for a virtual body. He displayed a virtual shoulder area.
</P>
<P>
   In January of this year, Rice was approved to get NASA funding
for his work. This year, he'll display an entire arm. The computer
simulation acts and looks like a real arm. It can also be moved and
felt.
</P>
<P>
   Also because of the 1996 program, Montana Biotech hooked up with
a NASA researcher. Both study organisms that live in extreme
environments. A person familiar with Montana Biotech attended the
program and put the small Montana-based business in touch with the
NASA researcher.
</P>
<P>
   The company and researcher collaborated informally, and Montana
Biotech later signed an agreement to work with NASA to study how to
sterilize rock samples containing bacteria. That research will be
used for handling samples collected from Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Combie, owner and vice president of Montana Biotech, said
the relationship has been mutually beneficial as the technology
developed may have commercial application in the future &UR; .  &LR; The
connection, said Montana Biotech president Fred Albert, has allowed
the company to progress more quickly on studying effects of
radiation on microorganisms.
</P>
<P>
   The NASA researcher has also added to Montana Biotech's
collection of organisms.
</P>
<P>
   Both praised the Inspection program with Albert saying he would
like to attend one in the future to see what else the company could
get involved in.
</P>
<P>
   Those interested in Inspection98 can get information by phone
(281-244-1316) or e-mail (inspection at jsc.nasa.gov). &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
