<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INS-DETAIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INS REQUIRED TO DETAIN CRIMINAL ILLEGAL IMMIGRANTS UNTIL
DEPORTATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN DRAKE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a two-year delay, a federal mandate became effective
Friday that requires the Immigration and Naturalization Service to
detain all criminal illegal immigrants until deportation.
</P>
<P>
   Some INS officials say the new policy will cause crowding
problems and budget headaches.
</P>
<P>
   The mandate, included in a 1996 federal law, no longer allows
INS officials to decide whether permanent residents who have been
arrested but are not considered dangerous can be released pending
the outcome of their deportation hearings.
</P>
<P>
   The provision, part of the Illegal Immigration Reform and
Immigrant Responsibility Act, was meant to toughen up U.S. borders
and immigration policy. But in testimony before congressional
committees, the INS had argued that it did not have the resources
to implement the new policy. As a result, the agency was granted
two one-year delays in implementing it.
</P>
<P>
   The INS still estimates it lacks 17,000 to 27,000 beds to
adequately detain the criminal illegal immigrants it has been
mandated to hold.
</P>
<P>
   In the INS region that includes Texas, officials said the ratio
of illegal immigrants they must keep in detention to those they can
release will stay about the same _ 75 percent to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But local offices in Texas had mixed reactions on how the new
mandate will affect them.
</P>
<P>
   The INS Service Processing Center in El Paso will face ``major
crowding,'' said Vincent Clausen, assistant district director for
detention and deportation there.
</P>
<P>
   Clausen said the office is using the new provisions from the
1996 law to speed up deportation, but his and other stations face
another problem _ ``non-removables,'' immigrants from countries
with no political ties to the U.S. These immigrants face long-term
detention because they cannot be returned.
</P>
<P>
   The INS agrees with Congress that criminal illegal aliens who
commit aggravated felonies or are deemed dangerous by an
immigration judge should be detained, and the agency has always
done so, said Russell Bergeron, a spokesman for the national INS
office.
</P>
<P>
   But Bergeron cited an example of a man who struggled with drug
addiction, was arrested for possession of narcotics, served a short
sentence and probation, went through rehabilitation and now has a
family and holds a job. If such a person visited relatives outside
the U.S. and truthfully answered whether he had ever been arrested
upon returning, the INS would automatically detain and deport him.
</P>
<P>
   The same provision that limits INS officials' discretion also
provides some new tools to deal with the mandate and more quickly
deport criminal illegal immigrants. INS officials can now:
</P>
<P>
   Immediately detain and deport an illegal immigrants who shows up
at any port of entry without proper documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reinstate prior orders'' or immediately deport someone who has
already been deported, without time-consuming paperwork or a
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Finish deportation paperwork while illegal immigrants serve
their criminal sentence so they are deported without delay upon
completing their sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The INS and Congress have blamed each other for the lack of
resources devoted to detention. Hill staffers say the INS never
provided Congress with information about what the provision would
mean and how much it would cost, and INS officials say Congress
doesn't really understand the immigration problem and has not
earmarked enough money.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was completely avoidable and unnecessary,'' said a
Capitol Hill staffer who works on immigration. ``They don't have
their act together. It's very troubling they come here at the last
minute and try to point fingers at Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bergeron places more responsibility on Congress: ``Clearly,
we have indicated to Congress through the two annual reports we
submitted, and with testimony, that the current levels would not be
sufficient to meet the mandatory detention requirements.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
