<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9351 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS-1STLEDE-COX     10-09 0367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Task force endorses using codes to track HIV cases
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDs: Writethru includes report on decision to use numerical
codes
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Georgia Task Force on AIDS decided on Friday to
endorse using numerical codes instead of people's names to keep
track of HIV infections in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The task force's recommendation to the state Department of Human
Resources is not binding, and DHR will continue to seek public
comment on the issue until the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   DHR will make its own decision on an HIV reporting system
sometime in the summer of 1999, and the system will be implemented
in 2000, said David Johnson, a senior public health adviser with
DHR.
</P>
<P>
   No one at Friday's meeting contested the need for some kind of
surveillance system that would allow doctors and epidemiologists to
learn which geographic areas and population subgroups are being
hard hit by the virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't get those numbers out, there's no way I'm going to
get funding,'' said Dr. Harold Katner, a task force member who
treats HIV-positive people in Macon. ``I don't know how else we can
set up programs to deal with areas with a high growth rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Some believe that using names to report HIV infections would
provide the highest possible accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   But community advocates strongly oppose reporting names, saying
it could create opportunities for breaches of confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   The numerical codes, or unique identifiers, recommended by the
task force would be similar to those now used in HIV reporting
systems in Maryland and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   These 12-digit codes include the last four digits of an
individual's Social Security number, the six digits of that
person's birth date, one digit representing race or ethnicity and
one digit for gender.
</P>
<P>
   To submit comments on an HIV reporting system, send letters to
the Department of Human Resources: HIV Reporting Comments, Georgia
Department of Human Resources, Epidemiology and Prevention Branch,
2 Peachtree St. N.W., Sixth Floor Tower, Room 6-407, Atlanta, GA
30303-3186.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
