<DOCNO> NYT19981009.0411 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9352 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-DIARY-$ADV11-NYT &LR;      10-09 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON THE ECONOMY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a 7-Year Summer, Economic Leaves Turn
</P>
<P>
   The outlook for the United States economy has ``weakened
measurably,'' Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, told a
group of economists last week. Though current indicators remain
fairly healthy, he said, ``we are clearly facing a set of forces
that should be dampening demand going forward to an unknown
extent,'' including a ``scary psychology'' in financial markets and
fears that gloomy market news will undermine consumer confidence
and chill spending.
</P>
<P>
   Fed watchers found in Greenspan's remarks strong hints that
further interest-rate cuts were in the offing.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after his testimony, J.P. Morgan economists said they
expect a recession in 1999, which would end the nation's longest
peacetime economic expansion. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   World Markets Keep Roiling; World Leaders Keep Squabbling
</P>
<P>
   A five-day conference of finance ministers and central bankers
in Washington ended without agreement on any coordinated steps to
bolster the world economy, despite a direct appeal for a unified
plan from President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   European leaders and the president of the World Bank broke with
the United States and the International Monetary Fund over
strategies for restoring stability in global financial markets.
Latin American governments, envious of what they consider lenient
treatment of Russia, called for more generous financial aid for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar sank sharply against the Japanese yen, not because
anyone thought Tokyo's new stimulus package would end the country's
recession, but because hedge funds and other investors were
unwinding dollar investments and buying yen to repay loans to
Japanese banks.
</P>
<P>
   The falling dollar took the wind out of the Treasury bond
market's sails; yields bobbed back up to levels of two weeks ago.
Stocks were exceptionally volatile, with the Dow soaring or
plunging wildly at times on several days, only to reverse course
and close nearly unchanged. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Market Turmoil Doesn't Kill Companies' Urge to Merge
</P>
<P>
   Mergers and acquisitions are crawling tentatively out of the
bomb shelters to test the wind again. Clear Channel Communications
said it would buy Jacor Communications for $2.8 billion in stock;
the combination would be the second-biggest radio station owner in
the country. Cardinal Health, a drug wholesaler, agreed to buy
Allegiance, which sells medical supplies, for $5.4 billion in stock
and debt.
</P>
<P>
   AMP won two rounds in its struggle to escape a hostile takeover
by Allied Signal; the Pennsylvania House passed a favorable bill,
and a federal judge challenged Allied's plan to install a group of
its employees as AMP directors. Allied said it would complete its
tender offer anyway. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Columbia/HCA's problems with the government metastasized far
beyond the criminal investigation of billing practices at some of
its Florida hospitals. In a civil suit, the government accused
Columbia and Quorum Health Group of systematic fraud involving
hundreds of hospitals collecting inflated reimbursements from
Medicare and other programs over a 14-year period. ... The Justice
Department sued Visa USA and Mastercard International on antitrust
grounds. ... The Philippine government brokered a deal among
unions, creditors and management that will allow Philippine
Airlines to resume operations this week. ... Citibank said it would
scrap hundreds of millions of dollars' worth of core back-office
computer systems and build a new Internet-based retail banking and
investment service from scratch. ... Republicans in the two houses
of Congress settled on a single version of a new bankruptcy law
that would make it much harder for consumers to get relief from
debts. Democrats urged President Clinton to veto the bill as too
harsh on low-income consumers. ... The chip makers Advanced Micro
Devices and Motorola turned in surprisingly good earnings reports. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SO TO SPEAK Rhyming and Reasoning
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bet your 10th-grade English teacher never called poetry ``a
process framework which enables individuals and groups to recognize
and act on opportunities.'' But then, your teacher probably never
met Barbara J. Babij.
</P>
<P>
   An accountant from Fort Erie, Ontario, Ms. Babij has written a
series of 8- and 10-line stanzas for PricewaterhouseCoopers, the
giant accounting and consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   The poems, which the firm has emblazoned on both sides of seven
colorful, laminated ``Poetry in Action'' cards, describe creative
problem-solving techniques and will be used as a ``strategic
marketing tool'' and training aid.
</P>
<P>
   A sample of Ms. Babij's work:
</P>
<P>
   Brainwriting is used for change incremental,
</P>
<P>
   It's a structured approach and not incidental.
</P>
<P>
   A worksheet is used, three columns of six,
</P>
<P>
   Fill in a row, then exchange for a mix.
</P>
<P>
   Options on options group members will build,
</P>
<P>
   Each one works alone, and voices are stilled.
</P>
<P>
   A large number of options in a short time,
</P>
<P>
   Many an option will be in its prime.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling creative yet?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 2047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
