</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS THINK PANTHERS WILL GO TO WALLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Carolina Panthers tight end Wesley Walls has
averaged 58.6 receptions a season over the past three seasons. But
part of the Panthers' winless record has been underscored by Walls'
lack of involvement in the offense.
</P>
<P>
   He has just seven receptions for 84 yards and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys expect the Panthers to try to change that tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the best tight ends in the league and he makes a
lot of plays,'' said Cowboys strong safety Darren Woodson, who'll
draw part of the coverage assignment on the 6-foot-5, 250-pound
Walls. ``When they were rolling on offense, he was making plays.
One reason they are 0-4 is because they have not gone to him as
much. I'm sure they'll go to him (tomorrow). They have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said that perhaps the club's
quarterback change might help Walls. Steve Beuerlein was selected
as the starter in midweek after Kerry Collins asked to be benched.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve is a smart enough quarterback that he will make sure
that he incorporates Walls into the offense,'' Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   A bigger role for Walls will put more pressure on Woodson and
the rest of the Cowboys' secondary, particularly first-year
starting free safety Omar Stoutmire.
</P>
<P>
   In five games this season, Stoutmire has been a sturdy run
supporter with 27 tackles, fourth-most on the team. But he has just
one pass defensed as the Cowboys have often taken him out on
passing downs.
</P>
<P>
   When he has played against the pass, he has tried to keep his
mistakes to a minimum. There have been two notable ones this year.
He was beaten on a 23-yard touchdown pass to Shannon Sharpe against
the Broncos when he was fooled on play-action pass. He also failed
to provided deep help on Leslie Shepherd's 40-yard touchdown pass
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Omar has made a couple of first-year mistakes,'' Gailey said.
``But there have only been a few. If you can keep your mistakes
down to a minimum the first year you start, then you are playing
pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoutmire said he knows teams will try to take advantage of his
youth. But he is confident that he can be a deterrent for passes
thrown his direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think I'd get suckered in a lot on play-action, but I've
been able to make some plays,'' Stoutmire said. ``I'm trying to get
better each week.'' &QL; 
BRIEFLY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said he is surprised that teams still punt at Deion
Sanders. ``I thought they'd reach that point. But do you want to
take a chance on aiming it hard out of bounds and risking an
18-yard punt? (Teams) are telling their guys that, `Hey, he's just
a guy. We can cover him.' I hope they keep telling their guys that.
He believes he can score a touchdown on every punt return.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive lineman Antonio Anderson, who has been out since
undergoing arthroscopic surgery on his knee last month, has been
working out and could play as soon as next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
