<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-FRESNOST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU RUNS A TAG TEAM TO SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By TERRANCE HARRIS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Limping off the field in the second overtime
Saturday against Vanderbilt, TCU tailback Basil Mitchell turned and
pumped his fist in encouragement to his replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's running had put the Frogs at the Commodores' 8-yard
line. But if TCU was going to win this game, it was going to come
down to the work of LaDainian Tomlinson.
</P>
<P>
   Tomlinson broke through for 4 yards up the middle. And then he
steamrolled inside for the final 4 yards for the winning touchdown
in a 19-16 victory.
</P>
<P>
   And still pumping his fist on the sideline was Mitchell, who
made the drive possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just so pumped up for L.T.,'' said Mitchell, who gained
125 yards against Vanderbilt. ``The thing is, I always want to see
him do good.''
</P>
<P>
   That unselfishness has given the Frogs one of the most potent
rushing attacks in the nation. The two have combined for 666 yards
and eight rushing touchdowns this season.
</P>
<P>
   TCU ranks second in the Western Athletic Conference in rushing
(250.3 yards a game) behind Air Force and eighth in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both very quality running backs who can just wear down
a defense,'' said Fresno State coach Pat Hill, whose Bulldogs face
TCU tonight at Amon Carter Stadium. ``They can just put you in so
many tough situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, who has been the Frogs' leading rusher the past two
seasons as a three-year starter, is more of an elusive runner.
Tomlinson, on the other hand, relies more on power and often seems
as inclined to run through a defender as he is to go around him.
</P>
<P>
   But even with their varying styles, TCU coach Dennis Franchione
says there isn't a situation where he would prefer one over the
other. Since he switched Tomlinson from fullback to tailback three
weeks ago, Franchione has allowed his two tailbacks to rotate
themselves in and out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't have that kind of confidence in those two, then
there's no way I would allow them to handle the substitutions,''
said Franchione, who has the Frogs off to a 3-1 start this season.
``But they are both good running backs and they are very unselfish.
As far as I'm concerned they are both starters.''
</P>
<P>
   Both have already been named WAC Mountain Division player of the
week. Tomlinson earned his honor after rushing for 99 yards and two
touchdowns against Air Force. Mitchell earned his after rushing for
186 yards and three touchdowns in the season opener at Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that says it all right there,'' running backs coach
Mike Schultz said. ``Any time you have two different guys in your
backfield receive that type of honor this early, then I think it
tells a lot right there.
</P>
<P>
   ``But even more gratifying than the yards and production is to
see how unselfish the two are. The only thing that really seems to
matter to them is winning. And that is what makes it fun for me as
a coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomlinson and Mitchell say what has made this season enjoyable
for them is the multiple-set offense brought in by Franchione,
which has allowed them to pick up yards off both the option and on
draw plays. It has also helped having an athletic quarterback such
as Patrick Batteaux, who is a consistent threat to run the
football.
</P>
<P>
   Batteaux, a converted wide receiver, is the Frogs' third-leading
rusher with 223 yards on a team-high 74 carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``This offense is designed to put us in the best position
possible,'' said Mitchell, who is averaging 6.5 yards per carry and
107.8 yards a game. ``We're getting the ball in a lot of one-on-one
matchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us a chance to show our athletic ability, as opposed
to us just running into a host of people. And because of that, the
results have been nothing but positive.'' &QL; 
CYBERCAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Today's TCU-Fresno State game will be available on cybercast at
www.totalcollegesports.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
