<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-NEBRASKA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGGIES LOOK TO SNAP TOP-10 JINX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Never one to dawdle when finding a seam
in an opposing defense, Texas A&AMP;M tailback Dante Hall is even
quicker to cut short a line of questioning about the Aggies' recent
struggles in high-profile games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, we have to win a game like this to get over the
hump,'' Hall said, providing the answer before a reporter could
finish his query about today's matchup between No. 18 A&AMP;M (4-1,
1-0) and No. 2 Nebraska (5-0, 1-0). ``I'll be glad when we do, so I
can start getting some new questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Until that happens, a common theme will continue to be the
Aggies' 10-game losing streak against top-10 foes they will carry
into today's 2:30 p.m. matchup in Kyle Field. But only two of those
losses occurred at Kyle Field and the Aggies had opportunities to
win both games before falling to No. 6 Texas, 16-6, in 1995 and to
No. 9 Arkansas, 23-22, in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Getting a chance to play the Cornhuskers in front of a pro-A&AMP;M
crowd and on a grass field, where coaches believe option teams are
less effective, has boosted the spirits of Aggies' players and
coaches as they attempt to record the school's first victory
against a top-10 opponent since knocking off No. 8 Houston, 17-13,
in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaches will tell you that option teams don't execute as well
on grass as on artificial turf,'' said A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum,
echoing sentiments expressed earlier in the week by Missouri coach
Larry Smith. ``They have more secure footing on turf. When you're
making those tight, 90-degree cuts, that really helps.''
</P>
<P>
   For an 11-point underdog like A&AMP;M, a raucous home crowd also
helps. A&AMP;M is 45-4-1 at Kyle Field during the 1990s. The .910
winning percentage at home that ranks fourth among Division I-A
teams in this decade. To liven the mood for Nebraska, A&AMP;M officials
have urged fans to wear maroon shirts as part of a ``Maroon Out''
promotion designed to inspire the home team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like we shouldn't let anyone come in here and take a
win from us at our home,'' Hall said. ``We need to feed off the
crowd and play with a lot of excitement. We've been playing hard.
But the excitement hasn't been there.''
</P>
<P>
   It has returned this week, said offensive guard Cameron Spikes,
a lifelong resident in the Bryan-College Station area who termed
today's contest ``the biggest game I can think of in A&AMP;M's
history.''
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, Nebraska represents the highest-ranked
opponent to visit Kyle Field since No. 2 Texas in 1983. The
Cornhuskers, in the estimation of A&AMP;M wide receiver Chris Cole,
arrive primed for a fall after struggling to beat Oklahoma State,
24-17, last week in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stage is set here for a big win and we're hungry for it,''
said Cole (23 catches, 387 yards), who has accounted for 59 percent
of A&AMP;M's receiving yards, as well as all three touchdown grabs.
``We've fiddled around with some of these lesser teams and didn't
put them away like we should. But this week, focus won't be a
problem. We need that big win to get into that elite class of
teams, and we're in a great place to take advantage of this
chance.''
OPTIONAL TRIM HERE
</P>
<P>
   The place will be Kyle Field, where Slocum has a 2-2 career mark
against top-10 foes. The field will be covered with grass, a
surface that yielded close calls for the Cornhuskers last week
against Oklahoma State and last season against Missouri (45-38
overtime win). The crowd should be loud.
</P>
<P>
   Anything else you need, R.C.?
</P>
<P>
   ``A nice, soaking rain wouldn't be all bad,'' Slocum said.
``Let's slow that thing down into a mudhole.''
</P>
<P>
   A higher authority has yet to rule on that last request.
</P>
</TEXT>
