<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-JONES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES' OUTFIELDER JONES EVOKES COMPARISONS TO GREATS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The average 21-year-old baseball player usually goes
through some ups and downs. But Atlanta Braves outfielder Andruw
Jones seemed to go through the extremes this season.
</P>
<P>
   He started in a 4-for-40 swoon that got him demoted from the
leadoff spot, then finished the season as the youngest player in
major-league history to hit at least 20 homers and steal 20 bases
in one season.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Cox pulled him from a game against the Chicago
Cubs on July 21 because of his lack of hustle, then a month later
proclaimed him the greatest center fielder in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a hard time at the beginning,'' Jones acknowledged.
``But I've worked out of that, and I'm happy with the success I'm
having right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are, too, but still they expect bigger and better
things. Young talent like Jones, along with an incomparable
pitching rotation, is why baseball's team of the '90s expects to
continue that success into the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Cox was pulling Jones out of the game, he still was
comparing him to baseball's greats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who doesn't respect the game enough to give 100
percent on every play needs somebody to talk to him,'' Cox said at
the time. ``Unfortunately I've talked to him a lot. He's got to
grow up; it's as simple as that. No one is bigger than the game. I
didn't act that way when I was 21, and neither did Willie Mays or
Hank Aaron.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, even if it is premature, do put Jones in the same
class as Mays and Aaron, and they were relieved to see him respond
positively to Cox's heavy-handed discipline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt bad,'' Jones said. ``Nobody likes to get pulled out of
a game. I lost my focus. I went out there and apologized for what I
did.''
</P>
<P>
   He also finished the season hitting .274 with 30 homers, 91 runs
batted in and 27 stolen bases. Aaron, at the same age, hit .314
with 27 homers, 106 RBI and three stolen bases. Ken Griffey Jr. hit
.327 with 22 homers and 100 RBI. Mays was in the military.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones' defense is what impresses most, and he's expected to
win the first of many Gold Gloves this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably one of the best center fielders in the game
today,'' Reds bench coach Denis Menke said. ``He makes all the
plays look easy. He reminds me of Devon White. He's one of those
players that you say, `Well, we've got something for quite a few
years.' I don't know of too many others who are any better.''
</P>
<P>
   The offense, already pretty good, should only get better, and
the Braves think they have a superstar who could one day put
together the kind of season Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa did this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't call myself a home-run hitter,'' Jones said. ``I do
whatever I can to help the team win. If I need to hit a home run, I
hit a home run. If somebody makes a mistake, you hit the home runs.
But I'm not like McGwire or Sosa or (Andres) Galarraga; I can't hit
them every day. I can, but I don't look to do that. I just go out
and do my game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
