<DOCNO> NYT19981009.0419 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9361 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXAS-OU-TEX     10-09 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-OU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS-OU THE BIG GAME _ JUST NOT NATIONALLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every player and coach who has taken part in a Texas-Oklahoma
game at the Cotton Bowl say the same thing. The rivalry is
unmatched in their experience in excitement, emotion and
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   ``OU weekend is unique, and it's not comparable to any other
games,'' Longhorns senior linebacker Dusty Renfro said. ``It's a
neutral site, and each team has the same number of fans. It's
always such a battle because of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each team is going to play above their heads no matter what
their records or rankings are.''
</P>
<P>
   Fair enough. But Texas enters today's game with a 3-2 (1-1 Big
12) record; Oklahoma is 2-2 (0-1). Neither team has received a vote
in either poll this week, which reflects the lack of national
clout.
</P>
<P>
   Former Oklahoma coach Barry Switzer, who has been advising
Sooners coach John Blake, won't make be makin' the scene today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the same anymore,'' Switzer told the ``Austin
American-Statesman,'' when asked about the Texas-Oklahoma rivalry.
``There was a time when one team would be No. 1 in the country and
the other would be No. 2. Both OU and Texas had national
prestige.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC Sports passed on carrying the game as a regional telecast,
the first time since 1989 the game won't be televised by a national
network. However, more people could see the game because it will
air on the Big 12's syndicated regional network. That telecast will
be available in 25.5 million homes, including markets such as
Boston, Detroit and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the kids care about that stuff,'' Texas coach
Mack Brown said of the TV situation. ``When you get out there to
play, the kids don't know who is watching it on TV. Our kids tried
hard last Saturday night against Iowa State, and it was on
pay-per-view.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does matter is that these kids were raised watching Texas
and Oklahoma.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Texas-Oklahoma _ or, if you prefer, Oklahoma-Texas _ is
still a Big Game around these parts, even if it doesn't have the
sizzle in national circles. College football fans are more likely
to ask about the outcome of the Tennessee-Georgia and UCLA-Arizona
games before seeking a score from Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anyone under 25 years of age has a very different view
of Texas-Oklahoma,'' said Chris Fowler, host of ESPN's ``College
GameDay'' preview show. ``I'm old enough to know what that game
means, and that's one of the games on my list that I'd like to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the national scene, Texas-Oklahoma is an afterthought. But
I think things are cyclical and there will be a time when
Texas-Oklahoma returns to national prominence.''
</P>
<P>
   And Texas-Oklahoma is not alone. The Florida State-Miami game is
not one of the top five games on tap for today, either. ``Who would
have thought that possible?'' Fowler said.
</P>
<P>
   This decade has contributed to a drop-off in the national
profile of the Texas-Oklahoma series. Counting today, the teams
have entered the Cotton Bowl with a combined winning percentage of
.631. In no other decade has that number been as low.
</P>
<P>
   The best decade for the series was the 1970s. From 1970-79, the
Longhorns and Sooners entered the game with a combined 62-4-1
record, a winning percentage of .925. In the '70s, on eight
occasions both teams were ranked and six times both were
undefeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know when I was at Texas in the early '70s, it didn't get
any bigger than that,'' Texas Tech coach Spike Dykes said. ``It was
really a big deal. I think it's still a showcase game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those games you look forward to because it's been
a rivalry for so long,'' Renfro said. It's probably the biggest
game for each team every year. There's a lot of testosterone
flowing. It's pretty intense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just going to be an all-out brawl for 60 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown was Oklahoma's offensive coordinator in 1984, so he will
experience the rivalry from both sides when he descends the Cotton
Bowl ramp shortly before noon.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Barry (Switzer) hired me, he said, `You need to
understand there is one thing that is really important at Oklahoma,
and that's to beat Texas,''' Brown remembered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
