<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9362 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-PREVIEW-TEX     10-09 1497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-PREVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALLAS HOPING TO SCRIPT A BLOCKBUSTER ENDING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Hollywood ending, that's all Stars '98 lacked.
</P>
<P>
   While basking in the silence of a Stars locker room seconds
removed from a Western Conference Finals-ending, season-ending loss
to Detroit in Game 6 in June, team owner Tom Hicks realized how
close he was to having himself a blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   A seemingly well-scripted season simply lacked an
audience-grabbing, good-guys-win finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I basically saw that we weren't able to match up with
Detroit,'' Hicks said. ``I went to Jim Lites and Bob Gainey and
said: `Bring me a proposal on what will make us match up with
Detroit.'''
</P>
<P>
   To ensure an ending fitting of a Presidents' Cup winner, general
manager Gainey and team president Lites suggested the Stars needed
two additional leading men, a Tom Cruise-like headliner and a
Steven Segal-like enforcer.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks opened his checkbook and signed on to almost $8 million in
additional payroll to go with $31.7 million he spent last season.
</P>
<P>
   He added ``Golden'' Brett Hull to a cast already peppered with
box-office draws like Mike Modano and Joe Nieuwendyk and then
signed brawler Brent Severyn to safeguard his investment.
</P>
<P>
   Like adding Matt Damon to a cast that already had Leonardo
DiCaprio, the Stars have a possible ``Titanic'' brewing this
season. Then again, if another meltdown happens, this season might
play like ``Waterworld''.
</P>
<P>
   The highly anticipated production premieres tonight at Reunion
Arena, and critics already acclaim that Dallas has assembled an
all-star cast capable of bringing back NHL's Oscar _ a Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, the pieces are in place to win a Stanley Cup,'' Gainey
said. ``In competition, though, things do not always unfold
according to script. A blockbuster has a lot of elements _ plot
twists, intrigue, hardship.''
Casting call
</P>
<P>
   Gainey began punching up the cast for this season July 3.
</P>
<P>
   Stars defenseman Derian Hatcher remembers preparing to tee off
that day when his cell phone rang.
</P>
<P>
   His agent had news. Hatcher had a new teammate. The Stars had
signed Hull.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started thinking: `Now we can go do it,''' Hatcher said. ``I
think we would've made a run anyway, but the acquisition of him put
us that much closer.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting ``that much closer'' cost Hicks $17 million, a price tag
that comes standard with established box-office draws like a
``Golden'' Brett for three years. Severyn took another $425,000.
Hicks spent another $4.5 million to keep his supporting cast from
heading elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Craig Ludwig and forward Guy Carbonneau had already
been re-signed, and deals with defenseman Darryl Sydor and forward
Jamie Langenbrunner followed.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' leading man, Modano, had been satiated with a
six-year, $43.5 million contract late last season.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks spent a lot on talent this summer. The Stars have a
payroll around $39 million as a result.
</P>
<P>
   The budget is set. Hicks said that's as big as it gets.
</P>
<P>
   A few critics evoke comparisons to a certain off-Broadway act
called the New York Rangers. That $45 million production failed to
land a playoff berth last season.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Stars have back-to-back Central Division championships
and added a Presidents' Trophy and a Western Conference finals
berth last season.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks has a break-even point for this season, too, a longer run
than last.
</P>
<P>
   A profit is highly unlikely until the new arena opens in 2000,
he said, when it's hoped a championship will pay off with sales of
luxury boxes and season-ticket packages.
</P>
<P>
   That's why he decided to field a winner at a loss. A happy
ending will provide an avenue to draw in a nontraditional hockey
fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it my investment,'' Hicks said. ``I realized that this
town loves a winner; look at the Cowboys and the Rangers. So I
decided to give them a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   It's up to Stars coach Ken Hitchcock to turn the ``pieces'' into
a winner from his rink-side director's chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the six-month battle you have to go through,''
Hitchcock said. ``If you ever want to the opportunity to play a
team like them sometime down the road when it's on the line, you
are going to have to get a lot better during the regular season.''
The storyline: us vs. `them'
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-nine million dollars, six months, 82 games and likely two
playoff series just to get another shot at ``them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Stars locker room, ``them'' needs no explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Back-to-back Stanley Cup champion Detroit has played Lex Luthor
to Dallas' Superman, Darth Vader to Dallas' Luke Skywalker, Dr.
Evil to Dallas' Austin Powers.
</P>
<P>
   A 3-6-2 record against a deeper, stronger, better Red Wings
lineup last season frustrated them. Another winless season at Joe
Louis Arena buried them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we added Hull, it had nothing to do with beating Detroit.
People will say that, but it had nothing to do with it,'' Hitchcock
said. ``It had to do with our viewing of the 100 or so hockey games
we played last year. We had a very difficult time in long stretches
with offensive production. ... That deficiency, which was there
during the regular season, became more magnified in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it be the failed ending or an inability to match up with
``them,'' Hull is here and so far the reviews have been dazzling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Stanley Cup goes through Dallas,'' Edmonton
president and general manager Glen Sather said. ``Dallas
strengthened themselves the most. Look on paper and Dallas
seemingly solved a lot of problems that they had.''
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the Stars return two proven goal scorers in Modano and
Nieuwendyk and added another in Hull.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the Stars return goalie Ed Belfour and a defense that
allowed an NHL-best 1.88 goals against average.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the Stars added an enforcer that everybody considered
so critical for the long-term health of the team.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the Stars added a blend of depth and pizzazz to match,
if not surpass, ``them.''
</P>
<P>
   So then does anything less than a Stanley Cup become a failure?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can say that,'' Hicks said. ``In any sport,
you have to take small steps.''
The final script
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig says that before him waits a group of players better than
most he played with in Montreal, a big compliment considering that
group won a Stanley Cup in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a contender,'' he says of his Stars teammates. ``We're
not a championship team ... yet.''
</P>
<P>
   To go from being an extraordinary array of talent to a Stanley
Cup champion, he explains, requires a certain touch, the steps that
Hicks speaks of.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia had plenty of talent last season, and lacked
chemistry to turn that into a Stanley Cup. Big-bucks forwards Eric
Lindros and Chris Gratton were unable to turn a 95-point season
into anything better than a first-round playoff loss.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado has talent that was good enough to win a Stanley Cup in
1996, and has lacked only toughness to return to Stanley Cup form.
Coach Marc Crawford had bailed from frustration by 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas had a lot of talent last season, and lacked health to
turn that into a Stanley Cup season. The Stars lost 318 man games
to injury last season, including long absences by guys like Modano
and Nieuwendyk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Modano and Nieuwendyk getting hurt, that may happen again,''
Sather said. ``Bryan Marchment is still out there lurking, waiting
in the wings.''
</P>
<P>
   Marchment sidelined Nieuwendyk less than 20 minutes into last
season's playoff opener with a torn anterior cruciate ligament.
Many, like Sather, felt that kept Dallas from a Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Minus Nieuwendyk, the Stars lacked enough firepower to topple
the Red Empire in a Western Conference Finals showdown. Modano,
Carbonneau and Jere Lehtinen accounted for six of the Stars' 11
goals in that series.
</P>
<P>
   Even with casting changes, a few questions will need to be
answered in the season-long script.
</P>
<P>
   How will Modano blend with Hull? Will the Stars be able to avoid
injury? Can the second line score in the playoffs? Will Belfour be
Superman in the playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   And the real cliffhanger, will it all be enough to win a Stanley
Cup?
Cue the ending
</P>
<P>
   If Hitchcock learned anything last season, it's this:
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are one step away, you might as well be 100 steps away
because that one step will keep you away forever,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   While bringing in Hull and Severyn has brought them closer,
final reviews will depend a lot on the ending.
</P>
<P>
   So how far away are they from producing a blockbuster instead of
a bust?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the hard thing to define,'' Gainey said. ``Maybe, the
better question is how far away were we. We were, last year, too
far away.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time the fans saw their Stars, they were limping off
into the sunset without the Cup, without the girl and without
defeating the Red Empire.
</P>
<P>
   End of season. Roll credits.
</P>
<P>
   The Cup, the girl and the empire still waits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 2052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
