<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SHUTDOWN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS PASSES STOPGAP FUNDING BILL TO KEEP GOVERNMENT RUNNING
THROUGH MONDAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a repeat of the stalemate that led to government
shutdowns three years ago, Congress was forced Friday to pass a
stopgap funding bill to keep federal agencies running through
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency measure, approved unanimously in the House and by
voice vote in the Senate, is necessary because Republican leaders
and the White House have been unable to reach agreement on a final
package of 1999 spending measures.
</P>
<P>
   Although both sides continued to express hope that their
differences over hundreds of items could be settled during weekend
negotiations, each staked out hard-line positions that, if
unresolved, could lead to a partial government closing early next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Nine days into the 1999 fiscal year, the Republican-led Congress
has passed only six of the 13 major appropriations bills needed to
fund government departments and agencies.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to finish up and begin campaigning for re-election,
lawmakers are trying to roll at least a half-dozen of the remaining
measures into one catchall measure known as an omnibus bill.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; But President Clinton has threatened to veto the legislation
if it does not include his demand for about $4 billion in
additional education funding. The money would be used to help hire
more teachers, remodel and build more schools.
</P>
<P>
   GOP members insist on holding the line on new spending. Rep.
Harold Rogers, R-Ky., described Clinton's requests as ``frills''
that could not be paid for under the strict spending limits agreed
to in the 1997 balanced budget agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP also accuses Clinton of trying to tap into the fiscal
1988 surplus to pay for his programs. Republicans prefer to use the
surplus to fund tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance at the White House with Democratic leaders,
Clinton blasted the Republicans as architects of a ``do-nothing''
Congress, noting that they had killed tobacco legislation, campaign
finance reform, a new minimum wage law and the so-called patients`
bill of rights that Democrats had tried to pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``This budget is purely and simply a test of whether after nine
months of doing nothing we are going to do the right thing about
our children's future,'' he said, adding that lawmakers ``should
not go home until they pass a budget that will strengthen our
public schools for the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he was determined to use the 1999 education
spending to ``make a down payment'' on hiring 100,000 new teachers
and reducing class size in the early grades.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans responded that the president was simply trying to
play up differences over education matters to ``invigorate'' the
Democratic Party's base in the upcoming elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not willing to increase spending so that the American
people's surplus is spent by this government,'' said House Majority
Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders also stressed that they are ``committed'' to
avoiding a repeat of the two government shutdowns. The GOP got most
of the political blame for those closings, and suffered some
setbacks in the 1996 elections because of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to work tomorrow. We may work Sunday. We are
going to stay here until we get the people's business done,'' said
House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress had failed to pass the short-term spending measure
Friday, most government operations would have come to a halt at
midnight when another stopgap budget measure, passed two weeks ago,
was due to expire.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress fails to reach an agreement with Clinton over the
weekend, another short-term measure would have to be approved to
keep agencies operating beyond Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Although the standoff Friday ensued because of a dispute over
education, other issues are also standing in the way of a final
spending agreement. They include funding and reform measures for
the International Monetary Fund, anti-abortion and
anti-environmental provisions, disagreements over how the 2000
Census should be conducted, and arguments over more than 150 items
contained in the individual spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some lawmakers have complicated the negotiations by
trying to attach favored provisions to the spending bills, moves
that could create more barriers between the White House and
Republican leaders.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Texas Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, wants language
added to the omnibus measure that would prevent the federal
government from claiming a large share of settlement money that
Texas and other states might get from tobacco companies. Billions
are at stake, but Hutchison's language would limit Washington's
take to $1.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   A proposal by Rep. John Murtha, D-Pa., would make changes to the
military pension system to make it easier for people who had served
for 20 years to get an increased pension, a measure that would add
millions to future government outlays.
</P>
<P>
   On the more ``absurd side,'' as one congressional official put
it, is language that Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.,
wants to add that would delay the start of duck-hunting season in
his state by a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   While lawmakers prepared to dicker over the spending bill
language and other weightier policy matters, government agencies
were preparing themselves for the possibility of a shutdown next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Bosses dusted off their emergency closing plans, which they used
during the two partial shutdowns in late 1995 and early 1996, and
began making decisions about which employees would have to report
to work and which ones would be furloughed until spending matters
are settled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep hearing them say, `We're not going to shut the
government down,' but I'm not sure any of us really believe that,''
said one Justice Department official. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 2102EDT &QL; 
