<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNOBLAUCH CAN'T ARGUE THIS CALL: HE'S NOTORIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Yankee second baseman Chuck Knoblauch was greeted as
a hero throughout Ohio Friday. The Akron Beacon Journal put him on
Page 1 and named him Cleveland's MVP of Game 2 of the American
League Championship Series. Fans at Jacobs Field gave him a
standing ovation when he was introduced during pregame ceremonies
last night. Knoblauch got more applause than first-ball tosser Bob
Feller (78 miles per hour on the black _ not bad for a 79-year-old
righthander).
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch made himself a national joke Wednesday night when he
stood and argued with an umpire while Cleveland's winning run
scored from first base on a bunt in the 12th inning of a playoff
game at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   He was the first batter of last night's game. Naturally. There's
a baseball adage about the player who makes the exceptional play
that ends an inning always coming to bat to start the next inning.
It must work the same way when you are the central figure in a
hardball controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch got a second resounding ovation when he led off the
game. It was sheer sarcasm, enough to infuriate any proud
professional. And so he ripped a single to left on the second pitch
and came around to score on Bernie Williams's two-out single.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the first, Knoblauch handled the first ball hit
by Kenny Lofton. It was as if the diamond god wanted him to shake
all the jitters in a single inning.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch's nonplay is already part of baseball folklore. On the
controversial Travis Fryman 12th-inning bunt, Knoblauch elected to
stand at first base and argue with the umpire that there had been
interference on the throw. Meanwhile, Enrique Wilson staggered
around the bases and swam across home plate.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch could not have known what was in store. He was in
total denial after the game, saying he would do the same thing
again if given the chance. He wanted to talk only about the
injustice of umpire Ted Hendry's noncall.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the avalanche. Before the Yankee charter touched down
in Cleveland, there were tabloid newspapers on the streets of New
York with headlines screaming, ``BLAUCH-HEAD.'' He was slaughterd
on the airwaves. The vaunted New York Times led its game account by
comparing Knoblauch with (gulp) Bill Buckner.
</P>
<P>
   Yeesh. You know it's bad when they're dropping a Buckner on your
head.
</P>
<P>
   A contrite Knoblauch met with the national media at Thursday's
workout. He said, ``I screwed up.'' He apologized more times than
Bill Clinton. But there was no way to erase the damning video.
</P>
<P>
   The replay has been aired a thousand times. It never gets any
better for Knoblauch. There he is, standing on first base, arm
outstretched, yelling at Hendry while the ball dribbles toward
right field and Wilson flops around the bases.
</P>
<P>
   It is the cardinal sin of sports, something we teach our kids
every season, every year. You keep playing until the whistle blows,
until the clock stops, until somebody calls time out. Play now,
argue the call later.
</P>
<P>
   Little League coaches will never forget Knoblauch. They will
cite his play the same way DARE police officers talk about famous
rock and movie stars who throw away careers for drugs. (itals)This
guy was famous and had everything. See what happened to him? Don't
let it happen to you.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   The Knoblauch gaffe is offensive for the same reason we hate to
see immature Chris Canty celebrating a tackle while the live
football sits on the ground next to him, begging to be scooped up.
Keep playing until the play is over. Argue and celebrate later.
</P>
<P>
   Yankee manager Joe Torre was compelled to hold a rare pregame
meeting in an effort to get his players' minds off the Game 2
finish. Knoblauch has to be hoping his teammates will get him off
the hook.
</P>
<P>
   If the Yankees go on to lose the series, Knoblauch no doubt will
take his place alongside Fred ``Bonehead'' Merkle, Mickey Owens,
and our own Buckner in Baseball's Hall of Shame. But if the Yanks
beat Cleveland, as they should, Knoblauch becomes merely a footnote
and a teaching tool for those who coach America's youth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
