<SLUG> BC-MEN'S-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Men's Wearhouse Drops Acquisition   By Carol Emert  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Men's Wearhouse yesterday said it has dropped plans to buy Moore's
Retail Group of Canada after a steep decline in the Fremont
discounter's stock price.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Men's Wearhouse, which operates 414 discount clothing stores,
said in August it would acquire the 112-store Canadian chain by
issuing 2.4 million new shares and assuming $57.4 million in
Moore's debt.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was valued at $130 million at the time. But Men's
Wearhouse shares have dropped by more than half from a high of
$36.88 in July to $16.13 yesterday, scuttling the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Men's Wearhouse shares tend to be volatile because the company
grows largely through acquisitions, a strategy that investors
consider risky, said an analyst who follows the stock but who
declined to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Men's Wearhouse, the nation's top menswear discounter,
rose $1.13 yesterday on news that the talks with Moore's had been
terminated.
</P>
<P>
   The analyst said he expects Moore's and Men's Wearhouse to
return to the bargaining table within a year or so. The combination
is attractive because it would give Men's Wearhouse its first
manufacturing capability and a large presence in Canada, the
analyst said.
</P>
<P>
   A company spokesman, Neal Rosen, said executives had not
discussed the possibility of a future deal.
</P>
<P>
   Men's Wearhouse shares have also been hit by fears that an
economic downturn could dampen demand for men's suits. But the
analyst said Men's Wearhouse tends to do well during recessions,
stealing market share from higher priced department stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``This stock (decline) reflects something significantly worse
than reality,'' the analyst said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
