<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTANA ON TOP OF ITS GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They are the University of Montana. In the world
of Division I-AA, that isn't just a mark of success, it's one of
supremacy. It's five straight playoff appearances, a national
championship in 1995 and 12 straight winning seasons. It's the
place to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to simulate the University of Montana,'' Cal
State Northridge coach Ron Ponciano said. ``So do we.''
</P>
<P>
   Montana wins. In the conference, on a national level and in the
postseason. But it's so much more.
</P>
<P>
   It's chartering a flight from Missoula, Mont., to Southern
California instead of flying commercially, a reward for averaging
17,988 fans per game last season. It's people in the malls wearing
nothing but maroon on football Saturdays, and bar-room talk solely
about Montana football.
</P>
<P>
   It's 500 or so fans making the trip from Big Sky country to CSUN
for today's crucial Big Sky Conference game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at Nebraska (playing) for two years and it's just like a
miniature Nebraska,'' CSUN offensive coordinator Rob Phenicie said.
``Game day, it's great. You go out on the field and there's kind of
a roar and then you get to the line of scrimmage and (the noise)
just picks up. Then after the play it dies down a little bit and
you get back to the line and it picks up again. I'm sitting
upstairs saying, `Man, this is great.'''
</P>
<P>
   The transition from also-ran to Montana-type stature won't
happen with one win, but a nice possibility presents itself to No.
23 CSUN (3-1, 2-0 Big Sky) in No. 18 Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Not only would a win entrench the Matadors atop the Big Sky
standings and turn heads nationally, it would leave the Grizzlies
(3-2, 1-1) needing a five-game winning streak to keep alive its
postseason hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the younger guys don't realize what the game is and
how important it is,'' CSUN senior receiver Drew Hill said.
``People will recognize us after we beat Montana. It's going to
symbolize our domination in the league and how dominant we can
become. It's bigger than the Eastern Washington game, bigger than
the Northern Arizona game.''
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't the case 15 years ago. The only thing people knew
about Montana was its rugged beauty, its inspiring vastness and its
lack of a football power. Grizzlies were things you brought home as
a trophy, not the team you feared.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to 1986, Montana had boasted just eight winning seasons
since World War II. Then Washington-Grizzly Stadium opened on Oct.
18, 1986, with a 38-31 win against Idaho State. It took eight years
before Montana lost there, and a power was built. The Grizzlies
haven't had a losing season since.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the epitome of a I-AA program now,'' Ponciano said.
``There's no question they are, but it wasn't long ago when Montana
couldn't beat Montana State. Everybody looks at what they've got
because they've had success, so everyone looks and says, `What do
they do?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The stadium _ and the winning _ aided in the recruitment of
better players. Kids stay home and play football now instead of
going away, and the excitement from getting the community involved
in the construction of the stadium lured fans into the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often it's a lot easier to get to the top than to stay
there,'' third-year Montana coach Mick Dennehy said. ``It's been a
program that we've been proud of, worked hard in developing,
graduated kids and fortunately been at the top or near the top of
the league. I don't think there's any magical formula or recruiting
ingredient except recruiting the right athlete.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
