A9433 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EAGLES-COX     10-09 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EAGLES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aerospace forerunner Engle visits museum
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If you didn't know him, you would never guess the
guy ambling casually through the Air Force Museum on Friday in a
plaid shirt, blue jeans and wide leather belt was one of America's
aerospace pioneers.
</P>
<P>
   Joe H. Engle was acting like a guy who just likes airplanes. He
was as happy talking about his little Piper L-4 Cub as he was the
X-15 rocket plane he flew beyond the edge of space, or the space
shuttle Columbia he piloted completely by hand, from orbit to
landing _ something no other astronaut has done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like flying Cubs, space shuttles and everything I can get
into in between,'' the retired Air Force major general said with an
easy laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Engle was visiting the museum as a participant in the
``Gathering of Eagles'' symposium. Sponsored by the Air Force
Museum Foundation and the International Association of Eagles, the
event brought 14 legendary aviators to speak here Friday and today.
</P>
<P>
   Speakers ranged from World War II aces to astronauts such as
Engle and retired Air Force Gen. Thomas Stafford, whose Gemini and
Apollo flights included commanding the Apollo 10 moon-orbiting
mission.
</P>
<P>
   While both Engle and Stafford are retired from spaceflight, both
are also still deeply involved in America's space program. Stafford
heads an independent review and assessment team for the
International Space Station; Engle is his deputy.
</P>
<P>
   The space station is the next big event on NASA's schedule after
the upcoming space shuttle mission that will take John Glenn on his
second space flight. He became the first American to orbit the
Earth in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Both Stafford, 68, and Engle, 65, support Glenn's flight. Both
think the aging research Glenn hopes to aid is a worthwhile effort.
But Stafford thinks one of the chief benefits will be the dramatic
demonstration ``that if you're over 40 and you stay in shape, you
can have a long, active life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gathering of Eagles has been an annual event since 1982 for
the Air Force's command and staff college at Maxwell Air Force Base
in Alabama, but this is its first year at the museum. Museum
officials hope to make it an annual event.
</P>
<P>
   Engle, a founding member of the event, said offering it at the
museum was ``an outstanding move. If it's done here, it can really
be a benefit to aviation . . . with all the core aviation history
and tradition here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
