r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  PM-PAPERS-SFCHRON &LR;      10-09 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 PM-PAPERS-SFCHRON  
 Newspapers' Web Readers Shanghaied   By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Readers attempting to access a dozen major newspaper Web sites _
including the San Jose Mercury News and San Francisco Examiner _
did not get news, weather and sports this week. Instead, they got
the ramblings of a former Ku Klux Klan leader and ex-con.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The online deception _ which lasted throughout the week _ wasn't
the result of hacking, but of legally registering Web addresses
that resembled the newspapers' names. For example, the Philadelphia
Inquirer's Web site is at  &LR; www.phillynews.com/inquirer; &LR;  the false
site was at  &LR; www.philadelphiainquirer.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  A shadowy Lake Tahoe man, who calls himself ``Ed Marlow'' and
claims to be a computer systems and Internet technician, said he
registered virtual addresses this month that include part or all of
the newspapers' names. He then redirected those addresses to
``Stormfront,'' a white nationalist site with links to other racist
pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just believe that all points of view should be accessible on
the Net, including those supporting the heritage and values of the
founding White (sic) majority in America,'' Marlow, 31, said in an
e-mail interview yesterday. ``I am not a supremacist.''
</P>
<P>
   While many of the newspapers immediately vowed legal action to
stop the use of the bogus online addresses, the problem underscores
murky trademark-infringement rules for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   There is no law banning individuals or companies from securing
addresses affiliated with brand-name firms. The violated companies
have been forced to go to court to stop that practice.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``This is not a First Amendment case. It's a
trademark-infringement case,'' said Mark Kipnis, general counsel
for the Chicago Sun-Times, another of the papers hit by ``Marlow.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; On Monday, the paper was the first to discover the subterfuge.
It filed court papers on Wednesday, and obtained a temporary
restraining order Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a term for them _ parasites,'' said Doug Edwards,
online brand manager for the San Jose Mercury News. ``We have
referred the matter to our corporate attorneys.''
</P>
<P>
   The Examiner said it is also pursuing legal action.
</P>
<P>
   Other newspapers targeted by ``Marlow'' were the Albuquerque
Tribune, Arizona Republic, Atlanta Constitution, Cleveland Plain
Dealer, Edmonton Sun, London Daily Telegraph, &UR;  &LR; Pittsburgh
Post-Gazette, Salt Lake Tribune and St. Louis Post-Dispatch.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle was not affected.
</P>
<P>
   Don Black, who produces Stormfront, denied any involvement in
the incidents, but he said he knows ``Marlow.'' He said he received
a temporary injunction notice yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've requested that it be stopped,'' said the West Palm Beach,
Fla., resident. ``There's obviously a trademark issue involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Black, 45, is a former Ku Klux Klan leader who learned how to
use computers while serving time in a federal prison in Texas for
planning the military overthrow of the tiny Caribbean island of
Dominica. He created Stormfront, which preaches ``White Pride World
Wide,'' in March 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marlow,'' who said he registered the newspaper names as ``a
test of Internet traffic,'' said he ceased use of the names as soon
as he was contacted by the newspapers' attorneys. ``I am compelled
to follow the laws of the court,'' he said in an e-mail interview.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a flurry of legal maneuvering by the newspapers, an
episode mimicking ``Stormfront'' could be repeated, legal experts
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a major problem for corporations who are trying to
protect trademarks,'' said Philip Sbarbaro, chief litigation
counsel for Network Solutions, the Herndon, Va., company that
registers the most popular Web addresses. ``Without a law, all a
company can do is file a trademark-infringement suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, an individual or company can quickly and easily buy the
two-year rights to any available online address for $70 at
 &LR; www.internic.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   As a result, companies are scrambling to register as many
Internet addresses with variations of their names as possible to
protect their trademarks online.
</P>
<P>
   NSI has a dispute policy that allows companies to challenge _
and remove _ Web sites that piggyback off their sites for
commercial gain. However, NSI does not impose a waiting period to
check out the commercial intent of Web registrants.
</P>
<P>
   The unpoliced dispensing of Web addresses has resulted in some
infamous sites masquerading as legitimate sites.
</P>
<P>
   An adult-oriented business called Whitehouse.com displays
pornographic images of President Clinton and Hillary Clinton. (The
official Oval Office Web address is  &LR; www.whitehouse.gov &LR; .) The
incident has driven U.S. Senator Lauch Faircloth, R-N.C., to draft
legislation that would prohibits private parties from using
government agency names for ``stealth'' commercial Web sites.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
