<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9436 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-NLCS-ADVANCE-BOS &LR;      10-09 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-ADVANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MADDUX THE MASTER TAKES THE MOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Why sing the praises of an understudy when the
featured artist has yet to take the stage? Before crowning San
Diego's Kevin Brown king of the postseason, let's check out the
performance of the man generally regarded as the best pitcher of
his generation.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Padres came home with a 2-0 lead over the Braves
in the best-of-seven National League Championship Series following
Brown's three-hit, 11-strikeout, 3-0 masterpiece Thursday, the
chief topic of conversation here Friday revolved around Atlanta ace
Greg Maddux, who will start Saturday's survival test. Brown was
superb. But now comes The Master. And Maddux wants to retain that
eminence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pride,'' he said. ``You want to win. You always want to
win, even if it's April or May. I don't think anybody wants to be
embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially not now, Maddux's favorite time of the year.
``Playoffs never get old, never,'' he said. ``It just doesn't. It's
better than Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a late-season slump that probably cost him an
unprecedented fifth Cy Young Award, Maddux racked up another
splendid season, going 18-9 with a 2.22 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Tom) Glavine won 20 games this year,'' said San Diego hit man
Tony Gwynn, referring to Atlanta's Game 2 loser. ``The only
difference is that Maddux adds 7 more miles an hour to his
fastball. He can beat you with his movement and location. The
catcher sets up and he's going to hit the glove. You don't see that
a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, we're up, 2-0, in the series. But we're going to have to
concentrate just as hard against him as we did against (John)
Smoltz and Glavine. You know it's going to be tough. You know
you're not going to go out and score six or seven runs off him.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux faced the Padres once in the regular season, lasting six
innings in a 5-1 loss Aug. 12. That came during his late-season
malaise. But in winning the Division Series clincher against the
Cubs, 6-2, Saturday, he reestablished his credentials as a money
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say I was back to my old self,'' said Maddux. ``But
I feel good about how I'm throwing now. For a while, I didn't
locate as well as I'd like, but I'm pleased at how I've been
throwing lately. It doesn't matter. What does is how I pitch on
Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux is a creature of rhythm and composure. Extremes _ either
high or low _ do not affect him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never felt I was out of sync,'' he said of his slump, in
which he lost three of his last four starts and was 6-7 after the
All-Star break. ``But I do think over a short period of time you
can have two or three games that inflate things. They (the media)
make a big deal out of everything. You expect it. It's the norm. No
matter which way you pitch, it's magnified. That's just how it
is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres aren't looking at Maddux through a magnifying glass.
They see him as he is _ a stopper who could halt the momentum they
have gained.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew coming into these playoffs that we were going to face
the best staff in baseball,'' said manager Bruce Bochy. ``We feel
very fortunate to have won two games. But we still have to face
Maddux. We know for sure that Maddux pitched well against the Cubs
in the division playoffs. Looks like he's getting on track. Maddux
is throwing well now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this shows you how good the Atlanta Braves are _
Maddux in Game 3. We can't change anything. We have to keep going
in the direction that we're going. We've got to continue to pitch
the ball, play defense, and hopefully get a hit every now and
then.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn says he will do what he normally does against Maddux _ try
to get a good pitch and drive it someplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our offense is still sputtering, but who cares as long as we
keep winning ballgames?'' he said. ``Guys can hit .220, .185, and
so on. Nobody remembers that if you keep winning. I'm surprised we
had to wait till Game 3 before seeing Maddux. But it doesn't hurt.
With all these guys, you have to really battle. You've got to
really concentrate and pay attention. With Glavine, we did a real
good job and made him throw a lot of pitches. And with Maddux, it's
the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux will face Sterling Hitchcock, who conquered Houston's
Randy Johnson in his last outing, the Game 4 clincher of their
Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no pressure on me,'' Hitchcock said. ``Remember, I'm
not supposed to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody else is when Maddux takes the mound.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
