<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, Md., Fla., Calif.)   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Battling It Out on the Links Is All in a Day's, uh, Work
</P>
<P>
   General Electric's official line is that while John F. Welch
loves to talk about the company's success, he keeps his golf game
private. A similar message comes from Sun Microsystems about its
chairman, Scott G. McNealy.
</P>
<P>
   But put your ear to the fairway, and you will hear more than the
thwack of golf balls. The two chief executives apparently learned
from Golf Digest last May that they were among the nation's top
golfing CEOs _ Welch has a 3.8 handicap index and McNealy a
slightly better 3.2. They agreed to play in Nantucket, and Golf
World reported that Welch emerged victorious.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed for details, the folks at Sun suggest that patience is
in order, with an announcement likely to emerge soon. Might it be a
copy of the scorecard? Not likely. Seems a ``gimme'' that the two
men cut a business deal on the links.
</P>
<P>
   That probably left little time to talk about the Big Question:
Who will succeed Welch, who turns 65 in 2000? But Robert Slater,
who has just written his third book about the GE chief, is betting
on James McNerney, head of GE Aircraft Engines.
</P>
<P>
   Slater says Welch's personal choice would be Robert Wright, the
NBC boss, but he figures that the final decision ``will come down
to age'' and go to the younger McNerney.
</P>
<P>
   _ ADAM BRYANT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but Can He Whistle Dixie?
</P>
<P>
   Who was that bearded man trading quips with his fellow basses in
the Dallas Symphony Chorus last month at the Morton H. Meyerson
Family Weekend of Concerts in the Morton H. Meyerson Symphony
Center in Dallas? Why, none other than Morton H. Meyerson.
</P>
<P>
   Meyerson, after decades as Ross Perot's corporate right-hand man
(and left-hand man, too, while Perot went off chasing the
presidency), retired from the Perot Systems computer-services
company last year to pursue his passion for music.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, he went on a European tour with the Morris Beachy
Singers, a University of Texas alumni chorus. And the centerpiece
of the Web site for his 2M Companies (www.2m.com), a group of small
technology and real-estate ventures, is a page with audio clips of
performances by the Dallas Symphony and its chorus (Tchaikovsky),
and the university singing group (``Deep River'').
</P>
<P>
   Meyerson joins a cadre of business leaders adept with bows or
batons, including Norio Ohga, the Sony president and orchestral
conductor, and James Wolfensohn, the World Bank president and a
cellist.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALLEN R. MYERSON &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other Alums May Take the Hint
</P>
<P>
   Never one to shirk the limelight, Michael R. Bloomberg has
rounded off his gift-giving to Johns Hopkins University at an even
$100 million. Bloomberg, the colorful _ some say egotistical _
founder of Bloomberg LP, says he will add $45 million to the $55
million he contributed three years ago. That makes him the
``largest single donor by double'' to the Baltimore school, a
spokesman for Johns Hopkins said, adding that Bloomberg, head of
its $1.2 billion fund-raising drive, is ``putting his money where
his mouth is.''
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg says most of the new money will go to undergraduate
financial aid. ``Even though the economy is softening and markets
go down, we still have to educate kids,'' said the author of an
autobiography entitled ``Bloomberg by Bloomberg.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he gave a similarly high-minded reason for his
original gift, but couldn't help adding that the donation generated
``great publicity for my company and the university.''
</P>
<P>
   _ GERALDINE FABRIKANT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All These Hard Feelings!
</P>
<P>
   Seth Flam's golden parachute isn't so golden after all. Flam got
a $4.8 million severance deal when he resigned in March from FPA
Medical Management Inc., which he founded and which filed for
bankruptcy protection last year.
</P>
<P>
   That seemed enough to allow him to enjoy the suburban San Diego
mansion he had just bought for $3 million. But the company now says
it terminated the package in July after paying only $255,000. And
doctors left with unpaid bills are going after even that pittance.
... Sylvester Stallone has come under a lot of heat from nearby
residents _ including Madonna _ for agreeing to sell his 12-acre
estate in Miami's Coconut Grove section to a hotel chain for $24.7
million. But the deal is contingent on rezoning of the neighborhood
for commercial use _ and Miami Mayor Joe Carollo says the chances
for that are ``slim to none.''
</P>
<P>
   Stallone, who bought the estate for $8.4 million in 1993,
retorts that Carollo ``has been getting reports tinged with
neighborhood hysteria.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
