<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARDINAL HEALTH ACQUIRING ALLEGIANCE FOR $4.5 BILLION
</P>
<P>
   The wholesale drug distributor Cardinal Health agreed to buy the
hospital supply company Allegiance for $4.5 billion in stock and
assume $890 million of its debt.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was a rebound for Cardinal, which dropped its bid for
Bergen Brunswig after a federal judge ruled last summer that the
deal raised antitrust problems.
</P>
<P>
   HOSTILE BID SENDS AMP SHARES UP
</P>
<P>
   The aerospace and automotive parts maker Allied Signal plans to
proceed with its $9.7 billion hostile takeover bid for AMP despite
a federal judge's ruling Thursday that part of its purchase plan
was unlawful. Allied said it would appeal the ruling. Shares of AMP
have climbed to $41.3125 since the takeover was first announced on
Aug. 4.
</P>
<P>
   FUND'S LOSSES SAID TO CONTINUE
</P>
<P>
   The troubled hedge fund Long-Term Capital has suffered losses of
$200 million to $300 million in the two weeks since it was salvaged
by a Wall Street consortium. Such losses would amount to 3 percent
to 5 percent of the $3.6 billion rescue package arranged by 14
banks and brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
   NEW FORD LEADERS MAKING CHANGES
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Nasser, who becomes chief executive of Ford Motor next
year, and William Clay Ford Jr., who becomes chairman, have
announced that 27 senior executives will retire or change jobs at
the end of the year. The most significant change is the creation of
a new position, chief of staff. A longtime ally of Ford, Peter
Pestillo, was named to that job.
</P>
<P>
   PLAN TO BOLSTER PATIENT POWER DIES
</P>
<P>
   Legislation to give patients more power in dealing with
health-insurance companies died in Congress, a casualty of heavy
lobbying by the insurance industry and of the sex scandal that has
enveloped President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT TRIAL DELAYED FOUR DAYS
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge delayed the start of Microsoft's trial on
antitrust charges until Oct. 19, and ordered the company to comply
with the Justice Department's request to examine Microsoft's
financial records.
</P>
<P>
   VOLKSWAGEN ENDING HIRING SPREE
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen said that it did not plan to add employees next year,
ending a four-year hiring spree that increased the company's
worldwide work force by 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ENERGY-RICH KAZAKHSTAN THRIVING
</P>
<P>
   To the benefit of energy-rich Kazakhstan, as foreign investment
has drained from most emerging markets and crude-oil prices have
fallen, the Caspian Sea's stature as a prized oil property has
remained high.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA SEEKING AID FROM EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Rocked by its worst harvest in 45 years and a plummeting ruble,
Russia appealed for relief aid from the European Union. It has also
approached the United States and Canada for help.
</P>
<P>
   SECOND BANKRUPTCY FOR MODEM MAKER
</P>
<P>
   Hayes, the company that introduced the personal-computer modem
in 1981, filed for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of
the Federal Bankruptcy Code. It was the second time Hayes had
sought bankruptcy refuge in five years.
</P>
<P>
   PRATT SET TO CUT 2,000 WORKERS
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft engine maker Pratt &AMP; Whitney plans to eliminate
about 2,000 jobs in Connecticut and Florida, or about 6 percent of
its global work force, by the middle of 2000 in a bid to increase
profits and absorb a decline in production.
</P>
<P>
   MOODY'S MAY REDUCE RATINGS
</P>
<P>
   Japan's life insurers may see their credit ratings cut by
Moody's Investors Service in the near to intermediate term amid the
nation's weakened economy and stock market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
