<SLUG> BC-BLACK-LABOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK LABOR LEADERS, POLICY EXPERTS DISCUSS ECONOMIC CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; African-American labor leaders and policy experts met at
Harvard University Friday to discuss ways to increase living
standards and wages among US workers who would be jeopardized if
the global economic crisis spreads to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Co-sponsored by the Harvard Trade Union Project and the
Coalition of Black Trade Unionists, Friday's economic summit
brought together some 50 black union leaders who represent 16
million workers around the country. Also participating were
Harvard's &UR;  &LR;  Afro-American studies department and the university's &UR;  &LR; 
Institute of Politics.
</P>
<P>
   Friday Labor leaders and policy experts discussed the economic
crisis that has gripped much of the world &UR;  &LR; , and then called for
the creation of a multiracial political coalition to address the
concerns of blue collar and middle class workers who would &UR;  &LR; be hurt
in an economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a strange and precarious situation in the United
States,'' Bill Fletcher, education director at the AFL-CIO in
Washington, D.C., told participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Asian crisis has gotten worse and worse. We were told it
would be contained, but it has kept spreading like an ink stain on
a white shirt,'' Fletcher said. ``Now Brazil and other parts of
Latin America are in trouble. Capitalism is unraveling.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Participants of the meeting applauded organized labor
for &UR;  &LR; successfully fending off &UR;  &LR;  fast-track trade &UR;  &LR; legislation that
would have expanded the president's ability to quickly negotiate
trade treaties. Labor has long maintained that fast track
legislation would have promoted global trade without adequate wage,
safety and environmental provisions. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   They also called for greater cooperation among white, Latino,
Asian, and African-American labor leaders as well as grass-roots
religious, community and political groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the government's actions and policies have exacerbated
rather than alleviated the economic stresses of ordinary
families,'' noted William Julius Wilson, the Malcolm Wiener
professor of social policy at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson criticized trade policies that he said ``encourage the
pursuit of cheap labor in the global market place; monetary
policies that artificially raise interest rates and thereby lower
employment rates; tax policies that favor the truly wealthy; and
military spending that cuts into revenues that could be used for
social programs.''
</P>
<P>
   He urged participants to consider ways to develop a multiracial
political coalition that would generate national debate on such
issues and prompt public officials to consider the impact of
certain policies on American families.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is not whether to trade,'' Wilson said. ``We all
know that trade is important for the overall health and growth of
the economy. The question is how to trade.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 2159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
