<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARRINGTON WOULD BE WILLING TO NEGOTIATE WITH VAUGHN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Mo Vaughn wants to meet with John Harrington to talk about
his future with the Red Sox, the door is open.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, through an alleged friend, reportedly said this week
that he was disapointed to read that the Sox CEO intends to leave
the contract negotiations with the All-Star first baseman to
general manager Dan Duquette.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Red Sox do not care who makes the deal for them. If
Mo wants to do it in private with Harrington, fine. That's what
this reporter was told when he called Fenway Park Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Mo has a big charity dinner next week in Boston. Harrington will
be there. Duquette will be there. If Mo can't dial Fenway Park for
some reason to make an appointment with Harrington, he can do it at
the dinner next week.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington is not bashful about dealing with Vaughn. Last
offseason, he drove to Mo's house to discuss the future. The Sox
always assumed that Vaughn wanted one of his agents, Tom Reich, to
negotiate with Duquette. But although they prefer to have Duquette
negotiate, they are ready to do whatever it takes to re-sign
Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WBZ-TV, Channel 4, in Boston, which gave us the unsubstantiated
story that the Red Sox had a private detective trailing Vaughn last
year, now comes forward with a report that racist letters were
written to Vaughn. But the station offers no letters as proof. Mo
has been playing in Boston for eight years and this is the first
time he's gotten hate mail? Is he the only member of the
organization that gets this kind of mail? Is this supposed to mean
that Mo will opt to leave town because of the alleged hate mail?
How did Mo's parents get this hate mail? If they got it from Mo,
why would he show it to them? ... This gets my vote as the sports
story of the year. This is the tale Deion Sanders told CBS
recently: ``I attempted suicide, but God had his hands on me. I ran
the car off the cliff, and it was like a 40- or 30-foot drop. The
car went down and there wasn't a scratch on me or the car.''
Sanders said he was driving about ``65 or 75 miles per hour'' at
the time. No one asked if he had a rubber car. No one asked how he
and his car got off the cliff or if God caught it in midair.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Patriots owner Bob Kraft said he didn't mean to be critical of
Packers general manager Ron Wolf when he knocked him last week in a
piece by Ron Borges. Kraft critcized Wolf for not getting more for
coach Mike Holmgren if and when he leaves the Packers at the end of
the year. Green Bay will reportedly be compensated with a
second-round draft pick from whoever lands Holmgren, if in fact he
leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft pointed out that he got first-, second-, third-, and
fourth-round choices when Bill Parcells left for the Jets and said
Packer stockholders were being shortchanged by Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf was surprised by Kraft's comments. ``I read what he had to
say and I feel it is so ridiculous that I don't want to respond,''
he said. ``Our agreement with Mike Holmgren was made long before
Bob Kraft was in the National Football League.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Wolf, the deal on Holmgren's departure was made
when he arrived in Green Bay. At the time, the Packers had to give
the San Francisco 49ers a second-round draft choice as compensation
for Holmgren. It was written into his contract with the 49ers that
if he ever left, the team he went to would have to give
compensation. The Packers did so and put a similar clause in his
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren signed with Green Bay in 1992. Kraft made his deal for
Parcells with the Jets in February 1997. Wolf therefore was
precluded from ever even attempting to make the kind of deal for
Holmgren that Kraft made with the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Great news for University of Massachusetts basketball fans.
Athletic director Bob Marcum is close to wrapping up a
home-and-home series with Michigan. The Wolverines, usually one of
the best teams in the nation, would be a tremendous draw ... One
scout who watched the Dolphins lose to the Jets last week says Dan
Marino's problem is that he has no receivers. His quarterback
rating is just about the lowest, and ``the guys he is throwing to
get no separation from the defensive backs,'' said the scout. ``The
best guy he has is O.J. McDuffie, and he couldn't start on a lot of
teams in this league.'' Marino will be in Jacksonville Monday to
face the Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is a scouting report on the Patriots' guests in Foxborough
Sunday, the Kansas City Chiefs, from a coach who faced them this
season:
</P>
<P>
   ``Great speed on defense. Play with high intensity. They are
small as defenses go but have a bunch of guys who can run to the
ball in a hurry. Derrick Thomas will be coming (on the pass rush)
off the corner all day. He always stays on the edge. He hasn't been
coming inside. Their two cornerbacks (Dale Carter and James Hasty)
might be as good as any pair in the league. They'll press the
receivers right off the line of scrimmage. Defensively, they are
very tough. If you can pound the ball at them on the ground, you
can score points. They want to put you in second-and-long,
third-and-long situations and just pass-rush from all over the
place. They bring a lot of speed when they are in that mode.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, they are just OK. Their running back (Donnell
Bennett) is really more of a fullback. The interior of their
offensive line, two guards and a center, is very good. Tackle is
their big question. New England's speed on the corner could give
those guys trouble. I think (quarterback Rich) Gannon is tougher to
play against. (Elvis) Grbac (who is supposed to start tomorrow) is
more of a pocket passer. They like to run play-action and bootleg
kind of stuff. They look to (Andre) Rison in the pass game first
and then back to the tight end, (Tony) Gonzalez. He can be
dangerous. He has good speed deep, better than most tight ends. And
they have a good kicking game in (punter Louie) Aguiar and
(placekicker Pete) Stoyanovich.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bruins GM Harry Sinden on why he thinks his team will be better
this season, even though most of the players are the same: ``A year
ago this time, our players didn't know if they could win. Some of
them didn't know how good they were personally. We showed last year
we could play with anyone in the league. Guys like (P.J.) Axelsson,
(Tim) Taylor, (Rob) DiMaio found out how good they could be. As a
group, all of them should play with the confidence of a winner, and
that's very important.'' ... Saints offensive tackle William Roaf
on why it is difficult to play against the Patriot defense: ``They
have such great speed to the outside and go so wide, when you go
out to block them, it opens up this big hole inside and one of
their defensive backs comes blitzing through. If you are not ready
for it, they are going to be after your quarterback all game.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
