<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9470 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-09 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A QUANDARY OVER READING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMARA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I should be ashamed to admit this, but I never read Dickens by
flashlight under the covers as a child. My father never read
``Treasure Island'' aloud by the hearth. My mother never had to
tell me to get my nose out of a book and go out to play.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, my eyes were weak even under full fluorescent light,
we didn't have a hearth and I liked to play outside as long as it
wasn't raining.
</P>
<P>
   I make this confession because we are at it again, wringing our
well-intentioned hands, holding high-minded symposia to scope out
the reasons our children have abandoned books.
</P>
<P>
   The word is out _ once more. Our children do not read, will not
read. They have been seduced by violent video games and sexy music
videos. They have been dulled by escapist electronic entertainment.
They have been rendered robotic by television, computer games and
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Disregard for the written word is nothing short of a crisis, say
some of the most literate minds in the nation. Hundreds of them,
including Maya Angelou and David McCullough, got together Friday at
the John F. Kennedy Library to examine what was described as an
epidemic of literary indifference among American children.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly there is plenty of statistical evidence to bolster
their claim. The Carnegie Council on Adolescent Development says
that children ages 9 to 14 spend more than 20 percent of their
waking hours watching TV but only 1 percent of their time reading.
The US Department of Education says that more than 40 percent of
our third graders read below grade level, that most boys will stop
reading for pleasure by the fifth grade and that most girls will
give up recreational reading two years after that.
</P>
<P>
   So, why can't I get worked up by this?
</P>
<P>
   It is not as though reading is the activity of choice among my
own children, ages 12, 10, and 7. Forced to compete with soccer,
Mario Kart and Beanie Babies, a good book is liable to lose. Forced
to choose between a visit to the public library and the local video
store, my back seat drivers will steer the Caravan toward
Blockbuster every time.
</P>
<P>
   It's just a guess, but perhaps what we need is fewer symposia
and more patience. We present our daughter with a favorite book
from our childhood and fret when she tosses ``The Secret Garden''
aside by chapter two. Isn't it possible she'll rediscover it on her
own next year? We give our son the book that changed our young life
and cringe when he pronounces ``A Wrinkle In Time'' too ``boring''
to finish. Isn't it likely he will develop his own literary taste?
</P>
<P>
   We tell our children that books are a joy, not a chore. Then we
require them to read for 20 minutes each night and shudder when
they set the timer on the stove to avoid inadvertently reading too
long.
</P>
<P>
   We want answers for why books do not hold the magic for them we
claim they held &UR;  &LR; for us, but how many of us romanticize our
pre-pubescent love for the printed page? Did we really love ``Silas
Marner'' that much? Didn't we just as often choose the movies over
the library on a Saturday afternoon?
</P>
<P>
   A love of books, like a love of music, is not foreclosed to a
child who takes her time to develop an attraction. If it were, the
Boston Public Library and Symphony Hall would both be dark. An
appreciation of literature is not inaccessible to the child whose
family income puts Barnes&AMP;Noble out of his reach. If it were,
Boston would not draw so many of its public high school
valedictorians from the ranks of this city's newest immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe our children don't read as much as we would like. Maybe we
didn't read as much as we remember.
</P>
<P>
   We are living in anti-intellectual times, in a culture that is
both superficial and ahistorical. At the behest of pop
psychologists, we have all spent at least one strained dinner hour
trying to explain Bill Clinton and Monica Lewinsky to our children.
But how many of us have taken the same opportunity to discuss
Richard Nixon and Andrew Johnson? Exactly how many of us have read
``Treasure Island'' aloud by the hearth?
</P>
<P>
   For eight hours Friday, a lot of good people got together on the
edge of the city to consider the intellectual future of our
children. Maybe I'm wrong not to be alarmed. Maybe what our
children need is yet another well-financed literacy campaign that
will convince them this time that reading really is fun.
</P>
<P>
   It was raw and damp at the Kennedy Library on Boston Harbor. The
kind of day that makes it hard for even the most earnest among us
to find the energy to solve the small problems, let alone the big
ones. The kind of day that makes you want to curl up with a good
book instead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
