<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONAS-TATE-REDMOND-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDMOND SAYS HE'LL BE BACK IN '99  
 INSISTS HE WON'T LEAVE ASU FOR NFL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Versatile tailback J.R. Redmond said Thursday that he's ready to
take on another role: college senior.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona State standout dismissed speculation that he will
leave school after his junior season to make himself eligible for
the NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going anywhere,'' Redmond said. `I'll be here. I'm
just now starting to get a handle on football as far as learning
the game. And I'm just starting to get a handle on my schoolwork,
too. I need another year to get better at both.''
</P>
<P>
   If Redmond returns, it also might give ASU an opportunity to
restart his Heisman Trophy campaign. He was considered a legitimate
candidate before the season, but a slow start by him and the Sun
Devils have diminished his chances.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond has rushed for 556 yards and six touchdowns. After
totaling 136 yards and one touchdown in the Sun Devils' first two
games, he has had 419 yards and five in the past three.
</P>
<P>
   He had the best game of his career Saturday against Southern
California at the Los Angeles Coliseum, when he accumulated an ASU
record 350 all-purpose yards and a career-high 214 rushing yards.
He became the 12th man in ASU history to rush for 200 yards in a
game.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond's rushing average of 111 yards per game ranks second in
the Pac-10. His 207 all-purpose yards per game rank first in the
conference and fifth in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   He also plays safety, although he has played little on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still consider myself a defensive back first who's learning
how to play running back,'' he said recently. ``I think I have room
to become a better tailback. I'm really trying to be a student of
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Most speculated that the lure of NFL money would prompt Redmond
to leave early. But the senior said completing his education is a
priority. He is majoring in English. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
