<SLUG> BC-KIDNAP-SUSPECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDNAP SUSPECT EYED IN GIRLS' SLAYINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLINTON, Mass. _ A man accused of trying to lure a young girl
into his car six weeks ago is under investigation for ties to the
murders of two children after police said he told them he was
nearby when Holly Piirainen and Sarah Pryor were abducted.
</P>
<P>
   John Robert Allen, 55, of Clinton was ordered to undergo a
psychia-tric evaluation last month after his arrest for attempted
kidnapping at a school bus stop in Dudley.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, who has pleaded not guilty, allegedly offered $25 to a
12-year-old if she would ride with him to Connecticut, but he fled
after a parent approached him.
</P>
<P>
   After his arrest, Allen told investigators he was in the area
when Piirainen disappeared in 1993 in Sturbridge, and when Pryor
vanished from Wayland in 1985, according to court documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is being investigated, and we are trying to be sure that
all avenues are being looked at,'' said the Sturbridge police
chief, Thomas Button. ``At this point, nothing has turned up that
would lead us in either direction _ that he is or isn't involved.''
</P>
<P>
   But Button said items seized from Allen's home and truck, and
the circumstances that led to his arrest, have prompted authorities
to consider him as a possible suspect in the other cases.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities from Dudley, Webster, and Sturbridge met recently
with State Police investigators to review the case and present
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say (Allen) is not as strong a possibility as when we
first looked at him,'' Button said. ``But we haven't discontinued
the investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested Allen Sept. 2 after the 12-year-old girl and the
parent who helped chase him away identified him in photographs.
Police said they searched Allen's 1998 pickup and found a knife, a
camera, an instruction book on tying knots, a pornographic
magazine, two full bottles of alcohol, and a piece of paper with
the word ``blonde'' written on it.
</P>
<P>
   According to court documents, Allen told the girl he ``was
looking for a `12- or 13-year-old blonde-headed girl named Molly'
and that Molly had a dimple like Marilyn Monroe.''
</P>
<P>
   Police said they later discovered that Allen had been carrying a
46-inch length of rope that was burned at both ends. Authorities
said Allen told them ``he had used the rope as a weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   In a search warrant affidavit dated Sept. 9, Michael P. Stevens,
a Dudley police investigator, said that ``throughout the interview
(with police) Mr. Allen provided spontaneous, unsolicited
statements regarding his whereabouts in relation to other
abductions, kidnappings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stated he was in the Sturbridge area `when that girl was
abducted, kidnapped, and murdered.' He went on to mention how he
also used to live in Sudbury, Mass., Route 117 near Wayland, Mass.,
when Sarah Pryor was abducted.''
</P>
<P>
   In the court papers supporting his request to search Allen's
Palmer Court home, Stevens said Allen ``appeared cognitive and was
well-spoken'' when he gave that statement.
</P>
<P>
   Allen's name does not appear on the state's sex-offender
registry, which traces criminal activity to 1981. However,
Stevens's affidavit says that Allen was the subject of a Peeping
Tom investigation in Boylston.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, Allen was suspected of peering through holes in
ceiling tiles ``to watch persons in their apartment rooms in
various states of dress/undress,'' according to the affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton neighbors said Allen once told two children in his
neighborhood that he was naked under his bathrobe and, in another
incident, once threatened to stab a neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   The items seized from Allen's home and shipped to the State
Police crime lab includ a blue comforter and a yellow pillow case;
trace samples from a shirt, a blanket, and the comforter; three
pairs of sneakers; and two pairs of gloves.
</P>
<P>
   Dudley police confiscated three bags of children's clothing, a
pair of girl's panties, hair elastics, children's caps, three
ropes, and a strongbox with pictures of nude women.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Worcester County Jail and House of Correction,
where Allen is being held, identified his attorney as Jennifer
Ginsburg. She could not be reached for comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   State Police referred questions about Allen to Worcester
District Attorney John Conte and Middlesex District Attorney Thomas
F. Reilly. Both declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Piirainen, 10, disappeared Aug. 5, 1993, while looking at
puppies at a neighbor's house. Hunters found her remains two months
later in a secluded and wooded area of Brimfield. State Police in
Sturbridge maintain a tip line (508-347-8173) to receive
information about her case.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, forensic scientists determined that human
remains found in Wayland almost three years before were those of
Pryor.
</P>
<P>
   The 9-year-old child disappeared in October 1985. Wayland and
State Police have tried to build a case against John R. Whirty, now
serving a life sentence after violating parole on a murder
conviction in Texas. Whirty, who was on parole when Pryor
disappeared, has denied involvement in the crime.
</P>
</TEXT>
