u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-PADRES-BRAVES-NYT     10-09 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PADRES-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES HAVE CROWD, BUT BRAVES HAD MADDUX  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO, Calif. _ The San Diego Padres are expecting more than
60,000 fans at Qualcomm Stadium this weekend, a far cry from the
low turnouts at Turner Field in Atlanta, where there were at least
7,000 empty seats for both Game 1 and Game 2 of the National League
Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres, who own a 2-0 lead over the Atlanta Braves, will
have the crowd _ and baseball history _ behind them for Games 3 and
4. Since the championship series went to a four-of-seven-game
series in 1985, no team that has lost the first two games at home
has rallied to win a trip to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect it to be totally different,'' Tony Gwynn, the
eight-time batting champion, said Friday. ``I think our fans are
excited. It doesn't happen that often here. If it's anything like
it was here last weekend, you better get some earplugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn was speaking about the division series, in which the
Padres eliminated the Houston Astros. But despite the disadvantage
of the crowd, the Braves still have one strong edge for Game 3 on
Saturday: Greg Maddux, the 18-game winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we're up, 2-0, I'd imagine we won't be favored in
either game,'' San Diego General Manager Kevin Towers said.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux will be matched up with the left-hander Sterling
Hitchcock. In Sunday's Game 4, Atlanta's Denny Neagle will oppose
Joey Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greg Maddux going in Game 3?'' Towers said. ``He's one of the
best pitchers baseball has ever seen. We have to pitch with them if
we're going to have a chance to win. If either game is a slugfest,
we're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for the Padres, neither of the first two games in
Atlanta came close to resembling a shootout. San Diego won Game 1
by 3-2 in 10 innings on a Ken Caminiti home run. And then Kevin
Brown continued his uncanny mastery of Atlanta in Thursday's Game
2, as he tossed a three-hit shutout, struck out 11 and contributed
a pair of key singles in a 3-0 victory over Tom Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Braves have the best rotation in baseball, the
Padres have Brown, who has won his last six decisions against
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Braves can somehow scrap their way back into the
series, they will have to find a way to get past Brown _ who
defeated them twice in last fall's National League Championship
Series while pitching for the Florida Marlins _ for the first time
since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were down 3 games to 1 to the Cardinals in 1996, and we
came back,'' Atlanta Manager Bobby Cox said after his team had lost
the first two games of a championship series for the first time in
the 1990's. ``We have the type of pitching and I think we've got
the hitting _ once it gets going _ that we could do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine said: ``It's not an enviable position to be in, down 0-2
going to the other ball park. But it wasn't too long ago that we
were up 2-0 in a World Series and wound up being swept. It can
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, of course, was referring to 1996, when the Yankees
rallied from two home losses to win the Series in six games. For
history to pay the Braves' back, however, they must get some
production from the middle of their lineup. Chipper Jones (1 for
8), Andres Galarraga (0 for 8), Ryan Klesko (0 for 5) and Javy
Lopez (2 for 7) are a combined 3 for 28 (.107) with 0 runs batted
in in the first two games of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Gwynn cautioned, ``Even though we're up 2-0, sooner or
later we're going to have to bust out offensively ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   And even though Maddux is just 3-5 with a 4.07 earned run
average in 9 championship series starts, busting out against him is
not the easiest thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whole pitching staff believes that good pitching
will beat good hitting on any day of the week,'' Maddux said. ``I
don't think there are going to many differences for me pitching in
San Diego.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
