<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9481 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-NLCS-GWYNN-TEX     10-09 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-GWYNN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GWYNN'S SPIRIT PREVAILS THROUGH THICK AND THIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The 1993 season was particularly hard on Tony Gwynn
and the San Diego Padres.
</P>
<P>
   They lost 101 games and finished with the worst record in the
major leagues. By the time the season was over they had dumped Fred
McGriff, Gary Sheffield, Greg Harris and Bruce Hurst in an effort
to save money.
</P>
<P>
   The future looked bleak. When the season was over, Charles Gwynn
sought out his son for a heart-to-heart chat.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father said, `You need to get out of there,' '' Tony Gwynn
said. ```They're not trying to win, you've got to get out.' I tried
to convince him I was happy here, it was good for my family and I
didn't want to leave. He died two days after Thanksgiving. I never
did convince him.''
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't left yet, either. Eighteen years after being drafted
out of San Diego State University, Gwynn has become a cherished
institution in San Diego, having won eight batting titles while
enduring seven losing seasons, four last-places finishes and the
wrath of the players' association for refusing to test the
free-agent market.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were those old brown uniforms the Padres used to
wear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started watching the Padres when I was in college, paying
$1.50 to sit in the bleachers,'' Gwynn said. ``I used to sit there
and say, `Those've got to be the ugliest uniforms I've ever seen.'
Then I got drafted by the Padres and I said, `Oh no, now I've got
to wear that ugly uniform.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But everything I've done in the major leagues, I've done it
with the Padres, whether it's in a good uniform or bad. That means
a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The feeling is mutual in San Diego, and when the Padres are
introduced at 3:15 p.m. today before their first National League
Championship Series home game since 1984, the loudest and longest
ovation will be reserved for Gwynn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got goose bumps when they gave him a standing ovation before
the Houston series,'' Padres pitcher Ed Vosberg said. ``They love
him there. They treat him like a king.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Padres president Larry Lucchino: ``The value of his loyalty
and identity is incalculable. We all need heroes, and San Diego has
a hero in Tony Gwynn. He's repaid the city for its adulation with
his commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn is hoping to repay that affection further by leading the
Padres back to the World Series for the first time since 1984.
There was a division title in 1996, but the Padres were knocked out
in the first round of the playoffs. Otherwise, it has been a lean
14 years with Gwynn's annual run at the batting title about all
there was to cheer about in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Gwynn had a long chat with Paul Molitor, who
bailed out after 15 long seasons in Milwaukee, signed as a free
agent with the Toronto Blue Jays in 1993 and played on a World
Series winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him what it was like to play in a World Series?''
Gwynn said. ``How does it affect you? He said it was quite an
elation after they won and after a month goes by, you realize
that's what this game is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn wants to enjoy that same feeling with the Padres. They
enter today's game with a 2-0 best-of-seven series lead against the
Atlanta Braves. Gwynn is halfway there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long wait for him,'' Padres manager Bruce Bochy
said. ``We'd like to get there for all of us, and especially Tony
Gwynn.''
</P>
<P>
   There isn't much time left. Gwynn is 38 and has two years left
on his contract. San Diego's stadium issue also hangs in the air.
If voters don't approve a new stadium in a November referendum, the
possibility exists the team could move to Northern Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ain't going anywhere,'' said Gwynn, referring to his family
and not the Padres. ``They might move, but I won't be going with
them. That's the good thing about baseball, if you have some
success, you can dictate your own situation. That's a big plus.''
</P>
<P>
   That hints at retirement, but there is one other unfinished
piece of business, beyond getting back to the World Series. Gwynn
finished the season with 2,928 hits, leaving him 72 short of 3,000.
Barring injury, which has become a factor with Gwynn, he should
reach that mark easily next season.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn, whose 5-foot-11, 220-pound pudgy body doesn't remotely
approach the prototypical athlete, remains one of the elite hitters
in the league, even if an Achilles' tendon injury and thumb injury
limited him to 127 games this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Old Blub,'' as he calls himself, hit .321, which is a great
season by most standards, but it ended a streak of four consecutive
batting titles. It was 18 points below his career average of .339
and was the first time in six years he did not raise his career
average.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm not close to being what I've been, I don't want to be
hanging on,'' Gwynn said. ``My goal is to play until 2000, and I
feel I can do that. I can't think of a year over the past 10 years
where I didn't have an injury, but that's not a big deal. They
linger, but you still play because I love to play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
