<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLIED-AMP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLIED SIGNAL TO PURSUE AMP DESPITE ADVERSE RULING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., N.J.)  (lb) 
 By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Allied Signal Inc. said Friday that it would proceed with its
offer of $44.50 a share to buy 9 percent of the outstanding stock
of AMP Inc., indicating confidence that Allied's $9.7 billion
hostile takeover bid would be successful despite a federal judge's
ruling that part of its purchase plan was unlawful.
</P>
<P>
   AMP, in an effort to show shareholders that it could add value
to the company, said Friday that it would buy back up to 30 million
of its shares, or about 14 percent, for $55 a share.
</P>
<P>
   AMP investors reacted favorably to the latest twist in the
takeover battle. Shares of AMP, which is based in Harrisburg, Pa.,
rose $3.5625 on Friday, to $41.3125, and those of Allied Signal
increased $1.50, to $36.
</P>
<P>
   Allied, an aerospace and automotive parts maker based in
Morristown, N.J., said it was appealing the Thursday ruling by U.S.
District Judge James Giles. He ruled that it would be ``unlawful''
for the company to pursue a plan to have AMP shareholders, through
written consent, gain control from the board over AMP's shareholder
rights plan, which includes an anti-takeover provision, or poison
pill.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the ruling, the judge, who sits in the Eastern District
of Pennsylvania, said that the poison pill could remain in place
until it expired in November 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors viewed another portion of the judge's ruling,
which temporarily halted Allied's plan to name 17 additional
members to AMP's board, as a sign that Allied should offer a slate
of nominees without ties to Allied.
</P>
<P>
   The judge delayed the solicitation of written consents to elect
board nominees until Allied stated that ``its director nominees
have a fiduciary duty solely to AMP.''
</P>
<P>
   Allied Signal said it expected to comply early next week with
the ruling. But it will offer the same nominees it originally
suggested: 14 current board members _ including the chief executive
of Allied, Lawrence Bossidy _ plus three other senior Allied
executives.
</P>
<P>
   AMP's $55 tender offer expires Nov. 20. In the meantime, if
Allied successfully complies with the judge's ruling, it can begin
after next Thursday to solicit written consents to have its
nominees elected to the AMP board.
</P>
<P>
   Several AMP shareholders said Friday that they hoped Allied's
persistence would prompt AMP executives to negotiate a friendly
offer for the company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
