<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROJANS, BEARS FEELING DEFENSIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If USC and California offer two accurate examples
of the West Coast offense, Bill Walsh will probably be wincing
somewhere today.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans enter the contest against Cal at the Coliseum ranked
last in the Pacific-10 Conference in passing. As for the Golden
Bears, they are slightly better: ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both West Coast offenses are struggling,'' USC coach Paul
Hackett said in a major understatement.
</P>
<P>
   While both teams are foundering offensively, they are being
saved by their defenses, and that accounts for the fact the game
has retained some importance. The Trojans (4-1, 2-0) and Golden
Bears (3-1, 1-0) are among five teams sitting atop the conference
standings.
</P>
<P>
   Since USC has won 16 of the past 20 meetings and is a 12{-point
favorite today, common sense dictates the Trojans will continue
their winning ways against Cal.
</P>
<P>
   But Hackett is probably more unsure of the offense today than
before the season. Tailback Chad Morton remains questionable with a
bruised back. Morton ran Friday afternoon but will wait until after
pregame warm-ups to decide if he will play.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do we play without Chad Morton? We don't know where we are
without Chad,'' Hackett said. ``Our flair (offensively) has been
the flair we had with Chad Morton.''
</P>
<P>
   Without him, Hackett has focused on the rivalry. He's a bit of
an expert, since he coached at Cal from 1972-75 and then went
directly to USC for five seasons (1976-80).
</P>
<P>
   ``Cal and USC have never had a love affair,'' Hackett said. ``As
a young coach at Cal, everything was based on whether you could
beat USC. Since then, Cal always looked at us as the premier
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett couldn't wait to tell the Trojans about comments earlier
this week that Cal players had criticized USC's tradition. It
didn't seem to evoke much of a response, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as our team, we have no room to talk. That's for high
school games,'' right guard Travis Claridge said.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Morton's status and the rivalry, there's a little
something known as the conference race that matters dearly to both
teams. It's early enough in the season for each to remain
optimistic, but the loser will clearly be relegated to also-ran
status.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of teams could jump up with good fortune and good
health,'' Cal coach Tom Holmoe said. ``That's what we're trying to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the Bears have won three games without their offense.
They have yet to rush for a touchdown this season and produced just
three points in their 24-14 victory over Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a team being carried by its defense,'' Hackett said. ``I
guess you could say their strength vs. our weakness and our
strength vs. their weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: Verle Sorgen, the Pacific-10 Conference's coordinator
of football officiating, faxed Hackett a letter Friday saying
Arizona State center Grey Ruegamer legally blocked USC defensive
tackle Marc Matock on the play Matock broke his ankle. ``It's
blindside and low, but it's from the side and it's legal,'' Sorgen
said. ``USC did (inquire) about it. It's a dangerous block, but it
was legal.'' Sorgen watched game tapes with sideline and end-zone
views before rendering his opinion. Hackett said earlier this week
that the play was legal, but USC wanted to get a rules
interpretation from Sorgen....
</P>
<P>
   Hackett was unsure Friday whether Matt Welch or Ken Bowen would
start at right tackle. Welch missed Wednesday's practice with a
sore shoulder but is OK. Both are expected to play....
</P>
<P>
   USC's No. 1-ranked water polo team will host No. 4 California
today at the Olympic Swim Stadium at 1 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
