<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 10/09/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) CHAPEL HILL, N.C. -- Oct. 09, 1998 --
PSYCHIATRIST-BLAME-1, 10-09 -- ``The person is ultimately
responsible for himself,'' says Dr. Myron Liptzin, 64, lost a jury
verdict of $500,000 to murderer, Wendell Williamson. Williamson,
who had been Kiptzin's patient, said that Liptzin had not made a
correct diagnosis, had not explained how seriously ill Williamson
was and had not followed up after their sessions ended. (Jennifer
Warburg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) MORGANTOWN, N.C. -- Oct. 09, 1998 --
PSYCHIATRIST-BLAME-1, 10-09 -- Wendell Williamson in the Day Room
of Ward 18 in the Harper Building of Broughton State Hospital.
Williamson, who took an M-1 rifle near the campus of the University
of North Carolina, where he was a law student, and killed two men
he had never met, is suing the psychiatrist who had been counseling
him because he did not diagnose him properly. (Jennifer Warburg/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- Oct. 09, 1998 -- FLA-GOV-RACE, 10-07 -- Last
month, Republican Jeb Bush, left, and underdog Democratic
candidate, Lt. Gov. Kenneth MacKay, generate support for their
gubernatorial campaigns. With Bush still a commanding front-runner
in the election for Florida governor, the two wasted no time on
niceties this week in the first of three scheduled debates.
(Phillippe Diederich/New York Times Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) KABUL, Afghanistan -- Oct. 09, 1998 --
AFGHAN-AID-GROUPS-2, 10-09 -- At the Indira Gandhi Child Health
Institute and Hospital Anayatullah Sarwat, 18-months-old, gets his
nutrition through a feeding tube in his nose. Since 30
international aid agencies have pulled out of the capital in a
dispute with the ruling Taliban, the hospital is critically short
of supplies. The nutrition unit lacks things as basic as milk and
vitamin-enriched biscuits. (Barry Bearak/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) KABUL, Afghanistan -- Oct. 09, 1998 --
AFGHAN-AID-GROUPS-1, 10-09 -- This a medical clinic was hit by
rocket fire on Sept. 21. More than 100 people were killed. The
rocket was fired by the forces of Ahmad Shah Massoud, the last
holdout of the so-called Northern Alliance in their battle against
the Taliban. The front line for Massoud's forces are about 12 miles
from Kabul and they can lob rockets into the capital at will.
(Barry Bearak/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Oct. 09, 1998 -- LIVENT-DRABINSKY, 10-09 --
Garth Drabinsky, chairman and chief executive of Livent Inc., the
Toronton-based theatrical production company, in his office at the
Ford Center for the Performing Arts in Manhattan. In June, cash
troubles had forced him to turn over control of Livent to Michael
Ovitz, former president of the Walt Disney Company, in return for a
$20 million investment. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) CAPE KENNEDY SPACE CENTER, Fla. -- Oct. 09, 1998 --
SCI-SHUTTLE-GLENN, 10-09 -- John Glenn and the crew of Space
Shuttle Mission STS-95, scheduled to launch on Oct. 29th, do a
dress rehearsal walk out to the Shuttle for a count down test
Friday. Curt Brown, at right front with mustache is the mission's
commander. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- 0ct. 09, 1998 -- CONGRESS-HEALTH, 10-09 --
House and Senate Democrats join President Clinton at the White
House after Republicans defeated an effort to get a ``Patients Bill
of Rights'' enacted. They are, from left, Sen. Ted Kennedy, Rep.
David Obey, Rep. David Bonior, Sens. Barbara Mikulski and Tom
Daschle, Clinton, Reps. Charles Rangel, Steny Hoyer, Nita Lowey,
Richard Gephardt and Robert Menendez. (Stephen Crowley/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- 0ct. 09, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 11 --
NY-DERMATOLOGIST, 10-09 -- Dr. Pat Wexler has earned a reputation
for being a skin genie as well as a comfy, if sometimes stern,
Jewish mother. Dr. Wexler began her career as an internist,
specializing in infectious diseases. But after deciding that it was
too emotionally wearing to treat seriously ill patients, she went
back for a residency in dermatology. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) FALL RIVER, Mass. -- 0ct. 09, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT.
11 -- MUTFUND-WINNERS-2, 10-09 -- Irving Levine, manager of the
$87.5 million Copley fund, in front of the original Berkshire
Hathaway building which was once a mill. Levine's fund has about 55
percent of its portfolio in a mix of telephone, gas and electric
companies, which pay the high dividends many investors seek in
uncertain times. (Kirsten Elstner/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) JERSEY CITY, N.J. -- 0ct. 09, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT.
11 -- MUTFUND-WINNERS-1, 10-09 -- William Reaves, who runs Strong
American Utilities, enjoys of view of Wall Street from across the
river. ``We've had a good portfolio all along,'' says Reaves whose
fund has $216.5 million in assets. ``We've just come into a period
when the sun is shining on our stocks for a change.'' (Chester
Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
