<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEN HAS EARLY WHITE CHRISTMAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta _ Josh Green jetted into a winter wonderland
Friday afternoon, Christmas Eve having arrived early in terms of
climate and circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   The weather outside was frightful, but for the Los Angeles
Kings' rookie right wing, the situation was delightful. A couple of
inches of snow sprinkled down on Edmonton, rolling out a white
carpet for the 20-year-old Green's NHL debut tonight in the Kings'
regular-season opener against the Oilers, the team he rooted for
growing up in Camrose, Alberta, about an hour away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember times that I sat up there and thought about
maybe being on that ice,'' Green said, referring to what once was
called the Northlands Coliseum and today is known as the Skyreach
Centre. ``Now that it's going to happen, it's really exciting for
me and my family. It's natural for a person to feel nervous, so I
just want to get that first shift under my belt, and hopefully it
gets easier from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of his excitement came from the simple pursuit of about 30
tickets for friends and family. Players are allotted two; the
Kings' media-relations staff scrounged up the rest. All of this had
Kings coach Larry Robinson reminiscing about his own debut, more
than a quarter-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``January 8, 1973,'' said Robinson, a Hall of Famer, instantly
reciting when asked to recall the game _ the Canadiens against the
Minnesota North Stars at the old Montreal Forum. ``I was scared,
nervous, a little bit of both. Anxious. The first shift, I ran
somebody, I don't remember who it was. I sent him flying in the
corner and it got me going.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think it's a lot different for the kids now. They know a
little more what to expect. The fact that (Green) has played in a
number of exhibition games and this is not his first training camp
gives him a bit of an advantage, and the fact that he played last
year in the American Hockey League better prepares him for the
start of the year here.''
</P>
<P>
   Green, a second-round choice in the NHL draft two years ago,
scored 51 goals for two teams in the AHL last season. At 6-foot-4,
212 pounds, Green's job is to play physically, go into the corners,
stand in front of the net to screen opposing goalies and deflect
shots from the point.
</P>
<P>
   He did all those things during the exhibition season, collecting
three goals and four points in six games and beating out
19-year-old Olli Jokinen for a spot on the roster. He will begin
tonight's game on a line with Luc Robitaille and Yanic Perreault.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can do is try to go out there and keep it simple and try
to give the puck to Luc and Yanic as much as I can and try to go to
the net and use my size,'' Green said. ``I think things will work
out. Playing with those two guys, good things will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged it might not be so simple, at least at the
start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably will be running around with my head cut off,''
Green admitted. ``But I think once I get that first shift, I'll
feel a little more comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, admiring the poise that belies Green's age, said he
isn't too concerned with jitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he's the nervous type,'' Robinson said. ``He's
kind of quiet out there.''
</P>
<P>
   It's playing so near to home that might lift his debut from
merely memorable to monumental for Green. His parents, Svend (``my
first coach'') and Carol, will be in the stands, and it will be
Green's first game at any level in the building so many of his
boyhood heroes once called home.
</P>
<P>
   Green said he and some childhood teammates did win a trip years
ago that earned them the chance to skate on the ice with such
Oilers icons as Mark Messier and Glenn Anderson. Tonight, however,
is a completely different occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it can be a distraction,'' Robinson said.
``Sometimes it can help, too. A lot of times, when you play in
front of your family it gives you a little bit of an emotional
lift, too. It gets your adrenaline going. Everybody reacts
differently to those situations. Some, it helps them, and some,
they try to do too much and make a lot of mistakes. But he's a
pretty focused kid. I don't think he should have too much of a
problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 2250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
