<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-NCSTATE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech task: Figuring out the Wolfpack
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Thanks to wins over Florida State and Syracuse, North
Carolina State is ranked No. 23 but still sort of hard to figure.
Georgia Tech will try today at 3:30 at Carter-Finley Stadium, site
of those two huge Wolfpack wins.
</P>
<P>
   N.C. State (3-1, 1-0) reinforced how good it can be with the win
over Syracuse, but outside of those two games the Wolfpack barely
showed up in a narrow win over Ohio and a loss to Baylor. Does the
apparent importance of the next game dictate which way N.C. State
will play? If that's the case, how does the Wolfpack feel about
Georgia Tech?
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, this is the biggest game of the season (in terms of)
where we are and what we need to do,'' said N.C. State coach Mike
O'Cain, and that's what he told his team. ``We've got to take care
of business. That's not to say it's a game we should win. They're
as talented as we are. (But) we're at home. It's a game we need to
win. . . . We'll have other big games, but this is it.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Baylor loss, O'Cain is figuring it got N.C. State to
this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure we'd have beaten Syracuse if we had beat
Baylor,'' O'Cain said. ``Any time you fall short of your
expectations, it slaps you in the face and brings you back to
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech (3-1, 2-0 ACC) got the same refocusing from its
season-opening loss to Boston College. Since then the Yellow
Jackets have been on a three-win roll. But this is Tech's first
true test of the season and the start of a very interesting stretch
of games. After N.C. State, there's Top 10 teams Virginia and
Florida State back-to-back.
</P>
<P>
   With a recent history of starting strong and stumbling, the
Yellow Jackets are eager to buck that trend and have homecoming
against Virginia with an undefeated ACC record and possibly a Top
25 ranking. They're trying to do it by concentrating only on the
Wolfpack, which is hard to do with a steady stream of Tech students
dropping by the Tech athletic association to pick up tickets for
Virginia and Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``(If you look ahead) you start getting confident, cocky,'' Tech
receiver Mike Sheridan said. ``We're trying not to do that. We're
concentrating on the next game and doing what got us here.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither N.C. State nor Tech win with dominating defenses, so a
high-scoring game would not be a surprise. This will be a showdown
between two of the top offensive teams in the ACC and the top two
quarterbacks in N.C. State's Jamie Barnette and Tech's Joe
Hamilton. Then there's Wolfpack receiver Torry Holt, who has the
ability to dominate a game on offense and on special teams as a
return man.
</P>
<P>
   Tech has won three in a row against N.C. State, but not when so
much was expected of the Wolfpack and never with this much at stake
for both teams. The winner will be tied with Virginia (5-0, 3-0)
atop the ACC standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had their number,'' Hamilton said. ``I think they'll be
ready for us.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
