<HEADER>
A9544 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ALNOTES3-COX     10-09 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALNOTES3-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Other Hernandez gets chance to star
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ His brother dominated the postseason headlines last
year. Now it's Orlando Hernandez's chance to turn heads.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander gets his first start of October tonight against
the Indians. The Yankees need a big start from the Cuban, who
hasn't pitched in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, our guy makes as good an impact as Livan did,''
Yanks manager Joe Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   It was Florida's Livan Hernandez who won the MVP in both the
league championship and World Series. Orlando faces Doc Gooden
today, and it just so happens the rookie has an affinity for the
Indians' veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a big fan of Dwight Gooden because I was able to see him
pitch,'' said Hernandez through a translator.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Hernandez was fabulous in the regular season,
going 12-4 with a 3.13 ERA. He hasn't spoken to his brother
recently, but said, ``As everyone knows, I've played in big games
before in Cuba. Obviously, I haven't played in a game of this
magnitude in the major leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Will the layoff effect Hernandez? ``No. Two weeks off are not a
justification for me having a bad game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lineup change
</P>
<P>
   Torre decided Friday night to bench Tim Raines and replace him
at DH with Chili Davis. Raines has been struggling, going 1-for-6
in the first two games with four strikeouts. Davis, who missed most
of the regular season with an ankle injury, is 1-for-1 in a
pinch-hitting appearance and certainly gives the lineup more power.
. . . Torre held a team meeting before the game, saying, ``With
everything that's been going on for the last day and a half, I just
wanted to make sure we go out there and think about (Friday)
instead of trying to make up for something that happened the other
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Tribe update
</P>
<P>
   While the Braves couldn't even come close to selling out their
first two league championship games, tickets here have been gone
for weeks and scalpers were getting as much as $350 for box seats
outside Jacobs Field. ... The Indians also moved around their
lineup Friday, starting Mark Whiten in left and moving David
Justice into the designated hitters hole. White is a former Brave
and has played for six different teams since 1995. ... The last
time Gooden pitched, in the divisional series against the Red Sox,
he lasted just two outs before being thrown out. Does that concern
manager Mike Hargrove? ``Doc is a professional and has worked very
hard to keep himself ready for whatever we've asked him to do.''
Said Gooden, ``That's over with. We got to the next level, which we
wanted to do and hopefully this time I will be out there a lot
longer.'' ... The AL has fined Yankees owner GS an undisclosed
amount after he made undispariging remarks about the umpires
following the loss in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
