<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRADLEY-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    San Diego catches the fever
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Bruce Bochy drove to work and ran upon a traffic
snarl on Friars Road. ``I thought it was for the football,'' said
the Padres manager, meaning the game San Diego State was to play at
Qualcomm Stadium eight hours later. ``But then I thought, `This
can't all be for the Aztecs.' '' What Bochy discovered was that the
cars were there to support another team _ his.
</P>
<P>
   This is considered a laissez-faire city, where living the good
life outweighs getting geeked up over some ballgame. Two victories
in Atlanta changed all that. A hundred fans gathered outside
Qualcomm to greet the team when it returned home Friday. The time:
2:30 a.m. PDT. ``Those,'' said reliever Donne Wall, ``are some
diehard fans.''
</P>
<P>
   KFMB, the Padres' flagship station, pre-empted its regular
morning programming to go with baseball talk as hosted by Randy
Jones, who won a Cy Young award, and Mark Grant, whose claim to
fame is that, while briefly a Brave, he demonstrated how to do the
Tomahawk Chop in a photo sequence in this very newspaper. One bit
of repartee went thusly:
</P>
<P>
   Caller: ``My mother has this thing she does whenever the Padres
get into a tight spot. She goes to the bathroom and listens to the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant: ``The bathroom?''
</P>
<P>
   Caller: ``It's not like she uses the bathroom. She just sits
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant: ``If it's a long inning, don't her legs get tired?''
</P>
<P>
   KFMB, 760 on your AM dial, likewise figured in the congestion
that made some Padre players late for their optional workout. The
station was giving away 1,000 envelopes outside the ballpark.
Couple the freebie-seekers with those who'd come to the stadium
looking to buy what tickets remained for Games 3, 4 and 5, and by
noon the Qualcomm parking lot looked like the staging area for the
world's largest road rally, a line of cars snaking halfway to
Ensenada.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been waiting an hour,'' said Dominic Oliveira. At the
moment, his truck was at least another half-hour from the KFMB
trailer. ``But they're giving away 1,000 tickets to the Padres
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Said the radio station's Glenn Erath: ``He's wrong, but we're
glad he's here.'' In each of the 1,000 envelopes was some sort of
prize, but only four contained actual tickets to this NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres drew 2.5 million this season, the most in franchise
history but only seventh-best in a 14-team league. But, as Erath
said, ``It's a very good fair-weather town.'' Even in balmy San
Diego, the weather never gets better than when the home team is two
wins from the World Series. Said Bochy: ``People are excited.
They're talking baseball. That's great to see. There have been a
lot of lean years here.''
</P>
<P>
   So consuming is this outbreak of Friar Fever that the San Diego
Union-Tribune took a headlined jab Friday: ``Time to stick a
tomahawk in blase Atlanta?'' Seeking to head off any squabbling,
Bochy himself rose to the defense: ``On behalf of Atlanta, they're
here every year. It's an annual thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres haven't graced an NLCS since 1984, so this is new. It
is so new that the word mentioned most often on KFMB was ``sweep,''
even though the job is just half-done.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bradley can be reached at markb(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
