</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PADRES10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves not ready to give up season
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ As brave fronts go, this Braves front is fairly
credible, and certainly better than their collective backs, which
are now against the blue outfield wall of Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   These are dire straits for a group who, during two nightmarish
nights at the Ted, were hardly the sultans of swing. Yes, the
Braves have walked this high wire before. No, no team has ever won
the National League Championship Series after losing the first two
games at home. Yet Tom Glavine hardly sees another October
apocalypse in his immediate future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're really looking beyond anything other than
we're down 2-0 in this series,'' Glavine said of the NLCS, which
resumes today at the Q when Greg Maddux meets San Diego's Sterling
Hitchcock in Game 3. ``I can't speak for everybody but I'm not
sitting here thinking, `Oh God, we're down 2-0, here goes another
postseason.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``By no means is this series over. We're focusing on (today).''
</P>
<P>
   Focusing, and seeking inspiration from other postseason
predicaments. ``We've been on both sides of the coin,'' said
Glavine. ``We were down 3-1 and came back to win a series (the 1996
NLCS against the Cardinals, when the Braves won Game 5 in St.
Louis, then easily took 6 and 7 back home). Two short years ago, we
were up 2-0 and lost (the '96 World Series to the Yankees after
winning the first two games in the Bronx).
</P>
<P>
   ``This is certainly not the position we want to be in, but by no
means is this series over.''
</P>
<P>
   Not with three weekend pitching matchups that appear to favor
Atlanta: Maddux (18-9) against the left-hander Hitchcock (9-7);
then Denny Neagle (16-11) Sunday versus Joey Hamilton (13-13); and,
barring a Padres sweep, a Game 5 rematch of the John Smoltz-Andy
Ashby opener.
</P>
<P>
   That would return the series to Atlanta. That would also mean
the Braves would again confront Kevin Brown, whose three-hit, 3-0
shutout in Game 2 was his sixth straight win over Atlanta, third
straight in NLCS play.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you going to do?,'' said the struggling shortstop
Walt Weiss. ``There's no secret. We've got to go out there and keep
competing until we run out of outs. We're definitely not doing
enough. What have we scored, two runs in two games? That's not
going to get it done.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've had two outstanding pitching performances (Ashby gave
up just one run in eight innings in a 10-inning, 3-2 opening win
before Brown struck out 11 Thursday). When things are not going
right, individually you have to make adjustments and collectively
you see results.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get some guys hitting,'' said second baseman
Keith Lockhart, ``and put something together.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially these guys: the Braves' 3-4-5-6 hitters. Chipper
Jones, Andres Galarraga, Ryan Klesko and Javy Lopez are in a
terrible, untimely funk. They're a combined 3-for-28 with eight
strikeouts, no homers and not a single RBI. This is in stark
contrast to the Padres, who surprised Houston in the Division
Series and have so far stunned Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they get guys in scoring position, they seem to turn it
up a notch,'' said Lockhart. ``They didn't get here by accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's middle-of-the-order malaise is largely due to Brown
and Ashby, but also Weiss' struggles. After going 2-for-13 against
the Cubs in the NLDS sweep, Weiss is 0-for-8 in the NLCS and hasn't
reached base once. He struck out in his last two at-bats in an
0-for-5 Game 1, then took a called third in the first inning
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not doing anything right,'' said Weiss. ``My job is to get
on base and I haven't done it. The only thing to do is make
adjustments. I think I got away from my game plan a couple of
at-bats (Thursday). (On Wednesday), I had a called third.
(Thursday), my first at-bat (another K looking), I thought there
were some tough pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ended up getting out of my game plan, which I should never
do.''
</P>
<P>
   That game plan: ``Go deep in the count.'' Indeed, Weiss has
tapped out three times to first base, twice on the first pitch. In
Game 1, on an attempted suicide squeeze, he popped up the first
pitch into a rally-killing doubleplay.
</P>
<P>
   All of that has been magnified, and scrutinized. So have
Atlanta's mistakes afield: Galarraga's two errors on one play in
Game 1 that allowed the go-ahead run to score in the eighth inning;
Chipper Jones' mental mistake of holding the ball aloft, instead of
holding the tag on Ruben Rivera, who tagged up and slid into _ and
beyond _ third just before Galarraga's double gaffe; and not one
but two pickoff throws Lopez made to second in the ninth inning
Thursday. The second bounced into center and allowed Brown to
advance to third and later score the first of two cushioning runs
that inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what generally happens in the post-season,'' said
Glavine. ``There's one or two things that are huge in the outcome.
The ninth inning (Thursday), or even the sixth, a couple of
15-hoppers (singles through the infield) that Lock almost knocks
down. That's the post-season. You try to tell people that. A play
here, a play there. So far, that's how it's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   And not gone unnoticed. ``In the post-season, everything is
broken down and analyzed,'' said Weiss. ``Just in a two-game span,
there's 10 million things to analyze and break down. In the regular
season, 90 per cent of that never gets noticed.''
</P>
<P>
   In the post-season, it not only gets noticed, but magnified
many-fold. ``In the post-season,'' said Weiss, ``it's almost like
four or five at-bats seem like 20, because they're analyzed so
much.''
</P>
<P>
   In the semi-final analysis, what's a Braves front to do? Don't
back down. ``You've got to win four games to end this series,''
said Weiss. ``They've still got to win two more games. I'm sure
they don't think it's going to be easy to beat us two more games.
We've got to win four.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get some momentum,'' said Lockhart. ``With Doggie
pitching, we've got to get some hitters going.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For us,'' said Klesko, ``the main goal is to beat up on 'em a
little bit, and get back to Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   In Game 6. In Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
