<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLMATCHUP310-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hitchcock's last start a turning point
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Greg Maddux remembers not only the game and the
batter but the exact pitch he threw when it all suddenly made
sense. Montreal. 1990. Delino DeShields. Fastball on the hands.
</P>
<P>
   Convinced that he could not make it, Maddux put the ball just
where he wanted and induced a soft groundout, encouraging the young
pitcher so much that he contends he was a different player from
that moment.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling Hitchcock may have made that same pitch this week. The
Atlanta Braves are hoping against it.
</P>
<P>
   In a series that has been all about pitching, Maddux faces
Hitchcock in tonight's Game 3 of the NLCS, trying to bail out a
postseason gone all wrong. Coming off the most consequential start
of his career, Hitchcock can deliver the San Diego Padres to the
World Series threshold. Unless Monday was some kind of fluke.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no pressure on me,'' Hitchcock said. ``I'm not
supposed to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock nailed down Game 4 of the League Division Series
against Houston Monday night, striking out 11 while allowing one
run on three hits before the Padres' bullpen took over in the
seventh. He has thrown a split-fingered fastball since high school,
but under the tutelage of Padres pitching coach Dave Stewart the
pitch has grown teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Astros, Hitchcock, 27, was demonic, flicking the
pitch out of the bottom of the strike zone as if on a bullwhip.
Against a free-swinging team like the Braves, the same pitch can
decide a game, if Hitchcock can duplicate it. That game may have
been a watershed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He goes out there against Randy Johnson and he knew he had to
pitch well,'' said San Diego manager Bruce Bochy. ``And he had
tremendous stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To get people out and give our team a chance to win is
basically all I can do,'' said Hitchcock. ``Get as deep in the game
as I can and keep us close.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux is expected to do more than that, and with the Braves'
offense dormant, he may have to. The Braves need one win to get off
the ropes and then another Sunday to fix the damage done in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it's April or May, you're out there, you want to
win,'' said Maddux. ``I don't think anybody likes to be
embarrassed. We want to win. We don't feel like we have to win or
else. There's not that sense there. But I think for our own
satisfaction, for our fans, for our city, for our families, I think
those are the reasons we want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   That, and bringing the NLCS back to Atlanta next week.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
