<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Free agent Brown hints he might not leave town
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Figuring to be one of the most coveted free agents
this off-season, Kevin Brown is hinting about a possible return to
San Diego. Money will be a major consideration, but after getting
burned by the breakup of the Florida Marlins, Brown also wants
assurances the team will remain competitive.
</P>
<P>
   A possible snag to his return is the hiring in Colorado of Jim
Leyland, his former manager with the Marlins. The Rockies are
willing to up their $50 million payroll and Brown is among the
players they'll target this winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty obvious I've enjoyed this ballclub all year,''
Brown said of the Padres. ``It's been a great place for my family
and myself. All things being equal, yeah, I'd like to be back.''
</P>
<P>
   The immediate question is whether Brown will come back on three
days rest and start Game 5 of the NLCS, if necessary. He did it in
Game 1 of the division series against Houston and struck out 16
Astros, returning four days later to start Game 3. If he were to
start Monday, there's the possibility he'd be available to work out
of the bullpen should the series go to a seventh game Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, probable Game 5 starter Andy Ashby had Atlanta
hitters off-balance in the NLCS opener and allowed but a run over
seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   It's not over yet
</P>
<P>
   Up 2-0 in the series and with a Qualcomm Stadium crowd of
65,000-plus expected this afternoon, the Padres aren't taking
anything for granted. Manager Bruce Bochy says his players are
``too intelligent'' to even think their tickets already have been
punched to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two games, you haven't done anything,'' Bochy said. ``It's
nice to win two games, but we still have to continue to play the
way we're playing right now. That's as good a club over there as
there is in the big leagues. Atlanta, you look at their defense and
offense. ... We can't relax.''
</P>
<P>
   With the warmer temperatures this afternoon in San Diego, Bochy
said there's a slight possibility left fielder Greg Vaughn
(strained quadriceps) could be back in the lineup. Bochy said
Vaughn has made a lot of progress since the injury in Game 1, and
he indicated a desire to play this afternoon, but Bochy is more
inclined to sit him another day.
</P>
<P>
   And the winner is ...
</P>
<P>
   When the topic of debate turns to the Cy Young Award, the
Braves-Padres series has the National League field virtually
blanketed. Atlanta left-hander Tom Glavine and San Diego closer
Trevor Hoffman rank as the favorites, followed by the Padres' Kevin
Brown and the Braves' Greg Maddux and John Smoltz.
</P>
<P>
   So who takes it? Cox likes Glavine. Padres manager Bochy favors
Hoffman, who converted 53 of 54 save opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a closer is more fitted for MVP,'' Braves manager
Bobby Cox said. ``But whoever you pick, you can't go wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   No three-and-out
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Braves have made a habit of waltzing through the
first round of the playoffs, Cox is among a growing number of
baseball people opposed to the best-of-five division series. Cox
and others would prefer a best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw what went on with the Cubs, the Mets and the Giants
(playing for the NL wild card),'' he said. ``They deserve better
than five-game series. It's just not fair to play that long, and
have it end so quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends
</P>
<P>
   Cox on the change at first base from Fred McGriff to Andres
Galarraga: ``Mac was a quiet leader. Andres is more verbal.'' ...
The Padres are the 12th team to own a 2-0 lead in the NLCS, and no
club has come back to earn a World Series berth after losing the
first two games at home. ... Around the NL, the contention is
Atlanta pitchers benefit from a generous strike zone, particularly
offerings just off the plate by Glavine that are often called
strikes. Tony Gwynn has said he takes his hacks right away against
the Braves, because anything is liable to be called a strike. But
in the first two games, Atlanta pitchers have issued 13 walks,
including season highs by Glavine (six) and Smoltz (five).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
