<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PADRESIDE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Leyritz hopes for another delivery
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ He's the chunky guy with the shaved head. Hardly the
look of a big leaguer dubbed Mr. October Jr., but Jim Leyritz cares
less about appearance than being in the fray come postseason.
</P>
<P>
   And this afternoon, Leyritz gets his first full-time duty in the
NLCS, serving as the personal catcher for lefty Sterling Hitchcock
in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   That's bad news for the Braves after nemesis Kevin Brown
continued his mastery in Game 2, as Leyritz has his own storied
history against the locals. Leyritz is still remembered for his
game-tying, three-run homer off Mark Wohlers in Game 4 of the 1996
Word Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife replays it when I come home and I'm slumping,''
Leyritz said of his vintage moment with the New York Yankees. ``She
says: 'You know how to hit, you've done it before.' It's a moment.
It was nice to have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a 3 1/2-year old boy that watches my hitting tapes.
It's on in his room every now and then, and I catch a glimpse of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz staged more highlight clips in the NL division series
against the Houston Astros, homering to tie one game and winning
another. Yet with first baseman Wally Joyner's strained shoulder
well enough for him to play, Leyritz has had only two late-inning
at-bats in Game 1 of this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be lying if I said I was happy,'' Leyritz said of his
reduced role. ``I was disappointed. The bottom line is it's a
seven-game series and I'm going to catch Hitchcock. This one game
might make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   When Leyritz joined the Padres in a midseason trade from the
Boston Red Sox, Hitchcock asked that Leyritz catch him because
they'd worked together when both were Yankees. Hitchcock claims
it's a confidence thing.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine, but what Leyritz does best is hit in the clutch. A
.269 career hitter, he's hit more than 10 home runs in a season
only three times in his eight-year career _ though making a name
for himself in the playoffs as a Yankee and now a Padre.
</P>
<P>
   ``His flair for the dramatic borders on unbelievable,'' said
Brown. ``He's the kind of guy who wants to be in those
situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz says it dates back to his years in New York, learning to
cope under the daily spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always joked that I get paid for April and October,'' he
said. ``April, most of the guys are hurt out of spring training and
I get to play a little more, and I've had some success in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``And throughout my career, because I've never been an everyday
player, every game that I've been in has kind of been a World
Series for me. I had to perform if I wanted to play again.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, he's paid handsome dividends for the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
