</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCARNOTES10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New rules for testing considered
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLADEGA, Ala. _ NASCAR officials are considering new testing
rules for 1999 that will make it more difficult for multi-car teams
to gain an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Under NASCAR's proposal, which is likely to be approved, each
manufacturer will be given four or five test sessions similar to
the GM and Ford tests held prior to each season.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules and test dates could be announced as early as the
end of October to allow teams to begin making plans for next
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal in whatever we do is to try and establish more
control in knowing who goes where and when and with whom,'' said
Kevin Triplett, NASCAR's director of operations. ``The whole thing
with the testing policy is economics.''
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR will likely have inspectors present at the sanctioned
tests to police which teams participate.
</P>
<P>
   Secure at last
</P>
<P>
   Wally Dallenbach Jr. no longer has to wonder where his next ride
will come from in 1999. The veteran Winston Cup driver will drive
the Hendrick Motorsports Chevrolet, which has been piloted by a
succession of drivers since Ricky Craven was released in
mid-August. Dallenbach has been at the wheel for 11 races this
year, including the last eight as a fill-in. He's posted three top
10 finishes in those 11 events. ``I really appreciate John
(Hendrick) and everybody at Budweiser for giving me this
opportunity,'' Dallenbach said.
</P>
<P>
   Number 500
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's Winston 500 will be the 500th start for Geoff Bodine,
becoming only the 19th driver in NASCAR history to reach that
milestone. ``It's something I'm very proud of,'' said Bodine, whose
first career victory came at Martinsville in 1984. ``They really
don't mean anything. ... They're just reminders of who we are and
what we are and what we've gone through. The world doesn't stop
when they happen, and certainly the world won't stop this weekend
at Talladega for my 500th start.''
</P>
<P>
   In memory of
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-year-old Thad Coleman of Greenville, S.C., starts 27th in
today's ARCA Bondo Hyde series with one objective _ to honor his
son Chad Coleman. Coleman died Aug. 28th from injuries he suffered
after hitting the wall head-on at Atlanta Motor Speedway Aug. 28.
``I'm racing here in memory of my son,'' said Coleman, who hasn't
raced since 1992. ``I'm sure he would want me to drive it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
