<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCARPOLE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Banzai run' for Schrader
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Server
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLADEGA, Ala. _ With most projections leaning in the direction
of the Labonte Brothers, Terry and Bobby, it was Ken Schrader who
stole the show and won the pole for Sunday's Winston 500.
</P>
<P>
   Schrader put his name in the Talladega record book with a lap of
196.153 mph and his first pole of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our restrictor plate program has always been good,'' said
Schrader, who is riding a seven-year winless streak. ``Our problem
is finishing. We were wrecked at Daytona (in the 125s) and wrecked
here in the spring. I haven't won in forever.''
</P>
<P>
   It's Schrader's fourth top 10 start in the last seven races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was going to be a good lap,'' he said. ``We never
made a full-fledged banzai run in practice, never put all that tape
on it and do all those other things. But, we're really happy with
it. It's a brand new car, and we might have something for the big
boys this week.''
</P>
<P>
   The big boys are Jeff Gordon and Mark Martin, who have their
eyes on the ultimate prize, the Winston Cup championship. Their
qualifying runs produced almost identical results. Gordon took the
sixth spot with a lap of 194.154 mph and Martin eighth in 194.058.
</P>
<P>
   ``This weekend we wanted to start a little closer to the front
and see if we can stay there,'' said Gordon, referring to last
week's 26th start at Charlotte. ``Come Sunday, it's going to be a
whole lot of drafting out there, and the guy who drafts the best is
going to win the thing. I think one of the guys going for the
million is going to win the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's viewpoint is anything is better here than one year ago
when he qualified 38th and had to take a provisional start and
finished 23rd, eight laps down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to then, I feel like we sat on the pole today,''
Martin said. ``I gotta take my hat off to these guys (in the shop).
I didn't think it was going to be that good.''
</P>
<P>
   Following Schrader were Bobby Labonte, Dale Jarrett, Terry
Labonte and Mike Skinner.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Buckshot Jones surprised by qualifying 11th. That's
three spots ahead of Dale Earnhardt, his best showing since Pocono
11 races ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost a little time, but we're not worried about that,''
Jones said. ``We just wanted to make the first round. The guys did
a great job with the car. But the big deal is going to be Sunday.
We want to finish this race.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
