<HEADLINE>
GALAXY MUST SURVIVE CLASH OF STYLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ In the most beguiling matchup on the road to
Major League Soccer's championship, the Los Angeles Galaxy and its
strike-at-any-time attack faces a most difficult challenge: how to
solve the maze constructed by the Chicago Fire's defense while
remaining true to its beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy will give it a go at the Rose Bowl, where the
best-of-three Western Conference series kicks off tonight with a
battle of styles and wits and of philosophies that is as much chess
match as soccer game.
</P>
<P>
   It's MLS' most potent attack against its toughest defense, the
high-flying ``showtime'' of the Galaxy's Cobi Jones against the
hard-nosed workmanship of the Fire's Lubos Kubik and Chris Armas.
Whichever is employed most skillfully, with fewer breakdowns, will
find a place in MLS Cup '98.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very tough when everybody's behind the ball and everybody
is matched up man to man,'' said Galaxy coach Octavio Zambrano,
whose attack found the going rough against Chicago during the
regular season, splitting four very tight encounters with the Fire.
``They defend as a priority and we attack as a priority.... It's a
matter of tastes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play our game. We have to make sure we're patient
and we have to make sure that we are constantly trying to break
them.''
</P>
<P>
   To do both, simultaneously, is the puzzle confronting L.A. It
wants to play its freewheeling style that requires space and
movement against a Fire squad that will attempt to limit both, then
counter the Galaxy's aggressiveness with an opportunistic offense
led by playmaker Peter Nowak.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a test of patience,'' said Galaxy defender Robin
Fraser. ``We need to pick and choose the moments we throw
everything into attack and we need to wait for the right
opportunity.... We need to play well. We need to execute. Chicago
is a very organized team and they're not going to give you
anything, so everything we do we need to do sharply, we need to do
crisply.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's kind of the bottom line. The team that executes better
is going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The key could be how well Armas, the former Galaxy midfielder
responsible for marking opponents' playmakers, can shut down
Mauricio Cienfuegos, who had five assists in L.A.'s first-round
sweep of Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see (that) week in and week out with Cien,'' said Fraser of
the tactic. ``But Chris is the best at it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
