<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANTS BY STEINBRENNER EARN A FINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The American League announced shortly before the
start of Game 3 Friday night that it had fined George Steinbrenner,
the New York Yankees' principal owner, an undisclosed amount for
``inappropriate comments'' about the umpiring in Game 2 of the
league championship series.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, Steinbrenner told a crowd of reporters that
Ted Hendry, the plate umpire in the game, was known to be among the
worst umpires in the league, adding that it was ``too bad this
great game had to be decided by a call like that.'' Hendry did not
call interference on a play at first base in the 12th inning of
Game 2; as play continued, the Indians scored the lead run and went
on to win, 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees manager Joe Torre was also critical of Hendry's
umpiring, on balls and strikes calls and on the play at first base,
and Torre, too, might have been fined. But the AL does not
acknowledge or announce fines of on-field personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner was generally not in a good mood Wednesday. USA
Today founder Allen Neuharth was quoted in The St. Paul Pioneer
Press as saying that he was in Steinbrenner's private box when
Chuck Knoblauch did not pick up the ball on the disputed bunt play
and that the Yankee owner ranted angrily after the play was
botched. The newspaper quoted Neuharth as saying that he mentioned
to Steinbrenner that he was flying to Minnesota on Thursday, and
Steinbrenner responded by saying he should take Knoblauch with him.
Steinbrenner could not be immediately reached for comment Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   After Wednesday's game, Steinbrenner made a point of going to
Knoblauch and telling him to keep his chin up, something the second
baseman said he appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   A Message From Torre
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre held a brief team meeting before Game 3, delivering a
simple and short message that he had been thinking about since his
Yankees lost Game 2 in such a bizarre fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to make sure we go out there and think about
tonight instead of trying to make up for something that happened
the other day,'' Torre said. ``Everything is so consumed with the
umpires, Chuck Knoblauch, and you just can't do anything about
that. Whatever the results were the other day, whoever messed up,
it's over with, and we can't do a thing about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I think managers' meetings are for him, for the
manager. Just so you feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   Gooden's Game 4 Outlook
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Gooden of Cleveland said Friday that starting the fourth
game of the AL Championship Series is what matters to him, not that
he is pitching against his former team. The Yankees declined to
pick up Gooden's $3 million option for 1999, allowing him to sign
with the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you take the mound, they're just another ball club,''
Gooden said about Saturday night's game. ``You might not believe
that, but that's what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gooden claimed that George Steinbrenner talked to him
about returning this season and that there would have been an
opportunity for him to come back. Even though Gooden said he felt
``it was time to move on,'' the Yankees obviously made that
decision for him by not exercising the option.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still felt I had a lot to give to that ball club,'' Gooden
said. ``Joe Torre thought differently, which you have to respect;
it's his club. The only thing that was tough for me leaving was
that I was leaving the city of New York, where I had been my whole
career.''
</P>
<P>
   Saving Strawberry's Place
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Strawberry was honored before Game 3. His place in line
during pre-game introductions was left open and the Indians flashed
his picture and a message for good wishes on the scoreboard.
</P>
</TEXT>
