<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO BE THE BEST, STARS MUST BEAT THE BEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can it be hockey season again already?
</P>
<P>
   It seems like only last week that the Stars trudged off the ice
in Detroit, pondering what went wrong and how they would ever stop
it.
</P>
<P>
   It seems like only last week that their ears stopped ringing
from the Joe Louis Arena din that they left behind. Red Wings fans,
the best in hockey, seem to love beating a bunch of
Eddie-Come-Latelies like the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to argue. While they're out raking leaves and
preparing for hockey season, we're still wearing shorts and
watching TV reports about Mike Modano's backswing. They drive
American cars; we don't even eat American food. They have a higher
per capita rate of guys named Vinny; the Stars' average fan is
named Todd.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing that Wings fans don't have anymore: the best team
in hockey.
</P>
<P>
   If I'm reading the national hockey magazines and the horoscopes
correctly, that honor now falls to the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   There is no cup that comes with it. But like the signs at the
theme parks say _ hold your arm out here _ you must be this good to
ride the roller coaster to the Stanley Cup Finals. And the Stars,
at last, are big enough.
</P>
<P>
   The ride begins tonight, when the best goaltender in the world,
Buffalo's Dominik Hasek, pays a timely visit. If the Stars, as
advertised, have solved their modest scoring deficiencies of a year
ago, Hasek will stamp their passports.
</P>
<P>
   A better test would figure to come a few weeks from now when Joe
Nieuwendyk makes his anticipated return to the ice. Injuries, those
good fans in Detroit will tell you, are an unrelenting part of
hockey.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Stars' case, losing Nieuwendyk 20 minutes into the
first round of the playoffs was a death blow. It robbed the Stars
of their scoring depth and, instead of strangling foes with
mismatches, it allowed opponents to concentrate on Modano.
</P>
<P>
   Since you brought it up _ that thug Bryan Marchment comes to
town with the San Jose Sharks in two weeks. Where are the Vinnys
when the Stars need them?
</P>
<P>
   It was Marchment, of course, who escorted Nieuwendyk's knee into
the boards at Reunion Arena and might well have changed the course
of the 1997-98 playoffs. But all's well that ends well for Stars
fans. Without Marchment, there might not be a Brett Hull.
</P>
<P>
   For the Stars to make good on all those magazine covers, Hull
will have to have a productive, democratic and, yes, somewhat
unusual season.
</P>
<P>
   Note to coach Ken Hitchcock, heretofore known as Colonel Hitch:
You want Hull to play ``what?''
</P>
<P>
   Hull has played with talented linemates before (See Gretzky,
Wayne). Hull has been asked to play defense before (See Keenan,
Mike). And Hull has never won a Stanley Cup before.
</P>
<P>
   But that's where Colonel Hitch comes in. If he can convince
players like Modano, Nieuwendyk and Pat Verbeek to be ``defensively
responsible'' _ ``suck the offense right out of them,'' as veteran
Craig Ludwig calls it _ maybe Hitch plus peer pressure can make a
happy camper out of Hull.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, simply having Hull on the ice with Modano and Jere
Lehtinen will present daunting matchup problems for most teams. The
Stars' power play prowess also figures to take a quantum leap.
</P>
<P>
   The other new piece to the puzzle is Brent Severyn, the
anti-Marchment. His added contribution may end up being more
noticed than even Hull's.
</P>
<P>
   When appropriately bristled, the Stars can now send out a line
that includes Severyn, last year's playoff hero Brian Skrudland and
Grant Marshall. They should get the ``energy level'' flowing again,
as Hitchcock likes to term it.
</P>
<P>
   Does it add up to the _ trumpets and choir, please _ best team
in hockey?
</P>
<P>
   As defenseman and team captain Derian Hatcher said yesterday, in
signing a new four-year contract, ``This is a great organization
and definitely one of the best in hockey, if not ``the'' best.''
</P>
<P>
   It is. But again, there is no cup that comes with that.
</P>
<P>
   The road to the rainbow still will have to go through Joe Louis
Arena at some point. The king will have to be dethroned before
there's a new king.
</P>
<P>
   It starts tonight with the world's best goalie in town. Hockey
season already?
</P>
<P>
   It's about time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 2317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
