<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the IRS Calendar, It's April in October
</P>
<P>
   The annual income-tax deadline _ the real one _ is at hand. On
Thursday, a few million citizens will have to file 1997 returns,
their six-month free ride at an end.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, the Internal Revenue Service publicizes a taxpayer's
right to apply for a four-month extension past April 15, a request
rarely denied. Some 7 million took advantage of the provision this
year, up from 6.4 million in 1997 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Not as well known is that these late filers can just as easily
get another two months, until Oct. 15. The IRS has no estimate of
the number who did that this year, but there were 2.3 million last
year.
</P>
<P>
   For many of the late filers, the extension amounts to a free
loan from Uncle Sam, as long as they have paid at least 90 percent
of their taxes in withholding or installments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, if you've paid 90 percent of your tax liability,
there's no penalty or interest'' due on the remainder paid by Oct.
15, said Terry Lemons, an IRS spokesman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ROBERT D. HERSHEY JR. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Moneyed Young America, With Great Expectations
</P>
<P>
   The robust economy may have everyone feeling a bit flush, but a
survey of young Americans suggests that the money culture is
building some strongly materialistic desires.
</P>
<P>
   Yankelovich Partners, working for the Phoenix Home Life Mutual
Insurance Co., interviewed 1,262 students aged 12 to 21 in
households with at least one parent earning $40,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that 57 percent expect to be wealthier than
their parents, up from 52 percent in a 1996 survey. Moreover, only
18 percent expect that they will have to work harder than their
parents to achieve that wealth.
</P>
<P>
   On average, college students in the survey expect an annual
starting salary of $36,000, up from $32,000 in 1997; 18 percent
expect $50,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   As for money and the comforts it can secure, 35 percent agreed
that ``being able to buy what you want'' is a very important
objective in adulthood, up from 31 percent in 1996; 15 percent said
the same about ``having a million dollars,'' up from 11 percent;
and 8 percent said it of ``owning an expensive car,'' up from 5
percent. Not all impulses were focused on the self: 41 percent said
that ``giving money to charity'' is very important, up from 36
percent two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   _ DANIEL M. GOLD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Footloose Worker: Why Employers Aren't Dancing
</P>
<P>
   Yet another indicator of the strength of the economy: Employee
turnover and retention have become significant problems for
American businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey of 378 companies in 15 industries by Manchester
Inc., a management consulting firm based in Bala-Cynwyd, Pa., more
than half _ 52 percent _ said turnover had increased in the past
year.
</P>
<P>
   The average annual turnover rate is now about 15 percent, with
more than a third of the responding companies saying turnover is
higher than 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Retail and food service industries have the highest turnover,
about 30 percent annually, while the chemical and utilities
industries report the lowest, at less than 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ DANIEL M. GOLD
</P>
</TEXT>
