<SLUG> BC-BBN-ONDECK310-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On deck for NLCS Game 3
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   -- When: 4:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   -- Where: Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   -- Radio/TV: Channel 5, WSB 750-AM.
</P>
<P>
   -- Probable starting pitchers: RHP Greg Maddux (18-9, 2.22 ERA;
18-9, 2.72 lifetime vs. Padres) vs. LHP Sterling Hitchcock (9-7,
3.93; 0-1, 5.65 lifetime vs. Braves.)
</P>
<P>
   -- Series history: Atlanta leads the all-time series 272-216 and
won its eighth straight season series 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   -- Past meetings: The Braves were 1-2 at Qualcomm Stadium this
season, the first losing record the club has accumulated there
since going 4-5 in 1991. Since the Padres joined the league,
Atlanta has a 130-115 record in San Diego, going 36-30 the past 10
years. In the Braves' only visit to Qualcomm this season, the
Padres beat Denny Neagle and Maddux on successive nights (Aug.
11-12), Maddux losing 5-1 to Andy Ashby. Tom Glavine averted the
sweep Aug. 13 in a 5-0 victory over Mark Langston. Atlanta managed
to outscore the Padres 33-29 and out-homer San Diego 11-6 over the
season. All the Padres' victories came against Atlanta starters.
</P>
<P>
   -- Padres leaders: Avg. _ Tony Gwynn (.321); HR _ Greg Vaughn
(50); RBI _ Vaughn (119); SB _ Quilvio Veras (24). W _Kevin Brown
(18); ERA _ Trevor Hoffman (1.48). Saves _ Hoffman (53). Strikeouts
_ Brown (257).
</P>
<P>
   -- Maddux update: Maddux is working on six days rest, having
last pitched in last Saturday's LDS-clinching game in Chicago. He
beat the Cubs 6-2, allowing both runs on seven hits while striking
out four. Maddux has a 2.51 ERA on the road, the second-lowest in
the league after Glavine (1.78). If he is vulnerable, it has been
early. Opponents have hit .290 against hit in the first inning but
the average tapers from there all the way down to .202 after the
seventh. Maddux's groundball/flyball ratio (3.25) was the best in
the majors this season. Expect the Padres to challenge him on the
bases. Everyone else does. Maddux allowed 28 stolen bases this
year, second-most in the league.
</P>
<P>
   -- Hitchcock update: He is a streak pitcher and after beating
Houston last Sunday to clinch the LDS, he appears to be on an
upward streak (six innings, three hits, one run, 11 strikeouts).
Hitchcock finished the year with only two wins in his last seven
starts. He tied the Padres club record for strikeouts Aug. 29, when
he fanned 15 against Montreal, testimony to how effective his
split-finger fastball can be. He is a far better pitcher at
Qualcomm, where he went 6-2 with a 2.68 ERA, nearly 2 1/2 runs
lower than his season rate. He drew no decision in his only start
against the Braves this year, but deserved better at Turner Field
May 9. He left the game with a 3-0 lead after the sixth, only to
have the Padres bullpen give up six runs in the last three innings
in a 6-4 Atlanta win.
</P>
<P>
   -- Who's hot: Gerald Williams, who gets his first NLCS start, is
2-for-6 against Hitchcock with four walks. Chipper Jones and Andruw
Jones are a combined 7-for-15 against him with four RBIs. Tony
Gwynn owns Maddux, as he does the Braves' top three starters, with
a .455 career average. Padres pinch-hitter John Vander Wal has
faced Maddux only once but homered off him in April when he was
still playing in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   -- Who's not: Andres Galarraga may have picked the wrong pitcher
for breaking out of his postseason slump. He is 1-for-7 lifetime
against Hitchcock, which is slightly better than Walt Weiss
(0-for-5). Padres center fielder Chuck Finley has a .197 career
average against Maddux. Wally Joyner is hitting just .190 but he
will be on the bench tonight in place of Jim Leyritz, who has never
faced Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
