<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Much is worth watching today
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's on Saturdays like this that your faithful
prognosticator becomes torn. Like all who love college football, he
wants to be in a football stadium somewhere soaking up the local
color. But one look at today's schedule makes him long for the
couch and the remote control.
</P>
<P>
   There is just too much good college football going on today to
confine one to a single locale: Two great showdowns in the SEC . .
. two more in the Big 12 . . . a late game between two Pac-10
powers . . . it's days like this that keep sports bars in business.
</P>
<P>
   We've gone 17-3 two straight weeks. Here's trying to keep the
streak going.
</P>
<P>
   No. 4 Tennessee (4-0) at No. 7 Georgia (4-0), 3:30 p.m. (CBS):
This game took a decided turn when UT running back Jamal Lewis was
lost with a knee injury. Expect QB Tee Martin to play his best game
of the season. But Georgia has a hot quarterback in Quincy Carter
and the desire to end a seven-game losing streak to the Vols.
Georgia 28, Tennessee 24.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech (3-1) at No. 23 N.C. State (3-1), 3:30 p.m.
(Channel 2): N.C. State has beaten a No. 2 (Florida State) and No.
11 (Syracuse) at home and lost on the road to Baylor. Georgia Tech
has beaten three bad teams but is improving. Quarterback Joe
Hamilton is having another superb season, leading the ACC and
ranking ninth nationally in passing efficiency. The Jackets are
capable of winning if they can control the ball and keep the
Wolfpack offense of the field. Georgia Tech 21, N.C. State 17.
</P>
<P>
   No. 11 LSU (3-1) at No. 6 Florida (4-1), 7 p.m. (ESPN): Jesse
Palmer will start at quarterback for the Gators, but he won't stay
there unless he can cure Florida's red zone blues. The Gators have
only 10 touchdowns in 22 trips inside the 20. LSU, it turns out, is
overrated, especially on defense. Florida 42, LSU 20.
</P>
<P>
   No. 5 Kansas State (4-0) at No. 14 Colorado (5-0), 7 p.m. (FX):
After playing a bunch of cupcakes, Kansas State finds out if it's
for real. The Wildcats will be stronger at running back with Frank
Murphy reinstated after a flap with the NCAA. Colorado is
undefeated but has had to squeak by some average teams. Kansas
State 31, Colorado 21.
</P>
<P>
   No. 2 Nebraska (5-0) at No. 18 Texas A&AMP;M (4-1), 3:30 p.m.: The
Cornhuskers were flat last week against Oklahoma State and it
nearly cost them. Now they must go back on the road with a
banged-up Bobby Newcombe at quarterback. But the Texas A&AMP;M offense,
as always, is woefully predictable. That won't cut it against the
Huskers. Nebraska 35, Texas A&AMP;M 17.
</P>
<P>
   No. 3 UCLA (3-0) at No. 10 Arizona (5-0), 10 p.m. (Fox SS): The
winner becomes the favorite in the Pac-10. Arizona won a thriller
last week against Washington and is becoming a darkhorse for the
national title. Since UCLA didn't play at Miami because of
Hurricane Georges, we're still not sure how good the Bruins are.
Arizona is deserving of this week's Upset Special. Arizona 17, UCLA
14.
</P>
<P>
   No. 8 Florida State (4-1) at Miami (3-1), 3:30 p.m.: This used
to be the best game in college football but Miami is trying to
rebuild from NCAA sanctions. Florida State has more talented
players but had better not struggle on offense and give the 'Canes
some hope. Miami would dearly love to atone for last year's 47-0
embarrassment in Tallahassee. Florida State 24, Miami 14.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn (1-3) at Miss. State (3-1), 12:30 p.m. (WXIA): With a
trip to Florida looming next week, it would behoove Auburn to find
a way to win. But no amount of coaching and motivation can overcome
the fact that Auburn is using too many young players on offense.
Miss. State 14, Auburn 7.
</P>
<P>
   -- THE REST
</P>
<P>
   SEC _ Alabama 28, Ole Miss 17; Vanderbilt 10, Western Michigan
7; Arkansas 31, Memphis 10; Kentucky 35, South Carolina 20.
</P>
<P>
   ACC _ Clemson 21, Maryland 17; North Carolina 17, Pittsburgh 10;
Wake Forest 28, Duke 20.
</P>
<P>
   Top 25 _ No. 1 Ohio State 45, Illinois 14; Purdue 24, No. 12
Wisconsin 23; No. 13 Penn State 28, Minnesota 10; Arizona State 17,
No. 22 Notre Dame 14.
</P>
<P>
   Last week: 17-3
</P>
<P>
   Season's record: 70-27 (72.2)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
