A9729 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UGA-SCENE10-COX     10-09 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-SCENE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fans flock to see game with Tennessee
 &HT;    By Plott Brice
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS _ To paraphrase Larry Munson, this town is rocking.
</P>
<P>
   Automobiles filled with football fans began to flood the city
Friday as road work on Atlanta Highway further congested traffic.
On U.S. 441, an armada of campers and RVs streamed into Clarke
County, then circled the Stegeman Coliseum parking lot, waiting to
pounce on the first-come, first-served spots that opened to
football fans at 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   As members of the national media arrived in droves, the
40-person staff of ESPN's ``College Game Day'' prepared to make the
University of Georgia and Sanford Stadium the focus of the college
football world. The College Game Day crew of Chris Fowler, Lee
Corso and Kirk Herbstreit began broadcasting Friday night from the
Tate Student Center behind the stadium. It's the first time the
national cable network has broadcast its popular all-day show from
Athens.
</P>
<P>
   Today's game against the Tennessee Volunteers is the biggest in
years for the Bulldogs. It's been sold out since March, but that
hasn't stopped people from trying, even flooding the Georgia ticket
office with calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been here 16 years and the only thing that comes close
is the year Florida played here (1995),'' said Freddy Jones,
Georgia's assistant athletics director for ticket operations.
``It's been unbelievable. Everyone wants tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone wants them, but no one's getting any from the Georgia
ticket office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say 90 percent of the calls we get are from people who
already have tickets but want one for a friend or relative,'' Jones
said. ``Businesses call. Some elected officials. They know the
situation. I guess they feel they have to make that one last try.
The fact is, there are none.''
</P>
<P>
   None, that is, unless you're willing to deal with street
capitalism, where opportunists welcome the inquiries of the
desperate.
</P>
<P>
   Some are ``letting'' their tickets go for as little as $75 each,
while some are bringing as much as $150, a downtown barber said
Friday. Some say the value per ticket is even higher.
</P>
<P>
   On campus Thursday afternoon, junior Brian Williby, a
21-year-old from Savannah, said there's ``no way I would sell my
ticket. But I know two students who sold theirs for $80 each.''
Williby said the two had a commitment out of town this weekend;
otherwise they'd be at the game.
</P>
<P>
   At the Tate Student Center, handwritten posters offered student
tickets at ``best offer.'' Some were willling to trade their
Tennessee tickets for Florida tickets. Buying tickets from any
source other than the UGA ticket office has its caveats. There are
some who probably remember all too well buying counterfeit tickets
to last year's Auburn game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say to anyone that if you buy from anyone other than us,
you are taking a chance,'' said Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said Georgia officials have pretty much undercut
counterfeit tickets, although it's possible someone may still try.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a hologram on this year's ticket that is darn near
impossible to duplicate. The 'Georgia' on the ticket is a hologram.
We've tried to copy it three different ways and we couldn't do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who enters the gate with a student ticket will be asked
to show a student ID. And after a theft of some 60 student tickets
Thursday, potential buyers should look closely. A bicyclist
snatched the tickets from a window at the Coliseum ticket office.
The tickets, reportedly for section 311, were to be picked up by
students who bought season ticket coupons at the beginning of the
season. Coupons must be redeemed for tickets before each game.
</P>
<P>
   The game has also attracted nationwide interest from several
media outlets. CBS will televise the game live; its crew of 75 hit
town earlier this week. More than 200 magazine and newspaper
reporters, including writers from Sports Illustrated, USA Today,
The New York Times, New York Post and New York Daily News, the
Washington Post, Boston Globe, Chicago Tribune and Los Angeles
Times, also will cover the game.
</P>
<P>
   The game is also expected to provide a financial windfall for
area businessess and restaurants, many of which are planning to
bring in extra staff members to accommodate the rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of game where business booms,'' said Jamie
Lofton, owner of three Locos pubs in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown at the upscale Harry Bissett's New Orleans Cafe &AMP;
Oyster Bar, the excitement was building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We opened in1986 and the only thing that compares to this
would be the year Florida came here (in 1995). It's going to be
crazy here,'' said manager Jim White. ``You'd be surprised how many
people will come here hoping to get a ticket and how many people
will come here just to be in Athens for this game. They'll sit in a
bar and watch it on television.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
