u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-INDIANS-YANKS-ART     10-09 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-YANKS-ART-765&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANS ROCK PETTITTE AND YANKS, 6-1, FOR SERIES LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The Yankees, who rolled through the regular season
in record fashion and the first round of the American League
playoffs in a three-game sweep, suddenly find themselves reeling
and in jeopardy of losing their place in history.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Pettitte was rocked for four home runs Friday night _ three
in one four-batter sequence in the fifth inning _ as the Cleveland
Indians rolled to a 6-1 victory that put the Yankees behind, 2
games to 1, in the best-of-seven AL Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Thome hit two of Cleveland's four home runs, as the Yankees
principal owner George Steinbrenner looked on sullenly, his chin in
his palm.
</P>
<P>
   With the Yankees desperately in need of a victory that would
even the series, Orlando Hernandez, the Cuban defector who is at
the end of his rookie season in the major leagues, will start Game
4 for the Yankees Saturday night against Dwight Gooden, the former
Met and Yankee who has never won a postseason game.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees seemed in command all season, finishing the year
with an American League record 114 victories. They stifled Texas in
the division series, sweeping the Rangers, holding them to only one
run.
</P>
<P>
   But the three consecutive victories against Texas and the five
runs the Yankees scored in the first inning of Game 1 of this
series masked a larger problem: Joe Torre's team has stopped
hitting. The Yankees had five runs and six hits in the first inning
of the series opener on Tuesday; in the 29 innings since, they have
a total of four runs and 16 hits. They went 4-for-7 with runners in
scoring position in the first inning of Game 1, and have gone only
2-for-21 in Games 2 and 3.
</P>
<P>
   Facing Cleveland's Bartolo Colon Friday night, the Yankees had
an advantageous situation: Colon had command only of his fastball.
But they managed only four hits, and after Chuck Knoblauch and
Bernie Williams each hit singles to provide a first-inning run, the
Yankees had only two hits and hit into three double plays.
</P>
<P>
   They would have had to score a bushel of runs, however, to
counter the horrid outing by Pettitte, who reverted to his form of
August and September that made Torre wonder if he would use
Pettitte as a starter in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The phone in the visitors' dugout at Jacobs Field is in the
opposite end from where the manager and coaches usually sit. When
calls are made to the bullpen, the pitching coach must get up and
walk the length of the visitors' dugout to reach the phone. Mel
Stottlemyre made this march repeatedly Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte fell behind seven of the first 10 batters he faced,
throwing ball one with his first pitch, and when he did stick the
ball over the plate, the Indians took full, destructive swings and
crushed the ball. Cleveland had runners at first and second with
two out in the first inning and Travis Fryman drove a line drive to
left _ directly at Shane Spencer, for the third out.
</P>
<P>
   Thome launched a 421-foot home run leading off the second
inning, however, and Mark Whiten ripped a double down the left
field line. Stottlemyre made his first trek to the bullpen phone;
Hideki Irabu began warming up. Enrique Wilson bounced a single
through the Yankees' drawn-in infield, scoring Whiten to make it
2-1. Pettitte barely got through the inning with Cleveland leading
by only a run.
</P>
<P>
   But Pettitte was like a dazed fighter at that point, waiting to
be knocked out, completely vulnerable. For Torre and Stottlemyre,
every out Pettitte recorded must have seemed like a miracle.
Somehow, Pettitte got through the third and fourth innings, using a
roundhouse curveball. They needed only to get him through the fifth
with the score close, and then Torre could give the ball to Ramiro
Mendoza.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte retired the first two hitters in the fifth inning. Just
one more out, one more out.
</P>
<P>
   With the count 0-1 on Manny Ramirez, Pettitte threw a fastball
low and away, a good pitch, and Ramirez reached out and slammed the
ball to right. Pettitte's head jerked as he watched the flight of
the ball _ and watched it carry into the Yankees' bullpen in right
field. Pettitte's body lurched in anger, as if he'd taken a fist in
the stomach.
</P>
<P>
   And he fell apart quickly. He walked Travis Fryman on a 3-2
pitch and Thome lifted a long drive that landed on the top of the
right field wall, and over, before Whiten, a former Yankee,
provided the coup de grace _ a tremendous 416-foot drive that fell
among the standing room only crowd far beyond the left field wall.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte turned and dropped his head, devastated by the beating.
He had never allowed four home runs in one game before.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As Torre emerged from the dugout to replace Pettitte, with the
score 6-1, David Wells and David Cone, two of Pettitte's brethren,
got up and walked into the runway, not wanting to see his
departure. Talking softly to himself, Pettitte walked off the
field, sat in the dugout, pulled on a jacket and got a cup of
water.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza warmed up and Pettitte stared onto the field, looking
straight ahead, his sightline frozen. Other Yankees approached him
and tapped him on the leg or the side _ Hang in there, man _ and
Pettitte never reacted, his eyes never moved. He didn't seem to
blink. Pettitte is extremely harsh in his self- indictments, and by
the look of him, he was staring ahead at a sleepless night or two.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   Shane Spencer was in Joe Torre's lineup for Game 3, in left
field, and Chili Davis made his first start as the designated
hitter, batting sixth. Tim Raines was not in the starting lineup,
Torre said, simply because he is not swinging well right now ...
The Indians have not officially announced their Game 5 starter, but
it appears that Chad Ogea will start in place of Jaret Wright, who
now shifts to the bullpen. The Yankees knocked out Wright in only
two-thirds of an inning in Game 1 and Ogea pitched well in relief.
</P>
</TEXT>
