<SLUG> BC-OBIT-PEARLMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPHEN PEARLMAN, 63, ACTOR IN MOVIES, TV AND THEATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KATHRYN SHATTUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stephen Pearlman, a versatile character actor in
theater, film and television, died Sept. 30 at his home in
Manhattan. He was 63.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, said his wife, Stefanie Solow Glennon.
</P>
<P>
   Tall, with a bellowing voice, Pearlman had a face that stirred
recognition on the street, though he was enough of an Everyman to
be often mistaken for a car salesman or store clerk, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Brooklyn and reared in Jersey City, N.J., Pearlman made
his living solely as an actor after his graduation from Dartmouth
College in 1954, where he acted in campus productions while
majoring in philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   He studied with Stella Adler and then worked for more than 40
years in genres ranging from the classics, in the American
Shakespeare Festival, to contemporary comedy, as an original member
of the Second City troupe in Chicago with Barbara Harris and Alan
Arkin.
</P>
<P>
   In 1959 Pearlman made his New York stage debut in ``The
Threepenny Opera'' at the Theater de Lys in Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   His off-Broadway credits also included Milton Erskine's ``Time
of the Key''; Arthur Miller's ``American Clock,'' in which he
played three characters, and ``A Shayna Maidel,'' of which he was
especially proud, having perfected a Yiddish accent for his role.
</P>
<P>
   He appeared on Broadway in the original productions of
``Barefoot in the Park,'' ``Children of a Lesser God'' and ``Six
Degrees of Separation,'' in which he played a Manhattan doctor who
gives his apartment keys to a young man posing as Sidney Poitier's
son.
</P>
<P>
   He also had a leading role in ``La Strada,'' Lionel Bart's 1969
musical starring Bernadette Peters and based on the movie by
Fellini.
</P>
<P>
   Pearlman's film credits included ``The Horse Whisperer,'' ``Die
Hard With a Vengeance,'' ``The First Wives Club'' and ``Quiz
Show.''
</P>
<P>
   On television, he was a guest star in episodes of ``Seinfeld''
and ``Law and Order.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearlman's most recent role was that of a Hasidic rabbi in
Darren Aronofsky's ``Pi,'' an independent film that won the
dramatic direction award at the Sundance Festival this year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, he is survived by two stepdaughters,
Leah Glennon of Brooklyn and Hope Glennon of San Francisco; his
mother, Ruth W. Pearlman of Jersey City, and two grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 2351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
