</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-FLYERS-235&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLYERS' VANBIESBROUCK THWARTS RANGERS IN OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Low-scoring hockey need not be boring. The New York
Rangers and the Philadelphia Flyers demonstrated that Friday night
at Madison Square Garden in their energetic season opener. The pace
was brisk, the hitting hard, the chances plentiful around the nets.
</P>
<P>
   Although the show was entertaining for the loud capacity crowd,
the result was unsatisfying for the home fans as the Flyers headed
home with a 1-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia got a power-play goal from Alexandre Daigle and a
shutout from goalie John Vanbiesbrouck, a former Ranger, who
stopped 20 shots. The Rangers had other shots at Philadelphia's
net, but they were blocked by Vanbiesbrouck's teammates, often a
sign of a cohesive team.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers, Stanley Cup finalists in 1997, were ousted in the
first round of last season's playoffs and hope to return to loftier
status in the Atlantic Division, the Eastern Conference and the
National Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers came close to evening the score with three seconds
remaining, after they had pulled goalie Mike Richter for an extra
attacker. Esa Tikkanen, uncovered next to the Philadelphia net,
fanned on a shot attempt and then broke his stick over the net in
frustration just before the buzzer sounded.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also complained on the play because Philadelphia's
Eric Lindros sent the stick of New York's John MacLean down the ice
after MacLean lost his grip on it.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   John Muckler took over last February as coach of the Blue
Shirts, but this was the debut of the new system that he hopes to
install in his first full season. His players put pressure on the
puck, even though two of his centers were really left wings who
were assigned to check Lindros. Muckler also got bursts of energy
from his fourth line of Harry York, Darren Langdon and Mike Knuble.
</P>
<P>
   Not in uniform was Manny Malhotra, the Rangers' rookie center
who was drafted in the first round last June and signed his first
contract this week. Although Muckler said he wanted ``to give the
veterans a chance,'' there was a practical reason for not starting
the promising 18-year-old Malhotra against a team like the Flyers
on opening night at home: Flyers coach Roger Neilson might have put
Lindros, the big center, against the Ranger rookie.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros, who is talented and powerful, might have initiated
Malhotra with skill and physical intimidation, resulting in a
setback to his confidence. Better to let Malhotra make his debut
against a lesser team, under less pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Checking Lindros for many shifts was Adam Graves, normally a
center who was moved to the middle this time. Also assigned to Big
88 was Niklas Sundstrom, a left wing last season who will probably
be the Rangers' second-line center, unless the Rangers make a
trade.
</P>
<P>
   The game marked the Philadelphia debut of Vanbiesbrouck, the
veteran goalie who was signed as a free agent from the Florida
Panthers. In the Ranger net was Richter, who used to share time
with Vanbiesbrouck when both were Rangers earlier in the decade. In
the first two periods, Richter was the busier goalie, stopping 20
of 21 shots. Vanbiesbrouck stopped all 11 that reached him in the
first 40 minutes and the Flyers held a 1-0 lead going into the
third period.
</P>
<P>
   Daigle, who scored the game's only goal, was acquired last
season from Ottawa in a trade. After Richter stopped an earlier
shot, the puck bounced high into the air, like a pop fly in
baseball. When it landed in front of the net, it set off a scramble
that included Philadelphia's Dave Babych knocking over Ranger
defenseman Jeff Beukeboom in the crease. With Beukeboom, Richter
and Brian Leetch tangled, Daigle found the loose puck and put it
over the line at 5 minutes 45 seconds of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   It was Philadelphia's fifth consecutive power play, and most of
them were legitimate. The Rangers could have got worse treatment
from the referee, Bill McCreary, when Ulf Samuelsson punched
Philadelphia defenseman Petr Svoboda in the face late in the first
period, drawing blood and instigating a brief fight. Although
Samuelsson could have been given a 10-minute misconduct or a game
misconduct, the referee gave him only two extra minutes for
roughing.
</P>
<P>
   SLAP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   When the Rangers visit Montreal on Saturday night for their
second game, they will play a depleted team. The Canadiens signed
their best defenseman, VLADIMIR MALAKHOV, to a two-year contract
Friday. Unsigned for Montreal are the forwards MARTIN RUCINSKY and
BRIAN SAVAGE. Defenseman PATRICE BRISEBOIS has back spasms, and
defenseman STEPHANE QUINTAL has a sinus infection.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Rangers officially signed ESA TIKKANEN, who came to
training camp on a free-agent tryout.
</P>
<P>
   _ KEVIN STEVENS, the Ranger left wing, has been put on waivers,
but that does not mean he is changing teams. Anyone claiming him
would have to pick up his salary of almost $3 million for this
season and next season. JOHN ROSASCO, spokesman for the Rangers,
said Stevens' waiver period lasts through Monday. Stevens played a
robust style, initiating many collisions, one of them injuring
Philadelphia's CHRIS THERIEN.
</P>
<P>
   _ . SCOTT FRASER, a Ranger right wing, missed Friday night's
game with a concussion he sustained in an exhibition game last
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
