A9738 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI &LR;      10-09 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON ON DEFENSIVE AS UTAH STATE COMES TO TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ When Wondame Davis' first serious fling in college
football had ended, he was virtually breathless in describing it to
Randy Hart, the University of Washington defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played like 37 plays,'' Hart says, ``and he said it seemed
like 10 minutes. He says, `Coach, I was getting the signal ... and
they were snapping the ball already!'''
</P>
<P>
   Which only goes to show you: Time flies ... and so does Arizona
quarterback Ortege Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not one of the game's best-ever clutch efforts _
Jenkins' loop-de-loop into the end zone with four seconds left to
play _ has departed their psyches, the Husky defenders must get
back on the field Saturday against Utah State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't got that much sleep this week, thinking back on
it,'' said linebacker Marques Hairston, one of the Huskies Jenkins
left on the ground when he went airborne for Arizona's winning
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to see that play again. I've seen it too many
times already.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona dramatically changed the landscape around the Huskies.
It snatched away the bonus Washington (2-2) had gained with the
stirring upset at Arizona State; it removed quarterback Brock Huard
and cornerback Jermaine Smith from the lineup for 2-3 weeks apiece,
to be replaced Saturday by Marques Tuiasosopo and Davis, who will
make his first college start.
</P>
<P>
   It robbed the Huskies of a burst of momentum off the Nebraska
mess, it refocused attention on the place-kicking follies, and it
got people to wondering why Washington has defended well at times
and hardly at all at others.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, Arizona didn't have much impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``By no means are we happy,'' Hart said, referring to the
defense. ``But there are reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies rank 83rd among 112 Division 1-A teams in total
defense. Nebraska can do that to you; play the Huskers, and you're
liable to spend the rest of the year trying to recoup a respectable
defensive ranking.
</P>
<P>
   For the next three weeks, it could be difficult to judge
Washington's defensive progress. After Utah State (1-4), the
Huskies host Cal and Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   While Cal and OSU have swatched together winning records, all
three Husky opponents have authored some miserable offense. Oregon
State is 87th nationally in total offense, Utah State is 90th and
Cal is 109th. If there ever were a time for the Husky defense to
get well, this is it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you saw us play against BYU, you know we can play better,''
said Hairston. ``If you saw us during spring, or two-a-days, you
know we can play better.''
</P>
<P>
   Hart and his cohorts have done a lot of head-scratching over the
defensive inconsistencies, and the consensus is that they have less
to do with mental breakdowns and blown coverages than they do
physical misplays.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches wear out listeners with the bromide ``We've got to make
plays.'' But that describes the Huskies, and no play is more
symbolic than Jenkins' leap.
</P>
<P>
   At times, Washington has played effective defense. The Huskies
stopped Arizona State just enough in the second half to give the
offense a chance to win, and they stuffed BYU, holding the Cougars
to 204 net yards.
</P>
<P>
   But on too many occasions, they didn't shed blocks against
Nebraska. Against Arizona, they allowed only five second-half first
downs until the final Wildcat possession _ and then five on that
drive.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive depth is young and the Huskies simply miss too
many tackles. On Trung Canidate's 37-yard touchdown run last week,
Washington shifted Lester Towns to his right over the tight end,
Arizona walled off pursuit, sent Canidate up the middle and he shed
free safety Brendan Jones' attempted tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Penalties are also taking a toll. After committing only 10 in
the first two games, Washington has 22 in the last two, many by
younger players who aren't yet distinguishing between valor and
discretion. Sophomore end Jeremiah Pharms decked the quarterback
after a whistle last week and Davis, who admits being a little
wired when he replaced Smith, was flagged for a personal foul on a
sideline tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little bit overwhelming for me,'' Davis says. ``I
didn't realize it (Smith's knee injury) was going to happen that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Offense, meanwhile, has been a struggle for Utah State, a
three-touchdown underdog to the Huskies. Quarterback Riley Jensen
is completing only 47 percent of his passes and the Aggies have
only 374 yards rushing in five games.
</P>
<P>
   Defense is a different story. Utah State ranks 16th nationally
and allows only 2.1 yards per rush, so even with the versatile
Tuiasosopo starting Saturday, offense could be at a premium for
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Says Utah State defensive line coach Mike Tuiasosopo, the cousin
of Marques' father Manu, ``He brings some things to the table, in
terms of preparation, that we don't get with the other kid
(Huard).''
</P>
<P>
   This is the replacement game for the Miami date (originally
Sept. 12) that the Huskies dropped to lighten a tough schedule. The
Aggies don't plan on allowing it to be a walkover.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess somebody wrote that this is the `Goodwill Games,'''
Mike Tuiasosopo said. ``So there's a little bit of,
Wow-what-a-slap-in-the-face. We're doing some very good things.
Quite honestly, our team is starting to come together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-09-98 2355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
