</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-HERNANDEZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERNANDEZ IS OUT TO STOP THE INDIANS COLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Armed with a video camera he recently purchased,
Orlando Hernandez walked through the Tower City Mall here Friday,
taping sights and sounds within a symbol of capitalism, for the
benefit of his two young daughters living in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, a Cuban defector, hopes, as well, that he has good
reason to send them videotape of his Game 4 start Saturday against
the Cleveland Indians and Dwight Gooden, the pitcher from whom
Hernandez adapted his high leg kick a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen days have passed since Hernandez last pitched _ he
threw five innings against Tampa Bay on Sept. 25 _ and he has told
coach Jose Cardenal that when he takes the mound Saturday, he will
be pitching in the coldest conditions he has ever faced, with
temperatures expected to be in the 40s. But Hernandez scoffed at
the idea that the required adjustments will be difficult for him,
recalling his past.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was pitching with the Cuban national team,'' Hernandez
said through an interpreter, Leonardo Astacio, ``we played in Italy
and Ireland, and other countries in Europe, and it was pretty cold.
I'm not sure what the temperatures were, but it was pretty cold.
And we all pretty much know my story _ I've been through some cold
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel that the cold on the field,'' he continued with a
smile, ``will affect my pitching tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez and Cardenal spoke about how the pitcher must adapt to
the cold. Hernandez plans to have much of his body rubbed down with
liniment to get ``as warm as possible.'' Hernandez will pitch
wearing a long-sleeved undershirt, and if he works up a sweat on
the mound, Cardenal said, Hernandez intends to return to the
clubhouse between innings, rather than sit in the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez has been trying to adapt to the colder weather since
he arrived in Florida in spring training. The weather in Tampa was
unusually frigid last March, and in his first days with the team
Hernandez would sometimes sit in front of his locker in a golf
shirt and Bermuda shorts, arms folded tightly, legs crossed. Asked
why he just didn't buy some warmer clothes, Hernandez said: ``I've
got to adjust to the cold. I'm going to be living here.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankees manager Joe Torre believes that Hernandez is capable of
adjusting, to the cold and to the fact that he has not pitched in
so long. But the first innings could be very critical for
Hernandez, Torre said, because the right-hander relies on finesse;
according to a scouting service, fastballs comprised only 60
percent of his pitches, an extremely low ratio. Hernandez needs to
have touch and feel and command of his pitches, his slider,
curveball and changeup. ``You really don't know what to expect,''
Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez may need an inning or two to re-acquaint himself with
the mound, with the feel of his breaking pitches or his changeup,
meaning that he could be vulnerable immediately.
</P>
<P>
   David Cone pitches like Hernandez in many respects, throwing
from multiple arm angles, relying on his slider, changing speeds.
He believes that pitchers of their ilk tend to adapt to change more
quickly, because they are always changing. ``Those type of guys are
more conditioned to coming back after long lay-offs,'' Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez pitched twice against the Indians this season,
throwing effectively on June 18, allowing seven hits and two runs
in seven and two-thirds innings in a no-decision, before getting
hit hard on July 13. That day, he gave up nine hits, including two
home runs, four runs, and two walks in six and two-thirds innings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Hernandez pitched almost exclusively to the
outside half of the strike zone, and the Indians hitters
essentially leaned over the plate and drove line drives to the
opposite field. Three weeks later, Hernandez began making a
successful adjustment, throwing more inside fastballs. Cleveland
manager Mike Hargrove said before Friday night's game that the
Indians did not expect that Hernandez would be any different since
the last time they saw him; if that was the case, then they would
be surprised.
</P>
<P>
   As Hernandez developed as a pitcher in Cuba in the 1980s, he saw
a videotape of Gooden pitching for the New York Mets, saw how
Gooden drew his front leg very high and held his hands close to his
body before launching himself toward home plate. Hernandez tried
this and liked it; at the time, he often brushed his left ear with
his knee. (His leg kick is slightly lower now.)
</P>
<P>
   Gooden grinned when asked about how Hernandez emulates him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has good stuff and any time you see a pitcher at this level
and any time they analyze you, it makes you feel good,'' Gooden
said. ``I'm too old now to get my leg up that high.''
</P>
<P>
   Does that make you feel old?
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me feel old,'' Gooden said, grinning again, ``but
he's probably my age, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   _ SHANE SPENCER was in JOE TORRE's lineup for Game 3, in left
field, and CHILI DAVIS was to make his first start as the
designated hitter, batting sixth. TIM RAINES was not in the
starting lineup, Torre said, simply because he is not swinging
well.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Indians have not made an official decision on their
starting pitcher for Game 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
