<SLUG> BC-FBC-COUGARS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON STATE TAKES ON ROLE OF PAC-10 TRAFFIC COP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PULLMAN, Wash. _ The detour sign isn't visible along State Route
195 just yet, but Washington State coach Mike Price hopes to start
redirecting Pac-10 traffic Saturday when the Cougars host unbeaten
Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The road to the Rose Bowl still goes through Pullman,'' Price
declared. ``Anyone who wants to go to the Rose Bowl has to come in
here and beat the Cougs, otherwise they may not go.''
</P>
<P>
   That's true, at least Saturday for the Ducks, followed by USC.
</P>
<P>
   With two straight Pac-10 losses to Cal and UCLA, the Cougars are
out of contention to repeat as conference champions. WSU is hoping
to avoid becoming the first Pac-10 team since UCLA in 1943 to go
from first to last in back-to-back seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks a little dim for us, but if Oregon wants to go to the
Rose Bowl, they've got to come in here and beat us,'' Price said.
</P>
<P>
   Diverting the Ducks, however, is going to take a formidable road
block.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon is averaging 50.2 points and 542 yards per game. The
Ducks are coming off a bye week after thrashing Stanford 63-28 in
their conference opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``This offense that we're facing might be the best in the
country,'' Price said. ``Right now (Akili Smith) is the hottest
quarterback in the country that I've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, riding a newly created Heisman Trophy campaign, is
leading the nation in passing efficiency (193.1), and junior
tailback Reuben Droughns ranks sixth nationally in rushing,
averaging 145 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   Price's other chore after affixing the Pac-10 detour sign is to
get his team up after an emotionally draining loss to UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt a lot of urgency and intensity before that game last
week. We were probably as emotionally and intellectually ready as
in any game we have played this season. Our guys were jacked before
the game,'' Price said.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Cougars, UCLA already proved the road to
the Rose Bowl begins and ends at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   SECONDARY THOUGHTS: The WSU secondary, with Lamont Thompson
leading the Pac-10 in interceptions (4), faces another test similar
to the one posed by UCLA's Cade McNown last week: a quarterback in
Smith who can escape from the pocket and break defenses down.
McNown also had a Heisman campaign of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Smith comes into the game leading the Pac-10 in passing
efficiency. But the Cougars are second in the conference and ninth
in the nation in defending against the pass, holding quarterbacks
to an average 88.8 rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our secondary is playing about as good as you can play,''
Price said. ``I don't know if we've had a better secondary at
Washington State than the one have right now.''
</P>
<P>
   SIRMON'S SUB: When Oregon's all-conference linebacker Peter
Sirmon went down two weeks ago with a season-ending shoulder
injury, it was considered a major setback. But his replacement,
senior Chris Vandiver, had 19 tackles in his first start, against
Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different not having him out there,'' Vandiver said of
Sirmon. ``It takes a lot of pressure off us when he is there and
you can look around and there's big Peter.''
</P>
<P>
   Told of Vandiver's numbers against Stanford, Price sighed: ``I'm
so happy for them. That's just what we need.''
</P>
<P>
   COIN FLIP: Heads or tails, Price already has his mind made up if
the Cougars win the coin toss: ``We're taking the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Price hopes his offense can control the game, avoid turnovers
and keep Smith off the field. The Cougars fell behind early to UCLA
and never recovered, just like Michigan State did in losing 48-14
to Oregon to start this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against Michigan State, they just killed them early,'' Price
said of the Ducks. ``Obviously, that happened to us last week and I
don't want it to happen this week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
